<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARRIAGE-TV-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARRIAGES MADE IN HEAVEN, AND OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the institution of marriage is to thrive into the coming
century, it will need a more articulate defender and a more careful
chronicler than Garry Marshall. He is proud that he and Barbara
have been married for 36 years. May they have 36 more. But just
because you've been socializing for decades, that doesn't make you
a sociologist.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall, the creator of winning television shows (``Happy
Days'') and movies (``Pretty Woman'') and an appealing comic actor
(``Murphy Brown''), is trying out a new role on Monday night. He is
the host-narrator-interviewer-director of a Showtime documentary,
``Marriage in the 20th Century: In Search of the Happy Ending.'' He
and his film are never less than engaging, but a seasoned pro like
Marshall ought to know that you can't hold an audience for two
hours with good intentions and pallid shtick: ``My wife was a
nurse,'' Marshall says. ``I was a hypochondriac. It was a marriage
made in heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   This film is the first in a monthly series of documentaries by
directors who are famous, but not for making documentaries. Each
installment is supposed to sum up some aspect of life in the
century. The next three are to be Robert Townsend on sex, Barry
Levinson on the future and Robert Zemeckis on ``smoking, drinking
and drugging.'' Things could get more interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night's program offers some overlong, under-edited
interviews with people who married (or entered other kinds of
committed relationships) at various points in the century. Most
lived happily ever after. The others split up. They all seem like
likable people, full of the wisdom that comes with experience. But
they don't have anything very interesting to say. And as an
interviewer, Marshall is no Murphy Brown.
</P>
<P>
   The best sequence focuses on commercial wedding chapels in Las
Vegas. After paying $35 for a marriage license, you can get hitched
at a drive-in window for $30. A ceremony inside the chapel starts
at $45. Elvis can give the bride away, but that costs extra.
</P>
<P>
   As for historical perspective, there isn't much to be gained
from the film's endless snippets of grainy old home movies,
newsreels and film comedies. Nor is there much insight in
Marshall's apparently ad-libbed lectures: ``I think the pioneers
had not a big choice. There was one farm, one girl, one daughter,
one son. If those two didn't get married, you didn't have much of a
shot.''
</P>
<P>
   OK You're not supposed to take all this seriously. But if the
filmmaker is just going to throw the thing together, why should you
take it at all?
GARRY MARSHALL ON MARRIAGE IN THE 20th CENTURY &QL; 
In Search of the Happy Ending  &QL; 
Showtime, Monday night at 10 &QL; 
Sandra M. Itkoff, series executive producer; Lesli Klainberg,
series producer; Garry Marshall, director; Liz Garbus, producer;
Karen Stirgwolt, co-producer; Jesse Moss, associate producer;
Alison Ellwood, editor. A 5759 Production in association with Buena
Vista Television Productions.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
