<HEADER>
A3944 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DIERKER-REAX-HNS &LR;      06-14 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DIERKER-REAX-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY WIZIG  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The Astros were a stunned group as they left the Astrodome after
Sunday's game, halted frighteningly when manager Larry Dierker
suffered a grand mal seizure during the bottom of the eighth
inning.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I saw the same kind of thing happen to my grandmother in the
Dominican (Republic),'' pitcher Jose Lima said about 90 minutes
later after a team meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Word had come while Dierker, 52, was en route to Methodist
Hospital that the manager was deemed out of danger and the problem
was not a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started crying,'' Lima said. ``I walked away because I
couldn't stand to see it again. They were trying to hold his legs
down because all you can think about when something like that
happens is to get as much air as you can.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry Dierker always has a smile on his face and is like a
father to us. To see him like that, laying in the dugout, it was
such a shock. We didn't know what it was. It was just scary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a great city like this, not in the Third World, and
we're probably three minutes away from a great hospital, and it
seemed like forever before the ambulance came. You can die in 20
minutes. That's how long it must have taken the ambulance to get in
there. It seemed like forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we will all say our prayers for him and carry on as best
as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Mitch Meluskey, one of the numerous injury victims this
season among Astros players and coaches, figured the game itself
was meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   ``It brought something home,'' Meluskey said after the game,
which was suspended with the Astros ahead 4-1, to be resumed when
the Padres return to Houston on July 23-25. ``Thirty-eight thousand
people got to witness it with us, and it was profound testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something really bad like this, when things are really bad,
shows that it's only a baseball game. That's real life, what Larry
Dierker is going through.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before game time, Dierker was following his routine,
signing autographs for fans standing behind the dugout, then
answering a reporter's questions about the upcoming Braves series,
which begins tonight.
</P>
<P>
   But the routine changed in the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was horrible to see something like that happen,'' said
starting pitcher Shane Reynolds. ``We said a team prayer on the
field, and we will continue to pray for him and his family.''
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Billy Wagner, outfielder Glen Barker and infielder
Ricky Gutierrez agreed on the shock of the scene that unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   ``A terrible thing to see,'' Barker said. ``You realize how
short life can be at a time like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Wagner said: ``The game is insignificant. Real life is what
Dierker is going through now. The thing to do is stay positive and
keep praying.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hated to see our skipper like that, and I had never seen
anything like that before,'' Gutierrez said. ``It seemed to take
hours before the ambulance got there.''
</P>
<P>
   San Diego manager Bruce Bochy played for the Astros when Dierker
worked for the organization after retiring as a player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to him (Dierker) on Friday, and he said he was
working out,'' Bochy said. ``I had heard he'd had a seizure before
(three years ago in San Diego while working on the Astros' radio
crew). There's no way anyone wanted to continue the game.''
</P>
<P>
   San Diego pitching coach Dave Smith, a former Astros pitcher,
said: ``I talked to him on Saturday before the game. I was
concerned that something was not quite right. He wasn't as upbeat
and laughing as he usually is but kind of quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   San Diego pitcher Woody Williams, a Houstonian, said: ``I met
him for the first time (during the teams' latest series). I had
come to the Dome to watch him pitch and had listened to him on the
radio. To meet him was special.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it shows how quickly things can change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
