<HEADER>
A3945 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-GALANTE-HN     06-14 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-GALANTE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The unsettling images that unfolded in the Astros' dugout during
the eighth inning of Sunday's suspended game won't go away any time
soon _ certainly not for Astros bench coach Matt Galante, who was
seated next to Larry Dierker when the Astros manager's grand mal
seizure began.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But the Astros must find a way to move on _ somehow, some way.
</P>
<P>
   And it will be Galante's job to restore some semblance of
normalcy over the next several days. General manager Gerry
Hunsicker tabbed Galante as the natural choice to serve as interim
manager during Dierker's indefinite absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never want to take over under these circumstances,'' said
Galante, who has been a coach in the Astros organization since 1980
and was considered for the manager's job when the club hired Terry
Collins in November 1993 and Dierker in October 1996. ``I really
don't feel like I'm taking over, because this is Larry's team and
things are going to be done the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Galante, 49, has been Dierker's right-hand man since the
beginning of last season, when he was named bench coach after Bill
Virdon retired. Galante consults with Dierker on in-game decisions
and has been as involved as any coach on the staff when it comes to
game management.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry and Matt work very closely on a day-to-day basis, and
Matt has extensive experience,'' Hunsicker said. ``He knows the
ballclub as well as anyone. I have all the confidence in the world
in him as a replacement.''
</P>
<P>
   Predicting the impact Dierker's absence will have on the Astros
is almost impossible at this point because it is uncertain how long
he will be out of the dugout. Dierker underwent a series of tests
beginning Sunday night, and the Astros should have a better idea
regarding a timetable once the results are known.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really don't know where this is headed,'' Hunsicker said.
``Until they finish running the tests, we won't know where we
stand. I think they'll keep him (in the hospital) for observation
for at least a couple of days. He's certainly not going to come
walking out of there tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker was in stable condition Sunday night, and Hunsicker said
he was coherent and even cracked a few jokes.
</P>
<P>
   As far as game management is concerned, expect Galante's style
to be similar to Dierker's. Both are popular in the clubhouse and
uphold the theory of letting the players play the game without
excessive interference from the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to play the game the way we've always played it,''
said Galante, who will be in charge beginning tonight when the
Atlanta Braves visit the Astrodome for a four-game series.
``Hopefully, Larry will be back shortly; until then, we're just
going to try to win them one by one for Larry.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker is the third member of the coaching staff to be
sidelined because of illness this season. First-base coach Jose
Cruz is expected to return Friday after receiving treatment for an
irregular heartbeat, and hitting instructor Tom McCraw has been out
since May 17 while undergoing treatment for prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   McCraw was replaced on an interim basis by Harry Spilman, but
Cruz's void was not filled. Until Friday, the Astros will operate
two coaches short.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll be OK there,'' Galante said. ``I think I can
handle my bench job as well as run the team until Larry gets back.
Cheo (Cruz) will be back (Friday), so that will help us.''
</P>
<P>
   And when the time is right, Galante said he will seek input from
Dierker, who has guided the Astros to back-to-back National League
Central Division titles and has a 223-161 record since replacing
Collins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll wait a couple of days, and we'll listen to the doctors
and let them tell us when it's OK for that,'' Galante said. ``I
don't want to talk to him about the club until the doctors say it's
OK to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   To a man, the players were shaken by Sunday's events, and the
clubhouse was uncharacteristically off-limits to the media
following the game. Hunsicker huddled with the team to update the
players on Dierker's status, and he believes the team will move
forward without its leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is certainly testing everyone's emotional strength,''
Hunsicker said. ``We've had more than our share of difficulties
this year. This is not to be taken lightly; it's another big blow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure (returning to the ballpark today) will seem strange,
but I think everyone will feel better when the test results are in
and we know where we're headed with this. We just need to get to
the point where we know where we are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, everyone was stunned and shocked to a certain
extent. This team has bounced back from adversity a number of
times, and it seems to never end. But I have all the confidence in
the world that we will continue to move forward. He'll be in all of
our prayers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
