<HEADER>
A3946 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DIERKER-HNS &LR;      06-14 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DIERKER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID BARRON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Astros manager Larry Dierker was struck by a violent series of
full-body seizures as he watched the Astros-San Diego Padres game
Sunday afternoon from the Astrodome dugout.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dierker was treated by medical personnel for more than 20
minutes before being taken by ambulance from the stadium floor to
Methodist Hospital, where he was reported in stable condition
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Astros spokesman Rob Matwick said tests were under way Sunday
night in an effort to determine the source of the grand mal seizure
that struck Dierker, 52.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is that there was no heart or cardiac damage,''
said Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker. ``This could be one of
those strange and inexplicable instances where the body reacts and
then it (the reaction) just goes away. He was conscious, and when
he was on the way to the hospital his condition stabilized.''
</P>
<P>
   After talking to Dierker at the hospital, Hunsicker said the
manager ``was alert, coherent and joking around. He was in good
spirits. He's still going to have a battery of tests, so we're
optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Both teams agreed to suspend the game, which the Astros led 4-1
in the bottom of the eighth inning, until the Padres' next trip to
Houston July 23-25.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker was stricken in the dugout along the first-base line,
out of view of most of the 39,773 fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was sitting in his regular spot, and Matty (Astros coach
Matt Galante) was next to him and looked over,'' Hunsicker said.
``He said Larry was looking up and didn't seem like he was himself.
He asked him if he was OK, and the next thing he was seizing.''
</P>
<P>
   With Jeff Bagwell at the plate, a police officer stationed in
the Astros' dugout ran onto the field and motioned toward
paramedics that help was needed.
</P>
<P>
   Paramedics and Astros trainer Rex Jones rushed to the home-plate
end of the dugout where Dierker lay. Witnesses said Astros
outfielder Derek Bell tried to stabilize Dierker's body, but the
force of the seizures was such that Bell was nearly thrown clear of
the stricken manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``The convulsions were pretty much constantly going on,''
Bagwell said. ``It was everything you've heard about seizures. It
was just horrible to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Astros players huddled around the dugout as fans, who were not
told what was taking place on the field, watched silently from the
stands. Judy Dierker was taken from the stands to be with her
husband, who was administered intravenous fluids and then loaded
into the ambulance for the trip to Methodist Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   As the ambulance left the Astrodome floor, Astros players
gathered on the field with team chaplain Gene Pemberton for prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked the Lord for a miracle to stabilize him,'' Pemberton
said. ``His word says that if we ask anything in the name of Jesus,
he'll give it to us. We just asked him, `Lord, will you do it? Will
you do it for your glory?'
</P>
<P>
   ``And he did. He (Dierker) stabilized in five minutes where for
20 minutes he had been having seizures.''
</P>
<P>
   After Astros owner Drayton McLane Jr. talked with Padres owner
John Moores, a former Houston resident, the game was suspended.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the San Diego players as well as our players, their heart
just wasn't into finishing this game, and the umpires felt the same
way,'' McLane said.
</P>
<P>
   Astros officials said the incident began at 3:55 p.m. A Houston
Fire Department spokesman said a 911 call was received at 4:02 p.m.
and an engine, ambulance and medic were dispatched a minute later.
</P>
<P>
   The engine arrived at 4:07 p.m. but was unable to gain access to
the Dome, forcing medical personnel to run from the center-field
gate to the dugout. The ambulance arrived at 4:13 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a response team on the benches, so we are ready to go
at any moment,'' McLane said. ``The fire department does not keep
an ambulance at the Astrodome, but normally the response time is
very good. Response time was not an issue. We had (medical) people
there who are on the bench for every game.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Payne, Mayor Lee Brown's communications director, expressed
concern that the fire truck was not able to enter the Dome field
and that there was no outside telephone line from the dugout that
would have allowed a more timely 911 call.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those issues will be addressed as far as Enron Field (the new
stadium that opens in 2000) is concerned,'' Payne said.
</P>
<P>
   Astros announcer Milo Hamilton, Dierker's broadcast partner for
more than a decade with the team, said Dierker suffered a mild
seizure in June 1996 in San Diego and was hospitalized overnight
for observation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had been on a lot of medication for an infection,''
Hamilton said. ``In fact, he used to give himself IVs on the plane.
We all thought then that it was just an outgrowth of the medication
he was on.''
</P>
<P>
   Reporters said Dierker appeared to be in good spirits before the
game, playing catch with his son, Ryan. But Padres pitching coach
Dave Smith, a former Astros pitcher, spoke with Dierker on Saturday
and ``something was not quite right. He wasn't as upbeat and
laughing as he usually is.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker was hospitalized in May 1996 after having fluid drained
from the perocardial sac surrounding his heart. He also suffered
torn ligaments in his thumb as a result of a skiing accident and
twice underwent surgery, the second time in July 1996 as a result
of an infection.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker has been with the Astros organization with only brief
interruptions since 1964 and is one of the most popular figures in
the history of Houston baseball. He won 20 games in 1969, pitched a
no-hitter in 1976 and still holds team records for starts, complete
games, shutouts and innings pitched.
</P>
<P>
   After more than a decade in the Astros' broadcast booth, he was
named manager in October 1996. He had led the Astros to
back-to-back National League Central Division titles and was named
last year as the league's Manager of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's most grim coincidence was that Dierker was stricken on
the same day that former Astros pitcher J.R. Richard threw out the
ceremonial first pitch. Richard's promising career was cut short
when he suffered a stroke while working out in the Astrodome on
July 30, 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Medical problems also have affected the Astros' coaching staff
this year. Hitting coach Tom McCraw is on medical leave while
undergoing treatment for prostate cancer, and first-base coach Jose
Cruz is on leave undergoing treatment for an irregular heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ````It has just been one of those very difficult years to get
through,'' Hunsicker said. ``Somehow we are going to get through
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Galante will serve as interim manager beginning tonight, when
the Astros host the Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``When someone you care about goes through something like that,
all you can do is pray,'' Bagwell said. ``This puts baseball into
perspective. Obviously we are here to play baseball, but this is
more important than playing a game out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writers John P. Lopez, Jerry Wizig and Carlton Thompson
contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
