   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Monday, June 14. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN (Undated) _ This is an outrage! Laredo, Texas,
was the most consistently hot city in the U.S. last year, eeking
out a win over Lake Havasu City by one day. Laredo and Lake Havasu
folks say what this means (with a little wisdom from the coldest
spot in the U.S. thrown in for good measure). By BILL GOODYKOONTZ.
Story will move in the ``L'' category
</P>
<P>
   RIOT (Phoenix) _ Sheriff Joe Arpaio blames Saturday night's tent
city riot on a flare up of inmate hostilities over smuggled
cigarettes and matches that were used to light mattresses and
toilet paper to set fire to seven tents. Arpaio stood among the
ashes Sunday and watched as a crew of inmates replaced the damaged
tents. He praised guards and deputies for ending what he called a
``bedtime disturbance'' without injury to anyone. Story will move
in ``A'' category. By GRACIELA SEVILLA.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
SLEEP (Phoenix) _ When jurors in the Scott Falater murder trial
begin deliberations later this month, they will wrestle with a
defense scenario that defies common sense: A man stabs his wife 44
times in his sleep, and, still sleeping, drags her into the pool
and holds her head under water. The bloody, protracted mayhem of
Falater's admitted attack weighs heavily against the defense. But
before jurors can reach a verdict on Falater, they must reach a
verdict on Dr. Roger Broughton, a heavyweight in the study of
sleepwalking. Is Broughton a credible scientist or an errant
egghead? &QL; 
Story will move in the ``A'' category. By JERRY KAMMER. &QL; 
