<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BICYCLIST-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BICYCLIST OVERCOMES HORRIFIC CRASH, JUMPS ON A BIKE AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HOLLY CAIN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The sound of her jaw pounding into the pavement
sounded like a potato chip crunching underneath someone's foot.
Carrianne Pullar still remembers the morning rush-hour traffic
whizzing by as she and her mangled bicycle lay helpless on the side
of the road, her jaw shattered.
</P>
<P>
   It's a horrific, full-sensory experience that has understandably
taken a long time for the 29-year-old Pullar to push out of her
mind.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this week _ three years after Pullar crashed while riding
her bicycle to work in West Seattle _ she is competing for the
Saturn of Bellevue, Wash., team against some of the world's top
cyclists in the HP LaserJet Women's Challenge in Boise, Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carrianne has a lot of spirit,'' said Pullar's aunt Ann
Fonken, who raised her.
</P>
<P>
   That is an understatement.
</P>
<P>
   On her way to work at a downtown Seattle bicycle messenger
service in February 1996, the front wheel of Pullar's bike suddenly
came off as she pedaled downhill on a freeway on-ramp. Pullar
tumbled head first, face down into the road. She wasn't wearing a
helmet and the impact shattered her jaw so severely a titanium
plate was inserted and her mouth wired shut. Her teeth were so
badly damaged she couldn't chew for 18 months; during that time she
lost 23 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   The worst part for Pullar was dealing with the massive doses of
morphine being pumped into her body to relieve the intense pain
during her weeklong hospital stay. For this self-proclaimed
``health nut,'' candy bars were foreign to her body _ forget
prescription narcotics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The drugs I was on made me depressed and nauseous and I kept
thinking that I was going to vomit through my wires and choke to
death like Jimi Hendrix,'' Pullar said. ``The more I worried about
it, the worse the nausea got.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was definitely ready to hang up the bike. I had decided God
was trying to tell me something _ that maybe I needed to take up
golf or tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   That's when Pullar's uncle, Lance Fonken, stepped in. As hard as
it was for the family to see Pullar depressed and in pain, Fonken
firmly reminded his young niece that she never had quit on anything
in her life. She was an accomplished soccer player and equestrian
and had been a good high school track athlete while growing up in
Renton, about 10 miles southwest of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Like being thrown from a horse, Pullar knew she had to get right
back in the saddle.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for her rehabilitation, the summer of 1996 was
beautiful and she summoned the courage to not only start riding a
bike again but to take a job as a bicycle messenger in downtown
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Her first day on the job, Pullar had to deliver a package from
the company's office on First Hill to a shop at Pike Place Market,
meaning she had to travel down one of the city's steepest streets,
Columbia Street.
</P>
<P>
   It was a daunting assignment not only because Pullar had to
repress memories of her crash, but also because of her fear of
heights. Her aunt remembers taking the family to the Green River
Gorge when her niece was a youngster and Pullar was so terrified
she wouldn't come near the bridge's scenic overlook.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working as a messenger forced me to ride knowing I had to make
a living,'' said Pullar. ``It also helped force me to ride again
without reliving the accident every five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first got on the bike, I had a death grip on the handle
bars and I wouldn't let up on the brakes. I had to learn not to be
intimidated. After all this was the one thing _ riding a bicycle _
that I had always enjoyed doing my whole life.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of deliveries and hundreds of casual rides later,
Pullar's competitive urges returned. Her first big test came in the
1997 Messenger World Championships in Barcelona, Spain.
</P>
<P>
   While running in the middle of the pack, Pullar was caught in a
chain-reaction accident that started in front of her. She injured
her hand in the pileup but her psyche got through it unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   She got back up and nothing's kept her down since.
</P>
<P>
   Pullar normally rides 250-350 miles a week through mountainous
terrain when training for a road race, such as the one this week in
Idaho. Her effort on the local road racing circuit during the past
two years caught the attention of noted Seattle rider Leigh
Fulwood, who invited her to ride for the highly regarded Saturn
team.
</P>
<P>
   Pullar has responded with seven wins in 10 races this season for
Saturn of Bellevue. A good showing in Idaho would help advance her
into a more competitive category on the North American Road Racing
circuit.
</P>
<P>
   The Women's Challenge is a 12-day event that covers 693 miles
and 13,870 vertical feet. It has 13 stages that feature eight road
races _ one with a climb of more than 3,000 feet through the
mountains of southwest Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   (As of Stage 6 Sunday, Pullar was in 87th place after riding the
25-mile Massacre Rock State Park course.)
</P>
<P>
   Normally this kind of grueling event would intimidate the best
of competitors, but not Pullar, not after what she's been through.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a lot to do with faith in yourself and faith in God,''
Pullar said. ``He never throws anything your way that you can't
handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I realize I don't want to be 80 years old, looking
back at the what-ifs. Women of our generation have so much going
for us and I want to take advantage of that, not take it for
granted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
