<HEADER>
A3959 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZ     06-14 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAREDO'S HOTTER? HOLY HAVASU! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is a red-hot outrage. It is an affront that we should not
take lying down in the shade. The entire state should be up in arms
_ sweaty, sunburned arms.
</P>
<P>
   Any Arizonan knows that Lake Havasu City, with triple-digit
temperatures as common as blown saves by the Diamondbacks' bullpen,
is the hottest place in the country, right? Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   According to ``Weatherwise'' magazine, Lake Havasu City was only
the second-most consistently hot city last year. The hottest?
</P>
<P>
   Laredo, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Laredo was the hottest place in the 48 contiguous states on 34
days in 1998, while Lake Havasu City _ No. 1 a year earlier _
topped the nation on 33 days. Close but no sunburn. Talk about a
matter of degrees . . .
</P>
<P>
   (Happily, Lake Havasu enjoys the lead in the long-term
competition, scoring the top temperature 511 days in the '90s.
Bullhead City is second at 202.)
</P>
<P>
   So what are we going to do about it? Is Lake Havasu going to
cook the books? Place the official thermometer on a molten strip of
asphalt?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, that's all in God's hands,'' said Bonnie Barsness,
director of the Lake Havasu Tourism Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say she wouldn't welcome a little divine
intervention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like notoriety here in Lake Havasu,'' Barsness said,
laughing. ``It's actually all part of our marketing plan. It gets
us on the national weather all across the nation. It keeps Lake
Havasu on the forefront of people's mind as a hot tourism
destination.''
</P>
<P>
   And you know what an attraction searing heat can be. To
suntan-lotion magnates anyway.
</P>
<P>
   `NOTHING TO BRAG ABOUT'
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, it doesn't sound as if Laredo is all that excited
over the title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any kind of first place can be good news if treated the right
way,'' said Miguel Conchas, president of the Laredo Chamber of
Commerce, ``(but) certainly it's nothing to brag about when you're
trying to attract business to the city. I don't think anybody's
going to want to keep the title.''
</P>
<P>
   Please. He's just sandbagging. Why else would the Laredo Chamber
incorporate jalapeno peppers into its logo?
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was that the city was hot in more ways than one,''
Conchas said. ``We take advantage of the title.''
</P>
<P>
   Ha. Busted.
</P>
<P>
   Barsness noted that the weather didn't really heat up in Lake
Havasu until July last year. The opposite effect in Laredo may have
let that city wrest away the title.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been hot here, but _ maybe it had something to do
with El Nino _ last year it was unusually hot,'' Conchas said.
``This year, it's turning out to be the same.''
</P>
<P>
   You see? Already he's angling for next year's crown. And this in
a place that is usually between a paltry 105 and 110 degrees in the
summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you go over 110, it tends to be unusual,'' Conchas
said.
</P>
<P>
   Any time it's 110 in Lake Havasu, it tends to be unusual as well
_ people wonder why it's so frigid.
</P>
<P>
   THE OTHER EXTREME
</P>
<P>
   Offensive as it may be for an Arizonan to do so, I had to ask
Conchas the Question: Is it a dry heat?
</P>
<P>
   ``Surprisingly, I think things have changed over the last few
years,'' he said. ``South Texas used to be a very dry heat, but
humidity has been on the rise.''
</P>
<P>
   Good. At least they're suffering.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, so are we. Even if Arizona is no longer home to the
absolute hottest spot, it's still brain-scramblingly hot here. Ah,
to be in Stanley, Idaho, the coldest spot in the contiguous United
States last year. A call last week to the city offices found
Connie-Roze Burr, city clerk, who issued this weather report:
``It's snowing.''
</P>
<P>
   It's June.
</P>
<P>
   Then again the low that day was only 29 degrees. In the winter,
Burr said, temperatures range ``from 32 to 49 below.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't worry about Burr. She uttered a familiar refrain when
talking about the cold in Stanley: ``It's not the same kind of
cold.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a dry one, no doubt. &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at (602) 444-8828 or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-99 0102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990614.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3960 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-14 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
YOU lean against the wall in his office or maybe stand next to him
behind the cage at Astros batting practice. And you just talk.
</P>
<P>
   About nothing. About everything.
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible not to like being around Larry Dierker. You
listen to what he has to say, and you take it all in. It's not
always about baseball; most often it's not.
</P>
<P>
   It's about the weather, his beloved Rockets, the food at a
restaurant, a good bottle of wine, the headlines in the day's paper
and whatever it is that happens to be behind that sly, crooked
smile of his.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker has been around the Astros for what seems like forever _
ever since he took the mound as an 18-year-old and struck out
Willie Mays in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible not to like the man _ the amble, the hands on
the hips, the head tilted to one side as if he's trying to figure
it all out.
</P>
<P>
   If Nolan Ryan, Jose Cruz, Craig Biggio and Jeff Bagwell are the
greatest stars in the history of this franchise, then Dierker
epitomizes it. He has embroidered himself across the fabric of this
club. He was an Astro then, an Astro now, and he'll be an Astro
forever.
</P>
<P>
   The priceless news we received Sunday evening, only moments
after things could not have appeared more grim, was that, yes,
Dierker should be around for quite a while more. Thank God. And
thank God for Larry Dierker.
</P>
<P>
   In this job, you always try to be objective, to walk the middle
of the road. But Dierker is one of those rare ones who makes it
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   You're always on his side. You always want him to win games,
because he deserves to win. He deserves to hop across the floor of
the Dome on some October night, flashing that smile, hugging
players and jumping around like a kid because he just won the world
championship.
</P>
<P>
   But this is about Dierker's winning a game none of us even knew
he was playing _ the one for his life.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker was sitting next to bench coach Matt Galante a little
before 4 p.m. Sunday afternoon, no doubt loving what he saw only
minutes earlier _ a grand slam by Derek Bell that gave the Astros a
4-1 lead over the San Diego Padres.
</P>
<P>
   He suddenly pitched his head backward as his face turned flush.
Galante asked Dierker if he felt all right. Dierker raised both his
arms over his head and hunched his shoulders as if to take a deep
breath.
</P>
<P>
   Then Dierker was on the floor, convulsing uncontrollably in a
violent seizure. His body contorted. His limbs flailed wildly. He
bounced on the floor of the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   A police officer sprinted to the field and waved for medical
personnel to come help. Players rushed around the dugout to see
what was happening and could not believe what Dierker was
experiencing. His mouth was salivating, his body shaking.
</P>
<P>
   The seizure was classified as a grand mal seizure, the most
violent known. It can be fatal. It can be caused by anything from a
serious neurological disturbance to simple sleep deprivation. It
lasted five minutes, 10 minutes, 15 minutes. Just call it forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not something you would ever want to see,'' Bagwell
said.
</P>
<P>
   It shocked nearly 40,000 fans into total silence. Biggio
crouched in front of the dugout and clenched his St. Christopher
medal between his teeth. Jose Lima ran to the opposite corner of
the dugout and cried, bowing his head and praying.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Everett covered his eyes with his hands and shook his head.
Judy Dierker rushed from the stands and stood by her husband's
side. Glen Barker kissed the cross on his necklace. Mike Hampton
took off his cap and began waving it above Dierker, trying to get
him some air.
</P>
<P>
   And there were heroes in the middle of it all _ real heroes.
</P>
<P>
   Among the first to reach Dierker, Bell did everything he could
to help, grabbing his manager's arms and legs as he convulsed and
not leaving Dierker's side until more paramedics arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Rex Jones, the Astros' trainer, jumped to the scene and acted
admirably in every way. Jones wrapped his arms around Dierker, kept
him from swallowing his tongue and barked instructions throughout.
</P>
<P>
   When the ambulances finally arrived, Judy Dierker jumped into
the front seat as her husband was carted into the back. Biggio
patted the side of the ambulance as it drove off.
</P>
<P>
   The team gathered around chaplain Gene Pemberton, their arms
around one another, and prayed. Umpire Brian Runge crossed himself,
then suspended the game. The crowd walked away silently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball is insignificant,'' Astros pitcher Billy Wagner said.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't about baseball. It was about a guy you love to be
around. It was about hoping that the next few days will provide
some sort of answer or medication that can control Dierker's
condition.
</P>
<P>
   And then this game can be picked up July 23 when the Padres come
back to town. See you there, Dierk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-99 0103EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
