<DOCNO> NYT19990614.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3964 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     06-14 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERLEAGUE FORMAT HAS WORN THIN IN NORTHWEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ You can come out now. Yes, you. The real baseball fan.
The purist.
</P>
<P>
   The siege _ or should we say the scourge? _ of interleague play
is over. For now, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, for some of us _ myself, for instance _ a week of root
canals stood in the way of really caring that the Mariners were
playing pointless games against National League West teams.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some baseball purists might even suggest a serious bout
of dentistry is preferable to devoting precious time and attention
to interleague action _ unless you're in New York, where Mets vs.
Yankees is perfect fodder for the over-the-top fans in the Bronx
and Queens.
</P>
<P>
   That sort of in-city subway series or cross-state rivalry
(Cleveland-Reds) is the only thing interleague is good for. And
it's good for only one, two-game series a season.
</P>
<P>
   Back here at home, however, where there is no natural NL rival,
the urge is to insist that games against the Yankees or Rangers
would have provided real whiffs of history, meaning, bad blood,
delicious rivalry, whatever.
</P>
<P>
   But no, the ruse continued. Instead of more Derek Jeter and Tino
Martinez, instead of Rafael Palmeiro and Juan Gonzalez, the
Mariners spent the last nine games toiling at this failing
marketing ploy called interleague.
</P>
<P>
   The M's were first sent to San Diego on their Bud Selig-enforced
march on the dark side of their baseball moon, as if seeing
Sterling Hitchcock again was anything Mariner fans cared a hoot
about.
</P>
<P>
   Next, it was off to Colorado for a thin-air, thinner plot-line
battle against the Rockies. Just because Denver has a nutty
ballyard built for NFL-sized scores doesn't mean innocent teams
from the AL West have to serve time there, too.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Giants were in town this weekend, giving Seattle
baseball fans the rare chance to see three-time National League MVP
Barry Bonds.
</P>
<P>
   But what Mariners fan yesterday relished witnessing Bonds come
up as a pinch hitter with the bases loaded in an eighth inning when
the Giants would come back to score five runs and swipe the 8-4
victory?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that Bonds at-bat, even though he walked, was the flash of
gratification interleague is geared to provide. But even Bonds
might be the first one to say something's got to give with this
whole interleague affair. During Saturday night's game, with the
M's trailing but making a charge in the sixth inning, Bonds watched
as a routine fly ball off the bat of Ken Griffey Jr. dropped right
next to him in short left center.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds was charged with an error, although the trickery of
interleague is that it challenges even the best players to get real
comfy, real quick, in unfamiliar stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Bonds, though, baseball in general deserves an ``E'' for
this already worn out ``novelty'' called interleague.
</P>
<P>
   Let's put it this way: you can buy a T-shirt at Target that
holds its shape and color longer than this interleague thing. And
apparently almost everyone outside of the marketing gurus in
baseball agrees.
</P>
<P>
   Three years into this unnecessary experiment, interleague is old
and tired.
</P>
<P>
   When the Phillies and Orioles are locked into two series, it's
overkill. When the Cardinals and Tigers are suddenly scheduled to
play each other six times, you would have to say something is
seriously wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire is so disappointed with interleague overkill even
he said interleague play ``doesn't do anything for the game'' and
went so far as to say ``we should go back to the way baseball
should be played.''
</P>
<P>
   However, instead of an outright order for interleague to cease
and desist _ as some purists would justifiably insist _ there is a
growing groundswell for, at the very least, some sort of
interleague modification.
</P>
<P>
   The hope that AL West and NL West teams would stir up rivalries
over time is not happening, so something else is needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why doesn't everybody get to play everybody?'' Mariner first
baseman David Segui said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Even Alex Rodriguez, a self-proclaimed baseball purist who has
maintained his allegiance to the old-fashioned schedule, said teams
should not be locked into an unalterable home-and-home schedule
against the same teams every season. ``We should adjust the
schedule to play different teams every season,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, A-Rod is a natural to root for a chance to play not
only against the Giants, Rockies, Dodgers, Diamondbacks and Padres,
but against the Mets and the Marlins. Born in New York and raised
in Miami, those were the first two teams A-Rod picked as his top
choices for new interleague series for the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a way to spice things up,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Until the lords of baseball get the message, interleague isn't
toast, it's just bland as oatmeal, which is a good food substitute
for dental patients but pablum for baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
