<SLUG> BC-BBO-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINER DEFENSE THROWS ONE AWAY TO GIANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Kingdome has two weeks of baseball life left in
it, but Sunday everyone acted as if they already had moved across
the street.
</P>
<P>
   For the first game this season, the local ballyard did not
permit a home run.
</P>
<P>
   For one of those rare occasions over the past two decades, a
Dome encounter was decided strictly by defense.
</P>
<P>
   And in one brief, excitable instance, the Mariners threw it all
away, losing 8-4 to the San Francisco Giants before a crowd of
33,500.
</P>
<P>
   Three and a half hours of finesse baseball came down to one Jose
Paniagua lob to second.
</P>
<P>
   In his hands, the reliever had a two-run, eighth-inning lead and
a rally-killing, double-play ball. When he let it go, everything
evaporated.
</P>
<P>
   Paniagua threw high and inside to Alex Rodriguez, pulling the
shortstop off base and bringing the first round of interleague play
to a demoralizing end for the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Home for just three games against the Giants, the M's head to
Detroit and Cleveland for eight games, starting the first of four
against the Tigers on Monday. Then it's home for the final six
games at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   Put to waste Sunday was another superb effort by rookie pitcher
John Halama. Ruined was an unusually patient hitting approach
against Giants ace Russ Ortiz.
</P>
<P>
   It was such a downer Manager Lou Piniella refused to speak about
it afterward, as did Paniagua.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens,'' Halama said, remembering a Class AAA playoff
game he botched with an errant throw. ``Paniagua is going to keep
getting called back out there. Hopefully, he can stay mentally
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Halama and Ortiz had no problems there. They matched each other
pitch for pitch. Both starters got through six innings, allowed
just five hits and struck out seven.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the game, the M's played on San Francisco's terms
and seemed to revel in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was definitely what a National League game feels like,''
said Butch Huskey, the Mariners' NL import in right field. ``It was
low scoring. It had a quick pace to it. Whoever gets the edge,
wins. They made the plays when they had to.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants felt lucky to leave town with two victories in three
tries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm certainly not sad leaving this place, but any time you
come in here and win two from this club in this building, you've
done a good job,'' Giants manager Dusty Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners took a 4-2 lead into the eighth inning, but quickly
got in trouble when Paniagua was touched for singles by Bill
Mueller and Armando Rios, the first two hitters.
</P>
<P>
   The reliever regrouped himself and got Jeff Kent on a called
strike. Against the next hitter, Stan Javier, Paniagua made the
pitch, but not thethrow.
</P>
<P>
   Javier bounced one right back to the mound, Paniagua wheeled to
second base and misfired. E-one.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez caught the ball, but couldn't drag his foot across the
bag. His timing off, the shortstop's throw couldn't nab Javier at
first either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went out and talked to him, and it seemed like everything
was fine,'' catcher Tom Lampkin said of his pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Paniagua, however, walked a pinch-hitting Barry Bonds on five
pitches to force in a run and draw the hook from Piniella. The
Mariners were still on top, 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   Closer Jose Mesa entered. He also made the right pitch. This
time, the catch didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   On his second offering, Mesa got J.T. Snow to send a foul ball
sailing toward the Seattle bullpen. Third baseman John Mabry gave
chase, as did left fielder Brian Hunter and Rodriguez, all
converging at the same time. Reliever Jordan Zimmerman, serving as
a bullpen sentry, scrambled to get out of their way.
</P>
<P>
   As Mabry reached for the ball, Rodriguez bumped him. Mabry's hat
was knocked off. The ball fell untouched. The official scorer ruled
no play. Another missed opportunity and more agony.
</P>
<P>
   Two pitches later, Snow grounded one between first and second to
drive in the tying and go-ahead runs, and the Mariners had given it
all away. The Giants would put together a five-run burst before all
the damage was done.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, the visitors got six outs in the inning. In any
ballpark, and especially in the Kingdome, that's nearly impossible
to overcome.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
