<SLUG> BC-BBO-MARINERS-NOTBEOOK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHEFFER NINTH ROOKIE PITCHER TO JOIN MARINERS STAFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Mixed among the plastic-coated name plates lining the
Mariner clubhouse Sunday was a piece of white tape fastened atop a
once spare cubicle, a name hastily scribbled on it with black felt
pen.
</P>
<P>
   Scheffer, 57.
</P>
<P>
   This would be Aaron Scheffer, the ninth rookie pitcher to join
the Mariner staff this season, a roster replacement for Rafael
Carmona and a sign of how rapidly things turn over in the big
leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Carmona was injured Saturday night, suffering a triceps strain
to his throwing arm while working in late-inning relief during a
15-11 defeat to the San Francisco Giants. He was placed on the
15-day disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Scheffer, a hard-throwing right-hander was recalled from Class
AAA Tacoma and joined the club midway through Sunday's contest
after traveling from Las Vegas. He pitched the ninth inning against
the Giants only hours after landing in Seattle and gave up a run on
two hits.
</P>
<P>
   Carmona felt ``a shock'' in the back of his right elbow on his
32nd pitch Saturday night and immediately was taken to the Mariner
training room. Sunday, he said his arm still ached, even when he
walked.
</P>
<P>
   The arm trouble was particularly disheartening for the Puerto
Rico native, who had rejoined the Mariners a month ago after a
one-year absence. He spent that time recovering from injuries,
including a broken right arm, suffered in a 1998 auto accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't give up,'' Carmona said. ``I have to keep working,
keep trying and get healthy again, and try to get back throwing the
way I was when I came up.''
</P>
<P>
   Scheffer, 23, started the season with Class AA New Haven. He
comes to the Mariners with a reputation as a control pitcher,
striking out 26 hitters and walking just five in 251/3 innings at
Tacoma. He was 1-2 with a 1.42 earned run average.
</P>
<P>
   ``He throws strikes,'' manager Lou Piniella said. ``He keeps the
ball down. Good sinker. Good changeup.''
</P>
<P>
   TAKING THE FIFTH: Frankie Rodriguez will make his second start
for the Mariners tomorrow at Detroit, even after pitching in relief
Saturday night. Luckily for him, his two-thirds of an inning
against the Giants required only three pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez (1-0) came to the Mariners as a reliever, claimed off
waivers May 26 from the Minnesota Twins' Class AAA entry, Salt Lake
City. He picked up a victory as a starter in Colorado last week,
allowing seven hits and three runs during a five-inning stint.
</P>
<P>
   In four big league seasons, Rodriguez has been predominantly a
starter, drawing 77 opening assignments. In 1996, he made 33 starts
for the Twins, going 13-14 with a 5.05 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to contribute,'' he said. ``Every day to be in the
big leagues is a plus. My heart is still saying I'm a starter, but
if their plans are to make me a reliever, that's fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, however, hasn't had much success against Detroit. In
10 games, his ERA is 7.99. Only the Texas Rangers have hit him
harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stink in Detroit,'' he said. ``I was checking the numbers.
I'll see if I can turn that around.''
</P>
<P>
   TIGER TALE: Six weeks after leaving the Motor City, Mariner left
fielder Brian Hunter returns to face his old club Monday. No
problem, says the former Tiger of two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I left on great terms,'' Hunter said. ``Both times I've been
traded, I left on good terms. I'm a pretty easy person.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing he doesn't miss is Tiger Stadium, scheduled for
demolition once Detroit's new ballpark opens next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the worst playing surface in baseball,'' Hunter said.
``The grass is so old. The drainage system is old. I wish they
could have strictly replaced the playing surface and kept the
stadium, because it's so traditional.''
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA POINT: Addressing Mariners at team chapel service Sunday
was Seahawk place-kicker Todd Peterson, a spiritually minded
individual who for five seasons has made this an annual outing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a unique situation because guys who come and speak to
them are not usually athletes,'' the kicker said. ``I can tell them
maybe I know what they're going through. It's a neat deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Peterson also questions his fellow pro athletes on their
commitment as role models. Are they speaking to school kids and
others because they want to, or because they have to?
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask them to consider, `Am I really trying to make a
difference?''' he said. ``That's a huge thing for us as athletes.
We have a platform. Other than politicians, we're listened to more
than anyone else in the country. I hope we are.''
</P>
<P>
   SICK LIST: M's catcher Dan Wilson was a late scratch Saturday
because of the flu. He showed up at the ballpark Sunday, but didn't
play for the second straight day, giving way to backup Tom Lampkin.
Wilson was on the flight for Detroit last night, and he's expected
to return to the lineup.
</P>
</TEXT>
