<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS AND COLANGELO KO'D
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Angels took one on the chin Sunday, their
3-1, 13-inning loss to the Arizona Diamondbacks just another in a
long line of setbacks due to a lack of offense. But it was nothing
like the blow rookie outfielder Mike Colangelo took in his
major-league debut before 29,176 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo, who joined the team Sunday after being called up from
Triple-A Edmonton the night before, was carried off the field after
a frightening collision with teammate Reggie Williams in
left-center field.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the looks of it, Colangelo was OK and back in the
clubhouse after a visit to UCI Medical Center. He was diagnosed
with a mild concussion and a sprained left thumb. X-rays on his
cervical spine and left hand were normal.
</P>
<P>
   The play took place in the top of the seventh inning when Steve
Finley hit a liner into the left-center field gap. Both Colangelo
and Williams raced for the ball and collided just as Williams made
the catch. Colangelo's head snapped back on impact and he lay
motionless on the grass until Angels trainers Rick Smith and Ned
Bergert arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he said, `You got it,' but he said `I got it,'''
Colangelo said. ``By that time I tried to get out of the way, but
it was too late.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a day Colangelo said he'll never forget. He singled in
his first major-league at-bat, drew a walk and also threw out a
baserunner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got my first hit, my first assist and I got knocked out,''
he said. ``It was an exciting day.... Reggie's a big guy. Running
full speed, it was like getting hit by a free safety.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me there should be some NFL scouts looking for me
now,'' Williams said. ``But when I play center field, what I do is
I go for the ball until I hear somebody call it. He said he didn't
think I could get to the ball. It was scary. I thought I heard
something snap.''
</P>
<P>
   But nothing snapped. Including the Angels' hitting slump. They
scored only one run on nine hits in 13 innings, wasting a solid
start by starter Omar Olivares (81/3 innings, 1 run, 6 hits).
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to start executing the offense,'' Angels manager
Terry Collins said. ``We did some things, we moved some guys
around. We just have got to get some hits.... We did the little
things, but we've got to get them in.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks started their winning rally with one out in the
13th with Kelly Stinnett's single off losing pitcher Mark Petkovsek
(5-2). Tony Womack got the big hit, driving a pitch into the
left-center field gap, scoring pinch-runner Hanley Frias from
first. Womack took third when shortstop Andy Sheets' relay throw
went all the way to the backstop.
</P>
<P>
   It cost the Angels a run, because Jay Bell followed with a
sacrifice fly to make it 3-1. It turned out it didn't matter,
because Gregg Olson set the Angels down in order in the bottom of
the 13th to earn his ninth save.
</P>
<P>
   Neither starting pitcher allowed a run through six innings, and
both were helped by the double-play ball. Olivares got double plays
in four of the first six innings and Diamondbacks starter Omar Daal
got three. By the end of the game, there were eight double plays in
the game, the most in the majors this season.
</P>
<P>
   Olivares tied a major-league record of hitting four batters in a
game. Angels teammate Steve Sparks also did it May 22. But Olivares
said it as a result of the Diamondbacks hitters' approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pitching inside because most of them were looking for my
sinker and diving out over the plate,'' Olivares said. ``The balls
were not really that far inside, but it's hard to get out of the
way when you're diving over the plate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
