<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3986 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBC-RICE-OSU-HNS &LR;      06-14 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-RICE-OSU-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NEAL FARMER  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
OMAHA, Neb. _ Early on, it looked like it would be 0-2 and barbecue
for the Rice Owls.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the College World Series, a team that loses two games is
eliminated and goes home, usually to a team barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   But you can hold the sauce for now.
</P>
<P>
   Overcoming a shaky start from pitcher Kenny Baugh, the Owls beat
Oklahoma State 7-2 at Rosenblatt Stadium on Sunday night, surviving
to play another day.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's doubleheader _ Miami beat Alabama 8-1 in a
winners-bracket opener _ drew 24,859, setting a CWS session
attendance record.
</P>
<P>
   With its win, Rice upped its school-record victory total to 59 _
against 14 losses _ and moved on to another elimination game
against Alabama at 2:30 p.m. Tuesday. Oklahoma State finished
46-21.
</P>
<P>
   Baugh struggled with his location until the fourth inning, then
settled in and systematically cut the Cowboys down. In the first
two innings, he overcame a pair of bases-loaded, none-out
predicaments, allowing no runners to score.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first couple of innings, I had a little adrenaline going _
maybe a little too much,'' Baugh said. ``I was short-arming
everything. But once I settled down, I was OK. I basically settled
down after I got out of those jams. I was more in the zone and
challenged the hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   Baugh (12-2) lasted 7 innings, allowing nine hits and two earned
runs while walking four and striking out five. He threw 130
pitches, his last deposited as a solo homer by Toby Rhodes to draw
OSU within 6-2. Jeff Nichols threw 1 scoreless innings of relief to
close the Cowboys out.
</P>
<P>
   Baugh gave up back-to-back singles and a walk to start the game.
But he struck out Josh Holliday and Lamont Matthews before Jay
McCullough grounded out to end the OSU first.
</P>
<P>
   Rice catcher Zane Curry said Baugh was throwing better than it
looked.
</P>
<P>
   ``His pitches weren't that far off,'' Curry said. ``I thought it
showed his courage to come back.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had the heart of their order coming up. The bases were
loaded, and those guys were wanting to hit a two-run double or a
grand slam. So Kenny realized that if he could throw a good
changeup, they weren't going to sniff it. So with the two hitters
he struck out, he probably threw about 80 percent changeups. They
didn't adjust. I thought that showed Kenny's mental toughness.''
</P>
<P>
   Baugh ran into more trouble in the second, however. This time, a
walk preceded back-to-back singles that filled the bases again. But
third baseman Matt Fox, atoning for Friday's three-error
performance in an 8-4 loss to Miami, turned in a superb defensive
play.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Gautreaux slapped a grounder to Fox, who stepped on third
base for a forceout, then threw a perfect strike home to Curry for
a double play. Baugh then induced Kevin Lucas to fly out to center
to end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Wayne Graham had considered not starting Fox but was glad
he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put his heart back in the game,'' Graham said. ``I believe
in his heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Baugh's good fortune continued in the third when OSU's Billy
Gasparino made full contact with a fastball for an apparent home
run to left field. But the ball was hit into a driving wind, which
held it up at the warning track, and with his back against the wall
Charles Williams made the catch.
</P>
<P>
   Curry started the Owls' scoring by doubling home Justin Berg in
the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   OSU tied the game at 1 in the fourth. Chris Becerra slugged a
one-out double and scored three batters later on a bad-hop single
by Gautreuax that bounced over the head of Rice second baseman
Brett Smith.
</P>
<P>
   It looked as if the Cowboys would get another run in the inning
when Lucas hit a grounder deep in the hole at shortstop. But Damon
Thames made a major-league stab of the ball, then twisted and threw
out Gautreaux at second for an inning-ending force play. Thames'
effort drew a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   The Owls regained the lead with two unearned runs in the fifth,
which started with Gasparino booting Fox's grounder to short.
Williams tripled Fox home, and two outs later, a Will Ford bunt
scored Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Rice added three more runs in the seventh to break the game
open, and Jason Gray hit his team-leading 20th homer, a solo shot,
in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Thames was just happy the Owls didn't repeat their 0-2 CWS
performance of 1997, the year they made their only previous trip
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you start 0-4 in Omaha, some people will begin to wonder
how good you are,'' Thames said. ``Now we just have to keep this
thing going because if you lose, you go home. We can still win this
thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
