<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSY DEBUT FOR ANGELS ROOKIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ During batting practice Sunday afternoon, a group of
Little Leaguers chanted the names of their favorite Angels players
as they took their turns in the cage. When new Angel Mike Colangelo
stepped in, there was a pause.
</P>
<P>
   Then they yelled: ``No.10! No.10! No.10!''
</P>
<P>
   Those in the crowd weren't the only ones who didn't know
Colangelo, who was called up after Saturday's game and was in the
starting lineup Sunday, hitting leadoff and playing left field.
</P>
<P>
   Many Angels players and coaches met Colangelo, 22, for the first
time Sunday. After spending most of the 1998 season at Single-A
Lake Elsinore, he spent spring training in minor-league camp and
opened the season at Double-A Erie.
</P>
<P>
   In 28 games at Erie, he hit .339 and was promoted to Triple-A
Edmonton on May 12. He hit .362 there in 26 games, and the next
thing he knew he was in the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I'd be here this fast,'' he said. ``I hope
everything works out. I came here today and the first day I'm in
there hitting leadoff. That's fine. I'm excited to be in the
lineup. I have to get on base so the big guys can drive me in.''
</P>
<P>
   He did his job Sunday, hitting a line-drive single to center in
his first major league at-bat, then drawing a walk his second time
up. He also got an assist when Andy Fox tried to tag up from first
on a fly ball to Colangelo, who threw Fox out at second.
</P>
<P>
   The game, though, ended abruptly for Colangelo after a collision
with center fielder Reggie Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo played 112 minor-league games before his promotion to
the majors. By comparison, Troy Glaus played in 109 and Darin
Erstad played in 88.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of confidence in myself,'' Colangelo said before
the game. ``I just put some good numbers together and they moved me
up quickly. Hopefully, I'll keep hitting.''
</P>
<P>
   Before being injured, Colangelo, a right-handed hitter, was
slated to platoon in left field with left-handed hitting Orlando
Palmeiro. With a lefty (Omar Daal) pitching for Arizona on Sunday,
Colangelo didn't have time to blend in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy's been swinging the bat good,'' said manager Terry
Collins. ``We might as well have him in there while he's hot.''
</P>
<P>
   The power's with Luke: Matt Luke also joined the club Sunday,
being called up from Edmonton after just six games there, where he
hit .429 (9 for 21) with five homers and 15 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   He started the spring with the Angels, but a back strain _
suffered during offseason weight-lifting _ forced him to the
disabled list for 2{ months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had to be patient about it,'' Luke said. ``It was a
situation where it didn't heal as fast as I wanted it do. But
finally my activity increased, I got some games at extended spring
and each day it felt a little better.''
</P>
<P>
   Luke wasted no time showing the Angels he was ready for the big
leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say I was surprised, but I was pleased with how my
body responded on a day-to-day basis,'' Luke said. ``It's something
I haven't done in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins said Luke will get a start in right field Wednesday in
Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Also: Garret Anderson, who had started all 61 games this season
in center field, was not in the starting lineup. Williams started
in place of Anderson, who is hitless in his past 16 at-bats.
Anderson, though, entered the game in the eighth inning as a pinch
runner and stayed in the game.... Arizona's Steve Finley singled
with one out in the ninth inning, his 1,500th major-league hit...
The Angels are off today and on Tuesday begin a nine-game road trip
to Toronto, New York and Seattle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
