   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-FUNDFRAISING _ As campaign finance legislation
languishes, Congress has gone on an all-out fund-raising binge
driven by the battle for control of the House. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-GUN-POLITICS _ A troika of New York area Democrats _ Nita
Lowey, Rosa De Lauro and Carolyn McCarthy _ have been leading the
Democratic charge in the House for gun control, and it's no
accident that they're all women. It is a strategy, blessed by party
leaders, that reflects an attempt to change the gun debate into an
issue of child safety and the belief that gun control advocacy will
sew up support for Democrats among women in the crucial elections
of 2000. Internal party polls show that women are caring more and
more about gun safety; this at a time when Al Gore's numbers among
women are not great. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   DEECEE-POLITICS _ The pragmatic and cautious mayor of
Washington, Anthony Williams, is a stark contrast to the legacy of
ethical blunders from the previous administration here; but new
campaign finance charges may tarnish his squeaky-clean image.
</P>
<P>
   ICKES-POLITICS-PROFILE _ A look at the first lady's campaign
honcho, Harold Ickes.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT16) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTERS-BIOLOGY (San Francisco) _ In a world where computers
were once casual and isolated tools, but are today increasingly the
very fabric of modern business life, computer researchers say they
are detecting an ominous trend toward programs that mimic viruses
and pestilence in the physical world. Like biological diseases,
which exploit the most basic mechanism of life: the power of DNA to
replicate itself, the subculture of modern virus writing is now
manipulating that same power within the world of interconnected
computers. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphics have been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   FALLING-TV-STARS (Undated) _ Where Have All the Big Stars Gone?
The great national television star of the past _ Milton Berle,
Lucille Ball, Ed Sullivan, Mary Tyler Moore, Bill Cosby, Jerry
Seinfeld _ has given way to clusters of little, lesser stars. Why?
By Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic showing stars' peak share of TV audience has
been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SUBSCRIPTIONS-SWEEPSTAKES (Undated) _ The crackdown on phony
sweepstakes mailings is a great blow for justice but it's lousy for
the magazine industry. The mailings were a key way to sell
subscriptions. Now a slew of magazines are reporting sharp declines
in renewals. By Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   PRIVACY-LAWSUIT (Washington) _ A Federal Trade Commission
lawsuit against a James J. Rapp, a private investigator, is being
billed by both sides as a landmark case, and Rapp is receiving
significant support from a coalition of other information brokers
and debt collectors, who see the government's action as a huge
threat to their livelihood. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   POWERS-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Austin Powers, the ludicrously
lascivious film character played by the comedian Mike Meyers in
``The Spy Who Shagged Me,'' has turned up in all sorts of
advertisements lately. Why are so many marketers so willing to go
along with such an overtly risque premise? By Patricia Winters
Lauro.
</P>
<P>
   METROWERKS-GALANOS (Undated) _ Profile of Greg Galanos and
Metrowerks, a company in the software ``tools'' business that has
deftly carved out a niche in which it seems to be successfully
operating below Microsoft's radar. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   ECOMMERCE-SPEED (Undated) _ Ecommerce companies are looking at
ways of alleviating the often interminable wait for a Web page to
show up on a computer screen. By Bob Tedeschi.
</P>
<P>
   CABLE-CONVENTION (Undated) _ The National Cable Television
Convention, which opens on Monday in Chicago, seems to be more
about Internet access than cable TV this year. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CARMINA-BURANA (Undated) _ Suddenly, Carmina Burana is
everywhere. By Ann Powers.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN-POWERS (Hollywood) _ How Austin Powers rose from sleeper
to blockbuster. By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   REVISIONS (Undated) _ Treating two recent recordings as case
studies in interpretation and composition. By Margo Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   OZZFEST-MUSIC-REVIEW (Holmdel, N.J.) _ Basic black and power
chords are constants in heavy metal, and there was plenty of each
at Ozzfest, the 16-band, 11-hour concert at the PNC Arts Center. By
Jon Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   ENIAC-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Christopher Lehmann-Haupt reviews
``Eniac: The Triumph and Tragedies of the World's First Computer,''
by Scott McCartney (Walker Books).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN (Washington) _ William Safire on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports column on the U.S. Open.
By Dave Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports column on the Knicks' Kurt
Thomas. By William C. Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NYT News Service &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
