<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4019 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BB-REDSOX-METS-BOS &LR;      06-14 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BB-REDSOX-METS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX AT LOSS FOR REASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Crisis? Mark Portugal, who was ready to turn in his
uniform for good just a couple of weeks ago, can tell you about a
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   And this, he said after the Red Sox lost, 5-4, Sunday to the New
York Mets for their seventh loss in their last eight games, doesn't
qualify.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's wondering why we're not playing that well,'' said
Portugal, thrown back in the rotation Sunday because Bret
Saberhagen cut his foot open on broken glass. ``You can't worry
about a two-week stretch in the middle of June in a 162-game
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, after a 10-day span against National League opponents in
which the Sox resembled strangers in a strange land, it wouldn't be
surprising to see them greet the Minnesota Twins with flowers and
chocolates Monday night on Yawkey Way. Familiarity may breed
contempt, but the Sox are hoping that returning home for a visit
from some American League cousins might brew a few wins, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the time to push the panic button,'' said Nomar
Garciaparra, who was given the day off until he entered the game in
the eighth as part of a double-switch, leading to his leadoff
double in the ninth that was wasted when the next three hitters
went down in order to Mets reliever Turk Wendell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still playing good baseball,'' Garciaparra said. ``The
thing that hurt us was last weekend, when we played Atlanta and
easily could have won all three of those games, but they came back
to beat us (twice). And here, we came back and won in extra innings
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pitching well, we're fielding well. We're just not
clicking. We've got to bring it back together, the way we did when
we were winning.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Sox are not doing is hitting. In the nine games against
the Braves, Expos, and Mets, who won Sunday behind 40-year-old Orel
Hershiser, the Sox batted just .209 and hit just five home runs,
including Troy O'Leary's 12th of the season Sunday. They've scored
just 15 runs in their last six games, with Sunday's four their
high-water mark in that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Trot Nixon struck out three times Sunday _ the last time
with two on and two out in the eighth _ after fanning just once in
his last nine games. Nixon also made an off-target throw to the
plate in the fifth when he had a chance to make a play on Hershiser
as he scored the Mets' third run of the inning. Nixon singled in
the seventh and scored the Sox' final run on Jason Varitek's
sacrifice fly, but he's hitting .125 (3 for 24) in his last eight
games, with one RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got nothing to say today,'' he commented as he made his
departure from the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   He's hardly alone, of course. Veteran Mike Stanley, who walked
as a pinch hitter in the seventh, is hitless in his last 21
at-bats. Jose Offerman, who hit a two-out triple in the fifth but
was stranded, had two hits in 12 at-bats here. Garciaparra was 2
for 11, Brian Daubach 2 for 9.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox were 1 for 13 with runners in scoring position Sunday _
O'Leary's fourth-inning RBI double was the only hit _ and they were
just 5 for 36 (.139) in the three-game set.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, meanwhile, spotted the Sox a 1-0 lead before five
straight hits with two out in the fifth produced three runs off
Portugal. The string began with a home run by the Hawaiian hammer,
Benny Agbayani, who was as obscure as the Belleville Basher,
Daubach, with whom he played in the Mets' system. Agbayani already
has 10 home runs, nine in his last 14 starts.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal was lifted after a leadoff double in the sixth by Mike
Piazza, who scored ahead of Brian McRae's two-run home run off Jim
Corsi. The Mets have hit 80 home runs this season, 51 in their last
34 games. The Sox, by contrast, have 58 home runs total.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the kind of team that thrives on momentum,'' Portugal
said. ``One hit gets it going for them, and it tends to snowball.
I've got to shut them down and avoid the big inning, and I didn't
do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, who loaded the bases with no out in the seventh, scored
twice on a fielder's choice and Varitek's sacrifice fly before Mets
reliever Dennis Cook struck out John Valentin to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox put the tying run on with one out in the eighth when
O'Leary singled for his third hit of the game. But Damon Buford,
trying to bunt for a hit, was called out when the ball bounced up
and hit him. Plate umpire Greg Bonin ruled Buford out on
interference, and he refused to listen to Jimy Williams's
entreaties to ask third base umpire Ed Rapuano whether Buford was
indeed out of the batter's box when the ball hit him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell, yes, I was in the box,'' Buford said after watching TV
replays. ``Find out how many times a year that play is called. Find
out how many times it's called right.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big play at a big time of the game. I was bunting for
a hit, but even if he threw me out, I knew we'd get a runner to
second. But that's the way things are going for us right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Williams as he prepared for the trip home, ``Hang with
us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-99 0211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990614.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 02:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4020 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STANLEYCUP-BOS &LR;      06-14 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STANLEY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUFFALO NOT TAKING BEST SHOT 
</HEADLINE>
 CUP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO _ If they're going to win the Cup, the Sabres have to
hope that Saturday night was just a hicCup.
</P>
<P>
   If it proves to be worse than that, then everyone here on the
shores of Lake Erie knows the drill. Disappointment is a cottage
industry in this town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, if you were here through the days when the Bills
reached the Super Bowl,'' mused Rob Ray, the Sabres' resident tough
guy who is now finishing up his 10th season, ``there was a lot of
excitement built into it. When they were unsuccessful, it was a
major letdown for the city. So you feel the pressure of winning for
yourselves, but also for everyone else as you walk down the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something you can't avoid, because they won't let you
avoid it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres looked and played Game 3 of the Stanely Cup final as
if they were skating through the shards of so many million
shattered souls. In the end, the scoreboard showed a 2-1 loss to
the Dallas Stars, but it was one of the most lopsided one-goal
games in Stanley Cup history. Buffalo managed only 12 shots _ one
every five minutes _ equaling the dirty dozen the Bruins so feebly
cobbled together in their 4-2 loss to the Oilers in Game 2 in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were the better team,'' Sabres coach Lindy Ruff said
Sunday, less than 24 hours after the crushing defeat that dropped
his club into a 2-1 deficit in the best-of-seven series. ``I'm not
going to sugarcoat it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars weren't so dominating as they were suffocating. In
fact, if not for Joe Nieuwendyk's dynamic touch around the net, the
Stars, as near-perfect as they were over two-thirds of the ice,
still could have lost. That, of course, is what happens when you're
up against Dominik Hasek in the Buffalo net.
</P>
<P>
   But there were factors that contributed to Dallas's own
goal-scoring deficiencies: (1) Mike Modano playing with an
impaired, braced wrist, which was injected with a painkiller before
the game, and (2) the loss of Brett Hull, who left after three
shifts in the first period, sidelined by a nagging groin strain.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the 32-year-old Nieuwendyk stands with one skate
up on the Conn Smythe podium. He came up with the 1-1 equalizer
late in the second period, sweeping home a backhander as he was
knocked down in the slot after first being turned back by Hasek on
a forehander. For the winner, set up perfectly by a Jamie
Langenbrunner pirouette and feed, he painted the top right corner
with a nasty roof shot.
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk's winner makes you wonder why coaches spend so much
time on 2-on-1 and 3-on-2 shooting drills. Clear shots off the rush
are so rarely available in today's game. But there are thousands
(no exaggeration) of opportunities from in tight, shots that
develop from the grit it takes to get the puck in the middle, or
come off rebounds, off mistakes. So few forwards can convert from
tight quarters, especially now that netminders, Hasek the best of
them all, are so adept at taking away the bottom half of the net.
Park a guy at the top of the crease, put a defenseman on his back,
and don't let him leave the ice until he pops home at least one
backhander and one forehander. Top-of-the-crease roof shots, sadly,
have gone the way of the hip check and the hoop game's two-handed
set shot.
</P>
<P>
   By periods, the Sabres' shot total read 3-6-3. While landing
only 12 on net, they saw 12 other attempts go wide and 19 get
blocked by Dallas forwards or defensemen. Derian Hatcher and Guy
Carbonneau led all Dallas shot blockers with three apiece. By
contrast, 29 Dallas shots reached the net, while four more were off
the mark and 14 were blocked.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo's attack _ a stretch of the word at best _ fell apart in
two places: (1) in the neutral zone, where the Stars continually
cut off passes or rubbed out puckcarriers, and (2) across the blue
line, where the Sabres, even on power plays, often wildly missed
the net. They never got around to testing Eddie Belfour in the
Dallas net.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres simply played too much like a team that was scared to
lose, their game timid and unsure _ not at all like the club that
confidently mashed its way through the likes of Ottawa, Boston, and
Toronto in the first three rounds. Where was their trademark speed?
Where was the irrepressible youth that was going to run rings
around the aging oak trees in the Dallas lineup?
</P>
<P>
   ``We hoped youth and speed would be on our side,'' said Ruff,
who continually changed his line combinations, looking for a spark
that never developed. ``But maybe cagey veterans know how to
conserve energy.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the Sabres who looked tired and out of synch. The Dallas
attack lacked flow, too, but showed far better stamina and
strength. Modano's shooting was off? So what. Hull checked out
early? Gee. The Stars just kept rolling, patiently and with
purpose. The Sabres, meanwhile, turned into the corkscrew that
couldn't shake itself from the cork.
</P>
<P>
   Monday is another day of rest before Game 4. The Sabres will use
their practice time to rearrange their parts, try to breath new
life into their power play (0 for 8 in Game 3), and regain that
enthusiasm that has been their trademark for almost two months now.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars, the wise and low-key graybeards, will stretch and
limber up, conserve their energy, dance around the questions about
Modano's wrist and Hull's groin. Even without their best guns, and
even with age allegedly conspiring against them, the Stars had what
it took to be a better defensive club than the Sabres. Here in a
city where the leading industries are worry and disappointment,
that could be a sign that the warehouse of woe (Scott Norwood is
the night watchman) is about to throw open its doors once more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
