<SLUG> BC-BB-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS CAN'T MANAGE TO FIND RED SOX ANSWER 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He's tried just about everything. Sunday Boston
manager Jimy Williams rested his best player for eight innings, but
still the Sox could not win. And Jimy couldn't even get himself
thrown out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The sad Sunday score was Mets, 5-4, giving Boston seven losses
in eight games, eight in 11 games, and a 2-7 record against the
National League East. A 1-5 trip through Montreal and New York saw
the Sox fall from first, probably for good. En route, they lost a
couple of quality pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   There's not a whole lot else Jimy can do. He can recommend no
beach volleyball parties at the homes of Pedro Martinez or Nomar
Garciaparra, but he can't be expected to keep winning with the
present roster.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, it's time for Dan Duquette to make a call to the New
York City water meter inspection department.
</P>
<P>
   The manager won't complain, but when he's behind closed doors _
crooning in that Fenway shower he so loves _ Jimy's got to be
singing, ``Please Mr. Statman, look and see. Is there a hitter for
me?''
</P>
<P>
   Don't wait for Williams to say anything in public regarding his
anemic lineup. Not his way. In his Rainman/Dana Carvey-as-George
Bushspeak, he'll keep saying all the positive things that Duquette
and some of the fans want to hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing good, we're just not winning . . . Need a few
more balls to fall in . . . A few more hits with two outs . . . Not
a panic situation . . . 2-7, but in every one of 'em to my
recollection, except for late in Montreal . . . Play the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still say it's pitching and defense . . . Sometimes you just
hit a bump in the road. Maybe we just had our bump in the road
against National League teams . . . Go home and get it going.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten minutes to Wapner.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, the schedule calls for the Triple-A-in-disguise
Minnesota Twins at Fenway Monday night. And Pedro Tuesday.
Meanwhile, it would be nice if the Duke could give his manager some
help in the form of an outfielder who can hit. If Mike Gimbel can't
come up with another Dwayne Hosey, maybe it's time to try one of
the Pawtucket flashes. Michael Coleman is the hot name of the hour.
</P>
<P>
   When Jimy was asked if it was time to ``go get somebody,'' he
answered, ``I haven't really thought about that. I think we have
good hitters here, I really do. If anything, they're probably
trying too hard (hello, Trot Nixon). But they can hit. They're
gonna hit.''
</P>
<P>
   After Saturday's loss, Jimy said, ``What can I do? Hell, I
couldn't hit when I played. I'm not going to hit the pitcher
eighth.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday he rested Nomar until the eighth. He hit Jason Varitek
second and Brian Daubach cleanup. He double-switched and tried a
raft of pinch hitters and relievers. He even made a noble effort to
get tossed.
</P>
<P>
   Williams bolted from the dugout in the eighth when Damon Buford
was called out for running into his own bunted ball. Jimy argued
long and hard with plate umpire Greg Bonin. He gave us the
arms-folded routine. He gestured. He started to leave, turned
around, and came back. But Bonin was patient and never tossed the
Sox manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``National League umpires make quick calls,'' said Jimy. ``There
really isn't a batter's box there. It's gone. The guy called a good
game and he's a good umpire, but I thought he might ask the third
base umpire if he saw it. I always thought that was the bottom
line. If somebody has an angle you make sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Third base ump Ed Rapuano never arrived to give his version of
events, but crew chief Frank Pulli came in from second base to tell
Jimy to go back to his dugout.
</P>
<P>
   When Williams was asked, ``Did Pulli give you anything?'' the
manager replied, ``About 30 seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a joke, folks. Jimy has a birchbark-dry sense of humor,
and it's nice to see he could still have a little fun after such an
arduous road trip.
</P>
<P>
   Had Williams been thrown out of the game, he could have mimed
the nitwit antics of Mets manager Bobby Valentine and come back to
the dugout with a phony mustache and glasses. But Jimy's not a
slapstick guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anything about that,'' he answered when the
Valentine Groucho getup was suggested. ``I'm just trying to win a
game.''
</P>
<P>
   There are Red Sox managers who could have used a disguise when
they worked in Boston. Life certainly would have been easier for
Don Zimmer if he'd been behind an iron mask in 1979 and '80.
</P>
<P>
   Not Jimy. Wouldn't be prudent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
