<HEADER>
A4023 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-US-ARGENTINA-BOS &LR;      06-14 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-US-ARGENTINA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS UPLIFTED BY FRIENDLY FINISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Yanquis said they weren't going to make a big
thing of it. This was just a Sunday afternoon friendly between two
teams on the build. And yet US 1, Argentina 0 _ anytime, anywhere _
is certainly worth popping open a jeroboam of Dom Perignon.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, it's a great win,'' US men's soccer coach Bruce Arena
declared Sunday, after the Revolution's Joe-Max Moore stunned the
world's seventh-ranked squad with a goal two minutes from time
before 40,119 at RFK Stadium. ``Does this mean we're back in the
right direction? Yes. But it doesn't say a whole lot more than
that. We're not going to blow it out of proportion.''
</P>
<P>
   What they'll do with it down in Buenos Aires is another matter.
Argentina had waited four years to avenge the humiliating 3-0
whipsong that the Americans laid on them at the Copa America at
Paysandu in next-door Uruguay. And even though they were playing
with only three of their World Cup regulars (Diego Simeone, Roberto
Ayala, and Javier Zanetti), the Pale Blues figured they could
handle a US squad that finished 32d out of 32 in France last summer
and is under reconstruction itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who wears a jersey for Argentina is a great player,''
said Arena, who is still looking for 20 good men to bring to next
month's FIFA Confederations Cup in Mexico, where the US must face
Brazil and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Americans are 4-1-2 since he took over for Steve
Sampson last October, Arena concedes that they're nowhere near a
world-class side and won't be until the millennium. ``We are a year
away from being a pretty good national team,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Only four of the men who started the World Cup match with
Germany were in uniform Sunday. Some have moved on, some weren't
available, and some may never be called again. Arena's mission is
to run as many fresh faces through the revolving door as he can
before Cup qualifying starts anew in the fall of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   He's already seen 40 players since November and has plugged a
bunch of them, ready or not, into the lineup for friendlies. Sunday
the US, which hadn't played in three months, had four starters
(midfielders Tony Sanneh, Chris Armas, and Eddie Lewis and defender
C.J. Brown) with seven or fewer caps.
</P>
<P>
   That made for some harrowing moments in the American half and
required acrobatic heroics by keeper Kasey Keller, who blocked a
penalty kick by Gustavo Lopez five minutes before intermission and
later swatted away point-blankers by Hugo Ibarra and Christian
Gonzalez to keep his mates alive. ``What can you say?'' shrugged
Arena. ``He doesn't stop that penalty kick, we don't end up winning
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   As the day wore on and the Pale Blues kept dashing into the
American kitchen, nil-nil was looking like a lovely result for the
hosts. ``There were some very obvious missed opportunities,''
moaned Argentine coach Marcelo Bielsa, whose side yielded a
77th-minute goal to Mexico on Wednesday and had to settle for a 2-2
draw in Chicago. ``We did not capitalize on the 13 goals we could
have had. The way we played, we deserved this result.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Yanks were master finishers themselves. Cobi Jones
put a ball inches wide in the 13th minute, Stewart missed a Sanneh
cross in the 37th, Claudio Reyna misfired from dead-on in the 43d,
and Sanneh bopped a header off the crossbar in the 63d.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Arena had sent in Moore, who had a hall pass to skip
Sunday's Revolution-Miami match at Foxborough. ``Go in and make a
difference,'' Arena told him.
</P>
<P>
   Moore waited until the 88th minute, when both sides seemed
resigned to a scoreless draw. Then he darted into the area and
collected a lovely backheel pass from Stewart. ``He played it right
into my stride,'' said Moore. ``I just struck the ball hard and
hoped it was on goal.''
</P>
<P>
   It was decidedly more than that _ the ball was rifled and roofed
beyond keeper German Burgos's outstretched right hand, and
Argentina was too stunned to answer before time ran out. ``Very
timely,'' Moore said. ``Very nice.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, so it wasn't as big as Paysandu, which has become a curse
word across the pampas. And the US will be facing a buzz saw when
they play the return match down there next winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next time,'' said Simeone, ``we have to play at the level
Argentina is capable of playing.'' But this time, the Yanquis will
take the W and move on _ and maybe crack open a bottle of bubbly on
the way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
