<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-FUSION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION PROVE GOOD TO LAST SHOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Revolution made things difficult for
both themselves and the Miami Fusion Sunday. But they survived a
frantic finish that produced a 3-3 tie in regulation time, then won
the shootout to move into a tie for third place with Tampa Bay in
the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   This was a game in which some of the Revolution's most
dependable players struggled and reserves such as Jamar Beasley,
Jeff Causey, Edwin Gorter, Paul Keegan, and Johnny Torres rallied
the team.
</P>
<P>
   Even player-coach Walter Zenga faltered, scuffing a clearance
which set up a Diego Serna goal to give Miami a 3-2 lead. But the
Revolution displayed resiliency, tying the score when Edwin Gorter
converted a Torres cross with three minutes left in a 52-minute
second half. The Revolution have 12 points in 12 games, and the
Fusion remain in last place with 8 points in 15 games. It was New
England's third straight win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are shooting ourselves in the foot too many times, giving
other teams tap-in goals from 6 to 8 yards in front of the goal,''
Revolution midfielder John Harkes said. ``We made some sloppy
mistakes, committed some silly fouls on top of the box, and our
passing was not as good as it was against Chicago (a 2-0 win).
We're happy with the win, even though it came in a shootout. Deep
down, we know we lost 2 points, but the main thing is we have a
winning record.
</P>
<P>
   ``We showed a lot of character, and that is important. You have
to be able to fight through some games. We've been talking about
how Manchester United won the Champions League when their
substitutes came in and changed the game within three or four
minutes. And that is what our substitutes did in this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Torres, starting only because Joe-Max Moore was playing for the
US national team, had his most productive game since joining the
Revolution last year. He placed a left-footed shot off the inside
of the far post after Giovanni Savarese had headed on a Zenga punt
in the 20th minute. Torres converted a penalty kick after Beasley
had been fouled by Arley Palacios to tie the score, 2-2, in the
85th minute. And, after Keegan had battled to retain possession,
Torres assisted on Gorter's goal.
</P>
<P>
   But the Revolution failed to click for long periods of time and
seemed destined to lose after Henry Gutierrez converted a free kick
in the 24th minute, and Tyrone Marshall gave Miami a 2-1 advantage
in the 64th minute.
</P>
<P>
   The Fusion seemed more athletic, more resourceful, and more
dangerous in attack with Diego Serna and Welton. The Revolution,
though, retained their composure even after committing crucial
errors and while being out of synchronization.
</P>
<P>
   After Marshall's goal, the Revolution became desperate. They
pressed forward in an attempt to tie the score, leaving Zenga
stranded twice against Serna. But Zenga stopped Serna both times.
</P>
<P>
   The Fusion paid for those failures as Gorter lofted a long lead
pass to Beasley on the left. Beasley, at 19 the team's youngest
player, faked past Arley Palacios, went to the end line and started
toward goal. Palacios took him down from behind and referee Alberto
Giordano called the penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Mike Burns, Gorter, and Harkes designated Torres for the
kick. And Torres, who had scored only three goals in 30 previous
MLS games, sent the shot past goalkeeper Jeff Cassar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great the veterans had confidence in me to step up and
take the penalty kick,'' Torres said. ``I had retrieved the ball
and was going to give it to one of the veterans to take.''
</P>
<P>
   But Torres will likely return to the bench when Moore returns
for the game at Columbus Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of whether I'm playing or not, I'll go out and work
in practice and show heart and fight every time I go in the game,''
Torres said. ``I'm a new player but I'm not new to soccer. I know
there are times when you score and times when you don't, but you
have to keep plugging away.''
</P>
<P>
   The game was nearly decided in the final seconds, when former
Revolution striker Tony Kuhn made an excellent turn and fired a
shot just under the bar from 18 yards. But Causey, who had replaced
Zenga only seconds before, tipped the shot over the bar to preserve
the tie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
