<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-GORTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORTER SHOWS HE'S FINISHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Edwin Gorter proved he was the master of
perfect timing Sunday for the Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   With 1:51 remaining in the match, Gorter took a feed from Johnny
Torres and smacked the ball into the goal to lift New England into
a 3-3 tie with the Miami Fusion.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the shootout, Gorter took the Revolution's fourth shot
and once again beat Fusion netminder Jeff Cassar, giving New
England an insurmountable 3-1 shootout edge and a 4-3 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Given his production, why isn't Gorter starting more
consistently? After missing two games while serving a suspension
and three others with injuries, he has been in the lineup for five
of the Revolution's last seven games. But Gorter didn't get into
Sunday's game until the 61st minute, subbing for Jair.
</P>
<P>
   Coach-goalkeeper Walter Zenga doesn't talk to the media about an
individual's playing time, but Gorter has his opinion. ``If I was
the coach, I would be on the field, but I'm not the coach,'' said
the 35-year-old, who had seven goals and seven assists last season
when he started every game but one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard,'' added Gorter. ``It's not easy at all. You want to
be a part of the team, especially the starting 11. That's all you
work for during the week. I'm ready for that, but I guess they
don't believe in me.''
</P>
<P>
   On Gorter's first goal, Torres was on the left side and sent a
crossing pass to Gorter. The kick went into the left side of the
net.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit it OK but it wasn't an unbelievable goal,'' said Gorter.
``Who knows, in two or three weeks, you don't remember the goal. I
don't believe in ugly goals. A goal is a goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Sunday, Gorter had been 0 for 4 in shootout attempts this
season. ``I always miss, normally,'' he said. ``I should go to the
church and light a candle. That's the first of four; that's bad for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Having seen Cassar guard the previous three shootout attempts,
Gorter had some idea what the Fusion goalkeeper might try. ``That's
good when you're the fourth or the fifth shooter,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It's been six weeks, Gorter said, since he's attempted a
shootout-type shot in practice. ``It's different in practice,'' he
said. ``There's nobody there, no 20,000 in the stands.''
</P>
<P>
   Six goals in regulation weren't a bad treat for the spectators.
``You look at the whole 90 minutes and you see that you're lucky to
get a couple in the second half _ a tie was the best result,''
Gorter said. ``For the people in the stands, they saw a great game.
It was in the afternoon, the sun was shining, there's 20,000, and
they see six goals. That's excitement.''
</P>
<P>
   It was exciting enough to make Gorter temporarily forget the
frustration of not starting. ``When you're sitting on the bench,
you're not happy with yourself,'' he said. ``But if the game ends
like this, it's something special.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
