<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 02:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4030 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLEEP-AZR &LR;      06-14 1257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLEEP-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHER'S CREDIBILITY KEY IN MURDER DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ When jurors in the Scott Falater murder trial begin
deliberations later this month, they will wrestle with a defense
scenario that defies common sense:
</P>
<P>
   A man stabs his wife 44 times in his sleep, and, still sleeping,
drags her into the pool and holds her head under water.
</P>
<P>
   The bloody, protracted mayhem of Falater's admitted attack
weighs heavily against the defense. But before jurors can reach a
verdict on Falater, they must reach a verdict on Dr. Roger
Broughton, a heavyweight in the study of sleepwalking.
</P>
<P>
   Is Broughton a credible scientist or an errant egghead?
</P>
<P>
   Broughton is the Canadian physician, neurology professor and
sleep-disorders researcher who last week testified that
sleepwalking ``is by far the most probable'' explanation of
Falater's admitted killing of his wife in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Broughton, who came to the trial with the resume of an academic
superstar and an easygoing manner, is the star witness for the
defense against the state's charge that Falater committed
premeditated murder.
</P>
<P>
   As Judge Ronald Reinstein told the jury, the prosecution's duty
to prove its case beyond a reasonable doubt means the jury can
convict Falater only if they are ``firmly convinced'' he
deliberately killed his wife of 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   While Broughton based his opinion partially on a scientific
analysis of Falater's sleeping patterns and brain waves, he also
relied on a chain of subjective conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Broughton said Falater had no motive, acted with typical
sleepwalker illogic, was ``obviously very distressed and confused''
after police arrested him, and had complete amnesia about the
events on that bloody night in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Falater, who is expected to testify this week, must persuade the
jury that he did not con the amiable Canadian.
</P>
<P>
   Former defense attorney Michael Perlin said Falater's defense
``almost has to put his guy (Falater) on the stand, because the
defense is so contrary to what jurors think of as common sense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As a defense attorney, you need to give the jury a sense of
who he truly is,'' said Perlin, whose criminal-law classes at New
York University often discuss mental condition as a defense.
``Juries are incredibly suspicious of anything they think can be
feigned.''
</P>
<P>
   The undisputed facts are that Scott Falater stabbed Yarmila
Falater 44 times with a hunting knife, dragged her into the pool at
their home and pushed her head under water.
</P>
<P>
   How could it be, prosecutor Juan Martinez has repeatedly asked _
sometimes with sarcasm and always with righteous outrage _ that
Falater was not jarred back to consciousness by the gory mayhem,
the screams of his wife, the cold water of the pool, the need to
put a bandage on his cut right hand?
</P>
<P>
   Falater, a former Motorola engineer who holds several patents on
electric devices, admits he's a killer. But he says that under the
law he did not commit murder because he didn't know what he was
doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a case about who did it or how it was done,''
defense attorney Michael Kimerer told the jury in his opening
statement. ``What we're going to prove to you in this case is that
knowing consciousness was not there.''
</P>
<P>
   Kimerer has told the jury that his client was in ``an
automatistic, somnambulistic state'' as he arose from bed, went
downstairs to the garage to change into work clothes, took a knife
to pry out a defective O-ring from the pool pump, then went into a
frenzy when his wife interrupted him.
</P>
<P>
   Falater's movements after the stabbing were described by a
neighbor, who saw Falater walk through his upstairs bedroom, come
back downstairs, make a calming motion to one of the family dogs,
return to the body and re-enter the house. The neighbor said
Falater emerged from the garage, putting on a pair of gloves,
dragged Yarmila to the pool deck, rolled her into the pool and held
her head under.
</P>
<P>
   Broughton estimates that Falater was sleepwalking for 45
minutes, a period that he acknowledges is unusually long.
</P>
<P>
   Broughton, whose academic writing about violence by sleepwalkers
includes an article titled ``Dangerous Behaviours by Night,'' said
that until recently researchers thought violent outbursts were
rare.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they are much more common than we used to think,'' he
said. He added that violence can be triggered by someone who
interferes with a sleepwalker.
</P>
<P>
   Kimerer, who guided Broughton through a slide-show seminar about
sleepwalking, is attempting to convince jurors that Falater's
defense, however improbable it may seem, is enough to create
reasonable doubt about his guilt.
</P>
<P>
   He is presenting the attack as a wild, unconscious eruption in
the placid sea of the Falater home, where there was no history of
violence or abuse.
</P>
<P>
   In laying out his case, Kimerer has offered answers to some
nagging prosecution questions:
</P>
<P>
   _Why would Falater use a hunting knife to work on the pool pump?
</P>
<P>
   Because Falater needed a pointed object to pry a defective
O-ring out of the leaking pump, Kimerer says.
</P>
<P>
   _Isn't the fact that Falater threw his wife into the pool proof
that he was trying to finish her off?
</P>
<P>
   No, Kimerer says. In fact, leaving the body floating in the
crimson water is exactly the sort of bizarre, illogical act that is
characteristic of sleepwalkers.
</P>
<P>
   _If he's innocent, why would Falater hide his bloody clothes in
a Tupperware container that he placed inside a plastic bag and
stashed in the wheel well of his car?
</P>
<P>
   Falater wasn't hiding anything, Kimerer says. He was simply
returning the work clothes to where he always kept them.
</P>
<P>
   When Broughton came to the witness stand last week, Kimerer
walked him through a lengthy list of credentials intended to show
that Broughton is not an opportunistic pseudoscientist offering
tailor-made testimony for a fat check.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Broughton is an internationally respected authority on
sleepwalking. He is a fellow of the Royal College of Physicians and
Surgeons of Canada, a professor of neurology at the University of
Ottawa and the director of a sleep disorders center. He has
received an award for lifetime achievement from the American Sleep
Disorders Association.
</P>
<P>
   Broughton said his work for Falater marked only his second
experience in a case where sleepwalking was the defense. The first
involved a Canadian man who was acquitted of murder, he said, and
he once turned down a lawyer whose client he believed to have been
lying.
</P>
<P>
   The bearded, bald, bespectacled Broughton matched the Hollywood
image of an expert witness. He maintained his professorial demeanor
even as Martinez asked incredulously if Broughton truly believed
that Falater was unaware of the mayhem he was causing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I believe that's possible,'' he said. ``I believe that's
what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Broughton acknowledged that some aspects of Falater's story had
made him ``pause'' on the way to his conclusion. But he said he
overcame those reservations after a complete review.
</P>
<P>
   If Falater is to walk out of the courtroom a free man, the
jurors _ only one of whom has been to college _ will also have to
put skepticism aside.
</P>
<P>
   That skepticism was apparent in some jurors' questions,
including one asking if the study of sleep disorders relied heavily
on speculation rather than science. Broughton responded that he and
his colleagues have ``very detailed knowledge about a large variety
of sleep disorders.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
