A4032 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RIOT-AZR &LR;      06-14 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIOT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIGARETTES LIT RIOT AT SHERIFF ARPAIO'S TENT CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By GRACIELA SEVILLA  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Sheriff Joe Arpaio blames Saturday night's Tent City
riot on a flare-up of inmate hostilities over smuggled cigarettes
and matches, which were then used to light mattresses and toilet
paper to set fire to seven tents.
</P>
<P>
   Arpaio stood among the ashes Sunday and watched as a crew of
inmates replaced the damaged tents. He praised guards and deputies
for ending what he called a ``bedtime disturbance'' without injury
to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Arpaio said he suspected the inmates obtained the cigarettes
from visitors who smuggled them in or while they were outside the
jail yard working on the chain gang.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the sheriff noted, ``there's a contraband problem.''
He said security measures for visits would be tightened.
</P>
<P>
   The uprising of about 200 inmates started about 9 p.m. Saturday
as a ``Star Wars'' bedtime story was being broadcast to the inmates
over the jail-yard loudspeakers. Bedtime Story Hour, the sheriff's
latest inmate program, kicked off this month and is designed to
increase literacy.
</P>
<P>
   Arpaio said it took guards and deputies ``five minutes'' to
quiet the uproar by using patrol dogs and pepper spray to gain
control of the convicts.
</P>
<P>
   Department officials and inmates reported that guards brought
the melee under control in about an hour. Despite the difference in
time lines, Saturday's riot ended quickly compared with the first
Tent City riot.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, more than 300 inmates battled guards in a fiery riot
that left two guards and three prisoners injured. That uprising
lasted more than four hours and was finally stopped after an armed
National Guard squad tore down barricades inmates had made from
their bunks.
</P>
<P>
   Arpaio said his department learned from that experience and was
better prepared to respond to Saturday's crisis. He credited extra
training for the guards, new equipment and ``good intelligence''
about brewing tensions with helping to bring a safe, quick end to
latest flare-up.
</P>
<P>
   Tent City guards reportedly had noticed tensions among inmates
Friday. Arpaio said one theory was that gang differences may have
sparked the uproar.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other is that they don't like my bedtime stories,'' he
quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman Pool, jailed because of parole violations and a member
of Tent City's maintenance crew, said he was just relieved no one
was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time there's fire, there's a possibility somebody could
get hurt or die,'' Pool said.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was the second Tent City riot in less than three
years, Arpaio said he intended to continue the highly criticized
open-air housing, where inmates sat sweltering Saturday as
temperatures reached 105 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``These tents will always be here. They're not going anywhere,''
he said. ``This is only the second little disturbance in the whole
jail system.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday night, a group of 35 inmates suspected of leading
the uprising were moved to the Towers Jail. Arpaio said deputies
were still working on identifying the culprits, most of whom
covered their faces with towels as the fires were started.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to try and identify them,'' Arpaio said. ``They
will be charged with arson and starting a riot.''
</P>
<P>
   An additional 100 inmates were displaced by the fire and moved
to other jail facilities. Tent City visits have been temporarily
suspended.
</P>
<P>
   As for the damage, Arpaio said there was little cost associated
with replacing the burned tents because he had other military
surplus tents in storage and was using inmate labor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Graciela Sevilla can be reached at (602) 444-4783 or at
graciela.sevilla(at)pni.com via e-mail. Republic writer Jodie
Snyder contributed to this article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
