A4228 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN16-COX     06-14 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: House crime bills would cause more harm than help
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With GOP leadership _ pardon the oxymoron _ bypassing committee
hearings and going straight to the floor, the House this week will
debate and vote on fake gun control and throwback juvenile crime
measures. With luck, the whole mess will politically self-destruct.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation is being rewritten on the fly, a moving target,
but as last glimpsed it tendered a muddle of crudely punitive
measures and versions of Senate-passed gun controls that have been
weakened to pointlessness.
</P>
<P>
   Where the Senate, for instance, corked the huge loophole that
allows firearm sales at gun shows without background checks, House
Republicans have redefined ``gun show'' so that it no longer covers
_ well, gun shows. The GOP is giving sound value to the National
Rifle Association for the $740,000 the lobby spent on a mail
campaign and the $300,000 it spent on phone banks to queer the
Senate gun provisions.
</P>
<P>
   (And as a bonbon, House Republicans would let dealers in some
situations go back to shipping guns interstate, illegal for the
past 30 years.)
</P>
<P>
   The gun games are being played out in the context of supposed
juvenile justice legislation that would do more to create adult
career criminals than to curb juvenile crime, snubbing effective
interventions for a return to brutish practices that we know from
experience _ and from endless studies, if you want to get academic
about it _ produce repeat offenders.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would allow juveniles as young as 13 to be tried as
adults for a broadened array of crimes and would let federal
prosecutors, without judicial review, make those decisions. It
would establish mandatory sentences for youths, some longer than
those for adults committing the same crimes. It would open juvenile
records.
</P>
<P>
   And it would lower the barriers against confining juveniles in
adult facilities, a practice that we know increases youth suicides,
rapes and beatings many times over.
</P>
<P>
   A neat if coincidental 100 years after creation of the juvenile
court system ended the worst abuses of young offenders, Congress,
in bipartisan hysteria, is trying to drag the nation back toward
the old ways.
</P>
<P>
   And all of this, mind you, while juvenile crime is plunging. The
juvenile homicide rate has dropped by almost half since 1993. The
juvenile arrest rate for all violence is down 37 percent in the
past five years, a larger decline than the adult rate. The
percentage of violent crimes attributed to juveniles is at its
lowest point since 1975.
</P>
<P>
   The excuse _ and it is only that _ for this legislative
malpractice is the horrid spate of schoolhouse shootings. (All
committed by suburban and small-town white boys. Guaranteed: Most
of the kids charged and jailed by the new ``justice'' would be city
minority kids. To hide that, the Senate has voted to gut a law
requiring states to study the gross racial disproportions in youth
arrests and incarceration.)
</P>
<P>
   A wise Congress would adopt the Senate gun controls, skip
regressive excesses and save youth crime prevention features. This
is not that Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
