 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No. 2549-- June 14, 1999  NEWS AND FEATURE
SUMMARY -- No. 2549 -- June 14, 1999 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. BENEATH THE FALLING BOMBS ``In a moral universe full of
shadows and grief, I have been an American correspondent working in
a country at war with America. My most searing memory is not of
physical horror - of the charred corpses from a bombed passenger
train, or the severed head near a rocketed column of Albanian
refugees. All that comes with war in the Balkans, when history and
high explosives collide. What will stay with me longest is the
memory of two large bearded Serbian men, hours apart, weeping
uncontrollably in my arms, the arms of the aggressor, over the
deaths of their friends from an American missile.'' By Steven
Erlanger. From The New York Times Magazine. 1,000 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 2.
SPRINGTIME WITH THE KOSOVO LIBERATION ARMY This is a rare look
inside the notoriously media-shy Kosovo Liberation Army, the
rag-tag group of rebel soldiers, many of them former waiters in the
cafes of once-prosperous Kosovo, who are now major players in the
strategy for a Balkans peace. By Janine di Giovanni. From The New
York Times Magazine. Full-length (4,800 words) + edited article
available.
_____________________________________________________________ 3.
THE FEATHER : MIRACLE OF NATURE (AND EVOLUTION) The feather, which
is now understood to have evolved from scales on the backs of
dinosaurs, is a multi-functional device of almost unimaginable
diversity. Not only did it allow earthly creatures millions of
years ago to rise above the planet and soar over mountains or
across oceans, it also helps them stand out or blend in, providing
camouflage and defence. Birds, it turns out, even renew and repair
their feathers in flight. By Uwe George. From GEO magazine. 2,500
words. (English translation available.) 
--------------------------------------------------------------------
------------- 4. SPAIN WANTS TO TURN GIBRALTAR INTO EUROPE'S
</P>
<P>
   ARMOUR-PLATED DOOR We have all heard about ``clean bombs'' and
``surgically precise air strikes.'' It looks as if similarly
high-tech methods may be about to be used by the Spanish for more
peaceful purposes: the restriction of illegal immigration. The
Guardia Civil has come up with a highly sophisticated project
called the ``South Plan'' which would turn the Strait of Gibraltar
into Europe's armour-plated door. By Marie-Claude Decamps. From Le
Monde. (English translation available.) 600 words.
_____________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>
   5. FROM NATURE NEWS SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   (N/A France and Spain. Embargo 19h00 BST June 16.)
</P>
<P>
   A. MACHINING METALS BY MICROWAVE
</P>
<P>
   If you thought that microwave ovens were useful for nothing more
than baking potatoes, think again. They can bake metal engine parts
too, without any need for conventional melting and pouring. By
Philip Ball. 500 words.
</P>
<P>
   B. THE RED AND SHINY ARMOUR OF TOMATOES
</P>
<P>
   Don't be misled by their sweet taste. Behind the blushing
appearance of tomatoes lies a chilling tale of death and deceit. To
avoid being eaten, tomato plants have an inbuilt defence response.
When provoked, by caterpillars for instance, they manufacture toxic
chemicals. By Marie-Thirhse Heemels. 500 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 6.
FROM MEDICAL TRIBUNE NEWS SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   A. GENETIC PROFILING MAY PREVENT DISEASES AND AID TREATMENT
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the anticipated completion in 12 months' time of 90
per cent of the working draft of the Human Genome Project - the
so-called blueprint of human beings - doctors will get red alerts
for potential diseases before symptoms develop in patients.
Lifestyle changes could then be made to counter the biological hand
dealt by our parents. 500 words.
</P>
<P>
   B. CARTOONS AND SEIZURES
</P>
<P>
   Japanese researchers may have found an explanation for why more
than 500 children experienced epileptic seizures during a popular
animated TV program several years ago: the seizures may have been
sparked by the rapidly changing colours in the cartoons. 350 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 7.
THE WAR BETWEEN MEN AND WOMEN Couples may struggle over money,
in-laws, ex-lovers ... and how much the woman's placenta should
grow when she gets pregnant. It's true : although he doesn't know
it, a man wants his woman to have a fast-growing placenta, while
the woman does all she can to keep it down to a reasonable size. By
Robert Sapolsky. Discover magazine. 1,100 words + photos. 
