<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Monday, June 14, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Tuesday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   YOSEMITE-MURDERS (Modesto, Calif.) _ Even though the ``principal
players'' are in custody and a key witness is talking, the FBI
admits the homicide case of three Yosemite tourists is so
complicated that ``it will likely be several weeks or several
months until charges are filed.'' Meanwhile, old friends and
associates of Eugene ``Rufus'' Dykes said they were stunned at
reports that the 32-year-old convicted felon from Modesto admitted
to involvement in the kidnapping and murder of three women
sightseers in February. By JIM HERRON ZAMORA.
</P>
<P>
   DIMAGGIO-HOUSE (San Francisco) _ The former home of the late Joe
DiMaggio, bought by the Baseball Hall of Famer for $14,600 in 1937,
is for sale at a list price of $1.4 million _ 100 times the
purchase price. By JULIAN GUTHRIE.
</P>
<P>
   SUTURE-LAWSUIT (San Francisco) _ Nine Northern Californians who
say they suffered raging infections after routine operations in
1994 and 1995 are blaming their ailments on improperly sterilized
surgical sutures. Ethicon Inc., a subsidiary of the giant Johnson &AMP;
Johnson medical supply firm and the world's leading suture maker,
has denied that its products made anyone sick. By LANCE WILLIAMS.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-VIOLENCE (Mexico City) _ Things aren't what they seem in
Mexico City, capital of contrasts, where 22 million people work,
eat and love. Lately, the talk has turned to violence. And the
issue came to a head last week when television host Francisco
Stanley was mowed down in a hail of machine-gun fire outside a
popular eatery. By SUSANA HAYWARD.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIAN-ANTHRAX (Undated) _ Buried bacteria at former Soviet
biological warfare sites are potentially so dangerous that the
United States should consider playing a closer role in the cleanup
effort, a think tank says in a new report. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-GAYS-METHODIST (Houston) _ Bering Memorial United
Methodist Church in Houston is taking a stand. The church and its
pastor, the Rev. Marilyn Meeker-Williams, will hold no weddings as
long as the United Methodist Church prohibits clergy from
officiating at same-sex union ceremonies. By CECILE S. HOLMES
(Photo available on NYT database.)
</P>
<P>
   DIET-GIMMICKS (Albany, N.Y.) _ There are plenty of gimmicks,
books and fad diets offering enticing ways to lose weight. Never
mind that these approaches eschew the best-known medical advice. To
lose weight, the best strategy remains to eat less and exercise
more. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-LOVE (Undated) _ A recent survey of homeowners conducted
for Home &AMP; Garden Television was revealing: More male homeowners
prefer working in the yard to having sex. By STEVE BARNES.
</P>
<P>
   KITCHEN-STONE (Albany, N.Y.) _ The kitchen has evolved into a
very high-tech environment, but many homeowners are adding a warm
touch, by stepping back to an earlier time and using natural
materials, such as stone. Granite and soapstone sinks were popular
in 19th-century farmhouses and Victorian town houses. Many of these
hand-carved sinks can still be found in older homes or historic
parts warehouses, or they can be purchased new. By FRANCES
INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   POST-WAR-RELIEF (Albany, N.Y.) _ Among Judy Meuwissen's memories
of World War II devastation in her hometown of Nijmegen, the
Netherlands, is a pair of sturdy brown oxfords sent by citizens of
Albany, N.Y., in 1947. The shoes had been distributed at
Meuwissen's high school in Nijmegen in the fall of 1947, part of
Albany's humanitarian effort to help the Dutch city get back on its
feet in the wake of catastrophic wartime losses. By PAUL GRONDAHL.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-RADIO (Albany, N.Y) _ With technology threatening to
further fragment the radio audience, a public radio station here
plans to launch a new national radio station that will broadcast
solely over the Internet. Officials at WAMC Northeast Public Radio
say ThePublicRadioStation.com could become a national forum for
independent radio productions. By JO-ANN JOHNSTON.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-LATIN-CROSSOVER (Houston) _ Two bands with ties to the
late Selena _ brother AB Quintanilla's Cumbia Kings and widower
Chris Perez's band _ are poised to crossover from Latin charts to
modern rock with new albums. By JOEY GUERRA.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-BUENA-VISTA (Undated) _ A new movie, ``Buena Vista Social
Club,'' is about the making of the groundbreaking Cuban music
album. We talk with Ry Cooder, who produced the album. The film is
directed by Wim Wenders. By RICK MITCHELL.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-EXPATRIATE (Undated) _ Bill Bryson is, once again,
befuddled. He's standing at the counter of a Sausalito coffeehouse,
puffing out his cheeks uncertainly and squinting at a menu that
runs to cappuccinos, Espresso Macchiatos, Caffe Americanos, Mocha
Freezes, Sumatra blends and Chai Lattes. The America Bryson has
returned to is bewilderingly different to him than the one he left
in 1972 for what eventually would become a career as a best-selling
humorist and travel writer in Great Britain. By JOHN FLINN.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-OKANAGAN-VALLEY (Okanagan Valley, British Columbia) _
Many travelers already have discovered the vitality of Vancouver,
the old-world European charm of Victoria and the recreational
wonderland at Whistler Resort _ all justifiably popular British
Columbia destinations. But ask Canadians about their favorite
summer escape, and chances are that the Okanagan Valley, in
southern interior British Columbia, will be high on the list. By
HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Undated) _ A survey of travel agents provides
insight into summer vacation preferences. No surprises here: Las
Vegas, Orlando, Fla., and San Francisco, in that order, for
domestic travel; Cancun, Paris and London for international
destinations. By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ When it's hot, California has
sensational houseboating, boat-in camping, rafting, water skiing
and water's-edge camps that are beautiful. Here are the best of the
best choices for outdoor activities during the summer. By TOM
STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (Las Vegas, Nevada) _ For nearly two years we
argued (and argued) about where the Lake Ladies should meet to
commemorate our collective 50th birthday. We settled on Las Vegas.
By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   WORD-GAMES (Orinda, Calif.) _ A friend of mine gets his words
all mixed up. He's a wonderful guy, does well in life, but he's one
of those people who substitute sound-alikes for the words they want
to say. The rest of us occasionally do the same thing, but he does
it all the time. And it tickles me. He often attends the sympathy.
He enjoys a glass of cherry once in awhile. His great favorite is a
Manhattan with a red sherry. By MARIE KRENZ.
</P>
