<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4282 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALIEN-ANNIVERSARY-SPE     06-14 1462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALIEN-ANNIVERSARY-SPECIAL-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ALIEN'-ATION: SCI-FI'S LANDMARK HORROR FLICK, 20 YEARS LATER  
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Ian Holm, Sigourney Weaver, Tom Skerritt
and John Hurt in a scene from ``Alien.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    The year was 1979.
 &HT;    Jimmy Carter, Anwar Sadat and Menachem Begin signed the Camp
David peace accords, and Ayatollah Khomeini replaced the Shah as
ruler of Iran. William Styron penned ``Sophie's Choice,'' and John
Wayne moseyed on into the next world.
 &HT;    And in space no one could hear you scream.
 &HT;    Believe it or not, it's been 20 years since Ridley Scott's
``Alien'' scared moviegoers silly with its moody atmosphere, nasty
mother alien, oodles of goop and, of course, John Hurt's notorious
chest-burster sequence, one of the most viscerally frightening
scenes ever filmed.
 &HT;    To commemorate the film's 20th anniversary, Twentieth Century
Fox has released video and DVD versions of ``Alien,'' ``Aliens''
(1986), ``Alien 3'' (1992) and ``Alien Resurrection'' (1997) that
include deleted sequences, behind-the-scenes footage and interviews
with most of the key players, onscreen and off.
 &HT;    To date, the sci-fi/horror series has generated more than $500
million at the box office. But it all began with a
down-at-the-heels starfreighter called the Nostromo, and a volatile
crew of space truckers _ Sigourney Weaver, John Hurt, Tom Skerritt,
Veronica Cartwright, Ian Holm, Yaphet Kotto and Harry Dean Stanton
_ facing off against fierce, sleek and deadly alien creatures.
 &HT;    ``You don't realize that something will become a classic in its
own vein,'' Hurt says. ``You don't think like that.''
 &HT;    Despite an impressive resume that includes ``Chariots of Fire''
(1981), ``The Madness of King George'' (1994) and ``The Sweet
Hereafter'' (1997), Holm is still most often recognized for
``Alien.''
 &HT;    ``Actually, `recognized' may not be the right word,'' he says.
``I've had people say, `Have you seen that movie, ``Alien?'''
 &HT;    ``I say, `Yes, I have. I'm in it.' They'll say, `You're in it?
What do you play?'
 &HT;    ``I'll explain I played the robot, and they'll say, `The robot?
Oh, my God!'''
 &HT;    Holm laughs.
 &HT;    ``It was hell to make,'' he says. ``It was not a comfortable
movie. Ridley was a real one-man band and real tough _ he tends not
to tolerate fools.
 &HT;    ``It was an extraordinary experience.''
 &HT;    The film's piece de resistance, of course, occurs about halfway
through, when a baby alien burrows its way out of Hurt's chest,
splattering blood over the other characters, then growls and darts
off.
 &HT;    ``I remember shooting that scene, vividly,'' Hurt says. ``I was
doubled over on the table. Then they cut away, and when they cut
away I went through a hole in the table and legs were built on, so
the prop guys could fiddle around with the little creature. It was
very low-tech.
 &HT;    ``A lot has been said about the other actors not knowing what
would happen,'' he adds. ``Of course they knew _ but they didn't
know there would be caps to splatter the blood around.
 &HT;    ``Ridley had four or five cameras on everybody to capture the
moment in closeups and two-shots. So a lot of it was done in one
shot.''
 &HT;    Cartwright, whose long career has included such other ventures
into the bizarre as ``The Birds'' (1963) and several episodes of
``The X-Files,'' has her own memories of the scene.
 &HT;    ``We were up in the dressing room for four or five hours while
they got John ready,'' she says. ``Harry Dean had brought his
guitar and was playing wonderful Mexican music in the hallways. We
all just wandered around, trying to figure out what the hell was
going on.
 &HT;    ``By the time they got us down to the set, everybody there was
wearing raincoats and everything was covered in plastic,'' she
continues. ``They had several cameras set up and had buckets of
`awful' _ all the guts and stuff _ soaking in formaldehyde. Ugh,
the stench! It was unbelievable.''
 &HT;    Scott told the other actors to bend over and stare at Hurt's
chest as the creature cracked through. He thoughtfully warned
Cartwright that she'd get a little blood on her.
 &HT;    ``A little blood,'' she says, snickering. ``I had a blood jet
pointed at my face!
 &HT;    ``The anticipation built because they had to fix John's shirt,''
she recalls. ``Then the creature punched through, and what you saw
was the first reaction on everybody's face.
 &HT;    ``When it burst all the way through, the blood jet went off in
my face,'' she concludes. ``I backed up, my knees hit the back of
the couch and I flipped upside down. The dailies were hysterical.
But I got up and ran back into the shot.
 &HT;    ``Ridley had his cameras trained on what he wanted, and that was
it. We did it once.''
 &HT;    Actually, it was almost someone else on that table. Hurt had
been Scott's first choice to play Kane, but the British actor had
already committed to another film about to be shot in South Africa.
 &HT;    At the last minute, however, he learned that he wouldn't be
allowed into South Africa, while at the same time hearing that the
actor playing Kane had fallen ill.
 &HT;    ``They'd already started shooting `Alien,''' Hurt recalls.
``Ridley rang me up and said, `Look, can I come around and talk to
you this evening?' He arrived around 10 p.m. and didn't leave until
midnight. He went through exactly what he wanted to do with the
film.
 &HT;    ``In a sense, I suppose he was pitching it to me, because he
really needed an actor for that part,'' Hurt says. ``Everything he
said that night was in the film _ everything.''
 &HT;    Cartwright had a less pleasant casting discovery, however. She
had auditioned for the role of Ripley, which ultimately made Weaver
a star. When she was called to make the film, she assumed she'd won
the part.
 &HT;    ``Originally I thought I had Ripley, as did my agent,'' she
recalls. ``I'd not even read the script from the point of view of
Lambert.
 &HT;    ``When they called to set up the wardrobe fittings, I was over
in England. They told me I'd be going in to try on costumes for
Lambert and I said, `Oh, no, there's a mistake. I think I'm
supposed to be Ripley.'''
 &HT;    Instead of having a tantrum, Cartwright threw herself into her
new role.
 &HT;    ``I reread it from her point of view,'' she says. ``I didn't
want her to be this whiny person. If you're a trucker in space,
you've obviously had a lot of experience.''
 &HT;    Lambert became the film's voice of practicality.
 &HT;    ``She wants to get the f--k off that ship,'' Cartwright says.
``She wants to use that capsule and she says, `Listen, a--holes,
let's get going!'
 &HT;    ``Always in those movies you go, `Oh, please, don't go back in
there! How stupid _ you're going to get it,''' she says. ``The
audience is saying, `Just get out of there!'
 &HT;    ``So that's what I did.''
 &HT;    Scott didn't tell Cartwright why she ended up playing Lambert.
 &HT;    ``He never said anything,'' she says. ``It was just a
miscommunication or something. I have no idea.''
 &HT;    Crucial to the film's success was its innovative design, as
conceived by H.R. Giger. The look of its much-imitated, buglike
monsters may have been the movie's most influential element.
 &HT;    ``I think it is a classic,'' Cartwright says. ``Every movie you
saw after it had an alien and it looked like our alien. Even
Godzilla looked like our alien.
 &HT;    ``All of these movies seem to have some part of `Alien' in
them,'' she says. ``Obviously, what Ridley created was horrifying.
 &HT;    ``It's pretty amazing, isn't it?''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on the 20th-anniversary edition of
``Alien,'' consult the Fox Home Entertainment Website at
www.tcfhe.com. And don't forget to visit The New York Times
Syndicate Website at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for
information on StarBeat and other features. &QL; 
