<SLUG> BC-BEHIND-THE-SCENES-ON-FELICITY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SENSE OF `FELICITY': BEHIND THE SCENES ON TELEVISION'S FAVORITE
NEW DRAMA 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Keri Russell, Scott Speedman and Scott
Foley in a scene from ``Felicity.'') 
 By ANDREW RYAN  
 c.1999 TV Guide Canada  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What a difference a year makes.
</P>
<P>
   This time last year, ``Felicity'' was being hailed by critics as
1998/99's only can't-miss new show _ and also suffering the
customary bashing that comes with front-runner status.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone had an opinion about ``Felicity,'' including plenty of
people who'd never seen a second of it.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, the WB drama about a pert California teen (Keri
Russell) who moves to New York to attend college _ and pursue her
handsome high-school classmate, Ben (Scott Speedman) _ has
established itself as a solid hit, not to mention making stars of
Russell, Speedman and Scott Foley, who plays the third leg of their
triangle, the thoroughly decent Noel.
</P>
<P>
   Before ``Felicity,'' Russell's biggest credit was a gig on ``The
New Mickey Mouse Club.'' Speedman had virtually no acting
experience, having been cast purely on the basis of a killer
audition tape.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, Russell says, getting used to the show has been much
like the adjustments their characters have gone through as
first-year college students.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely a parallel there,'' she says. ``None of us
knew what to expect when this all started. This show was a lot
different from anything I had ever worked on before, and it took
some adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, when I first signed onto the show, I was so
excited, but I was also so scared,'' she recalls. ``It was
completely overwhelming. Now I feel like I know what's going on,
and I know how to handle all the publicity and craziness. I have a
better sense of awareness, and I know how to pace myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Speedman says he never felt overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody kept telling me what a crazy year it was going to
be,'' he says, ``but it wasn't. I mean, it was crazy at times, but
that was mostly because of the workload and long hours. It was
pretty weird, but not that bad.''
</P>
<P>
   As the title character, Russell naturally got a more
concentrated version of the hype. She's become used to seeing her
character dissected as a role model _ and faring better than such
past victims as Murphy Brown or Ally McBeal _ and says she's been
delighted by the show's fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get tons of letters,'' she says, ``and everyone is just
completely cool. It's the same thing with the way people respond in
public _ they're pretty laid back: They don't come up screaming,
`There's Felicity!' They usually just come up and say, `We think
your show is so cool.'
</P>
<P>
   ``People tend to be a little calmer, I guess, compared to fans
of other shows,'' she adds. ``But those are the type of people the
show attracts. Our viewers are really intelligent. They're not
screaming, unless it's a pack of 12-year-old boys or something.
They always have positive things to say about the show, so for the
most part it's been great.''
</P>
<P>
   Speedman adds that the difference is more noticeable when they
get away from Los Angeles, which he says prides itself on letting
celebrities alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so many actors down there, they can't tell one from
the next,'' he says. ``It's when you go to a small town that it
gets kind of strange.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fans seem to be really polite,'' he says. ``They're not
overwhelming. We've got a small, really hardcore audience. Those
people who've come up to me are just really polite.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing the fans do get excited about, however, is Felicity's
vacillating between her longstanding crush on the often-arrogant
Ben and her new interest in the lower-key Noel.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the neighborhood I live in, there's an all-girl school,''
Russell says. ``I would be riding my bike to the post office or
whatever, and these girls would always come up to me and ask who I
liked better, Ben or Noel. Then they would chant, `Noel! Noel!
You've got to choose Noel!'
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the occasional few of them liked Ben,'' she says with a
joking sneer at Speedman. ``But I really liked the idea that girls
like Noel best, because he's definitely more of a friend.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a period for about a month last season where Ben
just got hit with one thing after another,'' Speedman says
defensively. ``He had a gambling problem, and so on. There was no
good news for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the writers make Noel a really pleasant guy, so there's
not much comparison.''
</P>
<P>
   The series began as a star turn for Russell, but seems to be
evolving into an ensemble show _ a development which she says suits
her just fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the idea that we've become an ensemble cast,'' the
actress says. ``And it did make things a bit easier on me. I'm
still working a lot, but it's a lot easier than those first few
episodes, when I was in almost every scene.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's also some really talented people in our cast,''
Speedman adds. ``They deserve their chance, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Felicity'' fans rave about the show's music, which offers a
much wider range than most teen shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I absolutely love the music on our show,'' Russell says,
beaming. ``Our music supervisor, Amanda Demme, is fabulous. Look at
our soundtrack album that was just released _ it has people like
Kate Bush, Peter Gabriel, Aretha Franklin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just teenybopper little songs,'' she says. ``It's the
same kind of music that I like listening to.''
</P>
<P>
   The series seems likely to continue indefinitely, but Speedman
doubts that it will rack up anything like the nine-year run of
``Beverly Hills, 90210.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all, like, 40 years old now,'' he groans. ``That show
is like a factory, just pushing out product. I'd leave the show if
we ever got like that _ which isn't likely to happen. Our show is
so different. We have great writers, and the quality control is
right there.''
</P>
<P>
   That's as much as either is willing to say about the future.
Nothing closer-range _ such as how they'll resolve last season's
teaser ending, which left Felicity torn between going to Europe
with Noel or driving home to California with Ben.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants to know what happens,'' Russell says, laughing.
``So many people have been asking me that question. And they're
just writing the new season right now, so it's still up in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of know what's going to happen,'' she says teasingly,
``but I have to keep quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Andrew Ryan is the features editor for TV Guide Canada, based
in North York, Ontario.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Felicity,'' consult the Warner
Bros. Website at www.wblot.com. And don't forget to visit The New
York Times Syndicate Website at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate
for information on StarBeat and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-99 1101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990614.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 11:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4285 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOEY-LAUREN-ADAMS-IN-     06-14 1431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEY-LAUREN-ADAMS-IN-BIG-DADDY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DADDY'S' GIRL: JOEY LAUREN ADAMS ENTERS THE GOOFY WORLD OF ADAM
SANDLER 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Joey Lauren Adams with Adam Sandler in a
scene from ``Big Daddy.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    The face is sort of familiar, but people can't quite place it.
Wasn't she ... no, no ... but still ...
 &HT;    And then she speaks, and everyone recognizes Joey Lauren Adams.
 &HT;    Hard to mistake that memorable little-girl voice, one part
Minnie Mouse mixed with one part Melanie Griffith.
 &HT;    ``I am one of the few actresses who isn't recognized by the way
she looks,'' Adams says. ``I'm recognized by the way I talk.''
 &HT;    The other day, she recalls during a breakfast conversation at
the Four Seasons hotel in Beverly Hills, she was in a hardware
store when a guy came up and told her, ``You sound awfully
familiar.''
 &HT;    Adams, who earned raves in the critically acclaimed independent
film ``Chasing Amy'' (1997), smiled.
 &HT;    Alas, he hadn't seen ``Chasing Amy.'' Or ``Michael'' (1996). Or
any of her nearly a dozen films.
 &HT;    ``I started listing my resume to this guy,'' Adams says. ``If
they're totally stumped, I will slowly admit, ```Married With
Children'' _ I'm the girl who took Bud Bundy's virginity.'''
 &HT;    She rolls her eyes.
 &HT;    ``I swear, lightbulbs go off when I mention that one.''
 &HT;    In not too long, chances are the lightbulbs will be popping for
something more recent, if not noticeably more sophisticated. On
June 25, she's opening in ``Big Daddy,'' opposite Adam Sandler.
 &HT;    It's her highest-profile role yet, and Adams _ pretty in a
down-to-earth way with brown, bobbed hair, khaki pants and a black
sweater _ says she has no reservations about undertaking so
commercial a project.
 &HT;    ``It was definitely my plan to do a movie that would be big at
the box office,'' the 31-year-old actress says. ``I think I was a
little naive after `Chasing Amy.' I thought I would be able to do
anything I wanted to do, and that wasn't the case.
 &HT;    ``At this point, I realize I have to do a few commercial films
that make money at the box office to do the projects I want,'' she
says. ``Plus I just don't have the patience to hold out for great
art each time.''
 &HT;    And besides, there's that voice.
 &HT;    ``I read scripts that I really, really like, but then my voice
can be a problem at the audition,'' she says. ``There have been
several times when a director has said, `Change it. It's grating.'
I'm even thinking I should change it and maybe talk a little
deeper.
 &HT;    ``But then I don't sound like me, and that freaks me out.''
 &HT;    The voice wasn't a problem for ``Big Daddy'' _ Sandler will
never pass for James Mason or James Earl Jones, either _ but there
were other considerations. For example, doing a love scene with the
genially inept Sandler, whose doofus-fest films have rarely
featured romantic interludes.
 &HT;    ``The kissing was no big deal for me _ I've done full-out love
scenes,'' Adams says. ``Adam was a little bit nervous. He was a
movie-kissing rookie. But soon he became very conscious of not
pushing my head out of the frame. And he was very sweet about it.
 &HT;    ``Never once did I think, `I'm kissing The Waterboy.'''
 &HT;    Waterboy or not, it's only the latest step in a career which
began in Arkansas 29 years ago, when the 2-year-old daughter of a
lumberyard worker and a housewife started performing in church
plays.
 &HT;    ``I was always the little angel,'' she says. ``My mom says that
if there was applause, I would really eat it up.''
 &HT;    Much as she enjoyed performing, however, the Arkansas native
never envisioned herself a movie star.
 &HT;    ``As a young girl, I didn't think a career as an actress was
really an option,'' Adams says. ``I just loved movies. And the
movies made me realize there was no culture in Arkansas _ I was
literally living in a vacuum.''
 &HT;    At 19, Adams packed her bags and headed out.
 &HT;    ``I didn't leave to become an actress,'' she says. ``I just
wanted to expose myself to life. For instance, I had never met
anyone from another culture. I never met a Hindu, I didn't know
what that meant. I was such a sheltered infant.''
 &HT;    She headed for San Diego and then to Los Angeles, where she got
her break in show business. Sort of.
 &HT;    ``I got a job singing backup with a country-western singer,''
she recalls, ``and we toured China.''
 &HT;    She pauses.
 &HT;    ``Well, we were supposed to tour China,'' she says. ``But we got
kicked out. Our singer would mean to take an upper and he would
take a downer. He would sing the same verse over and over again
until people were sick of it. It was just a nightmare, and we were
actually asked to leave the country.''
 &HT;    By that point, she adds, it was almost a relief.
 &HT;    ``The worst part is that I would have to stand there swinging my
hips, and the lead singer would come up and try to rub on us
girls,'' she recalls. ``And since we were onstage, you couldn't do
anything about it.''
 &HT;    Not long afterward, however, she began to find movie work,
beginning with a small role in Richard Linklater's cult classic
``Dazed and Confused'' (1993). She teamed with Parker Posey as a
singing duo in ``Sleep With Me'' (1994), and played a pie-eating
waitress who seduces John Travolta in ``Michael.''
 &HT;    Her other film credits include ``Coneheads'' (1993), ``The
Program'' (1993), ``Mallrats'' (1995), ``Bio-Dome'' (1996) and ``A
Cool Dry Place'' (1998).
 &HT;    But it was Kevin Smith's ``Chasing Amy,'' and her role as a
lesbian comic-book artist in love with a straight man (Ben
Affleck), that really caught people's eye. And it's no accident,
Adams says.
 &HT;    ``I've learned to be more comfortable as an actress, which makes
me more present,'' she says. ``Years ago, if I had an emotional
scene, I used to sit in my trailer and listen to really depressing
music and think about really awful, sad things.
 &HT;    ``I've learned that doesn't work,'' Adams says. ``It has to come
from inside.''
 &HT;    Adams just wrapped ``Bruno,'' Shirley MacLaine's directorial
debut, and has her eye on ``Tuesday's Child,'' a romance which
would co-star James Garner.
 &HT;    On the personal side, she says, things aren't going as well.
Relationships with Smith and then with her ``Cool Dry Place''
co-star Vince Vaughn didn't work out, which Adams says is as much
about her as about the relationships themselves.
 &HT;    Yes, she's in therapy.
 &HT;    ``I've just started dealing with a lot of father issues,'' she
says. ``It's liberating when you realize what effect your
upbringing has on you. I wanted to look at my relationship with my
father in a very honest way, and not in a 6-year-old-little-girl
way of looking up to your Daddy.''
 &HT;    She shakes her head.
 &HT;    ``You kind of sit there and feel like an idiot in therapy,'' she
says. ``I'm going, `Duh, my father didn't talk to me, so I don't
feel men understand me.'''
 &HT;    And no, being young, beautiful and near the top of the studio
hot lists doesn't mean that handsome Hollywood hunks are fighting
for her telephone number.
 &HT;    ``Where are they?'' Adams says, laughing. ``And just because
they're big stars doesn't mean they're great guys.''
 &HT;    Most of them can't even measure up to Adam ``Big Daddy''
Sandler, she adds with that little-girl laugh.
 &HT;    ``Try big duddies!''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Big Daddy,'' consult the Sony
Pictures Website at www.spr.sony.com. And don't forget to visit The
New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
