<SLUG> BC-ROCK-STARS-REM-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
R.E.M-PHATIC: ROCK'S QUIRKIEST BAND REINVENTS ITSELF 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of the three members of R.E.M.: Michael
Stipe, Mike Mills and Peter Buck.) 
 By GARY GRAFF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    ``Hi. We're R.E.M., and we're glad to be here,'' Michael Stipe
told the crowd at a San Francisco benefit concert last fall.
 &HT;    He might have added that R.E.M. was glad to be, period.
 &HT;    Prior to releasing its latest album, ``Up'' _ which the Athens,
Ga.-based group is promoting with a summer-long world tour that
kicked off on June 17 in Lisbon, Portugal _ R.E.M. wasn't sure it
would play again or release any more music.
 &HT;    After having redefined what was considered ``modern'' and
``alternative'' rock since 1983, the members of R.E.M. were afraid
it might be time to put their group to sleep.
 &HT;    Winding down a band that had sold millions of records might seem
extreme, but not to R.E.M. _ not after the 1997 retirement of Bill
Berry, the first personnel change in the band's history. The
drummer had suffered a near-fatal double brain aneurysm early in
the group's 1995 world tour, and though he fully recovered and
spent the rest of the year on the road, he found he no longer had
the enthusiasm for the rock 'n' roll lifestyle that he once had
felt.
 &HT;    His bandmates understood and respected his decision, but that
didn't make his leaving any easier for them to deal with.
 &HT;    ``Bill leaving R.E.M. is different from a drummer leaving a
regular band,'' Stipe explains. ``Each member had so much to do
with the music that we made and how we presented ourselves in
everything. It was a real blow.''
 &HT;    Berry's announcement didn't come out of the blue, however.
 &HT;    ``He told me that `I can't see doing this a whole lot longer,
probably three more records,''' guitarist Peter Buck recalls.
``That was two weeks before he quit.''
 &HT;    ``I knew he wasn't happy,'' bassist/keyboardist Mike Mills adds.
``We all knew he wasn't happy, but I knew that he was really
unhappy and wanting to get out. I didn't know when he would do it
or if he would do it, but to Peter and Michael it was a big
shock.''
 &HT;    In other words, it was the end of the world as they knew it. But
these days R.E.M. feels fine.
 &HT;    That's because the remaining trio is justifiably psyched about
``Up.'' Despite its disappointing sales, the record is a brave
departure, different from anything the group has ever released _
not to mention a daring way to start what's reported to be an $80
million new contract with Warner Bros. Records.
 &HT;    As it turns out, R.E.M. used Berry's departure as the occasion
for a radical rethinking of the way it makes music. Many of the
group's trademarks _ particularly Buck's stinging guitar _ are
gone, displaced by a lusher kind of ambience. Keyboards and strings
dominate the arrangements, with rhythm machines or drums played by
Buck and Mills providing color and texture rather than propulsion.
 &HT;    The musicians themselves changed their roles as much as they
changed the music. Mills relinquished his bass duties to Buck, for
instance, and the group employed instruments such as vibraphone and
tubular bells. Stipe even took a guitar solo on the song ``Why Not
Smile'' _ though he later explains that ``I drank way too much wine
that night.''
 &HT;    ``Having kind of brazenly decided we'd continue, we kind of had
two options,'' Stipe explains.
 &HT;    One was to hire a journeyman drummer _ ``a fake Bill Berry,''
Stipe says _ to carry on as usual. The other choice was simply to
accept and adapt to the circumstances.
 &HT;    ``It was really liberating to have things shook up that much,''
he says. ``We took every process and every way that we've ever had
of recording and just chucked it out the window and started with a
completely blank slate _ the sky's the limit, we can do anything,
we can go anywhere with this. Let's embrace it.
 &HT;    ``And we did _ not to say that it was easy or fun, because it
wasn't.''
 &HT;    All three members acknowledge that the making of ``Up'' was
turbulent.
 &HT;    ``It shook up enough stuff that it made us have to re-examine
everything,'' Buck says. ``Like how we work together, how we write
songs.''
 &HT;    Stipe even expected the group to break up while making the
album, he says.
 &HT;    But Buck believes that their exercise in drastic change actually
strengthened the band more than it weakened it.
 &HT;    ``We're extremely stubborn people,'' he explains. ``We just did
it. We didn't talk about it, like `Is this difficult? Is this hard?
Is this the right thing to do?' We ended up finishing the record
under a lot of stress, then sat down and talked about the
experiences.
 &HT;    ``Having done all that, we just realized we made a great
record,'' he concludes. ``And that we're still good friends. We
kind of walked through fire on this one.''
 &HT;    R.E.M.'s decision to tour is a testimony to that realization.
When the album was initially released, the group announced that it
was going to forgo a tour. The subtle material on ``Up'' seemed so
different that it wouldn't necessarily fit comfortably next to the
group's older material, they said.
 &HT;    But a series of promotional dates in the United States and
Europe, with three sidemen fleshing out the group's sound, helped
to change their minds.
 &HT;    And there's no denying that ``Up,'' which despite its name did a
quick slide down the charts after its release, could use the
additional push.
 &HT;    But while Stipe, Buck and Mills admit to being disappointed by
the album's weak sales, all three claim to be unfazed. The truth
is, they say, that change is sometimes harder for the audience than
it is for the performer, and ``Up'' is most definitely a radical
change from what their fans had been used to.
 &HT;    ``I feel like this is the first album of the new band,'' Buck
says. ``We're pretty much called R.E.M. because that's who signed
the contract. The three of us are a different band now.
 &HT;    ``Inventing something and compromising something is not as
easy,'' he says. ``But we've done this for a million years, and we
think we know what we're doing.''
 c.1999 Gary Graff  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Gary Graff is a Beverly Hills, Mich.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Up,'' consult the Warner Bros.
Records Website at www.music.warnerbros.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
