<SLUG> BC-HOLSENDOLPH15-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ruling key to Coke trial
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In filings last week, lawyers for the plaintiffs in
the discrimination case against Coca-Cola zeroed in on their
objective to prove that the company's personnel system works
against black employees.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, hanging in the air is an argument over
procedure, whether the plaintiffs brought their complaint in the
right way. There's the assertion by the company that because the
complaint may be framed incorrectly, the judge should, in effect,
drop the case as a class action.
</P>
<P>
   Most experts expect that in the next month Judge Richard Story,
the expeditious federal judge hearing the case, may make a
definitive decision about whether to move forward at full speed.
</P>
<P>
   Before that occurs, he could ask for more written arguments, or
he could announce oral agruments, when lawyers from both sides
appear before him to debate whether the case should proceed.
</P>
<P>
   The company, in its motion to dismiss the complaint as a class
action, emphasized that the four plaintiffs differed in ways that
did not add up to a class problem. But lawyers for the four _
Motisola Malikha Abdallah, Gregory Allen Clark, Linda Ingram and
Kimberly Gray Orton _ argued that their information shows a
discriminatory pattern that is generally unfair to
African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   In its papers opposing the Coca-Cola motion to dismiss the class
allegations, plaintiffs' attorneys said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Plaintiffs have brought this action to remedy specific
policies and practices of the Coca-Cola Co. that discriminate
against an entire class of employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plaintiffs are challenging companywide policies and practices,
including specific aspects of Coca-Cola's performance evaluation
system, job grade system, compensation system and promotion
system.''
</P>
<P>
   In letters and e-mail messages to me, I have heard many
African-Americans, claiming to be Coca-Cola workers or retirees,
say they think they detected unfairness in certain company
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   I also have received letters from people claiming to be white
Coca-Cola employees insisting that they think black employees get
preference, not discriminatory treatment.
</P>
<P>
   However, in papers filed last week, lawyers for the plaintiffs
insisted that all personnel policies, ranging from performance
standards to job posting to pay patterns, are controlled by the
North Avenue headquarters and have resulted in several negative
results, including the following:
</P>
<P>
   1. A compensation system that permits undue discretion (by
managers) and is based on discriminatory evaluations.
</P>
<P>
   2. A pattern and practice of placing African-Americans in lower
pay grades than ``similarly situated white employees.''
</P>
<P>
   3. A promotion system ``that denies African-American employees
the opportunity for fair and open competition.''
</P>
<P>
   4. Failure to monitor training, compensation patterns and
promotion decisions to detect discriminatory patterns.
</P>
<P>
   The thrust of the plaintiffs' contentions last week was that the
court cannot really examine these alleged discriminatory patterns
unless the court orders Coca-Cola to open the books or databases
and permit interviews of decision makers.
</P>
<P>
   In a first step in that direction, the court set up a schedule
for examining the company's materials and conducting the
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Still, unresolved now is the procedural dispute that must be
resolved before the court plunges fully into the examination of
Coca-Cola's personnel policies toward African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
