<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: It's all part of the job
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Halleluiah! We have another wage earner in the
household.
</P>
<P>
   It's been hard for our teen-age sons to grasp that ``earning''
an allowance from us for doing chores doesn't help the family's
economic bottom line. Nor does it keep the gas tanks of their cars
full.
</P>
<P>
   But, praise be, we now have a second somewhat-employed son
bringing in minimum wage. We are grateful, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   First jobs always bring on a slew of memories. What is it about
that unsuspecting teen-age worker that brings out the prankster in
some people?
</P>
<P>
   My husband worked construction one summer during high school and
remembers well his first day at a big hospital construction site. A
burly ironworker told him to run across the site to the supply
truck to get him a spool of ``left-handed tie wire,'' explaining
that he was a southpaw and wore it on the left side of his
workbelt.
</P>
<P>
   When my husband got to the truck and asked for the item, the
supervisor laughed. ``There's no such thing as left-handed tie
wire, son. Tie wire is tie wire. Someone's having some fun with
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Embarrassed, he walked back across the construction site and
handed over the spool of tie wire to the guffawing ironworker. Such
episodes nurture the desire in most of us to be self-employed.
</P>
<P>
   My husband's next job wasn't any more encouraging. On the first
day of summer vacation, he went to work at a deli in a small
shopping center. That very afternoon a huge tornado ripped through
town, flattening a retail area just a few blocks away. He tried to
convince his parents it was God's sign that he didn't want him to
work that summer, but I think they surmised that was a bunch of
bologna _ and hold the mustard.
</P>
<P>
   My dad had a similarly bad first work experience. He was a farm
boy, so he mostly worked at home. When he was 16, though, his dad
let him get a part-time job at the town grocery. He worked for 18
cents an hour and thought he'd hit the big time. His first day on
the job, fresh off the farm, he showed up ready to make his
fortune.
</P>
<P>
   A neighbor walked into the store, spotted my dad and quickly
apprised the situation. He asked him for some ``red bluing.'' If
you don't know, bluing is a rinse that folks used to put in their
wash to keep white clothes from yellowing. Eager to please, dad
scampered up and down the aisles searching for red bluing.
Exasperated, he finally had to ask the boss where it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Son,'' the boss said slowly, ``why do you think they call it
bluing? Because it's blue. There's no such thing as `red' bluing.''
</P>
<P>
   The neighbor chuckled over that one at church and PTA
gatherings, much to my father's chagrin, for years to come. Dad
soon decided farming was a good future.
</P>
<P>
   My first job as a teen-ager was baby-sitting for a neighbor boy
out in the country. The parents went merrily off, leaving me to
tend to their 6-year-old. All went well until it was time for him
to go to bed. Upstairs at the door to his bedroom, I encountered a
ferocious terrier that absolutely refused to let me enter the room.
The boy crawled into bed, but I had to stand outside the door, the
terrier growling and snapping at my feet. I spent the rest of the
evening praying the kid wouldn't get sick or the house catch fire.
It was the only time I ever baby-sat.
</P>
<P>
   So far, things have gone better for our newly employed son,
although his boss did walk out one day after he messed up a phone
order and told him, ``Turn in your cap and your nametag. You're
fired.''
</P>
<P>
   Stunned, he was reaching for his nametag when the manager smiled
and said, ``Just kidding!''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the real world, son.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco Tribune-Herald. She can be
reached online at VMKabat(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
