<SLUG> BC-TECH-REPORT15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A ticket to the digital age
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Has your dad put off signing up for Call Waiting? Does
your mom not understand how e-mail works? Is your brother stumped
when he tries to make a call on your cell phone?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's time for a make-over.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a cue from daytime television, AT&AMP;T wants to give some
``lucky'' people a technology make-over, to bring a chosen few
kicking and screaming into the digital age.
</P>
<P>
   The five people picked will be flown to California to attend a
two-day training course on new communications technologies at the
AT&AMP;T labs. The telecom giant will cover airfare, hotel and meals
and pay for one year of monthly recurring charges associated with
its phone network and Worldnet Internet access services. The
makeover also includes a wireless phone, a laptop computer and a
hand-held model.
</P>
<P>
   To apply, send a letter or e-mail of no more than 200 words
explaining how communications and other technologies could simplify
your life. Written letters can be sent to AT&AMP;T Communications
Make-over, 295 North Maple Ave., Room 2353F2, Basking Ridge N.J.,
07920. Send e-mails to rm
</P>
<P>
   -makeover(at)ems.att.com. The submission must reach AT&AMP;T by June
30. Winners will be notified in July.
</P>
<P>
   Those in Atlanta; Baltimore; Charlotte; Chicago; Dallas; Denver;
Detroit; Las Vegas; Minneapolis; Philadelphia; Phoenix; Pittsburgh;
Sacramento, Calif.; Salt Lake City; Seattle; St. Louis; Tucson,
Ariz.; Tulsa, Okla.; Washington, D.C.; and parts of North and South
Florida are eligible.
</P>
<P>
   DeLorme enhances its map offerings
</P>
<P>
   DeLorme is releasing an updated, enhanced version of its digital
topographical maps.
</P>
<P>
   The new features on the CD-ROM maps include contours every 20
feet, a 3-D engine, more than 300,000 miles of trails and new
drawing tools that let users customize maps. The disc also lets you
reach DeLorme on the Internet and download updates about
construction projects and events.
</P>
<P>
   The disc including maps of the United States retails for an
estimated $99. Six regional maps sell for $49.95 each.
</P>
<P>
   The company started in 1976 when David DeLorme created the Maine
Atlas and Gazetteer. The company now makes an atlas for each state.
The mapping software was developed in the early 1980s. The first
consumer software map was released in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   DeLorme Topo USA 2.0 requires at least Microsoft Windows 95, a
Pentium 120 or higher processor, 16 megabytes of RAM, 30 megabytes
of hard disk space, a CD-ROM drive, a 16-bit color monitor with
Super VGA graphics and a mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Genealogy CDs updated
</P>
<P>
   Broderbund released an updated version of its genealogy
software, the Family Tree Maker Deluxe 15-CD set.
</P>
<P>
   It includes a different type of family tree, one that includes
everyone entered into the family file, not just blood relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The version has census and marriage records, immigration and
passenger lists and military records. Users can search by first and
last names, varied spelling of names, married and maiden names,
nicknames, relatives, dates and locations.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-CD set includes the FamilyFinder index, which has a
listing of more than 200 million people on three CDs; two CDs of
the Social Security death index; international marriage records
index; birth records for the United States and Europe; U.S.
military records; and more than 15,000 actual family trees.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-CD set retails for about $80. An 8-CD set sells for about
$45. The sets are available in stores, on the Web at
www.familytreemaker.com and at 1-800-474-8696.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
