<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Golfers can easily swing to advice, news sites
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The most effective way to learn humility is to play
golf. In an average round, whether you've just taken up the game or
once played on the pro circuit, you will do several incredibly
stupid things that would make your own mother question your IQ.
</P>
<P>
   Several other times, you will strike the ball in such a way as
to convince the casual onlooker that not only have you never before
held a golf club but that you should not be allowed to hold one
again.
</P>
<P>
   Golfers will turn almost anywhere for help. In the course of a
playing career, most will spend time taking lessons from a pro,
buying weird gadgets that add to the humiliation of golf when worn,
reading books that contradict each other proudly, and nowadays
turning to the gods of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   There are some terrific sites that offer golf information _ as
long as you make your visits with the solid realization the advice
there is no different than you'd find from conventional sources.
You can get the same useless tips you'd hear from the books and
video courses. But you'll get them free.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, there's more to most commercial golf sites than
instruction. Let's drop in on one of the really good ones, Golf Web
at www.golfweb.com/. The opening page heavily emphasizes golf news.
You'll be able to click on any of the news summaries and be taken
to the full story. You'll also find links that take you to areas
where you can have live chats with other golfers and to leave
messages asking for advice (none of which will help, some of which
will hurt).
</P>
<P>
   One nice feature of this page is the classifieds section. You
can buy golf clubs and other used gear or sell your equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The next site on our cyber-tour is called Golfonline at www
</P>
<P>
   .golfonline.com/. At first glance, it offers the same sort of
information as the first site. The two even look a little alike.
But one of this site's pluses is that it is run by the folks who
publish Golf magazine. So you can look forward to good writing and
also a real feeling of golfing expertise. One fun feature is the
weekly survey. You can give your opinion and also read what others
think. When I last visited, users were surveyed on the most hated
rules of golf.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of other general purpose golf sites and _
frankly _ there doesn't seem to be a dime's worth of difference in
the look, features and appearance of them. You could try 19thHole
</P>
<P>
   .Com at www.19thHole.com/ or About.Com's About Golf site at
golf.about.com/. These are all good sites; there's just not much
difference in what you'll find. So pick your favorite.
</P>
<P>
   One of the real benefits the Web offers a golfer is a way to
check out a new golf course. Most of the Web sites mentioned offer
this service in one form or another. But some courses are too small
to be featured on these compilations.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, you'll find a listing of many courses at
www.netcaddie
</P>
<P>
   .com/ga/georgia.htm. If you live in another state, go to
www.netcaddie
</P>
<P>
   .com and select your state from the list. If you still can't
find a course, you can use one of the regular search engines such
as AltaVista at www.altavista.com and do the searching on your own.
Most state and private courses have some sort of a presence on the
Web, so there's a good chance you'll find the information you need
about course fees, layout and telephone numbers to make tee times.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
