<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Official site' too often means `corporately dull'
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Let's talk about the Backstreet Boys and the Web.
According to a study released by the Web measurement gurus at Media
Metrix, visitors to the Backstreet Boys' official Web site at www
</P>
<P>
   .backstreetboys.com are 86.9 percent kids. Based on no
scientific knowledge whatsoever, I would venture to guess that this
86.9 percent is probably preteen, teen-age and twentysomething
female fans looking for the latest official news and gossip about
these very cool and very cute pop sensations.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking as a former teen-age girl, I have to say the Backstreet
Boys' official site isn't really all that good, and this probably
has nothing to do with the guys themselves. The fault is with the
designers, the record company and everybody who had input into the
official site.
</P>
<P>
   An official Web site for anything, whether it's the new ``Star
Wars'' movie or a NASA mission, is usually the first place people
go to when searching for something. The innocent assumption is that
an official site will be the place where fans can get the real
inside news, look at the best photos, listen to officially
sanctioned clips and, in this case, have generally a really great
time staring at pictures of cute guys and listening to their cool
songs.
</P>
<P>
   However, the folks who run the Backstreet Boys' Web site clearly
have never met any teen-age girls. For one thing, the home page
plugs the guys' latest CD, ``Millennium.'' You don't have to have a
Ph.D. to figure out that most of the girls hitting the site already
own the CD and are looking for more detailed and personal
information, maybe some pictures. Really big, really cute pictures.
Or how about interviews with the band, or something that would take
advantage of the site's official status to show fans pictures they
haven't seen and tell them things they might not otherwise know?
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Irish alternative band, The Cranberries, used
its official site as the exclusive place to buy concert tickets
online. That's pretty cool. No boring Ticketmaster sites for
Cranberries fans; they get to check out a fan page when ordering
tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, nobody expects the Backstreet Boys to post their home
phone numbers on the Web site, and the server would probably crash
if they even thought about offering tickets on their site. Still,
it would be nice if sites like this one, which clearly know who
their audience is, would do a better job of giving fans what they
want. The Backstreet Boys, Brittany Spears, Ricky Martin and other
pop idols ought to have figured out by now that official Web sites
are to the Internet what music videos are to MTV _ an incredible
promotional vehicle if used right.
</P>
<P>
   The Backstreet Boys' official site has chintzy pictures (too
small, too hard to see and not labeled, so you can't even tell
where the guys are performing). Hard copy teen magazines do an
incredible job of describing every move, every twitch and every
last harmless detail of teen stars and celebrities, and they sell a
lot of magazines.
</P>
<P>
   The Backstreet Boys don't need to reinvent the wheel, they just
need to understand what their fans want to see. Alison's Backstreet
Boys Wonderland (www
</P>
<P>
   .geocities.com/SunsetStrip
</P>
<P>
   /Backstage/1823), a site built by a loyal fan, is a far better
site. Organized Yahoo!-style by various topics, including
biographies, song lyrics, the latest news and, best of all, really
big pictures, it has a ``gee aren't these guys cool'' tone that
really captures how much fun it is to read about your favorite
stars and stare at their pictures.
</P>
<P>
   What can be learned from a very brief tour of Backstreet Boys
Web sites is that the official site isn't always the best site.
When it comes to entertainment on the Web, sometimes fans can do a
better job of giving other fans what they want than the corporate
entities often responsible for the ``official'' sites.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, there was a woman named Bonnie, I think, who
was a huge fan of MTV's ``The Real World.'' For the uninitiated,
``The Real World'' is a popular series that throws seven strangers
into a very snazzy, trendy house in a trendy city, turns on the
cameras and lets the roommates go at each other. Bonnie's site had
cast photos, weekly plot summaries, ``where are they now''
information, bits of gossip almost always verified before they were
posted and an archive of past seasons. For ``Real World'' fans, it
was a wonderful site. However, as the years wore on, Bonnie's
interest in the show waned, and she decided not to keep up with
``The Real World'' any more.
</P>
<P>
   MTV decided to pick up the slack and offers a ``Real World''
area on its Web site that looks a bit like Bonnie's but is much
more corporate. The focus is less on the fun and more on promoting
the show so more people will watch it. That's where fan sites are
far superior to official sites in many cases. They don't have to be
told that TV shows, movies and rock stars are entertainment with a
focus on fun.
</P>
<P>
   If a user comes to a Web site called Backstreet Boys.com or
StarWars.com, they are clearly looking for fun. Publicity is nice,
but people will turn up at the concert, the movie theater, the
record shop and the toy store if the corporate types who build
official Web sites could remember that entertainment is meant to be
just that_ entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
