<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta's 10 most wanted bugs
 &HT;    By Keith Still
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Step outside in your back yard this summer and you
won't be alone. In fact, you'll be surrounded by countless insects
and spiders. Sounds creepy, but before you call the exterminator or
crush the critters with your shoe, remember that not all bugs are
pests.
</P>
<P>
   Your yard needs some bugs, such as butterflies, praying mantises
and ladybugs, to stay healthy, and you'll want them around because
they can keep annoying insects away.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be frightened by spiders, either. As long as it's not a
brown recluse or a black widow, it will eat flies and mosquitoes
while you finish off those curds and whey.
</P>
<P>
   If all of this sounds interesting to you, then you may want to
consider a career in the field of entomology, or the study of
insects. One of the great things about the study of entomology is
that it's a ``very, very wide field,'' says Fred Sherberger, an
entomologist at DeKalb County's Fernbank Science Center.
</P>
<P>
   Entomologists can be found teaching in universities, working in
museums and zoos, doing research or survey work for government
agencies, working in pest management or looking for new species of
insects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, there are about one million different species of
insects that have been identified throughout the world,'' says
Duane Jackson, Zoo Atlanta curator of insects and associate
professor of psychology at Morehouse College. He specializes in
insect behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year, entomologists find between 700 to 800 new
species,'' he says. ``A few have been found in people's back yards,
so it's possible that a kid could find an insect that has never
been identified before.''
</P>
<P>
   If you want to learn more about entomology, places like Fernbank
sometimes offer summer programs on the subject. Schools can
schedule field trips to Fernbank, where seventh-graders can take
Sherberger's ``Insects and Adaptations'' class and fifth-graders
can take a class called ``Creatures That Sting.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the entomology bug has bitten you bad, remember that one
of the best labs for studying insects can be found right in your
own back yard. You can start by entering our bug search contest
shown at right.
</P>
<P>
   Case File:
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Swallowtail (Papilio glaucus) _ If you like pretty flowers
in your yard, thank the Tiger Swallowtail for helping to pollinate
them. As the state butterfly of Georgia, this black and yellow
butterfly is easy to spot. It's also one of the largest butterflies
in North America, with a wingspan of up to 5.5 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Gulf Fritillary (Argraulis vanillae) _ This butterfly's upper
wings are red-orange with a few black spots. Its lower wings are
dull to rich brown or olive-colored and can have silver-white
streaks. It loves open, sunny areas with lots of flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Buckeye (Junonia coenia) _ Buckeyes are mainly brown butterflies
with eye-shaped spots on their upper and lower wings. Some people
believe the eyespots are used to scare away predators. Buckeyes
pollinate flowers and like open, sunny areas with low vegetation.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Spotted Skipper (Epargyreus clarus) _ Is the skipper a
butterfly or a moth or its own separate category? That's up for
debate. It has a thick body like a moth, but thin antennae like
butterflies. Like a butterfly, the skipper flies during the day,
but has a drab color like moths. Look for the silver spotted
skipper in open, sunny areas.
</P>
<P>
   Ladybug (Coccinella novemnotata) _ These cute, red-and-black
bugs feast on the aphids that like to eat your mom's favorite
plants. The Coccinella novemnotata is one of more than 350 kinds of
ladybugs found in North America. They have black dots on their back
and can be found perched on the leaves of a variety of plants.
</P>
<P>
   Hummingbird Moth (Hemaris thysbe) _ This moth got its name
because it resembles a hummingbird in flight. In fact, it's not
uncommon for people to confuse the two. Like butterflies and
skippers, moths help pollinate flowers, but they generally fly at
night.
</P>
<P>
   Honeybee (Apis mellifera) _ Honeybees play a key role in
pollination when they fly from flower to flower sipping nectar. As
their name suggests, they also make honey. The honeybee has a
reddish-brown body with orange-yellow rings on its abdomen. Its
head, antennae and legs are black. Look for them near a patch of
flowers in the bright sun.
</P>
<P>
   Praying Mantis (Mantis religiosa) _ Gardeners often place
praying mantises in their gardens because they eat a variety of
pests. You can find them perched several feet off the ground on
leaves or on the bark of trees. But look carefully _ they are very
well-camouflaged and will be small this time of year because they
just hatched.
</P>
<P>
   Black and Yellow Argiope (Argiope aurantia) _ All spiders
contain poison, but most of the spiders in metro Atlanta are no
more harmful to humans than a bee sting. The Black and Yellow
Argiope eats pests like flies and mosquitoes. Look in a sunny place
for its spiraling webs with an X-shaped mark in the center.
</P>
<P>
   Soldier Beetle _ also known as Pennsylvania Leather-wing
(Chauliognatus Pennsylvanicus) _ Soldier beetles eat aphids, which
are harmful to plants, and the larval form of certain moths that
can damage agriculture crops. They can be found along roads or in
meadows nestled among goldenrod blossoms.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
