A4318 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECHNOBUDDY15-COX     06-14 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elementary etiquette enhances e-mail enjoyment
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I go in spells _ in starts and stops like a balky 1974
Toyota _ when it comes to e-mail. It's one of those things that
seem to grow until, next thing you know, I spend most of my
evenings answering mail. Then I sort of shut down shop and decide
to move more of my life into the real world.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, when I do that, I discover all of a sudden that I
don't have a real life. Like a lot of people, I spend way too much
time at work, sometimes coming in before 8 o'clock and leaving
around that time in the evening. Once you factor in feeding the cat
and myself, that doesn't leave much time. So I start up that 1974
Toyota again and resume old conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these conversations span an enormous chunk of time _ my
longest-lived e-mail conversation goes back to 1993. So I think of
myself as a real expert on the important side of e-mail. You'll
read a lot, including from me at times, about security and
passwords and the mechanics of setting up an e-mail program. But
for today, we'll talk about some really basic tips that will make
e-mail more fun and that will increase the likelihood of a long and
interesting conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Husted's first rule of e-mail is that you must assume your
correspondent may have literally dozens of conversations going at
once by e-mail. Now that it is become part of daily life, most of
us get e-mail _ at home and work _ that is a mixture of personal
and business correspondence. When answering an e-mail, don't assume
the recipient remembers what he asked you several days before.
Include a snippet from the question, to avoid confusion. Otherwise,
like me, he may have to puzzle over the meaning of e-mails that
say: ``Yes, go right ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Along that same line of reasoning, you must assume your
correspondent has some sort of a life outside e-mail. Don't get
overly concerned if your mail remains unanswered for days, or if
you get a short and to-the-point reply. There's nothing worse than
turning a pleasant e-mail conversation into a guilt trip, in which
the recipient feels as if he has to answer quickly and at length.
When you are using e-mail as a modern substitute for having a pen
pal, the whole notion is to keep things fun.
</P>
<P>
   One really horrible trend, at least for me, is that folks
nowadays tend to attach two or three photographs or even a small
computer program. It's not that I don't like to see photos; it's
that they can take forever to download. At times I have gone home
for the evening, turned on the computer to check my e-mail and sat
for a long time watching photos and other attachments download.
</P>
<P>
   There's a second reason many of us don't like getting
unsolicited attachments: They can contain programs or even Word
documents with viruses. So don't stop sending photos and
attachments _ simply ask first if your recipient would like to
receive them. If I know I have photos or other data-heavy stuff
coming, I tell the sender when to send it and pick a time that is
convenient for me.
</P>
<P>
   But my real pet peeve comes from the well-meaning folks who
forward messages about viruses (there are more virus hoaxes than
viruses) or some other weird Internet scheme. Avoid forwarding
messages that Bill Gates will give the next 100 people who e-mail
him a million dollars or that a foundation in Des Moines is
collecting cigarette wrappers to buy an iron lung for some
deserving kid.
</P>
<P>
   Don't rely on the assurances of the sender that a friend told
him it was true. Just don't send it. Also, please don't simply
forward a joke you've found unless you know for a fact that your
friend loves to receive them. If you don't have anything to say at
all, try something really unusual these days: Just be quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Which is what I'm going to do right now.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
