<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN DO YOU WAVE OFF A WALK-IN? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 20)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics. Double parentheses
should be set as brackets.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I asked Rep. Chris Cox if the Chinese  &UR; walk-in &LR;  was a  &UR; dangle &LR; ,
and he  &UR; waved me off &LR; . Thirty years before, I asked Jim Angleton of
the CIA if the Nosenko  &UR; walk-in &LR;  was what he called a  &UR; dangle &LR; , and
he  &UR; waved me on &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Times change, adversaries shift, but spookspeak _ the inside
lingo of the intelligence trade _ lives on. Those who confuse a
 &UR; drop-dead &LR;  dress with a  &UR; dead-drop &LR;  address have not come in from
the cold and are unable to cope with delicious nuances of
espionage.
</P>
<P>
   In the three volumes published by the House Select Committee on
U.S. National Security and Military-Commercial Concerns With the
People's Republic of China, a k a the Cox Report
(www.house.gov/coxreport), this drama is teased: ``In 1995, a
 &UR; `walk-in' &LR;  approached the CIA outside of the PRC and provided an
official PRC document classified `Secret' that contained design
information on the W-88 Trident D-5 warhead.''
</P>
<P>
   The report helpfully cited the definition of  &UR; walk-in &LR;  in ``Spy
Book: The Encyclopedia of Espionage,'' by Norman Polmar and Thomas
B. Allen: ``an unheralded defector or a  &UR; dangle &LR; , a  &UR; `walk-in' &LR;  is
a potential agent or a mole who literally walks into an embassy or
intelligence agency without prior contact or recruitment.''
</P>
<P>
   Note those ``ors'': If the  &UR; walk-in &LR;  is a true defector, the spy
becomes a potential agent for the side walked in on; if he or she
is a  &UR; dangle &LR; , the spy is seen as a potential  &UR; mole &LR; , a word coined
by the novelist John le Carre to mean ``penetration agent.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dangle &LR;  is a Danish verb meaning ``to hang so as to swing
freely.'' In its espionage sense, a  &UR; dangle &LR;  is like a delicious
morsel swung in front of the nose of a slavering animal. The
 &UR; dangle &LR;  is a tempter, much like the serpent in the Garden of Eden,
offering an apple of discord to the spy agency that welcomes and
trusts the  &UR; walk-in &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Cox, a buttoned-up attorney not given to colorful language,
apparently felt the need for a cooler term for  &UR; dangle &LR; . He chose
 &UR; directed walk-in &LR; , ``purposefully directed by the PRC to provide
this information to the United States.'' (The specific
 &UR; purposefully &LR;  means ``with intent to carry out a given purpose'';
the general  &UR; purposely &LR;  means ``on purpose, not accidentally.'')
Spy novelists hope the compound, formalized Cox synonym for
 &UR; dangle &LR;  does not catch on.
</P>
<P>
   Although the earliest printed citation in the Dow Jones database
for  &UR; dangle &LR;  in the specialized sense is from 1985, I heard it in
1970 from the lips of James Jesus Angleton, the legendary
counterintelligence chief of the CIA.
</P>
<P>
   He was deeply suspicious of the bona fides of Yuri Nosenko, a
Soviet  &UR; walk-in &LR;  who transmitted to the United States information
about Lee Harvey Oswald dissociating Moscow from the Kennedy
assassination.
</P>
<P>
   Angleton, an orchid-raising fishing enthusiast and poetry lover
nicknamed Mother, talked of Nosenko as ``a probable  &UR; dangle &LR; '' and
what he brought in as ``feed material,'' both phrases taken from
fishing. To this day, his supposition that Nosenko was supplying
disinformation is fiercely disputed within the agency.
</P>
<P>
   When I asked if I would be wise to think of Nosenko as what
Angleton called a  &UR; dangle &LR; , he replied only that he would not  &UR; wave
me off &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   To  &UR; wave off &LR; , in hockey, means not to count a goal even though
it looks as if the puck went into the net. In auto racing, a driver
has the chance to  &UR; wave off &LR;  his qualifying laps if he doesn't
think his car is making good enough time. On aircraft carriers, it
is to abort a landing. In general colloquial use, it means ``to
disregard or dismiss.''
</P>
<P>
   In journalingo, akin to spookspeak because of their commonality
of snooping, to  &UR; wave off &LR;  means ``to suggest a hypothesis is
mistaken without denying it.'' The earliest citation I can find,
unfortunately, is in a column of my own in 1981: ``As columnist
Jack Anderson was about to write of the secretary's incipient ((I
meant imminent)) departure, the secretary of state ((Al Haig))
panicked to the point of begging the president to call the newsman
to  &UR; wave him off &LR;  the story. Mr. Reagan complied.''
</P>
<P>
   If the reporter is not  &UR; waved off &LR;  a story by a source, is the
source tacitly confirming it? No. In 1990, Attorney General Dick
Thornburgh deplored the fact that ``the media on occasion
interprets the fact that we will not deny information or  &UR; wave them
off &LR;  of a story as confirmation of an unauthorized disclosure.''
</P>
<P>
   However, when a source, worried about confirming a leak,  &UR; waves
a reporter off &LR;  a story that is true (as Cox did with my early
query about a  &UR; walk-in &LR; ), that is considered by the inquirer to be
a misstep in the symbiosis minuet.
</P>
<P>
   THINKING TO MYSELF
</P>
<P>
   Clifford Irving has just published the hoax he went to jail for
a generation ago, ``Autobiography of Howard Hughes.'' Because no
ordinary publisher would touch ``the most famous unpublished book
of the 20th century,'' Irving is selling it through
terrificbooks.com.
</P>
<P>
   I thought to myself, How can he get away with it? And he
replied:
</P>
<P>
   ``What other way can you think, other than to yourself? You
can't think to someone else, and you can only think aloud in
special fictional circumstances that are really not antithetical to
 &UR; thinking to yourself &LR; ; thinking aloud contrasts only with
thinking. Let's put a stop to this.''
</P>
<P>
   The Squad Squad, hunter of prolix tautologies, salutes him:
 &UR; Think to yourself &LR;  is redundant. As the Cartesians say, ``I think;
therefore I  &UR; think to myself &LR; .'' But still, I have to wonder, How
does Cliff get away with it?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-99 1124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990614.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 11:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4330 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PERENNIAL-LAVENDER-LI     06-14 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERENNIAL-LAVENDER-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERENNIAL LAVENDER GIVES MUCH AND ASKS LITTLE
</HEADLINE>
  Includes color photos of a field of lavender and a close-up of a
sprig of lavender 
 By MEG MCCONAHEY 
 c.1999 NYT Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the perfect garden plant _ bewitching, aromatic,
restorative, the stuff of romance and scented memories _ and it
doesn't ask for much.
</P>
<P>
   Breaker waves of hardy, old-fashioned lavender in deep purple
and violet blue are washing across the landscape as home gardeners
increasingly discover, or rediscover, the virtues of the perennial
herb that for millennia has inspired poets, perfumiers and natural
healers.
</P>
<P>
   Stubbornly self-reliant, demanding only infrequent watering and
repugnant to deer, gophers and other garden thieves, lavender is
both ornamental and practical. With a little attention to timely
pruning and selection, gardeners could arrange to have some
lavender in glorious purple bloom every month of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Its many useful products have found a place in modern spice
racks, medicine cabinets, dried flower arrangements, beside the
bathtub, in undie drawers and even on the bed in the form of tiny
''pillows'' that according to lore, foster sleep and sweet dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Lavender lovers hold forth with the zeal of religious converts.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you told me I could have only one plant in my garden it
would be lavender. It's wonderful. It's gorgeous. I'm just so
attached to it I can't seem to bring myself to grow anything
else,'' said Myra Portwood, whose property overlooking the
Freestone Valley in California is aflame in spring and summer with
100 to 200 lavender plants _ including a lavender hedge, a second
line of defense in front of her deer fence.
</P>
<P>
   Fueling the lavender fervor is Robert Kourik, a landscape design
consultant and garden writer whose book ''The Lavender Garden''
(Chronicle Books, $18.95) is quickly becoming the bible of American
lavender growers, the first book, he said, published in America by
an American for American lavender growers.
</P>
<P>
   Kourik selected 16 commonly found lavender varieties for the
book. He provides tips on planting, cultivating, pruning,
harvesting and drying and instructions on how to put a ''crop'' to
good use in potpourri, cooking and toiletries.
</P>
<P>
   ''The romance of lavender is back,'' said Kourik. ''A lot of our
mothers and grandmothers used it in some form so it has a floral
memory in people's brains, and it's very versatile both as a fresh
and dried cut flower. It makes a great landscaping plant, and it's
very low maintenance. It gets no diseases if you give it the
drainage it requires, and it grows prolifically. There are some
varieties that get up to 6 feet tall, and you can choose all the
way down to cute little compact plants that don't get any taller
than 8 inches. So there's a size to fit every section of the
garden.''
</P>
<P>
   Although lavender blooms in the spring and summer, has fall is
the perfect time to plant lavender to get that amethyst beauty and
heady scent by next spring.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you put the plant in, the top doesn't seem to be doing
anything, but the roots are growing into the soil with the winter
rains,'' he said. ''In the spring, it makes a full foliage but its
roots are more expansive, both in width and depth. Whereas, if you
plant in spring, when you're inspired, the plant doesn't have any
chance to get a root system in before the dryness of June hits.''
</P>
<P>
   Lavender planted in the fall may need little or no irrigation. A
monthly watering, said Kourik, could be enough. Lavender needs
alkaline soil, and little fertilization, just good drainage, so if
you have heavy, clay soil, plant in deep, gravel-lined holes or
raised beds. Also, growers in areas that have cold winters will
want to select a hearty variety.
</P>
<P>
   Kourik said his initial interest in the ornament herb was merely
pragmatic. It proved the ideal landscaping solution in an area
where deer were eating the plants. But practicality doesn't really
explain the sway the woody shrub holds over humans with, as Kourik
writes, its ''unique fragrance emitted by a complex oil with over
180 different constituents and unduplicated by the chemistry of any
other plant.''
</P>
<P>
   The lavender guru admits to being thoroughly besotted with the
aromatic shrub Romans used for luxurious baths, Medievals spread to
ward off the Black Death and French courtiers dabbed on their wigs
and gloves to mask the sins of poor hygiene.
</P>
<P>
   Kourik, who defined the genre of edible landscaping, started
experimenting with cooking lavender, even throwing the long stems
on the grill for smoking food.
</P>
<P>
   Lavender, which can easily substitute for rosemary, is finding
its way into more chef's recipes _ in ice creams, grilled foods and
with lamb and trout.
</P>
<P>
   More and more products also are being infused with a scent that,
depending on the variety, can be woody, floral, hay-like, citrusy
or any of dozens of other descriptors.
</P>
<P>
   Lavender is being paired with pumpkin in soaps and food as a
sort-of natural alternative to Viagra. And cosmetic and toiletry
companies are coming up with ever more lavender concoctions for
aromatherapy and personal pampering.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes Magazine last year declared the homespun herb suddenly
''chic'' _ with the price of the drid plant nearly doubling to $27
a pound as baby boomers with disposable income turn to lavender as
a cure-all for every ill from headaches and hair loss to dandruff
and bladder infections. Lavender is believed to be good for aging
skin, burns and muscle pain and by releasing serotonin in the
brain, induces a calming effect to relieve migraines and improve
sleep. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Meg McConahey writes for The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa,
Calif.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this ``separate buy'' article, call
New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
(732) 390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
