Mateo misses in first shot at hero's role 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ It could have been the stuff dreams are made
of.
</P>
<P>
   Ruben Mateo, in only his second major-league game, had his
chance, batting with two outs and two on in the ninth inning, his
team down by two runs. A home run there and the first chapter of
the Mateo legend would have been written.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the harsh reality of the big leagues prevailed.
Colorado Rockies closer Dave Veres struck out Mateo with a 2-2
fastball and the Rangers fell, 4-2, at The Ballpark in Arlington
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll all be put in that situation sometime,'' Rangers manager
Johnny Oates said. ``I'm sure Ruben will be critiqued every time he
takes a step, whether that's right or wrong. But he's young, he's
going to get a few hits in those situations before it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Mateo, 0-for-4 with two strikeouts, wasn't the only Rangers'
hitter to struggle yesterday. Other than back-to-back home runs by
Juan Gonzalez and Rafael Palmeiro in the fourth inning, the
Rangers' offense mounted little against Rockies starter Bobby Jones
and two relievers.
</P>
<P>
   Mateo had the best chance of erasing the Rangers' frustrations
with some ninth-inning heroics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he could handle it,'' Palmeiro said. ``He came up
yesterday and hit a home run. I thought he wanted to be in that
situation. I know it's a lot to ask, but he's an exceptional
player. He'll thrive on those situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Veres pitched the Rangers' rookie carefully with a diet of
off-speed pitches before getting the fastball by him for strike
three.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't trying to win it, I was just trying to get a base hit
or something,'' Mateo said. ``It just didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still a little bit excited, but I was much better today. I
know tomorrow it's going to get better. Every day will be better.
I'm going to be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro has thrived in those situations as much as anybody, but
he also missed his chance, striking out against Jones with two on
and two out in the fifth. Jones caught Palmeiro going after a pitch
out of the strike zone for strike three, an example of the
impatience the Rangers showed all afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their guys threw pretty good, but we helped them a lot,''
Palmeiro said. ``They threw a lot off-speed stuff and sliders and
we were swinging at them. It's going to happen. I wish we could do
it right every time, but it's not going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Starter Mike Morgan put the Rangers in their hole, allowing four
runs in the second inning. All came with two outs. Angel Echevarria
grounded a single through the right side, and Lenny Harris drew a
walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``A terrible walk, right there with two outs,'' Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan then threw a slider to Kurt Abbott, who crushed it deep
into the left-field bleachers for a three-run homer. Abbott was
0-for-6 with three strikeouts in his career against Morgan before
that blast.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Blanco followed with a triple, and Darryl Hamilton's
single gave the Rockies a 4-0 lead. Morgan rallied from that to
throw five scoreless innings recover from his early troubles].
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the best I've thrown since Toronto,'' said Morgan,
referring to a 4-3 victory on May 8 against the Blue Jays before on
onset of injuries. ``It's something for me to build on. But it's
still a loss and tough to swallow.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
