A4352 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     06-14 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NATIONAL MILESTONE FOR BIZARRENESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On June 13, 1994, news of the previous night's double murder in
Los Angeles was just beginning to spread across America. Over the
next 16 months, the crime and its aftermath would become a national
obsession.
</P>
<P>
   The victims were Nicole Brown Simpson, ex-wife of former
football star O.J. Simpson, and her friend Ron Goldman. They were
savagely stabbed and slashed to death _ a cop called it
``overkill'' _ outside Nicole's condominium.
</P>
<P>
   There may have been those who immediately jumped to the
conclusion that O.J. Simpson had committed this horrible crime, but
I wasn't one of them. My first reaction was sympathy for the
athlete/actor/commercial pitchman whose two young children had lost
their mother to a vicious killer.
</P>
<P>
   If memory serves, the early news reports noted that O.J. was in
Chicago on the night of June 12 _ a fact that seemed to suggest no
involvement by him. But Simpson's presumption of innocence didn't
last long.
</P>
<P>
   Five days after the killings, Simpson was charged with murder
and embarked on the infamous ``low-speed chase'' along the freeways
of Southern California. That adventure _ carried live on nationwide
television and ending with Simpson's surrender to police in the
driveway of his elegant home _ seemed plenty bizarre.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with events that would follow, however, the weird car
chase barely moved the needle on the bizarreness meter.
</P>
<P>
   It will surely be a long time before we witness a court
proceeding as bizarre as Simpson's murder trial in Los Angeles;
before we see an infomercial as bizarre as the post-trial videotape
that O.J. marketed in a futile attempt to convince the world of his
innocence; before we see a media juxtaposition as bizarre as the
near-simultaneous coverage of a presidential State of the Union
speech and the verdict in Simpson's civil trial.
</P>
<P>
   If none of that was bizarre enough for your taste, how about
Simpson's successful court fight for custody of the children whose
mother he allegedly butchered? How about his incessant print and
broadcast interviews proclaiming his innocence and predicting the
eventual apprehension of the ``real killer''?
</P>
<P>
   Or how about his carefree lifestyle, financed by a
$25,000-per-month, judgment-proof annuity that lets him while away
his days playing golf?
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the bizarreness spectrum, of course, there
are Ron Goldman's father and sister, who continue to hound Simpson
like Ahab chasing the whale. They won their civil suit _ and a
multimillion-dollar judgment that they'll never collect _ but still
can't come to grips with the reality of Simpson's acquittal in the
criminal trial.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yes, the criminal trial. The definition of ``bizarre.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors showed up with what they proudly described as a
``mountain of evidence'' and set about conducting a clinic in the
art of blowing an open-and-shut murder case. The cops who
investigated the murders and the assistant district attorneys who
presented the case exhibited such a breathtaking combination of
obnoxiousness and ineptitude that the jurors were more than ready
to consider the defense's relentless arguments for reasonable
doubt.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors who declared O.J. not guilty in October 1995 have
been vilified for their decision, but I say they had no choice. I'm
only slightly embarrassed to confess that I followed the trial
virtually gavel to gavel, and if I'd been on that jury, I would
have voted ``not guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution simply didn't prove Simpson's guilt beyond a
reasonable doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, I'm open to the possibility that O.J. didn't do it,
that his predictions of vindication might one day come true. It's a
long shot, I know, but when a defendant is found not guilty of a
crime by a jury of his peers, it hardly seems unreasonable to
wonder if the accused might actually be innocent.
</P>
<P>
   If Simpson got away with murder, well, nobody said our justice
system was perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the system survived the O.J. case, despite dire
warnings of its imminent demise. And that's the one shred of good
news in the whole sorry mess.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
