A4354 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-DYNASTY-TEX     06-14 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-DYNASTY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY PRECEDENT: ELDER BUSH REJECTS NOTION OF DYNASTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine _ They have the same name, the same facial
expressions, the same family background. Now the son is seeking to
share a place in history with his father.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 175 years after John Quincy Adams followed his father
into the White House, Texas Gov. George W. Bush wants to do the
same for his family. But don't use the term ``dynasty'' around his
dad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never felt entitled to something,'' former President Bush
said. ``Dynasty, to me, at least, connotes the expectation of
something coming your way. I never felt that way. I don't like the
concept of dynasty.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the sense of family destiny was hard to miss Sunday as
Bush and his son joined other relatives at the family compound on
the Maine coast. Under a sunny sky tempered by a cool coastal
breeze, the former president and his wife, Barbara, beamed at the
son who wants to reclaim the office that his father lost in a
humiliating defeat seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``What goes around, comes around,'' the elder Bush said. ``I got
some things right, maybe messed some things up. It's his turn now
in the family.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Bush put it in Texas terms: ``I feel like we done good
with this boy.''
</P>
<P>
   The 52-year-old governor, who took the day off between campaign
stops in Iowa and New Hampshire, said it was only fitting that he
come to Kennebunkport on his first presidential campaign swing.
Bush said that watching his father deal with his loss to Bill
Clinton steeled him for his own campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned that life doesn't end if you lose a campaign,''
he said. ``This is an appropriate place to talk about it. This is
the place where we find love and comfort, where we know the values
of life that are bigger than straw polls and caucuses and
primaries.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush clan, including three of the former president's four
sons, his daughter and his 10 grandchildren, gathered to mark the
elder Bush's 75th birthday Saturday. Florida Gov. Jeb Bush missed
the reunion, an absence that left the spotlight solely on his older
brother.
</P>
<P>
   George and Barbara Bush said they have been intently following
TV coverage of their son's campaign debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see George out in Iowa, and I say, `Hey, I've been there,'''
the elder Bush said. ``We thought it was a good start, but we would
admit that we are probably the two most nonobjective people in the
United States when it comes to support for this son of ours.''
</P>
<P>
   The proud parents maintained their good humor when a reporter
asked the former president to explain how voters could reject him
but put his son at the top of campaign 2000 polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he means is, you were unpopular,'' Barbara Bush joked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was,'' Bush said. ``Maybe I'm a little egotistical. I think
the American people, at least from surveys I've seen, have been
rather pleasant about me, and certainly about Barbara, so I don't
worry about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he refrains from giving his son advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't need a voice from the past,'' he said. ``I think
it's better to let George now make his own way, which he seems to
be doing very, very well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor has spent much of his life following a path
set by his father. Both Bushes attended prep school at the Phillips
Academy in Andover, Mass., before enrolling at Yale University,
where they both served as president of the Delta Kappa Epsilon
fraternity and joined the secretive Skull and Bones social club.
</P>
<P>
   Both men learned to fly in the military _ the former president
during World War II and his son as a member of the Texas Air
National Guard. Both sought their fortune in the West Texas
oilfields.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lived with being `George Bush's son' all my life,'' the
governor wrote in a Father's Day reminiscence for P.O.V., a men's
magazine. ``Growing up, I probably didn't want to be like him.''
</P>
<P>
   Family friends say that any teen-age resentment about life with
a famous father is long gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have unconditional love for each other,'' said Midland,
Texas, oilman Don Evans, one of the governor's closest friends.
``George, the governor, is just very content with who he is. He
doesn't spend a lot of time trying to figure out what his score
card looks like vs. somebody else's score card.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their many similarities, father and son have distinct
personalities, shaped in large part by their childhood
surroundings. Although they both claim Texas as home, the younger
Bush often says that the biggest difference is that he grew up in
Midland and his dad spent his childhood in Greenwich.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the younger Bush is more conservative, more
outspoken and more outgoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``George W. is much more Texan than his dad,'' said former
Transportation Secretary Andrew Card. ``President Bush wouldn't
like me saying this, but I see a lot more New England, Old Yankee
in his dad than I do in the governor. But I think that values that
come of that hearty New England stock are very much present in
Governor Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger Bush, who went fishing with his father Sunday
morning, said he considers his parental ties ``a huge plus'' in the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll just see what happens,'' he said. ``If it works out, I'm
ready. And if it doesn't work out, me and the old boy will spend a
lot of time fishing together.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
