r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAPTIST-VEGETARIANS-T     06-14 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTIST-VEGETARIANS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VEGETARIANS PLAN CAMPAIGN TO CONVERT SOUTHERN BAPTISTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Southern Baptists have targeted other groups for conversion in
the past. Now, the tables are turned. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This week, when thousands of Baptists arrive in Atlanta for
their national convention, they will be greeted by a 60-foot by
20-foot billboard declaring, ``Jesus Was a Vegetarian.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We are taking our message to Baptists that killing and eating
animals is inherently un-Christian,'' said Bruce G. Friedrich, a
spokesman for People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals. ``Jesus
was the Prince of Peace, not a butcher.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Baptists met in Salt Lake City and carried out
door-to-door evangelism campaigns among members of the Church of
Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints. Anti-Defamation League officials
objected three years ago when a resolution was approved calling for
a ``missionary'' to Jewish people. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The vegetarian crusade could be one of the more provocative
events in a convention in which about 14,000 delegates will focus
more on winning new converts than on conflict. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It won't be emphasized, but this year's meeting in the Georgia
Dome on Tuesday and Wednesday marks the 20th anniversary of the
beginning of the conservative rise to power over moderates in the
country's largest non-Catholic denomination. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It may seem unlikely that the pro-vegetarian crusade will win
over many of the Southern Baptists. But Friedrich said the animal
rights group plans to have a man dressed like Jesus parading
outside the Georgia Dome carrying a sign declaring, ``For Christ's
Sake _ Go Vegetarian.'' Another will dress like a chicken and
display a sign saying ``Meat is Murder.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Baptists have several banquets scheduled for the meeting, and
none are likely to be meatless, predicted Jennette Briggs, director
of alumni affairs at Southwestern Baptist Theological Seminary in
Fort Worth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She's in charge of an alumni luncheon where chicken enchiladas
will be served. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do have vegetarians, they are out of luck,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One Texas Baptist preacher said biblical evidence doesn't
indicate that Jesus refrained from meat. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the biggest bunch of baloney I've ever heard,'' said
the Rev. Charles Clary, pastor of the Tate Springs Baptist Church
in Arlington, Texas. ``All the Jewish feasts involved meat, and
Jesus was a good Jewish man.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clary said the stereotype about Baptists and chicken dinners is
accurate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This Baptist here eats chicken, beef, pork _ anything that's
not moving on my plate,'' he said. ``I've even eaten
rattlesnake.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The animal rights group's first ``Jesus Was a Vegetarian''
billboard was put up across from Oral Roberts University in Tulsa,
Oklahoma, in December. The sign carries the Dulles, Va.,
organization's Web site address, www.jesusveg.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When a ``Jesus Was a Vegetarian'' billboard was displayed in
Amarillo, Texas, on March 9, it received numerous protests. A sign
company quickly took down the sign after the Amarillo Society for
the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals reported that a caller had
threatened to burn one cat per day until the sign was removed. No
cats were harmed, police said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the two early leaders of the conservative movement, Paige
Patterson, is expected to be re-elected president of the convention
without opposition. The former Dallasite is also president of
Southeastern Baptist Theological Seminary in Wake Forest, N.C. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The man who teamed with Patterson in 1979 to begin unseating
moderates from control of the denomination, Judge Paul Pressler of
Houston, will be at the meeting promoting his new book, ``A Hill on
Which to Die.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Baptist convention business, conventioners are expected to
reject a proposal that the name ``Southern'' be taken out of the
denomination's name. Many have called for the change because the
15.7 million member convention now has churches in every state. A
$159.5 million budget, $5 million more than the current budget, is
expected to be approved. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton could come under fire again from his fellow
Southern Baptists at the 142nd annual convention. But that's
nothing new. He has long been condemned by conservative Baptists
for his stands on gay rights and abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Wiley Drake of Buena Vista, Calif., said he will
propose a resolution condemning Clinton's appointment of James
Hormel, an openly gay man, as ambassador to Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
   Drake, pastor of the First Baptist Church Buena Park, Calif.,
near Disneyland, also helped spearhead a Southern Baptist boycott
of Disney theme parks and products. Southern Baptists complained
because gays were allowed to have special days in theme parks.
Also, they contend that Disney programming is moving away from
traditional family values.
</P>
<P>
   Drake will also introduce a resolution _ not expected to receive
much support _ urging Southern Baptists not to hold their national
convention in Orlando, Fla., next year because he contends that the
city is too ``gay-friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   The convention's executive committee has already rejected
another motion that Southern Baptists not meet in Orlando because
it is the home of Disney World. The committee said it would be too
costly to move the convention because contracts already have been
signed.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
