<HEADLINE>
FALWELL SEES BUSH AS NEXT PRESIDENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rev. Jerry Falwell is in Atlanta to pray and vote at the
national Southern Baptist Convention this week. And he is singing
the praises of Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is our next president,'' Falwell said in an interview
before the opening of the convention Tuesday in the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anybody that could derail Mr. Bush at this
point,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Falwell is pastor of the 22,000-member Thomas Road Baptist
Church in Lynchburg, Va. He has been an independent Baptist most of
his life.
</P>
<P>
   But the Southern Baptist Convention's turn to conservatism led
him to align with that 15.7-million member group last year as well
as his own. His congregation is sending 10 delegates, called
messengers, to the convention.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, Falwell will officially be on the program of
the national convention, giving the closing prayer Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've spoken at the Southern Baptist Pastors Conference as a
guest,'' he said, ``but I've never been on the official program. I
consider it an honor.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Southern Baptists will play a major role in the next
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Falwell expects Vice President Al Gore to be the Democratic
nominee, but predicts that the scandals associated with President
Clinton will sabotage Gore's chances for a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore, unlike his boss, who also is a Southern Baptist, is a
man of character,'' Falwell said. ``But I don't think he is capable
of being president. He has the same problem Gerald Ford had'' after
the scandals of the Richard Nixon presidency, in which Ford was
vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Although Falwell has other Republican friends seeking the
presidential nomination, including Elizabeth Dole, he said the
polls so far indicate that Bush is unbeatable.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, Baptists took part in several pre-convention
events, including a ``crossover'' evangelistic campaign. It
included block parties, door-to-door visitations, magicians on the
street and ``prayer warriors'' who walk through designated
inner-city areas praying for the city.
</P>
<P>
   Baptists also reported that a record $101,713,066 was donated in
the annual Lottie Moon Christmas offering to support overseas
missionary work. The Woman's Missionary Union, meeting in Atlanta
before the main convention, is a major promoter of the annual fund
drive.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
