<HEADLINE>
TEEN THRIVES IN FISHBOWL OF MTV'S `REAL WORLD'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Eds: The season premiere is Tuesday, June 15 at 10 p.m. on MTV). 
(A version moved Friday, June 11)  
By MARLA MATZER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Seven attractive, co-ed roommates get chosen to
live in a ridiculously plush house in Hawaii _ landscaped with its
own pool and mini ``volcano'' _ for three months. Their only job?
To be TV stars and run a ``cafe and performance space.'' Par-tay!
</P>
<P>
   That's what Colin, a 19-year-old Thousand Oaks, Calif., native
figured when he tried out for MTV's ``The Real World,'' the
(ITALICS BEGIN)video verite(ITALICS END) program that throws seven
college-age people together in a different location each season.
The show returns 10 p.m. Tuesday with a one-hour special (regular
half-hour episodes run weekly at the same time).
</P>
<P>
   Colin (the cast isn't permitted to give out their last names
during the show's run) failed to make the cut the first time
around, along with 23,000 other hopefuls. According to MTV, that's
27 percent more young adults than applied to Harvard last year.
</P>
<P>
   As a consolation prize, he was tapped to host a TV special about
the casting of the show. Bummer ... but at least, he figured, he'd
get some on-camera experience from that gig. After all, he's an
aspiring sportscaster.
</P>
<P>
   But during the taping, the outgoing student's personality won
over the program's producers, who decided to reverse their decision
and give Colin a berth on ``The Real World.'' Colin was elated: On
the show's first episode, we see him collapse in a joyous frenzy
with a friend just after getting the news.
</P>
<P>
   Colin, though, ended up getting a lot more than he bargained
for. One of his roommates turned out to have an alcohol problem so
serious it landed her in the emergency room; another left the show
early, for a variety of reasons including just being tired of
living under a microscope.
</P>
<P>
   Colin, who turned out to be the youngest of this year's group,
admits he wasn't prepared for the experience of being constantly
on-camera with a bunch of strangers thrown together from all
different backgrounds. His roommates included Amaya, a 21-year-old
UCLA graduate; Justin, also 21, a child prodigy already in his
second year at Harvard Law School; Chicago native Kaia, 22, a fan
of fitness and African culture; Matt, a 22-year-old Del Mar native
looking for love; Ruthie, 21, whose alcoholism apparently stems
from a painful childhood in a foster home in Hawaii; and Teck, 22,
a minister's son-cum-ladies' man who aspires to a career in
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really went into this process naively, as most people
probably do. I figured it would be nice to have a break from school
and to just be on the show,'' admitted Colin, now a student at UC
Berkeley, in a phone interview from Hawaii. ``You really learn
quickly that it's a total loss of privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, is the appeal for MTV viewers, who have made
``The Real World'' the cable channel's top-rated show. It's also
been the top-rated show on basic cable for its time slot among
young adults for the past several years. Part soap opera, part
therapy session, ``The Real World'' has become a real-life
``Melrose Place'' for viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, a cast member finds he can't take living in a
glass house. This year, Justin, the 21-year-old law student, who is
active in gay causes, ended up jumping ship. Jonathan Murray, one
of the show's executive producers, says Justin ended up being
``uncomfortable'' with the show's process and regretted having
joined the cast.
</P>
<P>
   Murray says that from early on, they've sought out cast members
who didn't have acting aspirations _ part of a drive to keep the
show more diverse and unstaged. Still, the series has spawned a few
show-biz careers.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Nies went on from the show's first season to appear on
MTV's exercise show, ``The Grind,'' and host a series of popular
``Grind'' videos. Jacinda Barrett, a cast member of season four in
London, has gotten major television acting jobs, including on NBC's
``Wind and Water.'' Jason Cornwell, who appeared on the Boston
``Real World'' two years ago, has become an associate casting
director for the show. Also, a number of young people who have been
``rejects'' for the show have ended up working for ``The Real
World's'' production company, Van Nuys-based Bunim/Murray
Productions (see related story).
</P>
<P>
   Colin admits the show could help him in his ambition to go into
sports broadcasting. ``I knew it couldn't hurt, though that wasn't
the main reason I wanted to be on the show,'' he said. ``Of
course,'' he added, ``I also thought about the possible backlash.
... If you come off looking like a complete freak, it could end up
hurting you.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing Colin couldn't have bargained for was becoming
romantically involved with one of his housemates. He and Amaya, a
blond Oakland native, launched what MTV terms in a press release
``the first-ever serious romance between two of the roommates.''
Despite the fact that the show's producers make a policy of bowing
out if two of their young charges start ``getting busy,'' the
couple found the scrutiny a strain on their budding relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Colin graciously allows that ``I would really like to keep in
touch with her ... I can say we'll stay in contact.'' But the
couple admits the pressure of not really conducting their
relationship in the ``real world'' probably took its toll.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, though, Colin says he's glad he did the show. ``It
turned out to be some of the best of times and the worst of times
I've been through,'' he says philosophically. ``I don't think
there's anything in the world I can liken this experience to. It's
very unique.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
