<HEADER>
A4400 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRANSVESTITE-COMIC-LA     06-14 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRANSVESTITE-COMIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S MORE TO EDDIE IZZARD THAN WOMEN'S CLOTHES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(A version moved Friday, June 11)  
 
 
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ About midway through ``Eddie Izzard: Dress to
Kill,'' you start looking at the British comedian's face and think,
``That really is very nice makeup.''
</P>
<P>
   You see, Izzard is a transvestite, an ``executive transvestite''
as he is fond of saying, who also points out that he likes girls.
He describes his particular lifestyle choice of cross-dressing as
``male lesbianism.''
</P>
<P>
   And even though he does his ``running, jumping, standing still''
bit at the beginning to prove he can navigate on platform shoes,
that or his painted nails or his colorful Chinese jacket or frosted
hair have little to do with his humor. Or the fact that he is one
of the funniest stand-up comedians working today. Former Monty
Python member John Cleese has called him ``the funniest man in
England,'' but with this HBO special, he has staked a claim to both
sides of the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Filmed last September at San Francisco's Stage Door Theatre,
``Dress to Kill'' shows off the facile mind of Izzard, who slips
from the ironic to the silly to the hilarious with the greatest of
ease.
</P>
<P>
   That would make him interesting enough, but consider the topics:
druids, the Inquisition, the American Revolution, the Killing
Fields, violence in schools, original sin, the Church of England
and squirrels. OK, the Church of England and squirrels are
inherently funny, but Izzard manages to make this odd mix flow.
More than flow _ interconnect in unexpected ways by slyly
referencing an earlier joke or a topic.
</P>
<P>
   Izzard takes pleasure in poking fun at Americans' lack of
knowledge about history, particularly their own. After doing an
amusing impression of how the French in films about the American
Revolution are portrayed as friends of Lafayette, he turns to the
audience and smirks, ``You don't know who he is, do you? What is
it? The Spanish-American War? The French Banana War? What?'' Or he
gives hilarious instructions on how to sing the national anthem
when you don't know the words.
</P>
<P>
   Even when he's being topical, as when he talks about gun control
(remember, this was taped before Littleton) or perjury, Izzard
takes an unusual tack. If we can have different degrees of murder,
why not perjury, he reasons. ``Perjury one is when you say there's
no Holocaust. Perjury nine is when you said you shagged someone
when you didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   And Izzard has that cheeky, British wickedness in humor that
keeps you off guard, such as at the end of his bits on Engelbert
Humperdinck or when talking about the first women he nearly slept
with (we won't spoil the jokes).
</P>
<P>
   But no matter what Izzard takes on, he's consistently smart,
funny, surprising and fabulous. Did we mention his bit on the Roman
Empire? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (``Eddie Izzard: Dress to Kill'' shows on HBO Saturday, June 12
at 11:30; and repeats at midnight Tuesday, June 15; 3:30 a.m.
Friday, June 18; 10 p.m. June 21, 9 p.m. June 24 and 2:45 a.m. July
4). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
