financial news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Silicon Valley's charms can quickly pall. Meeting one hairy
millionaire in cycling shorts can be diverting. Meeting a
succession leaves you pining for less repellent forms of
conformity.
</P>
<P>
   Every now and then, however, you come across someone who is
doing something genuinely wacky: such as the leader of the local
branch of the AFL-CIO, Amy Dean.
</P>
<P>
   Forty years ago one American worker in three was a member of a
trade union. Today the figure is closer to one in seven.
</P>
<P>
   In Silicon Valley start-ups, trade unionists are about as thick
on the ground as manual typewriters. Yet it is here that Dean is
planning the rebirth of the American labor movement.
</P>
<P>
   As Don Quixotes go, she has an impressive record. She is part of
the new labor movement: young (36, and already a five-year veteran
as head of the South Bay labor council); well-educated (a degree in
sociology and economics would have led to postgraduate work had she
not been seduced into the Ladies' Garment Workers Union); and
plugged into the new economy (her husband works for a software
start-up).
</P>
<P>
   When she took over the South Bay branch of the AFL-CIO, it was
little more than a blue-collar rest home. Now it is humming, housed
in what looks like a high-tech hatchery, staffed by bright young
things, many of them Hispanic women, and elaborately ``networked,''
along the best Silicon Valley lines.
</P>
<P>
   A sister group, Working Partnership USA, which she set up in
1995, does research, trains local activists and cultivates
relations with universities.
</P>
<P>
   Dean can sound like an academic with the gift of the gab. Do not
be deceived: she is a street fighter.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, her organization not only trounced the bosses'
candidate in a brutal battle for a seat on the San Jose city
council. (``I was up against the single most powerful political
machine in the Valley,'' grumbled the loser.)
</P>
<P>
   It also won its campaign to force San Jose to adopt a ``living
wage'' for all municipal contractors.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose now has the highest minimum wage in the country, almost
twice the mandatory level in the state of California.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, the president of the AFL-CIO, John Sweeney,
recruited Dean to head a committee on the future of the labor
movement. She started by admitting what was obvious to everybody
but the movement itself: that it is on a hiding to nothing.
</P>
<P>
   The unions are still rooted in a world of vertically integrated
companies, glacial innovation and jobs for life, she says, in her
best academic tones.
</P>
<P>
   But these days firms are spinning into webs, innovation is
relentless and the average length of employment in California,
where the new economy is being forged, is three years.
</P>
<P>
   Given this, Dean is remarkably upbeat. Labor organizations are
not alone in failing to keep pace with economic change: the same
could be said of almost any public-sector institution.
</P>
<P>
   And there is nothing odd about unions failing in new industries:
the same was true of the infant car and electricity industries.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest reason for Dean's optimism is that she thinks
that the defining characteristic of the new economy _ its obsession
with flexibility _ will turn out to be a boon for unions.
</P>
<P>
   This seems counterintuitive. How can unions represent people who
might be changing job any day? And how can they recruit people who
fear that a reputation for bolshiness could stop them from getting
another job?
</P>
<P>
   The rise of temp agencies such as Manpower (which is now
America's largest employer) has coincided with the unions' decline.
</P>
<P>
   Against this, Dean points out, temporary workers are often
miserable workers. The worst-paid live a hand-to-mouth existence
without medical or other benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Even many of the best-paid are fearful of the future and envious
of those on the permanent payroll, as Microsoft discovered last
month when some ``permatemps'' won a class-action suit against it.
Microsoft is appealing.
</P>
<P>
   Dean's bright idea for reaching these discontented but elusive
temps is to establish a temping agency of her own, Together &LR; Work.
</P>
<P>
   The month-old agency is not only paying its workers better than
its rivals pay theirs. It also plans to give them medical benefits,
pensions and training. (This is not as unrealistic as it sounds:
conventional agencies charge fat commissions.)
</P>
<P>
   Dean wants her agency to become a stable point in lives
otherwise blown hither and thither by the flexible economy. This is
also her plan for the union movement as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   As firms become more nimble, workers will have to look elsewhere
for things that make life secure, from training to medical
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   In the 19th century some craft unions proved so good at
providing these that they controlled the supply of workers: when
people wanted a carpenter they went to the union.
</P>
<P>
   In some areas of the new economy, notably Hollywood, unions are
starting to play this role again; Dean would like it to become the
norm.
</P>
<P>
   Her heady vision raises all sorts of questions. Is she really a
convert to the flexible economy? Her most concrete achievement so
far has been to make wages in San Jose more rigid.
</P>
<P>
   Can trade unions really provide training in the new economy? At
the moment, her power base is in the public sector.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that Dean will not make her mark. She has
proved remarkably successful at bullying San Jose politicians and
raising questions the cyber elite would rather forget, such as why
wages for the low-paid in the world's center of wealth creation are
falling.
</P>
<P>
   The discontent smoldering among permatemps could become a blaze
when the economy turns down. And if the history of Silicon Valley
teaches anything, it is never to write off people with crazy
ideas. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
