<SLUG> BC-ELECTION-MONITORS-REVIEW-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NURTURING DEMOCRACY FROM THE GRASS ROOTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(lb) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ When he was a much younger man, Jose
Concepcion once found himself holding up a bullet and peering at it
through his thick glasses. ``They are shooting at us,'' he said,
more incredulous than afraid. That was 13 years ago in the
Philippines, when Concepcion and other partisans of democracy were
learning how to face down a dictator, and how a dictator fights
back.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he and scores of others are bringing such lessons to
places like Indonesia, applying them and building on them in the
growing number of emerging democracies. One of the founders of the
National Movement for Free Elections, known by the acronym Namfrel,
Concepcion helped end the 20-year rule of Ferdinand Marcos in 1986.
That experience helped him and others fashion a new instrument for
the spread of democracy: the independent, citizen-led
election-watch group.
</P>
<P>
   Vote-monitoring groups sponsored by the United Nations or the
United States or by independent American organizations have become
a fairly familiar sight in countries conducting elections for the
first time. But Concepcion's movement is different: These are
home-grown groups that take it upon themselves to visit neighboring
countries, help them launch democracies, and leave behind similar
home-grown groups to help the fledgling free society grow.
</P>
<P>
   So last week Concepcion was in Jakarta with a Namfrel delegation
keeping an eye on Indonesia's first free election in 44 years and
simultaneously training local poll-watchers to start a
self-sustaining effort here. Also here were scores of men and women
from other nations who were in effect his students.
</P>
<P>
   Following the example set in the Philippines, they had already
helped bring democratic elections to their own countries. Now, like
Concepcion, they were sharing the benefits of their experience.
</P>
<P>
   Feroz Hassan, for example, was here from Bangladesh, where he
helped found the Fair Election Monitoring Alliance in 1995, with
help and advice from Namfrel. ``They brought the idea and gave us
the training,'' he said. Hassan then took his poll-watch experience
to Kenya before coming to Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Lachmansingh was here from Guyana, where he formed the
Electoral Assistance Bureau in 1991. ``People were getting quite
fed up,'' he said. ``Elections were rigged on and on and on.''
</P>
<P>
   After that, he too went abroad, helping monitor elections in the
West Bank in 1995, in Sri Lanka in 1996 and 1997 and in Cambodia
last year before coming here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about the same anywhere you go,'' he said. ``Always in
people's mind is hope and a desire for change and democracy, which
they associate first with democratic elections. People often have
unrealistic expectations, but always there is that basic ingredient
of hope which propels concerned citizens to want to make a
contribution. Call it patriotism, saintliness, bravery _ martyrdom
sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   The religious imagery seemed apt. These are today's secular
missionaries, spreading the democratic faith in a time of mass
conversion around the world. They have carried the gospel of
democratic possibilities to places as far-flung as Yemen, Nigeria,
Panama, Taiwan, Romania, Bulgaria, Chile, Haiti, Nicaragua, Kenya
and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, the poll-watch groups they helped found remained
in place after the election was over, transforming themselves into
good-government watchdog organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a life-and-death choice, almost,'' said Lachmansingh.
``In Guyana, every single year of my life had been lived under an
authoritarian government. I was prepared to die for this. This is
something you have to do. You want your children to grow up and
have a better life than you've had.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But if democracy is something of a secular religion these days,
Hassan bridled at a suggestion that it is somehow a particularly
American creed. Democracy, he said, is a political belief that is
every bit as fundamental to an Asian or African.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't consider that democracy is defined by America only or
that it is biased toward American policy,'' he said. And as it
spreads around the world, he added, it is becoming redefined by its
many new practitioners.
</P>
<P>
   The notion that democracy is an American imposition is a not
uncommon misperception, Lachmansingh said. ``You know, your country
has a bad name,'' he told an American reporter. ``People talk about
an American agenda, and you almost always have to deal with that:
Who are you? Are you an American organization? What's your
agenda?''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the monitoring groups play many different roles
depending on the situation in each country.
</P>
<P>
   In Bangladesh, Hassan said, the priorities were to restore
confidence in the electoral process, to encourage larger-scale
participation and to deter fraud.
</P>
<P>
   In Guyana, Lachmansingh's group analyzed and discredited a voter
list so far removed from reality that people made jokes about it.
</P>
<P>
   In Sri Lanka, where elections were conducted relatively freely,
poll watchers guarded against violence that turned voting days into
a time of mourning.
</P>
<P>
   And after popular unrest forced the resignation of the
autocratic leader Suharto last fall, Indonesia faced most of the
challenges of an emerging democracy: intimidation, fraud,
disorganization and the lack of a culture of free choice. Even now,
with the results of last Monday's vote still not fully tallied, the
possibility of postelection violence hangs over the nation.
</P>
<P>
   There is a very simple but very difficult cultural lesson that
must be learned in order to make free elections work, said Dumaria
Tampubolon, a statistician with Rectors Forum, one of the largest
of 99 local groups that have registered to monitor the election.
</P>
<P>
   People must learn to lose,'' she said. Otherwise, elections
simply become the spark for more conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Poll watchers themselves remain at risk from people who have not
yet learned the concept of neutrality, said Smita Notosusanto, the
executive director of a local poll-watch group called Unfrel, which
has fielded about 100,000 volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of our volunteers are students, and they are threatened
from both sides,'' she said. ``The police and military in some
areas intimidate our volunteers just because they are students. On
the other side, the biggest challenge right now is that students
are facing threats from their friends who are against the holding
of the election.''
</P>
<P>
   Worst of all, she said, some of these people are right to
mistrust her volunteers. Until they signed up for poll-watch duty,
many of the students were angrily demonstrating against the current
government.
</P>
<P>
   And many of them are not prepared to believe that the government
could win in a fair election. ``I'm not sure I can convince my
students to accept the results even if they cannot confirm any
violations,'' Ms. Smita said.
</P>
<P>
   Concepcion pronounced himself pleased last week with Indonesia's
experiment in democracy, despite its rough edges. ``Generally
speaking, it was a free and fair and peaceful election,'' he said.
``Now it is up to the Indonesian people to work together to improve
the life of the people. After five more years they can fight
again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
