<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 13:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4477 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUYING-AFTER-DARK-NYT     06-14 1393
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUYING-AFTER-DARK-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LURING THE LATE-NIGHT SHOPPER  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special one-shot feature from W magazine _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ contact New York Times Syndicate Sales
Executive DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)
 &HT;    
 By THE EDITORS OF WWD 
 c.1999 Fairchild Publications  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   From New York, the city that never sleeps, to Los Angeles, the
city that never walks, after-dark shopping _ from about 9 p.m.
until as late as 2 a.m. in some cases _ is becoming more popular.
It seems to be happening in urban locations, apparently among
younger shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, shopping has become part of an evening's
entertainment, something to do between dinner out and club-hopping.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at the nocturnal shopping habits of consumers in
New York, Los Angeles and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In addition to stores along lower Broadway like Antique
Boutique, Yellow Rat Bastard, Canal Jeans, Urban Outfitters and
Joyce Leslie, which stay open until at least 9 p.m. during the
week, retailers in surrounding neighborhoods are keeping their
doors open longer.
</P>
<P>
   Purdy Girl Lifestyle, which recently opened on LaGuardia Place
in Greenwich Village, does business until 10 p.m. from Mondays to
Wednesdays and until midnight and later, depending on the traffic,
the rest of the week.
</P>
<P>
   The store, which carries apparel, accessories, cosmetics and
home accessories and caters to a young, hip customer, benefits from
its proximity to New York University and does a brisk business with
students, according to owner Corinne Purdy.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are really happy to find a cool store that's open after
hours,'' said Purdy, who does much of her business between 9 p.m.
and 11 p.m. ``They are just going out to dinner or are on their way
back from the bars or going to the clubs. They may prefer to shop
at night because it's part of their night out.''
</P>
<P>
   Purdy said she has seen customers walk out as late as midnight
with complete outfits _ the same merchandise people buy during the
day. Top sellers at night are clothes by Hybrid, messenger bags,
Buddha T-shirts and aromatic candles.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm working all day, I don't have time to shop,'' said
Yvonne Okoh, 21, a Colgate University physics major who was
visiting an NYU friend, as she eyed a skirt by Hybrid. ``It's great
to be able to stop in a place like this and pick up something for
the club when all the other stores are closed.''
</P>
<P>
   In the East Village and on the Lower East Side, young people
roam the streets at night looking for high-fashion vintage clothes
at the right price.
</P>
<P>
   Favorite nighttime destinations are Village Scandal on East
Seventh Street, Candy Store on Second Avenue and Marmalade on
Ludlow Street, all of which stay open late on weekends _ as long as
there are customers trickling in from neighboring bars or
restaurants. That can be as late as 2 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is something decadent and exciting about shopping at
night,'' said Billie Madley, a co-owner of Marmalade. ``We've seen
this place turn into a sort of nightclub of shoppers.''
</P>
<P>
   Madley said her nighttime clientele is largely young, barhopping
and ready to snap up any trends in fashion. Presently, items from
the late '70s and early '80s are doing particularly well _
reconstructed denim skirts, embroidered hippie tops and dyed slips,
which range in price from $25 to $60.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LOS ANGELES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At Diesel USA, located on the hip, happening Third Street
Promenade in Santa Monica, the music is groovy, the decor is cool
(mint and white) and customers are encouraged to shop till they
drop, which can be as late as 11 p.m. on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   According to manager Carol McNairy, shoppers tend to be under
30.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of couples out for dinner. They're pretty relaxed.
They mosey around and take their time. They're impulse shoppers,''
McNairy said. ``Surprisingly, we don't get a lot of returns.''
</P>
<P>
   An average Diesel outfit runs $125 to $155 for something like a
T-shirt and a pair of Walling antique dirty-denim jeans or a pair
of Kannoth cotton cargo pants with drawstrings.
</P>
<P>
   For the more fashion-hungry, there is the StyleLab section,
where a pair of polyurethane-treated linen pants is $199 and a sexy
jersey skirt and top costs $250.
</P>
<P>
   High-end sexy merchandise is the house specialty at Undercover,
another late-night destination. Beneath a chandelier and a replica
of Michelangelo's Sistine Chapel ceiling is an artful selection of
lingerie, jewelry, shoes, dressy separates and dresses bearing such
labels as Plein Sud, Yigal-Azrouel and Mark Wong Nark.
</P>
<P>
   A typical outfit _ dress and shoes or dress and jewelry _ might
run $500 to $600. But Adam Shaffer, owner of Undercover, is
currently ``trying to appeal to younger girls'' by offering
lower-priced prom dresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are paying an average of $250 for slim, elegant dresses
in beautiful colors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   During the week his latenight customers are mostly locals _ on
weekends, they're mostly tourists, according to Shaffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's a girlfriends' night out. They've had a glass
of wine or two and it's time to play dress-up,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   One recent evening, the girlfriends were Brenda Roos, a flight
attendant, and Susan Steinman, a medical sales representative.
</P>
<P>
   Roos, an established customer, said she was shopping past
Shaffer's official closing time, which is 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll offer to stay open for me. That's just an awesome
convenience,'' she said. ``I love the atmosphere and walking up and
down the street.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``With the weather being pleasant and with less traffic in the
evening, we're always busy at night,'' according to a manager at
Urban Outfitters on M Street in Georgetown. ``This store always has
a mix of all different kinds of people shopping at night _
tourists, neighborhood people and students.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always have people running in at the last minute in the
evening, picking up gifts for a party or birthday,'' the manager
said.
</P>
<P>
   Urban Outfitters is open until 10 p.m. Mondays through Fridays,
11 p.m. on Saturdays and 9 p.m. on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Allen and Kristen Cioffi jetted in from Harrisonburg, Va.,
for an evening in Georgetown. The James Madison University
undergrads made a night of it, visiting Urban Outfitters, Banana
Republic, French Connection and Kenneth Cole.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping in Georgetown at night is spectacular, the two said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nighttime shopping is getting better and better,'' said a
manager at Banana Republic. He said the bulk of customers at night
were students and young professionals who had gone to dinner, but
weren't ready to call it a night.
</P>
<P>
   Banana Republic is open until 9 p.m., Mondays through Thursdays,
until 10 p.m. on Fridays and Saturdays and 8 p.m. on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   ``The post-work crew is our prime evening customers,'' reported
a manager at the Ralph Lauren store. ``Usually they know what they
want; they've checked out the market and know what they need.''
</P>
<P>
   Lauren is open until 9 p.m. Mondays through Fridays and 6 p.m.
Saturdays and Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   ``People just get in the mood at night,'' Banana Republic's
manager said, noting Thursdays are traditionally the busiest for
his store, which is on the corner of Wisconsin and M Streets. ``By
9 or 10, the crowd is wall to wall. It's like daytime on Fifth
Avenue in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Huddled outside Georgetown Park Mall, Washington natives Ariel
Sutro and Stephanie Seems weren't quite sure where to head next.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you see something cool in the window at night, you're like,
`Wow! Let's go in,''' Seems explained.
</P>
<P>
   The mall is open until 9 p.m. Mondays through Saturdays and
until 6 p.m. on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   Sporting a pair of just-purchased Kenneth Cole open-toed heels,
Sutro noted, ``It's pleasant and convenient to shop at night.
Especially in the nice weather.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Mana and Maha Yamany said they were ``too sleepy'' during
the day to brave the throngs in Georgetown.
</P>
<P>
   ``After dark it's more relaxing and interesting,'' Mana said.
``We look at the clothes we want, think about it and then there's a
reason to go back.'' &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; c.1999 Fairchild Publications &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-99 1306EDT &QL; 
