<SLUG> BC-GREECE-TURKEY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR TURKEY AND GREECE, THE SPARK OF HOPE IN AN ANCIENT HATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (Editors: This is a late add; it replaces the previously budgeted
KOSOVO-TEACH-REVIEW)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ During the flurry of NATO meetings that have
accompanied the Kosovo crisis, a strange sight has been seen
several times. The foreign ministers of Greece and Turkey, the
alliance's bitterest rivals, have huddled for private talks.
</P>
<P>
   They have discussed ways to bring Yugoslav leaders to the
negotiating table, plans for sheltering refugees and ideas about
increasing the weight of NATO's southeastern flank. In fact, they
have discussed just about everything but the issue that people want
them to discuss: Greek-Turkish relations.
</P>
<P>
   Greek Foreign Minister George Papandreou said after one
conference that he and his Turkish counterpart, Ismail Cem, have
``very good personal communication.'' He even said he was open to
``new ideas and proposals'' to resolve the issues that have divided
the two nations for decades.
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovo crisis has underlined once more how closely Greek and
Turkish strategic interests coincide. Both would benefit enormously
from stability in the Balkans and the eastern Mediterranean. Yet,
in one of the most persistent and puzzling anomalies of modern
geopolitics, their dispute remains seemingly intractable. Though
joined by geography and history, they are divided by one of the
world's angriest and longest-running blood feuds.
</P>
<P>
   The feud has taken a turn for the worse in recent months,
following the capture of Kurdish guerrilla leader Abdullah Ocalan.
Ocalan, who is reviled in Turkey as a terrorist responsible for
thousands of deaths, was found to have been living under the
protection of Greek diplomats in Kenya. Turkish leaders accused
Greece of supporting a mass murderer in an effort to sow chaos in
Turkey. Greek leaders shot back, calling Turkey a thinly disguised
military dictatorship that brought the Kurdish problem on itself
through discrimination and repression.
</P>
<P>
   If Turks are outraged by Greece's role in protecting Ocalan,
Greece also has a new focus for its anger. Turkish leaders have
begun asserting that there are political ``gray zones'' in the
Aegean Sea, suggesting that Turkey has designs on islands that have
long been considered Greek. Dozens of interviews in both countries
suggest that the animosity between these neighbors is fed by a
combination of prejudice and political competition. But they also
revealed hope that a more positive relationship might emerge out of
the current trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever I am in Greece, what strikes me is how alike we
are,'' said Orhan Taylan, a Turkish painter who is a member of a
small Greek-Turkish friendship group. ``We have the same emotions,
we tell the same jokes, we eat the same food, we listen to the same
music, we look at the world the same way. That's what makes it so
awful that this conflict just keeps dragging on.''
</P>
<P>
   Studying the psychology of Greek-Turkish relations is a passion
for historian Hercules Millas, who was born to Greek parents in
Istanbul and considers himself at home in both countries. ``Neither
side has any empathy with the other or any doubt that it is 100
percent right,'' Millas said. ``The Turk you know personally may be
good, but the Turkish nation as a whole is a brutal and warlike
enemy. For Turks, Greeks are liars, full of intrigues and bad
intentions, definitely not to be trusted.''
</P>
<P>
   Turkey has nearly six times the population of Greece, a much
more powerful army and a crucial location that makes it a highly
desirable ally. Greece is more developed and widely considered more
democratic, but Turkey has far greater strategic value.
</P>
<P>
   History plays a great role in creating the suspicions that
infect the Greek-Turkish relationship. These may be the only two
countries in the world that fought their definitive wars of
liberation against each other. After centuries of subjugation,
Greeks drove out the Ottoman Turks to emerge as an independent
state in the 1820s, and a century later, amid the wreckage of the
Ottoman Empire, Turks drove Greek forces from Anatolia to establish
the Turkish Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between the nations warmed during the 1930s, but then
cooled and reached a breaking point in 1974, when Turkish forces
landed on the Mediterranean island of Cyprus and occupied a
substantial part of it. Turkey said it was acting to prevent the
slaughter of ethnic Turks by the ethnic Greek majority. Greece
called the act an illegal invasion of a sovereign country that
proved Turkey's expansionist nature.
</P>
<P>
   A few isolated rays of light have fallen on the Greek-Turkish
relationship in the quarter-century since the Cyprus operation, but
they have not been enough to brighten the darkness that has come to
envelop it. The nations have come to the brink of war several
times, most recently over a barren Aegean islet in 1996. Their
naval units still conduct maneuvers in the Aegean at the same time,
and their pilots routinely engage in mock dogfights.
</P>
<P>
   The suspicion that many ordinary Greeks and Turks harbor for
each other is fed by a remarkable lack of contact. There is little
trade between the two nations. Greeks and Turks rarely visit each
other's countries, and very few speak the other's language.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish leaders insist they can begin no dialogue with Greece
until the Greek government closes what they say are camps used to
train Kurdish guerrillas in Greece and declares the guerrilla
group, the Kurdistan Workers Party, or PKK, a terrorist
organization. But Papandreou insisted in an interview that there
are no guerrilla camps in Greece, and that his government is not
prepared to label the PKK terrorist.
</P>
<P>
   The PKK is not a legal organization in Greece and is not allowed
to exist here,'' Papandreou said. ``We do not say that it is or is
not a terrorist group. I think it's putting a blindfold on the
problem to say that this is only a problem of terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   In the days following Ocalan's capture in Kenya last February,
Greece was shaken by a political earthquake. Three ministers and
the chief of the intelligence service were forced to resign. Their
successors, including Papandreou, are considered strong supporters
of the relatively moderate prime minister, Constantine Simitis, and
less likely to embark on provocative adventures like sheltering a
man who is the most wanted fugitive in a nearby country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're beginning to come out of the worst of it not only
unscathed, but with some very positive changes,'' said Theodore
Couloumbis, director of the Hellenic Foundation for European and
Foreign Policy. ``We're leaving behind this idea that the enemy of
our enemy is our friend, which got us into this huge mess in the
first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Turkish anger over Greece's support for Ocalan has not faded,
however, and the victory of nationalist parties in Turkey's April
election may have made compromise more difficult. One of the elder
statesmen of Greek politics, Defense Minister Apostolos
Tsohatzopoulos, is among those who hope that the shock of the
Ocalan affair will lead to a new dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very heavy blow to Greece, and it created a
political and ethical crisis here,'' Tsohatzopoulos said. ``I see
it as a chance to change the bad perceptions that exist.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
