<SLUG> BC-BC-KAN-BUDGET-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Tuesday,
June 15. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News
Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   DEATH: Barring any last-minute stays, Missouri will execute
Bruce Kilgore at 12:01 a.m. Wednesday. This will be the seventh
execution in the state so far this year, a record since the death
penalty was reinstated. How many more executions are scheduled? And
what do both sides of the death penalty debate have to say about
all the recent cases that have been overturned? Lee Hill Kavanaugh.
25.
</P>
<P>
   CITY: Students from Rockhurst High School, a Catholic, boys-only
school drawing students from throughout the Kansas City metro area,
spend a week living in the central city, helping with soup kitchens
and other social programs to find out about life outside the
'burbs. Winston Ross. 15. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   TWA (business) _ Reaction to the TWA contract. By Randolph
Heaster
</P>
<P>
   SPRINT (business) _ Sprint names Louis Smith to its board of
directors. By Ted Sickinger. Photo
</P>
<P>
   FAIR (business) _ United for a Fair Economy reports on efforts
to hold down CEO pay. Diane Stafford.
</P>
<P>
   LAYNE (business) _ Layne Christensen Co. forms two joint venture
companies focusing on the mining industry. Randy Heaster
</P>
<P>
   VANGUARD (business) _ Vanguard Airlines returns to the Nasdaq
over the counter market. Mark Davis
</P>
<P>
   ROYALS (sports). Dick Kaegel. 16-18. Kansas City at Baltimore,
6:35 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   OPEN (sports). Howard Richman. 12. U.S. Open champ Lee Janzen
talks about preparing to defend the title.
</P>
