<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4529 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKE     06-14 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
(The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Theaters Move to Enforce Ratings
</P>
<P>
   An organization representing the owners of most of the United
States' movie theaters announced that they would begin requiring
young people who are not accompanied by adults to show photo
identification cards proving they are at least 17 years old, when
they try to buy tickets to R-rated films.
</P>
<P>
   The group, the National Association of Theater Owners, was
responding to public concern that violent movies lead teen-agers to
commit violence themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts were pessimistic, however. They said the move might
backfire by making the movies all the more alluring because of the
challenge of getting in.
</P>
<P>
   And many teen-agers expressed confidence they would find ways to
sneak into whatever movies they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   _ DAVID E. ROSENBAUM
</P>
<P>
   A Food Scare in Europe
</P>
<P>
   Belgian animal feed tainted with dioxin caused a food crisis
that scared governments around the world into banning many poultry,
meat and dairy products from all European countries because of
fears they contained the poison.
</P>
<P>
   Belgian authorities first discovered high concentrations of the
poison, which accumulates in fatty tissues, in sick chickens last
March, but waited until two weeks ago to tell the Belgian and
European public and take poultry off the market. Later, beef, pork,
and butter were added to the list while officials ascertained which
products were safe.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Belgians satisfied European Union authorities
that they had done so, filling their supermarket shelves and
resuming exports. But the Europeans remained furious at the way
Prime Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene's coalition government had handled
the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Belgian authorities say that they traced the problem to chicken
and animal feed from a single Belgian feed company, and that it is
now under control.
</P>
<P>
   _ CRAIG R. WHITNEY
</P>
<P>
   Court Frees Woman Who Threatened Cosby
</P>
<P>
   A federal appeals court in New York overturned the conviction of
Autumn Jackson, who was sent to prison for threatening to tell a
supermarket tabloid that she was Bill Cosby's out-of-wedlock
daughter unless he paid her $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jackson, who had served about 14 months of her 26-month
prison term, was released on Thursday, one of her lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have not yet said whether they will appeal the
decision of the three-judge panel, or retry Ms. Jackson and two
associates who were also convicted. Legal experts said the ruling
may have broader significance by helping to clarify what
constitutes an acceptable threat, as opposed to blackmail or
extortion.
</P>
<P>
   _ BENJAMIN WEISER
</P>
<P>
   A New Plan for Drug Coverage Under Medicare
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton wants to expand Medicare to cover prescription
drugs, and White House officials disclosed some details of the
proposal. They also said, however, that they were still trying to
figure out how to pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of elderly people say they cannot afford the drugs they
need, and many Democrats are hoping to retake control of the House
of Representatives in next year's elections by running on the
promise of Medicare drug benefits.
</P>
<P>
   John Podesta, the White House chief of staff, said the proposed
drug benefit would be ``universal and affordable,'' would have ``a
modest premium'' and would be ``better than anything you could buy
today in the open market.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ROBERT PEAR
</P>
<P>
   Look. Up in the Sky. It's a ...
</P>
<P>
   As a young man, George Bush had to bail out of a Navy fighter he
was piloting over the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   A little more than two years ago, at the age of 72, the former
president hit the silk again over Arizona, prompting his wife
Barbara to tell him, ``It's the first time you've been in free-fall
since 1992.''
</P>
<P>
   What else to do to mark his 75th birthday?
</P>
<P>
   Bush parachuted from 13,000 feet above his presidential library
at College Station, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Supreme Court Strikes Down Loitering Law Aimed at Gangs
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's anti-loitering law, a model for cities seeking to
reclaim the streets from violent gangs, was declared
unconstitutional. By a 6-3 vote, the Supreme Court said the law
gave the police too much discretion to sweep up innocent people in
their fight against crime.
</P>
<P>
   In his majority opinion, Justice John Paul Stevens said the law
didn't give police officers enough guidance. Under the law, he
said, ``it matters not whether the reason that a gang member and
his father, for example, might loiter near Wrigley Field is to rob
an unsuspecting fan or just to get a glimpse of Sammy Sosa leaving
the ball park.''
</P>
<P>
   But the opinion suggested that Chicago could solve the problem
by rewriting the law to define prohibited behavior more precisely,
and Mayor Richard M. Daley vowed that the city would do so.
Municipal lawyers said they hoped to have a new version ready
within 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for the American Civil Liberties Union, which
challenged the 1992 law, said it would be hard to write a broad
anti-loitering law that would be both constitutional and effective.
</P>
<P>
   African National Congress Seals an Election Victory
</P>
<P>
   Final election results showed that South Africa's ruling African
National Congress, the party of outgoing President Nelson Mandela
and President-elect Thabo Mbeki, was re-elected in a landslide on
June 2, gaining even more Parliament seats than it got in 1994
during the country's first post-apartheid elections.
</P>
<P>
   The party fell just one seat short of the two-thirds majority it
needed if it wanted to start making changes to the Constitution,
though it can no doubt put together such a majority by making
alliances with smaller parties.
</P>
<P>
   It is likely to face a boisterous opposition, however. The new
Parliament will include 12 opposition parties, up from six last
time; it also includes several new outspoken personalities and a
far larger Democratic Party, which captured 38 seats, up from
seven. That party has been a vocal and effective government critic
and seems determined to continue in that vein.
</P>
<P>
   _ SUZANNE DALEY
</P>
<P>
   25,000-Year-Old Footprints
</P>
<P>
   In a cave in Southern France, scientists have found human
footprints that they believe are the oldest in Europe. They
estimate that the four imprints on the moist soil belonged to a boy
about 10 years old who walked there 25,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Chauvet cave was discovered in 1994 by spelunkers.
Scientists have since recorded 447 engraved and painted images of
animals there; they include some of the oldest and most stunning
images left by the ice-age inhabitants of Europe. The scientists
began to examine the footprints only last month.
</P>
<P>
   Ancient footprints have been found before in other caves in
France, including in Niaux and Pech-Merle, but those are believed
to be 12,000 to 14,000 years old.
</P>
<P>
   _ MARLISE SIMONS
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A Confrontation With the Pope
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II was back in his native Poland again, this time
to focus attention on the 20th-century martyrdom of Christians and
underline the broad themes of his papacy.
</P>
<P>
   The visit took a bizarre turn when the chief rabbi of Poland,
Pinchas Monachem Joskowicz, introduced himself on a receiving line
and addressed the pope directly, saying: ``I have a favor to ask
Mr. Pope'' _ to seek to remove a cross at the walls of Auschwitz.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal, broadcast live on Polish television, shocked many
Polish viewers and embarrassed leaders of Poland's Jewish
community, who said the setting was inappropriate and the form of
address scandalous.
</P>
<P>
   Their fear was that the incident would undermine their own more
diplomatic efforts to find a compromise over the visibility of the
cross at a site of great Jewish suffering. It was put up to
commemorate the pope's 1979 visit to Auschwitz, and as a memorial
to Christian victims of the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   How 'Bout Those Cubs, er, Yanks?
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton took her most decisive step yet toward
running for the Senate from New York, declaring her lifelong
allegiance to the Bronx Bombers. At a White House ceremony honoring
the 1998 World Series champs, she got a Yankees cap that she tugged
over her forehead as she posed with the team.
</P>
<P>
   In this initial skirmishing over the Senate seat, Mrs. Clinton's
declaration amounted to a Bronx cheer to New York City Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, her likely rival and a diehard Yankees fan.
</P>
<P>
   The move raised questions about Mrs. Clinton's sense of loyalty,
since she was born and bred in Chicago and had worn her love for
the Cubs on her sleeve.
</P>
<P>
   No problem, Mrs. Clinton said. Because the Cubs were in the
National League, she has needed an American League team to root for
too.
</P>
<P>
   Play ball!
</P>
<P>
   _ KATHARINE Q. SEELYE
</P>
<P>
   Goodbye, TV. Hello, Net
</P>
<P>
   When Lou Dobbs, whose name is synonymous with televised
financial news from his 15 years anchoring CNN's ``Moneyline'' and
his founding of the CNNfn network, resigned to join an Internet
start-up called Space.com, his colleagues were baffled.
</P>
<P>
   Some said he had tired of ego-clashing with other top executives
at CNN. Some said he saw the money some Web entrepreneurs were
making, and wanted his chance to make a mint.
</P>
<P>
   Overlooked, Dobbs said, was a simpler notion: He is a space nut.
</P>
<P>
   He is also fully Net-savvy, having helped create CNNfn.com, the
leading business-news Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Dobbs denied interest in another television job, saying, ``My
full commitment is to the launch of Space.com on July 20 and to the
operation of the best Internet site on space.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
