<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4531 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUN-MILE-HIGH-BOS &LR;      06-14 1263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-MILE-HIGH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY VIE FOR A FIRST IN THIN AIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Congratulations!'' the letter begins. ``Your entry has been
accepted for the 39th `Run to the Clouds.' More than half of this
year's applicants were rejected in the lottery. Now that you are
IN, please take a few moments to read this letter carefully. The
information that follows will help you avoid problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Elated to learn that you will be allowed to run the Mount
Washington Road Race, in which just under 1,000 (pick one:
competitors, adventure-seekers, idiots) will begin the 7.6-mile
trek up the Auto Road from Gorham, N.H., to the 6,288-foot summit
at 10 a.m. Saturday, June 19, you read on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Course rises 4,650 vertical feet at an average 11.5 percent
grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carry extra clothing in case of dangerous wind chill above
tree line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have someone meet you at the top with mittens, a hat, and a
winter jacket.
</P>
<P>
   ``BE PREPARED!''
</P>
<P>
   Congratulations?
</P>
<P>
   ``You tell people you're running up the Auto Road, and they look
at you as if you have two heads,'' conceded Julie Peterson of
Beverly, Mass., who will run this year for the sixth time and has
never finished lower than third.
</P>
<P>
   Mount Washington is likely the steepest road race in the United
States, rising 611.8 vertical feet per mile, compared to 586.7 feet
for the Pike's Peak Ascent. The mountain's weather, some of the
worst in the world, includes a world-record wind speed of 231 miles
per hour during a storm in 1934. In June, the average temperature
at the top is usually around freezing. Gusts of 60 miles per hour
that blow runners sideways are common on race day, and there is
often fog above the treeline.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, you can't keep 'em away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most modern Americans are bored to tears, so they need a
challenge,'' theorized Bob Teschek, race director. ``It used to be
work or your daily life, now it's sport.''
</P>
<P>
   According to those who have done it, the challenge begins
stunningly quickly. Peter Watson of Rockport, Mass., who has run in
the race for 12 consecutive years, described the start in idyllic
terms: going over a little bridge, up a small incline, and into the
woods. Then, you turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as you take that right, the steepness hits you like a
sledgehammer,'' said Watson, 60. ``You have the sense the first
time that it never, ever lets up.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson finished 483d last year, in a time of 1 hour, 50 minutes,
and 19 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Dunham may have been 479 places and 47 minutes ahead of
him, but he shared the same impression.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we hit a turn I said, `It's got to flatten out,' ''
recalled Dunham, a three-time winner, of his first assault on the
course. ``It never flattens out.''
</P>
<P>
   That's never, as in not once. According to John Stifler, who ran
the race in 1989 and is now the race's media director, ``There is
literally not one level step.''
</P>
<P>
   After a quarter-mile of slight downhill at the start, the course
goes straight up, except for a brief stretch somewhere in the
second mile. ``I think it's 11 steps, maybe 12,'' said Stifler.
``But nobody remembers them.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps 90 percent of the entrants walk at some point, but
timing stops at three hours, so no one dallies. Hardly anyone gives
up, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a race to drop out of,'' explained Stifler. Besides
the pride factor, he said, ``at a certain point it can't get any
worse than it is, so you just keep going.''
</P>
<P>
   After the surprising steepness at the beginning and the steady
steepness in the middle comes a brief respite of just plain steep,
before the staggering steepness just before the finish line of a
22-percent grade, twice the pitch of the rest of the course.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way they could make it worse is to have you climb the
radio tower at the end,'' observed Dunham.
</P>
<P>
   Credit for the first timed run up Mount Washington goes to
George Foster, a medical student out to impress his friends in
1904, according to a history of the race. Foster finished in 1 hour
and 42 minutes, faster, at the time, than any automobile had ever
made the trek.
</P>
<P>
   In 1936, the first race was held, with 12 runners finishing. For
the next two years, the race grew, but then it wasn't held again
until 1961, when it was revived to commemorate the 100th
anniversary of the Mount Washington Carriage Road. That year's
winner was John J. Kelley, winner of the 1957 Boston Marathon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old chestnut is, `There's only one hill,' '' said Kelley
last week. ``You can fool your legs until about 2 miles (into the
race). The idea is, you didn't go out too fast, and you got slower
as you went,'' said Kelley, reached at his home in Mystic, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's been 38 years since that victory, the man still
known as Johnny the Younger (to distinguish him from the legendary
John A. Kelley, who has run Boston 61 times and won twice, in 1935
and 1945) can recall every detail: the weather (about 70 degrees at
the base, 34 degrees and sleet at the top), how he felt (``just as
whacked as the last 6 miles of a marathon''), what he worried about
(``from 3 to 6 miles I was quite concerned my legs would numb out
and cease to be operational'').
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, ``I enjoyed it as much as you can enjoy any
masochistic activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelley and Jacqueline Gareau are the only two Boston Marathon
winners to also triumph at Mount Washington, but they are not the
only elite marathoners to have success there. Just two years ago,
two-time Olympic marathoner Cathy O'Brien of Durham, N.H., won,
with Joan Benoit Samuelson right behind her, setting a women's
masters record (age 40-44) of 1:16:03 in coming in second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through stages of thinking, `Gee, this isn't so bad.
This is bad. This is terrible. This isn't so bad,' '' said O'Brien.
``Was that fun? (Running) it is something that in a weak moment you
could be talked into. It isn't rational.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, the race appeals especially to older runners. There are
almost as many entrants 60 and over this year (61) as there are
under 30 (71).
</P>
<P>
   Runners who have done all the other races and have run the
fastest marathon they're ever going to run start looking around for
new frontiers, and, voila, there's Mount Washington, explained
Stifler.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, there's nothing really special about the training.
If you're already a runner, doing some speed work or adding some
hills to improve your cardiovascular strength is really about all
you can do, since there is nothing like the course and conditions.
</P>
<P>
   While the ascent may be physically and mentally draining in the
extreme, the recovery is mercifully swift. Explained Watson: ``Your
feet don't get more than three inches off the ground at any one
point,'' so there is little impact, which minimizes the strain on
muscles and joints.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Campbell, 81, of Lynnfield, Mass., is a member of the New
England 65 Plus Runners Club. Last year, he shattered the course
record for runners 80-84, completing the trek in 2:19:48. He'll be
back Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the good Lord is kind to me, I'll do it as many years as I
can,'' said Campbell. ``I'd like to be able to run it into my
90s.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Hodge of Clinton, Mass., who has won the race a record seven
times, has perhaps the most basic outlook on the relentless climb,
the arduous effort, the implacable and mocking mountain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost everything in running is overrated in terms of
difficulty, even the marathon,'' said Hodge, who has run 19 times.
``It's just one foot in front of the other.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
