<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
25 YEARS WITHOUT DUENDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every day I read the newspapers and every day I miss George
Frazier more. In the 25 years since he died, on June 13, 1974, no
other columnist has come along to equal him. But as his friend
Charlie Davidson points out, how could anyone take his place? ``No
one says: `I want to be another Bobby Short,' '' Davidson said the
other day. ``He's a singular talent. So was George.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Lydon, host of WBUR's ``The Connection'' and another
FOG (friend of George), sees a lot of Frazier in Maureen Dowd,
Christopher Buckley, Christopher Hitchens, Stanley Crouch. These
writers and others show Frazieresque flashes of wit and mischief.
They can be irreverent or erudite, scathing or silly or lyrical.
But not one of them does it all. Frazier did, and he did it for a
daily newspaper, three, four, even six times week.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier was an unusually graceful and literate writer, a master
of a dazzling range of styles. He practically invented attitude. He
had a gift for irritating people, and he did it in the most
entertaining way. He was born, reared, and educated in Boston, and
knew this city's curious ways as well as any native, but he spent
most of his working life in New York. His Boston newspaper career
spanned only seven years, three years at the Herald in the 1960s,
four at the Globe in the 1970s. In those few years, he made a
powerful impact on readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He still has this extraordinary effect on people who knew
him,'' said Charles Fountain, who wrote a biography of Frazier,
``Another Man's Poison.'' Fountain said he still gets a dozen or so
inquiries a year from people who want to know where they can buy
the book.
</P>
<P>
   Fountain, a professor of journalism at Northeastern University,
included in his book a telling analysis of Frazier's value by the
poet L. E. Sissman, who in the magazine Metro likened Frazier to
Shaw and Mencken as someone willing to ``think the unthinkable and
say the unsayable in print.''
</P>
<P>
   Sissmen continued: ``Eccentric, erratic, irascible, and, more
important, irrational, he takes on targets of opportunity, beats
them with verbal bladders without regard for his own personal job
security, and makes us think about his targets and ourselves.
Frazier doesn't throw baby punches; he hits hard out of the
mounting waspishness most of us increasingly feel, and makes blood
flow.''
</P>
<P>
   And he did it with such grace and wit. We're feeling more
waspish than ever, but who could take his place? Don Imus's name is
mentioned. Obviously he's not a writer, but Imus has, or had, a
similar ability to provoke, to think the unthinkable, say the
unsayable. ``Don Imus five years ago, before he became a Fortune
500 company, was, in a way, what Frazier was when he was at the
Herald and the Globe,'' Fountain said.
</P>
<P>
   Lydon, too, sees a certain similarity. ``The beautiful thing
about Imus four or five years ago was the same thing that was true
of George,'' he said. ``They could bring you up to speed on the
whole Zeitgeist in about 10 minutes. TV. Sports. Politics. A book.
A joke.''
</P>
<P>
   It's tempting to wonder whether Frazier would like being
compared to Imus, even the Imus of a few years ago, before he
became a bloated parody of his former self. ``George would have
turned on him long ago,'' Davidson said.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years after his death, Frazier's name keeps coming
up. Just last Saturday, I heard Craig Mustard and Larry Johnson
discussing Frazier on WEEI Sports Radio. Johnson took umbrage at
Mustard's repeated use of the word ``duende,'' a favorite theme of
Frazier's.
</P>
<P>
   ``People bring him up all the time, when we talk about taste or
clothes or writing,'' said Davidson, owner of the Andover Shop in
Harvard Square. ``Every time I turn around, somebody's using
`duende,' and I know that half of them don't know what it means.''
</P>
<P>
   Frazier wrote that Duende (he capitalized the word) denoted
``electricity'' or ``the certain something that sets persons
apart.'' He wrote whole columns about who had it and who didn't
(``Fred Astaire has it to the degree that Gene Kelly lacks it . . .
Jack Lemmon is Duende, Tony Randall could not be less so . . .'').
When he wrote that the Andover Shop had Duende, Davidson swears
someone called to ask what colors it came in.
</P>
<P>
   Monica. O.J. Simpson. The death of Diana. Marv Albert. The
decline of Brooks Brothers. Bill Weld. Foodies. Elvis's death and
reincarnation. Mike Tyson. Madonna. The resurrection of Richard
``The Mad Bomber'' Nixon. Bob Kraft. Martha Stewart. The deaths of
Sinatra and DiMaggio. It seems impossible that Frazier wasn't here
for any of the above, and so much more. Many times I've wondered
what he would have written about one thing or another. I'll go on
wondering for the rest of my life. He was, as Charlie Davidson
said, a singular talent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
