<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SEASON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPENSE TO SPARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN KOCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
IN A DRY SEASON 
By Peter Robinson 
Avon, 422 pp., $24 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The murder victim in Peter Robinson's ``In a Dry Season'' has
been dead for half a century when this resonantly satisfying
suspense novel opens. That we come to care as much as we do about
the person who animated these old bones is a tribute to the
author's foremost talent. Able plotter and smooth stylist that he
is, Robinson is above all a gifted creator of fully fleshed and
vividly present characters.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the central role in the book played by Alan Banks
(this is the author's 10th Inspector Banks novel), the real
protagonist is the passionate, pretty, and ill-fated Gloria
Stringer. At first merely a forensic puzzle to Banks, she becomes
an obsession, both a magnetically appealing human being whose
reality he helps to rescue from the past, and a symbol of the
tragedies of victimization that drove him into police work.
Attractive, likable, complexly flawed, and fatally wronged, she
generates a charge that is felt on almost every page of this
eminently readable novel.
</P>
<P>
   Her skeleton is discovered accidentally in the muck of the
empty, ruined North Yorkshire village of Hobb's End, once covered
by the waters of a reservoir but now exposed again in an especially
dry season. Banks, himself a richly realized character _ a
grittier, funkier version of Colin Dexter's Inspector Morse _ is
assigned to investigate the remains for disciplinary reasons. His
officious superintendent dislikes him for being vaguely
insubordinate _ in fact, the reflective and often philosophical
Banks is merely independent and unsuited to office politics.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the intended putdown turns into a plum as Banks
gathers (forensically fascinating) evidence suggesting an
unreported and unavenged crime of passion committed during the
1940s. Into the bargain, Banks, estranged from his wife, aquires an
enchanting girlfriend in the person of Annie Cabbot, an intuitive
and self-determining detective sergeant in the mold of Banks
himself.
</P>
<P>
   By braiding together three distinctly different narrative
strands, Robinson creates a suspense novel with many of the dynamic
qualities of more literary fiction.
</P>
<P>
   One strand is the lively present-day police procedural following
Banks's investigation, enriched by his risky romance with a
subordinate and the complications of his imploding middle-aged
life. His son has renounced university life to pursue a career in
pop music, aggravating the tension between them. Smoking too many
cigarettes and brooding about his choice of profession, his ancient
hatred of schoolyard bullies, and his own unappreciative
working-class parents, Banks is as deeply and thoroughly faceted as
any serial detective, British or American, I can think of.
</P>
<P>
   A second narrative element is a journal by Gwynneth Shackleton,
chronicling her life in Hobb's End and, in particular, her close
wartime friendship with Gloria Stringer, a mysterious refugee there
from the London blitz. Gloria eventually marries Gwynneth's brother
but also manages to inflame a number of other men, including
several posted at the American air base established nearby late in
the war.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson masterfully embodies the voice of the awkward,
literarily inclined Gwynneth and, through her, paints a remarkable
picture not only of Gloria but also of English wartime existence,
filled with colorful and intriguing historical details. Gloria, for
example, comes to Hobb's End as a member of the Women's Land Army,
a corps of young women assigned to replace soldiers who did farm
work. There is much attention to the stringent rationing of the day
and the hardships of nightly blackouts. In one country town,
``People had ... put little dabs of luminous paint on their
doorbells, which glowed like fireflies all along the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   The third narrative line involves an aging crime writer, the
best-selling Vivian Elmsley, who's increasingly disturbed by the
nationally breaking news of Banks's investigation. As more is
disclosed about the old bones and the violence they reveal, she is
assailed by feelings of grief and guilt. But just what role the
unraveling author played in the wartime crime isn't made clear
until the novel's melodramatic but neatly satisfying conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   British crime novels tend to be baggier than their leaner, and
generally meaner, American counterparts, and often seem padded with
digressions and eccentric swatches of local color that curb their
narrative drive. But Robinson's book justifies its considerable
length with its well-built and finely polished multi-voiced
structure. His rather daring approach to the genre has the effect
both of deepening the form and intensifying the anguish and
excitement we expect from good suspense fiction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
