<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-ELECTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELECTION IN INDONESIA IS HARDLY SETTLED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ After Indonesia's first democratic
elections in 44 years, the ruling party of ousted autocratic
President Suharto has conceded defeat, ending decades of one-party
rule.
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to a complex and indirect voting system, the race for
the presidency is just beginning and the final winners and losers
in Indonesia's transition to democracy are not at all clear.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, the outcome of every election here was well known
in advance; the ruling Golkar party banned most opposition and
rigged results when intimidation and vote-buying did not work. But
even if massive cheating finally ended with last Monday's vote,
that does not mean the widely reviled ruling party has been
eliminated from power.
</P>
<P>
   A year after anti-Suharto riots claimed 1,200 lives and forced
the autocrat to step down, voters' expectations for democratic
change are soaring. If a split vote enables Suharto's old party to
cobble together a coalition, analysts suggested that Indonesians
may take to the streets again in fury.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, ``the opposition has restrained itself, because they
are expecting to win,'' said Jusuf Wanandi, chairman of the
Jakarta-based Center for Strategic and International Studies.
</P>
<P>
   But what if those hopes are dashed?
</P>
<P>
   Megawati Sukarnoputri's Indonesian Democratic Party for Struggle
still leads official and unofficial vote counts, but nearly every
tally has Golkar in a surprise second-place finish in the
parliamentary race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not really talking about a choice among 48 parties, but
between the Suharto order and a new political system. . . . Even if
20 percent of people voted for Golkar, that means four-fifths of
the people want a new government,'' said Wimar Witoelar, an
oppostion political commentator and radio host.
</P>
<P>
   But the voters will not choose the next president. It will be
the national assembly _ made up of 462 newly elected members, 38
military appointees, 135 regional electors and 65 representatives
from minority groups. That leaves the field open for deal-making
among 700 people who will choose the leader of the world's
fourth-most populous nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thinking now among potential winners is that we've got to
avoid being mathematical about it, and we have to play the game and
show which way the political wind is blowing so those people
capable of buying votes realize they cannot do it,'' Witoelar
added. ``Those who select the president in November should realize
they will face the wrath of the people if they do not choose one of
the leaders of the reform movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Even without dirty dealing, however, votes for Parliament do not
translate directly into seats. Indonesia's district/proportional
voting system overrepresents thinly populated provinces, and the
ruling party remains strong in many outlying islands. For example,
the province of Irian Jaya has 1 million people and gets 12 seats
in Parliament, while the capital city Jakarta has more than 10
million people, but gets just 18 seats. By Golkar's count, it will
control the votes in 13 provinces, the same number as Megawati's
party.
</P>
<P>
   Projections based on the national distribution of votes indicate
that even with 38 percent of the vote Megawati's party holds so
far, it would get only 27 percent of parliamentary seats. In
contrast, Golkar, with 16 percent of votes, would get a
disproportionate 24 percent of seats. Golkar is farther ahead in
unofficial tallies that have tabulated more votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're conceding defeat in terms of the electoral count, but in
terms of the formation of the government, it's not over yet,'' said
Marzuki Darusman, cochairman of Golkar. Darusman said Golkar's
strategy was to boost its credibility among the public by accepting
technical defeat and thereby counter allegations of vote-tampering,
while ``building up the acceptability of cooperation'' with other
parties.
</P>
<P>
   The armed forces were long associated with Suharto, and military
appointees to Parliament may align themselves with the party of the
old regime. An array of small Muslim parties is also likely to side
with Golkar, partly because many could not accept a woman as
president and partly because her party represents secular rather
than religious interests. Megawati has also opposed granting
significant autonomy to restive provinces, a position that could
undermine her support with assembly members from those regions.
</P>
<P>
   That means it is conceivable that Megawati, the candidate
favored by the largest bloc of voters, may not have enough support
in the assembly to lead the next government.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said the likely outcome would be a compromise
candidate, such as the sultan of Yogyakarta, the Muslim scholar
Nurcholis Majid or even General Wiranto, head of the armed forces.
``Golkar cannot control the government, it's not possible,'' said
Arbi Sanit, a political scientist at the University of Indonesia.
``But Megawati herself may not be the winner.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet that outcome would almost surely be unacceptable to the
nearly 40 percent of people who apparently voted for Megawati. That
in itself, some analysts said, could make any government without
her at its head unsustainable, because it would spark such outrage
and unrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Golkar leads the government, what will be the reaction of
the people?'' asked an Asian diplomat posted here. ``People are not
interested in the intricacies of how votes are allocated. They
thought they were voting for president, and voted for her.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
