<DOCNO> NYT19990614.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4552 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSUMER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-14 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS RATES FALL, DIGITAL CELL PHONES SWITCHING ON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL AND PATRICIA WEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You don't have to look far to see that digital cell phones, as
opposed to the traditional analog ones, are fast becoming the most
popular type of wireless phone in this country.
</P>
<P>
   These tiny handsets are tucked into backpacks, briefcases, and
purses everywhere, and sales are brisk. In the first three months
of this year, 75 percent of the people who signed up for cellular
phone plans chose digital, not analog, service.
</P>
<P>
   There's good reason: Prices of the phones and plans are
dropping. And new plans come in simple bulk-rate packages _
hundreds of minutes at a flat monthly rate _ so people aren't so
anxious about each minute's cost.
</P>
<P>
   Also, more people are addicted to the convenience of a cell
phone in their everyday life, no longer seeing it as something only
for an emergency. And the more you use the phone, the more
cost-effective it becomes to buy a digital plan.
</P>
<P>
   Analog phones remain a good buy for emergency users, largely
because the monthly cost can stay in the $15 range if you keep your
usage very low. But there's no question analog handsets are on
their way to extinction. In a few years, analysts say, analog
phones will be like black-and-white TVs.
</P>
<P>
   Analog service does have the benefit of being around longer.
There are more analog antennas up, offering superior coverage at
this time, particularly in rural areas. But analog relies on a
less-efficient technology: A person's entire voice is transmitted
across the radio channel, taking up more space along the channel.
With digital, a caller's voice is converted into a stream of binary
1's and 0's, which enables calls to be greatly compressed.
Per-minute charges with digital are generally cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   Rae Walton, an energetic 78-year-old, is among the new digital
converts. She just came to the end of a two-year contract with Bell
Atlantic Mobile, in which she had a clunky analog phone and paid
$15 a month for the service, as well as 35 to 99 cents a minute for
each local call. She wanted the phone for emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   But now she wants to use the phone more often, keeping her in
touch with family and friends regardless of where she is. After
looking around at all the carriers, she chose the Bell Atlantic
Mobile DigitalChoice plan that offers 200 minutes at $29.99, with
free nights and weekend calling. She also gets the entry-level
phone, a BAM300D, for $50 after rebates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The convenience of these cell phones excites me,'' said
Walton, a retired school psychologist. ``It's fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to price for a moderate user, it's hard to beat
the Bell Atlantic and the Sprint entry-level digital plans. AT&AMP;T's
plans become more competitive if you are a more extensive user, and
Cellular One and Omnipoint offer cheaper monthly deals but with far
fewer minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond price, you have to consider what carrier offers the
best coverage for your needs. A cheap plan is useless if you can't
get a dial tone. Don't accept the mistaken notion _ often
perpetuated by cellular phone sales staff _ that your area is full
of cellular antennas providing blanket coverage.
</P>
<P>
   There are gaps in coverage in the Boston area, for example, and
it's particularly noticeable if you rely on digital service only.
Carriers are scrambling to put up digital antennas, while facing
opposition from some communities.
</P>
<P>
   To find out what carrier is best for you, you have to do your
own homework. There's no simple chart available. It depends on
where you live and where you travel. Ask carriers for their
coverage maps and antenna locations, and talk to people who have
cell-phone experience in the areas where you travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``With competition and lots of choice, it requires people to do
a lot of research,'' said Mark Lowenstein of the Yankee Group, a
telecommunications research firm in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   If you want the maximum amount of coverage, it's best to stick
to dual-band phones, offering analog and digital service, and buy a
bucket of minutes that includes both types of calls. When you buy a
bucket of minutes with Bell Atlantic Mobile, AT&AMP;T Wireless, and
Cellular One, you get analog and digital types of minutes included.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint's bucket only covers digital calls, with analog costing
extra. And Omnipoint phones can only handle digital calls, with no
option to roam onto analog service.
</P>
<P>
   Another thing to consider is if you want a local or national
one-rate plan. Calls outside that area bring about extra per-minute
long-distance charges, as well as a deduction from your allotment
of minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The national one-rate plans are more costly and require the
purchase of more minutes, but the amount you buy covers local and
long-distance calls. If you're a heavy long-distance caller, these
plans might be good for you.
</P>
<P>
   When evaluating plans, think about what is truly important to
you. Some don't charge for the first incoming minute, which can be
a big benefit if you receive many calls that are only a sentence or
two. If you're unsure of how much you'll like the digital service,
you might want a month-to-month plan.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, take your time in doing your research and don't get
pressured into a deal because a sales person warns you a special
promotion is ending. Competition is fierce, and carriers want your
business badly. This week's Father's Day specials will probably be
next month's Fourth of July bargain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Odds &AMP; Ends
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --On-line fraud and junk mail. A survey released last month by
the National Consumers League, ``Consumers in the 21st Century,''
found that 7 percent or 6 million Internet subscribers experienced
on-line fraud or misuse of information related to their credit
cards. The study from the nonprofit consumer advocacy group also
found that two-thirds of Americans think that by the year 2020 all
banking will be done on line. When it comes to the biggest everyday
gripes, consumers put junk mail and automated phone-answering
systems at the top.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(We want your consumer ideas and tips. Please e-mail Wen at
wen(at)globe.com or Mohl at mohl(at)globe.com. Their postal address
is Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
