<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4554 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACK-ANCESTORS-ART-B     06-14 1671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-ANCESTORS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCH CHALLENGES IDEAS ON RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON AND JORDANA HART  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Documentary-film researcher Mario Valdes was
born in the Caribbean Basin country of Belize, part of a family
ensconced in the country's white power structure.
</P>
<P>
   When he was a teenager, he stumbled upon a family secret: His
roots actually dug deep into the Caribbean black majority,
considered by many whites to be lower-class descendants of slaves.
</P>
<P>
   Moved by what he learned about the blurring of family lines, and
his growing sense of the futility of racial distinctions, Valdes
embarked on a quest to challenge assumptions about race by tracing
the unknown African lineage of world figures.
</P>
<P>
   His latest genealogical effort _ in negotiations for an English
television documentary _ is causing an international stir: He
exposed the alleged black roots of England's Queen Elizabeth.
</P>
<P>
   After the Sunday Times of London reported his findings last
week, Valdes became a sought-after man. He received calls from the
media across the British Commonwealth, and negotiations began for a
documentary series, including notables of African descent _ a
famous Russian poet and the first duke of Florence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This upsets the whole paradigm of the social ladder where
black is at the very bottom and royal houses at the very top,''
said Valdes, a light-skinned man of 58.
</P>
<P>
   The key to Valdes's claims about Queen Elizabeth is the family
tree he charted of England's Queen Charlotte, who died in 1818 and
who has been rumored for nearly two centuries to be a direct
descendant of a black woman.
</P>
<P>
   On the heels of a recent scientific article that cited DNA
evidence of a probable relationship between Thomas Jefferson and
his slave Sally Hemings, and this year's 200th birthday of Russian
literary giant Alexander Pushkin _ a direct descendant of Ethiopian
Prince Ibrahim Hannibal _ the likely blood tie between the British
royal family and Africa again illustrates the extent of mixing of
black and white blood throughout the centuries.
</P>
<P>
   And, in the eyes of Valdes and other historians, it exposes the
resistance, particularly in white society, to acknowledge how much
race-mixing went on here and throughout Europe over the centuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``This tells us that we ought to be careful about defining race
and issues pertaining to race,'' said Selwyn Carrington, a British
Imperial historian at Howard University in Washington, D.C. ``That
outer layer of white or black is so subjective.''
</P>
<P>
   It took Valdes nearly two decades to trace the British royal
family's black blood line, but he said genealogical charts firmly
link Charlotte, the wife of King George III and grandmother of
Queen Victoria, to a Portuguese king and his Moorish mistress in
the 13th century.
</P>
<P>
   But because royals tended to intermarry, Valdes said, he traced
six connections between Charlotte and Madalena Gil, the Moorish
``rite of conquest'' of a king who defeated her father's army at
Faro, a town in Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   Although Valdes might well be the first to document, link by
link, the strongly rumored black blood line of the British royal
family, he is not the first to give voice to the claims.
</P>
<P>
   During the black nationalism movement in the 1970s, blacks
throughout the British Commonwealth embraced Queen Charlotte as one
of their own. In Halifax, Nova Scotia, Canadians of African
ancestry insisted on having a black Mountie stand by the portrait
of Charlotte, which hangs in Government House in Halifax, Valdes
said.
</P>
<P>
   African-American historian Joel Rogers noted in his book ``100
Amazing facts about the Negro'' that Charlotte was of African
descent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a drum that has been beating in the black community
for a long time,'' Valdes said.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte, a 17-year-old German princess, was perceived to have
strong African features, which set off rumors of her ancestry as
soon as she arrived in England to marry the king in 1761. Sir
Walter Scott, a contemporary of the queen, described her family as
``ill-colored,'' and her personal physician, Baron Stockmar, said
she had ``true mulatto features,'' Valdes said. She had ``a nose
too flat . . . a mouth too large,'' Nora Lofts wrote in her book,
``Queens of England.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte was a handpicked bride for George III. The marriage
was a success: The couple remained close despite the king's illness
and alleged insanity, and they produced 15 children.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews this week, some specialists on British peerage
tried to minimize Valdes's findings, saying the racial connection
is nothing more than a historical blip, given that it stretches
back so many centuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is so remote,'' said David Williamson, co-editor of
Debrett's Peerage, a guide published in London every five years on
barons, dukes and duchesses, marquises, and other titled people.
``In any case, all European royal families somewhere are linked to
the kings of Castille. There is a lot of Moorish blood in the
Portuguese royal family and it has diffused over the rest of
Europe. The question is, who cares?''
</P>
<P>
   Said a Buckingham Palace spokesman, David Buck: ``This has been
rumored for years and years. It is a matter of history, and
frankly, we've got far more important things to talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, many people celebrated the racial and cultural
ramifications of Queen Charlotte's lineage, saying the notion of a
shared ancestry could have important ramifications for multiracial
nations such as Britain and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the public doesn't want to acknowledge what has been
a long-hidden secret, especially in America,'' said Shirlee Taylor
Haizlip, author of ``Sweeter the Juice,'' which chronicles the life
of her black family members who passed as whites. ``One of the
major cudgels of slavery was that black people were inferior to
white people. But it can be demonstrated that black people and
white people were very much intertwined.''
</P>
<P>
   Haizlip said she and others estimate that 70 to 95 percent of
European Americans have some black ancestry, and 80 percent of
black Americans have some white ancestry.
</P>
<P>
   One historian predicted that reaction to the African link would
probably be muted, even a little hostile, in certain British and
American circles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This looks like a quest for political correctness,'' said
Eugene Black, a European history professor at Brandeis University.
``We have all these questions now about not-pure Anglo-Saxon
bloodlines, and I don't think that will play particularly well over
the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Haizlip, a former university lecturer on race, argued
that Pushkin, the Jefferson-Hemings link, and the black lineage of
Queen Elizabeth are ``important because (they) show that one group
is not less human or inferior to the other.''
</P>
<P>
   In London, playwright Valerie Mason-John said, ``Most people are
not aware that the royal family has this black heritage. Not only
is it fascinating, but also people would want to know just how
diverse their background is because they are seen by many as the
model family.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the revelations about the alleged lineage of the
British royal family fulfilled Valdes's desire to make a strong
point about the merging of racial bloodlines.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Sullivan, executive producer of the WGBH ``Frontline''
series of documentaries, said: ``He (Valdes) is the real thing. He
is on this gigantic personal quest to expose a view of race that I
think most of us are completely unaware of.''
</P>
<P>
   Previously, Valdes researched a number of cases of racial
crossing for film producer June Cross's Emmy-award winning
documentary ``Secret Daughter.'' Sullivan said ``Frontline''
created a Web site after Valdes provided a number of examples of
famous people with African blood links, including Alessandro De
Medici, the first duke of Florence, whose mother was reported to be
an African servant.
</P>
<P>
   He first started trying to unlock the riddle of Charlotte's
ancestry when he moved from what was then the crown colony of
British Honduras to the Boston area in 1967. Initially, he was
stumped to find that her lineage showed not a trace of a black
ancestor: ``Four generations of her genealogy and she was
absolutely lily-white. No illegitimacy. They were all German.''
</P>
<P>
   He gave up until he moved to Montreal in the 1970s and resumed
his research. All along, he had struggled fitfully to identify the
wife of Charlotte's ancestress _ the wife of Lieutenant Jean De
Neufchatel of Burgundy. That's when he contacted a genealogist from
the New York Public Library, who returned his call almost
immediately with the name of the lieutenant's wife _ Margarita de
Castro y Sousa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bingo!'' said Valdes.
</P>
<P>
   The de Sousas are widely accepted among genealogists as a black
branch of the Portuguese royal family, he said. ``The next question
was why, if her black ancestry was so far down the line, could
(black features) show up so vividly in Charlotte?''
</P>
<P>
   The key, he discovered, was that Charlotte was descended from
the black line in a number of ways: When Alfonso III of Portugal
conquered Faro, a small Portuguese town controlled by the Moors in
the 13th century, he took the African daughter of Faro's governor _
Ouruana, who is later baptised Madalena Gil _ as his ``droit de
seigneur,'' or rite of conquest. One of their sons, Martin Alfonso,
married into the de Sousa family, who also had black ancestry,
Valdes said. Back then, it was proper to take the name of the most
powerful family.
</P>
<P>
   Although Charlotte was chronologically distant from her Moorish
ancestors, Valdes said royal inbreeding was common.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only was the black blood repeated in six different ways,
but in my calculation, she was between an octoroon (one-eighth
black) or someone of one-sixteeth black,'' Valdes said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
