<HEADLINE>
SHORT REVIEWS OF RECENT MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   !!! ``After Life'' It looks like a rundown school building,
staffed by civil-service interviewers, but it's actually a way
station for the just-deceased in Japanese director's Hirokazu
Kore-eda's original and compassionate fantasy where the pilgrims
are asked to choose one vivid memory to take with them into the
afterlife. (Unrated)
</P>
<P>
   (FL) !!! ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me'' More of the
same: Mike Myers's toothy '60s airhead recycles his Carnaby Street
James Bond-wannabe routine, reveling in a screenful of campy
artifacts, most psychedelic. He also doubles as Powers's nemesis,
Dr. Evil, a pussycat who can't manage his dysfunctional family,
much less dominate the world. Heather Graham's nubile CIA operative
named Felicity Shagwell is a big plus in this good bad movie.
(PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   (FR) !! ``Besieged'' Bernardo Bertolucci tries for a
cross-cultural love story in a Roman villa. But there's no depth of
character or point of believable connection between Thandie
Newton's African medical student and political refugee and David
Thewlis's eccentric concert pianist. He falls for her after she
comes to work for him as a domestic, setting off master-servant
vibes that never realize their sexual or political potential. (R)
</P>
<P>
   !!! ``Twice Upon a Yesterday'' Beguiling romantic fantasy, set
in contemporary London, that beats the odds by gambling on gentle
magic to sort out a couple of relationship crises. This impressive
debut film from Spain's Maria Ripoll is given a big boost by
Penelope Cruz's softly luminous romantic, who helps Douglas
Henshall's loose-cannon actor get the rain out of his shoes _ with
an assist from Elizabeth McGovern's bartender, who may be dishing
out magic along with pints of bitter. (R)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-99 1333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990614.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4558 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-ELLISON-BOS &LR;      06-14 1280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-ELLISON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELLISON TAKES UP THE AMERICAN STORY OF RACE AND IDENTITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With its singular ardor voice and uncompromising vision, Ralph
Ellison's ``Invisible Man'' merged the underworld of midcentury
black America with the infinitely subterranean quest for
self-identity. Striving only to become a good man, the nameless
narrator of the novel finds chicanery and cruelty almost
everywhere; but much of his journey is underscored by his
grandfather's dying words to his son: ``Live with your head in the
lion's mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   The dark and endless odyssey of the novel was a vast literary
undertaking defined by brilliant riffs of language and metaphors of
light and shadow, and it was recognized upon its publication in
1952 for the modernist classic it was to become. By the time of his
death, at 80, in 1994, it would be Ellison's only published novel _
a poignant fact that allowed for mythic possibility, in the form of
another manuscript, unpublished, some 40 years and 2,000 pages in
the making.
</P>
<P>
   Although a relatively small portion of that fugitive second
novel was destroyed in a fire in 1967, most of the manuscript was
intact and incomplete when Ellison died; the last excerpt had been
published in 1977, but he told David Remnick of The New Yorker in
the months before his death that he still expected to finish the
book. Of such absences great expectations are made, and so it has
been with ``Juneteenth'' _ an extraction by Ellison's literary
executor of one-third of the story, meant to stand alone as ``the
true center of Ellison's great, unfinished house of fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   Even aside from the manuscript's legendary status, the apparent
motives behind John F. Callahan's revisions and selections (which
had the full blessing of Ellison's widow) are understandable.
Scholars have access to the full work-in-progress, including
Ellison's notes and letters, now housed at the Library of Congress;
this curatorial placement was the only request the author made
about the novel before he died. But the reading public, too,
deserves a glimpse of what so consumed and eluded Ellison for four
decades. In letters and interviews over the years, he revealed his
wish to articulate the profoundly American story of race and
identity that he had begun in ``Invisible Man''; as an unstructured
whole, the projected second novel would move between Washington,
D.C., and Oklahoma, back and forth in time from the beginning of
the 20th century to the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to distill a narrative ``that best stands alone as
a single, self-contained volume,'' Callahan has chosen the
intertwined story of two men, set in the 1950s: Bliss Sunraider, a
racist senator of indeterminate birth who is probably mostly white,
and Daddy Hickman, the huge-hearted black jazzman turned preacher
who raised him.
</P>
<P>
   Named for the June 19, 1865, day of celebration, some two years
after the Emancipation Proclamation, when word reached slaves in
Galveston, Texas, that they were free, ``Juneteenth'' is structured
as two antiphonal narratives between Bliss and Hickman; they are in
the hospital, where Bliss lies dying from an attempt on his life on
the Senate floor. Because the novel opens with this assassin's
bullet, when Hickman has traveled to Washington to see Bliss and
perhaps warn him of the attack, we will learn their stories through
a retrospective exchange, much of it unspoken. As with Faulkner's
alternating narrators in ``As I Lay Dying,'' the same events are
relayed and retold from different perspectives; as with Faulkner's
mythic mysteries in ``Absalom, Absalom!,'' events of central
significance elude us until the end of the story.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the mark of Faulkner is all over the narrative of
``Juneteenth,'' but these comparisons are technical rather than
qualitative. While the novel contains rhapsodic passages,
particularly those illuminating the interplay between Baptist
revivalism and political rhetoric, the story itself manages to feel
both bloated and gauzy. Stripped of any larger meaning at the time
of their introduction, Bliss's oratories (born, it turns out, from
learning at Hickman's knee how to swoon a crowd) take on the
eye-glazing quality of a literary filibuster. And while the
sorrowful ironies surrounding Hickman's rearing of Bliss may speak
beautifully to the tragedies of race in America, these revelations
occur so haltingly _ most of them at the end of the novel _ that
the preceding story lacks any real compelling thrust or urgency.
</P>
<P>
   The very sketchiness of the characters' history, especially
Bliss's, suggests their having been gleaned from a much larger
work, and suggests, too, some of the troubles Ellison must have
faced in completing his work. There is ample evidence here of a
brilliant mess, decorated with dazzling language and high-wire
wisdom, but a mess nonetheless. One can imagine the excerpts over
the years seeming breathtaking in their promise: Daddy Hickman
eventually emerges as a strong creation, equal parts ``horn-blowing
gambler'' and holy giant, and drawn from the same enigmas that
touched Rinehart in ``Invisible Man.''
</P>
<P>
   When Bliss is shot at the beginning of the novel, Hickman,
seated in the Senate's visitors' gallery, rises and begins to sing
_ ``his white head towering over his clustered flock, tears
gleaming bright against the darkness of his face, creating with his
voice an atmosphere of bafflement and mystery no less outrageous
than the shooting which had released it.'' This is the man who
sheltered the light-skinned Bliss as an infant and raised him
within the abiding love of a black religious community; his
lamentation, then, is in part a heartbroken song of homecoming to a
prodigal son.
</P>
<P>
   If the failings in ``Juneteenth'' are large, they are not flaws
of mediocrity, and Ellison's admirers will find discrete treasures
to sustain their regard: passages on the forced migrations of
slavery, on modernity's fracturing of linear time, on Bliss's
horrid circus experience or Hickman's standing before the Lincoln
Memorial. More than anything Ellison was a passionate writer, and
passion is unquestionably present in ``Juneteenth,'' even in the
weakest and most indulgent parts of the novel. With his somber
comprehension of the near-fatal wounds of race, Ellison also
understood inexorable longing _ a quality that hovers over Bliss's
story, from his yearning for a mother he never knew to his
misguided path away from Daddy Hickman. This emotional eloquence,
carefully muted in ``Invisible Man,'' was one of that novel's
greatest gifts; its presence here, however scattershot, is a
reminder of just what kind of writer Ellison could be.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike too many efforts by literary executors to publish
posthumously everything but recipes, something of Ellison's unknown
opus warranted print. Whether it was ``Juneteenth,'' Callahan's
apparently well-intended vision, will be for scholars who view the
entire manuscript to ascertain. But one gets the feeling from
reading ``Juneteenth'' that Ellison could never assume the
requisite mastery over this work to make it what it needed to be.
He long paid homage to the influences of Faulkner and Twain and
Stephen Crane and Henry James, and he must have envisioned an epic
that would take him across his own version of America's territories
_ across decades of history and miles of struggle, to that part of
land and memory with ``everything wide open and hopeful.'' But like
some great unfinished surveyor's map, filled with colors but no
final coordinates, it sprawled out before him into a vast,
uncharted unknown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
