<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRONT-RUNNING, BUT ON WHAT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not quite Caesar crossing the Rubicon, but from the billing
in Republican circles, this week's big event seems almost as
momentous. George W. Bush is crossing the Merrimack.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor comes to New Hampshire for two days of
campaigning with GOP hopes and expectations, as Groucho Marx once
quipped of his taxes, as high as an elephant's eye.
</P>
<P>
   So far, this hasn't been a campaign so much as a coronation.
Bush, on the strength of four and a half years as governor of
Texas, has benefitted from a coalescence of party support that
eluded his more accomplished father even after a lifetime of public
service, including eight years as vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Without ever putting Texas in the rear-view mirror, George the
younger has powered by two-time cabinet secretary Elizabeth Dole
and 1996 New Hampshire victor Pat Buchanan. So large does he loom
that Lamar Alexander, undercapitalized and overshadowed, has scaled
back his campaign from a full-fledged national effort to a
hope-for-a-stumble stand in Iowa and New Hampsire.
</P>
<P>
   ``In New Hampshire as well as the across the country, Bush is
the frontrunner,'' said David Moore, New Hampshire-based managing
director of the Gallup Poll. ``But we just completed a big survey
that found that seven of 10 Americans said they need to know more
about him.''
</P>
<P>
   No surprise there. As many have noted, it's odd indeed that the
Republican Party has annointed as its savior the son of man who
only a few short years ago was reviled by many conservatives as a
tax-raising apostate to the party's fiscal faith. It's odder still
since George W. has collected scores of endorsements and millions
of dollars while hardly offering a clue about why he should be
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can't be what he stands for,'' notes Tufts University
political scientists Jim Glaser. ``Who the heck knows what he
stands for?''
</P>
<P>
   So what's powering Bush's candidacy? Big-state status, a
well-known name, and a sense (affirmed by polls) that he could beat
Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But frontrunning electablility is marshy soil on which to build
a primary campaign. So far, it's often made Bush's candidacy seem
conceived in committee and consumed with caution.
</P>
<P>
   Which is where New Hampshire comes in. It's a state whose
Republicans admire forthright, plain-spoken aspirants, a state
whose penchant for surprise led to it back Henry Cabot Lodge's
absentee write-in effort against party titans like Nelson
Rockefeller and Barry Goldwater in 1964, to flock to the
take-charge qualities of a Ronald Reagan in 1980 and to reward the
mince-no-words conservatism of a Patrick Buchanan in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush is going to have to take some stands and answer some
tough questions and New Hampshire will really be the first forum
where he he has to do that,'' said John Camobreco, professor of
political science at the University of New Hampshire. ``And this
state has never been particularly kind to his father.''
</P>
<P>
   No, it hasn't. Even as vice president, the elder Bush barely
staved off a challenge from Bob Dole there in 1988, and then only
with the all-out help of then Gov. John Sununu. In 1992, New
Hampshire Republicans gave GOP insurgent Pat Buchanan 37 percent of
the vote _ enough to fuel his campaign against President Bush well
into the South.
</P>
<P>
   And George W. is no time-tested party leader who can lay claim
to the Republican rites of political primogeniture. Indeed, he
might not even make the top 10 list of the nation's most effective,
innovative, or hard-charging Republican governors.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly he's been no Tommy Thompson pushing a radical overhaul
of welfare in Wisconsin, no Gary Johnson, waging a hammer and tong
war for school vouchers in New Mexico, no Christine Todd Whitman,
winning big tax cuts in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, as governor, Bush has been the GOP equivalent of a
second-term Mike Dukakis, a smart, cautious practitioner of the
possible rather than a determined reformer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He likes to set modest, achievable goals, around which there
exists a preordained consensus so he doesn't have to do much
persuading,'' said Bruce Buchanan, professor of government at the
University of Texas at Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Which is apparently the way he intends to run for president. As
he comes to New Hampshire, Bush says he will focus on four issues:
tax cuts, free trade, beefing up the military, and improving
education.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, some of Bush's stands, such as his 1995 support
for an NRA-backed ``right to carry'' law overturning a long-time
ban on concealed weapons, will certainly provide general-election
fodder. In an era when HMO has become a dirty word, his 1995 veto
of a patients rights bill might even hurt inside a Republican
primary.
</P>
<P>
   And though it would have been a net tax cut, his 1997 tax plan _
in which he proposed raising the sales tax and taxing professional
services to finance a property tax reduction _ could lend itself to
the sort of distorted attacks President Bush launched against Bill
Clinton in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, George W. seems to have some of the true Texas grit
that eluded his father. State Representative Tommy Merritt, a
Democrat, loves the Republican governor because he has put himself
on the front lines in the citizens' war against drugs, twice coming
to Kilgore in northeast Texas to join a group of activists
targeting drug dealers in their neighborhoods. The activists gather
outside crackhouse and drug dens to shout slogans and keep watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He not only does the talk, he walks the walk,'' enthuses
Merritt. ``He actually puts his feet in the street.''
</P>
<P>
   But on other high-profile issues, Bush has struck a low profile
in courage. Take this year's attempt to pass a hate-crimes bill.
That legislation, named after James Byrd Jr., the African-American
whose June 1998 murder by being dragged behind a truck horrified
the nation, would have stipulated stepped-up penalties for crimes
motivated by animus against one's race, ethnicity, gender,
religion, or sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   Signing such a law, with the sexual orientation clause, would
have angered religious conservatives, an important GOP primary
voting bloc. But vetoing it would haved angered moderates (one
Texas poll showed 70 percent of Texans favored the bill.)
</P>
<P>
   So Bush temporized, trying to duck while his Senate allies
worked to keep the bill bottled up in committee. That stance led to
an uncomfortable meeting with Darrell Verrett, Byrd's nephew, and
Renee Mullins, Byrd's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   An emotional Mullins appealed to Bush for help with the bill.
``I would hate to see my father die in vain,'' she said, her cousin
remembers.
</P>
<P>
   Distant and seemingly ill at ease, Bush was noncommittal, saying
there were some parts of the bill he objected to.
</P>
<P>
   Which ones? Bush said he would have to read the bill before
specifying. Verrett produced a copy, handed it to the governor, and
asked again what bothered him. Surprised, Bush set the bill aside,
making it clear he wouldn't read it then and there, and politely
ended the meeting, Verrett says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the whole meeting was just a political strategy
move,'' he said. ``He had to say he had met with Byrd's family and
was somewhat sympathetic . . . but it was an empty meeting that
didn't resolve anything. He was very vague, defensive and
unemotional.''
</P>
<P>
   If that's the bad side of cautious incrementalism, others say
Bush also has those qualities so missing among the the GOP's
Washington wing in recent years: An willingness to work with the
opposition. Norman Newton, executive director of the Associated
Republicans of Texas, remembers that immediately after his election
in 1994, the new goveror walked the Capitol halls in Austin,
meeting with legislators of both parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went into virtually every legislative office, Democrat or
Republican, just to find out what their concerns were,'' Newton
said. ``He is very good at sitting down with the Democrats and
working with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet beneath that storied geniality, there is a steely side to
Bush. Thomas Pauken, a former Texas Republican Party chairman who
served as executive director of ACTION, the federal volunteer
agency under Ronald Reagan, was a Bush family friend until he
decided to support Bob Dole for president in 1988. He recalls an
encounter with George W. Bush in the early summer of 1988, at a
Texas Republican barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Bush had vanguished Dole, the nomination was
wrapped up, and the Bush forces could afford to be magnanimous. But
George W. Bush wasn't. Making a beeline toward Pauken, he delivered
a stinging message.
</P>
<P>
   Paraphrasing what he recalls Bush saying, Pauken says: ``It was
like, `Pauken, you have burned the bridges . . . you have broken
with the family, and you are going to play a price.''' That said,
Bush turned and stalked off, Pauken said.
</P>
<P>
   Temporary pique? The old George W.? Well, perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Pauken says that Bush and his top operatives opposed him
when he ran, successfully, to be Texas Republican Party chairman in
1994, and worked behind the scenes to help his opponents last
spring when he ran, unsuccessfully, for attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets very personal,'' said Pauken. ``He has a very thin
skin and a very short fuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush claims to have doused that fiery temper, though others
wonder if he's simply grown better at banking the ire. Either way,
a presidential campaign will test will try his temperament the way
Texas's good-old-boy politics haven't.
</P>
<P>
   Put it all together and what does it suggest?
</P>
<P>
   Just this: In market terms, what New Hampshire will see this
week is George W. Bush's initial public offering. Unless the
product proves compelling, don't be surprised if his political
stock falls.
</P>
<P>
   (Scot Lehigh is the Globe's Focus writer.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
