<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW DEEP CAN DIVERS GO? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. What are the depth limits for an aqualung, and the old time
canvas and brass-helmet diving suits?
</P>
<P>
   A.A., Medford, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. First, the records. Then a firm word of warning from Dr.
Peter Vann of the Divers Alert Network, an internationally
recognized dive safety organization.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing an aqualung, or SCUBA (Self Contained Underwater
Breathing Apparatus) and breathing regular air, a diver made it to
525 feet. And then he blacked out. When he floated back up to 440
he realized how lucky he was to be alive.
</P>
<P>
   Using SCUBA and breathing a special mix of oxygen, nitrogen and
helium, called trimix, a diver made it 925 feet. Vann says another
diver who tried that, died.
</P>
<P>
   Vann warns that the recommended maximum depth for recreational
divers is 130 feet, whether you're using SCUBA or a helmet and
suit. Beyond that, no matter how you're getting your air, you start
facing trouble, depending on how deep you go AND how long you stay
down.
</P>
<P>
   On the way down, the first problem is nitrogen narcosis. As you
descend, the water pressure pushing in on the air-filled spaces in
your body _ the lungs, sinuses, and ear cavities _ increases. At
100 feet, all that extra water over you pushing down is equivalent
to four times the air pressure at the surface. The rest of your
body is mostly water and doesn't mind the increasing pressure. But
the air-filled spaces do. To compensate, SCUBA gear includes
regulating devices that push enough air from the tanks into your
lungs to match whatever the outside pressure is. The deeper you go,
the greater the pressure of air from your tanks being supplied to
your lungs, provided through the regulator (that big chunky thing
in a SCUBA divers mouth that makes you sound like Darth Vader).
</P>
<P>
   What that means is the deeper you go, the more molecules of
oxygen and nitrogen you're getting per breath. The oxygen is used
up by your body. But nitrogen is inert. It's not consumed by human
metabolism. The extra nitrogen builds up in your blood. But at
higher-than-normal levels nitrogen acts like a narcotic, though
researchers don't know why.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it the martini rule,'' Vann says.
</P>
<P>
   Every fifty feet down you go is like drinking one martini. The
deeper you go, the ``drunker'' you get. Feeling drunk underwater
can make you do stupid, even fatal things. Dive safety books say
nitrogen narcosis starts to get serious around 90-100 feet,
although Vann says there is wide variation among individuals, the
same as varying individual reactions to alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Go a little deeper and oxygen can start to be a problem. Too
much oxygen can cause convulsions and seizures, and death, by
interfering with brain chemistry. Regular air, with it's 21 percent
oxygen content, can be toxic at 218 feet as greater pressures push
more oxygen molecules into your lungs with each breath.
</P>
<P>
   To counter the effects of nitrogen and oxygen, technical divers,
like those who work on drilling rigs, or military divers, use
special gas mixes like trimix, which replaces nitrogen with helium,
or nitrox, which boosts the oxygen and reduces the nitrogen. With
these mixes commercial divers can operate at 1,000 feet. But they
still face the problem all divers face in coming back up.
Decompression sickness, known as the bends
</P>
<P>
   You consume greater and greater amounts of nitrogen the deeper
you go and the longer you stay down. As the nitrogen builds up in
the blood it behaves just like carbon dioxide in a soda bottle.
Under pressure the nitrogen stays dissolved. But swim back up and
it's like popping the cap on the soda bottle. The pressure release
lets the nitrogen turn to bubbles, which can cause not only pain,
but death.
</P>
<P>
   The bends got it's name from the old time hat and suit divers
who built underwater caissons for bridges. They breathed in too
much nitrogen, came up too fast, and walked around bent over from
the excruciating pain of those bubbles, concentrated mostly in
their joints.
</P>
<P>
   Dive charts tell recreational divers breathing regular air how
long they can safely stay down, at various depths, before they have
to do one or more decompression stops on the way back up. Since the
blood is constantly carrying excess nitrogen to the lungs, we're
breathing some of it out with each breath. Decompression stops
allow divers to hover in the water and just by breathing, rid
themselves of the excess nitrogen so it cannot turn into bubbles
when they surface back into regular atmospheric pressure.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write to
How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
