<SLUG> BC-FILM-FESTIVAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROVINCETOWN FINALLY GETS ITS PREMIERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For an event most would believe has a natural home in
Provincetown, Mass, the international film festival took its time
coming to fruition.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, various people and organizations tried
unsuccessfully to mount a film festival in Provincetown. Though
each attempt was thwarted, usually by lack of planning or financial
backing, it never ceased to seem a logical fit _ cutting-edge films
presented in a town renowned as a community for the more creatively
inclined.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any event takes the right synergy, and particularly an event
of this magnitude,'' said P.J. Layng, a Provincetown businesswoman.
``It took a long time, but finally the stars lined up, the right
people got involved, and we had ourselves a film festival.''
</P>
<P>
   The first Provincetown International Film Festival begins
Friday, about two years after Layng, the festival's executive
producer and an avid film fan, got it in her head that she could
succeed where so many others had failed. With Connie White and
Marianne Lampke, the festival's co-producers, Layng garnered the
community's support and energy for the event, which concludes next
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Among the offerings are Gregg Araki's latest trippy outing,
``Splendor''; Rose Troche's ``Bedrooms and Hallways''; ``Run Lola
Run,'' a German thriller that snagged a share of the audience prize
for best foreign film at this year's Sundance Film Festival;
Bernardo Bertolucci's ``Besieged''; ``The Red Violin,'' starring
Samuel L. Jackson; Francisco Manso's ``Testamento''; and ``The
Source,'' an exploration of Beat generation writers William S.
Burroughs, Allen Ginsberg, and Jack Kerouac.
</P>
<P>
   There are also two restored classics: ``A Hard Day's Night,''
celebrating its 35th anniversary as the first Beatles romp, and
Billy Wilder's ``Some Like It Hot,'' starring Jack Lemmon, Tony
Curtis, and Marilyn Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   All films will be shown at the New Art Cinema on Commercial
Street.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the festival honors John Waters with its first
Filmmaker on the Edge award. ``An Evening with John Waters'' is a
celebration of the deliciously tasteless filmmaker who unleashed on
the world the late 300-pound transvestite Divine, star of such
Waters films as ``Pink Flamingos,'' ``Polyester,'' and
``Hairspray.'' There is also a ``director's cut'' showing of
Waters's 1975 film, ``Female Trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Later that night, the latest edition of ``Towniewood Squares,''
styled on television's ``Hollywood Squares,'' will be played at the
Mews restaurant with comedy writer and ``Hollywood Squares''
regular Bruce Vilanch in the center square. Vilanch is also the
subject of the film ``Get Bruce,'' which details his life as one of
Hollywood's best comic writers.
</P>
<P>
   When Layng moved from Boston to Provincetown four years ago, she
wasn't thinking about film festivals. A former health-care
administrator, she wanted to try her hand at the antiques and
retail business and opened two stores _ Roots for the Home and
Garden, and Roots Furniture and Rug Gallery. While the main
in-season months of July and August were good, she found business
slow in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``June is a difficult month to have a business here because
you're competing with graduations and weddings,'' she said.
``You've already hired everyone for the season, and they just sit
there. You've got a big payroll, big rents, big bills, and no
people.''
</P>
<P>
   A draw for June
</P>
<P>
   What Provincetown needed, Layng decided, was a June event to
draw people into town.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more through the years it became clear to me that we
were an arts community, but with no film. And I love film,'' she
said. ``Watching movies is what I do for my fun and relaxation, and
I just felt like it was missing.''
</P>
<P>
   Layng was introduced to White and Lampke, who lease and operate
Cambridge's Brattle Theatre and also founded Boston's International
Festival of Women's Cinema.
</P>
<P>
   ``There had been conversations between people about this sort of
idea for years, and because Marianne has a home down there, every
now and then she would get pulled into the conversations,'' White
said. ``We never believed things would come to fruition, but this
time it did.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the town's sizable lesbian and gay population, most
assume any film festival in Provincetown would be a lesbian and gay
film festival. True, there are a number of gay-themed films in the
festival, such as ``Better Than Chocolate,'' ``Leather Jacket Love
Story,'' and ``Golden Threads.'' But the organizers were quick to
point out that this is not a festival for just one part of the
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to do something for everyone,'' White said. ``If you
try to do something for everyone, then you fail. But we did try to
take an overview of Provincetown. This has been an arts community
for 100 years, it has a gay and lesbian population, and that's all
kind of intrinsic, being out on the edge and taking artistic
chances. So we used that as a starting point, and we're really
pleased with how things went.''
</P>
<P>
   Choosing to forgo a gay and lesbian film festival was ``not an
easy decision,'' but it was the correct one, Layng said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The community was certainly divided, and it basically came
down to what we _ me, Connie, and Marianne _ wanted. I was the most
vocal on insisting that this not be exclusively gay and lesbian,''
she said. ``My personal opinion is it just doesn't matter. What
matters first is that this is a film festival that celebrates
filmmaking on the edge, and celebrates the community as it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``The film festival should reflect the magnificence of
Provincetown, which is its diversity, acceptance of lifestyles, the
arts, the overall beauty of the environment, the Portuguese
community,'' Layng said. ``This is what makes Provincetown
Provincetown. That's why it's so special, and we wanted the film
festival to reflect that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
