<HEADLINE>
OUTRAGE GROWS AMID HIGH-PROFILE CRIMES IN MEXICO CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSANA HAYWARD  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ In two weeks of sensational crimes in Mexico, a
jovial television host was gunned down at high noon, masked pirates
seized a tourist boat in the seas of Cancun and robbers held up a
subway car in a posh Mexico City neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   There also was the incident involving presidential candidate
Vicente Fox, whose chauffeur was robbed and wounded. That prompted
his campaign to ask the federal government for a security detail of
at least 18 guards.
</P>
<P>
   After all, they said, the ruling party presidential contender,
Leopoldo Labastida Ochoa, has more, compliments of President
Ernesto Zedillo's secret service.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Labastida said he couldn't be too careful. Look
what happened in 1996 to presidential front-runner Luis Donaldo
Colosio, assassinated on a campaign swing.
</P>
<P>
   But while the grisly crimes were being committed, restaurants in
this capital burst with patrons and culinary treats, nightclubs
with song and dance and museums with fine art.
</P>
<P>
   Things aren't what they seem in Mexico City, capital of
contrasts, where some 22 million people work, eat and love. Lately,
they argue about the lack of security in the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am scared to go to the bank, scared to take a taxi, scared
to go home at night,'' said a young executive, who was too scared
to give her name.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of violence came to a head June 7, when television
host Francisco ``Paco'' Stanley was killed in a hail of machine-gun
fire at midday outside a popular eatery. Stanley was traveling with
four bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of outraged people clamored for justice and blamed the
tide of violence on Mexico City Mayor Cuauhtemoc Cardenas.
</P>
<P>
   Capturing the irony of the moment, an editorial cartoon in the
newspaper Reforma showed a television anchor carrying a sign: ``No
more violence. Lynch Cardenas.'' The nation's two main television
networks, Televisa and TV Azteca, also demanded action.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are hostages of delinquency,'' Televisa anchor Jacobo
Zabludovsky told the audience in round-the-clock coverage of the
Stanley murder. ``In every place of the city, even in the airport,
people are kidnapped.''
</P>
<P>
   The anchor was referring to a newspaper report that a
businessman had been recently kidnapped for ransom at the crowded
Mexico City airport. The police denied the report.
</P>
<P>
   The frenzy died down when it became evident that Stanley, who
was part of TV Azteca's ``Live Without Drugs'' campaign, had a
penchant for cocaine and had a false government credential that
allowed him to carry guns.
</P>
<P>
   While sensitive about their image abroad, people here are the
first to tell outsiders the perils of their streets: Don't hail a
cab, remember your credit card personal identification numbers,
watch out for carjackers and even kidnappers.
</P>
<P>
   The reality, say some experts, is that crime is down, and it's
not even as bad as it seems, not as bad as other large urban areas,
including New York City, Paris or Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   Experts trace the rise in criminality to the 1994 peso
devaluation that greatly diminished the buying power of Mexicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is delinquency in the capital from 1994 to 1996 grew
immeasurably. It doubled,'' said Rafael Luis Harrell, a
criminologist at the National Autonomous University of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have not had a chance to become accustomed to those
statistics,'' he said. ``While crime is a common factor in every
major urban city, we are not used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Crime, said Ruiz, was once limited mostly to working-class
neighborhoods. Today, it also affects those with the loudest
voices: the rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is affecting the middle-class, the wealthy,'' Ruiz said.
``There is a great hysteria, without a doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz said the same phenomenon existed in other Latin-American
countries at the end of authoritarian dictatorships.
</P>
<P>
   Ruled for most of the century by the Institutional Revolutionary
Party, Mexican society is experiencing flashes of democracy in
elections and in its news media.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could say crime is a product of democracy as a society
opens up,'' Ruiz said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
