<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4567 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIAN-ANTHRAX-HNS &LR;      06-14 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIAN-ANTHRAX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT SAYS EX-SOVIET WEAPONS SITE POSES SERIOUS MENACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Buried bacteria at a former Soviet biological warfare site are
potentially so dangerous that the United States should consider
playing a closer role in the cleanup, researchers say in a new
report.
</P>
<P>
   In the twilight years of the Cold War, in a top-secret operation
on an island in the Aral Sea, Soviet soldiers hurriedly buried one
of history's scariest weapons: killer anthrax bacteria, according
to researchers at the Monterey Institute of International Studies.
The soldiers assumed that the buried bacteria _ having been soaked
in bleach, then entombed underground _ would eventually die off.
</P>
<P>
   The menacing bacteria didn't. Now the institute, based in
Monterey, Calif., is helping figure out how to prevent a potential
environmental cataclysm _ the leakage of anthrax via ground water
into the ecosystem of Kazakhstan and neighboring Uzbekistan, and
perhaps beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Stored inside 66-gallon containers, the bacteria were originally
buried under several feet of sand on the island. But erosion has
reportedly worn away the sand and exposed at least some of the
containers.
</P>
<P>
   And the risk is literally growing with time. Because of poor
irrigation practices in the former Soviet Union, the Aral Sea is
quickly disappearing. As the sea level drops, Vozrozhdeniye Island
expands. In little more than a decade the island might reconnect
with the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anthrax spores can survive in soil for decades, creating an
enduring source of contamination,'' according to an advance copy of
the institute's report.
</P>
<P>
   ``The contamination of Vozrozhdeniye Island presents a growing
threat to the nearby population and the environment because of the
desiccation of the Aral Sea, which has increased human and animal
access to the formerly isolated island.''
</P>
<P>
   The sea is an inland body of salt water located east of the
Caspian Sea in the former Soviet republics of Kazakhstan and
Uzbekistan.
</P>
<P>
   There's a danger of animals and insects crossing a land bridge
and contaminating the Uzbekistan mainland, said Jonathan C. Tucker,
director of the Chemical and Biological Weapons Nonproliferation
Project at the Monterey Institute.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, ``let's not panic,'' said Eric Croddy, a
senior research associate at the Monterey center. ``The whole place
is cordoned off.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet hopes for a cleanup have been stymied by the regional
administrative chaos following the collapse of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, a cleanup ``shouldn't be that big a production,
really,'' Croddy said. But the physical state of the bacteria
remains uncertain because the authorities in the region have
refused permission for Monterey Institute officials to get a close
look. That makes it impossible for them to tell whether the
bacteria exist in a powdery form that could easily be blown around
by the wind or in a sludge or cake-like form that is likely to stay
put, Croddy said.
</P>
<P>
   The institute is a private graduate school for people planning
careers in international fields ranging from business to diplomacy.
The Center for Nonproliferation Studies is a branch of it that
trains people, up to the master's degree level, who plan to enter
the field of arms control.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1989, the institute is funded mainly by organizations
such as the Ford, Rockefeller, MacArthur, W. Alton Jones and
Plowshares foundations. It also gets grants from the U.S.
Department of Energy.
</P>
<P>
   The institute report _ by chemist Gulbarshyn Bozheyeva,
biologist Yerlan Kunakbayev and physicist Dastan Yeleukenov, all of
whom work at the institute's Kazakhstan branch office _ provides
insights not only into the causes of the Vozrozhdeniye Island
crisis but into the history of the Soviet Union's biological
warfare programs.
</P>
<P>
   Soviet troops buried the anthrax on the island in a desperate
attempt to prevent it from being discovered by international arms
control inspectors, the report says.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1992, Russian President Boris Yeltsin ``admitted that
the Soviet Union and then Russia had conducted a top-secret
offensive biological warfare (BW) program in violation of the 1972
Biological and Toxin Weapons Convention (treaty) banning the
development, production, stockpiling, and transfer of these
weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Monterey report says that as early as the 1950s,
Vozrozhdeniye Island was a leading Soviet center for biological
warfare research.
</P>
<P>
   ``The island was apparently chosen for open-air testing of
biological weapons because of its geographical isolation,'' the
report says. The Aral Sea is ``surrounded by large, sparsely
populated deserts and semi-deserts. ... The island's sparse
vegetation, hot, dry climate, and sandy soil that reaches (140
degrees Fahrenheit) in summer all reduced the chances that
pathogenic microorganisms would survive and spread.''
</P>
<P>
   In its heyday, the Vozrozhdeniye Island facility was a sort of
Soviet version of Los Alamos, the top-secret community in the New
Mexico desert where the United States developed the atomic bomb.
Vozrozhdeniye Island had hundreds of employees, even families,
living in a community.
</P>
<P>
   The institute said that biological warfare agents tested on
Vozrozhdeniye Island included anthrax, tularemia, brucellosis,
plague, typhus, Q fever, smallpox, botulinum toxin, and Venezuelan
equine encephalitis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
