<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4568 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-WEATHER-ART-BOS &LR;      06-14 1909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WEATHER-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORECASTING HITS HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Meteorologists are not quite ready to predict the weather in
your own backyard, but they're getting closer.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to ever more powerful computers that can quickly digest
billions of pieces of weather data and turn them into easily
understood graphic images, commercial forecasters are increasingly
able to predict weather conditions in a particular city
neighborhood _ and one day hope to forecast it in an area as small
as a picnic table.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, there appears to be an insatiable consumer
appetite for weather information. Since its 1982 launch, the cable
TV Weather Channel now reaches an audience of up to 1 million
viewers a day.
</P>
<P>
   Weather Web sites, meanwhile, are getting hundreds of millions
of ``hits'' each month, including services with forecasts by zip
codes or predictions tailored to golfers, sailors and private
pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past year, hundreds of thousands of Americans have
purchased weather radios from electronics stores that sound an
alarm when the National Weather Service issues severe storm
warnings for county-sized areas programmed into the receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Radio Shack, which began selling the radios last year for $79,
was swamped at first but this year has finally been able to keep
enough in inventory, said Rick Borinstein, senior vice president
for merchandising with the chain.
</P>
<P>
   The state of Florida has purchased more than 15,000 radios and
handed them out to schools, day-care centers, nursing homes, and
local emergency-management officials. Former service director Joe
Friday has called the system a key part of its goal to have ``a
weather radio in every home, just like a smoke detector, and in all
schools, hospitals, and other public gathering places.''
</P>
<P>
   Demand for the radios has been much higher in the Deep South and
Tornado Alley states like Oklahoma and Kansas than in
Massachusetts, which had 74 severe weather warnings in 1997 and 73
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, Massachusetts has only 10 summer days with
sufficiently violent thunderstorms that merit a severe weather
warning, and a handful of days with flash flood risks.
</P>
<P>
   But Glenn A. Field, who coordinates weather warnings at the
Taunton weather service office, said lives could probably be saved
if more Bay State residents owned the radios. Worcester County, for
example, has seen 36 tornadoes since 1950, and statistically is
well overdue for another one.
</P>
<P>
   Wind gusts over 100 m.p.h. have been recorded in both Worcester
and the Brockton-Whitman area in the last three years. Although
this kind of weather is much less likely to occur in Massachusetts
than in Alabama or Oklahoma, ``I wouldn't want to downplay the
importance of having (a weather radio),'' Field said.
</P>
<P>
   On the commercial side, weather forecasting is becoming a
booming business. Billerica-based Weather Services International
Corp., for example, is rolling out new products for local cable
television franchises that could produce specific forecasts for,
say, Brookline, Cambridge, and Newton, or show the day's predicted
highs in one-degree increments. A Tampa cable system is to begin
broadcasting super-local forecasts this month.
</P>
<P>
   And IBM's ``Deep Thunder'' forecasting system, which grew out of
forecasting innovations for the Atlanta 1996 Olympic Games, has
been improved to the point where _ at least in theory _ it could
generate meaningful forecasts for areas as small as 17 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Clemson University researchers in South Carolina are
perfecting a model to predict maximum hurricane wind speeds by zip
codes. And an Arizona company has during the last five years
completed a system of sensors _ initially developed around the
Space Shuttle launch pad in Florida _ that shows nearly
instantaneously, within a quarter mile, anyplace in the US where
lightning is striking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just starting to realize these capabilities,'' said Jim
Brihan, senior meteorologist and marketing director for Weather
Services International in Billerica. ``You've got to believe that
what we're now doing on a 5-to-10-kilometer scale we're going to be
doing on an even smaller scale in the not too distant future.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest limitation to the development of ever more localized
forecasts is the variable quality of weather data coming in. While
models are constantly being tested against actual weather
conditions and refined, companies generally are reluctant to
publicize scorecards that show how well their systems are working
because forecasting is still a less than precise science.
</P>
<P>
   Most forecasts _ for all of New England or a single town _ use
the basic building blocks of global weather models developed by the
National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration or a similar
European Community forecasting center in England.
</P>
<P>
   Predicting how much rain will fall in each of several coastal
communities two days from now may depend heavily on accurately
measuring cloud cover and moisture over areas far out in the
Atlantic Ocean where storms develop. Much of that information is
derived from satellite observations that have gotten markedly
better in recent years, but are still frustratingly far from
perfect for meteorologists.
</P>
<P>
   A forecast model that aims to predict weather for, say, the area
covered by the Boston phone book will start by ``initializing'' the
model, or loading it with data from areas north, east, south, and
west of the forecast zone that are derived from a government-run
global or continental weather model.
</P>
<P>
   Once the storm is over, say, in Connecticut, where there is
abundant data from radar installations, observation stations, and
airplanes, predicting where it will go in the next several hours
becomes more feasible because there is much more accurate baseline
data than can be derived from out at sea.
</P>
<P>
   IBM's Deep Thunder system, for example, ``works well when you
have a lot of meteorological observation stations,'' says Zaphiris
Christidis, an IBM researcher who helped develop it. ``If the
infrastructure is not good to support it, then it's not going to
work as well, and you are going to have `garbage in, garbage out.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Deep Thunder _ the name is a play on ``Deep Blue,'' the IBM
chess-playing computer that analyzes millions of moves each second
_ got its start with the 1996 Olympics in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   IBM and Weather Service officials took a modeling system
developed at Colorado State University and plugged it into an
ultrapowerful supercomputer with advanced three-dimensional
visualization systems. The system was capable of producing 6- to
24-hour forecasts in areas as small as 1.5 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   In an early test during the August 1995 Olympic Sports Festival,
IBM researchers scored a coup that reflected at least as much good
science as good luck: At 5 p.m. one  &UR; afternoon &LR; , they warned that
violent storms were going to sweep through the Aquatic Center at
the Georgia Institute of Technology at 5:45 p.m. Venue managers
quickly evacuated the stands and the thunderstorms roared through
at 5:46 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The following year, the system gave managers 32 minutes warning
before a windy storm blew down a tent at the track and field
trials. And it also gave them confidence that rain would hold off
long enough to go ahead with the closing ceremonies at the new
Olympic Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   To feed the forecasts, the Weather Service upgraded nearly 100
observation stations to report data four times an hour instead of
once, and added more ocean buoys and weather balloons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The accuracy of environmental forecast models is reaching
levels undreamed of 10 years ago,'' said D. James Baker,
administrator of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration, which last October signed a $35.6 million,
four-year contract with IBM for a Deep Thunder system at its
Maryland prediction center.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Deep Thunder, here are some other commercial efforts
underway:
</P>
<P>
   _ A Weather Services International product called StormCast can
merge weather information with street-level maps to show the
location of violent weather cells in a given neighborhood or the
difference in current rain intensity in downtown Boston compared to
Hyde Park.
</P>
<P>
   As storms sweep over a region, the system can show where within
a pie-shaped area a storm cell might pass in the next 30 minutes,
with an up-to-the-minute prediction for different cities _ a big
help if you are trying to decide, for example, when to leave the
office to go buy a sandwich, for example.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state of the art is not perfect yet, but at least it gives
us a rough order of magnitude when it might affect you,'' Brihan
said. Several big electric utilities use a similar system to
determine where to dispatch repair crews during major storms.
</P>
<P>
   In another application called PrecisionCast, the system will
produce maps showing the predicted daily highs to the degree in a
zone extending from, say, Ipswich to Boxford _ a big leap over the
traditional ``highs in the upper 80s, cooler at the coast'' summer
forecast usually heard on local TV and radio forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   _ This month, Time Warner Cable will be rolling out
24-hour-a-day forecasts specific to local communities on its Tampa,
Fla., cable systems, not just a Central Florida overview. Time
Warner news vice president Kirk Varner calls it ``the next
generation of local weather coverage on television.''
</P>
<P>
   _ AccuWeather, through its corporate Web site, offers a forecast
for every zip code in the country, which will include slight
differences in projected highs and lows in, for example, Yarmouth
versus Wareham versus New Bedford.
</P>
<P>
   A rival site developed by Weather Services International called
Intellicast.com offers forecasts tailored for golfers, sailors,
skiers, and even kite flyers, as well as local forecasts for 150 US
cities, drawing 2 million visitors a month. Intellicast is also
being marketed to cable systems.
</P>
<P>
   _ Clemson University researchers are developing a model they
hope to unveil next year that will predict maximum hurricane wind
speeds in each of several zip codes during storms.
</P>
<P>
   A lead researcher on the project, associate professor of civil
engineering David Rosowsky, said his team hopes to produce a model
that would incorporate insurance industry data to produce estimates
of the likely dollar damage of a coming storm in a given zip code.
</P>
<P>
   Field said given the vagaries of the weather, he would be
extremely uncomfortable for the foreseeable future using a model
that attempted to predict the exact path of a violent storm rather
than just a likely ``swath'' it might hit.
</P>
<P>
   But given the relentless march of technology, meteorologists are
confident they will continually get closer to being able to make
more precise and reliable _ and ever more local _ forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all has to do with computer power,'' said Lans P. Rofthusz,
the government meteorologist who headed the Olympic forecasting
office. ``The more computer power you get, the more specificity you
can get in your computer model.''
</P>
<P>
   IBM's Jeff Gluck said, ``The dream is to be able to say what's
the weather going to be like in my back yard at 3 o'clock, because
that's when we're going to have our barbecue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
