<HEADER>
A4569 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-14 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOL PLACES FOR THE HOT SUMMER IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When the weather finally turns hot, or at least
warm, California has sensational houseboating, boat-in camping,
rafting, water skiing and water's-edge camps that are beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   Here are my picks for the best of the best in each prominent
category at lakes, rivers and the coast:
</P>
<P>
   RAFTING
</P>
<P>
   Main Stem Tuolumne River: When it comes to rafting, ``The T'' is
simply the best. Many rafters are baptized by the cool, clear,
pounding waters of the Tuolumne River. Here you'll find one of
California's most thrilling rapids, Pinball, and one of the most
terrorizing, Clavey Falls. The 18-mile run, from Meral Pool
downstream to Ward's Ferry, is rated Class IV-plus. Anybody who
runs it will have experienced the true essence of exhilaration.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Echo, 800-652-3246; California Outdoors Rafting Hot
line, 800-552-3625.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSEBOATING
</P>
<P>
   Shasta Lake: This is the boating capital of the West. Giant
Shasta Lake has 365 miles of shoreline and 22 species of sport
fish. From a houseboat, it takes about five or six days to see the
whole thing. With all the houseboaters on the water, it can seem
like one big party of happy people. The water skiing and swimming
are excellent, with surface waters ranging 75 to 80 degrees. The
fishing now is also excellent for salmon, trout and bass.
Meanwhile, if you want peace and quiet, or a parking spot for the
night, just head into one of the coves.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Holiday Harbor, 530-238-2383; Shasta Cascade,
800-474-2782.
</P>
<P>
   BOAT-IN CAMPING
</P>
<P>
   Bullards Bar Reservoir: This is a big, beautiful lake set at
2,000 feet in the Sierra foothills, and get this: Not only are
there two boat-in campgrounds at Bullards Bar, but boaters are
allowed to create their own primitive campsites anywhere along the
lakeshore (a chemical toilet is required). The lake also has great
fishing for small but tasty kokanee salmon. When compared with the
other reservoirs in the Central Valley foothills, Bullards Bar
Reservoir stands out like a silver dollar in a field of pennies.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Emerald Cove Resort, 530-692-3200.
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY DESTINATIONS
</P>
<P>
   Edison Lake: Here is one of the great summer family camping
destinations in California. Edison Lake is set at an elevation of
7,650 feet in the central Sierra east of Fresno, and it has
everything you could ask for: Four lakeside camps, a resort, a boat
launch, boat rentals, horseback riding rentals, a nearby trail head
to the Pacific Crest Trail, and yes, good fishing. A 15-mph speed
limit keeps the water quiet, and there's twice-daily ferry service
across the lake to the trail head at the head of the lake. The lake
is fed by Mono Creek, a cold, pure, and pristine trout stream, with
a good trail alongside for access.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Vermillion Valley Resort, 559-855-6558; Pine Ridge
Ranger District, 559-855-5375.
</P>
<P>
   WATER-SKIING
</P>
<P>
   San Joaquin Delta: Yeah, it gets insane here, and that's exactly
why so many people like the San Joaquin Delta. There are boats,
boats, boats everywhere, not to mention boat owners who are on
weekend vacations trying to escape the reality of their
Monday-to-Friday lives. And the waterskiing? You've never seen so
many boats ripping up and down, with happy (and somewhat insane)
folks aboard and bright white wakes trailing behind. The best areas
here are out of Bethel Island, with access to the Delta's quietest
waters, and also at Brannan Island State Recreation Area, where
there are docks and campsites available.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Brannan Island State Recreation Area, 916-777-6671;
Bethel Harbor, 925-684-2141; Discovery Bay, Byron, 925-634-5928.
</P>
<P>
   SCENIC DESTINATION
</P>
<P>
   Emerald Bay, Lake Tahoe: One of the premier outdoor experiences
in the world is boating in Emerald Bay, which brings you right into
the heart of Tahoe's incomparable scenic beauty. No matter where
you go in the bay, you'll be floating on clear, cobalt blue waters
and surrounded by a mountain rim that is often topped with bright
white snow. The sight is always remarkable, often breathtaking.
There are 20 boat-in campsites to make it work. Precise advance
planning with reservations are a must; expect tons of people in
summer, of course, and competition for the best spots.
</P>
<P>
   Information: 530-541-3030 or 530-525-7277; reservations at
800-444-7275.
</P>
<P>
   BEST ISLAND
</P>
<P>
   Santa Rosa Island: This is my favorite of the Channel Islands.
Because the boat ride to Santa Rosa takes longer than the one to
Santa Cruz Island, this place is often overlooked by visitors who
are on a one-day, round-trip adventure, making it extra special.
The ``Painted Caves'' of Santa Rosa Island make this a world-class
destination for kayakers, as well as a great spot for hiking and
exploring. A great trip, well worth the effort.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Island Packers, 805-642-7688; Ventura Visitors
Bureau, 800-333-2989.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
