<HEADLINE>
`LUGHNASA' ACTING SUPERB; `JANE DOE' FOR ALLY FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES: ``Dancing at Lughnasa'' _ Pat O'Connor's
respectful adaptation of Brian Friel's play concerning five Irish
sisters in the '30s features a crafty performance by Meryl Streep.
It's a bit too sentimental, but the acting is superb, and O'Connor
wisely cut the play's length down to a manageable size.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little Voice'' _ Michael Caine deserved the
best-supporting-actor Oscar for his portrayal of an ambitious and
shady yet touching theatrical agent. Jane Horrocks shows off her
gift for vocal mimicry in the title role, as the reclusive girl who
may have a career reproducing the sounds from the records who have
been her only friends. But it's worth the price of the rental to
hear Caine's rendition of Roy Orbison's ``It's Over.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jane Doe'' _ ``Ally McBeal'' fans might be curious to see
Calista Flockhart in this downbeat tale of drug addiction.
Self-destructive Jane (Flockhart) starts going down from the
beginning, so there are no surprises. A claustrophobic rendering,
with much of the dialogue boring and tedious.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``PRIVATE RYAN'' UPDATE: Video retailers have ordered more than
1.2 million copies of Steven Spielberg's World War II epic,
``Saving Private Ryan.'' The award-winning film, starring Tom
Hanks, generated nearly $9 million in rentals over Memorial Day
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW ON DVD: Check out ``Aliens Special Edition,'' which looks
great in a high-definition remaster from director James Cameron. It
lacks commentary from the director, but it does include an
interview with Cameron conducted when the film was first released,
in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMING ATTRACTIONS: June 22: ``Waking Ned Devine,'' ``Patch
Adams,'' ``A Simple Plan,'' ``Rushmore,'' ``Hurlyburly,'' ``Wishful
Thinking,'' ``Jawbreakers,'' ``Sweethearts,'' ``The Life of
Birds,'' ``Storm of the Century.'' June 29: ``The Thin Red Line,''
``Still Crazy,'' ``Varsity Blues,'' ``Lansky.'' July 6:
``Affliction,'' ``The King and I'' (animated), ``Kidnapped in
Paradise,'' ``Siberian Lady MacBeth,'' ``The Red and the White.''
July 13: ``Life Is Beautiful,'' ``A Civil Action,'' ``She's All
That.'' July 20: ``Down in the Delta,'' ``Virus,'' ``Telling You,''
``Mercenary 2: Thick and Thin.'' July 27: ``October Sky,'' ``Reach
the Rock.''
</P>
</TEXT>
