<HEADLINE>
REGIONAL PUBLIC RADIO NETWORK TO LAUNCH NATIONAL WEB SITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JO-ANN JOHNSTON  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ This summer, WAMC Northeast Public Radio will
launch a new national radio station that broadcasts solely over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The new venture, called ThePublicRadioStation.com., is intended
to help the network keep listeners as new technology threatens to
further fragment the radio audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people will be getting their radio through their
computer,'' said Alan S. Chartock, WAMC executive director. That's
increasingly possible as audio speakers are routinely sold with
computer systems. Motorists with cellular phone may even listen to
Internet radio broadcasts using their cell phone as a receiver in
the future, Chartock said.
</P>
<P>
   ThePublicRadioStation.com will ensure that WAMC has an audience
among future listeners who may abandon current radio technology or
want to supplement it, and who may live outside WAMC's broadcast
signal, Chartock said.
</P>
<P>
   WAMC, like many other radio broadcasters, already operates its
own site on the World Wide Web that allows listeners to tap into
some of the audio content of the station through personal computers
equipped with speakers. But not many radio broadcasters have yet
started an operation whose broadcasts are made solely over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're right at the beginning of this technology,'' said David
Galletly, WAMC assistant executive director. However, National
Public Radio, which provides WAMC with national news coverage and
programming, also plans to launch an on-line network. And in the
Boston market, some commercial radio stations have added
Internet-based broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   WAMC Northeast Public Radio, which is based in Albany, is a
regional network that serves parts of Connecticut, Massachusetts,
New Hampshire, New Jersey, New York, Pennsylvania and Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   ThePublicRadioStation.com will have some content that differs
from what is broadcast on WAMC, Chartock said. Some programs
produced here that cover topics of national interest, such as an
education show, ``To The Best of Our Knowledge,'' will be broadcast
over both WAMC and ThePublicRadioStation.com. But
ThePublicRadioStation.com will also offer fare including
English-language coverage of world news events from Radio
Netherlands, and probably other broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the Internet station can be a broadcast outlet for the
many radio producers nationally who are seeking forums for their
independent programs and documentaries, Chartock said.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, WAMC will use its traditional radio broadcasts to the
regional audience to publicize the launch of the Internet station,
Chartock said. He acknowledged it will be a promotional challenge
to get the Internet station noticed nationally, but would not
divulge the strategies he intends to pursue. No specific launch
date has yet been revealed.
</P>
<P>
   ThePublicRadioStation.com will be able to accept advertising
banners on the Internet page the audience will actually see,
Chartock said. However, the Internet radio station won't start
making a lot of money for WAMC soon, Chartock said.
</P>
<P>
   However, he added: ``The name of the game is to get there
first.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS. &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt the Internet is a compelling communication
medium, said Jack Kelly, president of Albany Broadcasting, whose
properties include WROW in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's not even clear to all commercial stations how they
can successfully expand their advertising revenue base by having an
Internet-only station, Kelly said. The consumer market would be
geographically scattered, and that can make it hard to woo any
particular advertiser.
</P>
<P>
   So WROW, like many other stations, has confined its Internet
presence to audio broadcasts from its Web page, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all want to get someplace, we just don't know where we're
going,'' Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is technical. The modems most people have now
don't allow for high quality sound of Internet broadcasts,
particularly on portable devices such as laptop computers, said
Rick Miller, a senior Internet analyst with the Boston-area market
research service Cahners In-Stat Group. For that reason,
traditional radio will be around for a long time, Miller said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
