<HEADER>
A4572 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-TARZAN-BOS &LR;      06-14 1301
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-TARZAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S THE SAME OLD LOINCLOTH ON A NEW TARZAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It seems he has graced the screen forever _ swinging
through the trees, fighting leopards and crocodiles, and emitting a
scream to make the elephants stampede. Raised by apes, and
believing he is one them, despite his hairless skin and loincloth,
Tarzan is one of the most indelible images on film.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1918, just six years after Edgar Rice Burroughs sold his
first version of the story, there have been more than 40 movies
based on the character, from the silent ``Tarzan of the Apes'' to
last year's ``Tarzan and the Lost City'' (which might have worked
better with no dialogue). But ``Tarzan,'' which opens Friday, marks
the first time the oft-told tale has been brought to feature-length
animated life. It was something Burroughs always wanted; he
expressed his desires in a 1936 letter to his son. Any animated
film of his most famous creation, Burroughs wrote, would have to
``approximate Disney excellence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Luckily we didn't get that letter until a few months ago, when
the film was almost finished,'' joked Chris Buck, the film's
codirector. ``I'm pretty confident this film will do more than
approximate Disney excellence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tarzan'' is a Disney film, the studio's latest traditionally
animated movie. With a soundtrack by Phil Collins, it features the
voice talents of Tony Goldwyn as Tarzan,TARZAN, Page N4 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Minnie Driver as Jane, and Glenn Close, Rosie O'Donnell, Nigel
Hawthorne, Brian Blessed, Lance Henriksen, and Wayne Knight.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the film, Disney's big entry in the summer movie
sweepstakes, wasn't something Buck or codirector Kevin Lima were
originally interested in pursuing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was first approached with the material, I thought, `I
don't want to make this _ I don't want to do a Tarzan film,' ''
said Buck, during an interview in a hotel smack-dab in an urban
jungle otherwise known as midtown Manhattan. ``I had Johnny
Weissmuller so stuck in my mind. But when we went back to the book
and found there was a wealth of material for this to be done in
animation, we wondered why anyone hadn't done this before.''
</P>
<P>
   Burroughs himself tried and failed in the 1930s, the height of
cinema's Tarzan fever. The first film, the 1918 ``Tarzan of the
Apes'' (starring Elmo Lincoln) was fairly faithful to Burroughs's
book, but it wasn't until 1932's ``Tarzan, the Ape Man,'' starring
former Olympic swimming champ Weissmuller, that the story really
began to swing. It took extraordinary liberties with Burroughs's
novel, but it was a welcome, entertaining respite from the doldrums
of Depression-era America. Weissmuller's semiliterate, clean-cut,
well-sculpted man of the wild became an instant icon, spawning
several sequels including ``Tarzan and His Mate'' (1934), which
introduced Maureen O'Sullivan's Jane; ``Tarzan Finds His Son,'' in
which Tarzan and Jane complete a jungle adoption of an abandoned
child _ named Boy _ played by too-cute Johnny Sheffield; and
``Tarzan's New York Adventure,'' which found Tarzan trying to
negotiate indoor plumbing and rush-hour traffic while searching for
his kidnapped son.
</P>
<P>
   The enterprise proved so successful _ it's second only to
Dracula as filmdom's favorite suject _ that other actors such as
Buster Crabbe, Lex Barker, and Jock Mahoney donned the loincloth.
Even ``George of the Jungle'' is very loosely based on Tarzan.
Other entries include 1984's deadly serious but enjoyable
``Greystoke: The Legend of Tarzan, Lord of the Apes'' and 1981's
laughable, soft-porn ``Tarzan, the Ape Man,'' memorable only for
its obsession with what Tarzan and Jane really did in the jungle
all those years.
</P>
<P>
   In most, the back story was the same. Tarzan was raised by apes
after his shipwrecked parents became a blue-plate special for a
leopard. But what all these films could never do was portray Tarzan
as Burroughs truly imagined him. Wrote the author of his hero: ``He
could spring 20 feet across space at the dizzying height of the
forest top, and grab with unerring precision and without apparent
jar, a limb waving wildly in the path of an approaching tornado.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how much Olympic glory and athletic prowess
Weissmuller and the other Tinseltown Tarzans possessed, there
simply weren't _ and aren't _ any actors who dare risk such
superhuman feats. But as anyone who's ever watched a ``Road
Runner'' cartoon can tell you, animated flesh and bones can do
absolutely anything.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's Tarzan skids down a tree limb like a rollerblader
riding the rails of a street course. Watching his acrobatic turns
and twists is like watching a skateboarder pop 540s in the
half-pipe. He's skateboard master Tony Hawk in a lioncloth, with a
physique that will have South End boys doubling their reps at the
gym.
</P>
<P>
   ``We patterned him after an extreme athlete,'' Lima said. ``He's
a guy who had to survive to live in this jungle. He grew up with
the gorillas, but he also mimics other animals. So we thought of an
extreme athlete and his psyche, what's he all about. No live actor
can do what our guy can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief animator Glen Keane styled the character's movement on his
own son's skateboarding exploits.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Glen, the inspiration for Tarzan was there in his house,''
Lima said. ``Those movements would make it a little different, and
give it that edge to make it speak to a contemporary audience. This
will be an introduction to a whole new generation of kids. We
didn't want it to take over _ we didn't want Tarzan to talk like a
surf dude. But we thought the living-on-the-edge physicality and
mentality could really pay off.''
</P>
<P>
   With an animated feature, Buck and Lima found they could more
fully explore Tarzan's ability to talk with his animal friends _
and what's a Disney film without wisecracking creatures?
</P>
<P>
   ``He can actually talk to the animals,'' said Lima, ``and they
can talk back, so we can have a sense of who Tarzan is as a person
and what it was like to grow up in the jungle with these
creatures.''
</P>
<P>
   Tarzan's best pal is Terk, a Mohawk-coiffed jokey gorilla who
looks like (and we mean this in the nicest possible way) the woman
who supplies his voice, Rosie O'Donnell. Many of the characters,
especially Driver's Jane and Hawthorne's Professor Porter, bear
more than a passing resemblance to those who lend them their
voices.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a coincidence. The characters are drawn after the voice
talent signs on, Lima said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What tends to happen is we cast the actors as we're doing
exploratory drawing, so we already have an idea of where we want to
go with the character,'' he said. ``We have a tendency at times to
pull facial expressions or attitudes into the character. Rosie
looks like Terk because we used her mouth, and the way she uses her
mouth as an actress is very specific. We also videotaped the vocal
recording sessions so the animator gets a copy of what the voice
talents did.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there was one particular aspect of Tarzan that Lima and
Buck refused to mess with _ that loincloth. No matter how skimpy,
that loincloth has always seemed out of place since Tarzan believes
he's an ape, and none of the other apes are so modest about their
nudity. (Of course, this being a family film, no one wanted to give
the notion of Tarzan swinging through the jungle a whole new
interpretation.) But Buck insisted that keeping Tarzan's
tried-and-true fashion sense intact was necessary for other
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the pop icons we associate with the character, and
I think we wanted to hold onto certain things, like the yell and
the stampede of elephants,'' he said. ``These were things we wanted
to see, and we felt an audience would want to see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
