<HEADLINE>
IN LOVE WITH OUR GARDENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE BARNES  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Not tonight, honey, I want to plant a shrub.'' That line of
dialogue is suggested by a survey of homeowners conducted for Home
&AMP; Garden Television. Among the results:
</P>
<P>
   _ For ``fun and enjoyment,'' more male homeowners prefer working
in the yard (52 percent) to having sex (47 percent).
</P>
<P>
   _ More than a quarter of all homeowners (27 percent) find
gardening a way to relax, about the same percentage as cited
sports, exercise, eating and drinking as their preferred methods of
relaxation. People who call themselves gardeners would rather
garden (42 percent) than socialize (40 percent), eat in a
restaurant (37 percent) or go for a drive (34 percent).
</P>
<P>
   _ Female home enthusiasts would rather organize or decorate
their home (42 percent) than go to the movies (39 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   LONG, BROAD VIEW: The Bushnell company, maker of sport optics,
has introduced a binocular line called Xtra-Wide, aimed especially
at baseball fans. It promises a field-of-view three times as wide
as conventional binoculars and allows stadium spectators to see
more of the game magnified.
</P>
<P>
   Bushnell's research turned up the common complaint that fans
were frustrated by being unable to follow more of the action
through their binoculars and instead were using the magnification
to focus on a specific play or player. The Xtra-Wide series comes
in three powers of magnification: 4X (four times closer than the
naked eye, with a 900-foot-wide field of view at 1,000 yards), 7X
(700 feet wide) and 10X (500 feet wide).
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM WATCH: This will be worth a bundle in 30 years, we
think, plus the hit of your millennial-eve party on Dec. 31: a neon
sign that alternately blinks ``1999'' in red and ``2000'' in blue
($169.50). It comes from a company called Idea Express, which is
marketing only millennium-related products. (What will they do next
year, we wonder?)
</P>
<P>
   Among the many other items are a candle shaped like Earth and
girdled by an equatorial band with ``2000'' on it ($12.49), candles
inside champagne glasses ($8.95), wristwatches ($24.95), a bear
that chirps ``Happy Millennium'' when squeezed and wears a hat with
the same sentiment (pictured; $10.95), and T-shirts emblazoned with
messages such as ``Survivor of World's Largest Mass Hangover'' and
``Same (Excrement), Different Millennium'' ($13.95).
</P>
<P>
   Speculator alert: Significant discounts if ordered in bulk.
Order by faxing 818-385-0909 or visiting
http://www.idea-express.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
