<HEADER>
A4606 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-14 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROLLING THE FUZZY DICE FOR THE 50TH 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For nearly two years we argued (and argued)
about where the Lake Ladies should meet to commemorate our
collective 50th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   It had to be something out of the ordinary: Four of us have
known each other since junior high school; all six of us go back
more than 20 years, and none of us will turn 50 more than once.
</P>
<P>
   I, in San Francisco, wanted an exotic destination that required
a passport. Barbara, in West Lafayette, Ind., wanted a beach to
walk on. Patty, in St. Louis, said she couldn't go any place where
people would be begging for money on the street.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn, in Denver, was drawn to Puerto Vallarta, where she
rents a house each spring and choreographs her own fiesta caliente.
Helen, in Grand Rapids, Mich., wanted something ``resort-y,''
possibly a cruise. Joyce, in Phoenix, asked: How about the Grand
Canyon?
</P>
<P>
   Just when it looked as if we'd ax-murder one another, Joyce
said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't we go to Vegas?''
</P>
<P>
   We call ourselves the ``Lake Ladies'' because, every summer for
the past 20, we have gathered for a week in an A-frame wood cabin
on tiny Rocky Fork Lake in central Indiana. When we were kids,
learning to waterski and lie to our parents, Marilyn's mom and dad
owned the cabin. Now we own it.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, we have collected dozens of ``team photos'' and
tons of Lake Ladies gear, from sweatpants to tank tops to fanny
packs. We've also collected about a million memories, transformed
our teen-age anecdotes into legends and amassed a series of
hilarious (to us) home videos. (``Helen and Marilyn Install the New
Toilet'' is one of my favorites.)
</P>
<P>
   But to say that the Lake Ladies move and think as a seamless
unit is like saying the Jackson Five had an idyllic childhood. At
one particularly low point during the 50th birthday negotiations,
Helen suggested we forget it and start planning our 60th.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky for us, Bugsy Siegel had a crazy dream.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn and Joyce had visited Las Vegas enough to know their way
around, but the rest of us were Vegas virgins. When we arrived at
the teeming, slot machine-encrusted McCarran International Airport,
the temperature was 58 degrees and it was pouring rain.
</P>
<P>
   As we would soon learn, in Las Vegas it matters not if Mom
Nature is in a bad mood. Real life (such as it is) goes on indoors.
One's environment _ or global hemisphere _ can be altered by
walking across a street or hopping an inter-casino tram.
</P>
<P>
   Joyce, being a Macintosh genius, made each of us a replica of a
U.S. passport, navy blue with gold lettering. But ours says:
``Passport: Lake Ladies World Tour '99,'' and has our official logo
on it.
</P>
<P>
   To make Barbara's wish come true, we chose the $950 million,
43-story Mandalay Bay Resort and Casino as our home base.
</P>
<P>
   They have a real sand beach that _ when things are properly
working _ gets kissed by a 6-foot surf from an 11-acre freshwater
``bay.''
</P>
<P>
   But we loved the live birds in the lobby, the water-spouting
faux elephant heads all over the grounds and the aromatic bath
salts for the minispas in each room.
</P>
<P>
   Despite our, ahem, diverse interests, Vegas delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Following the designated destinations in Joyce's passports, we
clomped from Egypt (the Luxor) to Camelot (the Excalibur) to Lake
Como (the Bellagio) and passed Paris, Venice and Treasure Island
along the way.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, we even time-traveled back to our own teens:
Tom Jones at the MGM Grand.
</P>
<P>
   Although we threatened every day, we never made it onto the
roller coaster at New York, New York. Patty and Helen tied for
first prize in our Vegas memorabilia scavenger hunt and received
bags full of chotzkhe _ like fur dice and painted shot glasses _
for their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn groused about losing money every place she gambled, but
recouped some of her deficit at the airport while she waited for a
7 a.m. flight home.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara copped the ``best over-heard'' when a man next to her in
some casino snarled into a cellphone: ``I said I need you to send
me $77,000 and I need it NOW.''
</P>
<P>
   On our last full day, we piled into Joyce's minivan and drove to
Hoover Dam for a two-hour ``hard-hat'' tour. I had joked that we
ought to see at least one thing that was older than we were. But
that gorgeous concrete monument to human vision and American
ingenuity is a rarity that deserves the term ``awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   By Monday night, all Lake Ladies were back in their homes in six
states. The world tour was over, the collective 50th marked.
</P>
<P>
   Every time I imagine planning our 60th, I get a headache. Then I
remember: Macao, Montana or Mars, we'll be together. That's the
only thing that ever matters.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her e-mail address is
salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
