<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, June 15:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 3 pages of stories on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Pristina) _ Ledeall: More mass graves are found;
another German journalist is killed; another 100 Russians reported
ready to move in from Bosnia; U.S. Marines enter the province. By
Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Washington) _ President Clinton talks to Boris
Yeltsin on the status of Russian troops in Kosovo and other
matters. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (Berlin) _ German officials confirm reports that a
Swedish-born financier, Peter Castenfelt, was used by Russian and
European Union officials as a secret envoy to the Yugoslav
president, Slobodan Milosevic. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-EUROPE (Berlin) _ The Kosovo war has brought radical
changes to the European continent, thrusting Germany into a leading
military role not seen since 1945, galvanizing attempts to forge a
common European defense policy, and altering Europe's relationship
with the United States. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PRIZREN (Prizren, Kosovo) _ Tension and color as Serb
forces pull out of the German sector of Kosovo. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIA (Kukes, Albania) _ Developments at the border:
hundreds of refugees try to cross border back into Kosovo, sneaking
through; NATO forces had closed the border for security reasons. By
Elisabeth Bumiller. &UR; (BU) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GERMANS (Berlin) _ Reaction to the deaths of three German
journalists. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-NUKE (Washington) _ The Foreign Intelligence Advisory
Board issues a report on nuclear espionage. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DISSENT (Beijing) _ Top government officials meet with the
leaders of a Buddhist sect _ the one that held the recent silent
demonstration in Beijing _ to deny rumors they are dealing with
U.S. to send sect leader back there. Officials say members can
practice their exercises, but warned against spreading rumors or
inciting disturbances.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-POLITICS (Cape Town) _ South Africa's second freely
elected National Assembly was sworn in on Monday, and chose the
African National Congress's leader, Thabo Mbeki, as the country's
next president. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-EUROPE (London) _ The turnout was small, but the Labor
Party did very poorly in European Parliament elections here. By
Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   POLAND-POPE (Dateline to kum, Poland) _ Pope John Paul II
changes his plans, and will go to Armenia at end of his Polish trip
to visit a dying orthodox patriarch. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   BELGIUM-POLITICS (Brussels) _ The Belgian prime minister,
Jean-Luc Dehaene, resigned on Monday after voters swept away his
coalition government, heavily criticized for its handling of a
dioxin scare that cleared poultry, beef, eggs and butter from food
stores and frightened countries around the world into halting food
imports from Europe. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SMALLPOX (Undated) _ Until modern medicine banished it,
smallpox was once the world's most remorseless killer. Now, as
health and military officials fear the ancient scourge could
return, scientists have renewed interest in research and questions
regarding the virus and the aging vaccine stocks. What makes the
virus so deadly? How well do old vaccinations work? What about new
drugs and vaccines? How likely is a smallpox attack? By William J.
Broad with reporting by Lawrence K. Altman and Judith Miller. (3600
words; an abridged version of about half this length will also
move.)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   For other science stories, see the separate Science Times
budget.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-GAMBLING (Washington) _ A federal law banning casino ads
on TV is unanimously ruled unconstitutional by the Supreme Court.
This decision is in keeping with the high court's increasingly
protective attitude toward commercial speech. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-RDP (Washington) _ A roundup of other Supreme Court
action: The justices take a case that challenges government
spending on computers and other equipment in religious schools;
other cases. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   CLEAN-AIR (Washington) _ The Environmental Protection Agency
announces a strategy to side-step recent unfavorable court
decisions and allow New York and the New England states to continue
demanding national action for cleaner air. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NH-BUSH (Derry, N.H.) _ George W. Bush, the Texas governor,
campaigns for president in New Hampshire. By Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   QWEST-USWEST (Undated) _ Developments in the takeover battle
between Qwest and Global Crossing to acquire US West and Frontier,
focusing on Qwest and its objectives. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   WALMART-ASDA (London) _ Wal-Mart Stores Inc., the biggest U.S.
retailer, is buying Asda Group PLC, one of Britain's leading
supermarket chains, for about $10.7 billion. In backing the
Wal-Mart deal, the board of the British chain reneged on a
previously approved merger with Kingfisher PLC. It is the first
deal in Britain for Wal-Mart, which moved into Europe in 1997. By
Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   GREENSPAN (Washington) _ The chairman of the Federal Reserve,
Alan Greenpan, discusses technology and productivity before the
Joint Economic Committee, but gives no clear indication about
whether the Fed will raise rates later this month _ a signal that
the markets are convinced will come on Thursday when he testifies
again, on monetary policy, before the same committee. By Richard W.
Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At midday, the industrial average was up 85
points, or 0.8 percent, and the Nasdaq index was down 12 points, or
0.4 percent. Elsewhere, prices slipped 0.1 percent in Tokyo and
edged ahead a 0.1 percent in Hong Kong. They fell 0.1 percent in
Frankfurt, dropped 0.8 percent in London, rose 1.2 percent in
Brazil and dropped 0.5 percent in Mexico. On the American debt
market, the long bond was up 21/32 point, with the yield at 6.10
percent. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ The Microsoft antitrust trial
continues. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-AIR-SHOW (Paris) _ The Outlook for Boeing's 100-seat
jetliner at Paris air show. By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Lewis' ``Abroad at Home'' and Thomas L. Friedman's
``Foreign Affairs.''
</P>
