<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT'S TRIUMPH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON &UR;  &LR; _ Of Slobodan Milosevic's endgame canards, none is
sicker than his boast that his beaten armed forces never gave up
Kosovo, and never will give up Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The boast is understandable in the context of this murderous
loser's effort to stay in power. But its absurdity suggests an
awareness of the domestic consequences possibly in store for him
should the citizens of his shrinking ``country'' come to understand
the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Hard to see how they can be shielded from it, given what is
about to unfold. The NATO victors have yet to discuss Kosovo's
future in detail, mostly because Russia's large contribution to the
diplomatic side of the conflict merits a decent respect for its
concerns, but NATO's planning envisages a future where any notion
of Yugoslav ``sovereignty'' on paper will have no meaning on the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, the fact that sovereignty should not be permitted
is a major consequence of the end of the fourth conflict Milosevic
has started within what used to be a functional Yugoslav federation
of six republics plus the then-autonomous province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   For this consequence, the world has Madeleine Albright to thank.
Unlike her counterparts and foreign policy establishments
throughout the West still mired in Cold War old thinking, she has
spent years thinking about the conflict between self-determination
of peoples and the sovereignty of states.
</P>
<P>
   I remember her euphoria in 1989 as European communism began to
shatter, especially as the Velvet Revolution of her friend, Vaclav
Havel, succeeded in her native Czechoslovakia; so was her concern
as Czechoslovakia split in two. Then the Soviet Union went through
the demise that spawned more than a dozen new nations. And, as the
1992 presidential campaign was still taking shape, she was positive
that the pivotal test would come as mass murder in the name of
virulent nationalism began under the guidance of Milosevic in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Even before becoming UN ambassador, Albright had no illusions
about the conflict and the test. At its extreme, self-determination
could produce a phenomenon linked to the very region in flames _
Balkanization; and at its own extreme, respect for sovereignty
meant tolerance for the kind of mass murder within borders. She was
also realistic about the challenge of uniting Europe against even a
monster with the political genes of Hitler and Mussolini. She was
similarly aware of the difficulties in summoning US will against an
evil not widely seen as directly threatening. And she acknowledged
that there had to be a link between an effort to respond to evil
and an ability to make a difference, meaning the United States
could not act with force in every situation, and that it would
almost always need allies in situations where making a difference
was possible.
</P>
<P>
   But she was convinced that sovereignty could not be immune from
challenge in a post-Cold War world, and, above all, not in Europe's
still-unstable South. And so she went to work.
</P>
<P>
   Progress was maddeningly slow, but military action from the air
leading to peacekeepers on the ground was at long last taken in
Bosnia in 1995 and now in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's blather aside, consider the record: Slovenia, free;
Croatia, free; Bosnia, de facto partitioned, still a mess, but
independent and peaceful; Montenegro, its hold on autonomy from
Belgrade tenuous but real; Macedonia, free and probably out of
immediate danger of destabilization from Milosevic's assault by
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, it is also impossible not to believe that ideals
of democracy and free markets haven't been strengthened in Albania,
Bulgaria, and Romania, and that Turkey and Greece don't have even
stronger reasons for settling their dangerous differences over
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
   And now, Kosovo. As Albright said, Milosevic has lost his
control. The currency for the immediate future is most likely to be
the dollar and the mark; the new trade patterns will flow south and
west, not north to Serbia; and once the armed perpetrators of
murder and displacement are back in Serbia, their return becomes
inconceivable.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say the NATO, European Union, UN, and other plans for
reconstruction involve a gradual erection of civilian leadership,
beginning with local elections. But every so often an official will
slip up privately and refer to the next level of elections down the
road in Kosovo as ``national.'' If ever tears and blood can be said
to qualify a people for internationally sanctioned
self-determination, the Kosovars are entitled.
</P>
<P>
   When we spoke by phone from Cologne Thursday night, Albright was
totally focused on the enormous scale of her tasks ahead, but
obviously aware a major corner has been turned _ in this crisis and
in the broader friction between self-determination and sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   Aware of the false euphoria that produced ``new world order''
babble in the Persian Gulf period, she is wary of grand summary,
but also venue-shopping for a major speech soon.
</P>
<P>
   Because of what has happened, Albright will get the hearing she
richly deserves.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
