<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4641 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-REVIEW-EXPATRIAT     06-14 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-EXPATRIATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPATRIATE FINDS HE'S A STRANGER IN HIS OWN LAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN FLINN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Bill Bryson is, once again, befuddled. He's
standing at the counter of a Sausalito coffeehouse, puffing out his
cheeks uncertainly and squinting at a menu that runs to
cappuccinos, Espresso Macchiatos, Caffe Americanos, Mocha Freezes,
Sumatra blends and Chai Lattes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd just like a cup of, uh ... regular coffee,'' he says. The
young man behind the counter purses his pierced lips and regards
Bryson with suspicion, as if he'd just requested a tankard of
hemlock.
</P>
<P>
   Bryson gets that look wherever he goes. The America he has
returned to on the eve of the new millennium is bewilderingly
different to him than the one he left in 1972 for what eventually
would become a career as a best-selling humorist and travel writer
in Great Britain.
</P>
<P>
   It's as if he's just been thawed out after having spent the past
couple of decades in a cryogenic freeze chamber, just like Austin
Powers _ except that Bryson spent his formative years not in
Swinging London, but in decidedly unswinging Des Moines.
</P>
<P>
   He's chronicled the joys and tribulations of reacquainting
himself with his native land in his latest book, ``I'm a Stranger
Here Myself'' (Broadway Books, 288 pages, $25).
</P>
<P>
   A cross between de Tocqueville and Dave Barry, Bryson writes
about today's America in a way that's both trenchantly observant
and pound-on-the-floor, snort-root-beer-out-your-nose funny.
</P>
<P>
   sHe was astounded to discover that gas station road maps are no
longer free, and wonders why his dental floss needs to carry a
number for a 24-hour Floss Hotline: ``As a rule of thumb, I would
submit that if you need to call your floss provider, for any
reason, you are probably not ready for this level of oral
hygiene.''
</P>
<P>
   The son of a Des Moines Register sportswriter, Bryson, 48, left
Iowa in 1972 for a summer of European vagabonding and cashed in his
return ticket. Settling in Britain, he worked for several London
newspapers before moving to the Yorkshire Dales and establishing
himself as one of Britain's best-selling writers with such books as
``The Lost Continent,'' ``Neither Here nor There,'' ``The Mother
Tongue'' and ``Notes From a Small Island.''
</P>
<P>
   As his reputation grew, he was contacted by a film producer,
Uberto Pasolini, who wanted him to write the script for a movie
about a group of unemployed Manchester steelworkers who become male
strippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was so farfetched and unbelievable that I wanted
nothing to do with it,'' Bryson says, speaking in an unplaceable,
vaguely British accent that could be best described as
``Iowashire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't until years later, when I saw Pasolini's name in the
closing credits, that I realized this was `The Full Monty.'''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his large following in Britain, Bryson was virtually
unknown in his native land until the success of last year's ``A
Walk in the Woods,'' a hilarious account of his hike along the
1,800-mile Appalachian Trail that spent six months on the New York
Times bestseller list.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 he moved back to the United States with his wife and
four children, choosing Hanover, N.H., ``for no other reason than
it seemed an awfully nice place.'' He chronicled his efforts to
rediscover America in a weekly column for the Sunday Mail, and
those columns evolved into ``I'm a Stranger Here Myself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I left, in 1972, Richard Nixon was still president, the
war in Vietnam was still going on and America was still in a time
of social ferment,'' he says. ``It could hardly be more different
now.''
</P>
<P>
   The America he remembers was a place of motor-court motels with
white-painted wagon wheels out front and diners staffed by
waitresses who refilled your cup with coffee _ regular coffee _ and
called you ``honey.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, even the most modest American eating establishment
describes its fare ``with a sumptuousness and panache that are
seldom less than breathtaking and always incomprehensible.''
</P>
<P>
   At a restaurant in rural Vermont, he writes, the evening's
special sounded to him like ``a crepe galette of sea chortle and
kelp in a rich mal de mer sauce ... baked in an inverted Prussian
helmet and layered with steamed wattle and woozle leaves.''
</P>
<P>
   What astounds him most about today's America is the giddying,
bounteous abundance of just about everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more than you cope with _ too many books to read, too
many movies and TV shows to see, more videos than you could ever
rent, more items in the stores than you can possibly keep track
of,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Britain ``still has this sense of austerity, like
the war has just finished: `Can't have too many ice cubes until all
the boys are home.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bryson was startled when his eldest son went out to look for a
summer job in Hanover and landed one the next day. ``There's a
dynamism and energy in American society that we take for granted
here, but it really is dazzling,'' he says. ``To a European, the
words, `Can you start tomorrow?' are just never heard.''
</P>
<P>
   With a gifted eye for the absurd, Bryson notes that life in
America is every bit as dangerous as Europeans imagine it to be _
in part because harm lurks where it's least expected.
</P>
<P>
   Quoting from the Statistical Abstract of the United States'
figures on injuries from consumer products, he notes that last year
``paper money and coins (30,274) claimed nearly as many victims as
did scissors (34,062). I can just about conceive of how you might
swallow a dime and then wish you hadn't (`You guys want to see a
neat trick?'), but I cannot for the life of me construct
hypothetical circumstances involving folding money and a subsequent
trip to the E.R. It would be interesting to meet some of these
people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
