<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIXFLAGS-ADS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN AN ADVERTISING SHIFT, SIX FLAGS IS TARGETING `MOM'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SEAN WOOD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Last year, ads for Six Flags Over Texas
showed a long-haired kid in a T-shirt running toward a trash can
while music from ``Chariots of Fire'' played. As his friends
cheered him on, the boy threw up in the trash can after getting off
a thrill ride.
</P>
<P>
   This year, grunge boy has been replaced with Disney-esque images
of children meeting Bugs Bunny and Foghorn Leghorn. There is
footage of roller coasters and stage shows and a singer urges
viewers to ``discover the magic.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of targeting teens and young adults in its ads, Six
Flags, like other businesses, is now aiming at the ultimate
guardian of the purse strings: Mom.
</P>
<P>
   Although the teen market is big _ teen-agers collectively spent
more than $141 billion last year, according to Teenage Research
Unlimited in Northbrook, Ill. _ the family market is bigger.
</P>
<P>
   Families with children ages 2 to 12 spent nearly $500 billion in
1998, said Traci Blanks, senior vice president of marketing for
Premier Parks, which owns and operates Six Flags Theme Parks. And
it's Mom who makes many of the spending decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moms have a major say in the family's activities,'' Blanks
said. ``So we advertise a lot to moms.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost as important is the loyalty of the family customer base,
she said. ``They are not as fickle as the teen market is,'' Blanks
said. ``I think Nike found out how fickle that market can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Nike watched its sales plummet when teen-agers' ardor for its
shoes cooled, sending its stock price down and the company
searching for new products. Other companies also have experienced
the perils of marketing to teen-agers. Gadzooks, a Carrolton,
Texas, clothing company, watched its stock price plummet 80
percent, from a 52-week high of almost $30 per share to a little
more than $10 a share when teen-agers snubbed its private-label
line.
</P>
<P>
   Six Flags parks found out firsthand about those perils last
year. Premier targeted teens and young adults with its ``You In or
You Out'' campaign. When attendance sagged at Six Flags parks,
Premier quickly returned to its traditional core audience,
marketing to families, and attendance rose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Premier has always been focused on family,'' said Gary Slade,
publisher of Amusement Today, an industry trade publication based
in Arlington. ``It's an important core. It gives you your base for
annual attendance. Then you can put the teens and the tourists on
top of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Others in the amusement and entertainment industry have also
increasingly focused on marketing to the women who control the
family purse strings.
</P>
<P>
   One of Six Flags Over Texas' neighbors, the Texas Rangers,
unveiled a series of commercials this year designed to appeal to
women. ``Women control our leisure time in the entertainment
industry,'' Charlie Serapahin, vice president of marketing for the
Rangers, said recently. ``It is only logical to target our message
to the person who makes the entertainment decisions in the
family.''
</P>
<P>
   Six Flags focuses on two things when marketing to Mom: value and
image.
</P>
<P>
   It has been hammering home the value message with season-pass
ads.''We've had a huge increase in season pass purchases across the
company,'' Blanks said. ``Most of our families are season-pass
holders.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because, Blanks said, the season pass lets families visit
the park for three to four hours at a time and still feel like they
are getting their money's worth. Families who visit once a year
tend to feel like they have to spend an entire day to make it worth
their while.
</P>
<P>
   Portraying a warm and friendly family image with a sense of
tradition is also important, Six Flags officials said. One theme is
the ``Magic of Six Flags'' and another ad, ``street party,''
focuses on the park's Texas heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six Flags Over Texas is a tradition,'' said James Geiser, vice
president of marketing for the park. ``In the ads, you're watching
kids have a great time. It pulls on more of the emotional
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If all we showed is Batman the Ride, we'd be putting our eggs
in one basket,'' Geiser said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six Flags has built a reputation for thrills,'' Blanks said.
``But we believe thrill will mean different things to different
people. It is just as thrilling for a little girl to meet Tweety
Bird as it is for someone to ride Batman.''
</P>
<P>
   So one ad combines images of children meeting Looney Tunes
characters with some of the more thrilling rides like Batman, the
Texas Giant and the Flashback.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
