<SLUG> BC-KITCHEN-STONE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD LOOK FOR THE MODERN KITCHEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The kitchen has evolved into a very high-tech
environment, but many homeowners are adding a warm touch, by
stepping back to an earlier time and using natural materials, such
as stone.
</P>
<P>
   Granite and soapstone sinks were popular in 19th-century
farmhouses and Victorian town houses. Many of these hand-carved
sinks can still be found in older homes or historic parts
warehouses, or they can be purchased new.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sell a few hundred soapstone sinks every year,'' said Glenn
Bowman, owner of Vermont Soapstone in Perkinsville, Vt. ``They can
be custom-manufactured in any size and cost approximately $800 to
$1,200 for an average-size sink. They are all constructed so that
the apron of the sink can be exposed. You find a lot of soapstone
sinks in butler's pantries and turn-of-the-century Victorians.''
</P>
<P>
   For 10 years, Stone Forest in Santa Fe, N.M., has been making a
variety of innovative hand-carved granite elements for the home,
from garden ornaments to fountains and sinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stone sinks have been popular for about eight to nine years
now,'' said Peter Singdahlsen, manager of Stone Forest. ``But they
are not just limited to older home restorations, they are being
purchased for high-end homes, including luxury condominiums. This
type of sink lends itself to a wide range of styles, from adobe to
Victorian. Our farmhouse sink is modeled after a traditional
European design.''
</P>
<P>
   The farmhouse sink can be installed as a top mount, which sits
on top of the cabinetry, or as a self-rimming unit, where it's
recessed into the counter, which can also be of matching granite.
Sinks are available with a rough front apron, polished (or rough)
rim and polished basin. Stone Forest sinks, which are all made from
Asian granite, cost approximately $850 for a single bowl (175
pounds) to $1,400 for a double basin (330 pounds). Colors for Stone
Forest sinks are beige granite, rose, blue/gray and black (which is
a special order and $200 extra).
</P>
<P>
   Granite sinks are sealed with a stone tile sealer prior to
shipping and require resealing once a year. Any high-quality tile
cleaner can be used to remove hard-water deposits. Stone sinks are
made to accept most disposal drain assemblies and fixtures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
