<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-HOCKEY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOCKEY BUILDING A FEMALE FAN BASE
</HEADLINE>
 
(DUPLICATION ALERT! Story moving in ``a'' general news category and
``s'' sports category) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARY DOCLAR 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Glance into the stands at Reunion Arena, and they're
everywhere, screaming themselves hoarse.
</P>
<P>
   They're fervent followers of the Dallas Stars, cheering goalie
Ed Belfour's saves and chewing out the referees when defenseman
Derian Hatcher is sent to the penalty box.
</P>
<P>
   They're wearing more green than the Irish on St. Patty's Day,
waving pompons and rally towels with abandon and comparing notes on
stick handling and power plays.
</P>
<P>
   Who are they? It's ``the girls,'' guys.
</P>
<P>
   Ice hockey has made ardent fans of many females, who say they
find the sport's aggressive action appealing and the game a
family-oriented affair with role models who haven't run afoul of
the law.
</P>
<P>
   As the Stars battle the Buffalo Sabres in the Stanley Cup
Finals, the fans' interest only grows. The Stars lead the
best-of-seven series, two games to one, with Game 4 scheduled for
Tuesday night in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an easy game to understand,'' said Jean Nicolosi, 50, of
Flower Mound, who attended Game 2 on Thursday with her
daughter-in-law, Stephanie Nicolosi, 29. ``There's so much more
action, and you're part of the action. Maybe that's the thing _
it's more intimate.''
</P>
<P>
   But hockey has done more than turn women into statistic-spouting
fans who wile away the hours debating right-winger Brett Hull's
slap shot and Buffalo goalie Dominik Hasek's shot-blocking ability.
</P>
<P>
   More women are taking to the ice to play on amateur women's
teams, such as the Dallas Banshees, an organization that just a
short time ago had trouble persuading women to pick up a stick.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Banshees, they play an extremely good game,'' said Jimmy
Newby, a retired Dallas truck driver who coaches the team. ``Their
skating abilities are phenomenal. Women are so meticulous about
getting it right. They're passing and shooting as good as any
player I've seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Hockey is viewed by many as a female-friendly sport,
particularly after Manon Rheaume briefly played goaltender for the
Tampa Bay Lightning in 1992, becoming the first woman to play in
one of the four major U.S. professional sports leagues. The
gold-medal success of the U.S. women's Olympic hockey team at the
1998 Olympics in Nagano, Japan, also brought a higher profile to
the sport.
</P>
<P>
   National Hockey League research shows that women comprise 42
percent to 43 percent of arena attendance during hockey games,
which is about the same percentage of women attending major-league
baseball games but higher than that attending football or
basketball games, said Bernadette Mansur, the NHL's vice president
of communication.
</P>
<P>
   ``The skill and the finesse, the quickness of the skating, the
color of the game ... it all appeals to them,'' said Mansur, adding
that 55 percent of employees in the league's New York City
headquarters are women.
</P>
<P>
   Some women said they like hockey because it seems more
family-oriented and fan-friendly than other professional sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, for the Dallas Stars at least, they seem to have more
of a family organization,'' said Janice Fallin, 40, a longtime
hockey fan and member of the Stars booster club who drives a green
car covered with the win-loss records from the Stars' postseason
play. ``That comes across somehow through the players and the way
they represent themselves. I think maybe that end of it is more
attractive to women.''
</P>
<P>
   Fallin said her feelings toward the players are maternal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know for me, the way I feel about the Dallas Stars is
they're my babies,'' Fallin said. ``It's like a female tiger
defending her cubs. I don't have kids, but they're like sons or
brothers. I'm very protective of them.''
</P>
<P>
   While many women are content to experience hockey from the
stands, USA Hockey, an amateur hockey organization, reports that
more women are playing the game. Since the organization, which is
based in Colorado Springs, Colo., began tracking female
participation in the 1990-91 season, female membership in hockey
has increased 330 percent and the number of registered women's and
girls' teams has increased 619 percent, according to NHL figures.
</P>
<P>
   Newby's daughter, Melissa, 20, a University of Texas at
Arlington student, said she first became interested in hockey
during junior high, when her parents started taking her to
minor-league games. She learned to skate and started playing with
the Dallas Junior Hockey Association, where she was one of only two
or three girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It forced me to learn a lot really quick,'' said Melissa
Newby, who now plays for the Banshees. ``A lot of the guys had been
playing longer. They were bigger than me. They actually hit you a
lot harder when you're a girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Irving resident Scarlett Chambers, 26, another Banshees player,
said that although she initially struggled to get other women
interested in the sport, the team now has a player list of about 70
women, who range in age from 19 to 50, including one grandmother.
About 20 are part of the competitive team, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole idea is to get enough interest so we can have a
league,'' said Chambers, whose team traveled to Bethany, Okla.,
last weekend for a tournament. ``We want people so we can play
ladies on ladies. We play against the guys, and they get all
nasty.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
