<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRODY-HEALTH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL HEALTH: IN A CULTURE OF SUNBATHERS, TIPS FOR SHIELDING THE
SKIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By JANE E. BRODY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As warm and wonderful as it feels to bask under the rays of the
summer sun, it is not very good for the body. In my teen-age years,
we had tanning contests to see who could get the darkest the
fastest. In my 20s, I slathered my bikini-clad body in baby oil to
attract as many tanning rays as I could in the little time I had
for sunbathing. Now, decades later, when I look at the spotted skin
that has begun to wrinkle on my arms and legs, I cannot help
wishing I had known then what I know now.
</P>
<P>
   Although most Americans still precede the word ``tan'' with
``healthy,'' it is anything but. A tan, which results from the
formation of the pigment melanin in skin cells called melanocytes,
is the body's attempt to defend itself against sun damage.
</P>
<P>
   Melanin absorbs some of the incoming rays to keep them from
harming other cells. But this protection is far from complete. I
only hope that by protecting my skin from further sun damage I will
not end up like my my grandmother, who lived on a beach and whose
skin resembled elephant hide by the time she reached 70.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, we all should know better, but I still see
sunbathers galore, mostly teen-agers and young adults and a fair
number of baby boomers minimally clad and well greased as they seek
a so-called ``healthy tan.'' Because it is unlikely that sun-loving
Americans will suddenly take to the shade, pharmaceutical and skin
care companies have come up with a host of new products that can
help to minimize _ though not eliminate _ the damage of sun
exposure.
</P>
<P>
   By now everyone knows that it is ultraviolet, or UV, rays that
both tan and damage the skin. The wavelengths of concern are UVB
(290 to 320 nanometers) and shorter and longer UVA (320 to 400
nanometers). The atmosphere's ozone layer blocks another type, UVC
(200 to 290 nanometers), as well as large amounts of UVB. But the
closer the sun is to the earth's surface and the more degraded the
ozone layer, the more UVB gets through.
</P>
<P>
   Although UVB has long been recognized as the cause of sunburns
and superficial skin cancers called basal-cell carcinomas, recent
studies have implicated it as a cause of melanoma, the most serious
form of skin cancer, as well. One or two blistering sunburns early
in life can greatly increase the risk of developing a potentially
fatal melanoma.
</P>
<P>
   Also, those who are exposed to occasional bursts of sunlight,
like indoor workers who spend weekends and vacations in the sun,
appear to be at greater risk of melanoma than people who are
continuously exposed, like farmers and fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   However, farmers and fishermen and others who are always in the
sun get many basal-cell carcinomas on exposed parts of their
bodies. The fairer the skin, the more prone people are to
developing superficial skin cancers. A blond, blue-eyed friend just
had 14 of these lesions removed from his face and back. Though not
as deadly as melanoma, these cancers can eventually spread if not
removed, a process that can leave noticeable scars, especially on
the face.
</P>
<P>
   UVA radiation may also be implicated in cancer. It can damage
the genes, especially a tumor suppressor gene called p-53, and
impair the workings of the immune system. But the damage it most
commonly causes is premature aging of the skin, or photoaging:
wrinkled, leathery skin pockmarked with brown spots.
</P>
<P>
   The longer rays of UVA can penetrate the deeper layers of the
skin where they degrade the elastic fibers and collagen that keep
the skin smooth and firm. If you would like to know how young your
skin would look had it not been repeatedly exposed to UVA, check
your buttocks. Or compare the skin on the outside of your arms with
the side against your body.
</P>
<P>
   People who frequent tanning salons are assaulting their skin
with high doses of UVA radiation. UVA can also penetrate window
glass, including car windows. It passes through water and it is
released as well from fluorescent and halogen bulbs. Unlike UVB,
which is more intense in summer, at midday and at higher altitudes,
UVA radiation is much less affected by season, time of day or
altitude. It is present all day year-round everywhere and it
represents more than 90 percent of the UV radiation that reaches
the earth's surface.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone shopping for skin protection products is bound to be
confused. Labels state sun protection factors, or SPF, ranging from
4 to 60 and make claims like ``waterproof,'' ``water resistant,''
``sweat proof,'' ``all-day protection,'' ``complete protection''
and ``total sunblock.'' New regulations, which the Skin Cancer
Foundation worries will further confuse the public, will create
only three categories ``minimal'' (SPF 2 to 12), ``moderate'' (12
to 30) and ``high'' sunburn protection (30 or more).
</P>
<P>
   The first fact worth noting is that the rating refers only to
the product's ability to reduce exposure to UVB radiation.
Laboratory tests using liberal amounts of the product reveal how
much longer a person may be protected from sunburn than if no
sunscreen were applied. Thus, if you would normally burn in 20
minutes in the sun, using a product with an SPF rating of 15 would
theoretically keep you from burning for five hours.
</P>
<P>
   However, there are three important limitations. One, to be most
effective, sunscreens should be applied half an hour before
exposure. Second, most people do not apply nearly enough sunscreen
to achieve laboratory levels of protection. The amount an
average-size adult in a bathing suit should use is one ounce per
application, repeated every few hours. The way most people use
sunscreen the rating would be only half or less what the label
states, so you would be wise to choose a product with high sunburn
protection. Third, unless you use a product that offers good
protection against both UVB and UVA radiation, even if you do not
burn, you will be exposing your skin to a lot of UVA damage.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than two dozen new products available that offer
more complete UV protection. These contain either micronized zinc
oxide or titanium oxide or Parsol 1789 (avobenzone). Other products
containing benzophenone also reduce exposure to UVA but not as
effectively, studies have indicated.
</P>
<P>
   Women who wear face makeup would be wise to choose a product
that offers such protection, and everyone who is in the sun even
sporadically during the day can benefit from the use of a face
lotion that offers UVA and UVB protection; it should be applied
liberally and reapplied whenever the face is washed. Also apply a
lip balm with full protection repeatedly throughout the day. Note,
however, that it is not yet known whether products containing
vitamin E, vitamin C or other antioxidants enhance their sun
protection value.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the best way to avoid sun damage is to stay out of it
as much as possible. When in the sun, wear a hat with a brim at
least three inches wide and protect your eyes with sunglasses (UV
light can cause cataracts). Relax in the shade, but since UV rays
scatter, use sunscreen even if you are under an awning or beach
umbrella. And, whenever possible, cover your skin with clothing.
</P>
</TEXT>
