<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990614.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4716 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-LATIN-CROSSOVER     06-14 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-LATIN-CROSSOVER-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO TEXAS BANDS WITH TIES TO SELENA HOPE TO ROCK THE SIZZLING LATIN
CROSSOVER SCENE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOEY GUERRA 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Chris Perez is standing in an upstairs lobby of the
Doubletree Hotel, reluctantly waiting to take his place during an
impromptu photo shoot. He smiles warily, plays with his fingers
nervously and looks around the room.
</P>
<P>
   An instant later, he is gone.
</P>
<P>
   A quick escape would seem a likely move for the admittedly shy
musician, but something has caught Perez's eye in a nearby hotel
laundry room. He sticks a quarter into the video game and takes his
mark. For a few minutes, Perez is transfixed by the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Though Perez's eyes still seem pained, even scarred by some
incomprehensible hurt, this is clearly not the same man who, just a
few years ago, hovered in the shadows while the media devoured
every bit of information about his late wife, Tejano superstar
Selena.
</P>
<P>
   Since Selena was murdered in 1995 by her fan club president,
Yolanda Saldivar, Perez and the Quintanilla family have relived
countless moments of joy and pain, thanks to a big-screen movie, a
flood of books, news reports and a seemingly endless catalog of
unreleased Selena music. (A recent-hits collection was certified
gold, proving the public still loves its Corpus Christi princess.)
</P>
<P>
   Selena's brother, AB Quintanilla III, has forged ahead musically
with AB Quintanilla y Los Kumbia Kings. The eight-member group
continues the fusion of cumbia, pop, reggae, rap and rhythm and
blues that helped put Selena on the map; its debut album, ``Amor,
Familia y Respeto,'' was released in March on EMI Latin.
</P>
<P>
   Perez's own musical aspirations didn't vanish when his wife
died. He was a guitarist for Selena y Los Dinos, and now he returns
to music with the Chris Perez Band. The bilingual rock outfit
includes vocalist John Garza, keyboardist and former Dino Joe
Ojeda, bassist Adriel Ramirez and drummer Jorge Palacios. The
band's debut album, ``Resurrection,'' was released May 18 by
Hollywood Records. It features production from Julian Raymond, who
has worked with Fastball and the Wallflowers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that the CD's out, I'm really excited that people are
going to be able to find out who we really are,'' Perez, 29, said.
``I think with the media, a lot of the hype surrounding the movie
and these unauthorized books and whatever else, the focus of who I
really am as a person got shifted. They relate to the person in the
movie, they relate to the person in books. Sometimes I feel it's
been forgotten that, first and foremost, I'm a musician.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Perez has read and written music since the age of 10,
and he played piano, French horn, B-flat horn, trumpet and snare
drum throughout his school years. He played in various rock and
Tejano bands before landing a spot with Selena y Los Dinos in the
early '90s. With Selena's death, however, Perez earned a new title:
widower.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started playing guitar at age 15, that was an awakening
of sorts. That was a way to express myself _ through that or
through the craft of songwriting,'' Perez said. ``I think all that
kind of was forgotten about, and I was just a widower. I'm more
than that. It's something I went through and all that, but it just
kind of seems to bring about all these dark feelings. I hope ...
maybe not that (the public) will forget about that, but it won't be
the first words out of their mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   To help the process along, Perez and his band embarked on a
promotional tour that includes English and Spanish radio events and
in-store appearances in California, Florida, Illinois, Puerto Rico
and throughout Texas. A complete list of tour dates will be
announced soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been exciting,'' Perez said. ``I've never been to any
rock stations, so to speak, in English, to do interviews and stuff.
It's something new to me, and I enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Two singles from ``Resurrection'' have been simultaneously
released. The scorching, shades-of-Santana title track is receiving
airplay on modern and mainstream rock radio, and the ballad ``Por
Que Te Fuiste?'' has been shipped to Latin pop radio stations.
Perez said the results have been unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think they (rock stations) were going to be so
receptive of the music,'' Perez said. ``I just thought that we were
going to get a little bit more support from Tejano radio, but then
again, we're not playing Tejano. It's a business, and we're still
trying to find our place.''
</P>
<P>
   The road to ``Resurrection'' began in 1996, when Perez finally
decided that music _ specifically ``rock en espanol'' _ was
something he still wanted to pursue. He had been toying with the
idea before that, but he hadn't felt that the time was right for
him to venture back into the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``After everything happened with Selena, I couldn't. ... A
couple of months went by before I even picked up a guitar. Once I
did again, it wasn't the same,'' Perez said. ``It took me a while
to get back into the groove and start writing again and start
expressing myself in that way. Once that happened, everything just
kind of fell into place, almost like I was guided in this
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   During this time Perez met Garza, a local singer in Corpus
Christi. They began writing songs together for fun, with no
intention of forming a band or landing a record deal. Garza also
introduced Perez to Venessa Villanueva. The pair has been together
for more than two years and have a 4-month-old daughter, Cassie.
It's a fact Perez is content with, despite the rumors and
chastising he's received from fans and press.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I've been through already with the media,
sensational-type media especially, I don't think they can say
anything that's going to shock me, that's going to hurt me, that's
going to make me angry,'' Perez said. ``I refuse to let my private
life be affected by that. I've been there, done that with Selena.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to play the game. I lay my cards out on the table.
There's still my private life that I keep to myself, but I'm not
going to deny that I have a girlfriend and that I have a beautiful
baby and that I'm happy just to sell more albums. If people accept
it, cool. If they don't, too bad. I'm not here to please them all
the time.''
</P>
<P>
   As Perez and Garza's songwriting became more serious, the rest
of the group fell into place. They headed to Los Angeles in
November 1996 to cut a few demos and shop them around to labels.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe it or not, it was hard, man,'' Perez said. ``They were
willing to listen to it, but back then what was happening on the
chart was real ballad-types. You had your Enrique Iglesias ballads,
Ricky Martin ballads, Luis Miguel ballads ... all the way down the
charts. I guess that's what (record) companies were looking at.
</P>
<P>
   ``They loved our music, so they said, but they didn't know where
to take it. We could have sat down and written a whole album of
ballads, but we just didn't want to do that. So we kind of took our
chances and stuck with what we wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The perseverance paid off when the band landed a meeting with
Bob Cavallo, chairman of the Buena Vista Music Group. Cavallo flew
to Austin to hear the band during a rehearsal, and they signed a
deal in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   For some of the public (and fans of Selena), Perez's choice to
play rock music comes as a surprise, despite his penchant for
guitar solos and his rock-star looks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are people out there who think I'm coming out
with a Tejano album,'' Perez said. ``I could've done that, but I
didn't even go there. I figured I'd played with the best. I don't
know if I'd be able to handle being up onstage playing Tejano music
and not having what I had before.''
</P>
<P>
   The album features six tracks in English and nine in Spanish,
which Perez says is a good representation of the band's music. It
also begs the question of crossover appeal, a factor Perez was
conscious of long before Martin was livin' ``la vida loca.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Latin explosion,'' Perez said, with a hint of sarcasm in
his voice. ``These guys that are considered part of the Latin
explosion, you know they've been doing it for years. They deserve
the exposure they're getting, but it just sounds like such an
overnight thing, and it's not that at all. It might be an explosion
to people in the English mainstream part of the industry, but it's
been there all this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid all the frenzy, however, Perez feels one name has been left
out of the loop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it would be this intense or popular if Selena
hadn't come along, and I don't think I've heard her mentioned in
any of this Latin explosion thing,'' he said. ``Really, I think
she's the one who kicked the door open.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
AB QUINTANILLA Y LOS KUMBIA KINGS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AB Quintanilla III is also hoping to fulfill the dream his
sister never did during her lifetime: to bring his music to
English-speaking fans.
</P>
<P>
   It might not be be such a faraway fantasy, given the Kumbia
Kings' youthful image and energetic sound. The group's debut album,
``Amor, Familia y Respeto,'' features old-school R&AMP;B, salsa and
cumbia rhythms. Guests on the album include Perez (who plays guitar
on the new single, ``Fuiste Mala''), Sheila E., R&AMP;B group Nu
Flavor, reggae star Vico-C. and late R&AMP;B singer Roger Troutman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The album that I put together for Kumbia Kings is using just
basically the same formulas that I used with Selena,'' said
Quintanilla, calling from his Kat Kave Studios in Corpus Christi.
``Everything I am is because of (Selena), and for me, I'm just kind
of continuing what I did with her. I've got a guy singer (Jason
``DJ Kane'' Cano), but he's an R&AMP;B singer, real soulful, like
Selena, and I apply it to cumbia.''
</P>
<P>
   Quintanilla's formula seems to be working. Since the album's
release in late March, it has already sold more than 100,000 copies
_ an impressive number in the Tejano market. The group has an
upcoming show with Earth, Wind and Fire in El Paso, and Quintanilla
recently produced three tracks for Latin dance singer Angelina's
upcoming album, which features the Kumbia Kings. That's a
much-needed shot in the arm for the ever-shrinking Tejano market.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Selena passed away, (Tejano) kind of took a little
slump. I'm not saying that she was the whole heart of the market,
but at the same time, she was bringing a lot of attention to the
market, and it was spilling over to artists like Emilio and La
Mafia. But now, all the power bands have disappeared,'' said
Quintanilla. ``I can't say that Kumbia Kings are the answer or the
solution to the market, but I'm just trying my hardest to do my
part.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened is you went from (Selena's No. 1 hits) ''Techno
Cumbia`` and ``Bidi Bidi Bom Bom`` and your real pop-oriented
cumbia back to block one, with norteo music. You turn on the Tejano
radio station now, and all you hear is accordion, song after
song.''
</P>
<P>
   Quintanilla, who is reluctant to admit his age, was born on a
Friday the 13th on an Indian reservation in Washington state, and
he grew up listening to the Eagles and Van Halen before being
turned on to Latin and Mexican music. It was that fusion of sounds
that helped create Selena y Los Dinos' unique style. Along with
older brother Quintanilla and husband Perez, the group featured
older sister Suzette on drums.
</P>
<P>
   Quintanilla has also shared his producing talents with
international artists, including Thalia, Olga Tanon, Christian and
Veronica Castro. His work with Selena, however, remains most
important.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through a little area where I didn't even touch cumbia,
period,'' Quintanilla said. ``Everybody goes through their
reflection of life. You've got to keep in mind that ... she was my
world, man. That's who I got up every morning for, and that's who I
was dedicated to writing for and producing. Other artists had
asked, but that's who mattered to me in my life, and all of a
sudden one day, it's not there. You kind of wonder, what are you
going to do with yourself. I wasn't sure where I was going to go.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing Quintanilla decided was to stick with EMI Latin, the
label that was home to Selena y Los Dinos. He was looking around at
record labels before finally deciding to stay with something
familiar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what I didn't want to do was just follow everything
the same as what I did with Selena,'' Quintanilla said. ``I still
go to my dad for advice, and I got a call from (EMI president) Jose
Behar, and they both said, `Why not stay with your family?' I'm 100
percent happy with EMI. They're making all my dreams come true with
the Kumbia Kings.''
</P>
<P>
   An unexpected surprise on ``Amor, Familia y Respeto'' is ``Oh
No,'' a song originally written in English by Selena and her
brother for her planned pop album. It may eventually be recorded in
its original version by dance diva Taylor Dayne.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just held onto the song, and I recorded it in cumbia,''
Quintanilla said. ``We wrote the song, and, unfortunately,
everything happened. I love the song, and it ended up on my
album.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite that touch of a Tejano legacy, Quintanilla isn't trying
to replicate his sister's success. He hopes old fans and new
listeners tune into his sound simply because the music is good.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will never be another Selena. Chris or I aren't trying
to re-create a Selena y Los Dinos. That was part of our life, but I
think we have to work double hard because we're coming out of
something very big,'' Quintanilla said. ``People don't realize that
this doesn't make it any easier. It helps if you have the last name
Quintanilla and you're AB and you wrote the hits for Selena, but
people want to know, what are you offering them now? It's a totally
different ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
