<DOCNO> NYT19990614.0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4721 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-BUENA-VISTA-HNS &LR;      06-14 1426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BUENA-VISTA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DOCUMENTARY REVISITS PLAYERS OF `BUENA VISTA SOCIAL CLUB' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICK MITCHELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The crowd on the Havana street corner gathers around the vintage
convertible. As the camera rolls, 91-year-old Cuban guitarist and
singer Compay Segundo asks for directions to the building that was
home to the Buena Vista Social Club.
</P>
<P>
   Several people remember the place. The problem is, their
memories don't all agree. One person points this way, one person
points that way. Before long, the amazingly spry Segundo is out of
the car, puffing on a cigar and offering his sage advice on how to
cure a hangover.
</P>
<P>
   The actual Buena Vista Social Club may be but a fading memory.
But the album inspired by that semimythic musical meeting place has
become an international sensation.
</P>
<P>
   Produced in Havana by American guitarist Ry Cooder, ``Buena
Vista Social Club'' has sold more than 1 million copies worldwide
since its 1997 release. The success of the album has revived the
careers of the half-forgotten legends of prerevolutionary Cuban
music who participated, including Segundo, pianist Ruben Gonzalez
and vocalist Ibrahim Ferrer.
</P>
<P>
   Now, acclaimed German filmmaker Wim Wenders has directed a
documentary to accompany the album.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about telling the stories of these people; that's the
important thing,'' Cooder says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The music is great, but you have to vibe off these people,
pick up on who they are and where they're from. And then you learn
something that the records don't get across. You learn something
about what it is to be a human being.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooder has approached his recording career with a musicologist's
delight in unearthing obscure and forgotten folk forms. In addition
to the Depression-era blues and country songs found on his first
albums, he's introduced the roots-rock audience to Flaco Jimenez's
Tex-Mex accordion, Gabby Pahinui's Hawaiian guitar and Ali Farka
Toure's West African griot-blues.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing had the impact of ``Buena Vista Social Club.'' Now
he says he's been spoiled when it comes to working with other
musicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are great players,'' he says. ``They're among the best
there are.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie was shot when the film crew accompanied Cooder _ who
has done scores for several of Wenders' movies, including ``Paris,
Texas'' and ``The End of Violence'' _ on a return trip to Havana.
The purpose of the trip was to record a follow-up to ``Buena Vista
Social Club'' featuring Ferrer, whom Cooder describes as ``a Cuban
Nat `King' Cole.``
</P>
<P>
   (The album ``Buena Vista Social Club Presents Ibrahim Ferrer''
was released last week. Like its predecessor, it was recorded for
the European World Circuit label and licensed by Nonesuch for
American distribution.)
</P>
<P>
   While in Havana, Wenders filmed the recording sessions with
Ferrer and taped interviews with key participants in the original
``Buena Vista Social Club'' recording.
</P>
<P>
   Segundo, looking dapper in a checked sport coat, ever-present
cigar in hand, explains that he has five children and is hard at
work on the sixth. Gonzalez recalls his glory days with Arsenio
Rodriguez, the most popular Cuban orchestra of the prerevolutionary
era. Ferrer, who was shining shoes when Cooder's Cuban advisers
tracked him down, explains his devotion to his guardian saint, or
``orisha.''
</P>
<P>
   What comes across is the way music flows through these men,
despite the hardships of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our society, we see ourselves as vehicles for consumption
so much of the time,'' Cooder says. ```How am I supposed to look?
What car am I supposed to drive? What do I do with myself?' It's
all out there on a menu for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beautiful thing is to see somebody who you connect with,
just because they seem so interesting. They have this inner life in
them, and I think that's what's compelling about these people.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Wenders keeps his arty, avant-garde
tendencies in check, although he alternates between grainy
black-and-white, colorized and full-color film. The contrast
effectively conveys a sense of traveling back in time when visiting
Havana's older neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of the way through the film, the focus shifts as the
crew joins the members of the Buena Vista Social Club on tour in
Holland and New York's Carnegie Hall. The latter trip results in
some comic exchanges, as the elderly Cuban musicians _ most of whom
had never been off the island _ argue about the true location of
the Statue of Liberty and the identities of the John F. Kennedy and
Marilyn Monroe busts seen in a storefront window.
</P>
<P>
   Although the film opens with one of the musicians cracking a
joke about Che Guevara letting Fidel Castro beat him at golf,
Wenders largely avoids political issues.
</P>
<P>
   Cooder says he has no idea how the Castro regime regards the
Buena Vista Social Club project.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their priorities are pretty great. I mean, they've got to get
thermometers into the hospitals, they've got to fix the streets,
they've got to try to get enough food for everybody, trying to get
computers into the country. They've got terrible priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we do comes in pretty low on their radar, and that's
good, because we can work and no one has to pay too much attention
to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the revival of interest in prerevolutionary musical
forms, sparked by ``Buena Vista Social Club,'' has generated a
backlash among some of the more ardent young supporters of the
communist revolution. Juan de Marcos Gonzalez, a younger Cuban band
leader who served as Cooder's musical consultant on the project,
stood up at a press conference in Havana and defended the music as
an essential expression of Cuban culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a brave guy because this has not necessarily been
politically correct down there,'' Cooder says.
</P>
<P>
   Although some Cuban-Americans remain adamantly opposed to any
cultural exchange as long as Castro is in power, Cooder said the
response from the Cuban-American community generally has been
favorable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cuban people in the United States like this music, because
they remember this music. At least I think they think that. It
seems like they do. In fact, I've heard some of them they say this
is our music. They have no hatred or resentment for these musicians
in particular.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, this is a volatile situation in this
country, and you never can tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Maneiro, a local political consultant and past president of
the Casa Cuba board that produces the annual Festival Cubano in
Houston, said it's difficult for non-Cubans to understand how many
Cuban-Americans feel about the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think that we're almost anti-Cuban because we're so
steadfastly opposed to any kind of interaction with the Castro
government. So far as the musicians and filmmakers are concerned,
they're just doing what artists do, making art. But they're
allowing themselves to be used as propaganda by the government to
help soften its image,'' Maneiro said.
</P>
<P>
   Maneiro was born in Cuba and moved to Houston in 1972 when he
was 2 years old. He said he's heard the ``Buena Vista Social Club''
album and liked it, but he doesn't own a copy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we're all great fans of the music. The only problem
I have with it is that it only presents one side of the picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Luis Ricardo, a local Cuban musician and music programmer for
Festival Cubano, said he thinks it's great that the ``Buena Vista
Social Club'' album and movie are introducing new fans to Cuban
music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's fantastic that they're able to travel abroad.
It's all Cuban music, whether it's done in Cuba or Miami or
wherever. I don't think we should bring politics into the
equation.''
</P>
<P>
   With the success of the Buena Vista Social Club, the key members
have been in demand for individual live appearances in Europe.
Cooder says Ferrer and Gonzalez are planning a joint U.S. tour in
the fall, operating under nonprofit rules for cultural exchange
between the U.S. and Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Cooder said he doesn't know how the increasing international
interest in Cuban music will impact the country's internal
political situation. But he hopes the cultural bond eventually will
help bring Cuban people together.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt in my mind that the only way you're going to
reunite the diasporic Cubans and the national Cubans of Cuba is
through cultural identity. And what symbolizes that culture, more
than anything else, has got to be the music.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
