<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4722 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-GREER-SFCHRON &LR;      06-14 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-GREER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOTALLY GERMAINE: GREER IS ANGRY ALL OVER AGAIN IN FOLLOW-UP
TO  `FEMALE EUNUCH' 
</HEADLINE>
   By NEVA CHONIN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ An unlit Gitane in one hand and a glass of
champagne in the other, Germaine Greer is singing the Spice Girls'
``Stop'' in her rich, smoke-damaged Australian alto: ``Stop right
now/ Thank you very much/ I need somebody with a human touch.''
Laughing, she flops onto the couch of her hotel room and lights her
cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's quite an interesting song,'' she says. ``It's saying,
`Just climb off. This may be hot, but it's inhuman. Just go.' The
Spice Girls get more interesting the more you listen to them. Quite
complex attitudes. They're a package, but what in the 1990s
isn't?''
</P>
<P>
   Greer's publishers have been trying to package the mercurial
author for almost 30 years, ever since her groundbreaking 1971
treatise on women's liberation, ``The Female Eunuch,'' became an
international best-seller and transformed her from a firebrand
academic into the most influential and controversial feminist since
Simone de Beauvoir.
</P>
<P>
   Now she's ignited a new controversy by doing what she swore she
never would: writing a sequel. ``The Whole Woman,'' published last
month by Alfred A. Knopf, re-examines many of the same topics as
``The Female Eunuch'' from a distinctly '90s perspective and with a
fresh dose of anger.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bay Area as part of a promotional tour, Greer, an elegant
60 with gray eyes that match her gray suit, says she was compelled
to write ``The Whole Woman'' when she determined that younger
feminists weren't addressing the fact that so-called equality
hadn't translated into liberation. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  ``It just cut me to the ventricles to see that they were still
caring about the same s_: `You hurt me. You hurt me so much that I
become anorexic and tear my skin over you,''' she says, knitting
her brow and smoking fiercely. ``I thought, `Damn! Why is this
happening?' When I wrote `The Female Eunuch,' I thought women's
emotionalism was a sign of weakness or abjectness. But it won't go
away. We talk and talk and try to beef up women's independence, and
they're still being gutted by the same old knives. Now I've come to
the conclusion that we should just accept that. It's who we are.
We'll always be the ones who give a s_.''
</P>
<P>
   As a professor of English and comparative literary studies at
England's Warwick University, Greer has had ample opportunity to
watch young women mature and, in some cases, crash and burn, bogged
down by the weight of what Greer calls ``the same old crap.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Recently I was giving prizes to a sixth-form class that had
just graduated from high school,'' she says. ``And up came all
these students with double-A grades with their little Ally McBeal
sparrow hands and little sparrow legs. They're my best students and
high achievers and completely anorexic. Then another bunch of girls
came up, and they were enormous. They came up clumping, walking
with their feet apart and making a big play out of being clumsy and
stupid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two are opposite sides of the same coin, these two sorts
of people who are both apologizing for themselves. What I didn't
see was a girl who was just healthy, strong and confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer sighs. ``It made me want to bang my head against the wall.
This is nonsense. It's not just to do with boys or fashion. It's
got a lot more to do with being full of anger and hostility and
having no way of expressing it. So they tear themselves to
pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer was born in Australia and educated by Irish nuns before
pulling up stakes to attend England's Cambridge University. When
she wasn't living the academic life, she explored the fields of
'60s pop culture, hanging out with rock bands and chronicling her
adventures with the same boldly sexual approach that later ignited
a maelstrom of debate with ``The Female Eunuch.''
</P>
<P>
   An unabashed attack on sexual mores and feminine conventions,
the book got Greer labeled everything from ``a super heroine'' by
Vogue magazine to ``a bad feminist'' by peers within the women's
movement. The praise and furor calmed to some degree with the
publication of her later, less polemical books, including a
literary study on Shakespeare, a rumination on absent fathers and a
reassessment of menopause titled ``Change: Women, Aging and the
Menopause.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, on the cusp of more controversy, Greer says she's
disappointed in the way the sexual revolution gave men carte
blanche to pursue their passions while leaving women stranded in a
double standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm interested to know just where women's bodies are going to
end up in the current panoply of pornography,'' she says. ``Do you
know they have cyber granny porn now? I wonder if I should pop in
there to get a few pointers. Maybe I could post a notice: Good
conversationalist seeks young, stupid stud.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer, who was briefly married in the '60s, is in the process of
recovering from a love affair that ended tumultuously shortly
before her book tour began. ``You have to eventually get to a point
where you just let each other live,'' she says with a shrug. ``And
passionate, stupid woman that I am, I never learned how to do that.
So I'm always the knock-down, drag-out mistress and never a
partner.''
</P>
<P>
   She chuckles and takes a long draught of champagne. ``God, I've
spent my whole f_ing life studying men, and they're still a mystery
to me. I'm sick of myself, really. I'm heterosexual to the point of
being a total pervert.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
