<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4723 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-OKANAGAN-VALLE     06-14 1600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-OKANAGAN-VALLEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OKANAGAN VALLEY SERVES ACCLAIMED VINTAGES AND A BANQUET OF
DIVERSIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKANAGAN VALLEY, British Columbia _ Labels on bottles at Gray
Monk Estate Winery reveal the first clue that folks in Canada's
Okanagan Valley eschew formality and relish a good time.
</P>
<P>
   Let's see, here's Pinot Noir. Merlot. Chardonnay.
</P>
<P>
   And Kerner.
</P>
<P>
   Kerner?
</P>
<P>
   ``Named for Doc Kerner from our old hometown in Germany,''
explains Gray Monk founder-owner George Heiss. ``He was a poet, a
doctor and the town drunk. And he chased everything that had a
pulse.''
</P>
<P>
   Any surprise that Kerner is a very dry wine? (It's also quite
tasty.)
</P>
<P>
   Next, mosey on down Highway 97 from Okanagan Center to Peachland
and pause at the Chinese Laundry. But don't count on dropping off
socks and shirts: Chicken Chili Laundry Style and Ginger Prawns are
on a menu, not a soiled-clothing list, at this restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   If the Laundry's soup leaves a hot-and-sour tingle in your
mouth, continue south to tiny Okanagan Falls, home of Tickleberry's
and ``the best darned ice cream you ever slung a lip over.''
</P>
<P>
   Just make certain you get back to the houseboat in time to savor
the sunset over Lake Okanagan. And keep a lookout for Ogopogo, the
sea serpent _ like the Loch Ness monster but friendlier _ said to
live 800 feet beneath the surface of this 82-mile-long, glacier-fed
center of recreation.
</P>
<P>
   Barrels of wine. Barrels of fun. Take your pick. Or both.
</P>
<P>
   Many travelers already have experienced the vitality of
Vancouver, the Old World charm of Victoria and the recreational
smorgasbord of Whistler Resort _ all justifiably renowned British
Columbia attractions.
</P>
<P>
   But, hush now, can you keep a secret? Though largely
undiscovered by Americans, the Okanagan Valley _ tucked between the
Cascade and Monashee mountain ranges 300 miles east of Vancouver _
is among Canadians' favorite summer playgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to appreciate why so many people fall under its spell.
Some come to tour one of the world's newest but already acclaimed
wine regions, others to swim and sail and fish in a succession of
clear blue lakes or pursue dozens more outdoor activities, still
others simply to slow the pace of life.
</P>
<P>
   Escaping the summer chill _ stumble over those last two words,
did you? _ is a top priority for many Canadians. With temperatures
reaching the 80s and 90s, the Okanagan is a far cry from the
``frozen North,'' and shorts and sneakers are standard attire this
time of year. But the stifling humidity of Houston summers is
absent here.
</P>
<P>
   With an exchange rate of $1 U.S. to $1.50 Canadian and few
tourist traps to inflate prices, this vacation retreat is easy on
Americans' pocketbooks, too.
</P>
<P>
   The region is compact enough for leisurely exploration. Its main
attractions _ wineries and orchards, lakes and parks, small cities
and don't-blink-or-you'll-miss-them hamlets _ are situated along or
just off Canada 97 between Osoyoos, two miles from the U.S. border,
and Vernon, 115 miles to the north (though the valley itself
extends north from Vernon).
</P>
<P>
   In many stretches, especially a 26-mile segment between
Penticton and Peachland, this is a riveting drive, hugging the
water and proceeding up and down gently sloping hills dotted with
sagebrush and pine.
</P>
<P>
   The main roadway yields repeated glimpses of vineyards and trees
draped with fruits of the season: cherries, apples, peaches, pears,
apricots and others.
</P>
<P>
   At almost every turn, another recreational pursuit beckons:
Golfers choose among 19 courses beside the water or etched into
hillsides and canyon walls; anglers cast for 20-pound trout in Lake
Okanagan; and birders seek out the elusive burrowing owl and
Canada's largest concentration of golden eagles at Vaseux Lake
Provincial Park, next to a wildlife sanctuary near Okanagan Falls
(of Tickleberry's fame).
</P>
<P>
   Hikers and mountain bikers relish the challenge of the abandoned
Kettle Valley Railway trail in the central Okanagan, especially a
five-mile loop around horseshoe-shaped Myra Canyon that includes 18
wooden trestles _ with railings to guard against unplanned downward
detours _ and two rock tunnels.
</P>
<P>
   Others delight in rafting and kayaking on rivers, rock climbing,
wind surfing, horseback riding or enjoying nature's serenity in one
of about 40 provincial parks.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, life on a houseboat can be yours. Though less focused
than Shuswap Lake to the north (the ``houseboating capital of
Canada,'' with more than 1,000 miles of shoreline to cruise), Lake
Okanagan, too, offers houseboat rentals.
</P>
<P>
   At the valley's heart is Kelowna, its largest town, with 100,000
residents and jet airplane connections from Vancouver and Calgary,
Alberta. Despite frequent traffic jams that remind too much of
home, this is a good overnight base with small orchard and wine
museums and a lovely lake-front park.
</P>
<P>
   The Okanagan's fruit-growing propensity dates to the mid-19th
century, when Father Charles Pandosy, a French priest, established
a mission near Kelowna and introduced apples. Today its orchards
are Canada's most productive, benefiting from more than 2,000 hours
of annual sunshine, mild winters and ample water pumped from lakes
to offset an average yearly rainfall of only 12 inches in some
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Want a taste? Consider a half-hour respite at Granny's Fruit
Stand beside the highway near Summerland; just keep your eyes
peeled for a driveway framed by an intoxicating rainbow of floral
and fruit baskets, then follow the scent.
</P>
<P>
   Or spend half a day exploring 75 acres of fruit orchards and
vegetable and flower gardens at Davison Orchards, a
third-generation family farm in Vernon. Walking paths are open free
of charge 8 a.m.-8 p.m.; signs along the route offer information on
crop technology and history.
</P>
<P>
   Although the first grapes also were planted almost a century and
a half ago, the valley's wine industry has blossomed only in the
past two decades. Not until 1988 did most growers begin placing a
primary focus on quality. Two years later, the government
established the British Columbia Wine Institute, which adopted
strict control standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a real revolution over the past five years,''
says Robert Simpson, a Vancouver wine specialist who created the
annual British Columbia Wine and Oyster Festival and who travels
internationally as a taster and judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only about 2,000 acres (of vineyards) in all of the
Okanagan, but the '98 vintage was fantastic, and there is great
potential,'' Simpson says.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony von Mandl, proprietor of Mission Hill Winery near
Kelowna, has an even bolder vision. ``Our goal is to become one of
the top 10 wineries in the world,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Mission Hill wines have won several international awards,
including the 1994 Avery's Trophy, signifying the world's best
chardonnay as determined by the International Wine &AMP; Spirit
Competition in London, and gold medals for pinot gris, merlot and
two chardonnays in prestigious competitions last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a pretty ideal climate for growing grapes,'' Mission
Hill executive Kevin Moul says of the Okanagan. ``We don't have a
lot of dampness, yet we have almost unlimited access to water. The
summer sun and heat develop the sugar. Our cool nights help. And
there aren't many enemies of the vine here (resulting in limited
usage of pesticides).''
</P>
<P>
   Limited production and restrictive export laws have kept most
British Columbia wines from crossing the border, but von Mandl
envisions increased exports to the United States in the new
century.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine a more idyllic backdrop for touring the
estates, even if you don't sip a drop.
</P>
<P>
   At Gray Monk, a 45-minute drive north of Kelowna, deli
sandwiches and award-winning wines are served on a patio surrounded
by bougainvillea, with panoramic views of vineyards along Lake
Okanagan.
</P>
<P>
   Heiss and his wife, Trudy, began planting government-approved
hybrid varietals in the early 1970s. Frustrated by a lack of
progress, they regrafted to European vinifera varietals, and in
1982 they established North America's northernmost winery on the
50th parallel.
</P>
<P>
   Complimentary tours provide insight into the production process.
As at other wineries, tastings are free. A large gift shop stocks
about 20 varieties, including a peach- and almond-tinged Pinot
Auxerrois and one of the world's rarest ice wines. (Yes, it does
get cold in winter.)
</P>
<P>
   Mission Hill's setting, high on a bluff in Kelowna's Westbank
suburb, is no less spectacular. A new wine shop and visitor center
help make this a popular stop.
</P>
<P>
   On the lake's opposite bank, the most striking sight at
Summerhill Estate Winery is a 3,600-square-foot (1/8-size) replica
of Egypt's Great Cheops Pyramid; its shape is considered ideal for
aging premium wines and champagne within. Just beyond, the
stone-and-cedar Champagne House stands amid a hot springs nature
preserve overlooking the water and city, with a restaurant on the
covered veranda.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, in Summerland, Sumac Ridge Estate shares a
hillside with a golf course. Next to its wine shop is the Cellar
Door Bistro, acclaimed for luncheons and dinners.
</P>
<P>
   The Okanagan region has more than 30 wineries, including Calona,
British Columbia's first, founded in 1932 in downtown Kelowna.
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry if you are tempted to inspect several: Companies
gladly arrange tours for those wise enough not to sip and drive.
</P>
<P>
   Tuckered out by now? Your houseboat awaits.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
