<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHECKING THE PULSE OF TRAVELERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rarely does a week pass that I don't receive notice of a survey
whose results purport to give a new perspective on traveler habits,
trends and needs.
</P>
<P>
   Some elicit a chuckle: for instance, the much-anticipated annual
Novotel New York study on whether more men or women accidentally
lock themselves outside of their hotel room wearing little or no
clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Most polls are blatantly promotional: Are we supposed to be
surprised that a ``scientific'' survey sponsored by a sunscreen
product determines that exposure to the sun is a main concern of
travelers in the tropics? Or that a roadside motel chain
``discovers'' that most travelers prefer to park vehicles close to
their rooms?
</P>
<P>
   But two new surveys provide intriguing food for thought.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SUMMER DESTINATIONS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 15 Houston-area agencies affiliated with Carlson Wagonlit
Travel were polled to determine their clients' 1999 summer vacation
plans. It's the first in a series of ambitious localized surveys
planned by the Minneapolis-based firm.
</P>
<P>
   And what destinations are we booking most? No surprise here: Las
Vegas, Orlando, Fla., and San Francisco, in that order, are our
preferences for domestic travel; Cancun, Paris and London are our
top three international choices.
</P>
<P>
   Value-priced tour packages to Cancun represent the ``best summer
deal,'' according to 64.3 percent of the Houston-area agents. Las
Vegas packages were mentioned second.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to name the most popular national park with clients, 28.6
percent named Grand Canyon, closely followed by Yellowstone. Rocky
Mountain, Yosemite and Zion also were named, but 50 percent of the
agents reported no national park bookings _ not so much an
indication of any waning interest in our parks but an affirmation
that those vacations are usually self-planned.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty percent of the Carlson Wagonlit agencies said that the
NATO military action in the Balkans has had no impact on bookings
to Europe. None reported any cancellations; those experiencing a
decline in reservations compared with last year cited Greece,
Italy, Turkey and Mediterranean cruises. (Other reports indicate a
significant nationwide decline in European cruise bookings,
resulting in lower fares as lines scramble to fill cabins.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
EUROPEAN ITINERARIES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mike Weingart, president of Carlson Wagonlit Utopia in Houston,
says his agency's bookings to Europe are brisk. ``We've had nobody
cancel, and we're actually seeing an increased interest in Italy
this year,'' says Weingart. ``We've found Rome as popular as
Paris.''
</P>
<P>
   Weingart says cruise bookings in Europe and Alaska are slightly
down compared with 1998, but that Panama Canal and fall foliage
(New England/Canada) itineraries are growing in popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest trend we're seeing with cruises is toward more
upscale lines such as Windstar and Silversea,'' says Weingart.
``What's happening is that the lines have come up with creative
methods to maintain price stability while not sacrificing quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are at all flexible on your travel dates and
open-minded about destinations, you can save a minimum of 25
percent and up to 50 percent or higher off cruise brochure prices
this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Weingart's agency also has seen increased interest in the
Canadian Rockies. ``The problem is that the resorts there are so
popular that they are already sold out for the summer,'' he says.
``Now is the time to book for next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide concern about low bookings for year-end events
apparently is a factor here, too. ``We made our first millennium
booking last week,'' Weingart says. ``I thought we'd see a lot of
Holy Land 2000 interest by now, but it hasn't happened yet.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, following Cancun, Paris and London in the
Carlson-Wagonlit agencies' listing of international bookings are
(4) Rome; (5) Cozumel, Mexico; (6) Madrid, Spain; (7) Montego Bay,
Jamaica; (8) Nassau, Bahamas; and (9) a tie between Florence,
Italy, and Puerto Vallarta, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Following Las Vegas, Orlando and San Francisco as top domestic
bookings are (4) New York, (5) Honolulu, (6) Los Angeles, (7) San
Diego and (8) a tie among Anchorage, Alaska (primarily associated
with cruises), Miami and New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   In weighing these results, it's important to remember that most
Houstonians don't use travel agents to assist with driving trips to
New Orleans, San Antonio and other close-to-home destinations. But
several agents, including Weingart, cite an increased interest in
combination air-land packages to Biloxi, Miss., and its new Beau
Rivage resort.
</P>
<P>
   Another study, sponsored by the industry publication Travel
Weekly, focuses on the services travel agents provide in comparison
with six other professional occupations.
</P>
<P>
   This nationwide survey of 250 travelers (54 percent male, 46
percent female, $77,000 average household income) ranked travel
agents higher than doctors, stockbrokers and lawyers with respect
to the value they provide for their work. Agents were ranked below
teachers, pharmacists and accountants in terms of value.
</P>
<P>
   Pharmacists scored highest in every other category:
trustworthiness, reliability, professionalism, knowledge,
friendliness and respectability. Lawyers ranked last in every
category except knowledgeability (in which they were rated ahead of
only stockbrokers).
</P>
<P>
   Travel agents' highest ranking, in the Travel Weekly survey, was
for friendliness (tied for second with teachers). Agents were
ranked fifth among the seven professions in all other categories.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, just in case you are curious: More men are trapped
outside hotel rooms sans clothing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
