r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOCKEY-NEOPHYTES-TEX     06-14 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOCKEY-NEOPHYTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOCKEY NEOPHYTES JUMPING ON STARS' BANDWAGON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hockey mania has struck deep and hard in North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   There's the neighbor who doesn't know icing from high-sticking
but who, nevertheless, flies a Stars flag. The friends who are
suddenly hunkering down for hours in front of their TVs or who
dicker with scalpers for expensive seats.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to explain, says historian Jerry Rodnitzky.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to identify with a winner,'' said Rodnitzky, who
teaches a course on 20th century popular culture at the University
of Texas at Arlington. ``I think it's a pretty common cultural
phenomenon in America.''
</P>
<P>
   And folks aren't embarrassed in the least to admit it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I'm watching because they're winning,'' said Meredith
Mangum, 21, a Texas Christian University student and hostess at the
Blue Mesa Grill, who hasn't missed a game on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, it's a windfall for the Stars and the
networks that broadcast the games.
</P>
<P>
   During the regular season, Fox's television station KDFW/Channel
4 was lucky when the team drew more than 5 percent of the area's
viewing population. Tuesday night's broadcast of the first Stanley
Cup Finals game attracted 26.7 percent of the population and a 42
percent share of people who had their sets on, said Andy Alexander,
the station's vice president of research.
</P>
<P>
   But Nielsen and Co. might have missed Elaine Green.
</P>
<P>
   The 57-year-old postal clerk in Bedford got so nervous, she
switched channels.
</P>
<P>
   ``They work so hard to get (the puck) down there, and then it's
gone,'' explained Green, who has never attended a game but misses
few on the tube.
</P>
<P>
   Hordes of eager newcomers to the sport are just fine with the
team, which has seen 80,000 miniature, green-and-black Star flags
snapped up and displayed like it was a patriotic duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in the process of making fans, as opposed to getting
existing fans more excited,'' said Jeff Cogen, the Stars' vice
president of marketing and promotion since 1993. ``And it's clearly
easier when you're winning.''
</P>
<P>
   The craze hits at a time when North Texas has been quietly but
heavily infiltrated by Yankee transplants. Many have been hooking
unsuspecting natives on the often violent contact sport for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a great group to watch with, all our kids and
friends,'' said Wisconsin-born Rhea Noggle, who moved to the area
13 years ago and owns a skin care and ``body contouring'' business,
Ultimate Image, in Roanoke. ``I've always been a hockey fan and was
so glad when the Stars got here,'' the Trophy Club resident said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the hockey zealots is Curtis Bogan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talk about it with the kids on my youth baseball team that I
coach,'' acknowledged Bogan, 42, of Fort Worth. ``I'm an old Iowan,
and I began following them in Minnesota when they were the good ol'
North Stars.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's hockey, more than a particular Dallas team, that
intrigues Bogan, insists his 14-year-old son, Robert, who is not a
Stars fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loves hockey. He just doesn't like the Stars,'' the son
said of his father. ``He tends to follow players more than teams,
and the players he likes are not on the Stars.''
</P>
<P>
   Even electronic geeks are pulling themselves away from their
computers long enough to form an addiction.
</P>
<P>
   Al Chia's colleagues at Texas Instruments in Dallas can't stop
discussing the Stanley Cup competition, he said. It's reached the
point where ``we're planning our work schedule around games so we
can watch them,'' the 28-year-old engineering technician added.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Medina, 34, of North Richland Hills, works at night but
doesn't let his job keep him from following the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The security guards have it on television,'' said Medina, an
employee at a Dillard's distribution center in Fort Worth. ``And
the drivers tell us what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Abernathy is an American Airlines pilot from Southlake who
acknowledges that he's following the Stars mainly because they're
in the finals.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Abernathy said he was moved Tuesday night when, heading
into Minneapolis from Chicago, an air traffic controller told him
the results of the game between the Sabres and the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I just thought you would want to know that our Stars
lost in overtime,''' Abernathy said. ``I was kind of touched.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are just as willing to admit that they're fair-weather
fans, in it to share the heightened drama and the glory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm one of those playoff watchers,'' conceded Al Gonzales, 48,
owner of Grapevine's Main Street Barber Shop.
</P>
<P>
   But two colleagues _ Deanna Mesi, a Buffalo, N.Y., native, and
Mike Flores, a Houston native _ are serious enough to gamble more
than money on the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Sabres win, Mike has to have a Buffalo emblem shaved
into the back of his head,'' Gonzales said. ``If Buffalo loses,
Deanna has to shave a star into her head. Everybody is excited
about the bet. The customers are really into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Armey, 30, a Denton County commissioner, insists that he's
been a diehard fan since the Stars moved to Dallas. But, still,
there's nothing like the Stanley Cup competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cowboys have been in Super Bowls, but the Super Bowls
haven't been in Dallas,'' said Armey, who was still hoarse after
yelling during Game 2. ``The Mavericks and Rangers haven't reached
their finals. This is the championship and it's right here in
Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   There's remarkable candor among the newly frenzied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm from the South, and this is relatively new to me,'' said
Mike Conrads, 38, of Southlake. ``I've watched a few games through
the season, but what has really gotten me excited is the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
