<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4728 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DMA-CHANGES-1000(2Tak     06-14 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DMA-CHANGES-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR NEW DIRECTOR, THE DMA IS AN UNFINISHED MASTERPIECE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Twice before, in San Francisco and Pittsburgh, Jack
Lane has brought museums to the point of greatness.
</P>
<P>
   And in both instances, he left them so that his successors could
bring in that glorious harvest. Last December, however, trustees of
the Dallas Museum of Art asked Lane to address a slightly different
situation.
</P>
<P>
   Trustees hired Lane, 55, after a yearlong search for a new
director. Their hope was that, under his leadership, they could
realize a dream of greatness looked for since at least the
mid-'80s, when the DMA moved from Fair Park to the Arts District
and hired a charismatic scholar named Rick Brettell as its new
director.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1903, the DMA is an anomaly in North Texas. Unlike
the privately supported and highly specialized museums in Dallas
and Fort Worth, the DMA relies on a mix of public and private
funds, and collects and shows an encyclopedic range of artworks.
Both factors have made it difficult for the DMA to consistently
build toward the kind of reputation enjoyed by the Meadows,
Kimbell, Carter and Fort Worth Modern, not to mention the equally
diverse (but privately funded) Museum of Fine Arts, Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the Dallas museum has presented a number of
important exhibitions _ of native North American Indian works, of
contemporary paintings, of decorative arts and other materials. An
O'Keeffe exhibition in the late '80s was its best-attended show in
the past 15 years. It has collected internationally recognized
masterworks by Jackson Pollock, Henri Matisse, Edward Hopper and
others.
</P>
<P>
   But neither Brettell nor his successor, Jay Gates, who served
from 1993 to 1998, turned trustees' dreams into reality.
</P>
<P>
   And even though Lane brings a balance of dynamism, discipline
and experience neither Brettell nor Gates could claim, his success
hinges on a handful of issues as yet untested.
</P>
<P>
   It's not his scholarly credentials and professional standing.
Lane is highly respected by his colleagues and holds a fistful of
degrees that would warm the collective heart of any search
committee: His B.A. is from Williams College (home of the so-called
Williams Mafia, whose members head a number of prestigious American
museums); his M.A. and Ph.D. are from Harvard University. Just for
good measure, perhaps, Lane also holds an M.B.A. from the
University of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   It's not necessarily his ability to raise money _ which he did
in both his previous posts, successfully overseeing capital
campaigns for new buildings in San Francisco and Pittsburgh. Or his
skills as a manager, as glowing reports from former employees
attest.
</P>
<P>
   Lane's acid test likely will have to do with his support for the
DMA's encyclopedic program. It is a museum that needs to be all
things to all people, but for too long has seemed to be about
nothing in particular.
</P>
<P>
   Lane's scholarly background is in modern art, his experiences in
contemporary, his enthusiasms clearly disposed toward both. Modern
and contemporary are recognized areas of DMA strength. But so,
perhaps even more so, are African, pre-Columbian and Indonesian
art, and American furniture and decorative arts.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Lane exudes a forcefulness, sophistication and
charm that instills confidence. And he makes a point of reiterating
his desire, already expressed in the museum newsletter, to
``re-animate the idea of an encyclopedic museum.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I sense here the same energy and ambition that I felt at the
San Francisco Museum of Modern Art in the late '80s,'' Lane says.
``Dallas has a group of people who want to advance their museum _
and I just love that. It's hard for me to think of many, if any,
American art museums with as much potential as this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lane effectively understates what could be the most
severe case of trustee frustration of any big metropolitan museum.
</P>
<P>
   Almost as soon as he was hired, Brettell started stirring up
excitement. But he also built a massive addition to the new museum
without securing funds to operate it. After he departed, trustees
turned to Gates to put housekeeping in order. He did, but at the
cost of interesting acquisitions and shows.
</P>
<P>
   As such, no one mourned when Gates quietly left for another
directorship. The search committee went to work.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Lane. As former director of SF MoMA and, prior to that,
the Carnegie Institute in Pittsburgh, Lane had transformed those
institutions into players on a national stage.
</P>
<P>
   Search committee head and former DMA board President Deedie Rose
notes that her expectations of Lane were enormous _ and that they
thus far have been exceeded.
</P>
<P>
   Current board President Jeremy Halbreich also paints a rosy
picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're hoping now is for the DMA to emerge as a respected
leader locally, regionally and nationally in three areas _
collections, exhibitions and education _ that are the focus of our
strategic planning,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   Lane envisions a detailed plan that exploits the museum's global
range and its spacious and flexible gallery spaces (the largest in
North Texas). He plans to bring to Dallas the sort of traveling
shows shared by major venues in New York, Chicago, Los Angeles and
Washington, among others.
</P>
<P>
   He looks to capitalize on area collectors' passions for
contemporary, modern, impressionist, post-impressionist and
19th-century American art. He sees the planned Nasher sculpture
garden _ which will open next door _ as a means of bringing
international attention to the museum. Lane also wants the museum
to celebrate its centennial, in 2003, to the fullest.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Jack's vision is well-defined, the trustees will pull
together to bring it home,'' says Harry Parker, director of the
Fine Arts Museums of San Francisco. As DMA director in the '70s and
early '80s, Parker steered the museum's move from Fair Park to the
Arts District.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dallas is capable of that,'' Parker says. ``And when Dallas
gets its act together to concentrate on a mission, it's something
to behold.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dallas museum is not the best,'' he concludes. ``But it's
a comer in the category that also includes Museum of Fine Arts,
Boston, the Cleveland museum and the Art Institute of Chicago.''
</P>
<P>
   Lane is the best man to take Dallas to the next level, says
Michael Auping, chief curator of the Modern Art Museum of Fort
Worth and a close colleague of Lane's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember Jack saying to me once, in a moment of complete
innocence, `I really like being a museum director,''' Auping says.
``What that says about his overall sanity, I won't say. But that is
an attitude that makes for a great museum director.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
