<P>
   SCI-SMALLPOX (Undated) _ Until modern medicine banished it,
smallpox was once the world's most remorseless killer. Now, as
health and military officials fear the ancient scourge could
return, researchers have renewed interest in research and questions
regarding the virus and the aging vaccine stocks. What makes the
virus so deadly? How well do old vaccinations work? What about new
drugs and vaccines? How likely is a smallpox attack? By William J.
Broad with reporting by Lawrence K. Altman and Judith Miller. (3600
words; an abridged version of about half this length will also
move.)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-REVERSE-COMPUTING (Undated) _ Computer scientists, working
toward the perfect computer, are using a billiard ball program to
learn how to work in reverse, like the universe itself. But an
ordinary computer is irreversible, grating against the natural
grain of the universe. Once it churns out an answer, there is no
way to go back and find out what the question was. By George
Johnson. (1620 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WIND-OCEAN (Undated) _ The continuous interplay between wind
and ocean, whether as gentle as a kiss or as harsh as a slap,
eventually affects almost everything else on Earth through its
influence on weather and climate. Yet, except for occasional
sampling, this crucial interface between sea and sky goes mostly
unmonitored. This should change later this week when a new
ocean-observing satellite called QuikScat, for Quick Scatterometer,
goes into orbit to begin at least two years of daily measurements
of this critical wind-sea boundary area. By Warren E. Leary. (1300
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NEURAL-STEM-CELLS (Undated) _ The elusive neural stem cell,
the founding cell from which perhaps the whole brain develops, has
at long last been discovered _ again. In an unusually direct
disagreement, two scientists say they have discovered the site in
the brain where neural stem cells lurk, but each has a different
candidate. By Nicholas Wade. (1100 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ Short items on science: What happens to
bugs when they fall prey to bug zappers (hint: don't eat nearby);
dust in the solar system that begets ... dust; and arsenic found in
the ocean's hydrothermal vents. (670 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LIGHT-CHAOS (Undated) _ A device assembled by three
physicists at the University of Maryland is little more than a
stack of four reflective balls similar to Christmas tree ornaments.
But it is proving vital it is for studying the effects of chaos on
light beams. When a light beam enters the array of balls, its image
is chopped into shards that appear to copy themselves in an
infinite progression of steps to ever smaller scales. By Malcolm
Browne. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FOSSIL-THEFT (Undated) _ The theft of valuable fossils on
public lands has become so much of a problem that one Federal
paleontologist, at Fossil Butte National Monument, has taking to
packing a gun. ``With the values so high for these rocks, there is
a real motive and incentive to collect these things,'' he said. By
Mindy Sink. (1400 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Personal Health: What's new in the
world of protection from the sun, and why those rays are so
dangerous. By Jane E. Brody. (1225 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HYMAN-MENTAL-HEALTH (Undated) _ Scientist at Work: The new
director of the National Institute of Mental Health is something of
a maverick and does not come from the ranks of clinical psychiatry,
and his ways are irritating some people. But supporters say the new
director, Dr. Steven Hyman, is just what is needed, as be
integrates his clinical research on the mind and body and the
latest developments in molecular biology. By Erica Goode. (1500
words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FOSTER-CARE (Undated) _ A former foster child discusses the
needs of foster children in America, who now number more than half
a million. By Francine Cournos, M.D. (950 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-YOGA-CHILDREN (Undated) _ Yoga-for-kids is a burgeoning
industry _ a recent outgrowth of the latest adult trend. There are
courses for children and mommy-and-me yoga classes. There are also
