<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4746 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFORMJEWS-TEX     06-14 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORMJEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETURN TO ROOTS: REFORM JEWS GOING BACK TO TRADITIONS TO RECAPTURE
IDENTITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Rabbi Ralph Mecklenburger doesn't wear a
yarmulke, or skull cap, as he leads worship services at his Reform
Judaism temple in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``But more and more of my congregants are wearing traditional
head coverings, and that's just fine,'' said Mecklenburger.
</P>
<P>
   It's a cultural phenomenon of the times, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is changing so fast that people are looking for
roots _ for the warmth and stability of traditions to hold onto,''
said Mecklenburger, rabbi at Beth-El Congregation. ``This drifting
back to more tradition is happening in Christianity and Islam and
also in Judaism.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why he and other members of the Central Conference of
American Rabbis last month overwhelmingly approved a revised
``Statement of Principles'' clearly pointing Reform Jews toward
more traditional Jewish practices.
</P>
<P>
   The new document, last revised in 1976, calls for study of
practices sometimes rejected by Reform Jews in the past _ praying
and studying in Hebrew, following kosher dietary laws and wearing
tallits, or prayer shawls, and yarmulkes to show reverence for God.
</P>
<P>
   There are 1.5 million Reform Jews in the United States _ the
largest and most liberal branch of American Judaism. By a 324-68
vote, rabbis representing that group affirmed the central tenets of
Judaism _ God, Torah and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Then they added: ``We are committed to the ongoing study of the
whole array of mitzvot (Jewish commandments), and to the
fulfillment of those that address us as individuals and as a
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Lance J. Sussman of Binghamton, N.Y., one of the
document's opponents, said the revision, though vaguely worded,
moves Reform Judaism away from the ``progressive theology'' on
which the movement is based.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have believed in changing certain practices of Judaism
because we felt it was what God expected of us,'' said Sussman,
rabbi of Temple Concord in Binghamton.
</P>
<P>
   He cited such changes as allowing men and women to sit together
in synagogue and letting women sing during worship services.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm worried that this whole business of rediscovering old
Jewish traditions means we are no longer willing to talk about
progressive changes we may need in our faith,'' Sussman said.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Sheldon Zimmerman, president of Hebrew Union College in
Cincinnati, argued for the new principles during debates at the
meeting in Pittsburgh, saying Reform Judaism needs to recapture its
roots.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman, a former Dallas rabbi who now heads one of the
largest and most influential Jewish universities in the nation,
said that it is a blessing that Jews have become so accepted and
Americanized, but that Reform Jews now are struggling to define
what it means to be Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   Reform Judaism first organized with the creation of the Union of
American Hebrew Congregations in 1873. Its goals were to adapt and
change some trappings of the faith to fit into the American way of
life, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt Judaism had to change to exist,'' Zimmerman said.
``One thing we did was adopt the Western practice of taking off our
hats in places of worship, rather than the Eastern practice of
covering our heads.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman never wore a yarmulke when he was rabbi of Temple
Emanu-El in Dallas from 1985 to 1996. It was almost a law that
rabbis did not cover their heads in the Dallas temple, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a way of showing we were different from other branches
of Judaism,'' he said. But he began introducing traditional Jewish
practices of emphasizing religious holidays and studying the faith
more intensely.
</P>
<P>
   Another Tarrant County Reform Judaism congregation, Congregation
Beth Shalom in Arlington, fully embraces the return to tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been doing this all along,'' said Janet Aaronson,
executive director of Beth Shalom. ``Almost all of our congregants
wear prayer shawls and yarmulkes, for example.''
</P>
<P>
   Many in the Arlington congregation also observe Jewish dietary
laws, and there has been some talk about putting in a kosher
kitchen at the temple, Aaronson said.
</P>
<P>
   Hilda Golden, a member of Congregation Kol Ami, a Reform
congregation in Flower Mound, especially welcomes the trend toward
Jewish traditions because she grew up in an Orthodox congregation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen more and more people covering their heads when they
come to worship,'' she said. ``I always wear something on my head,
because I think it shows respect for God.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he doesn't wear a yarmulke or keep kosher dietary
laws, Mecklenburger said he favors returning to many traditional
observances. He has been leading his congregation in that
direction.
</P>
<P>
   More Hebrew is spoken in Mecklenburger's worship services,
though English predominates. About a third of his congregants wear
yarmulkes, including some women. Also, both sexes often wear prayer
shawls. He wears a prayer shawl, but no yarmulke.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I arrived in town 15 years ago, I was told Reform Jews
don't have cantorial music,'' he said. ``But we experimented with
it and, lo and behold, we found this practice was spiritually
satisfying.''
</P>
<P>
   Another return to tradition is that a new temple being built for
Beth-El Congregation in southwest Fort Worth will face toward
Jerusalem. The current temple south of downtown Fort Worth does not
face toward that holy city.
</P>
<P>
   David Taffet, vice president of Congregation Beth El Binah, a
predominantly gay and lesbian Reform congregation in Dallas,
praised the document because it reaffirms Reform Judaism's
opposition to discrimination based on sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   He also believes there is a need to return to more traditional
Jewish practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our parents and grandparents were trying to shed the ghetto
image of Jews,'' Taffet said. ``Now we have been assimilated into
American life, and we feel a need to go back to our roots.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
