u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-FAGAN15-COX     06-14 0294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-FAGAN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fagan-Martin manse placed on market _ for $3.5 million
 &HT;    By Sanjay Bhatt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The Mediterranean-style manse by the ocean
where convicted kidnapper Stephen Fagan lives could be yours.
</P>
<P>
   For $3.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Four bedrooms, 5 1/2 baths.
</P>
<P>
   An agent at Martha Gottfried Inc. of Palm Beach confirmed Sunday
the real estate company is listing the 6,592-square-foot dwelling
at 870 S. Ocean Blvd. at that price. He declined to offer further
details.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   He and his fourth wife paid $1.6 million for the property in
1996, according to the Palm Beach County property appraiser's
records. Two weeks after his April 1998 arrest, Harriet Golding
Martin bought out her husband's stake in exchange for $450,000, the
records show.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, her lawyer said the transfer was made for ``estate
planning'' purposes.
</P>
<P>
   When Fagan and his wife bought the 19,166-square-foot property,
he used the name William S. Martin. The house was Pepto-Bismol pink
and William S. Martin was a popular Palm Beach socialite who had
claimed to be, among other things, a Ph.D., an international
consultant and a former presidential adviser.
</P>
<P>
   The house has since been painted pumpkin yellow. And William S.
Martin has since been unmasked as Stephen Fagan, in reality a
lawyer, a former bouncer and an accused art thief.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan, 57, was convicted last month of kidnapping his two
daughters 20 years ago in a custody fight with ex-wife Barbara
Kurth.
</P>
<P>
   Sanjay Bhatt writes for The Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. Barbara Shapiro contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
