<HEADLINE>
LOOKING FOR A COOL SPOT? YOU MIGHT FIND IT IN OKLAHOMA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OUACHITA NATIONAL FOREST, Okla. _ As the days turn hot and
evenings muggy, lowlanders dream of vacations near cool waterfalls
and on mountain slopes shaded by tall, leafy trees. The problem is,
they mournfully conclude, the family budget won't allow for trips
to the lush vistas of Washington State or New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   The good news, however, is that waterfalls and mountain retreats
are closer than you think. For Texans, at least, they are just a
few hours' drive from downtown Fort Worth in neighboring Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   The popular belief is that Oklahoma epitomizes the Dust Bowl,
miles of flat terrain for as far as the eye can see, with clouds of
swirling dirt whipped by the dry, hot winds. It is a view popular
with those whose exposure to the Sooner State has been limited to
excursions on Interstates 35 and 40.
</P>
<P>
   But there is another Oklahoma, one with idyllic settings tucked
away in corners of the state that are only a short drive from the
main highways. These mountains, lakes and forests rival the most
verdant areas of New Hampshire or Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Even better, the motels and restaurants in these areas have not
become acquainted with the exorbitant prices for rooms and haute
cuisine like in the better-known escapes up north. For a few
hundred dollars, you can pack up the kids, water toys and hiking
boots and enjoy a cool, inexpensive getaway in a state close to
home.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Gene Autry Museum
</P>
<P>
   Oklahomans like to pay homage to native sons such as Gene Autry,
Will Rogers, Sequoyah, Tom Mix, cowboys in general. This is a fine
museum, with exhibits chronicling the life of Gene Autry and other
singing cowboys such as Rex Allen. It will probably persuade you to
visit a few other Oklahoma museums as well.
</P>
<P>
   How to get there: Just follow the signs on Interstate 35 north
after crossing into Oklahoma from Texas. The museum is in the town
of Gene Autry.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Turner Falls
</P>
<P>
   The magnificent 77-foot Turner Falls roars majestically in the
hills outside the tiny town of Davis. This is nature at its best.
</P>
<P>
   The surrounding public park is low-key and pleasant. For $6
apiece, you and your family can enter for a few hours of laid-back
fun. No thrill ride at a high-profile amusement park is quite like
wading in the cove where the waterfall meets a dark blue pond of
cool water. Toddlers can splash around in shallow adjacent streams.
</P>
<P>
   There are barbecue pits, picnic tables under shady trees, caves
to explore and vigilant lifeguards to keep tabs on the kids if Mom
and Dad decide to nap after lunch. It's a gorgeous spot.
</P>
<P>
   A round-trip visit to Turner Falls makes a perfect one-day
excursion and is a jewel in Oklahoma's geographic crown.
</P>
<P>
   How to get there: Soon after crossing the Red River, about an
hour's drive out of Fort Worth on Interstate 35, you'll be greeted
by road signs for Oklahoma attractions, among them Turner Falls.
Just follow the signs.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma City
</P>
<P>
   Tragedy has visited Oklahoma City twice in recent years.
Visitors are drawn to the Murrah Federal Building, which was
destroyed by a terrorist bomb. The area is fenced off now, and
construction is under way at the site to erect a permanent
memorial.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, parts of Oklahoma City and surrounding communities
were leveled when tornadoes cut a destructive path through the
area.
</P>
<P>
   But Oklahomans pride themselves on being resilient, and they are
determined to overcome any adversity they face.
</P>
<P>
   The tragedies have overshadowed the fact that Oklahoma City has
several tourist attractions that visitors may find intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   The Myriad Gardens on the southern edge of downtown are a visual
delight; the 17 acres of flora and fauna are protected from the sun
by a giant glasslike tube. You can walk around the outside gardens
for free. There is a $2 admission fee for a stroll inside.
</P>
<P>
   A half-mile away is Bricktown, a refurbished warehouse district
that now features a strip of snazzy restaurants. It is a culinary
delight and offers the widest assortment of food in the state.
</P>
<P>
   How to get there: Just take I-35 north.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Tahlequah
</P>
<P>
   This is where the U.S. government relocated the Cherokee Nation
after the tribe left its ancestral home in the Carolinas.
</P>
<P>
   You'll like Tahlequah. An interesting sight is the billboards
promoting candidates running for chief, not city council or
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The main attraction is the fabulous Cherokee National Museum,
open Tuesday through Saturday. The entry fee is $5 for adults and
$3 for kids. There are exhibits extolling the achievements of the
Cherokee as well as an account of the Trail of Tears that
chronicles the tribe's relocation to Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   How to get there: Interstate 40 to Oklahoma 69; north to
Oklahoma 62 and follow signs for Tahlequah. You'll pass Henryetta
on the way, which avid Dallas Cowboys fans know is Troy Aikman's
hometown.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The Indian mounds of Spiro
</P>
<P>
   This small town entices visitors with signs proclaiming
``Mysterious Mounds!!!'' and ``Wonder of Man and Nature!!!'' Follow
the signs until you reach a small, fenced preserve. There's no
charge to enter, but a $3 donation is suggested.
</P>
<P>
   After making your donation, you are given a trail map that shows
the way to the legendary burial mounds that supposedly hold
skeletal Indian remains. You look and look, until finally it dawns
on you that those lumpy little hillocks to one side of the path
are, in fact, the wondrous mounds.
</P>
<P>
   How to get there: From Tahlequah, head south on County Road 82,
a lovely scenic route that encompasses hills, forests and massive
Tenkiller Lake. When County Road 82 intersects with I-40, take I-40
east again to U.S. 59. Travel south to U.S. 271 and follow signs to
the Indian Mounds of Spiro.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Ouachita National Forest
</P>
<P>
   This is the oldest national forest in the South, and it
encompasses parts of Oklahoma and Arkansas. There are 33 outdoor
recreation areas and more than 600 miles of hiking, biking and
equestrian trails. There are camping grounds and great fishing
holes. Ouachita is the French version of the Indian word
``Washitah,'' which means good hunting grounds. This remains as
true today as it was hundreds of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   For those who prefer to do their hiking by car, the Talimena
Scenic Byway is a 54-mile road that provides travelers with
breathtaking views of the Ouachita Mountains and the national
forest. The drive is uphill, and you will not want to exceed 20
miles per hour on the twisting, turning road. You will probably
want to stop at more than one of the two-dozen scenic overlooks to
take photos or simply gaze at the beautiful panoramic view.
</P>
<P>
   How to get there: From the Indian Mounds of Spiro, follow U.S.
271 south as it gently rises through the mountains until you see
signs for Oklahoma 1. At this intersection, there is a large
billboard announcing the start of the 54-mile Talimena Scenic
Byway.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
