<DOCNO> NYT19990614.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4786 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RACAK-0615-COX     06-14 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RACAK-0615-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AS SERBS WITHDRAW, DETAILS OF A MASSACRE EMERGE
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-MEN; KOSOVO-RUSSIA; KOSOVO-RENEWAL
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RACAK, Yugoslavia _ ``With my own eyes I saw 23 dead bodies,''
said Agim Kameri, 32, who slipped out of the woods Monday to
revisit the site of one of the most horrific massacres of the Serb
ethnic cleansing campaign in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the corpses have no eyes,'' he said. ``Some of their
hearts had been ripped out. And most of them had their heads cut
off from their necks.''
</P>
<P>
   Another ethnic Albanian farmer from this town, Shefqet Beqiri,
50, pulled out the identification card of his 20-year-old son,
Zehel.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my basement I saw a Serb policeman kill my son last
January about 6:45 in the morning,'' he said. ``About 8:20 a.m., I
had fled to the edge of the woods. I saw the same policeman come
back, pull out a big knife and cut out my son's heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Beqiri told Cox Newspapers that he knows the killer by name and
has heard he still works as a policemen in the nearby town of
Stimlje.
</P>
<P>
   Ismet Aimini, 45, produced more grisly evidence. From the breast
pocket of his black leather jacket he pulled out a rounded bone
that he claimed was a piece of his dead brother's skull.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews by Cox Newspapers with eight surviving eyewitnesses
yielded similar stories, albeit with many details confused and some
in conflict. Their estimates of deaths ranged from 40 to 70.
</P>
<P>
   It was impossible to search for physical evidence to verify
their stories because both villagers and nearby British NATO
peacekeepers said that the trails and houses off the main road of
Racak are full of land mines.
</P>
<P>
   When rumors of the Racak massacre first reached Western ears
last January, the resulting indignation was an important factor in
convincing reluctant NATO countries that big-power intervention in
Kosovo was necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Western intelligence officials believe that Serb forces entered
the farming village, about 20 miles south-southeast of the Kosovo
capital of Pristina, in a failed search for rebels of the Kosovo
Liberation Army, or KLA. Then, unable to find the rebel fighters,
the Serbs reportedly massacred up to 70 civilians as a gruesome
warning to the ethnic Albanian population.
</P>
<P>
   Until NATO moved in and the Serbs withdrew on Monday, the town
had remained all but empty and cut off from the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   In the two days, Serb police have moved out, KLA groups have
taken control and departed villagers have begun trickling back on
foot and in tractors pulling carts.
</P>
<P>
   A Racak woman, Hajrie Ishmajli, 46, said after a bitter return
to her birthplace: ``When I saw my brothers without heads, without
eyes, without feet, I was emotionally destroyed and have been ever
since.''
</P>
<P>
   Her former neighbor, farmer Avdi Beca, 54, returned to the
village Monday, carrying a leather bridle and looking for a stolen
horse. ``There were 54 victims,'' he insisted. ``I saw them with my
own eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how many died in this village of about 2,000 people is
something international investigators may be able to determine. In
plain sight on a slope above the village is a cemetery with rows of
fresh mounds covering the victims. One of the graves is still open,
dug for a woman who disappeared and has never been found.
</P>
<P>
   After five months of hibernation, Racak was beginning to come
back to life. But the score of people who have moved back from the
wooded mountains of Kosovo are living on the edge of privation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have enough food, and the water is not safe,'' said
the town's only functioning authority, KLA commander Abdullah
Muhammad.
</P>
<P>
   Racak has been designated by NATO as part of the British sector.
On Monday, British officers drove in armored vehicles to the edge
of Racak for ongoing informal talks with KLA commanders to
determine when the rebels would turn over the town to NATO
peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   Driving away from Racak, a reporter struck up a conversation in
Russian with the commander of a Serb army unit that had been caught
in a traffic jam while en route back to Yugoslavia in compliance
with the Yugoslav-NATO agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav officer smiled broadly and pressed a drink of the
fiery Yugoslav brandy called Rakia on the journalist.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing is all politics,'' the commander insisted when
asked about events at Racak. ``Serbian soldiers and NATO soldiers _
we can work together because we know how to follow orders.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
