<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4788 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-KNEE-INJURY-NYT &LR;      06-14 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-KNEE-INJURY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ACHILLES HEEL, IN THE KNEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By MARY DUFFY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last Thursday, 43 seconds into the New York Liberty's home
opening game, Rebecca Lobo jumped for a rebound, pivoted and fell
to the floor clutching her knee and screaming in pain. An
off-balance landing resulted in a torn anterior cruciate ligament,
an injury that will require surgery and months of rehabilitation.
For the Women's National Basketball Association star it means
sitting out the season.
</P>
<P>
   The same day researchers and physicians from around the country
gathered in the Hunt Valley of Maryland for a symposium on ACL
injuries and the female athlete, sponsored by the American Academy
of Orthopedic Surgeons, and earlier this month, the American
College of Sports Medicine presented a half-day workshop on the
topic at its annual conference. The Journal of Athletic Training
has devoted its current issue to exploring the potential risk of
such injuries and possible preventive measures.
</P>
<P>
   Why all this attention? Knee injuries are a serious problem for
female athletes. According to the National Collegiate Athletic
Association, women playing soccer and basketball suffer three to
five times as many ACL injuries as their male counterparts.
According to the American Orthopedic Society for Sports Medicine,
10,000 women experience debilitating knee injuries a year at the
college level; on the high school level, the number rises to
20,000. Soccer, basketball and volleyball, sports that involve
pivoting, cutting and jumping, pose the most risk.
</P>
<P>
   The anterior cruciate ligament controls the pivoting motion of
the knee. With the hamstring and quadriceps muscles _ back and
front of the thigh _ the ligament helps stabilize the joint. If the
muscles are not up to the task, when an athlete jumps or twists,
the ligament may bear more force that it can handle, resulting in a
tear.
</P>
<P>
   To withstand the twists and turns of aggressive sports,
hamstring muscles should be 60 percent to 70 percent as strong as
the quadriceps, said Dr. Frank Noyes, director of the Cincinnati
Sports Medicine and Orthopedic Center. In female athletes, the
ratio is actually 45 percent to 55 percent. Whether the difference
is cultural or anatomical, women tend to rely on their quadriceps
when jumping and pivoting, while men depend more on their
hamstrings. Since the hamstring muscles are more protective of the
ACL that muscular imbalance is considered a risk factor in knee
injuries, Noyes said.
</P>
<P>
   Some researchers speculate that women's wider hip-to-knee ratio
may be a factor in knee injuries. Other evidence suggests that at
certain times in a woman's menstrual cycle, hormones may cause her
ligaments and tendons to become more lax and more susceptible to
injury. Less early exposure to sports or less experience with
weight training may also make women more vulnerable to knee
injuries. The degree to which anatomical and hormonal differences
affect women's athletic development and likelihood of injuries
puzzles experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt that there are neuromuscular differences
between males and females,'' said Dr. Ed Wojtys, a professor of
surgery at the University of Michigan Medical School and team
physician for the university athletic department. ``Depending on
their sex,'' he said, ``athletes fire different muscles for the
same task. Women also tend to run, jump and land in a more upright
position than men.''
</P>
<P>
   While researchers are teasing out the hormonal, biomechanical
and cultural factors that cause this disparity in knee injuries,
Dr. Timothy Hewett and Dr. Thomas Lindenfeld and others at the
Cincinnati center, have shown that a preseason neuromuscular
training program can significantly reduce the number of injuries in
girls. They have developed a jump training and conditioning program
called Cincinnati Sportsmetrics, which is being adopted in hundreds
of high schools and colleges and is available by videotape. After
four players from the girls' championship high school basketball
team in Galesburg, Ill., tore their ACL's in 18 months, Ed Massey,
the coach, incorporated Sportsmetrics into his team's training
program.
</P>
<P>
   The Cincinnati researchers have shown that by strengthening the
hamstrings and quadriceps, landing in a crouched position after
jumping and learning to fire the hamstring muscles, female athletes
can reduce their knee injuries to a rate comparable to that of
males. They also improve their jumping ability by 10 percent, said
Lindenfeld, the orthopedic surgeon who conducted the research.
</P>
<P>
   In the four years the Galesburg basketball team has followed the
program, players have improved their strength and have become more
agile and confident in their jumping ability, Massey said. ``The
team has been free of knee injuries and has fewer stress
fractures,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts suggest conditioning programs tailored for girls
and women. It is not a matter of female athletes' being deficient
in any way, said Dr. Patty Freedson, graduate program director of
the department of exercise science at the University of
Massachusetts at Amherst. ``There should be a focus on the specific
goals and needs of women,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Woyjet: ``Women shouldn't accept ACL injuries as the price
they have to pay for being athletic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
