<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4789 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-MISCARRIAGE-NYT &LR;      06-14 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MISCARRIAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COMMON LINK IN FAILED PREGNANCIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By ERIC NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Refining the understanding of a crucial step in early pregnancy,
researchers have pinpointed the time frame in which a fertilized
egg needs to implant itself into the uterus.
</P>
<P>
   In a study of 221 healthy women who were trying to conceive,
researchers from the National Institutes of Health found that in
most successful cases, implantation occurred 8 to 10 days after the
women ovulated. Of perhaps more interest, they found that the later
the egg implanted itself, the greater the chance the pregnancy
would fail.
</P>
<P>
   The study, published in the current issue of The New England
Journal of Medicine, might influence the practices used at
infertility clinics that perform in vitro fertilization of fetal
transplants, experts said. It might also give pause to doctors
looking into ways to increase the window of time each month when
women with fertility problems can become pregnant, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Allen J. Wilcox, the principal author of the study and an
obstetric epidemiologist at the institutes, said the main
importance of the findings was the glimpse they provided into the
still little understood time when the newly fertilized egg attaches
itself to the lining of a woman's uterus. It then develops into an
embryo.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's been the the most unobserved step in pregnancy,''
Wilcox said of implantation.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was most struck by what appeared to be a strong link
between how late a fertilized egg attaches to the uterus and how
often the pregnancy has an early failure.
</P>
<P>
   Among the women studied, 82 percent had early failures when
implantation occurred more than 11 days after ovulation, when a
mature egg is released from an ovary. That was a failure rate
significantly higher than when eggs attached on the 11th day (52
percent), and more than three times as great as when they implanted
on the 10th day (26 percent). The rate of early pregnancy loss
through the 9th day after ovulation was 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   One theory, Wilcox said, is that a woman's body may reject a
late-implanting egg because it might not be healthy. The window of
time in which a uterus will accept an egg may thus have a specific
purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's the case, then we may want to be careful about any
attempt to expand that window artificially,'' Wilcox said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Joseph A. Hill, director of reproductive medicine at Brigham
and Women's Hospital in Boston, said the study added weight to the
theory that prospective mothers and fertilized eggs might
communicate with each other very early in the process, possibly by
sending messenger proteins to ``discuss'' things like where and
when to implant.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a growing body of evidence that suggests that there's
a cross-talk between the embryo and the mom,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the study was also valuable because it was done on women
with normal fertility. Until now, most of the implantation research
has involved women receiving in vitro fertilization.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, women who experience early pregnancy loss do not
know they were pregnant. The study was conducted by having the
patients provide urine samples every day for six months.
Researchers then studied the samples for the hormones indicating
fertilization and, later, implantation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-99 1634EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990614.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4792 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOSEMITE-MURDERS-HNS &LR;      06-14 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOSEMITE-MURDERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARGES IN YOSEMITE KILLINGS MAY BE MONTHS AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MODESTO, Calif. _ Even though the several men are in custody and
a key witness is talking, the FBI admits the homicide case of three
Yosemite tourists is so complicated that it could be months before
charges are filed.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, old friends and associates of Eugene ``Rufus'' Dykes
said they were stunned at reports that the 32-year-old convicted
felon from Modesto admitted to involvement in the kidnapping and
murder of three women sightseers in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see Rufus killing those girls,'' said Tommy, who asked
that his full name not be used. ``That doesn't seem like him. There
are a lot of things that wouldn't surprise me about him, but
killing some tourists like that is just not Rufus.''
</P>
<P>
   The friends and acquaintances all asked not to be identified in
print. They said they feared retribution from Dykes' associates and
harassment from investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no good that can come from saying you know Rufus,''
said another man, who said he grew up with Dykes. ``His name is
trouble around here.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI won't say what Dykes has told them about the abduction
and killings of Carol Sund, 42, of Eureka, Calif.; her daughter,
Juli, 15; and Silvina Pelosso, 16, a family friend from Argentina.
The three were on a trip to the Yosemite National Park in when they
disappeared in mid-February.
</P>
<P>
   Sources told the Modesto Bee newspaper that investigators are
frustrated by inconsistencies in statements Dykes made.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have had difficulty corroborating much of what Dykes
has told them, and his story apparently has changed several times
since his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Dykes was arrested March 5 during a parolee sweep in the small
community of Empire outside Modesto. He now is charged with being a
convicted felon in possession of drugs and a gun. He has prior
convictions for burglary, forgery and false imprisonment of a
17-year-old girl.
</P>
<P>
   The top FBI agent on the case and the Tuolumne County district
attorney both said last week that they believe the principal
players in the case are behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to build an airtight case,'' FBI Special Agent
Nick Rossi said. It is expected that the FBI will conclude its
investigation, then hand the case over to Tuolumne County
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities have interviewed more than 1,000 potential
witnesses in the investigation, focusing on a loose-knit group of
parolees in and around Modesto, many involved in the
methamphetamine trade in the mountain counties around Yosemite
National Park.
</P>
<P>
   But agents have been somewhat stymied.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're dealing with individuals in the crank trade or
circles, one of the byproducts generally is these people are not as
responsible or aware of details. We're not dealing with people who
have regular jobs and regular lives,'' said FBI Agent-in-Charge
James Maddock.
</P>
<P>
   Several acquaintances of Dykes said they were shocked when they
saw published reports that Dykes' girlfriend, Maria Ledbetter,
talked to investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Ledbetter told the Associated Press that ``I know in my heart he
was involved.'' She said she gave investigators Dykes' gun and
knife.
</P>
<P>
   Dykes and his half-brother, Michael ``Mick'' Larwick, 42, are
among a group of ex-cons with violent histories the FBI has been
scrutinizing since March.
</P>
<P>
   Larwick is a Modesto resident whose criminal record stretches
back to 1975 and includes convictions for the rape of a relative
while her children cowered nearby in a car, and separate incidents
of manslaughter, assault, drug possession and attempted escape.
</P>
<P>
   Since March 16, Larwick has been in the Stanislaus County jail
awaiting trial on charges of attempting to kill a police officer.
</P>
<P>
   Larwick has proclaimed his innocence in jailhouse interviews and
offered to submit to a lie detector test.
</P>
<P>
   None of those interviewed in Modesto on Sunday said they knew
Larwick very well. Many of them said they know two other Modesto
men whose names have been publicly linked to the investigation:
Jeffery Wayne Keeney, 32, and Kenneth Alan ``Soldier'' Stewart, 24.
</P>
<P>
   Keeney, who faces drug charges, was arrested March 26. Keeney
denied any involvement in the killings. Stewart was arrested June 7
and charged with attempted murder in an unrelated case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
