<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FITNESS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THERAPIES: A Fountain of Youth, in Music Class
</P>
<P>
   A new study has found that teaching healthy elderly people to
play music decreases their anxiety, depression and loneliness.
</P>
<P>
   The study, undertaken jointly by the universities of Miami,
South Florida, Kansas, Western Michigan, Michigan State and the
Karolinska Medical Institute in Sweden, examined 130 retired people
in an effort to link learning music with wellness. Sixty-one of the
retirees learned to play the organ over a period of two 10-week
semesters while 69 other participants did not.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers ranked the participants according to the Mental
Health Inventory Anxiety Scores, the Profile of Mood States
Depression/Dejection Scores and the UCLA loneliness scale before
and after the semesters.
</P>
<P>
   They noted a marked decrease in anxiety, depression and
loneliness among those retirees who were attending the music
classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Music is the oldest method of relaxation in the world,'' said
Mahendra Kumar, professor in the department of psychiatry and
behavioral sciences at the University of Miami School of Medicine
and one of the contributors to the study. ``We've studied the
effects of music on patients who suffer from dementia. Music
therapy seemed to help. We thought if healthy elderly people
learned music, they may not have as much depression, anxiety or
loneliness.''
</P>
<P>
   The researchers also took blood samples from the participants
before the first lesson and after the participants completed the
last lesson in order to monitor any changes in hormone levels that
may be associated with wellness. They found that elderly
participants who received group music lessons increased their
levels of human growth hormone (hGH).
</P>
<P>
   ``Some say this hormone is the source of eternal youth,'' Dr.
Kumar said. While there was no doubt that when the elderly
participants learned to play the organ hGH levels increased in
their bodies, there was debate over the effect this hormone had on
well being. Although the indications are positive, some researchers
say more research is needed
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Pauline Maki, a fellow at the National Institute on Aging,
said, ``We're far from being able to say that hGH is something you
could give to elderly people to enhance their well being because we
haven't established similar results in large-scale clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we can say we've found the fountain of youth, we have
to test the water.''
</P>
<P>
   _ALISHA BERGER
</P>
<P>
   NOSTRUMS: Poor Grades for Thigh-Reducing Creams
</P>
<P>
   The act of slathering on expensive thigh-reducing creams may
provide an upper body workout, but users should not expect to see
weight loss in their thighs, a new study reports.
</P>
<P>
   The research, presented recently at the annual American College
of Sports Medicine conference in Seattle, showed no significant
reduction in thigh circumference when overweight and normal-weight
women applied the creams for six weeks. Unlike previous research in
which the subjects, who were obese, also dieted and exercised, the
11 women in this small study were asked not to change their
exercise or eating routines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only did we find no difference in each volunteer's thighs
at the end, but the volunteers themselves said they could see and
feel no difference either,'' said Dr. Bonita Marks, assistant
professor of exercise and sport science at the University of North
Carolina at Chapel Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Research has shown that the active ingredient in thigh-reducing
creams, aminophylline, dissolves some fat cells. With that in mind,
manufacturers began putting it in creams.
</P>
<P>
   Colleen Peters, owner of Alchemy Health and Beauty Products in
Las Vegas, sells four ounces of a sculpturing cream for $19.95 and
contends that it works. ``I personally tried it and lost half an
inch in the thigh area,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   About $17 million worth of such firming cream products were sold
in the United States last year, according to NPD Beauty Trends,
which tracks sales of beauty products.
</P>
<P>
   -ALISA TANG
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SAFETY: When Children and Guns Live Together &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Gun owners who are parents tend to be more careful about storing
their weapons than gun owners without children _ but both groups
are more careless than they should be, according to a recently
published study.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1994 survey of 5,285 households by researchers from the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta, about
one-third reported having at least one firearm at home or in a car.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, whose results were published this month in the
Archives of Pediatric and Adolescent Medicine, found that 21
percent of the gun owners kept at least one firearm loaded and in
an unlocked setting. Thirty percent kept the guns unloaded and
locked up, and the rest fell somewhere in between.
</P>
<P>
   In households with children, 41 percent kept their weapons
unloaded and locked and out of reach, while 11 percent left them
loaded and unlocked.
</P>
<P>
   Guns rank high among hazards to youngsters in the United States,
the researchers wrote, citing previously unpublished C.D.C. figures
that list firearms as the second-leading cause of death to children
between 10 and 14, and the eighth-leading cause for those ages 1 to
4.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Elise Becher, an assistant professor of pediatrics and
health policy at the Mount Sinai School of Medicine in New York,
who did not take part in the study, said that previous research had
established that the presence of a gun raises the household's risk
of a death by homicide, suicide or accidental discharge. ``You
don't make your family safer by getting a gun to protect against
intruders,'' she said. ``You make your family safer by keeping any
gun you have locked in one place and the ammunition locked up
separately.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate recently passed, and the House will soon begin
considering, gun-control measures, including a requirement that
handguns be sold with trigger locks to reduce the risk of
accidents.
</P>
<P>
   The study's lead researcher, Dr. Gail Stennies, said the article
had been accepted for publication last fall and that its appearance
now was a coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stennies said she hoped the study would underscore the need
to treat gun injuries as a preventive health issue. ``We hope it
would be on the checklist of routine preventive messages, like
bicycle helmets, boat safety and vaccinations,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   _JOHN O'NEIL
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
