u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT &LR;      06-14 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Revenge of the Bugs
</P>
<P>
   There is a certain sense of satisfaction that comes from
plugging in the electric bug zapper on a hot summer evening, the
knowledge that every zzzzzzzzzttt! means one less fly to flit on
the potato salad, one less mosquito to feast on a forearm.
</P>
<P>
   But the bugs, it seems, may be getting their revenge _ going
out, if not in a blaze of glory, then at least in a shower of
microbes.
</P>
<P>
   That is the conclusion of a team of researchers at Kansas State
University, who studied what happens when an insect is electrocuted
in a bug zapper. In brief, the heat from the electrical charge
causes the insect to explode. It is not a pretty sight.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a particularly healthy one either, because the heat is
not enough to kill all of the bacteria and viruses on and in the
bug. So the result is a cloud of insect particles that, depending
on where the bug has been spending its time, could be more or less
contaminated. The researchers recommend that the zappers not be
used near food.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dusty Solar System &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The solar system could stand a good dusting. There are tiny
grains everywhere, many of them concentrated in the ring systems of
the larger planets.
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers have long thought that this dust is created by other
dust _ interplanetary particles that hit moons or other bodies in
the solar system at high speed, ejecting puffs of debris into
space. Now, measurements from the Galileo spacecraft orbiting
Jupiter have provided the first direct evidence of dust begetting
dust.
</P>
<P>
   The research, by scientists from Germany, Russia and the United
States, used data from a detector aboard the spacecraft taken as it
drew near Jupiter's largest moon, Ganymede. The instrument, kind of
a high-tech dust mop, measures the mass of grains as well as their
direction and speed.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists, who reported their findings in the journal
Nature, found that the source of the dust around Ganymede was the
moon itself. The data are also consistent with the dust being
created by high-speed impacts of other particles.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the dust forms a thin cloud around Ganymede, but some of
it is ejected at high enough speeds to escape the moon's gravity
completely, and is then drawn into Jupiter's ring system. The
researchers note that the planet's larger moons supply less dust
than the smaller ones, because the larger moons' stronger
gravitational fields allow fewer grains to escape.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Underwater Arsenic &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Hydrothermal vents, those fissures in the sea floor that spew
scalding water laden with minerals and chemicals, create some of
the most inhospitable environments anywhere. And among vents, few
could be worse than those in the shallow waters of Tutum Bay, off
Ambitle Island in Papua New Guinea, which produce the highest
concentrations of arsenic found in any marine setting.
</P>
<P>
   The vents pump about three pounds of arsenic into the small bay
every day. Since, as fans of murder mysteries know, arsenic is
highly toxic, it might be expected that marine life in the bay
would be adversely affected.
</P>
<P>
   But a study by scientists from the University of Ottawa and the
Geological Survey of Canada found that this was not the case. The
diversity and health of the coral reef at Tutum Bay is
indistinguishable from similar reefs that do not have hydrothermal
vents. The researchers found that coral skeletons and clam shells
did not even contain elevated levels of arsenic.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, who described their work in the journal
Environmental Science and Technology, determined that the arsenic
was controlled by dilution, and by incorporation into iron
compounds that precipitate out of the seawater when the fluid from
the vents mixes with seawater. The findings, they suggest, could
help in developing new methods to treat arsenic contamination in
other settings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-99 1642EDT &QL; 
