<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4805 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-YOGA-CHILDREN-NYT     06-14 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-YOGA-CHILDREN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARDLY OUT OF DIAPERS AND NOW INTO YOGA 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By RANDI HUTTER EPSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I was the oldest one in the exercise class by nearly
30 years, and I'm only 36. As a yoga novice, Jack, my 5-year-old,
was allowed to bring his mother along.
</P>
<P>
   Yoga for kids, I soon learned, is a burgeoning industry _ a
recent outgrowth of the latest adult trend. There are courses for
children and mommy-and-me yoga classes. There are books galore and
video tapes. We now own the video, ``E-i-E-i Yoga.'' It is of the
Barney ilk with farmer Yogi Oki Doki replacing the purple dinosaur.
</P>
<P>
   Instructors say that the increased flexibility and strength yoga
provides improve children's abilities in other sports. I was even
told about toddlers who, through yoga lessons, learn to take deep
breaths instead of throwing tantrums and kindergartners who put
themselves to sleep by imagining gardens. Teachers say yoga helps
pre-teen and teen-age girls feel comfortable with their bodies.
</P>
<P>
   I was skeptical but figured even if these claims were only
partly accurate, I had a lot to gain. I envisioned a calm, peaceful
household. After a few sessions, my children would live in peace
and serenity. My body-mind-connected children would take deep
breaths, do a yoga pose and learn to share.
</P>
<P>
   Jack and I started with a class just for children at Jivamukti,
a yoga studio in Manhattan. I was told that these kids-only classes
were more playful than courses with parents, which are geared
toward ``family bonding.'' Our class was in a large lavender room
with photographs of Indian yogis.
</P>
<P>
   Jack's enthusiasm plummeted as soon as he realized he was the
only boy and the only beginner in a class with five lithe, giggly,
blonde girls, ranging in age from about 6 to 9. Their mothers
either took classes for adults in nearby studios or waited in the
neighborhood until the class ended. As a first-timer, I was allowed
to stay and take the class with Jack. The teacher, Kate Donovan,
assured us that no level of fitness was necessary to do yoga. The
only requirement is comfortable clothing and bare feet to avoid
slipping.
</P>
<P>
   We sat in two rows facing each other, sitting with our legs in a
pretzel, as one instructor gave commands and the other helped us
get in proper form. ``We need a really cool thing to inspire us,''
Ms. Donovan said. ``Ganesh is powerful,'' she said, pointing to the
Indian god on her T-shirt. ``Whenever we think we have a problem,
we can think of Ganesh. We can also chant.''
</P>
<P>
   Next she told us to cup our hands over our ears and listen. That
sound of nothing is ``om.'' Jack giggled. One of the girls said she
chanted with her family at home.
</P>
<P>
   Then we started our poses, the Asanas. They are derived from
yogis' in India mimicking animals. That fact offered a twist for
children. We got on all fours, yelled, ``moo,'' we arched our backs
and ``meowed.'' There was also a ``downward dog'' pose, known as
``adho mukha svasana.'' We made our bodies into an upside-down
``V'' _ our legs straight, buttocks in the air and palms on the
ground. We arched our heads upward.
</P>
<P>
   We did a tree pose, also called ``virksasana.'' That was the
easiest one. We balanced on one leg, toes spread apart, and the
other leg bent so that foot would rest on our thigh. Then we
extended our arms, like branches, and faced our palms upward.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Donovan started slowly and then increased the pace. Our
classmates, ever so flexible, were an intimidating bunch. Jack took
his mat and dragged it far away from the girls. I started to regret
that I had lured him here. I realized quickly that I should have
brought Jack with one of his friends.
</P>
<P>
   After a few more animal poses, we did some deep breathing and
then headstands against the back wall. Then we lay on our backs
while Ms. Donovan told us a Hindi tale and gave each child a head
massage. Finally, we placed our palms together pointing upward and
chanted a final ``om.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack whispered, ``I'm not coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   As newcomers, we were sent home with the video, ``E-i-E-i
Yoga,'' which, surprisingly, Jack and his younger brother and
sister watch repeatedly. Though he says he will not go back to that
class, he does yoga poses around the house, lectures to his
siblings about its benefits (he has memorized the video) and even
asked me to take him to another class with school friends.
</P>
<P>
   My second yoga class was for parents and children at the Reebok
Club, also in Manhattan. Jack backed out so I brought my twin
3-year-olds, Martha and Joseph. It was quite a contrast to the
downtown class. The instructor was a sliver of a woman who played
the popular '70s cassette of Marlo Thomas singing ``Free to Be, You
and Me.'' We did a few poses that required two people and were told
to feel free to make up our own movements around the room.
</P>
<P>
   There were about four other girls, ranging in age from about 8
to 12, and their mothers. It seemed more like a stretching class
than yoga. Most of the participants had never done yoga before and
did not seem very interested. Maybe they were killing time before a
spinning class.
</P>
<P>
   We started the class sitting with with our legs in a pretzel,
palms facing upward. Then we did some basic poses, including
``downward dog.'' Then we did poses with our children. We sat on
the floor with our legs spread apart facing one another and holding
hands, rocking back and forth. During the free-form time, I just
could not get myself to frolic around the room like the instructor.
My children went right for the crayons and coloring books in my bag
and proceeded to color in the middle of a gym mat. I think they
were bored and so was I.
</P>
<P>
   After two classes and weeks of the yoga for kids video, I am
starting to become convinced that yoga can aid children physically
and emotionally. Mine have fun stretching and mimicking animals.
They try to make up their own poses. But my house with three yoga
kids is no calmer than in our pre-yoga days. But then, again, we
are just novices. There is still hope.
</P>
<P>
   Many yoga studios and some health clubs offer classes for
children or classes for parents and children, usually costing about
$10 a session. Having your child watch a video or read a book about
yoga before the class will acquaint them with poses.
</P>
<P>
   The Yoga Journal publishes a directory of teachers, available
for $5. Contact the Yoga Journal Book and Tape Source, 2054
University Avenue, Berkeley, Calif. 94704-1082; (800) 436-9642. You
can also choose from a number of books and videos for children,
including ``Yoga for Children,'' by Mary Stewart (Simon &AMP; Schuster,
1992) and the ``Children's Book of Yoga: Games and Exercises Mimic
Plants and Animals and Objects,'' by Thia Luby (Clear Light, 1998).
</P>
<P>
   Helpful tapes include ``E-i-E-i Yoga'' (Mystic Fire Video) at
(800) 292-9001 and ``Yoga Kids,'' which is available from the Book
and Tape Source.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
