<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SORE LOSERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It must be maddening to be a Republican in Congress
these days.
</P>
<P>
   GOP lawmakers' near-universal loathing of President Clinton
drives them to distraction.
</P>
<P>
   They agree on no principles or policies. Gun control? Chaos.
Social Security? Ditto. Budget priorities? Double ditto.
</P>
<P>
   What they have aplenty is pure petulance.
</P>
<P>
   Their only common bond is their unconcealed distrust of a
president they have been unable to destroy. What passes for a
governing philosophy is automatic opposition to anything Clinton is
for, no matter how meritorious.
</P>
<P>
   Their selfish reaction to the Serbian troop withdrawal from
Kosovo was shameful. They acted as though the success of NATO's
bombing campaign was a personal insult. Once again Clinton had
slipped through their fingers just as they were about to close
their hands around his throat.
</P>
<P>
   What sore losers. Throughout the crisis they had grumbled that
Clinton was going about things all wrong, calling it ``Clinton's
war'' and blaming him rather than Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic for the torture and destruction of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   They predicted Clinton would fold and NATO fly apart. They
didn't support the air strikes and they didn't want to send in
ground troops either. They didn't vote to finance the bombing until
it was practically over.
</P>
<P>
   They displayed little pity for the Kosovo refugees but groused
endlessly about NATO bombing errors that killed Serbian civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Donald Manzullo, R-Ill., was typical. After the Serbian
retreat began, he condemned Clinton for having ``destroyed a
country.'' Funny, we thought it was Milosevic that destroyed the
country with his campaign of ``ethnic cleansing'' by killing,
raping and driving Kosovars from their homeland. NATO airstrikes
did not trigger that campaign. Milosevic had been secretly working
up to it for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a humanitarian disaster,'' harrumphed Assistant Senate
Majority Leader Don Nickles, R-Okla. We know that. But we also know
it would have been worse had NATO not forced Milosevic to pay such
a heavy economic and political price that he finally gave in. We
were slow to move, and Milosevic held out longer than we had
anticipated, but we did stop the killing.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans never put forth a realistic alternative of their
own. They saw all sorts of problems but offered no good solutions.
They talked stupidly about making ever more diplomatic overtures
while the Kosovars were being slaughtered. ``Give peace a chance,''
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., whined long after it
was clear that Milosevic understood only force.
</P>
<P>
   They simply didn't want to have anything to do with the Balkans,
regardless of the consequences for the inhabitants and the rest of
Europe. Foreign policy is Clinton's responsibility, and by golly
they weren't going to give him a hand. So much for the good old
days when partisanship ended at the water's edge.
</P>
<P>
   As the cease-fire was reached, House Republicans wanted to cut
off funding for peacekeeping forces in Kosovo by Oct. 1, abandoning
the refugees to their cruel fate just to spite Clinton. But after
the president sent an urgent letter, common sense prevailed and the
proposal was hastily killed.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton deserves credit here for standing tall and doing the
right thing, however messy and inept the handling of it. His
stomach for military fire was put to the test, and he passed. ``The
dangers of acting,'' he had said, ``are far outweighed by the
dangers of not acting.'' Despite the GOP's carping, he did not
fold.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who had backed the NATO mission, was
one of few Republicans to concede that Clinton had won a victory.
So was Senate Armed Services Committee Chairman John Warner, R-Va.,
who credited Clinton with holding NATO together and getting
European leaders to promise they would bear the major cost of
rebuilding Kosovo. Warner predicted that NATO's toughness will
contribute to stability in Europe and ``deter anyone else from
trying to duplicate what Milosevic did.''
</P>
<P>
   But their voices were drowned out by all the Republican
sourpusses. What they think they gain politically by refusing to
acknowledge the obvious is a puzzlement. They look cranky,
small-minded and unpatriotic.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the 2000 GOP presidential
frontrunner, tried to diminish Clinton's success by raising new
questions he knows perfectly well the president cannot answer at
this point. ``We need to hear from him when the troops will be
coming home,'' Bush said. If that is the new GOP line, it won't
sell. Americans will come home when the job is done, and no one can
say now how long that will take.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton himself is being cautious about his victory because
there is much left to be done to restore decent living conditions
and sanity to the Balkans. Besides, Milosevic remains in power
although he is now an indicted war criminal.
</P>
<P>
   But unless some dramatic disaster intervenes, Kosovo will not be
the political burden for Clinton and Vice President Al Gore that
the Republicans had hoped. It may even be a plus as the memory
fades of the tactical mistakes and the wisdom of the strategic
policy of a new internationalism sinks in.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at 202-298-6920 and, by e-mail,
at means(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
