<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4807 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-LIGHT-CHAOS-NYT &LR;      06-14 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-LIGHT-CHAOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SHINY GADGET CAPTURES CHAOS IN LIGHT BEAMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md.)  (nk) 
 By MALCOLM W. BROWNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The apparatus is simple enough for a child to construct, and the
kaleidoscopic images it generates fascinate onlookers with their
dazzling complexity. But this is not a toy; it is a tool for
studying the effects of chaos on light beams.
</P>
<P>
   The device, assembled by three physicists at the University of
Maryland, is little more than a stack of four reflective balls
similar to Christmas tree ornaments. In their study of stacked
balls, published recently in the journal Nature, Dr. Edward Ott,
Dr. James A. Yorke and a graduate student, David Sweet, described
an experiment with their shiny gadget as ``a simple laboratory
demonstration of an interesting type of fractal geometry.''
</P>
<P>
   When a light beam enters the array of balls, its image is
chopped into shards that appear to copy themselves in an infinite
progression of steps to ever smaller scales.
</P>
<P>
   Fractal geometry is a field of mathematics founded in 1975 by
Dr. Benoit Mandelbrot. Since then, many mathematicians and
scientists have professed to see fractal patterns almost everywhere
in nature.
</P>
<P>
   A fractal is a pattern that is irregular, but self-similar at
all size scales; for example, a small patch of ground may have the
same general appearance as a larger patch or even a huge area seen
from high above. Mountain ranges, in which small piles of rocks may
look like diminutive versions of the peaks towering above them, are
often cited as examples of fractals in nature.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Maryland fractal generator consists of four
mirrored balls, each of them one foot in diameter. (However, Ott
said in an interview, the original version was assembled from
ordinary Christmas-tree decorations.)
</P>
<P>
   Three of the balls are placed in a triangular pattern on a flat
surface, each one touching the other two. A fourth ball is placed
on top, in contact with the first three, making a simple pyramid.
</P>
<P>
   The ``inner chamber'' bounded by the balls was specified by the
scientists as a tetrahedron (a solid with four sides, each an
equilateral triangle) defined by imaginary straight lines between
the centers of all four balls. When a flashlight with a
high-intensity bulb is aimed from the proper direction at one of
the faces of this imaginary tetrahedron, the light is reflected by
all four balls, and a viewer looking into the tetrahedron sees a
spectacular fractal light pattern.
</P>
<P>
   To improve contrast between the shards making up the fractal
image, the physicists assembled the array on top of a sheet of
white paper lighted from beneath. Blue paper was then placed
against one side of the pyramid of stacked balls and red paper
against a second side. The red and blue paper was illuminated by
reflections of the light coming up through the white paper. By
turning off the laboratory lights, the remaining side of the
tetrahedron produced black reflections, giving the resulting
fractal patterns a mixture of four colors _ red, blue, white and
black.
</P>
<P>
   A viewer (or camera) looking into the black face was then
treated to a beautiful fractal array, in which slivers of color
appeared in ever receding patterns, created by the almost endless
reflective bounces light undergoes inside the chamber bounded by
the four balls.
</P>
<P>
   The image captured by a camera exhibits many boundaries between
different colors, like those between states on a map, Ott said. But
in the fractal pattern created by the four balls, he said, a tiny
circle placed astride any boundary between colors will always
contain all four colors, however small the circle is drawn.
</P>
<P>
   In both experiments and computer simulations, it is possible to
calculate the complicated paths that light beams take as they
bounce among the four silvered balls. But beyond a certain huge
number of reflections, Ott said, it becomes impossible to predict
the path the light will take.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the beam becomes a victim of chaos, and its path
can be computed again only if it chances to leave the trap.
</P>
<P>
   Chaotic scattering is a subject that interests topologists,
mathematicians specializing in the nature of shapes. But the
mathematics, Sweet said, apply not only to topology theory but to
chemical reactions, celestial mechanics, fluid flow and quantum
cosmology, among other fields.
</P>
<P>
   One of the objects of their project, Ott said, is to compare
details of computer simulations of light paths with actual
laboratory experiments. The team intends to experiment with other
reflective systems, including a tube with a square, mirrored
interior containing a reflective ellipsoid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
