<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4811 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-0615-CO     06-14 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-0615-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ALBRIGHT, COHEN SEEK TO END KOSOVO STANDOFF WITH RUSSIA
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-MEN; KOSOVO-RACAK; KOSOVO-RENEWAL.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Defense Secretary William Cohen and Secretary of State
Madeline Albright will meet with Russian counterparts in coming
days to attempt to resolve the dispute over Russia's role in the
NATO-led peacekeeping campaign in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   As a small but politically significant contingent of Russian
troops continued to maintain control of the Pristina airport,
President Clinton and Russian President Boris Yeltsin spoke by
telephone for the second day in a row about the impasse over
Russia's role.
</P>
<P>
   But with no end in sight to the impasse, NATO generals
downplayed the significance of the Russian military presence and
decided not to deploy British and French troops at the airport
occupied by the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin, asserting that it played a significant part in
brokering an end to the war and the withdrawal of Serb forces from
the Kosovo province, wants a more prominent peacekeeping role not
bound by the command structure of NATO. Russia, a traditional ally
of the Serbs and Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, wants its
troops to patrol a separate enclave of Kosovo, in addition to the
five that have been divided between the NATO forces of the United
States, Britain, Germany, France and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Russia must have ``a considerable role in the political
resolution of the Kosovo conflict, including the international
peacekeeping operation under the U.N. aegis,'' Prime Minister
Sergei Stepashin told a security council meeting called to discuss
the standoff with NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Albright told reporters at the White House that she and Cohen
would travel to Helsinki, Finland, ``in the next few days'' for
meetings with Russian Defense Minister Marshal Igor Sergeyev and
Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said she and Cohen would seek to ``work out the
longer-term issues about the participation of Russians'' in the
peacekeeping mission in Kosovo, known as KFOR.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott left Moscow on Sunday
after three days of unsuccessful talks.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin spoke with Vice President Al Gore. No details of the
conversation were available.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian force of about 200 troops, which had been on
peacekeeping duty in Bosnia, entered Kosovo early Saturday before
the first NATO troops and took control of the small airport in
Pristina, the provincial capital.
</P>
<P>
   Russian news media also reported that Yeltsin and his generals
took the decision without informing his defense and foreign
ministers. Nor did he consult Viktor Chernomyrdin, presidential
aspirant and special Russian envoy to the Balkans who helped
negotiate an end to the war over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to sending a signal to the West about Russia's
desire to play a prominent role in the Balkans, a region Moscow
once dominated during the Soviet era, the move was widely viewed in
Moscow as a domestic power play by Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian president, dogged by illness and fading political
power as he enters the final year of his second term as president,
sought to remind Russia's political circles that he is in charge
and maintains close ties to the country's military command
structure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeltsin meant to explain who is the master in the house,'' the
newspaper Noviya Gazeta wrote on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian Defense Ministry expressed concern Monday that the
NATO peacekeepers in Kosovo were not disarming members of the
Kosovo Liberation Army, the ITAR-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin complained to Clinton about KLA threats against Russian
troops and continuing ``provocations'' that were causing Serbs to
flee the province. He said this threatened to unravel the whole
process of regulating the crisis, his press service said.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has about 10,000 troops, including airborne and special
forces units, standing by at air bases to travel to Kosovo to join
the peacekeeping mission. But the troops will not move until a
political decision is reached to define Russia's role, according to
the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is unclear whether Russia could afford to supply and
maintain a large peacekeeping contingent under its current budget
woes. Russia is currently negotiating with the West for financial
assistance to help it recover from an ongoing economic crisis that
hit last August.
</P>
<P>
   ``The generals are breaking their lances over the question of
whether there will be a separate zone of responsibility for the
Russian contingent. But at the same time, the Defense Ministry has
no money for the maintenance of the contingent in Kosovo. This
means that, in addition to asserting their right to play the
decisive role in the peacekeeping, we have to ask the aggressors
for money,'' Sevodnya newspaper wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
