<SLUG> BC-JERKY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN'T GET ENOUGH JERKY? THERE IS A CURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESA, Ariz. _ Codee Hayes, 9, doesn't invite her little friends
over for tea parties.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the girls like to make up a fresh batch of beef jerky,
discussing the latest trends in Barbie while the family oven slowly
dries meat into a succulent snack.
</P>
<P>
   Why go out for jerky when you can make it at home?
</P>
<P>
   That's what Codee's father, Mike, thought when his son, Casey,
24, became overwhelmed with orders for wild-game jerky at his meat
processing plant in Flagstaff, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes' wife, Cathy, began to help out as Casey fell behind in
production during last fall's elk season. The plant does custom
butchering for hunters who bag deer, elk, buffalo and even the odd
zebra and want it turned into steaks, chops, sausages and salami.
</P>
<P>
   And jerky.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is so much demand for jerky, he couldn't keep up with
production,'' says Hayes, a retired detective sergeant for the Mesa
Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   In stores, good beef jerky can cost as much as $2 an ounce,
Hayes says. Now he and his wife have started packaging the
seasonings and curing ingredients to turn 25 pounds of raw meat
into jerky for a fraction of that cost.
</P>
<P>
   Made from commercially manufactured spices, Jerky At Home comes
as a kit _ a bag of spices and a bag of cure packed in a box
suitable for gift-giving. It is sold at $13.95 a pack by mail with
no additional cost for postage and handling.
</P>
<P>
   The price is strictly an introductory offer, Hayes says. Once
the company starts rolling, the price will increase.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes touts the simplicity of his recipe. A lean cut of meat,
such as boneless round or London broil, is cut into strips. Any
length will do, but the strips must be one-quarter inch thick for
optimum results.
</P>
<P>
   Seasonings are sprinkled on both sides of the strips. The cure,
which is made of sodium nitrate, can be used to preserve the jerky.
Jerky that will be eaten within a few days need not be cured.
</P>
<P>
   Cured meat could last almost indefinitely, Hayes says, or
``until the mice eat it.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the meat has been seasoned and refrigerated overnight, it
goes into a warm oven, not more than 200 degrees, spread out on the
metal rack. Drying will take about four hours in a convection oven,
six to eight hours in a regular oven.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so simple. It's effortless,'' Hayes says. ``The hardest
part of making this jerky is parking in the parking lot of the
grocery store.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayes makes frequent batches to keep on hand when friends stop
by. He doesn't know how long it stays fresh. It's eaten too fast to
find out.
</P>
<P>
   Intense flavor is what makes the product so good, he says. Jerky
At Home comes in five varieties: regular, Cajun, pepper, teriyaki
and hot teriyaki. The spicy pepper flavor is his favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Made from lean meat, jerky is also a more healthful snack than
cookies and candy, Hayes says. It can be made from almost any kind
of meat, including beef, game and turkey. Hayes, a recreational
fisherman, once made jerky from striped bass. It wasn't bad, he
says, but he hasn't been tempted to try fish jerky again.
</P>
<P>
   His son has made jerky from caribou, bear and a zebra one hunter
brought in.
</P>
<P>
   Pork should not be used, because the meat is not cooked at a
high enough temperature to kill trichinosis, a disease caused by a
tiny nematode worm.
</P>
<P>
   Rattlesnake? Too small. Too dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Beef is best, Hayes says, and the leaner the meat, the better
the jerky.
</P>
<P>
   Jerky At Home can be ordered via the Internet by logging onto
www.jerkyathome.com or by writing to M&AMP;C Hayes Enterprises Inc. at
P.O. Box 22067, Mesa, AZ 85277-2067.
</P>
<P>
   Jerky's reputation as being tasty but tough need not intimidate
customers who no longer have their own teeth, Hayes says.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can sit there and gum it,'' he promises denture wearers.
``Eventually, it will dissolve.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
