<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARKINSON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPLANT TRANSFORMS PARKINSON'S SUFFERERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JODIE SNYDER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - When she gets married this fall, Paige Bremer wants to
release butterflies at the ceremony to remind her friends and
family of the power of change.
</P>
<P>
   With a tiny device placed inside her brain, Bremer is undergoing
a transformation of her own as her body's tremors and rigidity from
Parkinson's disease are electrically lulled into calmness.
</P>
<P>
   Bremer, 31, is the first Arizonan to have a stimulator implanted
4 inches deep into her brain to control her body's movements.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has made all the difference in my life,'' said Bremer,
who is no longer physically exhausted by trying to fight her body's
errant movements.
</P>
<P>
   Bremer, of Scottsdale, underwent surgery in early May at Barrow
Neurological Institute. Last week, she went in for a checkup.
</P>
<P>
   But she already knew how much she had improved.
</P>
<P>
   She recently hiked five miles near Carefree, Ariz. It was the
first time in 18 months that she had been able to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had done that before, I would have been physically
exhausted for days,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can definitely say that it is worth the risk. Anything that
helps give you control back is worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bremer is used to being at the forefront. Parkinson's affects
500,000 Americans but only a handful of people younger than 30.
</P>
<P>
   The muscle-control disorder is caused when the brain doesn't
produce a chemical called dopamine. Without it, the brain sends out
jumbled messages, causing the body to have tremors, rigidity, slow
movement and balance problems.
</P>
<P>
   Bremer remembers attending one of her first Parkinson's support
groups and being asked if she was there for her grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   At first, even she had a hard time believing it herself. At 21
years old, while she was attending Northern Arizona University in
Flagstaff, her left hand started to shake. Bremer convinced herself
it wasn't important. She continued working, hiking, rock-climbing,
even though her hands shook and her feet dragged.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until three years later, when her family stepped in,
that she finally went to a doctor and was told she has Parkinson's.
</P>
<P>
   Bremer was put on medication that began to supply her body with
dopamine. Eventually, side effects from the drug caused her body to
have different kinds of uncontrollable movements.
</P>
<P>
   Bremer's condition worsened. It took her 20 minutes to pull her
hair back into a ponytail. She couldn't cut her own food and found
it excruciatingly difficult to open a can of soda.
</P>
<P>
   During her exams, her neurologist, Dr. Mark Stacy, would conduct
a ``pull test'' in which he would tug on her shoulders. It only
took a mere touch to throw Bremer off balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got to be so sad we didn't even do the test anymore,''
Stacy said.
</P>
<P>
   Stacy, who is the director of the Muhammad Ali Parkinson
Research Center at Barrow, told Bremer about the possibility of
implanting electrodes into her brain _ in essence a brain
pacemaker.
</P>
<P>
   Barrow surgeons had already performed about 35 operations,
implanting the device into the thalamus, which acts as a relay
center for movement.
</P>
<P>
   The thalamic implant was developed in Europe when surgeons
realized they already knew which part of the brain controlled
movement because they operated on it to minimize tremors. Instead
of cutting that piece of the brain, why not figure out a way to
permanently stimulate it?
</P>
<P>
   But Stacy wanted to go deeper into the brain _ about one-half
inch deeper into the subthalamus, an even more specialized area for
movement. Going deeper would help Bremer with her rigidity and
movement problems as well as her tremors, Stacy told her.
</P>
<P>
   Either surgery would have its drawbacks. The implant in her
brain would be connected by a thin wire to a pacemaker about 1.5
inches wide and 2 inches long implanteded near her collarbone. The
connecting wire would run along the side of her face, behind her
ear and down her neck. Bremer would have to turn the device off and
on by waving a magnet over her chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of mechanics to fool around with,'' Stacy said.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike a thalamotomy _ a procedure involving burning out of
brain cells that was performed on actor Michael J. Fox to control
his Parkinson's _ the implants can be reversed. They can be easily
removed without hurting the brain.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Stacy's cautions, Bremer wasn't scared off by the
newness of the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, Bremer said, she decided to face her diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   Once, a counselor told her to lie about her physical
difficulties if she didn't want to explain them to strangers.
Forget that, Bremer said. She didn't have anything to apologize
about.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning of the operation, doctors took an MRI _ a
snapshot of Bremer's brain in action _ locating the exact spot for
the implant.
</P>
<P>
   Then they fitted Bremer with a ``halo,'' a structural device to
prevent her head from moving. The halo was attached by screwing the
frame against her skull.
</P>
<P>
   Next, surgeons drilled a hole into her skull, exposing the top
of her brain. Since there are no sensory nerves inside the brain,
Bremer couldn't really feel anything.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the hole, surgeons implanted a four-headed device, with
each head being about one-eighth-inch wide.
</P>
<P>
   Bremer was fully awake so the doctors could determine whether
the high-tech version of blind-man's buff in the brain was working.
When the electrode was properly placed, doctors told her, she'd
know it.
</P>
<P>
   Bremer was awake during the entire surgery. As they were
inserting probes inside her brain, Bremer said she could
immediately feel tingly, a fuzzy warmth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very good tingle,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After the implant, surgeons turned off the operating-room lights
to get a better look at the monitor measuring the brain activity _
similar to turning off the lights in order to see the television
better.
</P>
<P>
   In the darkness, Bremer could hear the ``music'' inside her head
better. Putting in the electrode was like putting a needle into the
groove of a record, Stacy said. The electrodes read the electronic
discharges made by brain cells and turned them into sound.
</P>
<P>
   For Bremer, hearing her brain cells fire was like hearing
``thunderstorms when you are standing outside.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was that loud.''
</P>
<P>
   Listening to her brain in action was thrilling, but the bigger
excitement came three days later when Bremer returned to Barrow to
have the pacemaker adjusted.
</P>
<P>
   Stacy and other physicians dialed into the frequency of the
devices inside Bremer, trying to figure out which level of
electrical stimulation would block the signals that cause the
shaking and rigidity.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Bremer's hands showed no sign of improvement. Her
engagement ring clattered against the wooden arm of her chair; her
Parkinson's seemed to be barely affected. But slowly, subtly over
20 minutes, her hands became more steady and less rigid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was such an awesome feeling. This tingly feeling happens
and you look down and everything is so much more controlled,''
Bremer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't imagine how good it feels.''
</P>
<P>
   The device's manufacturer, Medtronic, which is based in
Minnesota but has operations in Tempe, wants to see if it can be
used to treat epilepsy and other brain disorders.
</P>
<P>
   Stacy, who says he is delighted with Bremer's progress, plans to
test the device on patients with dystonia, a rare muscle disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Another piece of good news: insurance carriers, such as Bremer's
group, CIGNA Healthcare of Arizona, are willing to pay for the
$30,000 to $50,000 implant. Only Medicare is dragging its feet on
the covering the procedure, Stacy said.
</P>
<P>
   Bremer is beaming after the operation. But her experience with
Parkinson's has taught her there are more important things inside
her than mechanical devices. Living with the disorder has made her
appreciate others, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lot from this. God only gives you as much as you
can handle.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Jodie Snyder can be reached at jodie.snyder(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
