<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY WOMAN CAN'T SAVE SISTER FROM LIFE ON STREETS OF FORT
WORTH
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: The names in this story have been changed for reasons of
privacy.) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARY ROGERS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ She crumples the cigarette package in her
tiny fist and refuses to sit down. Her hair is a tumble of dark
ringlets and her eyes are clear and black, but troubled _ guarded.
She stares straight ahead, often ignoring my questions, sometimes
giving me a patronizing smile, occasionally telling a transparent
lie.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time she stands very still, daring me to trespass
into her secret life. I think of a wounded deer ready to run at the
slightest movement. I hold my breath, willing her to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``May I be dismissed?'' she asks.
</P>
<P>
   She might have been a college coed in olive-green thigh-high
jumper and brown hiking boots. She certainly doesn't look 34. It is
easy to see that once she was a pretty little girl with round, dark
eyes and a shy smile.
</P>
<P>
   She is pretty now; but she wears paranoia like a stained
overcoat.
</P>
<P>
   Her oldest sister, Alicia Martin, of Freehold, N.J., remembers
that when Amy was small, she liked ruffles and bows in her hair and
tea parties with her dolls.
</P>
<P>
   She was quieter than her two sisters. They thought she might
have been their mother's favorite child. Maybe she was only the
child who needed a mother's love the most, Martin says now.
</P>
<P>
   Once Amy was a college student, then a glowing bride, a happy
romantic who could brave any world for love's sake. She kept a
spotless house and became an excellent cook.
</P>
<P>
   So how did Amy end up homeless in a land of abundance? For each
of the millions of homeless Americans who drift across the land
like sand driven before a hot wind there is a friend, a neighbor or
a onetime business colleague who has wondered what went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a family that frets and cries and carries the
stigma of homelessness. No one is proud to say their parent, their
sibling, their child is on the street _ and so they don't.
</P>
<P>
   Martin doesn't ask why her sister is homeless. She doesn't
wonder how this happened. She is matter-of-fact and no-nonsense.
She never panders. She is frustrated and disappointed and sometimes
angry with her sister, but she is a ferocious advocate for family
unity and she won't let Amy go.
</P>
<P>
   Reluctantly, Martin, 47, agrees to tell her story in hopes that
it will dispel some of the myths about homelessness and strip away
some of the guilt families feel. She knows that for the homeless
there is no safety net, no safe harbor _ and sometimes no escape.
</P>
<P>
   SPLINTERED FAMILY: When Amy was 24, she had a baby boy, Johnny,
a beautiful child who gurgled and cooed. Later she had a daughter
and three years ago another son, but she doesn't read to them or
kiss away their hurts.
</P>
<P>
   She's never there when they run a fever or need to be corrected.
The last three years must be like a confused watercolor for her,
with no hard edges, no resemblance of truth. Amy can't remember
that Johnny is 10. She says he is 7.
</P>
<P>
   That's how old he was three years ago when they showed up
together at the Presbyterian Night Shelter just east of Fort
Worth's central business district. Night Shelter director John
Suggs remembers that in less than a month, Amy brought all three of
her children to the shelter, and her hold on reality was slipping.
</P>
<P>
   Now she is adrift and bewildered, so disconnected that she can't
maintain any relationship for long _ and still her sister won't let
her go.
</P>
<P>
   The Martins have no children of their own and have welcomed
Johnny into their home. They would like to keep all the children
together, she says, but the court awarded custody of Johnny's
half-sister and half-brother to their father. Martin shares legal
custody of Johnny with Amy, who is her half-sister.
</P>
<P>
   Determined that Johnny and his siblings won't grow up strangers,
the Martins have all the kids at their New Jersey home on holidays
and summer vacation and put them together in hotel rooms on quick
visits to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Martin sees to it that Johnny writes to his mother at least once
each week. He faxes the letters to the Presbyterian Night Shelter.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our family,'' Martin declares. ``In this case, mental
illness is part of the deal. My sister is just as sick as if she
had cancer. There's no secret about it. It's the secret that
creates the shame, so we are very open about all of it. Johnny has
nothing to be ashamed of,'' she says. The boy joins her on a couch
in an Arlington hotel lobby. She puts her arm around him and pulls
him close. He smiles.
</P>
<P>
   It is plain that Martin loves Johnny and that the affection is
returned _ but she is careful not to call him ``son.'' She
introduces him as her nephew.
</P>
<P>
   She says Johnny is strong enough to handle the truth: She is not
his mother. His mother is homeless and mentally ill and getting
more troubled by the day. It is better for Johnny to live in New
Jersey, but he cannot _ must not _ forsake his mother.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
