<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDATED: MARLISE SIMONS 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Confrontation With the Pope
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II was back in his native Poland again, this time
to focus attention on the 20th-century martyrdom of Christians and
underline the broad themes of his papacy.
</P>
<P>
   The visit took a bizarre turn when the chief rabbi of Poland,
Pinchas Monachem Joskowicz, introduced himself on a receiving line
and addressed the pope directly, saying: ``I have a favor to ask
Mr. Pope'' _ to seek to remove a cross at the walls of Auschwitz.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal, broadcast live on Polish television, shocked many
Polish viewers and embarrassed leaders of Poland's Jewish
community, who said the setting was inappropriate and the form of
address scandalous.
</P>
<P>
   Their fear was that the incident would undermine their own more
diplomatic efforts to find a compromise over the visibility of the
cross at a site of great Jewish suffering. It was put up to
commemorate the pope's 1979 visit to Auschwitz, and as a memorial
to Christian victims of the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   How 'Bout Those Cubs, er, Yanks?
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton took her most decisive step yet toward
running for the Senate from New York, declaring her lifelong
allegiance to the Bronx Bombers. At a White House ceremony honoring
the 1998 World Series champs, she got a Yankees cap that she tugged
over her forehead as she posed with the team.
</P>
<P>
   In this initial skirmishing over the Senate seat, Mrs. Clinton's
declaration amounted to a Bronx cheer to New York City Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, her likely rival and a diehard Yankees fan.
</P>
<P>
   The move raised questions about Mrs. Clinton's sense of loyalty,
since she was born and bred in Chicago and had worn her love for
the Cubs on her sleeve.
</P>
<P>
   No problem, Mrs. Clinton said. Because the Cubs were in the
National League, she has needed an American League team to root for
too.
</P>
<P>
   Play ball!
</P>
<P>
   _ KATHARINE Q. SEELYE
</P>
<P>
   Goodbye, TV. Hello, Net
</P>
<P>
   When Lou Dobbs, whose name is synonymous with televised
financial news from his 15 years anchoring CNN's ``Moneyline'' and
his founding of the CNNfn network, resigned to join an Internet
start-up called Space.com, his colleagues were baffled.
</P>
<P>
   Some said he had tired of ego-clashing with other top executives
at CNN. Some said he saw the money some Web entrepreneurs were
making, and wanted his chance to make a mint.
</P>
<P>
   Overlooked, Dobbs said, was a simpler notion: He is a space nut.
</P>
<P>
   He is also fully Net-savvy, having helped create CNNfn.com, the
leading business-news Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Dobbs denied interest in another television job, saying, ``My
full commitment is to the launch of Space.com on July 20 and to the
operation of the best Internet site on space.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
</TEXT>
