<HEADER>
A4888 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HYMAN-MENTAL-HEALTH-2     06-14 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HYMAN-MENTAL-HEALTH-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIRELESS, OUTSPOKEN AND ATYPICAL, MENTAL HEALTH CHIEF ROCKS THE
BOAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  (ms) 
 By ERICA GOODE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If, as social scientists sometimes insist, the best predictor of
future behavior is past behavior, then Dr. Steven Hyman was an
unlikely candidate when the National Institute of Mental Health was
searching for a director three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Other psychiatrists who had filled that post were clinical
psychiatrists. But Hyman, though he saw patients one morning a
week, was a bench scientist at heart, at home with pipette and
petri dish, deeply immersed in the molecular underpinnings of
addiction and mood disorders. And he was only 43, much younger than
previous directors.
</P>
<P>
   There were other anomalies. He had little administrative
experience. The interdisciplinary Mind, Brain and Behavior program
he ran at Harvard University could hardly compare to a government
agency with a budget close to $900 million. Nor did he walk and
talk much like a Washington bureaucrat. Bearded, genial and often
missing a tie, he answered direct questions directly, thrived on
intellectual argument, could discourse as fluently upon Descartes
as upon dopamine receptors, and he had an alarming habit of
speaking his mind, even when what he had to say was unpopular.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it was these attributes that convinced Dr. Harold E. Varmus,
director of the National Institutes of Health, that Hyman was the
person for job, though some doubted the wisdom of the appointment.
</P>
<P>
   A revolution was taking place in the neurosciences, advances in
genetics and technologies like PET and MRI scanning offering
unparalleled opportunities for understanding the workings of the
human brain. But psychiatry, Varmus felt, had been slow to take
advantage of these new tools. The mental health institute was
trailing behind when, as the nation's major underwriter of research
on mental illness, it should have been leading the way.
</P>
<P>
   What was needed, he thought, was a leader who was younger, in
touch with the cutting edge of molecular science, someone who could
bring together mind and brain and had a strong commitment to public
health. ``I was searching for somebody out of the ordinary,''
Varmus said. ``Steve was extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward: it is close to 90 degrees in the director's
office. The ventilation system in the institute's shiny new
headquarters still does not work properly. But Hyman does not seem
to notice.
</P>
<P>
   He has just emerged from a meeting and will soon run to a job
candidate's colloquium, followed by more meetings and two precious,
late afternoon hours spent in his lab. An official dinner, the
latest in an endless series, means it will be late when he finally
goes home to his family. His staff says that he seems tireless:
that they are used to receiving e-mails at three in the morning,
that he recently gave a lecture an hour after breaking his leg on
the ski slopes. ``Nobody was surprised,'' said David Shore, the
institute's associate director of clinical research. ``Nothing
stops him.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years into his tenure, there are many who believe Hyman
has proved the perfect antidote to a flagging institute, exerting
strong leadership at a time when mental health is attracting
unprecedented public attention. At the White House Conference on
Mental Health last week, President Clinton announced the start of a
$7.3 million institute study of the prevalence and severity of
mental disorders in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Hyman's supporters use terms like ``tough but fair'' to describe
him. They credit him with raising the scientific bar for research,
taking strong stands on issues like psychiatric research ethics,
serving as an eloquent ambassador on Capitol Hill, building bridges
between basic scientists and clinical researchers, and extending a
welcoming hand to advocacy groups, like the National Alliance for
the Mentally Ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve has been refreshingly open and available, not only
accepting critical feedback but actually looking for it,'' said
Laurie Flynn, executive director of the alliance. ``I would not
have expected this from someone who was a classic bench scientist.
He has stepped up to the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   He has also irritated more than a few people in the process.
Some longtime researchers have been encouraged to seek work
elsewhere. Well-known investigators who once had their grant
applications rubber stamped now find they must actively defend the
importance of their work. ``It's not enough with Steve to say `Oh,
these people are doing cutting-edge research and we've been funding
them for 20 years, so let's fund them,''' said one institute
official.
</P>
<P>
   Even close colleagues are not immune. Charles Nemeroff, chairman
of psychiatry at Emory University School of Medicine and a member
of the institute's National Advisory Mental Health Council, who
supports Hyman, recalled a grant application he submitted last
year. ``I'm as close to him as anybody,'' Nemeroff said, ``and he
looked me right in the eye and said, `We're not going to fund
this.'''
</P>
<P>
   Hyman's critics are happy to list their complaints, though few
will do so on the record. They assert that his conception of
psychiatry is too narrow, limited to molecular genetics on one hand
and ``cookie cutter'' clinical drug trials on the other. That he
has dismantled the institute's internal research program. They
think that when advocacy groups criticized the ethics of studies
involving human subjects, he should have defended the field and its
researchers instead of halting 29 studies and establishing a
Federal committee to oversee all experimental protocols. ``Why is
it that only NIMH is putting in this extra level of bureaucratic
review?'' asked Dr. Donald Klein, director of research at New York
State Psychiatric Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Hyman, others suggest, is ambitious, a ``Varmus clone,'' who
hopes to inherit the institutes' top job.
</P>
<P>
   He is aware that he is not universally applauded. ``I'm perhaps
a little too impatient and demanding,'' he said. ``I've always just
been very direct with people. If you do it in a way where people
realize that there's no malevolence or ulterior motive, I think
most people respond very well. But obviously, some people remain
upset.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Hyman makes no apology for tightening ethical controls on
psychiatric research. Not to do so, he argues, would be to lose the
public's trust. ``Good ethics and good research are inseparable,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   The large-scale clinical trials he has initiated are important
because they address questions the drug industry neglects, or has a
vested interest in, he says. ``Investigators don't want to do
clinical trials. They think it's not creative, it's `dog work.' But
there is an important role for the federal government in being an
impartial, unbiased investigator of certain sensitive areas.''
</P>
<P>
   The last criticism, that he is too ambitious, makes him laugh.
``I do have an enormous ambition,'' he said, ``which is to return
to academia and to my lab.''
</P>
<P>
   At 4 o'clock, ensconced in his laboratory, the director of the
N.I.M.H. is more relaxed than he has been all day. He jokes with a
graduate student, proudly shows off a gene gun that shoots DNA into
cells, sits in the coffee room trading stories.
</P>
<P>
   Though his passion is basic science, it was patients who drew
him to psychiatry. In medical school, he was moved by seeing
``young people who were as psychotic as you could imagine a human
being to be'' transformed, with the help of lithium and
anti-psychotic drugs, into ``someone you would enjoy having a
conversation with.''
</P>
<P>
   It is this intersection of mind and body that has always
fascinated him, fueling his dual passion for the sciences and the
humanities in high school, and later at Yale University. He began a
graduate degree in philosophy, but then applied to Harvard Medical
School. Eventually, he focused on molecular science because it
seemed to him that it was such research that would make the biggest
difference in people's lives.
</P>
<P>
   His choice was not a popular one at the time. His advisers told
him that ``molecular biology has nothing to do with psychiatry''
and warned that he would ruin his career. He did it anyway. ``I
think that illustrates some strength in Steve's character,'' said
Dr. Eric Nestler, Jameson professor of psychiatry and neurobiology
at Yale and a fellow resident in the 1980's at MacLean Hospital in
Belmont, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   For Hyman, speaking out is just something he has always done.
Perhaps it is the influence of his grandmother, a Russian immigrant
who survived the 1911 Triangle Shirtwaist Factory fire, and
testified against the factory's owners. Perhaps it is a matter of
genes and neurotransmitters. ``I could be less outspoken,'' he
said, ``but I would have needed a brain transplant.''
</P>
</TEXT>
