<HEADER>
A4889 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMELESS-SISTER-2ndTa     06-14 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMELESS-SISTER-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
FORT WORTH, Texas: his mother. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CUSTODY BATTLES: Amy is leery of everything, especially her
sister. She is certain Martin means to steal her children.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Amy phones Martin in New Jersey. If it's a good day
she is flip. ``Hey, Nikoroonie. I'm letting you know I'm off the
streets and still at the PNS,'' she'll say. If it's a bad day, she
is cool _ suspicious if an answering machine picks up the call.
She'll say she wants to see her children and asks Martin to give
her a ``real phone number and a real address.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin shrugs off her sister's mistrust. It is not so easy for
her to lay aside the suspicions of the legal system, she says.
Working to protect the children, fighting to get them out of the
Night Shelter, offering her home as a refuge, flying back and forth
from New Jersey to Texas, she is surprised that some
child-protection advocates also question her motives and even
suggest that she wants her sister's children because she has none
of her own.
</P>
<P>
   Martin shakes her head in a gesture of disbelief. ``Johnny will
say, `How come you and Uncle Tim don't have children?' I'll say,
`Well maybe God knew we needed to be here to help take care of you
and your brother and sister. Maybe we wouldn't have been able to do
that if we had other children of our own,' '' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The Martins have fought a legal battle to keep Johnny out of the
foster-care system. ``Once Amy was picked up on a mental warrant
and put at John Peter Smith Hospital. She was out in 24 hours, but
we got a call saying Johnny was going to a foster home. It didn't
make any sense. Here we were blood relatives who wanted him, and we
had to fight to get him.''
</P>
<P>
   FRANTIC: There was a time about four years ago when Amy tried to
get Martin to keep the boy. Martin remembers desperate calls in the
night. Her sister was frantic. There was no food. No money. They
had no place to stay. Help. Please help.
</P>
<P>
   Airline travel was arranged. Amy arrived with all the children
in tow. They were thin, dirty and frightened. Her life was out of
control. Could Martin keep Johnny? Just Johnny? Please?
</P>
<P>
   Why not the other two? Who knows. Maybe she felt responsible to
their father, to whom she was still married. Johnny is not his
child. Maybe she felt she had complete custody of him, says Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Johnny wouldn't stay. Would you?'' Martin says, hugging
him again. He looks down and shakes his head. ``You were worried
about your mom?'' she asks. He nods. ``Well, you're a good son,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   There were other trips. Amy grew more fragile, more fragmented
with each visit. Just one phone call from her husband would send
her hustling back to Texas and an uncertain life.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Amy's marriage ended in divorce. Her life seemed to
splinter into tiny fragments. Now she is too fractured to keep a
roof over her head, too emotionally unstable to care for her
children.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny loves her still.
</P>
<P>
   THE COMING STORM: Martin remembers the earliest markers of the
emotional storms that were to devastate their family. Amy had
married and was pregnant with Johnny when their mother died of
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought that marriage was pretty much on track, and then my
mom died. She was pregnant with Johnny. Amy took her death very,
very badly. She seemed to become a little withdrawn, and then we
learned that her marriage was falling apart. She became very quiet.
The family didn't know how bad things were. She lived in South
Carolina. I lived in New Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   She takes a deep breath and looks around the hotel lobby as if
the right words are hiding in the corners there. ``In the
beginning, you don't think anything is too wrong,'' she says at
last.
</P>
<P>
   Amy's depression spread like poison ivy in summer, and in the
late spring of 1989 she agreed to a short hospital stay _ six weeks
and she was out. That's about the time she met her second husband.
They married, and though the doctor advised them to wait several
years before having children, Amy became pregnant very quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Martin was concerned, but she hoped for the best. ``Looking back
on all this now, I think she was overwhelmed. She had a little girl
and then another little boy, and that marriage wasn't working out
either.''
</P>
<P>
   There were reports of arguments and lost jobs. The family moved
often. One minute Amy wanted Martin's help. The next minute she
resented the intrusion. One winter night she ran out of Martin's
house with no shoes, no coat. ``She'd just panic and run,'' says
Martin, who begged her sister to see a doctor again. Amy said she
didn't need medical attention.
</P>
<P>
   PROTECTING A GROWN WOMAN: Amy doesn't think she needs medical
help now, either. When she arrived at the night shelter three years
ago, Amy believed money _ money and breast-enlargement surgery _
would solve all her problems, says Suggs.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
