<HEADER>
A4890 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMELESS-SISTER-3rdTa     06-14 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMELESS-SISTER-3rdTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
FORT WORTH, Texas: says Suggs. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Suggs has witnessed Amy's slide down the rabbit hole into a
world of fantasy. ``When she first came, I thought she didn't
belong here. I thought we could help her. She kept clean then. She
always was dressed nice, always fixed up. Now she smells, a lot of
the time. Sometimes she wears crazy clothes, you know, a dress over
pants over shorts, three shirts even if it's 100 degrees outside,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   Every day she steps a little further from reality. For a time
she used powdered Kool-Aid to color her lips. She'd lick her
finger, dip it into the powder, then smear the goo onto her lips.
``Her lips were a mess. Cracked. Dry,'' Suggs says.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very secretive, too. She talks in circles. She doesn't
want anyone to know her business.''
</P>
<P>
   Suggs is so concerned about Amy he has given her a special pass
so she can stay inside the shelter even during the day, when others
must leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really afraid she'll be hurt,'' he explains. Amy is pretty
despite her days on the street. She is petite and mysterious, a
magnet who attracts men _ often abusive men. Suggs even barred one
man from the shelter when he tried to choke Amy.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wouldn't do anything to defend herself,'' Suggs says.
``She's not going to commit suicide or hurt someone else, but I
think it's dangerous here for her. She's not exercising any
judgment about these guys she's hooking up with. She does pickup
work, things like cleaning up The Ballpark (in Arlington). But she
can't make a sensible decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Suggs estimates that at least 50 percent of the Night Shelter
population is mentally ill, incapable of making sound life
decisions. He believes many would benefit from a prescribed regimen
of medication. He knows the administration of such medication would
have to be supervised and enforced. Amy is one who would benefit,
he says.
</P>
<P>
   Martin agrees. She thinks Amy could function if she lived in a
controlled environment where someone saw to it that she took the
proper medication. Martin believes it is her sister's only hope for
a real life. With the right medication and supervision Amy could
hold a little job, keep her house clean, even take care of her
children some of the time, says Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Martin and Suggs know Amy would not agree. Amy thinks everything
is fine. ``She's a grown woman. She's 34 years old. How do you make
someone get help if they don't want it? What do you do if they
don't believe they need it?'' asks Martin.
</P>
<P>
   This disturbing question cuts to the heart of the problem of
homelessness created by mental illness. Texas judges are reluctant
to commit people to a mental facility against their will, says
district probate judge Pat Ferchill, who is one of two Tarrant
County judges who has jurisdiction over civil commitment for the
mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   A person must pose a clear danger to themselves or others before
a judge will even consider forcibly putting a citizen into a mental
facility, he says. ``The burden of proof on the state is high, and
the ultimate result is a deprivation of liberty,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Americans value liberty above all else, and so it is no surprise
that over the last three decades there has been a trend toward
making it more difficult for the mentally ill to be committed, he
explains.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a question of what's in the best interest of the
proposed patient, says Ferchill. Courts must ask, ``Is there clear
and convincing evidence that the proposed patient is likely to
cause serious harm to himself or others?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of stripping a person of their civil rights.
Americans are reluctant to take away someone's rights,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Suggs has come to accept the complex maze of the legal system as
almost hopeless.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that Amy _ like many of the homeless _ has chosen her
life on the street, but Suggs discounts that decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``In her right mind, Amy wouldn't live here,'' he declares.
``It's like falling off a cliff. She's in a different world, and
from what I've seen, it gets progressively worse, just like any
other illness that's untreated.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who tries to examine her sister's condition without
passion, doesn't know what to call Amy's mental illness, but she
knows pity or anger or withdrawal won't solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
   She acknowledges that when she leaves the Night Shelter, she
cries. ``Amy is a prisoner. She's in the box and she can't get
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Amy's family is stuck, too. ``We live so far away. Maybe if we
lived in the area; maybe if I wasn't a working person too. ...''
her voice trails off. She takes a deep breath. ``So we do what we
can.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
