<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4897 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOSTER-CARE-NYT     06-14 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOSTER-CARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORRIES OF A SURVIVOR OF FOSTER CARE 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo  is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ms) 
(Francine Cournos, M.D., is a professor of clinical psychiatry at
Columbia University. Her book, ``City of One: A Memoir,'' was just
published by W.W. Norton.) 
 By FRANCINE COURNOS, M.D.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The federal government tells us there are 520,000 children in
foster care, enough to fill the entire city of Seattle. And given
the AIDS epidemic, that number grows daily.
</P>
<P>
   As a former foster child myself, perhaps in telling my own story
I can shed some light on the needs of those half-million children
whose stories remain untold.
</P>
<P>
   My troubles began when I was 3 years old and living in the South
Bronx and my father died abruptly of a brain tumor. My older
brother was 5, and my mother was pregnant with my younger sister.
My maternal grandparents moved in to help my mother support and
care for us. Two years later, my grandfather died suddenly when he
hemorrhaged from a stomach ulcer, and a few months after that my
mother was found to have breast cancer. She struggled for six years
with her illness and died when I was 11. Of the four adults who had
raised me, only my grandmother was now left.
</P>
<P>
   But my grandmother, who spoke only Yiddish and never learned to
read, was becoming increasingly forgetful, which further restricted
her already limited ability to negotiate the world.
</P>
<P>
   Watching so many people die was frightening, sad and confusing.
Still, the most traumatic event of my childhood was my placement
into foster care.
</P>
<P>
   Although my aunts and uncles hinted at the possibility, I never
believed they would really give me away. I figured we would just
live with them. But I figured wrong.
</P>
<P>
   My family concluded that my grandmother was no longer able to
care for us, but none of them wanted to take us in. One day the
uncle who had been designated my legal guardian took my sister and
me to some mysterious office where a woman I had never met before
announced that we were being placed into foster care. That was in
1958, when I was 13 and my sister was 9. My 15-year-old brother had
already been placed separately from us, and we never lived with him
again.
</P>
<P>
   I was taken to a series of appointments with various strangers,
until I eventually met the couple selected to become my foster
parents. I tried to be polite and show a little enthusiasm, but it
was a half-hearted and unconvincing act. I didn't want to go
anywhere with these strangers.
</P>
<P>
   On the day my family carried out its final act of abandonment, I
was taken to the foster agency headquarters for a physical
examination. I felt humiliated as I took off my clothes. It
reminded me of movies I'd seen of horses on the auction block, the
customers looking for defects before they decided to put down their
money. I certainly felt like damaged goods.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow we passed inspection. My sister and I were ushered to a
car, and a mysterious driver and social worker smoothly swept us
away from everything familiar. We arrived at a gray stone house in
the suburbs of Long Island where the little private dwellings and
sparsely populated streets seemed a world apart from the colorful
South Bronx neighborhood I had grown up in.
</P>
<P>
   My foster father, Jack, a shoe salesman with a gravelly voice,
kept a low profile while his lively, talkative wife, Erma, stayed
home and ran the show. They didn't have biological offspring, but a
year earlier they'd taken in another pair of children, a sister and
brother who were then 2 and 4. Erma figured we'd be like them,
needy children who were looking forward to having new parents to
replace the ones we had lost.
</P>
<P>
   But I'd had enough of the cycle of attachment and desertion.
After two weeks, Erma felt hurt and rejected. The more angrily she
demanded that I treat her like my mother, the more I recoiled.
</P>
<P>
   Soon I fell into a fragmented and unfamiliar state. Toward the
outside world I was withdrawn and detached, and when the foster
care agency scheduled visits with my aunts and uncles, they seemed
distant relatives I had once met but barely knew.
</P>
<P>
   Erma spoke repeatedly of her disappointment in me and angrily
talked about sending me away. I knew from my brother that foster
children often go from place to place and that being physically or
sexually abused was common, so it seemed less frightening to stick
it out with her even if she didn't want me. I was relieved when
after about a year Erma decided to let me stay.
</P>
<P>
   During the following years, I continued to float through time
and space in a state of numb, disorganized misery, going through
the motions but not really alive. I believed I was peculiar, and
had no idea that my feelings were a common response to trauma. At
17 I developed the sensation of a lump in my throat and became
convinced that I was about to choke to death. I was afraid to go to
sleep, terrified that once I dozed off, I would stop breathing
forever. I had no labels for any of my experiences, so I didn't
realize this latest state was a form of anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout these years, I remembered my mother's primary lesson:
it is essential to function no matter what goes wrong. So I always
followed her stoical example, worked after school to help pay my
expenses, and graduated from high school as an honor student. By
that time, Erma and I had reached a state of truce, even had some
appreciation for each other. Still, I was far different from the
happy child I had once been.
</P>
<P>
   Placement in foster care is always traumatic, and the long-term
consequences severe. In many ways, I grew up in a fortunate time
and place. Various kinds of public benefits _ low-cost housing,
low-cost health and mental health care, and free education through
college _ allowed me to keep on going.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there is good reason to wonder whether the disadvantaged
children in foster care will be given the same chance to survive
and prosper that I was given. There is considerable doubt whether
these children in need can find, anywhere, the kind of help that
was essential to my recovery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
