<HEADER>
A4900 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-WIND-OCEAN-2TAKES     06-14 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WIND-OCEAN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRAFT TO TRACK CLIMATE-AFFECTING LINK OF SEA AND WIND 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By WARREN E. LEARY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The continuous interplay between wind and ocean,
whether as gentle as a kiss or as harsh as a slap, eventually
affects almost everything else on earth through its influence on
weather and climate. Yet, except for occasional sampling, this
crucial interface between sea and sky goes mostly unmonitored.
</P>
<P>
   This should change later this week when a new ocean-observing
satellite goes into orbit to begin at least two years of daily
measurements of this critical wind-sea boundary area.
</P>
<P>
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration's Quick
Scatterometer, or Quikscat, satellite is to be launched on Friday
on a Titan 2 rocket from Vandenberg Air Force Base in California.
</P>
<P>
   The satellite's sole instrument is a radar device called a
scatterometer, which will continually sweep the ocean tops that
cover two-thirds of the world and measure the speed and direction
of the winds that stir them. The dividends from these measurements,
picking up where similar readings from earlier satellites left off,
will be both immediate and long-term, scientists say.
</P>
<P>
   Without satellite measurements, only limited and often
inaccurate wind-sea data are available from ships, aircraft and a
few ocean buoys, scientists said, and even these readings are not
available for huge areas of the world's oceans.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ghassem Asrar, head of NASA's Office of Earth Science, said,
``Knowledge about which way the wind blows and how hard is it
blowing may seem simple, but this kind of information is actually a
critical tool in improved weather forecasting, early storm
detection and identifying subtle changes in global climate.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Daniel Cayan, director of climate research at the Scripps
Institution of Oceanography in San Diego, said satellites provided
information about conditions in Southern Hemisphere and other
less-well-traveled oceans that was not available elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winds over the oceans are the key to how oceans evolve and
produce big changes, such as El Ninos and other widespread
effects,'' said Cayan, who is not involved in the Quikscat project.
``Winds are important in understanding how heat and moisture are
exchanged between the air and water, and the effect this has on
large-scale climate change.''
</P>
<P>
   Asrar said Quikscat was unusual in that the satellite was built
in record time because scientists felt there was an urgent need for
the wind-sea measurements after the failure of an earlier satellite
providing them. Using many readily available satellite components,
the spacecraft went from conception to completion in about a year,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory, which is part of the
California Institute of Technology in Pasadena, had designed an
advanced scatterometer called Sea Winds for a future mission.
Engineers there were able to build a Sea Winds instrument early and
the Ball Aerospace and Technologies Corporation of Boulder, Colo.,
moved quickly to integrated it into the 1,910-pound Quikscat
satellite.
</P>
<P>
   The satellite was to have been launched last November, but the
flight was delayed because of a recent series of rocket failures
that grounded the Titan launcher fleet. After a giant Titan 4
exploded during launching last August, and two other Titan 4
launchings went awry in April, failure reviews delayed further
flights of this type of booster. Quikscat, atop a smaller Titan 2,
could not be launched from Vandenberg until a Titan 4 on a nearby
launching pad flew first, which it finally did last month.
</P>
<P>
   James E. Graf, the Quikscat project manager based at the Jet
Propulsion Laboratory, said the launching delay added $5 million to
the $93 million cost of the Quikscat mission, a price that includes
the satellite, its rocket and mission science support, and would
prevent the spacecraft from being fully operational during the
current hurricane season, as was planned.
</P>
<P>
   Scatterometers are instruments that transmit high-frequency
microwave pulses to the ocean surface and measure the
``backscattered,'' or echoed, pulses that bounce back to the
originating satellite. These signals give an indirect measurement
of the speed of wind near the water in clear or cloudy weather.
</P>
<P>
   By taking readings from pulses fired at slightly different
angles, scientists can also use the backscattered signals to
calculate the direction of the winds.
</P>
<P>
   Scatterometers of increasing sophistication have flown in space
since the early 1970's. The first, demonstrating the feasibility of
the instrument, flew aboard NASA's Skylab space station in 1973 and
1974. The European Remote Sensing Satellite, still operating since
its launching in 1991, carries a radar instrument that works part
time as a scatterometer and has provided limited but continuous
sea-wind data for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   The most advanced instrument until now was the NASA
Scatterometer, or Nscat, launched aboard the Japanese Midori
satellite in August 1996. Nscat made more than 190,000 wind
measurements daily as it mapped more than 90 percent of the world's
oceans every two days. But the satellite suffered a solar power
failure in June 1997, and scientists lost this critical stream of
data.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Freilich of Oregon State University, the principal
investigator of the Sea Winds instrument, said the Midori failure
spurred the rapid development of Quikscat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will pick up basically where Midori left off,'' Freilich
said. ``We have a more advanced instrument that will make more
refined measurements than before, seeing more small-scale wind
variabilities than was previously possible.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-99 1736EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990614.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4902 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-WIND-OCEAN-NYT &LR;      06-14 0377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WIND-OCEAN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: possible.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Quikscat will cover 90 percent of the earth's ice-free oceans
each day, a job that took Nscat two days, and will cover a
1,120-mile swath during each orbit, one-third wider than its
predecessor, Freilich said. To cover such a wide area, signals will
be sent from the satellite using a dish antenna that rotates 18
times a minute to continuously sweep across the broad track.
</P>
<P>
   For winds moving at 7 to 45 miles per hour, the wind speed
measurements are expected to be accurate within 4.5 mph, and for
winds of 45 to 70 mph, the measurements are expected to be accurate
within 10 percent. Ninety-nine percent of all ocean winds fall
below these speeds, Freilich added. Scientists cannot accurately
predict weather without good wind data, and lacking such
information for the 70 percent of the world covered by water
hampers everyday forecasting, Freilich said. ``The difficulty in
predicting future weather is that we don't really know what the
weather is today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Combining Quikscat's wind data with information on ocean height
from another satellite, the American-French Topex/Poseidon
spacecraft, will give scientists a more complete look at wind
patterns and their effects on sea waves and currents, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   The Sea Winds instrument will be turned on about 18 days after
the launching, and scientists will spend another four months
calibrating the instrument and verifying the mathematical formulas
used to interpret the data. After that, the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration, a major partner in the project, will
distribute the wind information to weather forecasters and climate
researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Graf, the Quikscat project manager, said the spacecraft would
travel in a 500-mile-high orbit that crosses close to Earth's North
and South Poles. Although the satellite's mission is scheduled for
a minimum of two years, Graf said the spacecraft was designed to
operate for four to five years.
</P>
<P>
   A second Sea Winds instrument is being built and is to fly on a
Japanese satellite that will replace the lost Midori spacecraft in
November 2000. The two scatterometers are to fly in slightly
different orbits that allow them to make complementary
measurements, Graf said.
</P>
</TEXT>
