<HEADER>
A4903 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CABLE15-COX     06-14 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CABLE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Industry execs not ready to bury two-way T.V.
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Two-way television, thought to have been killed off by
the Internet, is rising from the dead here at the annual convention
of the cable television industry.
</P>
<P>
   Top industry executives are now saying they are ready and
willing to use two-way technology. And equipment makers such as
Atlanta-based Scientific-Atlanta say they have the technology ready
for installation.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, TV programmers such as Atlanta-based Turner
Broadcasting are ready to embrace two-way technology and the
Internet to make their shows interactive.
</P>
<P>
   What a change in attitude from last year, when two-way
television was considered the false promise of the early 1990s. No
longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interactive television didn't flop,'' said AT&AMP;T Chairman C.
Michael Armstrong. ``It just didn't get rolled out.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's company, when it completes its acquisition of
MediaOne, is expected to become the nation's largest cable
operator. And as such, AT&AMP;T will aggressively roll out interactive
television, said Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   Two-way TV, which requires cable television's new digital
networks, lets viewers use their sets to send e-mail, buy
merchandise, respond to a program or play a game against somebody
across town.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong expressed his support for two-way television in a
press conference Monday here at the National Cable Television
Association convention, held through Wednesday. His press
conference came after Armstrong delivered the keynote address to
the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Some 30,000 industry executives are attending the convention,
including Scientific-Atlanta, Cox Communications, Turner
Broadcasting and the Weather Channel.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T can't roll out two-way television without the right
equipment. An increasingly big manufacturer of two-way systems for
television is Scientific-Atlanta. Indeed, Scientific-Atlanta has
staked its future on the acceptance of its digital two-way network
called Explorer 2000. It is a bet that is starting to pay off.
</P>
<P>
   The company announced here Monday that it was increasing
production of the two-way Explorer 2000 systems to 500,000 a
quarter from 250,000. The systems include set-top boxes, software,
networking equipment and servers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Explorer 2000 set-top is now in commercial deployment in
nearly 40 systems throughout the United States and Canada,'' said
Greg Taylor, Scientific-Atlanta's vice president of worldwide
manufacturing. ``It is evident that we are entering the phase where
demand for our product will be driven by consumer interest and we
need to increase our production.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Scientific-Atlanta is dividing its Explorer line
into three models. The most powerful will be the Explorer 6000.
Next in line comes the 3000 and then the 2000S, which will be a
low-priced model.
</P>
<P>
   Equipment manufacturers aren't the only ones noticing the
growing interest in interactivity among viewers. Turner
Broadcasting says it is designing its latest cable television
channel as a multimedia effort that will extend to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The channel, as yet unnamed, will cater to upscale women.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet and its interactivity has changed how we do our
networks,'' said Terry McGuirk, Turner Broadcasting chairman and
chief executive . He explained that Internet sites tied to TV
channels generate additional revenue, through advertising and
electronic commerce and help promote new channels. And the channels
help promote the Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the blend of the two businesses that make new channels
profitable,'' said McGuirk.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
