<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DiMAGGIO-HOUSE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 MODEST DiMAGGIO HOUSE HAS FEW POTENTIAL BUYERS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIAN GUTHRIE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Descending the stairs of the Marina District
home owned by the late Joe DiMaggio, a prospective buyer said
Saturday, ``Joe was definitely a better baseball player than
decorator.''
</P>
<P>
   The modest, two-story house on Beach Street, bought by the
Baseball Hall of Famer for $14,600 in 1937, is listed at $1.4
million.
</P>
<P>
   It's a price that astounds real estate agents and might be
deterring the expected hordes of buyers. Real estate agent Joan
Smith of TRI Coldwell Banker, who snagged the listing through a
personal friendship with DiMaggio, feels the price is out of the
ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida lawyer in charge of DiMaggio's $30 million estate _
who already sold the ball player's 1991 $18,000 Mercedes for
$75,000 _ set the price, believing in the allure of the Yankee
Clipper legend.
</P>
<P>
   But DiMaggio, the gawky Italian-American kid from the San
Francisco area who performed magic on the field and became the
nation's most enduring sports hero, would be hard-pressed to turn
this highly spun offering into a financial home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love having this listing, and I want to sell the house,''
said Smith, who was wearing a Yankees T-shirt. ``I'm trying to sell
the DiMaggio name, but the house is ... in its original form.''
</P>
<P>
   In real estate parlance, ``original'' is a euphemism for
outdated.
</P>
<P>
   There is a two-car garage where DiMaggio parked his Toyota. The
garage door opens manually. The floors are said to be a beautiful
hardwood. But they're covered by beige carpeting. The linoleum is a
pattern Smith describes as ``what my mother picked out in the
'70s.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no dishwasher, garbage disposal, washer or dryer.
</P>
<P>
   There is a back yard, where Marilyn Monroe supposedly sunbathed
while she was married to DiMaggio. But it is currently a concrete
slab. There is a small ``knotty-pine bonus room,'' where DiMaggio
reportedly kept his trophies. Now there are only a few nails on the
wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joan was telling us about the little bottles Joe collected on
planes and the room off the laundry where he kept his trophies,''
said a prospective buyer from Connecticut who declined to give his
name. ``Other than that, there was nothing to suggest Joe DiMaggio
lived here. Strange.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio, who grew up in San Francisco, bought the Beach Street
home for his parents. It has been occupied since then by various
DiMaggio siblings, most recently his sister. DiMaggio, who retired
from baseball in 1951 and married Monroe in January 1954 at San
Francisco City Hall, lived there off and on until the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   In March, DiMaggio died at his Hollywood, Fla., home. He was 84.
</P>
<P>
   His 56-game hitting streak remains unsurpassed. His house was
put on the market May 25, and listed in the Wall Street Journal
last week. Smith said she's even considering contacting eBay, the
Jose on-line auction company. So far, she hasn't received many
calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``As great as he was, I don't think the Joe DiMaggio name is
going to sell that property,'' said Terry Chaffee, an agent with
McGuire Real Estate in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Even in San Francisco's heated real estate market, buyers will
not make offers on homes that are overpriced, said Laurie
Nierenberg, who is with TRI Coldwell Banker.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Joe DiMaggio house, it's in its original condition,''
Nierenberg said. ``If it were beautifully renovated, and in the
highly desirable blocks of the Marina neighborhood, and had a buyer
who admired Joe, perhaps he or she would be willing to pay a little
premium. But, it's still all about location, condition and,
ultimately, the price.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
