<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4906 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-FOSSIL-THEFT-ART-     06-14 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FOSSIL-THEFT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE EARTH'S GRAVEYARDS, LITTLE PROTECTION AGAINST THEFT 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Wyo., S.D., Ariz., Ill., Va.) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (The Science Times) 
 (nk) 
 By MINDY SINK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEMMERER, Wyo. _ By way of introduction, Vincent Santucci patted
his belt and said, ``As you may know, I'm the only pistol-packing
paleontologist in the National Park Service.''
</P>
<P>
   Santucci is the chief ranger and resident paleontologist at
Fossil Butte National Monument in southwestern Wyoming, where he
patrols over 8,000 acres of seemingly barren land that is actually
home to some of the best preserved plant and animal fossils in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The gun, he says, is not only to help protect visitors from
troublemakers but to deter looters from stealing fossils, often 50
million years old, for private collections or for profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing more and more criminal activity on public
lands,'' he said, adding: ``We have to be careful out there because
we are often alone. With the values so high for these rocks, there
is a real motive and incentive to collect these things.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a long history of theft at prehistoric graveyards like
Fossil Butte, Badlands National Park in South Dakota, Petrified
Forest National Park in Arizona and other public lands. During the
1980s, Santucci and other researchers set up a sting operation at
Petrified Forest to measure the resource loss. Dozens of pieces of
fossilized wood were marked with invisible paint and put in
discreetly roped off areas. After six weeks, visitors had removed
over 32,000 pounds of wood from the sites.
</P>
<P>
   Recent events have only made matters worse, preservationists
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing was `Jurassic Park,' '' Marianne Mills, chief
of resource education at Badlands National Park said, referring to
the 1993 movie about dinosaurs recreated through cloning. The movie
created a new generation of fossil lovers. ``Then the finding of
Sue in South Dakota and the selling of Sue, those things created a
lot more interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Sue, the 67-million-year-old Tyrannosaurus rex skeleton
purchased by the Field Museum of Natural History in Chicago for a
record $8.36 million at Sotheby's in 1997, showed just how valuable
old bones could be.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the commercial market for fossils is booming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Currently on the Internet, you'll see ammonites, those are
prehistoric snails, for $1,000 to $3,000,'' Ms. Mills said. ``Or
baculites, a precursor to the squid which left a
mother-of-pearl-like impression, can get over $3,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of those fossils are legally obtained, but not all. Hard
figures are not available, but Santucci, who has been involved in
cases all over the country, said fossil poaching was way up. ``In
the 1980s, it was just a handful,'' he said. ``In the 1990s, it's
in the thousands, and it has not plateaued yet.''
</P>
<P>
   And laws against fossil theft have not kept up with the sizzling
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is legislation for everything from wildflowers to
grizzly bears, but not for fossils,'' he said. ``There are specific
laws for archeological theft, but not for paleontological.
Oftentimes it is just a misdemeanor for years of public theft.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a case in South Dakota that illustrated the disparity
between penalty and value and which led Santucci to his dual
vocation.
</P>
<P>
   Working as a seasonal volunteer in Badlands National Park in the
early 1990s, Santucci stumbled across an elderly man who freely
admitted he had been taking fossils from the park for more than 25
years and said he had been able to raise a family on the sale of
what he took.
</P>
<P>
   ``He saw himself as almost heroic because the park was letting
these fossils `erode,' '' Santucci recalled. But after months of
investigation, when it came time for prosecution, the man was
convicted of a petty offense, given a $50 fine and probation.
``That's when I decided to pursue law enforcement before my
Ph.D.,'' Santucci said.
</P>
<P>
   Fossils do not have specific federal protections; the
Archaeological Resources Protection Act, for example, does not
include fossils. Instead, fossil poaching is punished under laws
dealing with theft of government property, with a $50 to $500 fine
possible if the specimen is valued under $1,000. The charge is a
misdemeanor. If the value is more than $1,000, it can be treated as
a felony, punishable with jail time and a $1,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, someone can be jailed for stealing ancient Indian
bones or pots, but it is unheard of for someone to spend time in
jail for stealing dinosaur bones or fossilized fish.
</P>
<P>
   On June 21, Santucci and members of other public land agencies
will participate in a public meeting in Virginia to discuss fossil
management and to pursue stronger penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Santucci acknowledges that not everyone who takes a fossil is a
criminal. ``A lot of people say, `Well, my grandma used to come out
here and bring some home,' '' he said. ``But these fossils belong
to us all, and no one has the right to take them to their castle in
Germany or their underwear drawer in Kentucky.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At most federal parks, signs are posted on trails and at
visitors center, warning visitors that it is illegal to remove
fossils. Still, at the end of May, two people were caught stealing
ammonites from Badlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were charged with theft of government property,
destruction of natural resources, and the specimens were
retrieved,'' Ms. Mills said. ``It was like the seven stages of
denial _ they didn't know it was our land, they didn't know it was
wrong, they were sorry, then they were angry and so on.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unusual to catch thieves red-handed, though, because there
are so few law-enforcement officers for so much land. In Badlands,
there is one law-enforcement ranger for every quarter million
acres, and they are not trained scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Another element that makes protecting fossils a challenge is the
divided land interests. Fossil Butte National Monument is one
fraction of the Fossil Basin in Wyoming which during the Eocene
Epoch, some 40 million to 60 million years ago, was much like
southeast Asia today, with palm trees, towering vegetation,
crocodiles, lizards, monkeys and numerous other mammals, and huge
lakes full of fish.
</P>
<P>
   The land that borders the monument is also fossil rich, but it
is owned by private landholders, the Bureau of Land Management and
other public agencies with differing interests. Some of the private
land is even leased to quarry companies which often use bulldozers
to work through the rock.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in some cases, some of those agencies other than the park
service may be involved in prosecuting fossil theft. An agent with
the Bureau of Land Management was responsible for the case brought
against David A. Hutchison of Richmond, Va.,, who for 20 years
stole turtles for his private collection. After pleading guilty to
theft of federal property from Bureau of Land Management areas that
border Fossil Butte National Monument, Hutchison was sentenced on
Thursday to two years' probation, fined $5,000 and ordered to pay
$10,000 in restitution.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison's lawyer, Frank Dunham of Arlington, Va., said the
effort to charge his client with a felony was punishment enough.
``It's like using a sledgehammer to go after a flea,'' Dunham said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said that in this case there was something of a
happy ending because the fossils _ estimated to be worth $220,813 _
had not been sold. Instead, the rare specimens were the best
evidence and may now end up in museums.
</P>
<P>
   However, the loss of scientific data during amateur removal of
the rocks may never be fully recovered. ``It's like tearing the
pages out of a book, and then that book is unreadable,'' said Dr.
Laurie Bryant, regional paleontologist for the Bureau of Land
Management in Cheyenne, Wyo. ``Even in the best-case scenario, we
may only know 10 percent of the history of the Earth. So with
everything removed, we know less and less.''
</P>
<P>
   Santucci agrees that researchers and scientists need to view the
fossils in their setting to learn more about the ecosystem that
existed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a needle in a haystack to discover the mysteries of
the past,'' he said. ``But the real thing is that we owe it to the
kids; we have an obligation to the kids of the future to learn as
much as we can about these fossils and the world they lived in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
