<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LOVE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Love flourishes in Carolina
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ Maybe by Sunday night, they will be calling
him Davis Love No. 3
</P>
<P>
   Love will feel a definite comfort level at Pinehurst No. 2 this
week during the 99th U.S. Open. His roots grow deep into the North
Carolina sandhills. Born in Charlotte and schooled at Chapel Hill,
Love won Pinehurst's 1984 North-South Amateur at No. 2. He played
the course in his mid-teens with his late father, who regularly ran
a summer Golf Digest instructional school on the famous property.
</P>
<P>
   To win any U.S. Open would delight Love, a Sea Island resident,
who figured at 35 to have acquired more than one major championship
by now. After letting an Open title get away at Oakland Hills in
1996, to win one at Pinehurst might even rival the rainbow that
materialized above Winged Foot during his title run at the 1997 PGA
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a lot of great memories around there, especially
spending time with my dad there, growing up,'' said Love, ranked
third in the world rankings. ``No. 2 is kind of where I learned to
play a big course for the first time. It's a course that most
people hope to play someday, and I've been lucky that I've gotten
to play it a lot. I've been lucky to slip out there a bunch in my
formative years.''
</P>
<P>
   It was at the 14th hole, Love remembered, that his long-time
teacher, Jack Lumpkin of Sea Island, ``taught me how to pitch the
ball.'' On a hole that runs adjacent to the road leading into the
village of Pinehurst, Love learned how to cut the ball off the tee,
knowing the ball would either fade or find asphalt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, Pinehurst is one of our U.S. homes of golf,'' Love
said. ``I'd like nothing better than to win my first U.S. Open
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Love will not be as disoriented as other players, who were
forced to finish a rain-delayed tournament on Monday in Memphis. He
already understands the perils of Pinehurst's crowned greens, which
cause errant shots to roll into collection areas, but he has not
experienced this U.S. Open setup.
</P>
<P>
   It will not be a traditional U.S. Open but more like a Masters,
where players must be creative. They will contend with deeper rough
than is normal for the course and greens that were made faster and
firmer with G-2 bentgrass not in place when the Tour Championship
visited in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``The golf course is going to be extremely difficult,'' Love
said. ``It's not going to be what any of us who've ever played it
in the past have been used to. You're not going to be able to get
the ball on the green as much as you want to. You're going to have
to be patient and hole a lot of putts for par.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinehurst's Bermuda rough is not that thick, so players should
be able to play to greens. But shots from the rough, minus
backspin, will not stop on the crown-shaped greens. That could
change if thunderstorms, predicted for today and Wednesday, soften
the course.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll see some shots played around the greens a lot like you
see at the Masters -- bump-and-runs or putts from from just off the
edge of the green,'' Love said. ``The greens aren't very big, so
(the preference might be to) get it on the green front-middle and
try to two-putt. I think maybe it will be a little like Winged Foot
in that you're not going to want to land it back in the corners of
the greens. If you go over or to the sides, you're going to be in
deep trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Love hopes to avoid a repeat of his Open run in 1996, when he
bogeyed the final two holes after being tied for the lead with Tom
Lehman. He finished a stroke behind Steve Jones. After 3-putting
the 18th that day, he was caught on camera putting both hands to
his throat.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are players who put themselves in position to win, and
they win,'' Love said. ``And there are guys who put themselves in
position to win, and it gets away from them. . . . I need to get
there enough times where I win them from ahead, I win them from
behind, when somebody gives it to you and when you snatch one away.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Sheeley writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
