<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CABLE-TV-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURN TO CABLE FOR SUMMER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAY HANDELMAN   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The major broadcast networks continue to hurt themselves by
filling their summer schedules with reruns, interrupted by
commercials for their fall series that are still months away.
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder cable viewership is growing? Pay channels like
HBO and Showtime have garnered praise for their original series,
which are more daring than those on broadcast networks.
</P>
<P>
   HBO is winning new viewers thanks to its dramatic comedy ``The
Sopranos,'' about a troubled Mafia family and probably the best new
show of the season. (HBO is rerunning the first 13 episodes. New
episodes begin next winter.)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Showtime launches a series that may have more limited
interest but has a similar creative spark. ``Beggars and Choosers''
was created by the late Brandon Tartikoff, longtime president of
NBC. Sure enough, it's about a network president. The two-hour
premiere airs at 10 p.m. Saturday, followed by 60-minute episodes
at 10:30 p.m. Saturdays beginning June 26.
</P>
<P>
   Though physical violence isn't on view as it is in ``The
Sopranos,'' ``Beggars and Choosers'' is just as much about
back-stabbing, power-grabbing and greed.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it's a satiric look at the cut-throat television
business, focusing on Rob Malone (Brian Kerwin), president of the
struggling LGT network, which is in the ratings cellar. Watching
him deal with constant problems makes you realize why network
presidents often don't last long.
</P>
<P>
   Malone's daughter, Cary, is dating the network's biggest star
(played by Paul Provenza), who has been pressing Malone for a huge
raise. The network's biggest new show, a Thoreau-inspired drama
called ``The Mountainmen,'' is an instant hit with viewers, but
advertisers are furious when the characters burn the products that
help pay for the show.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte Ross plays a vice president angling for promotions
while making sure she doesn't fall if Malone fails. Tuc Watkins is
the vice president of talent, a closeted gay man who is accused of
sexual harassment by a spurned actress. He's also asked to hire a
prostitute for the wheelchair-bound network owner.
</P>
<P>
   Kerwin plays the role with strength, worry, fear and power in
every breath. He tries to act on top of things even when they're
beyond his control.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the strong language and brief nudity in the premiere,
directed by Michael Ritchie, seems extraneous, but this is pay
cable after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beggars and Choosers'' may seem too inside for some viewers,
but those with an interest in how television is run are sure to
laugh their way through the show.
</P>
<P>
   A different sort of audience may find humor in Comedy Central's
``The Man Show,'' an intentionally insulting and disgusting comedy
that premieres at 10:30 p.m. Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   It's part sketch comedy and part talk show, hosted by Adam
Carolla (from MTV's ``Loveline'') and Jimmy Kimmel (from ``Win Ben
Stein's Money'').
</P>
<P>
   They have a clear purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to reclaim the airwaves. To take back the medium
that we (meaning men) invented,'' they boast. What do guys want to
see on TV? Apparently girls jumping on trampolines, monkeys,
flatulence jokes and the fastest beer drinker in the world. They
deliver that in each episode.
</P>
<P>
   Kimmel has a wry sense of humor, but I'm not sure what Carolla's
appeal is supposed to be. Then again, you're supposed to be
watching those buxom girls bouncing around behind the beer-drinking
piano player.
</P>
<P>
   The show has one redeeming bit of satire. Kimmel and Carolla try
to get women's support on a petition against suffrage. Sadly, most
of the women think they're talking about women's suffering, not
their right to vote.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
