<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NC-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANCE REVIEW: JAZZ AND MOVEMENT MINGLE AT A FESTIVE COCKTAIL
PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.C. _ The American Dance Festival's new season, which
is devoted to an unusually large number of premieres (16) and
special events, has opened here with ``Out Some Place,'' a lively
and inspired collaboration between the choreographer Bill T. Jones
and the jazz pianist Fred Hersch.
</P>
<P>
   The entire piece is an urban poem, surprisingly deep in its
ruling metaphor of life as one big cocktail party.
</P>
<P>
   But like Hersch's Gershwinesque score, the choreography Jones
has created for the Bill T. Jones/Arnie Zane Dance Co. is complex
and multilayered. The dancing on Saturday night in Page Auditorium
at Duke University repeatedly revealed dramatic incidents within
the consistently unfurling choreography.
</P>
<P>
   The wonder of the piece is how truly choreographer and composer
have collaborated, with each allowing for some improvisation within
set structures. Hersch shuttles onstage between a grand piano and
an upright, and his score moves easily from progressive cool to
barrelhouse rhythms and to an ecstatic finale.
</P>
<P>
   But the overall look of ``Out Some Place'' is abstract. On
another level the piece has a larger theme: the use of jazz as a
meeting ground in social gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   Intentionally or not, Jones and Hersch remind us that the jazz
pianist, in speak-easy or cocktail lounge, is the mediator in a
human situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out Some Place'' is the fourth of six works commissioned
jointly by the festival and the John F. Kennedy Center for the
Performing Arts through the Doris Duke Millennium Awards for Modern
Dance and Jazz. The Pilobolus, David Parsons and Paul Taylor
companies created the earlier entries. Each commissioned premiere
is scheduled to be seen at the festival's home at Duke and at the
Kennedy Center in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Jazz music has been foreign to virtually all the choreographers
involved until now , so the project has had some risk. Answering
questions after Saturday's performance, Jones referred to the
creation of ``Out Some Place'' as an assignment, adding: ``This is
a transitional piece for me. I don't know where I am going, but it
shows me a place where I can go.''
</P>
<P>
   Where Jones is going, in this work at least, is toward a
loosened-up style. (``I just wanted to play,'' he said.) The 10
cast members must move fast and athletically. There is an
exceptionally difficult combative duet for Eric Bradley and Daniel
Russell Kubert, who encounter each other head to head like young
stags and partner each other with changing wraparound lifts. At his
most typical, Jones likes to boil down or heighten gesture. Both
processes are at work here more strongly than ever, so that the
gestures are so abstracted that they are virtually erased of
literal meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the essence remains. One can spot a tipsy woman balancing a
glass on her knee, and raised beer glasses evoke a toast and
nothing else. Nonetheless the dancing is created out of isolated
movements of the body, reorganized and recombined.
</P>
<P>
   The variety of black costumes by Liz Prince are remote from
streetwear and all the better for darting into the wings. Robert
Wierzel's excellent lighting design, including projected spheres
and an onrush of white spots, suggests a cosmic disco. Drops of
sound on the piano bring forth a group emerging from the darkness.
The dancers raise their glasses and slap their laps, a percussive
motif enlarged later through stamping and clapping.
</P>
<P>
   Social contact evolves. The music meanders and grows assertive
as the dancers collide and spool off from one an other with lifts
and leg-swinging motifs. Hersch crosses over for his stride-playing
passage on the upright.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the grand piano he accompanies an exuberant ensemble
whose clapping and yelling leads into the climax of the brilliantly
performed male duet. As a tango seeps into the music, Jones plays
with propulsion: a woman uses two men as a springboard to push off
and land into the arms of another partner.
</P>
<P>
   When one group is silhouetted to a cocktail-lounge sound, the
image appears deliberate even if another group is on its knees and
four women execute a hiccupping stag leap until everyone undulates.
A man collects the drinking glasses, and Hersch raises his glass.
The party is over, and it is a model for others in the Duke dance
and jazz series.
 &UR;  &LR; The other admirable dancers were Miguel Anaya, Germaul Barnes,
Alexandra Beller, Stephanie Batten Bland, Catherine Cabeen,
Christian Canciani, Rosalynde LeBlanc and Toshiko Oiwa.
</P>
<P>
   All except Ms. Beller performed ``D-Man in the Waters,'' a
signature piece set to Mendelssohn's String Octet in E. Revised
last year, the work retains its life-affirming exuberance as a
delirious ovation demonstrated.
</P>
<P>
   Jones performed ``Etude,'' a new solo to music from Beethoven's
Quartet No. 16. A progression of isolated images, it is a showcase
for Jones as dancer and storyteller, even if the story consists of
fingers moving across an extended arm.
</P>
<P>
   The program was introduced by Charles L. and Stephanie Reinhart,
the festival's directors, and its dean, Martha Myers. The season is
dedicated to the benefactors Samuel H. Scripps and Luise Elcaness
Scripps, his wife. The annual $25,000 Samuel H. Scripps American
Dance Festival Award will be presented to the choreographer Pina
Bausch on Sunday by Harvey Lichtenstein, the president of the
Brooklyn Academy of Music. Another highlight on campus is an
exhibition, ``Full-Bodied Expressions of Modern Life: Modern Dance
and the American 20th Century,'' which includes rare material from
the festival's archives and is organized by Laura Clark Brown. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
