<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL SURFING ON THE NET 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., June 20) 
(jt) 
 By L.R. SHANNON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If your summer weeks away from work go beyond basking on a
beach, Dick Francis at hand, or lolling alongside a mountain lake
with Danielle Steel, you could learn about the Civil War or how to
cook haute or basse cuisine or even study real French. Thousands of
Web sites offer educational trips, and you could spend an entire
three-week vacation without getting to the bottom of them. But Shaw
Guides can streamline the search.
</P>
<P>
   EASY NAVIGATING
</P>
<P>
   www.shawguides.com
</P>
<P>
   There are detailed data about more than 3,500 arts and crafts
workshops, cooking vacations, educational travel programs, golf
schools and camps, language vacations, photography workshops and
tours, tennis schools and camps, water sports schools and camps,
and writers' conferences. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I put in a request for any type of educational travel from the
end of July to the end of this year, and came up with 263. I looked
at a bunch of them, including Holt's Battlefield Tours, an English
outfit; the Four Corners School of Outdoor Education, in Utah; and
the Sitka Center for Art and Ecology, in Oregon. A typical listing
gives the program's Web addresses, though not all the entries are
on the Web; year established; a brief description; number of
programs a year, their length and group size; location and months
of operation; and all the names and numbers you need to make
contact. This is followed by a paragraph on each of the trips
scheduled.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shaw Guides is a clean site and easy to navigate, light on
graphics and therefore fast. The programs included do not pay to be
listed, and you can use the site without payment or registration,
although you can enter your e-mail address to be notified of
vacations you might be interested in.
</P>
<P>
   SMITHSONIAN TOURS
</P>
<P>
   www.si.edu/tsa/sst
</P>
<P>
   More than 300 ``learning vacations'' are offered by the
Smithsonian Institution and can be sampled at its Web site. The
site is clean and mercifully unexciting; design has matured in the
last few years. The vacations range from three days to three weeks,
and generally take 20-some people. The prices, which are not low,
include hotels (unless listed as optional), most meals,
sightseeing, lectures, tips and transportation on the tour;
transportation to the beginning of the vacation is often extra. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Web site sorts the trips into cat-egories. Family adventures
are aimed at parents and children or grandchildren. Four were
listed for this summer. One, Tuscan Summer for Families (children
age 7 to 18), cost $3,895 per adult and $2,995 to $3,395 per child,
depending on age, with accom-modations but not air fare. North
American Study Voyages offered two cruises on sailing ships, one to
Greenland, the Arctic and Maritime Canada, the other to Nova
Scotia, coastal Maine and New England. For those not worried about
Y2K problems, voyages in the year 2000 include Cajun and Creole
Louisiana, the Mississippi from top to bottom, and Baja California.
The featured international study tour was Opera Lover's France, 10
days in Paris and Lyons in November. The Odyssey Tours are for the
classically or traditionally minded: Treasures of Italy (starting
at $3,599); Christmas in London ($2,399), Coastal California
($1,949) and many more, with accommodations and air fare from
Wash-ington. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The trips are open to Smithsonian Associates _ members who, for
$24 a year, also get a subscription to Smithsonian magazine and
discounts at museum shops. You can join on line, of course, and
register for a trip at the same time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
