<HEADER>
A4914 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAMET-WINSLOW-NYT &LR;      06-14 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAMET-WINSLOW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: THAT MAMET BOY SEEMS AT HOME ON UNEXPECTED
TURF 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   From its appearance on the London stage in 1946, to the opening
of a new movie version in April, ``The Winslow Boy'' has been a
victory of professionalism over improbability. What began as a
transformation of borrowed material by adroit stagecraft has lately
become a demonstration of a movie maker's finesse in adaptation.
</P>
<P>
   When, soon after the end of World War II, Terence Rattigan first
declared his intention to write a play based on a famous 1908
lawsuit, he was warned by Anthony Asquith, who would direct the
first movie version, that the required big trial scene would break
the production budget. Yet who would have predicted that a trial
play without a trial could be made to work for the West End?
</P>
<P>
   And a half-century later, who could have predicted that David
Mamet, poet of rough 20th-century American types, all those
unscrupulous, uncouth, expletive undeleted and shadily pathetic
characters, would turn his attentions to reworking an audience
grabber populated by an upstairs set of dignified, well-spoken,
clean-minded Brits?
</P>
<P>
   Both the play and Mamet's new movie proved surprising successes.
Rattigan, whose popularity as a facile farceur had been growing
even as serious critical attention remained elusive, received an
Ellen Terry award for the best play of the 1946 London season and
then the New York Drama Critics' Award. As for Mamet,
already-appreciative critics of his work have been impressed by the
new range and touch of his movie.
</P>
<P>
   Rattigan's inspiration was the case of Archer Shee, a British
cadet who was expelled from Osborn Naval College for stealing a
five-shilling postal order from another cadet's locker. When a
famous lawyer, Edward Carson, came to the boy's defense, the case
became a newspaper sensation.
</P>
<P>
   Rattigan's approach, to which Mamet has been remarkably
faithful, was pretty much to ignore young Ronnie Winslow, the lad
of the title, except for two strong made-for-the-stage
confrontations, one with his father and one with the barrister,
here called Sir Robert Morton. The focus instead is on the whole
family. One student of Rattigan's work credited him with developing
``for the first time characters, who, in spite of the melodramatic
qualities of their situation, are not only credible but
memorable.''
</P>
<P>
   The play, which covers the two years of the trial, is set
entirely in the Winslow drawing room. Courtroom developments reach
the audience at second hand. That can be stagy, as when a maid is
given the duty of imparting the court's final decision. But for the
most part Rattigan had the skill to turn his technical problems,
both of space and time, to his play's advantage. The audience finds
itself inside a warm household under increasing strain, and
sympathy flows readily to its inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   As for Mamet, his camera can take us into Parliament, a
newspaper office and elsewhere. But home remains where the plot is.
</P>
<P>
   Rattigan played to the public appeal of respectable and likable
citizens who make big sacrifices in the interest not just of young
Ronnie, but of right being done as well. There is Arthur Winslow,
the boy's father, a banker of liberal temperament and sometimes
crusty disposition, with a commitment to justice; Catherine, his
prematurely liberated daughter, and Sir Robert Morton, the
sardonic-seeming, soft-at-the-center Conservative politician,
originally played by Emlyn Williams. A few subsidiary characters
are inserted to draw attention to the principals' sterling
qualities, and the dialogue is smartly paced.
</P>
<P>
   Rattigan confessed after the play's appearance that he was far
from true to the facts of the case. The real-life Catherine, for
example, was no suffragette. At the heart of ``The Winslow Boy,''
however, is an abiding faith in the course of British justice.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing odd about that, coming from a well-born Tory
like Rattigan, but such an acceptance of a higher authority is not
what one would expect from the street-smart American. Yet if Mamet
harbors any doubts about the British judicial system or class
system around 1908, he keeps them to himself.
</P>
<P>
   Much abetted by Sir Nigel Hawthorne, who carries the movie with
his portrayal of Arthur Winslow, we are returned to an ideal
Britain that might have produced Mrs. Miniver. Although ``The
Winslow Boy'' is melodrama, its world is without real villains. The
glimpses we get on screen of Sir Robert's opponents are relatively
benign, and the issues are cushioned in legalisms.
</P>
<P>
   Rattigan's England was being transformed after World War II,
when the Conservative Party was kicked out. But the playwright
understood that for the theater's purposes, the appeal of the
Shee-Winslows cut across party lines. If you were taking the play
more seriously than it can bear, it might be seen as a V-Day
tribute to British justice and fair play, a touch slow to assert
itself but finally triumphant.
</P>
<P>
   Even audiences who see through Rattigan's mechanics and who may
be let down by Mamet's Anglophilia can depart with a feeling of
uplift. Both men, and particularly Mamet, who has a reputation as a
poker player, managed to beat the odds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
