<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DANGEROUS KISS': THOSE LIPS! THOSE EYES! THAT MOJO'S WORKING! 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Note language in grafs 1, 3 and 8; publication notes are at
end of review.) 
(ms) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hel-lo, Hel-lo: Austin Powers here. First up, baby, let me tell
you why I dig Jackie Collins' Hollywood. You know how they say
Hollywood is just high school with money? Well, to me, Jackie's
Hollywood is the 60s with money. Free love still reigns in Jackie
Land: people are still having promiscuous sex with many anonymous
partners without protection, while at the same time experimenting
with mind-expanding drugs in a consequence-free environment. My bag
exactly! And the babes are all so groovy: they've all got big hair
and tiny frocks, and they all shag like minxes. None of this PC
bull: what these chicks all want is a good-looking cat with a nice
set of twig and berries.
</P>
<P>
   Like Lucky Santangelo, the heroine of Jackie's latest gig,
``Dangerous Kiss.'' Yeah, I know, I know. Lucky's supposed to be a
legend in her own time _ this super-smart Hollywood fembot, the
mongoose to all snakes, the pit bull to all yorkies. She's supposed
to be what you 90s people call a feminist. Au contraire: she's
really just this switched-on babe with mojo. Her idea of running an
``equal opportunity'' studio means the guys, as well as the chicks,
have got to get naked in her movies: you know, equal time, equal
exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky, I have to say, is pretty shagadelic herself, one smashing
baby, baby. Listen to this description: ``Lucky was a slender,
long-limbed woman with an abundance of shoulder-length jet curls;
dangerous black opal eyes; full, sensual lips; and a deep olive
skin.'' She likes to wear red dresses slit up to her heinie, and
her Dad calls her ``Miss Balls of Fire.'' A Bond girl by another
name _ am I right, or am I right?
</P>
<P>
   Steady now, don't have a thrombo, but practically every chick in
this book is a Bond girl. There's Lucky's frisky best friend, Venus
Maria, ``all platinum hair, luscious cleavage and glossy lids and
lips''; and Lucky's sister-in-law, Mary Lou, ``a glowingly pretty,
curvaceous black woman'' with ``huge brown eyes, shoulder-length
black curls and a totally captivating smile.'' Also, there's
Lucky's goddaughter, Brigette, who's ``blond and curvaceous, with
luminous peaches-and-cream skin, enormous blue eyes fringed with
the longest lashes, and full pouty lips''; and Brigette's best
friend, Lina, ``an incredibly exotic-looking black girl'' who goes
``through men at an alarming rate.'' Needless to say, Brigette and
Lina are both supermodels _ a caliber of chick I know only too
well.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, two of Jackie's girls get themselves into trouble. This,
baby, is where I've got a problem. You'd think Jackie could at
least give her chicks a worthy nemesis _ like my old friend, Dr.
Evil. But, no. No ill-tempered, mutated sea basses; no quivering
pools of liquid hot magma; no monstrously fat, bag-pipe-playing
henchmen. Just a rancid little bird who wants Mary Lou's jewelry,
and a conniving count named Carlo who's after Brigette's money. If
these two sniveling creatures aren't the Diet Coke and Fresca of
villains, then I'm not London's swingingest photographer.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, you know everything's going to turn out just fine. It
always does in Jackie's world, same as in mine. Since yours truly
isn't around to put things right, Jackie's No. 1 Bond Girl, Lucky
Santangelo, swings into action. Lucky, whose father was some sort
of gangster, believes in what she calls ``Santangelo justice'' _ in
other words, the old eye for an eye, the old break the other's
guy's twig and berries. Ouch, very ouch! She vows she's gonna
liquidate Carlo, the evil interloper who doped up her beloved
goddaughter, and she also vows she's gonna get that pathetic bit of
business who iced her sister-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   But then, baby, things begin to get weird. Turns out that
Lucky's husband, Lennie, hasn't come clean about his own past, that
he had a thing with this Italian chick when he was being held in
this underground cave in Sicily a few years back, and this chick _
who's dead sexy, by the way _ has now turned up on their doorstep.
An underground cave in Sicily? Crikey! That's a whole 'nother
story.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, this producer cat named Alex is hitting on Lucky, and
Lucky's half-brother Steven _ yeah, the mourning widower of the
unfortunate Mary Lou _ is getting it on with Brigette's friend
Lina, who has been shagging a movie star named Charlie Dollar, who
is engaged to a chick named Dahlia. Like I said, everyone in
Jackie's world is so busy wearing fabulous clothes and partying
like it's 1969 that they don't even know it's the 90's.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, behave!
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `DANGEROUS KISS`
</P>
<P>
   By Jackie Collins
</P>
<P>
   559 pages. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
