<P>
   CABLE _ CHICAGO _ C. Michael Armstrong, AT&AMP;T chairman, is the
keynote speaker at the big cable show in Chicago. Later in the day,
Ted Turner will offer more details of the new women's channel.
(Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   QWEST _ ATLANTA _ A look at what the Qwest deal means for
BellSouth. Shares of U S West Inc. and Frontier Corp. rose after
the companies received unsolicited bids totaling about $66.4
billion from Qwest Communications International Inc., the No. 4
U.S. long-distance phone company. On Sunday, Qwest offered to buy
the companies in an attempt to get millions of customers for its
high-speed phone and data network and thwart an earlier bid from
Global Crossing Ltd. Qwest, which expects to complete a nationwide
network this month, wants customers from local provider U S West
and long-distance carrier Frontier to compete with AT&AMP;T Corp. and
MCI WorldCom Inc. (Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   REYNOLDS _ For the first time in nearly three decades, the stock
of R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. starts trading Tuesday on the New York
Stock Exchange, but Betty Cranford's investment club won't touch
the stock. ``With the controversy over tobacco, we do not feel
secure with that stock,'' the president of Forysth Investors said.
The nation's second largest tobacco company faces skeptical
investors now that it's been spun off from Nabisco Foods. (Burritt,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   REYNOLDS-TIMELINE _ A turbulent history: It's been 28 years
since the stock of R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. has traded publicly.
(Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   HOLSENDOLPH-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ In filings last week, lawyers for
the plaintiffs in the discrimination case against Coca-Cola zeroed
in on their objective to prove that the company's personnel system
works against black employees. Most experts expect that in the next
month Judge Richard Story, the expeditious federal judge hearing
the case, may make a definitive decision about whether to move
forward at full speed. (Holsendolph, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
