<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-BLACKS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIDS ACTIVISTS REFOCUS ON BLACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By Catherine Hollingsworth   
 New York Times Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The epidemic of AIDS cases among African-Americans
throughout the country has AIDS activists _ from health officials
to black church leaders _rethinking how to better target blacks at
risk of contracting the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Gay black men are in the highest risk category, followed by
intravenous drug users. And black women who have sex with these
individuals are increasingly becoming infected with the AIDS virus.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a decade, the U.S. Department of Health and Human
Services has grappled with the fact that the disease
disproportionately affects blacks. Now the department is refocusing
its efforts, trying new approaches to AIDS prevention in black
communities by requiring, for instance, that programs be
administered mostly by minority staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely looking for organizations to design their
programs with that cultural competence in mind,'' said Megan Foley,
an AIDS program analyst at the department's Atlanta-based Centers
for Disease Control.
</P>
<P>
   Foley added that the emphasis on African-Americans was warranted
because of the ``skyrocketing'' infections. ``It is clear a more
targeted effort is needed,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The department is providing $9 million this year to faith-based
organizations and other groups that serve areas with the highest
number of African-American AIDS and syphilis cases.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Leon Seymore, pastor of a mostly black congregation in
Jacksonville, Fla., illustrates the kind of tailor-made approach to
AIDS prevention that health authorities would like to duplicate in
black communities nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Giving no thought to his critics, Seymore established an AIDS
testing site and condom distribution center at his Pentecostal
church, Tabernacle of the Temples. He also extended the ministry
beyond the church walls to places where blacks might be most
susceptible to exposure to the AIDS virus.
</P>
<P>
   With a team of volunteers, he canvassed housing projects and has
even crashed parties and made the rounds of local bars to warn
people about the threat of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're radical,'' Seymore said. ``The goal is to meet them
where they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Seymore first got involved with AIDS victims four years ago when
he was sought out by relatives of two gay black males who were
dying of AIDS and in need of counseling. Other black pastors had
shunned the men because of their homosexuality, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't a concern of mine. The concern was that these
individuals needed pastoral support,'' Seymore said. Though the men
he counseled died after just two sessions, he continued his
outreach to AIDS victims through a church AIDS ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gained an understanding that AIDS doesn't have a color, nor
does it have a sex,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Catherine Hollingsworth is a correspondent in the Washington
bureau of the New York Times regional newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
