<SLUG> BC-ADS-DIVERSITY-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISERS STRIVE FOR MORE DIVERSITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DEBORAH CIRCELLI   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKELAND, Fla. _ A woman in a wheelchair models a dress in a
Dillard's ad for new spring wear.
</P>
<P>
   A deaf actress uses sign language to tell a story about cake
decorating at Publix Super Markets.
</P>
<P>
   And employees from a variety of ethnic backgrounds at Wal-Mart
are interviewed for television commercials about their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising agencies say companies are making a concerted effort
to bring more diversity to their commercials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think companies are more conscious of it, but I'd like to
see more diversity and use of people with disabilities,'' said Joe
Pisani, chairman of the department of advertising at the University
of Florida in Gainesville. ``After all, it is a part of life.
People relate to that more. They see that companies are trying to
do something that is socially responsible. I think it makes a big
difference. The more a company can make a situation believable and
more realistic, the more effective the advertising will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Howard, spokeswoman for McDonald's in Oak Brook, Ill., said
McDonald's began using ads showing ethnic diversity in 1965. And in
1986, the company aired ``Silent Persuasion,'' its first commercial
featuring people who were hearing impaired.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's long been a part of our corporate philosophy,'' Ms.
Howard said. ``We've always been a part of the community in which
we serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Kilb, an attorney with the Disability Rights Education and
Defense Fund in Berkeley, Calif., said it was encouraging to see
companies incorporate people with disabilities in their ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a recognition that people with disabilities belong in the
mainstream and are in fact functioning in the mainstream,'' Ms.
Kilb said.
</P>
<P>
   Heide Gardner, vice president of diversity and strategic
programs for the American Advertising Federation in Washington,
said it was still rare to see models in a wheelchair or with
prosthetics.
</P>
<P>
   The federation encourages advertisers and advertising groups to
hire more minorities and use more multicultural advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gardner said that only 1 percent of the $200 billion spent
annually in domestic advertising targets people of color.
</P>
<P>
   She said some companies are using montages in commercials to
incorporate various racial and ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a real opportunity for companies to look at how
they can grow their business by looking at the strategic value of
these markets,'' Ms. Gardner said. ``Brands have been known to go
from No. 3 to No. 1 in ranking when companies successfully target
demographic groups to their brand.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Many companies just don't understand the value of targeting,''
Ms. Gardner said. ``They make the mistake of thinking they
automatically are selling to these customers through general market
advertising. While they might reach people of color, they are not
necessarily selling to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gardner said successful advertising goes beyond using
different ethnic groups in commercials. The message also has to
relate to the groups, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart Stores Inc. uses real associates in its advertising to
show diversity in its hiring practices and as a way to relate to
its customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to worry about how they come across on
television,'' said Jessica Moser, spokeswoman for Wal-Mart in
Bentonville, Ark. ``We know that customer service will shine
through on our commercials. Our goal is that our associates reflect
our customer base, so we want that to be seen in our commercials as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Kmart Corp. uses both models and celebrities and on some
occasions employees.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Jarvis, spokesman for Kmart, said the company has used
closed-captioning on its commercials for several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to ignore any segment in our advertising,''
Jarvis said.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
