<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SLOWLY, TENSION SUBSIDES AMID SIGNS OF RENEWAL IN PRIZREN SUBURB
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-RUSSIA; KOSOVO-MEN; KOSOVO-RACAK.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUSUS, Yugoslavia _ One man is ready to go home even though the
geography of his once-charming hillside suburb of Kosovo is scarred
by war and still fraught with danger.
</P>
<P>
   Looking down at the Spanish tile roofs and the flower gardens,
62-year-old Yasha Shala points toward the central mosque. That's
now known as the area where one neighbor was killed and mutilated.
The white house down to the right, that's where the troops burned
the paralyzed girl to death.
</P>
<P>
   At least 60 homes -- in different areas of the neighborhood of
about 2,000 homes -- are empty hulks. The red roof tiles are caved
in and expose the remnants of the charred rafters.
</P>
<P>
   On the dirt road where little girls pick cherries, heavily armed
guerilla fighters now patrol and politely warn visitors that the
road they're on and the homes they see may be mined.
</P>
<P>
   Just a short walk from downtown Prizren, Tusus (pronounced,
``TOO-ses'') was emptied and nearly destroyed in the Serb campaign
of terror against Kosovar Albanians. But there are now small signs
of renewal, starting with the sturdy little Shala and his return.
</P>
<P>
   Though much of his family fled with other residents to refugee
camps in Albania, he and his wife stayed with cousins in Prizren,
Kosovo's second largest city. Older people were less subject to
arrest from Serb police and paramilitary forces. He checked his
house frequently and Monday, buoyed by the site of NATO helicopters
occasionally buzzing through the valley, he and his wife planned to
spend their first night back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder what happened to all the people,'' he said.
``Starting today, maybe they will come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, NATO troops are flooding into Prizren and Serb troops are
pulling out. But, these hills were the location for heavy fighting
between the Serbs and the rebels of the Kosovo Liberation Army. The
latter seeks Kosovo province's independence from Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting increased during the 78 days of NATO air strikes on
Yugoslavia. About three weeks ago, Serb troops told residents that
two of their soldiers had been killed and they were going to exact
their revenge on the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   They burned dozens of homes in different parts of town clearly
visible from the hill. According to residents, Serbs killed more
than two dozen people. Most homes were looted.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Sherif Barisha, an ethnic Albanian, works in a dilapidated
300-bed hospital nearly adjacent to the lower entrance to the
suburb. He remembers the day of the Serb attack. Afraid of being
found as a witness, he hid beneath his window sill, peeking at the
morgue where the Serbs left the bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were throwing them like a log, like animals,'' he said,
adding that he saw several bodies but did not count them. He said a
relative i
</P>
</TEXT>
