<HEADER>
A4936 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPOT-BJT15-COXUPDATE     06-14 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BJT15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 UPDATE &HT;    UPDATE
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Tuesday, May 15, 1999.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDS: CHURCH-VAN; KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-MEN; deletes: KOSOVO-MAIN
</P>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MEN _ PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ The missing men of Kosovo.
As hundreds of thousands of ethnic Albanian refugees streamed
across the borders out of Kosovo during the 78-day NATO bombing
campaign against Yugoslavia, there was always one question people
watching the exodus would ask: Where are the young men? According
to several of these men interviewed by Cox Newspapers on Monday,
they were locked away in jails and prisons around Kosovo, being
starved and beaten mercilessly on a daily basis. They were released
on June 10 after the signing of the Military Technical Agreement,
but their skeleton-looking bodies remind you of death warmed-over.
Developing. (Kunstel, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   w/KOSOVO-RENEWAL _ TUSUS, Yugoslavia _ In this isloated suburb
of troubled Prizren there are already signs of renewal, as members
of the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army are busy cleaning up and
preparing the more than 50 burned-out homes here for the eventual
return of ethnic Albanians who had abandoned them over the past
several months. And on a day when tensions between Serb and NATO
forces continued all over Kosovo province, there were signs here of
the situation being defused. DEVELOPING. (Kaplow, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RACAK _ RACAK, Yugoslavia _ The atrocities that took
place in this small village in southern Kosovo province in January
were among the first to arouse the anger of the world towards the
Serb-led Yugoslav forces ethnic cleansing campaign. We visit this
devastated village and talk to some of the survivors. DEVELOPING.
(Albright, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA _ MOSCOW _ Defense Secretary William Cohen and
Secretary of State Madeline Albright will meet with Russian
counterparts in coming days to attempt to resolve the dispute over
Russia's role in the NATO-led peacekeeping campaign in Kosovo. As a
small but politically significant contingent of Russian troops
continued to maintain control of the Pristina airport, President
Clinton and Russian President Boris Yeltsin spoke by telephone for
the second day in a row about the impasse over Russia's role. But
with no end in sight to the impasse, NATO generals downplayed the
significance of the Russian military presence and decided not to
deploy British and French troops at the airport occupied by the
Russians. (Holmes, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
