<HEADLINE>
`REAL WORLD' STILL GETS NO RESPECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE REAL WORLD 
On: MTV 
Time: Tuesday at 10 p.m. 
Rated: TVPG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now in its eighth year, MTV's ``The Real World'' can get no
respect. To some, the infamous docu-opera is little more than a bad
joke about Generation X, Generation Y, and Generation CU-SeeMe,
those media-savvy kids who'd sell their parents into indentured
servitude for 15 minutes of fame in the halls of America's malls.
To others, it's nothing less than the death knell of privacy,
mindless fodder for Our Nation of Peeping Toms, and further
evidence of the media manipulation that was condemned so poignantly
in Jim Carrey's cracked fairy tale, ``The Truman Show.'' Whew!
</P>
<P>
   So let's just forget about Sodom and Gomorrah for a few minutes
and squeeze the juice on this year's edition of ``The Real World,''
which is set in the eminently telegenic state of Hawaii. And a
juicy season it will be, if the latest hourlong premiere is any
indication. Indeed, the Honolulu crew promises to be the most
exhibitionistic cast of the series so far, a gathering of vigorous
egos who clearly know they were hired to make dishy revelation. Of
the seven 19- to 22-year-olds _ Amaya, Colin, Justin, Kaia, Matt,
Ruthie, and Teck _ only one, gay Harvard Law student Justin,
appears to have any resistance to the process of exposure. The
others fall more at the Teck end of the spectrum, Teck being an
aspiring filmmaker with a Dennis Rodman 'do who throws his arms
around each cast member arriving at the house. Looks like he'll be
the court jester and party dude, if he sticks to his favorite
motto: ``All day, every day.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's not just fun-loving feelings and flip philosophies that
this year's roommates are eager to bare. Less than 15 minutes into
the first episode of ``The Real World VIII,'' two of the gang peel
off their Gap wear for some euphoric skinny-dipping in the house's
glorious pool. And soon after that a third cast member, Kaia, the
Most Likely To Push People's Buttons, tugs off her blouse to share
her healthy self-esteem with millions of cable subscribers. (``I .
. . really, really like looking at myself,'' she says. ``Call it
narcissistic if you like.'') MTV calls it inappropriate, of course,
and blurs out all naughty regions. To be fair, Amaya, a UCLA grad,
does admit to some ``blazing insecurity'' about her body in
general, and ``the twins'' in particular, but her modesty promises
to dissipate in the coming weeks, as she'll be shacking up with
frat boy Colin in the series' first-ever on-screen roommate
romance.
</P>
<P>
   Usually it takes a few episodes for the heavy drama to kick in _
if it kicks in at all (see under: London). By the middle of last
season, the Seattle cast was a mire of bad behavior, with Irene
storming off the show, Stephen slapping her and tossing her beloved
teddy bear into the brine, and poor Nathan struggling with booze
and monogamy. Seattle became some pretty twisted theater, and
that's probably why it turned out to be the series' highest rated
year so far. But the craziness begins immediately in Honolulu, as
the roommates learn Ruthie's dark secret on the second night in
residence. A bisexual raised unhappily by foster parents, Ruthie
drinks herself not only into oblivion but into the hospital with
alcohol poisoning. It's not a pretty sight, watching her on the
bathroom floor with her eyes rolling up into her head, and she
appears to be a dangerous alcoholic. Later in the season, she'll
take a 30-day leave of absence from the cameras. Justin too will
leave the show, although he'll bolt permanently and for more
mysterious reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Is it perverse to think ``The Real World'' is more fun in
proportion to how much the roomies suffer? Let's just say that no
one _ not even the most passive MTV viewer, not even the crustiest
TV critic, not even Malcolm McDowell in ``A Clockwork Orange'' _
should have to sit through a boring season of ``The Real World,''
the sort of sullen, attitude-heavy aimlessness that defined the
years in London and Boston. It doesn't matter how picturesque the
location is _ and the house in Hawaii is breathtaking _ if there's
no conflict and passion and engagement among the cast members. So
go ahead and edit that footage into a ``verite'' narrative, MTV,
and go ahead and show off for the camera, kids. You'll all end up
with improved career opportunities, and we'll enjoy 22 episodes of
sanctioned voyeurism. After all, we all take the bait in that
tropical aquarium they call ``The Real World.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
