<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4943 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POST-WAR-RELIEF-HNS &LR;      06-14 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POST-WAR-RELIEF-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOES RECALL TIES OF FRIENDSHIP BETWEEN U.S., DUTCH CITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ After a half-century, Judy Meuwissen still
remembers the shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Among Meuwissen's memories of World War II devastation in her
hometown of Nijmegen, the Netherlands, is a pair of sturdy brown
oxfords sent from generous Albany residents in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd only had hand-me-downs from my older sisters before. Those
were the first new shoes I ever had,'' recalled Meuwissen, who was
17 at the time. ``The leather soles didn't have a mark on them. I
was so grateful for those brown shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   She wrote a thank-you note to Albany 52 years ago. ``I never
imagined I'd end up in Albany many years later.''
</P>
<P>
   Meuwissen, now 69, moved to the Albany area in 1970 with her
husband, Dr. Hilaire Meuwissen, an Albany allergist and
immunologist who is also a native of the Netherlands. The brown
shoes had been passed out at Meuwissen's high school in Nijmegen in
the fall of 1947, part of Albany's humanitarian effort to help the
Dutch city get back on its feet in the wake of catastrophic wartime
losses.
</P>
<P>
   An offensive the Allies had launched in September 1944, led by
the U.S. 82nd Airborne Division, drove the Germans out of their
last line of defense in the strategic city of Nijmegen at the
confluence of the Rhine, Waal and Meuse rivers near the German
border. It was some of the heaviest bombing of the war.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of the Allied victory and liberation for Nijmegen was
high: 800 U.S. soldiers dead and thousands more wounded; 2,200
civilians killed and 5,500 wounded; 2,260 homes destroyed and 1,300
damaged; three-quarters of the city center reduced to rubble.
</P>
<P>
   Although four years of German occupation had left the 120,000
residents of Nijmegen in dire straits, their resistance against the
Nazis was not broken. They sacrificed what little food they had for
themselves to keep the American soldiers fed. Nijmegen residents
risked their lives during bombardments to shuttle supplies dropped
by Allied planes to American troops pinned down during three days
of intensive fighting.
</P>
<P>
   In return for the courage and collaboration of the people of
Nijmegen, Maj. Gen. James M. Gavin, commander of the 82nd Airborne
Division, suggested the relief campaign. Albany residents responded
in a major way to help a city with which they had 17th-century
ties: Some of Albany's earliest Dutch settlers had Nijmegen-area
roots.
</P>
<P>
   During a Nijmegen Week donation drive in the spring of 1947, a
house-to-house canvass was made across Albany. ``If no parcel is
found on the doorstep, we will ring the doorbell and ask for it,''
said Nijmegen Committee chairman John Davis Hatch Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Albany Mayor Erastus Corning II, who served as an Army
infantryman in World War II, was a driving force behind the
adoption of Nijmegen.
</P>
<P>
   Albany's assistance in Nijmegen's postwar reconstruction
included a 300-ton shipment of donated medical supplies, food,
clothing, toys, window glass, building materials and other goods
valued at nearly $1 million. It was loaded onto the cargo ship
Westerdam at the Port of Albany on July 9, 1947.
</P>
<P>
   Included was a donation of 20,000 pairs of shoes and winter
overshoes from Swartz and Levison, an Albany shoe store. Shoes and
leather were among the most coveted items at the time in Nijmegen,
where some residents had to revert to traditional wooden shoes. The
Albany load of shoes included ``baby shoes and the soft type of
shoe worn by the elderly ... even ballet slippers for youngsters
with ambitions to be dancers,'' according to a story in the Albany
Times Union.
</P>
<P>
   The American city's generosity gained national attention. ``This
campaign was undoubtedly a unique success from the point of view of
one town in this country adopting a town abroad,'' Time magazine
reported in a December 1946 article.
</P>
<P>
   There were several byproducts of Albany's humanitarian effort. A
sister city relationship developed with Nijmegen. Formal exchanges
increased between the Dutch and the Dutch-settled capital city on
the Hudson. Albany's inaugural Tulip Festival took place in 1949.
And a subsequent visit by a Dutch princess inadvertently spurred
construction of the Empire State Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   In 1959, Princess Beatrix of the Netherlands visited Albany _
reprising a 1942 stop by her mother, Queen Wilhelmina _ and
received a downtown tour from Mayor Corning and Gov. Nelson A.
Rockefeller. Rockefeller was embarrassed to show the princess the
shabby streets and dilapidated buildings, Corning later recalled,
and vowed he would give Albany a major makeover. It was the
beginning of a vision that grew into the 98-acre state government
complex that bears Rockefeller's name.
</P>
<P>
   In gratitude for the Nijmegen relief, Queen Wilhelmina conferred
on Corning her country's highest citizen honor, making him an
officer in the Order of Orange. Nijmegen's burgomaster, or mayor,
Charles Hustinx, visited Corning in Albany several times after the
war, and the two politicians corresponded for years.
</P>
<P>
   Hustinx commissioned ``The Mayor Corning March'' from Nijmegen
composer A.H.J. Kotter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The close connection eventually faded between Albany and
Nijmegen, a prosperous city of 250,000 today. ``Mayor Corning would
occasionally mention Nijmegen and I dug into the institute files
once or twice for historical background,'' but the relationship had
dissipated when he arrived in Albany in 1953, said Norman Rice,
former director of the Albany Institute of History and Art. (Hatch,
the Nijmegen relief organizer, was a predecessor of Rice's in that
post.)
</P>
<P>
   The bond was revived for Mark Heller, an Albany attorney, during
a trip to Nijmegen six years ago. Heller retraced a visit by his
father, the late Julius J. Heller, a Knickerbocker News reporter
who accompanied an Albany goodwill contingent in 1947. The son
visited a cemetery for American soldiers, where Nijmegen residents
help tend the graves of their liberators.
</P>
<P>
   Heller saved several reels of 16mm film his father used to
document the devastation and reconstruction of Nijmegen. ``I
haven't seen those movies since 1947, when I was 13 and my father
told me the stories of his trip,'' Heller said.
</P>
<P>
   Meuwissen is not sure what became of her shiny brown oxfords
from Albany. They were certainly durable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I outgrew them before they wore out,'' Meuwissen said.
Since she had no younger sisters to hand them down to, she figures
they had a second life somewhere _ passed on to a less fortunate
girl in her neighborhood.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
