<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Success smiles on nice guy Will Smith
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Will Smith, star of the highly touted summer movie ``Wild Wild
West,'' is riding high on the covers of Vanity Fair ($3.95) and
Ebony ($2.50). ``I'm probably the first black guy who ever saved
the world,'' quips the star of ``Independence Day'' and ``Men in
Black.'' You'll find nothing negative in either article. In fact,
says Vanity Fair writer Ned Zeman, Smith is such a nice guy that
when he approaches the film crew ``it's like de Gaulle returning to
Paris. Rarely do you see teamsters reach out for hugs, but they
can't help themselves when confronted with all that bright-eyed,
jug-eared Will Smithness.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in Vanity Fair is a revealing article about Ernest
Hemingway and his affair with celebrated beauty Jane Mason.
(Especially revealing is a rear-view nude photograph of Hemingway
on a fishing boat.) When the affair ended, Hemingway portrayed
Mason as the character Helene Bradley in ``To Have and Have Not,''
and the thrice-married Mason took a fourth husband, Esquire founder
Arnold Gingrich. Hemingway's close relationship with the magazine
was never the same.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE SON ALSO RISES: In a cover story and interview, Newsweek
($3.50) attempts to find the real George W. Bush beneath the
well-orchestrated image. A son of privilege, Bush is campaigning as
a ``compassionate conservative.'' What that means is a mystery even
to his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  FUTURE FICTION: In a special double issue, The New Yorker
($3.95) showcases 20 young writers for the 21st century, from the
relatively unknown Jhumpa Lahiri to acclaimed authors such as Rick
Moody, Ethan Canin and Edwidge Danticat. The issue ``is a Polaroid
of this generation,'' editor Bill Buford writes, ``snapped as the
century turns.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  SHYING AWAY: Shyness in moderation can be endearing, but
sometimes social anxiety can be debilitating. U.S. News &AMP; World
Report ($2.95) delves into the mental disorder suffered by one out
of eight Americans. Some are so timid about meeting people that
they have panic attacks. It's difficult to become ``unshy,''
experts say, but there are ways to cope, such as focusing on others
rather than yourself. Besides, many famous people _ including
Eleanor Roosevelt and Robert Frost _ have suffered from shyness.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  REVENGE OF THE NERD: In his ``Saturday Night Live'' years,
Adam Sandler got less respect than Rodney Dangerfield. Now, thanks
to hit movies such as ``The Wedding Singer'' and ``The Waterboy,''
Sandler is one of the most bankable stars in Hollywood.
Entertainment Weekly ($2.99) profiles the prankster and previews
his new film, ``Big Daddy,'' in which Sandler stars as an
irresponsible law school graduate who adopts a 5-year-old boy in a
ploy to win back his girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  BIG SPENDERS: F. Scott Fitzgerald was right. The rich are
different. This week's People ($2.99) looks at the shopping habits
of celebrities for whom spending money is a guilt-free pleasure. On
a recent spree, Goldie Hawn paid $3,000 for three sweaters, and
Jennifer Tilly slipped into a pair of $530 stilettos and a $6,420
silk-and-linen car coat sprinkled with plastic beads. ``Who needs
friends when you have clothes?'' Tilly asks.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  UNFADED ROSE: In 1993, Axl Rose was one of the biggest rock
stars around. But after completing a world tour with Guns N' Roses,
he became a recluse. What happened? Spin ($2.99) tracks down the
latest rumors and reports that Rose is holed up in various Los
Angeles studios recording and re-recording what may be the most
anticipated comeback record of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A NEW LIST: Will the Tom Cruise-Nicole Kidman movie ``Eyes
Wide Shut'' become the sexiest film of all time? US ($3) fuels the
speculation by polling readers on the sexiest movies to date and
asking the magazine's movie critic Peter Travers to pick the
sexiest movie rentals. Readers chose ``Basic Instinct'' and
``Titanic'' as their favorites, while Travers opted for
``Barbarella'' and ``Last Tango in Paris.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in the saddle
</P>
<P>
   Vanity Fair takes a ride with rapper-turned-actor Will Smith on
the eve of the release of his summer movie, ``Wild Wild West.''
</P>
<P>
   Reclusive Rose
</P>
<P>
   Where in the world is Axl Rose? Spin goes in search of the Guns
</P>
<P>
   N' Roses singer who dropped out of sight six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
