<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4963 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIAN-ARMY-HNS &LR;      06-14 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIAN-ARMY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS SAY RUSSIAN TROOPS IN KOSOVO WERE FOLLOWING ORDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL And ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The defiant occupation of Kosovo's main airfield by
Russian army troops was an impromptu effort by President Boris
Yeltsin to assuage anti-western nationalism at home rather than a
mutinous takeover by Russian armed forces, U.S. experts said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials, seeking to downplay the incident, said
Yeltsin had given a ``general order'' to Russian commanders to move
troops from peacekeeping duties in Bosnia across Serbia into
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeltsin, in a sense, gave an order for the Russians to
participate _ and the generals took it from there,'' said National
Security Adviser Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the degree of Yeltsin's involvement in the surprising
maneuver, the Russian army leadership publicly promoted the
commander of the 50-vehicle Russian column that raced into Kosovo,
elevating Lt. Gen. Viktor Zavarzin to colonel general.
</P>
<P>
   Russia experts, including scholars who have served in the
Clinton administration, said there was no evidence that Russian
armed forces' had defied Kremlin civilian leadership and raced into
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they said, the troop movement reflected a response to
domestic Russian political sentiment and the Kremlin's bid to force
a better deal from NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Ivo H. Daalder, who served as Clinton's director of European
affairs at the National Security Council and has written, ``Getting
to Dayton: The Making of America's Bosnia Policy,'' said the
``pre-emptive troop deployment is forcing our hand to try to work
out a deal that gives Russians greater latitude in the Kosovo
operation.''
</P>
<P>
   James Goldgeier, Clinton's former director of Russian, Ukranian
and Eurasian affairs at the National Security Council, said
Yeltsin's decision reflects the Russian president's ``balancing
act'' between cooperation with the West and Russian armed forces'
``anger and humiliation'' over NATO's expansion to the East and its
bombing of Yugoslavia, a long-time Russian ally.
</P>
<P>
   ``The military leadership in Moscow really resents what is going
on in Kosovo where NATO is dictating the terms of Russian
participation,'' Goldgeier said. ``They wanted to change the facts
on the ground so they would be reckoned with _ and they did.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben Lambeth, a Russian military expert and author of a
forthcoming book on Russian air power, said the Russian military
remains subservient to civilian control.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russian military is a basket case economically and
socially, but it's still under pretty tight discipline and
leadership,'' Lambeth said. ``It is still a professional military
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia's civilian leaders still retain direct control over the
arsenal of Soviet-era nuclear weapons, Lambeth added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the things we can be certain about in post-Soviet
Russia, the command and control of their intercontinental nuclear
missiles is not a problem,'' Lambeth said.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Russian troops' swift invasion of Kosovo late
Friday, Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov first told Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright that he knew nothing about the
maneuver, then that it was a ``mistake'' and finally that the
Kremlin would order an immediate Russian troop withdrawal. Russian
officials said Monday the troops will remain.
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart dismissed the Russian
airport takeover as ``not a militarily significant event,'' adding
that Russian commanders had merely ``jumped the gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart warned: ``It's easy to make more of this than you
should.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia has offered to send 10,000 troops into Kosovo but
independent of NATO command. NATO has insisted on a unified command
structure. The issue was still hanging when the Russian troops
raced into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton ordered Albright and Defense Secretary William
Cohen to travel to Helsinki, Finland, to negotiate arrangements for
joint allied-Russian occupation of post-war Kosovo. The U.S.
officials will meet with Ivanov and Russian Defense Minister
Marshal Igor Sergeyev before an expected Clinton-Yeltsin summit in
Cologne, Germany, next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Retired Army Maj. Gen. Edward B. Atkeson, a former top
intelligence officer for U.S. forces in Europe, said Yeltsin's
maneuver could pay huge political dividends back home.
</P>
<P>
   Atkeson, now associated with the Center for Strategic and
International Studies in Washington, D.C., said: ``Yeltsin and his
military leadership are looking for superpower status _ and at
least for now they've got it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Atkeson said Yeltsin is trying to retain effective power in the
face of mushrooming anti-western sentiment before the Russian
parliamentary elections on Dec. 19 and the Russian presidential
election next June.
</P>
<P>
   ``Communists and rightwingers are gaining strength,'' Atkeson
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Bosnia model for deploying Russian and NATO troops appeared
unworkable in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops now serve in Bosnia under the command of a
Russian general posted at NATO headquarters who reports to Gen.
Wesley Clark, NATO's top military commander and the commander of
all U.S. forces in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But since those arrangements were crafted in 1995, the 16-nation
western military alliance has expanded to the East to embrace
Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic _ nations once allied with
the Soviet Union. NATO also has carried out the first offensive
military campaign of its history, conducting an 11-week bombing
campaign against Yugoslavia, formerly a Russian ally.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bosnia model is insufficient for the Russians,'' Goldgeier
said. ``The politics are completely different. NATO has expanded;
NATO has gone to war. After that, the Russians are not going to
serve under NATO command.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The experts cautioned that the U.S.-led military alliance cannot
allow Russia to operate a separate zone in Kosovo because Serbs
might try to use the Russian-controlled area as a safe haven from
which to stage guerrilla raids on ethnic Albanian Muslims or the
Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   As Goldgeier put it: ``It's just too dangerous for NATO not to
be in control of the entire military operation.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright echoed the priority in remarks at the White House: The
Russians ``understand the unity of command and that every inch of
Kosovo has to be under KFOR'' _ the acronym for the Kosovo
international security force.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com) (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at
202-298-6920 and at the email address eric(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
