</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NHL expansion team might have first new face
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ In the first of what figures to become a long
list of obscure-sounding names to Atlanta sports fans, the
Thrashers' original roster could begin with this one: Hugo
Boisvert.
</P>
<P>
   Boisvert, a 23-year-old center who just completed his junior
season at Ohio State, probably will become the first player to sign
with the Thrashers. Boisvert recently hired an agent, effectively
ending his college eligibility, with the intention of signing with
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``There could be some issues in the contract (about guarantees)
that we may not be able to agree to, but I feel pretty confident it
will get done,'' Thrashers general manager Don Waddell said.
</P>
<P>
   Boisvert, a finalist for the Hobey Baker Award as college
hockey's top player, will be one of 15 to 20 unrestricted free
agents the Thrashers sign for their 40-man roster. The rest will
come from the expansion and entry drafts. Boisvert is a free agent
because he is over 21 and was not drafted when he played junior
hockey in Ontario for three years before enrolling at Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-0, 200-pound Boisvert scored 147 points in 121 career
games, including 24 goals and 27 assists in 41 games as a senior.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting old, and I thought with an expansion team I would
have a chance to play in the NHL sooner,'' Boisvert said from his
parents' home in Quebec. ``If I signed with Dallas or Detroit, it
would've been pretty hard to get a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Schultz writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
