<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; DeFOREST KELLEY: THE REAL McCOY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (750 words) Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of
DeForest Kelley with William Shatner in ``Star Trek V: The Final
Frontier.'') &QL; 
 &UR; By IAN SPELLING &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Ian Spelling, the noted science-fiction writer and author of The
New York Times Syndicate's Inside Trek &AMP; Sci-Fi column, remembers
``Star Trek'' star DeForest Kelley _ who died on June 11 _ in this
special column.
</P>
<P>
   ``All he ever wanted was to be a doctor,'' Spelling writes.
``And to millions of `Star Trek' fans around the world, DeForest
Kelley was exactly that. Even though his family couldn't afford to
put him through medical school, the actor made his mark as Dr.
Leonard `Bones' McCoy, the irascible medic aboard the starship
Enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   ```My legacy is that I have inspired a great number of people to
enter the medical world,' he said last August. `These people are
doctors now, all kinds of doctors who save lives and help other
people in other ways.
</P>
<P>
   ```That's something that very few people can say they've done.
I'm very proud to say that I have.'''
</P>
<P>
   For information on this story, contact New York Times Syndicate
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at
732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   (slugged: BC-TREK-REMEMBERING-DEFOREST-KELLEY-ART-NYTSF,
priority code w, category code e)
</P>
<P>
   (Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
