<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, June 15, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Morning showers and thundershowers will cross the Northeast on
Tuesday ahead of a cold front. Breezes will increase from the
southwest until the front passes, then winds will blow from the
northwest. Drier air moving to the south behind the front will
bring mostly sunny skies from southern New England to the Ohio
Valley. In the wake of the front, cool air will bring an
unseasonable chill from New England to the Great Lakes Tuesday
night. Farther south along the front, a weak area of low pressure
will aid in the development of scattered thunderstorms over the
Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered showers will move into the northern Plains ahead of a
low pressure system sliding out of the Rockies. Warm, moist air
ahead of this low will provide the fuel for showers and
thunderstorms. A cold front trailing to the north and west will
direct flow up the east slopes of the northern Rockies, causing
more numerous showers and thundershowers.
</P>
<P>
   A disturbance at 18,000 feet over west Texas will trigger
showers and thundershowers. Weak flow aloft means that the storms
will be slow-moving, bringing torrential rain, possibly even
causing localized flash flooding. The Gulf Coast will be very warm
and humid with a few isolated thundershowers.
</P>
<P>
   Low pressure approaching the Pacific Northwest will usher low
clouds onshore. In addition, some locations very near the Coast
will experience a few showers. Other than some patchy low clouds at
the Coast, mostly sunny skies will be widespread over southern
California. The Southwest will remain bright, very hot, and dry.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Presidential Warmth
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was one of the warmest June days in recent memory on
Mount Washington in northern New Hampshire. The mercury rose to 67
degrees just before 3 p.m. eclipsing a record that had stood since
1969. The warmth was associated with a large ridge of high pressure
that crested over New England this past weekend. The circulation
around the high brought ocean-cooled air to the New England coast
while drawing balmy air northward along the west slopes of the
northern Appalachians. A strong cold front will pass through the
region Tuesday with some snow likely on the peak later this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
