<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREK-REMEMBERING-DEFOREST-KELLEY-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 DeFOREST KELLEY: THE REAL McCOY  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of DeForest
Kelley with William Shatner in ``Star Trek V: The Final
Frontier.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    All he ever wanted was to be a doctor.
 &HT;    And to millions of ``Star Trek'' fans around the world, DeForest
Kelley was exactly that. Even though his family couldn't afford to
put him through medical school, the actor made his mark as Dr.
Leonard ``Bones'' McCoy, the irascible medic aboard the starship
Enterprise.
 &HT;    Kelley played the role from 1966 to 1969 on the original ``Star
Trek'' series, as well as in six feature films and a guest
appearance in ``Encounter at Farpoint,'' the series premiere of the
show's first spinoff, ``Star Trek: The Next Generation.''
 &HT;    Kelley's journey ended at noon on June 11, when the 79-year-old
actor, who was a longtime smoker, succumbed to a lengthy illness at
the Motion Picture and Television Country Home and Hospital in
Woodland Hills, Calif. His wife of nearly 55 years, Carolyn, was at
his side when he passed away.
 &HT;    ``My legacy is that I have inspired a great number of people to
enter the medical world,'' he told ``Inside Trek &AMP; Sci-Fi'' last
August. ``These people are doctors now, all kinds of doctors who
save lives and help other people in other ways.
 &HT;    ``That's something that very few people can say they've done.
I'm very proud to say that I have.''
 &HT;    As McCoy, Kelley represented one-third of ``Star Trek's''
leading troika, which also included William Shatner as the heroic,
libidinous Capt. Kirk and Leonard Nimoy as the ever-logical Vulcan,
Mr. Spock. Millions for fans never tired of McCoy and Spock's
verbal sparring, and always welcomed the repetition of the doctor's
catch phrase, ``He's dead, Jim.''
 &HT;    Looking back over three decades of ``Star Trek,'' Kelley had his
favorites. He ranked the time-travel romance ``The City on the Edge
of Forever'' as the show's finest episode, and 1986's ``Star Trek
IV: The Voyage Home'' as the best of the original-cast features.
 &HT;    By the time he achieved fame as a futuristic good guy, Kelley
had already spent two decades as an actor, often playing villains
in films and television shows set in the Old West. Among his many
television credits were ``The Lone Ranger,'' ``Gunsmoke,'' ``Bat
Masterson'' and ``Bonanza,'' while his films included ``Raintree
County'' (1957), ``Gunfight at the O.K. Corral'' (1957) and
``Apache Uprising'' (1966).
 &HT;    Kelley's last acting job was as the voice of a satellite, the
Viking I, in last year's direct-to-video release of ``The Brave
Little Toaster Goes to Mars,'' an animated children's film.
 &HT;    Offscreen, Kelley was considered by fans and friends alike a
warm and humble man who adored his wife. So low-key and beloved was
he that, in the many books written about ``Trek'' by his co-stars _
several of whom famously quarreled _ no one penned a negative word
about ``De,'' as he was called by friends.
 &HT;    ``It's nice to hear that people think well of you,'' Kelley said
last year. ``I knew about the feelings on the set, of course, but I
just divorced myself from that and tried to keep my eyes straight
down the road.
 &HT;    ``I've always tried to do my job without digging into somebody's
personal life, without making waves,'' he added. ``I'd like to
think that served me well.''
 &HT;    In lieu of flowers, Carolyn Kelley has requested that donations
be made to the Motion Picture and Television Fund, the North Shore
Animal League and the Harvard Medical School, which will soon
establish a DeForest Kelley Scholarship Fund for medical students.
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Website
at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Inside Trek
&AMP; Sci-Fi and other features. &QL; 
