<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QWEST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gamesmanship or land rush? Qwest move makes communications
picture blurryBy Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The stunning attempt by Qwest Communications
International to snare two much bigger telecommunications carriers
has dragged BellSouth Corp. into a complex and uncertain game that
could turn into anything from a two-party bidding war to a five-way
alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Qwest's hostile offers for U.S. West and Frontier
Communications, valued at $66 billion Sunday were worth only $53.2
billion based on stock values after Monday's trading. But Qwest
means to outbid the $52 billion proposal already mounted by Global
Crossing.
</P>
<P>
   That proposition comes after a series of multi-billion mergers
by telecommunications companies from upstarts like WorldCom, which
swallowed MCI, to giants like AT&AMP;T that have purchased a range of
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The Qwest bid pits two hard-charging executives against each
other: Qwest Chief Executive Joseph Nacchio and Global Crossing CEO
Robert Annunziata, who said Monday that he plans to brush past
Qwest and complete the takeover of the two companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is definitely some gamesmanship going on,'' said analyst
Marc Bacurin of JC Bradford &AMP; Co. ``It could also be as simple as a
land rush.''
</P>
<P>
   Telecom analyst Jeff Kagan said the need for bandwidth _ the
lines that can carry huge amounts of data demanded by video _ is
behind the frantic buying. ``Customers will demand more from their
communications providers tomorrow. Today the Internet is pictures
and text. But tomorrow, video will play a large role in the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   The confrontation could spin BellSouth in a new direction, only
two months after the Atlanta-based company paid $3.5 billion for 10
percent of Qwest, aiming for access to the company's high-speed
network and long-distance service. BellSouth's interest in
acquiring the rest of Qwest has been stymied by federal law that _
at least for now _ limits the ownership of a regional Bell in a
long-distance company to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Should Qwest's two proposals be completed, millions of Qwest
shares will be distributed to owners of US West and Rochester,
NY-based Frontier, so current shareholders in Qwest would find
their ownership diluted. BellSouth's portion of Qwest would shrink
to less than 4 percent, and BellSouth would then have the option of
increasing its investment, said Qwest Chief Executive Joseph
Nacchio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel very comfortable with BellSouth being a 10 percent
owner, (or) we wouldn't have done the original transaction,''
Nacchio said. ``I think we're just going to let this play out.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth officials would not say whether the company would make
that additional investment nor whether it approved of the Qwest
maneuver. ``We consider this a merger or acquisition on which we
wouldn't comment,'' said spokesman Jeff Battcher. ``But the
announcement they have made doesn't change anything for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet if Nacchio succeeds, quite a few things might change. For
instance, Qwest would morph from a company with revenue of $4.5 to
one with $22 billion _ nearly equal to BellSouth. The combined
company's stock value might also rival BellSouth's $87 billion
value, while employing 71,000 people _ about the size of
BellSouth's local phone unit. Qwest would also have a wireless
phone unit, one with technology that does not mesh with that of
BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   Although neither Nacchio nor BellSouth would discuss it, it
seems unlikely that Qwest would have pursued the double-bid over
strenuous objections from BellSouth. But it also seems possible
that BellSouth was less than enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth officials have repeatedly stressed that the company
does not view bigger as better, but in talking to reporters Monday,
Nacchio emphasized the advantages of scale.
</P>
<P>
   And in making its bid, Qwest is also proposing to reshape the
company in which BellSouth invested. From high-speed and
long-distance, its business would expand to include local phone
service through Frontier as well as in US West's 14-state turf.
</P>
<P>
   A rapid-growth company, Qwest would shift to much slower growth.
And that change drew immediate rejection from Wall Street, where
Qwest stock Monday plummeted 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. West is a profitable local phone company that may be ahead
of BellSouth in introducing new high-speed services. But the
company has a reputation for less-than-stellar customer service.
U.S. West also sits astride the weakest, smallest region of any
Bell, and it looks even smaller now that SBC and Bell Atlantic are
consuming other regional companies.
</P>
<P>
   While those mega-deals thundered around them, BellSouth
officials have scoffed at the notion of buying U.S. West. But Qwest
is now drawing BellSouth into a complicated version of that
purchase. And perhaps Qwest is setting the stage for a five-company
chain.
</P>
<P>
   US West has a pending investment in Global Crossing, even if
their deal falls through. So the Qwest proposal potentially links
BellSouth _ strong in local, wireless and Latin America _ with
Qwest's long-distance, US West's cash engine, Frontier's
smorgasbord of services and Global Crossing's high-speed oceanic
lines.
</P>
<P>
   Global Crossing and Qwest might yet work out an amicable
settlement that pleases all the parties.
</P>
<P>
   And whether or not there is a five-way accord, BellSouth could
reassure investors and clinch a deal by entering the fray and
sharing the cost of Qwest's bid, said analyst James Hern of Olde
Discount Corp. ``They would add a more stable currency into the
mix.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecting the five could mean cheaper transport, making them
all more competitive, Hern said. ``Is it far fetched? Well, a
couple of years ago it would have been unthinkable.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
