<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INHOFE-PORNO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAYS CALL SENATOR HYPOCRITICAL AFTER HIS STAFFERS COLLECT PORN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation's largest gay rights organization
attacked Sen. James M. Inhofe Monday after staffers for the
Oklahoma Republican were found to have downloaded pornographic
material from the Internet into the Capitol Hill computer system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the ultimate hypocrisy,'' said David Smith, spokesman for
the group, the Human Rights Campaign. ``The sanctimonious,
holier-than-thou veil was ripped from the face of Senator Inhofe.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator, a hero to the religious right, has infuriated gay
activists since last year when he and three other conservatives put
a so-called ``hold'' on President Clinton's nomination of San
Francisco philanthropist James Hormel to become ambassador to
Luxembourg. That action blocked a vote on the nomination, which
requires Senate approval.
</P>
<P>
   On June 4, while Congress was on a 10-day break, Clinton
announced he was giving Hormel a recess appointment, which will
allow him to serve without Senate approval until the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Inhofe has said he feared Hormel, who is homosexual, would use
his post to promote a gay-rights agenda and would not be a proper
choice to serve as ambassador to a predominantly Catholic country.
Hormel's critics have also attacked him as a purveyor of smut
because he has financed a collection of homosexual material at San
Francisco's Main Public Library. Hormel has pledged not to pursue a
gay agenda in his new diplomatic post.
</P>
<P>
   After a Capitol Hill newspaper, Roll Call, revealed Monday that
Inhofe had taken action against some of his staffers for
downloading pornography from the Internet, the Human Rights
Campaign issued its attack.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said Inhofe was hypocritical in blocking Hormel's
nomination because of what the senator ``perceives to be a lack of
morality,'' when ``his own staff is downloading pornography on the
Senate computer system under his own nose on the taxpayers dime.''
</P>
<P>
   Inhofe spokesman Gary Hoitsma said Monday that the senator
``doesn't tolerate this sort of thing,'' which was discovered last
week by experts making a Capitol Hill computer systems check.
</P>
<P>
   Hoitsma said the senator's office has ``taken immediate,
forceful and appropriate disciplinary action,'' against the
staffers, but he refused to disclose how they were being punished.
``We're not going to get into the specifics,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Inhofe threatened to block all pending civilian
appointments by Clinton _ about 150 are pending _ unless the
president agrees to warn senators ``in advance of a recess'' that
he plans to make such an appointment while they are on leave.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Inhofe sent a letter to his fellow senators asking
them to support his plan as a protest against Clinton's recess
appointment of Hormel.
</P>
<P>
   But Hoitsma said the senator is not trying to force Hormel to
resign, ``We don't want to undo Hormel _ we understand that's a
done deal,'' Hoitsma said.
</P>
<P>
   Inhofe said in his letter that he is following a precedent set
by Sen. Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., in 1985, when Byrd as minority
leader blocked President Ronald Reagan's appointments until Reagan
agreed to stop making additional recess appointments.
</P>
<P>
   John Czwartacki, spokesman for Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott, R-Miss., said Lott was angered that the White House did not
notify him of Hormel's appointment until the evening before Clinton
announced it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lott very much shares the same concerns that Inhofe has about
how this administration has handled this appointment,'' Czwartacki
said, but he added that he expects the issue will be resolved
before any nominations are blocked in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're confident that this is going to be resolved,'' before
the dispute blocks key nominations, including Lawrence Summers as
treasury secretary and Richard Holbrooke as ambassador to the
United Nations, Czwartacki said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
