<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4998 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELGIUM-POLITICS-NYT     06-14 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELGIUM-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUDIATED BY VOTERS, BELGIUM'S PRIME MINISTER RESIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Prime Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene of Belgium resigned
Monday after voters swept away his center-left coalition government
in elections on Sunday. The government had been heavily criticized
for its handling of a dioxin scare that cleared poultry, beef, eggs
and butter from food stores here and frightened countries around
the world into halting food imports from Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Dehaene, who was Europe's senior statesman after seven years in
office, said he was thinking of quitting politics. ``I think that
for myself it is time to start doing other things,'' Dehaene, 59,
told journalists in Brussels Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-nation European Union is unhappy with his decision late
last week to put food products certified as safe back on the
shelves and clear them for export. The union's agricultural experts
said they were not convinced by Belgium's assurances that it had
identified all the meat-producing customers of a company that
supplied them earlier this year with animal and chicken feed
contaminated by fuel oil that contained cancer-causing dioxin.
</P>
<P>
   Dehaene, a leader from the Flemish-speaking northern part of the
country, said it was important to form a new government quickly to
deal with the crisis. But Belgian politics are so fragmented across
ideological, ethnic and linguistic lines that it almost always
takes months after an election to put a coalition together.
</P>
<P>
   The two biggest regions, the prosperous north where the language
is close to Dutch, and the unemployment-ridden industrial rust belt
in the French-speaking south, are almost like separate countries,
each with its own political parties, labor unions, television and
radio stations. With Brussels and a small German-speaking region in
the east, they share passports, armed forces, a national railroad
system with trains going almost everywhere, and a king, Albert II,
who accepted Dehaene's resignation offer Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Dehaene's Christian Democrat party in Flanders won 14 percent of
the vote, 3.2 percentage points fewer than it did in 1995. With the
biggest single share of the vote won by the pro-business Liberal
party in French-speaking Wallonia, with 24.3 percent of the vote
and 41 seats in the 150-member Parliament, there was speculation
that its leader, Louis Michel, could be the next prime minister.
Unlike many people in the southern part of the country, he is said
to speak good Flemish as well as French.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalist parties made gains, with 20 seats, but so did
the ultra-nationalist Vlaams Blok party in the Flemish-speaking
part of the country. It will have 15 seats and wants independence
for Flanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The era of the big parties is over,'' said Jacky Morael,
leader of the Ecolo party in the French-speaking region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-99 1838EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990614.0321 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5000 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REYNOLDS-COX     06-14 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REYNOLDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tobacco branch of RJR Nabisco front and center _ and on its own
_ in NYSE
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. _ Shares of R.J. Reynolds Tobacco begin
trading publicly today for the first time in 29 years, but Melrose
Stocks isn't buying.
</P>
<P>
   ''Tobacco is still under massive attack,'' said Stocks, a
retired Winston-Salem school teacher who inherited 403 shares of
RJR Nabisco stock from her deceased husband.
</P>
<P>
   She plans to ''play a wait-and-see game'' on the hope that the
new shares' value will increase. She added, though, ''If I were a
new investor, I probably would go somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Skepticism among investors greets the return of America's
second-largest cigarette maker to the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   RJR Nabisco Holdings Corp.'s recent spin-off of its tobacco
business created two independent publicly traded companies.
</P>
<P>
   Parent RJR Nabisco has been renamed Nabisco Group Holdings
Corp., and it remains the nation's largest cookie and cracker maker
with brands including Oreo and Ritz. It trades under the symbol
``NGH.''
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco spin-off is R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Holdings Inc.,
trading under the symbol ``RJR.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday was the last day RJR Nabisco Holding's shares traded.
They reached a 52-week peak of $33.56 1/4 before finishing at $32,
down 43 3/4 cents. Nearly 30.6 million shares changed hands, or
about 15 times average daily volume.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Nabisco Group Holdings rose 37 1/2 cents to $21.81 1/4
in when-issued trading. R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Holdings fell $1 to
$32.25. Shareholders on Monday received one share of R.J. Reynolds
Tobacco stock for every three shares of Nabisco Group Holdings they
owned as of May 27.
</P>
<P>
   The stock last traded as R.J. Reynolds Tobacco in 1970. That's
when directors renamed the company R.J. Reynolds Industries Inc. to
reflect its 1960s diversification beyond tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Now standing on its own as a pure tobacco company for the first
time since 1963, Reynolds faces the full brunt of legal and
competitive threats, coupled with declining market share.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds' share of U.S. smokers has fallen in recent years. It
ended the first quarter at 24.4 percent, compared with 25.2 percent
in 1998. By contrast, No. 1 Philip Morris boosted its share to 49.4
percent in the last quarter, up from 48.6 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''If this trend continues, it could adversely affect Reynolds
Tobacco's sales volumes, financial condition and/or results of
operations,'' a report warned last month.
</P>
<P>
   That potentially ominous outlook came not from a skeptical
analyst, but from Reynolds documents preceding its stock trading.
</P>
<P>
   Yet with drastically reduced debt, Reynolds is poised to
''reward shareholders'' and show investors that it can stabilize
and increase earnings, Chief Executive Andrew Schindler said in an
interview Monday.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare for the spin-off, RJR Nabisco sold its international
tobacco business to Japan Tobacco Inc. for $7.8 billion. Part of
the proceeds reduced Reynolds' debt from $6.5 billion to $2
billion. Coupled with $1.1 billion in cash, Reynolds now figures
its debt at $900 million.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a very, very strong balance sheet we are ending up
with,'' said Schindler, a 25-year Reynolds veteran.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from paying an attractive dividend that over time could be
increased, Schindler said Reynolds now has the resources to invest
in its key brands, which include Camel, Winston, Salem and Doral.
The board also may consider acquisitions, said Schindler, a
54-year-old director.
</P>
<P>
   He said he recently wrapped up two weeks of meetings with
institutional investors, and he came away feeling ''very positive''
about the company's prospects.
</P>
<P>
   In a skittish sign, however, the institutional investors were
most interested in how large a dividend the company will pay,
Schindler said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have speculated that Reynolds could pay as much as
$3.60 a share in a yearly dividend, resulting in a yield of 9
percent to 10 percent. That would easily surpass the dividend of
No. 1 cigarette maker Philip Morris' dividend yielding 4.17
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The company's board of directors, still being assembled, plans
to set a dividend July 28.
</P>
<P>
   Although he wasn't willing to characterize the company's
dividend as ''rich,'' Schindler said investors ''would buy Reynolds
stock for the purpose of getting a meaningful dividend and one that
produces a competitively high yield....More importantly, it would
be sustainable.''
</P>
<P>
   In Winston-Salem, Reynolds' birthplace 124 years ago, brokers
were reluctant to talk publicly about Reynolds' stock. Some said
local interest in it had been scant.
</P>
<P>
   Such hometown reluctance differs sharply from a decade ago, when
townsfolk watched in amazement as the takeover fight for RJR
Nabisco vaulted the stock over $100 a share.
</P>
<P>
   The 1985 merger of Reynolds and Nabisco Brands set the stage for
the $26.4 billion buyout of RJR Nabisco in 1989 by Kohlberg Kravis
Roberts &AMP; Co., at that time the largest leveraged buyout in U.S.
corporate history.
</P>
<P>
   But the hard-fought deal, chronicled in the best-selling
''Barbarians at the Gate'' burdened RJR with $700 million to $800
million in annual debt. It weakened Reynolds against No. 1 Philip
Morris and made Reynolds more vulnerable to mounting health-related
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds' problems dragged down the stock of RJR Nabisco, which
resumed trading in 1991. Directors faced nearly constant pressure
from shareholders to separate tobacco from the food and beverage
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   RJR Nabisco's board announced the spin-off in March. Even now,
some investors remain wary of Reynolds' prospects.
</P>
<P>
   There were 653 cases pending against RJR Nabisco and Reynolds
Tobacco as of May 14. The Justice Department plans to sue to
recover federal health-care costs associated with cigarette
smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Jones broker Jim Barrett said some of his clients who
hold the stock are hoping for a big dividend, but he's seen little
interest from new buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are still shell-shocked by the modest
performance of RJR in recent years,'' said Barrett, of nearby
Kenersville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Burritt writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-99 1839EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
