<SLUG> BC-SUTURE-LAWSUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LAWSUIT TARGETS SUTURE MAKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LANCE WILLIAMS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Nine Northern Californians who say they suffered
raging infections after routine operations in 1994 and 1995 are
blaming their ailments on improperly sterilized surgical sutures.
</P>
<P>
   Ethicon Inc., a subsidiary of the giant Johnson &AMP; Johnson
medical supply company and the world's leading suture maker, has
denied that its products made anyone sick.
</P>
<P>
   But in a lawsuit filed last week in Alameda County Superior
Court, the nine patients charged that they had become ill because
Ethicon had distributed millions of its trademark Vicryl sutures in
1994 even though they were contaminated during processing in a
sterilizer unit prone to breakdowns.
</P>
<P>
   According to the lawsuit, Ethicon downplayed the risks the
sutures posed to patients and failed to issue timely warnings to
doctors and hospitals. As a result, the nine patients said they had
become ill _ some for years _ without knowing why.
</P>
<P>
   That changed in February, they said in the complaint, when the
San Francisco Examiner published a series of stories on the
sterilizer breakdown and its aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   The stories quoted from lawsuits and U.S. Food and Drug
Administration records indicating that more than 100 patients in
nine states had blamed the sutures for debilitating post-operative
infections _ from staphylococcus and a rare bacteria related to
tuberculosis _ in 1994 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The stories gave the nine patients their first clue as to why
they became ill, said Wendy York, the lead lawyer in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is, Ethicon got caught. Now a lot of people
know why they got their post-op infections,'' the Sacramento lawyer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Prodded by FDA inspectors, Ethicon in September 1994 issued a
voluntary recall of some 3.6 million sutures that had been
processed in a new sterilizer system at its San Angelo, Texas,
plant. About 25 percent were returned, the FDA now says, instead of
the 2 percent it earlier reported.
</P>
<P>
   The sterilizer had malfunctioned repeatedly, and the company
finally shut it down in May 1994, court records show. Since the
incident, the company has made confidential settlements in lawsuits
brought by 22 victims who blamed the sutures for their infections,
according to public records.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Odenthal, a spokeswoman for the company, said Ethicon had
no comment on the Alameda County lawsuit because corporate
officials had not had time to review it.
</P>
<P>
   In other lawsuits and in letters to Congress, Ethicon has
contended that its sutures didn't cause any postoperative
infections.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit filed in Alameda County says Ethicon's insistence
that the sutures were basically safe despite the sterilizer
breakdowns misled doctors, causing them to ``misdiagnose or
inadequately treat'' their patients.
</P>
<P>
   The nine patients joining in the lawsuit had surgery for a wide
range of problems _ from back and shoulder ailments to breast
cancer _ but all allegedly involved Ethicon's Vicryl suture, which
is supposed to gradually dissolve as the surgical incision heals.
</P>
<P>
   The patients say their operations were routine, but that they
then developed infections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
