<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore hits on gun control topics at mayoral conference
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Youths aged 18 to 20 make up 4 percent of the U.S.
population but commit one-fourth of the nation's gun murders, and
that's why Congress needs to raise the legal age for handgun
possession to 21, Vice President Al Gore said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the simplest terms, 18- to 20-year-olds represent the group
most likely to kill, the most likely to kill with a gun, and the
most likely to use a gun when committing a crime other than
murder,'' Gore told more than 300 mayors and other officials
gathered here for the annual U.S. Conference of Mayors. His
statistics came from a joint federal study released Monday by the
Justice Department and the Treasury Department.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also called on Congress to pass a law requiring child
safety locks on guns and requiring background checks for people who
buy firearms at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who are fighting against closing this loophole are
fighting against common sense,'' he said. The Senate, thanks to
Gore's tie-breaking vote, passed a measure requiring background
checks at gun shows, but the legislation is meeting resistance in
the House. ``I had not reckoned on the power of the National Rifle
Association.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's proposals were welcomed with applause by the mayors. The
proposed legislation echoes proposals detailed in a letter sent
Monday by the mayors conference to House Speaker Dennis Hastert.
The House is debating gun control this week on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great speech,'' said Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell, who
was in New Orleans for the conference. ``I'm delighted he's taking
such a strong position.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thinks Congress will pass tougher gun laws, Campbell
said Americans are demanding it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember that the same proposal failed in the Senate and then
passed after the carnage in Littleton and Conyers,'' he said,
referring to the two most recent school shooting tragedies. ``We're
closer than we've ever been.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell and New Orleans Mayor Marc Morial have joined leaders
in at least 17 other cities in filing lawsuits against the gun
industry. New Orleans filed the first such suit.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said he thinks it's funny that people were shocked that
he filed Atlanta's lawsuit against the gun industry just as the NRA
was headed to town for a convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want them to come back unless they have background
checks at their gun shows,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's proposals for stricter gun laws were one part of a
three-pronged approach he advocates for creating more livable
communities. The second strategy is connecting Americans who
usually fall through the cracks to jobs and other opportunities,
and the third is to overhaul the nation's schools.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Gore was host at a $1,000-per-person
fund-raiser in a Bourbon Street jazz bar. Gore staffers said the
event raised more than $250,000, more than twice the amount tallied
at a similar event for President Clinton four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Though he's often painted as a robotic speaker, Gore broke with
tradition by strutting into the Storyville Jazz Bar in the city's
French Quarter district with a musical procession known as a Second
Line and took a few dance steps to the music.
</P>
<P>
   The speeches were Gore's last major addresses before he
officially announces his presidential candidacy Wednesday in his
hometown of Carthage, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Rochell Konigsmark writes for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
