<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5042 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NIEUWENDYK-BOS &LR;      06-14 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NIEUWENDYK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIEUWENDYK A STAR AMONG STARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Speed and youth have collided with age and
experience here in the Stanley Cup finals. The Buffalo Sabres, the
new kids on the block, have clashed three times now with the Dallas
Stars, the National Hockey League's playing tribute to the American
Association of Retired People.
</P>
<P>
   Take heart, Baby Boomers, thus far gray hair and wrinkles have
it all over Generation X. The Stars aren't old; they're
distinguished. The Sabres are young and have been made to look
foolish, their legs racing but going nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the advantage lies in young legs right now,''
mused Buffalo coach Lindy Ruff, his club in a 2-1 disadvantage
headed into Game 4 here Tuesday. ``If that was the case, the game
the other night, we should have looked a lot better against them _
because that was three games in five nights. I was thinking that
theory a lot earlier, but I'm not thinking it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece in Dallas's why-old-people-do-good-things
revival show is Joe Nieuwendyk. The 32-year-old pivot popped in the
winner in Game 3, a 2-1 triumph, giving him six winners this
postseason, tying the league record held by Joe Sakic. An
exceptional lacrosse player in his youth, Nieuwendyk scored the
winner with a menacing forehand lift to the top right corner that
not even the great Dominik Hasek could touch with his
lightning-quick glove.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's more instinct and reaction,'' said Nieuwendyk after the
Stars' afternoon workout here at Marine Midland Arena, where the
best-of-seven series resumes at 8 p.m. ``In a situation like that,
you don't get much time to think about taking it upstairs. There's
not much room. Things happen pretty fast. I just went with my
instinct.''
</P>
<P>
   In today's game of programmed defenses and strict adherence to
positional play at both ends of the ice, the instinctual,
spontaneous player has become a rarity. For the most part,
Nieuwendyk's game is based more on defense than touch. The Stars
have the talented Mike Modano and Brett Hull as their primary
creators and shooters. But Nieuwendyk, a key to the Calgary Flames'
Stanley Cup championship in 1989, is the best blend of offense and
defense rolled in the same Lone Star suit.
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk now leads all playoff scorers with 11 goals and 21
points in 20 games. When the series with Buffalo began, he and
Sabres captain Michael Peca stood even as candidates to win the
Conn Smythe Trophy as postseason MVP. Headed into this game,
however, the 6-foot-1-inch, 195-pound Nieuwendyk stands as the
prohibitive favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he felt like he got cheated last year,'' said Dallas
defenseman Craig Ludwig, another of the Stars' oldsters. ``But he's
making the most of it right now. He's not just scoring goals, he's
scoring timely goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk exited last year's playoffs in the first period of
Dallas's first-round match against the San Jose Sharks, clobbered
from behind by one of Bryan Marchment's patented brutal hits. The
Stars went on to beat the Sharks, rubbed out the Oilers in Round 2,
and then folded up in the Western Conference finals. When the
playoff ride ended, Nieuwendyk already was almost a month into his
rehabilitation from surgery on both knees. Had he not been
disabled, the Stars might have made it to the finals last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was difficult, not to be part of it,'' recalled Nieuwendyk,
who teams now on a line with Jamie Langenbrunner and ex-Bruin Dave
Reid. ``When you get to (the Cup finals), you realize what it takes
to get through the playoff run. To get to this point and not be
there last year was disappointing. I'm thrilled to death to be
healthy, playing, and doing what I can to help this team win.''
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, just two years removed from the Cornell campus,
Nieuwendyk hoisted the Cup high with his Calgary teammates. He was
not even 23 years old. Spiraling salaries and the imbalance between
the American and Canadian dollar hadn't yet crippled the
small-market Flames.
</P>
<P>
   As the years rolled by, though, the Flames found it tougher to
compete and tougher to pay. Eventually, Nieuwendyk was dealt to the
Flames (for Corey Millen and Jarome Iginla) after a protacted
contract holdout at the start of the '95-96 season. Nieuwendyk went
from '90 to '97 playing on clubs that didn't make it out of the
first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think it's going to be easy,'' said Nieuwendyk, reflecting
on the Flames' initial success when he arrived there, which
included his winning the Calder Trophy as the league's rookie of
the year in '88. ``You think this is going to be the way it is in
the NHL. You realize it can be tough to get back.''
</P>
<P>
   But he's back now, playing longer and better than he has in the
playoffs in a decade. His presence makes Buffalo's defensive task
maddening. If Peca has to check Mike Modano's line, usually with
Jere Lehtinen and Brett Hull, he can't be rolled out to stop the
Nieuwendyk trio. The beat goes on for Nieuwendyk and the Stars, and
it has turned into a beating for the Sabres.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
