<HEADER>
A5049 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-GAMBLING-NYT &LR;      06-14 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-GAMBLING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT RULING IS MAJOR WIN FOR CASINOS AND BROADCASTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., Miss., N.J., Nev., Conn.)  (See also SCOTUS-RDP) 
(mk) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Monday unanimously struck down
a 65-year-old ban on broadcast advertising of casino gambling,
ruling on First Amendment grounds that the federal law ``sacrifices
an intolerable amount of truthful speech about lawful conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision, reflecting the court's growing solicitude for
advertising and other forms of commercial speech, was a major
victory for the casino industry and for broadcasters, who have
challenged the ban in cases from Atlantic City, N.J., to Las Vegas.
The case Monday was from New Orleans, where a group of broadcasters
sued the federal government for the right to carry advertising for
casino gambling in Louisiana and Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcasters, along with the commercial gambling industry, have
grown increasingly restive under the advertising prohibition
because Congress amended the law in 1988 to permit gambling
advertising by casinos owned by Indian tribes. That meant, for
example, that the Mashantucket Pequot Indians in Connecticut could
advertise gambling in their popular Foxwoods casino to the New York
radio and television market, but that the casinos in Atlantic City
could not advertise gambling. The restrictions permitted general
advertising of casinos as vacation destinations.
</P>
<P>
   In striking down the ban Monday, the court focused on the
irrationality of making distinctions among advertisers, while at
the same time suggesting that a more uniform and ``coherent''
policy of advertising restrictions might well have been upheld.
</P>
<P>
   That analysis, which ratified the court's current approach to
commercial speech, left the door open for the court to uphold, in
future cases, restrictions on the advertising of other lawful
products, like tobacco. In its next term, the court will decide
whether the Food and Drug Administration, which has proposed broad
restrictions on cigarette advertising, has jurisdiction to regulate
tobacco products.
</P>
<P>
   The ban on casino advertising, part of the original
Communications Act of 1934, which prohibited advertising for all
forms of gambling, has had a mixed record recently in the lower
federal courts. The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, which is
based in San Francisco and includes Nevada in its jurisdiction,
struck it down in a 1997 decision that the Supreme Court declined
to review. The U.S. District Court in Camden, N.J., also overturned
the ban, in a case now on appeal to the 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals, in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   But in New Orleans, the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
rejected the broadcasters' attack and ruled last year that the ban
was a reasonable way for the government to control the demand for
gambling, and thus to limit the social ills that flow from it.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the court on Monday, Justice John Paul Stevens said
that while the government's interests were valid, and theoretically
defensible, the law as it exists ``is so pierced by exemptions and
inconsistencies'' that good intensions could not salvage it or
``overcome the presumption that the speaker and the audience, not
the government, should be left to assess the value of accurate and
nonmisleading information about lawful conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that not only had Congress authorized broadcast
advertisements for tribal casinos, but that an earlier amendment,
in 1975, created an exception for state-run lotteries. In addition,
Stevens said, the Federal Communications Commission, in
administering the law, has interpreted it in ways that ``underscore
the statute's infirmity.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, broadcasters may carry advertising for
``Vegas-style excitement'' but not ``Vegas-style games.'' The court
noted that the commission approved a television commercial stating
that the ``odds for fun are high.'' Establishments that have
``casino'' as part of their name may use it in their
advertisements; for these and similar reasons, advertising for
casino gambling may in fact appear ubiquitous in many markets, but
what is now being advertised is not the gambling as such, but the
casino as an exciting vacation destination.
</P>
<P>
   But the court's primary focus, for reasons of both pragmatism
and First Amendment doctrine, was on the distinction between tribal
and non-Indian casinos. With 33 states now having tribal casinos,
compared with 11 that permit non-Indian casino gambling, it was
evident to the court that the exception was essentially swallowing
the rule. And further, Stevens said, ``decisions that select among
speakers conveying virtually identical messages are in serious
tension with the principles undergirding the First Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Had the federal government adopted a more coherent
policy, or accommodated the rights of speakers in states that have
legalized the underlying conduct, this might be a different case.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the court's recent commercial speech decisions, including
a 1996 ruling that struck down a Rhode Island law prohibiting the
inclusion of prices in liquor advertising, the government was
considered likely to lose this case, Greater New Orleans
Broadcasting Association vs. U.S., No. 98-387. The open question
was what analysis the court would use and what the implications of
the decision might be.
</P>
<P>
   Sidestepping invitations contained in numerous briefs to revise
its approach to commercial speech and elevate it to the high level
of protection now accorded political speech, the court instead
applied long-settled law and broke no new ground. Notably, the
court did not adopt the categorical view, urged by Justice Clarence
Thomas in a separate concurring opinion, that the First Amendment
does not permit the government to restrict advertising about a
product that is legal to sell.
</P>
<P>
   That approach would have placed a daunting obstacle in the path
of regulating tobacco advertising. While a settlement last fall
between 46 states and the tobacco industry included an array of
advertising restrictions, accepted by the industry as part of the
agreement to terminate lawsuits by the states, the Food and Drug
Administration has proposed more sweeping restrictions that the
industry is challenging as unconstitutional. The question of their
constitutionality, however, will ultimately be decided only if the
Supreme Court finds, in a case to be argued next fall, that the
agency has jurisdiction over tobacco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
