<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5060 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-EUROPE-NYT     06-14 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-EUROPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAIR REMAINS STEADFAST DESPITE SURPRISING CONSERVATIVE GAINS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Prime Minister Tony Blair said Monday that his
government would stick to its pro-European stance despite the
apparent rejection of that policy by British voters electing the
country's 87 members of the European Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives, in their first success against Blair since he
became prime minister two years ago, won 36 seats to Labor's 29,
and the Tories' leader, William Hague, said it was his hardline
campaign to keep the country from adopting the euro as its currency
that was responsible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have struck a blow for the independence of our country and
the future of the pound,'' Hague said of the surprising Tory
showing. Pledging to intensify his anti-euro campaign, he said:
``Political parties who think they can bounce the people of this
country into abolishing their currency without debating it properly
have had something of a shock in this election, and I think they're
in for a bigger shock in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   While the size of the Tory victory was surprising, its
importance was called into question by the low turnout, 23 percent
of the voters, the lowest figure ever recorded in a national
election.
</P>
<P>
   It fit into a pattern across the continent, where center-right
parties succeeded in overturning socialist and center-left
dominance of the European Parliament for the first time since the
Strasbourg assembly became directly elected in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Subdued and appearing chastened, Blair told a press conference
in the Rose Garden behind 10 Downing Street, the official
residence, that ``obviously these are very disappointing results,
and I don't pretend otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added, ``We have got to hold firm to the position we
have,'' saying that ``for this country to pull away from Europe all
together, when over 50 percent of our trade is with Europe, when
millions of jobs are dependent on Europe, would be a very big
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair's position has been to prepare British business and public
opinion for eventual entry into monetary union but to postpone a
promised referendum on the decision until joining would be more
economically advantageous to Britain, probably in two or three
years.
</P>
<P>
   During Hague's embattled two years as party leader, he has
toughened the Conservative stance against the euro, saying Britain
should drop all ideas of joining anytime in the next eight years
and should maintain a dubious attitude about ever signing up.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to furthering the anti-euro cause, the Tory
performance shored up Hague's ebbing leadership and threw on the
defensive critics within the party who had claimed his
uncompromising ``save sterling'' position was costing the party the
mainstream support it needs to get back into power.
</P>
<P>
   The general British unhappiness with the idea of integration
with the Continent was illustrated by the unexpected capture of
three seats by the new, single-issue U.K. Independence Party, which
is opposed to all relations with Europe except trade.
</P>
<P>
   In Northern Ireland, the last area of Britain to report results,
the Rev. Ian Paisley of the militant Ulster Democratic Unionists,
was once again the largest vote-getter, with John Hume, the leader
of the moderate Social Democratic and Labor Party, coming in
second, and James Nicholson of the Ulster Unionists edging out
Mitchel McLaughlin of Sinn Fein, the political wing of the Irish
Republican Army, for the province's third seat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
