<DOCNO> NYT19990614.0340 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5087 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-14 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: LORDS AND JUDGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ANTHONY LEWIS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Imagine that appointees to the Supreme Court of the
United States were first made members of the Senate. Imagine that
the justices heard arguments in a Senate committee room, announced
their decisions on the Senate floor _ and in addition to deciding
cases, could vote as senators on legislation.
</P>
<P>
   That fantasy is reality in Britain. The 12 Law Lords, making up
the country's court of last resort, are members of the upper
chamber of Parliament, the House of Lords; they sit as its Judicial
Committee. As part of the fiction that they are a mere committee of
the House, they do not wear robes and wigs as other English judges
do. They hear arguments in business suits.
</P>
<P>
   All that may change, and not just to straighten out the
confusion of appearance and reality that often marks British
institutions. The law has become a much more important factor in
the British system, and many believe it is time to have a genuine,
demonstrably independent supreme court.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, British judges performed a much narrower function
than their American counterparts. Because Britain had a unitarian
system of government and no written constitution, its judges did
not have to sort out intergovernmental conflicts or pass on claims
that constitutional guarantees had been violated.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the Law Lords themselves restricted their role. In
interpreting legislation, they looked only at the face of the
statute, refusing to read legislative history. They had a rule
against reconsidering their own past decisions. And they rarely
reviewed what administrators had done; they were, Lord Devlin said,
``quite anxious not to tread on the executive toes.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last 30 years those traditional attitudes have undergone
what amounts to a revolution. Today the Law Lords look at
legislative history, reconsider past decisions and often stamp on
government toes by finding administrative decisions unlawful.
</P>
<P>
   And now the courts are about to perform something like American
constitutional functions. Scotland has been given its own
Parliament, so there will inevitably be conflicts between its
powers and the central government's _ conflicts to be resolved in
court. And next year the European Convention on Human Rights _ with
free-speech and other guarantees _ will become enforceable in
British courts.
</P>
<P>
   As presently constituted, the judicial House of Lords is ill
equipped to cope with these larger duties. The judges have little
if any support staff. They have no regular courtroom. They sit in
panels of five or occasionally seven, with retired judges
participating when needed; the accident of who sits can matter.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the extraordinary position of the lord chancellor.
He is a member of the Cabinet _ that is, part of the executive. He
chooses the judges. He is the speaker of the House of Lords, so he
is part of the legislature. He is the head of the judiciary in
England and Wales, and can sit as a Law Lord whenever he wishes.
His multifarious character might have been invented by Gilbert and
Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   A leading legal organization, Justice, has called for changes in
the position of the Law Lords and the lord chancellor. It urges
that the judges of Britain's highest court should not be members of
the House of Lords _ because it is inappropriate for them to look
like and sometimes act as legislators. They should form a supreme
court, with its own building and ``sufficient resources.'' The lord
chancellor should not sit as a judge and should cease being head of
the judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal by Justice went to a royal commission that is
considering reform of the legislative House of Lords. The focus has
been on how to choose its members when hereditary peers, as
planned, lose their vote. But the potential is also there for a
significant change in the legal structure.
</P>
<P>
   The present lord chancellor, Lord Irvine, is likely to resist
change in his role. And he is close to Prime Minister Tony Blair.
</P>
<P>
   But the trend is toward what has been required by the U.S.
Constitution but has always been ignored here, the idea of the
separation of powers _ or at least the judicial power. The court of
last resort has become too important to be treated as an
afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
