<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5093 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-ART-2TA     06-14 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE AWKWARDLY GOES FROM UNDERSTUDY TO LEADING ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: N.H., Tenn.)  (Eds: 2nd take is scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET) 
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ Al Gore is walking up the path to a home here
where 40 people have gathered to listen to his pitch. He has shed
his blue suit (as per President Clinton's instructions) for a green
polo shirt, khakis and cowboy boots. Spotting his host, who is
wearing a tie and sports jacket, Gore calls out, ``I hope I'm not
too informal!''
</P>
<P>
   That may be wishful thinking. Even in his casual, earth-tone
clothes, Al Gore seems pressed and starched. His language, too, has
that same formal quality. ``I want to engage in a dialogue with
you,'' he begins, then jumps straight to what he alerts his
audience is ``my punch line: I want to be president and I need your
support.''
</P>
<P>
   As he sets the stage for the official announcement of his
candidacy Wednesday in Tennessee, the vice president still seems to
be painting by numbers, following the chalk while he is learning to
dance, telling his audience as much as reminding himself exactly
what he is doing and why.
</P>
<P>
   For all of his years of practice for the 2000 election _ he was
groomed in a political family in Washington, has already run for
president once, and has understudied with a political master for
the last seven years _ Gore seems oddly unprepared for it.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Gore probably has a more extensive record on issues
than anyone else running for president. From his votes in 16 years
in Congress, his authorship of a book on global warming and more
than six years as Clinton's vice president, Gore has had to take
specific stands on hundreds of topics _ from abortion rights to
ethanol subsidies to trade with China (he favors them all) _ in a
way that few other candidates have.
</P>
<P>
   Still, voters do not know who Gore is and what he is about _ his
pollster Mark Penn calls him ``famous but unknown.''
</P>
<P>
   His campaign hopes to change that on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore camp views the announcement speech as an opportunity
for Gore to emerge from Clinton's shadow and begin to define
himself. The speech also gives him the chance to try to close the
book on a period in which most of the information seeping out about
Gore has been negative: his exaggerated claims about creating the
Internet, his questionable money-gathering at a Buddhist temple,
his steadfastness to Clinton during impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most importantly, it gives him a chance to present
himself in human terms _ he will talk a lot about himself and his
family _ and to try to overcome the perception that he is a wooden
technocrat, or, in the word that most people said in a Pew poll was
the one that immediately came to mind when asked about Gore,
``boring.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With our announcement, we are now in the next phase of our
campaign,'' Tony Coelho, the former California congressman who is
chairman of the Gore campaign, said in an interview. ``The vice
president will be dealing directly with the American people on
specific issues.''
</P>
<P>
   It is highly unusual for a presidential candidate to get as
specific as Gore intends to this early in a campaign. But Gore
aides believe this will help the vice president separate himself
from Clinton and show up the weaknesses in the two rivals he is
most worried about, former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey on the
Democratic side and Texas Gov. George W. Bush among the
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   While he has adhered to Clinton's policies, Gore is starting to
put his stamp on certain issues. He has already given a speech on
education and called for universal preschool. He wants to increase
the federal government's reliance on religious institutions to help
with social programs, like drug-treatment. He wants to revive the
fight for health-care coverage for people without insurance. He
wants to limit suburban sprawl and traffic jams as part of what he
calls his ``livability agenda.'' And he will be giving policy
speeches regularly from here on out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing,'' Coelho said, ``is for Al Gore to
say who he is before the Republicans say who he is and before
Bradley says who he is, and to have the American people relate to
him.''
</P>
<P>
   The strategy is also intended to smoke out Bush, whose inaugural
speeches this week have been broadly thematic. By being specific,
the theory goes, Gore will force Bush to take positions that might
reveal himself to be more conservative, on gun control and
abortion, for example, than swing voters are willing to tolerate;
if Bush does not get specific, the Gore camp says, he will appear
inexperienced and unprepared to lead the country.
</P>
<P>
   Specificity also helps Gore distinguish himself from Clinton.
Gore has a tricky task here. He wants to live up to Clinton's
successes, but he must also live down his failures.
</P>
<P>
   The glaring Clinton success is the economy. Gore is running as
the man who can continue the prosperity of the Clinton years. ``We
know what works,'' he assures audiences.
</P>
<P>
   The glaring Clinton failure is on the character issue and the
extramarital activities that led to his impeachment. Pollsters say
that ``Clinton fatigue'' _ a weariness with the administration's
scandals _ has been sapping energy from the Gore candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   To counteract that, Gore advisers said the vice president would
emphasize his family-man credentials _ married 29 years, father of
four, expectant grandfather. To reinforce the message, Coelho said,
Gore is to appear on the ABC program ``20/20'' on Wednesday, the
day of his announcement speech, and make it clear that he
disapproved of Clinton's personal behavior.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Gore was hesitant to criticize his boss in public.
Forced by reporters to confront the issue last September, Gore
would only use the president's own words, ``I agree with him that
it's indefensible.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore also declared Clinton a great president on the day in
December when the House voted to impeach him _ an image the Gore
campaign would like to erase, instead making it clear that Gore
condemns such behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Marla Romash, the deputy campaign manager, said that most people
do not know much about Gore and that at the top of her list of
qualities was this: ``He's a loving father.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore is mentioning his wife, Tipper, at every turn. This helps
him solidify the family image, puts some personality on his blank
slate and is intended to help him connect with women voters. As
Gore told his audience here, he had to cancel their anniversary
dinner last month because he needed to break a tie vote in the
Senate on a gun-control measure _ which, he added, was fine with
his wife. ``She is, if anything, more anti-gun than I am,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In its increasingly extensive use of Mrs. Gore, the campaign is
also presenting her, subliminally, as the anti-Hillary. She has
said she would not be the same kind of first lady as Hillary Rodham
Clinton. She has acknowledged a bout of depression, giving her an
air of vulnerability and casting the Gore family as close-knit and
caring. The Gores have let it be known that during impeachment,
while Gore was backing the president, Mrs. Gore was unforgiving.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
