<SLUG> BC-YUGO-KLA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KLA MOVE INTO KOSOVO TOWN HEIGHTENS TENSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRIZREN, Kosovo _ The Kosovo Liberation Army swept in early
Monday morning and took control of two major neighborhoods in this
city, setting up a potential political conflict with international
peacekeeping troops and a possible military clash with
yet-to-depart Serb militia.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-afternoon, KLA soldiers in full uniform and armed for
battle had set up checkpoints in Albanian streets of this
multi-ethnic city, in apparent violation of the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not allowed,'' said Col. Rolf Bescht, an officer with the
German peacekeeping troops who have been arriving for the past
several days. Bescht said Kosovo Force (KFOR) representatives had
informed the KLA it was in the wrong, but conceded that ``we cannot
be at every point in the area.''
</P>
<P>
   The presence of the KLA _ which leaders said was 1,000-strong _
complicates what already has been a very tense and violent
transition of power in this region.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs were supposed to be out of the area by midnight and a
peacekeeping force of German and Dutch soldiers is supposed to then
have full control of the town.
</P>
<P>
   But while the international peacekeepers clearly had a more
established presence in town Monday, the issue of who controls
Prizren was still very much in question.
</P>
<P>
   Serb civilians scuttled to pack their cars and leave town,
fearful that they would be the target of vengeful Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   KLA commander Rexha Aekrem, who goes by the nom-de-guerre of
Commander Drini, said his soldiers would keep order in the area as
long as they were needed.
</P>
<P>
   The KFOR troops ``are not enough'' to protect civilians from
attacks by lingering Serb military or civilians, Drini said. ``We
will be the force who will control the situation,'' he said from a
local KLA post, just 200 yards from a KFOR tank.
</P>
<P>
   Drini warned of a possible showdown between the KLA and the Serb
paramilitary, which he said were occupying two apartment buildings
near the KLA local command. The 17 paramilitary were rumored to be
planning to loot and torch the buildings as they left.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told KFOR (this) and we will be very happy if they would be
there,'' Drini said. But ``we will not stay and wait for them.''
</P>
<P>
   As a parting shot, Serb military trashed and burned Albanian
houses early Monday morning, less than a day after peacekeepers
entered the city, witnesses said. The slogans ``Death to
Albanians'' and ``Serbia All the Way to Tokyo'' were spray-painted
on the outer walls of the Albanians' houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's terrible. I'm afraid of booby-traps and mines,'' said a
shaking and weeping Zade Hoxha, standing at the threshold of her
virtually destroyed home. Hoxha had been hiding with her husband in
a neighbor's house when, she said, the Serbs smashed, shot up,
burned and then left the Hoxha home they had been occupying.
</P>
<P>
   The scheduled Serb withdrawal from this western region of Kosovo
_ the site of the heaviest fighting and worst reported atrocities
of the war _ is not going smoothly. Peacekeepers turned back
drivers headed toward Djakovica Monday, saying it was not yet safe.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-morning, Serb soldiers awaiting departure hunkered down
at a corner and had already started drinking, worrying KFOR that a
confrontation could occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's dangerous,'' Bescht said.
</P>
<P>
   A Sunday night fight between Serbs and KLA in nearby Suva Reka
left one KLA soldier and seven or eight Serbs dead, and 12 Serbs
``arrested'' by the KLA, Drini reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an incident. It is not the war,'' Drini said when asked
if shooting, deaths and the taking of prisoners meant the war was
not finished.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA never had a strong presence during the war in Prizren,
an old, picturesque city in Kosovo's southwest. With a mosque and
an Orthodox church Prizren was always among the most ethnically
harmonious of Kosovo cities, home to Serbs, Albanians and a sizable
Turkish population.
</P>
<P>
   The arrival Monday of KLA soldiers _ outfitted with assault
weapons, pistols, hand grenades and hunting knives _ was the
biggest visible presence the city has seen, locals said. Drini said
the KLA had virtual control of Prizren, but the presence of the
soldiers was only heavily visible in two neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Under the peace agreement, the KLA is supposed to
``demilitarize,'' though the details and schedule of the task is
not clear.
</P>
<P>
   The rogue army came into Prizren about 5 a.m. Monday from the
mountains. Locals who had been too afraid to step out onto the
cobblestone streets were out in droves Monday, clamoring around the
KLA soldiers and thrusting flowers at them. KLA soldiers swaggered
triumphantly through the city square.
</P>
<P>
   Children invited peacekeepers and other Westerners to autograph
their forearms. The men of Prizren _ practically invisible during
Serb military occupation of the city _ reclaimed their usual posts
in cafes and on storefront steps, smoking scarce cigarettes,
sipping coffee and exchanging war stories.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA, Drini said, would protect these people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will control the places where the internatiuonal forces
will not be present,'' he said. ``The situation now is at the level
where we have to be here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
