   SMART-GUNS (Baltimore) _ In the decade since the idea of a smart
gun came up _ a gun that could not be fired accidentally by a child
or violently by a criminal who stole it _ it has come to be seen as
a quick fix, cited in lawsuits and in legislatures by pro-control
advocates seeking a way to reduce gun violence. So far, legislation
requiring that all new handguns be smart guns within five years is
pending before at least eight state houses, including New York,
Pennsylvania and New Jersey. Yet it is becoming increasingly clear
that putting smart guns may not be the simple solution that many
proponents think they are. By Leslie Wayne. (Scheduled to move by 9
p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.) 1,900 words.
