<HEADER>
A5099 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLAND-POPE-NYT     06-14 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLAND-POPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN UNEXPECTED MOVE, POPE TO VISIT AILING ARMENIAN ORTHODOX LEADER
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOWICZ, Poland _ Racing to mend the centuries-old breach between
Orthodox and Roman Catholic believers, Pope John Paul II has turned
Vatican planning upside down and decided to go ahead with a
previously canceled meeting with the head of the Armenian Apostolic
Church in Yerevan after leaving Poland.
</P>
<P>
   The pope, who has often spoken of his dream of reconciling the
Eastern and Western Christian churches by the year 2000, had hoped
to build on his historic visit to Romania last month, the first
trip by a pope to a predominantly Orthodox country in almost 1,000
years, by visiting Armenia for three days in July.
</P>
<P>
   Those plans were postponed indefinitely last Friday, when
Karekin I, who leads more than 6 million Armenian Orthodox
believers around the world, sent an envoy to Warsaw to meet the
pope and express his regrets.
</P>
<P>
   Catholicos Karekin, 66, is suffering from throat cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Holy Father said he was very sorry, and then he asked me,
`What can I do?''' Archbishop Khajag Barsamian, primate of the
Diocese of the Armenian Church of America, who relayed the message
in Warsaw, recalled. ``I told him that the catholicos would be
very, very touched by a personal visit, and the pope replied, `I
should do that.'''
</P>
<P>
   The following morning, according to the Vatican spokesman,
Joaquin Navarro-Valls, the pope told his entourage, ``I am going to
Yerevan.'' Navarro called the decision, ``unexpected.'' It was the
same morning that the pope slipped and cut his head, requiring
three stitches, while getting ready to leave the Vatican embassy
for a Mass in Sandomierz.
</P>
<P>
   He still wore a bandage Monday at a Mass in Lowicz and a prayer
service in Sosnowiec, but as his change of plans suggests, he has
no desire to slow down. ``The Holy Father was thinking and thinking
and thinking, but we got the news Saturday morning,'' Navarro-Valls
said.
</P>
<P>
   The pope decided that he wanted to pay his respects to the
Armenian patriarch, who shares his interest in ecumenical dialogue
and in 1996 went to the Vatican to sign a joint declaration that
formally buried a theological dispute that had divided the two
churches for 1500 years.
</P>
<P>
   Karekin, whose formal title is Supreme Patriarch and Catholicos
of All Armenians, did so over the objections of most of his
bishops.
</P>
<P>
   His eventual successor might not prove as eager to invite the
leader of the world's Roman Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   It could well be the pope's best chance to personally bring his
message of reconciliation _ and powers of persuasion _ to a country
that won its independence from the Soviet Union in 1991, and where
more than 90 percent of its 3 million inhabitants describe
themselves as Orthodox Christians. Armenia has a small Catholic
minority, and also a small number of Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this visit, which also has the character of an ecumenical
pilgrimage, John Paul II wishes to express to Catholicos Karekin
his spiritual closeness in this moment of suffering,''
Navarro-Valls said in a prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary plans call for the pope to spend an additional night
in Krakow on Thursday, and fly to Yerevan on Friday morning,
returning to Rome the same night.
</P>
<P>
   As the first nation to adopt Christianity as a state religion,
in A.D. 301, Armenia has a special significance for the pope, as
does his close relationship with Karekin I. But a fruitful meeting
there will not necessarily bring the pope any closer to his
long-awaited goal of visiting Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   The Armenian Apostolic Church belongs to the Eastern Orthodox
tradition, but it became independent from other Christian churches
in A.D. 451, several centuries before the schism between
Constantinople and Rome in 1054.
</P>
<P>
   It remains independent from the other Orthodox churches, and
while the Armenian patriarch is on good terms with Aleksy II, the
patriarch of the Russian Orthodox Church, he is unlikely to soften
his Russian counterpart on the subject of Catholics. Aleksy II has
steadfastly refused to meet with the pope or invite him to Russia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
