<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-GRAVES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US SOLDIERS GUARD POSSIBLE MASS GRAVE SITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KACANIK, Yugoslavia _ As American soldiers stood guard Monday
over what NATO officials say may be a mass grave of civilians
killed by Serb forces, refugees streaming back to this town in
southern Kosovo told a chilling story of how men, women and
children were massacred more than two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, British soldiers saw local people bringing flowers to
a spot in the town graveyard in back of a gas station. By Monday,
that gas station had been commandeered by members of the US Army's
82nd Airborne, and the grave site had been cordoned off to allow
for a forensics examination by the international war crimes
tribunal at The Hague.
</P>
<P>
   British Army Capt. Vicki Wentworth said there were 81 stakes to
mark the graves of local people allegedly killed by Serb forces
during a killing spree which villagers said took place April 9.
</P>
<P>
   In the town center, residents told of at least two separate mass
killings. In one, according to Dr. Lul Raka, who works at the town
hospital, 17 people were shot dead on New Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were mostly elderly people,'' said Raka. ``Some were
shot in their houses, some running on the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Raka said that because of the confusion, with local residents
having fled before and after the massacre, the exact number of
people killed won't be known unless the bodies are exhumed for
examination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows? They buried them, we didn't,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest slaughter, according to witnesses, was up a hilly
gorge lined with houses, where a group of about 80 civilians fled
when Serb forces opened fire on the morning of April 9. Witnesses
said 46 people were killed at Rakoc, and that the Serbs took all
but a few of the bodies down the hill later in wagons pulled by
tractors.
</P>
<P>
   Skender Sopa, 37, led a group of journalists up the hill, next
to a stream, where he and other civilians fled, the Serbs in hot
pursuit. The dirt road leading up the hill was strewn with hundreds
of bullet casings, some from conventional rifles, others five-inch
anti-aircraft shells.
</P>
<P>
   Sopa, who escaped by hiding in a nearby house with nine other
people, said he buried three of the victims at the massacre site
before the Serbs removed the bodies. He named the victims as
Mukadeze Lika, 38, Tefik Nalbani, 45, and Xhyli Rexha, in his
mid-60s. He pointed out three graves behind a house in which some
of the victims were shot.
</P>
<P>
   Kacanik was apparently singled out for brutality because it was,
and is fast becoming again, a hotbed of the rebel Kosovo Liberation
Army. Monday, KLA rebels walked the streets of the town, all but a
few of them without guns per an edict from NATO.
</P>
<P>
   A three-man patrol of soldiers from the 82nd Airborne walked the
streets, too. Spc. Matt Smith, Sgt. Charles Chiri and Staff Sgt.
George Person said they had been greeted warmly throughout the
town.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are happy to see us,'' said Chiri, 35, from Santa
Clara, Calif. ``We're here to show our presence, let them know
we're here.''
</P>
<P>
   Chiri said the KLA had been instructed not to carry weapons,
with the exception of the local commander and his deputy, who were
allowed to carry sidearms.
</P>
<P>
   That KLA commander, Xhabir Zharku, used to manage restaurants in
Greenwich, Conn. But he moved back to Kosovo two years ago, and
Monday he sat behind the desk and in the office of the former
leader of the Serb paramilitary police unit which allegedly carried
out the April 9 massacres. He said the Serb police abandoned the
building last Friday, the day before NATO entered Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Zharku said his rebel soldiers would keep their arms ``until we
know there are no Serbs here.'' He claimed that NATO agreed with
that strategy. He said his forces were searching for Serbs they
believe were involved in the massacres. He said they had not found
any yet, but if they did they would hold them and turn them over to
NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Zharku said he had asked NATO not to allow refugees to flood
back until his troops had been able to reconnect the water, get the
hospital up and running, and clear mines and booby traps from homes
in the area. He said he needed 5 to 10 days to get the town ready.
</P>
<P>
   But many people cannot wait. Those who were not in the refugee
camps but were instead staying with relatives in Macedonia have
been coming back to the village over the last few days. Monday,
Faik Lata broke down in tears when he returned to his home and
found that it had been looted but not destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Lata, 45, his wife, Nebahat, and their 15-year-old nephew left
his sister's home in Skopje, the Macedonian capital, and took a
taxi to the border. They walked into Kosovo, walked for some time
on the highway, then got a lift to Kacanik.
</P>
<P>
   Given the devastation in this town, where every shop has been
looted and some of them completely destroyed, Lata got off
relatively easy. The three-story apartment block where he lives was
still standing, and while his apartment was trashed, it was simply
a matter of cleaning up.
</P>
<P>
   The Serb forces stole his TV, his black leather jacket, 6,000
Deutschemarks he had hidden in the closet, and 10 kilograms of
coffee. But Lata considered himself lucky that, unlike many other
returning refugees, he had something to build on.
</P>
<P>
   Lata's restaurant, Perparimi, was destroyed, like every other
business in town. But he vowed to rebuild it, and rename it in
honor of US President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be here without NATO,'' he said. But he also said
he won't stay unless the KLA is allowed to remain armed.
</P>
<P>
   Sabit Raka's daughter, Jehona, was a nurse who was killed when
she tried to help the wounded who had fled up the gorge where the
46 civilians were allegedly massacred.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was at home,'' said Raka, 52, who is a captain in the
local KLA and is not related to Dr. Raka. ``When they needed first
aid, they called her, and she would go.''
</P>
<P>
   He said she had done that, and had climbed the steep gorge to
attend to the injured when she was shot. Dr. Raka brought out the
stainless steel first aid kit she was carrying. The metal was torn
by a bullet hole.
</P>
<P>
   Melihate Shehu, a nurse, said her brother, Rashat, was among
those killed at the gorge. She said two other nurses who rushed to
the scene were killed along with Jehona Raka. Monday, Shehu and a
group of nurses and doctors from the local hospital brought flowers
to the mass grave.
</P>
<P>
   Lulzim Zaku, 23, a KLA volunteer, said he watched from a nearby
hill as the Serbs collected the bodies the day after the April 9
slaughter. He said they used a tractor to ferry the bodies down the
steep gorge.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bulldozer came and opened a big hole,'' he said, describing
two large graves. ``They just grabbed them and threw them in.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents in the nearby village of Stagovo said there was a
massacre there around the same time as the killings in Kacanik.
Ahmed Bajrami, 31, said at least a dozen people were killed, the
youngest a boy of seven, the oldest, the village elder, 95-year-old
Ramush Jaha.
</P>
<P>
   KFOR officials said they had not yet investigated those claims.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
