A5102 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-CASINO-HNS &LR;      06-14 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-CASINO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT STRIKES BAN ON GAMBLING ADS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Broadcast stations that reach viewers and listeners
in Texas can now trumpet Louisiana gambling halls without violating
federal law.
</P>
<P>
   A unanimous Supreme Court on Monday struck down as
unconstitutional a federal ban that had kept some casino
advertising off Houston televisions and radios.
</P>
<P>
   The broadcasters had failed to convince lower federal courts
that the U.S. government's ban on interstate radio and TV ads
illegally restricted their First Amendment right of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals _ with jurisdiction over
Texas, Louisiana and neighboring states _ had agreed with a federal
district court that the government's goal of curtailing compulsive
gambling justified the ban on interstate advertising. The Supreme
Court disagreed, saying the government failed to defend its
restriction as sufficiently narrow to justify the restriction on
the broadcasters' speech.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the government belied its goal of combatting
compulsive gambling by exempting from its advertising ban many
forms of wagering that are just as addictive as private casinos,
the court said. Under the law, advertisements regarding casinos on
American Indian reservations, state lotteries and horse races are
permitted.
</P>
<P>
   These forms of gambling are legal and advertised in Texas and
many other states that outlaw private casinos. American Indian
casinos operated by the Tiguas tribe in El Paso, Texas, and the
Kickapoos tribe in Eagle Pass, Texas, are thriving, a point not
lost on the justices as they rejected the government's argument
that reservations are far removed from populated areas and do not
merit free-speech concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government's suggestion that Indian casinos are too
isolated to warrant attention is belied by a quick review of tribal
geography and the government's own evidence regarding the financial
success of tribal gaming,'' Justice John Paul Stevens wrote for the
court. ``If distance were determinative, Las Vegas might have
remained a relatively small community, or simply disappeared like a
desert mirage.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashton Hardy, a Metairie, La., lawyer who pressed the Louisiana
broadcasters' case before the justices, praised the decision as
giving broadcasters ``the same First Amendment freedoms that are
enjoyed by the other media'' that can legally advertise casinos.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission, which regulates
broadcasters and defended the federal law, had no comment on the
court's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   In its decision, the high court said the government has given
``no convincing reason'' for subjecting private casinos to an
advertising ban not imposed on similar places and forms of
wagering. The justices said the federal government could still
legally fight compulsive gambling with regulations, and thereby
avoid the risk of running afoul of the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The power to prohibit or regulate particular conduct does not
necessarily include the power to prohibit or regulate speech about
that conduct,'' Stevens wrote. ``It is well settled that the First
Amendment mandates closer scrutiny of government restrictions on
speech than of its regulation of commerce alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Legitimate regulations, for example, could prohibit casinos from
extending credit to gamblers, limit the use of cash machines in
gambling houses and restrict the permissible amount of bets, the
justices said.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Clarence Thomas, the only member of the nine-person
court who declined to join Stevens' opinion, wrote separately to
express his strong disdain for the government's advertising
restriction. ``I continue to adhere to my view that in cases such
as this, in which the government's asserted interest is to keep
legal users of a product or service ignorant in order to manipulate
their choices in the marketplace
</P>
<P>
   such an interest is per se illegitimate,'' Thomas wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In other high court news:
</P>
<P>
   -- The justices agreed to decide whether taxpayer dollars can be
used to provide computers and other high-tech educational equipment
to parochial schools without running afoul of the Constitution's
separation of church and state.
</P>
<P>
   In a case from Louisiana, the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
struck down as unconstitutional a federal program that provides
funds that local school boards can use to provide computers to
public and parochial schools. The appeals court said the use of
public funds for religious schools violated the First Amendment
prohibition on government endorsement of religion.
</P>
<P>
   -- The high court also agreed to decide whether Texas courts
violated the constitutional rights of a man serving a life sentence
for aggravated-sexual assault and related offenses on a 14-year-old
girl. Scott Carmell claims Texas prosecutors should not have been
permitted to allow his alleged victim to testify against him.
</P>
<P>
   Carmell, in his successful request that the justices hear his
appeal, argued that Texas law at the time of his 1992 offense
prohibited sexual-assault victims from testifying if they waited
longer than six months after the offense before telling a person,
other than the defendant, of the purported attack. A 1993 amendment
to the law removed the six-month deadline, and the victim was
permitted to testify at Carmell's 1997 trial, even though she had
waited more than six months to tell of the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Carmell said the Constitution's prohibition on ex post facto
convictions prohibited prosecutors from using at-trial testimony
that would not have been permitted at the time of the attack. That
argument, however, lost in Texas courts, prompting Carmell to
appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The justices are expected to hear arguments in the Louisiana
case, Mitchell vs. Helms, and in Carmell vs. Texas this fall or
early next year and to render their decisions by July 2000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
