<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5107 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EPA-POLLUTE-BOS &LR;      06-14 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EPA-POLLUTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EPA CHIEF PROMISES `DOWNWIND' STATES ACTION AGAINST POLLUTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thwarted by a federal court in her effort to clean up air
pollution that drifts from other regions to the Northeast, the head
of the US Environmental Protection Agency said Monday she would
give in to the demands from four states to take direct action
against polluters.
</P>
<P>
   EPA Administrator Carol Browner said she had hoped to avoid
enforcing the unusual petitions from the states, which blame power
plants and industrial boilers in 12 states from Indiana to Maryland
for part of the summertime smog problem in Massachusetts,
Connecticut, New York and Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   But she said a federal appeals court last month forced her hand
by at least temporarily stopping a 37-state pollution reduction
plan from taking effect. The ruling was the second this spring in
which the three-judge panel found that the EPA has overstepped its
authority in making new air pollution rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Northeast has been waiting a long time for these pollution
reductions,'' said Browner in a briefing for reporters. ``We had a
sensible path to get us there. The courts robbed us of that
opportunity, but we are not giving up. We are going back and
finding another path to travel.''
</P>
<P>
   Northeastern air pollution officials said Browner was making the
best of a bad situation after the court stopped tougher new smog
standards as well as the regional cleanup of nitrogen oxides, which
turn toxic in the summer sun. The state petitions will cut nitrogen
oxide emissions by 717,000 tons a year instead of 1.1 million tons,
but officials said that's better than nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real measure of success is whether EPA insures that all
major smokestacks in the eastern US have modern pollution controls
by the 2003 ozone (smog) season,'' said Jason Grumet of the
Northeast States for Coordinated Air Use Management, which advises
states on air issues. ``Based on the choices available, this
strategy seems most likely to produce that result.''
</P>
<P>
   However, owners of the plants that would bear the brunt of the
EPA crackdown said Browner's new strategy is ``dramatically
weaker'' because the agency cannot hold them to the tougher smog
standards. A diminishing number of regions within states violate
existing standards _ Boston meets them, for example _ making it
hard for states to argue that distant smokestacks are causing a
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is: Are the impacts'' that Massachusetts and
other states petitioned EPA about ``significant?'' asked Patrick
Dal Porto, staff engineer for American Electric Power, the
Ohio-based utility that owns many coal plants that would be
targeted.
</P>
<P>
   Browner's initiative is the latest move in a highly technical
tug-of-war that, at its root, is both simple and important:
</P>
<P>
   Scores of older power plants across the Midwest and South,
mostly exempted from current pollution control standards, pump
countless tons of emissions out of tall smokestacks that are
carried on the prevailing wind to other states, mostly in the
Northeast. The question is: what should be done?
</P>
<P>
   EPA, under pressure from New England and other so-called
``downwind'' states, had pulled together a 37-state group of upwind
and downwind states to work out a regional plan, leaving it to the
22 individual states that ``export'' pollution to decide how to
control it.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, EPA developed more restrictive limits for
ozone, an ingredient of smog that is formed when nitrogen oxide and
other pollutants are cooked in hot summer sun. In developing their
plans, the 22 pollution ``exporting'' states would have to meet the
new, lower standard.
</P>
<P>
   But the EPA strategy crumbled on May 14 when the US Court of
Appeals in Washington declared the new ozone standard ``an
unconstitutional delegation of legislative power.'' Two of the
three judges agreed that EPA could not enforce an ozone standard
that was tougher than the one in the Clean Air Act.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on May 24, the court stayed the 37-state regional nitrogen
oxide clean up, on the grounds that it, too, exceeded EPA
authority.
</P>
<P>
   Browner has called the rulings ``bizarre,'' and the agency plans
to appeal. In the meantime, Browner turned to petitions from 11
``downwind'' states that ask her to force power plants and
industrial boilers to clean up. The Clean Air Act allows states to
appeal directly to EPA to solve pollution problems caused outside
their boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, these petitions also face a challenge by utilities
and others in the same appeals court, but Browner hopes to
short-cicruit legal challenges by tossing out any references to the
new ozone standard. As a result, she said petitions from Maine, New
Hampshire, Rhode Island and Vermont had to be rejected, and 10 of
the 22 pollution ``exporting'' states would not have to undertake
new pollution controls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always regarded the petitions filed by the Northeast
states as an insurance policy, the backstop to the regional plan,''
said Browner. If EPA is able to reinstate the ozone standards and
37-state cleanup plan, she said the petitions would be voided.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
