<DOCNO> NYT19990614.0357 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5111 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MEN-0615-COX     06-14 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MEN-0615-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KOSOVO'S MISSING MEN BEGIN TO SURFACE WITH WOUNDED BODY, SPIRIT
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-RUSSIA; KOSOVO-RENEWAL; KOSOVO-RACAK.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Emaciated young men slowly walk the
twisting, narrow alleys of an ethnic Albanian neighborhood here,
while others too injured to wander recuperate in homes where they
were lucky to find care and shelter.
</P>
<P>
   They are the missing men of Kosovo, and they are beginning to
turn up here in sad shape after weeks of what they describe as
extreme maltreatment in Serb-run prisons or other detention.
</P>
<P>
   In a single small neighborhood in northern Pristina seven of
these still dazed men were found Monday, all of them released from
prisons or the hospital last Thursday. It was the day after
Yugoslavia agreed to pull its troops out of Kosovo, when Serbs here
learned they were about to be confronted with responsibility in the
eyes of the world for their noxious campaign of ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I'd get out of there,'' said Ramadan Sadriju,
a 20-year-old ethnic Albanian with hollowed cheeks and ribs jutting
from his skinny torso. He referred to the feared prison at Lipjan,
the place he spent six gruesome weeks packed into a single cell
with 38 others.
</P>
<P>
   Now he was out, but he still seemed unable to smile.
</P>
<P>
   His 16-year-old brother Berat was just as physically debilitated
-- as they sat without shirts their heartbeats were easily visible
-- but Berat was too withdrawn to answer a journalist's questions
or describe his stay in the same prison.
</P>
<P>
   The pair and four other men interviewed were grabbed by Serb
forces from refugee convoys trying to escape into Macedonia or
Albania, just like tens of thousands of other men reported
separated from families trying to leave the terrors of Kosovo. A
seventh man was shot and injured during an attack on his village,
then taken away by Serb soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   All are patients of a remarkable young doctor, Murat Abdazi,
himself only aged 25. Abdazi, working sometimes with a nurse and
medical assistant, has spent these grim months racing from one
disastrous case to the next.
</P>
<P>
   For a while his team worked a nearby mountain village under
siege, but mostly he has snaked his way through sniper fire and
stronger assaults here in Pristina, delivering babies, treating
people beaten and shot, and generally trying to keep alive the
ethnic Albanians hiding his own neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was prepared for this. I had saved the medicine,'' said
Abdazi, who was greeted by almost every passing person as he led
two journalists through the hilly district of houses with a rural
village look.
</P>
<P>
   But he had nearly exhausted his supplies, and he was worried
about treating some of these ex-prisoners who were his latest round
of emergency patients.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most seriously injured was Bahtir Zeciri, 26, who was
wounded in the same Serb military attack that killed his father in
their village of Kolatec north of here on May 26. He was shot in
the left shoulder and right arm, and another bullet grazed his
upper lip.
</P>
<P>
   Police picked up him and two other men, he said, and he ended up
in what sounded like a special interrogation room in a basement
here in Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   ``For three days I had no food or water,'' Zeciri said. He was
blindfolded the entire time and had no medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Like others interrogated, Zeciri said the Serbs tried to make
him admit to being a member of the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army and
to give information about the KLA, which has been labeled a
terrorist group by the Yugoslav government.
</P>
<P>
   He was released after the three days, but en route home to his
village was cornered by Serb paramilitary forces who beat him
severely. That apparently is when he suffered the broken left arm.
</P>
<P>
   Zeciri finally ended up in the main surgical hospital of
Pristina, but it was no safe haven for an ethnic Albanian brought
in by Serb security.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone who came into my room beat me,'' he said, citing the
nurses, the doctors and two army officers who threatened to throw
him out the window. ``People from the prisons came to the hospital,
but they were treated like they were in prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar stories have circulated already about the Pristina
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The Serb-run hospital, too, discharged its prisoner patients on
June 10, and Zeciri staggered out into the city. A young woman from
Dr. Abdazi's neighborhood found him and brought him home.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor said Zeciri's broken arm was set, but he had not
removed the cast to see it yet. He said wounds to the young man's
right arm and wrist were not well doctored, and the patient cannot
move his ring finger on that hand.
</P>
<P>
   Veton Berisha, 22, is another of the complicated cases the young
doctor has been trying to treat with few resources.
</P>
<P>
   He and his 48-year-old father Ilmi had been pulled from a convoy
on April 30. They also were dispatched to Lipjan prison, which Ilmi
Berisha described as a house of horrors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several died in the cell with us from beatings,'' said Ilmi
Berisha, describing pitiless living conditions in which some 160
people from four cells shared one toilet. Food was marginal and
beatings came almost every day, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Prisoners in his cell were aged 13 to 75.
</P>
<P>
   After 20 days in custody, authorities took three or four people
from each cell, and they never were seen again in the prison, said
the elder Berisha.
</P>
<P>
   His son was severely injured on the day prisoners were ejected
from Lipjan. In weakened conditions they were forced to walk the 12
miles to Pristina, then encountered brutally hostile Serbs in the
city. It was one day after Kosovo's ethnic Serb population learned
it had lost out to NATO, which would be sending international
peacekeeping troops to secure the city at the same time Yugoslav
troops would be required to leave.
</P>
<P>
   In the city both men were beaten to unconsciousness. Abdazi said
the younger Berisha was hit at least 20 times in the head, based on
the wounds he found, had his jaw broken and his left ear nearly
ripped off. The father and son were dropped into a building that
was then set afire.
</P>
<P>
   They were fortunate that neighbors saw what had happened and
busted through a window to retrieve them. Finally they were brought
to Abdazi's neighborhood, where he is trying to treat them.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
