<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5112 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SERBIA-PEC-NYT &LR;      06-14 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERBIA-PEC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEAR OF REBELS DRIVING LAST SERBS OUT OF KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEC, Yugoslavia _ Shala Selvinaze pulled back the tatty wool
carpet in her tiny living room to show precisely where Serbian
paramilitary men slit the throat of her son, Ymer.
</P>
<P>
   She had cleaned the top carpet, she said. She had to. If she
wanted to live, the Serbs said, she had to remain in the house, on
devastated Ramiz Batusha Street in this devastated city. She
couldn't live, she said, with the sight of her son's blood.
</P>
<P>
   Underneath, a second carpet was stained rusty red. Mrs.
Selvinaze, 65, pulled that back. A sheet of cardboard beneath bore
a larger, darker stain. She was flooded with tears.
</P>
<P>
   A scouting party of Italian NATO forces finally arrived in Pec
on Monday at around 6 a.m., but she hadn't dared leave the house.
She kissed the hand of the first foreigner she saw.
</P>
<P>
   Pec, like most of Kosovo, is a ruin, and nearly empty of people
now. The downtown has been looted and burned with a methodical
hatred. Very few Albanians remain in the city, most of them old or
ill, and the Serbs who lived here have been fleeing by the
thousands, fearful of the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   Pec was a city of some 70,000 before the war _ 120,000 including
the surrounding villages. About 30 percent of the people were
Serbs. Now, the Serbs are fleeing and the Albanians have not yet
returned from their exile.
</P>
<P>
   On a burned Albanian building, the graffiti reads: ``Serbia to
Tokyo!'' Now, the Serbs are following their withdrawing army and
police and fleeing back to Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Selvinaze said the paramilitaries came on the night of May
10. With no electricity, she and her son, Ymer, 35, were sitting in
candlelight when the knocks came on the door.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs had already come twice before and stolen her washing
machine and her old television. They took the wedding ring from her
finger and the earrings from her ears. They were her grandmother's,
she said; the only pair she owned.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `Give us money or we'll kill you.' And I said, `I
have only my soul to give _ take that and kill me.'''
</P>
<P>
   They searched the house, saying that they were looking for
weapons. They took anything they wanted, she said.
</P>
<P>
   When they came again, she said, she told her son to run. ``I
told him to rush to the neighbors,'' Mrs. Selvinaze said. ``He
said, `No, mother. You run there. What can they do to me? I've done
nothing.'''
</P>
<P>
   She went next door. Then she heard him screaming, she said,
screaming, ```Oh mother, I'm dying. I'm dying.' They cut his throat
with a knife.''
</P>
<P>
   When she came back to her house and saw Ymer, she fainted, she
said, beginning to whimper, making small noises like a toy bellows.
</P>
<P>
   She said she left Ymer's body overnight where it lay. She went
back to her neighbors. ``What could I do?'' she pleaded.
</P>
<P>
   She could not bury him, she said, because her little courtyard
is concrete. That night, she said, the Serbian police came back and
bundled him into a blanket and took him away in a green van. Where,
she has no idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't even cry,'' she said, still dressed in black. ``So
I'm eating bread and salt. I went mad when they killed Ymer. If
they kill me now, I don't care. I heard him screaming, `Oh mother,
I'm dying,' and I told him to run away.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Serbian soldiers and police remain in Pec, and Mrs.
Selvinaze has spent the last three nights in a neighbor's cellar,
as Serbs fired weapons and burned more houses. She carefully took
her visitor outside, to house number 63, a large establishment with
a satellite dish that was burned by Serbs on Sunday night, she
said, and was still smoldering.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street, she went into the garden of another ruined
house. Two fresh graves were mounded amid the bright red peonies
and the weeds. She helped her neighbor Sena dig them two days ago.
Sena's mother, Naja, 75, and her brother, Hasan, 55, were killed by
the Serbs. Sena buried them and then fled.
</P>
<P>
   In the street, houses smoked. A woman's shoe lay in the road,
next to part of an electric iron. Serbian names like Goran and
Milos are spray-painted on charred, broken walls.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Selvinaze said she could not hate the Serbs. Her Serbian
neighbor, Jela Lakovic, looked after an old Albanian man named
Rustam Muja. ``She brought him bread and yogurt,'' Mrs. Selvinaze
said. ``She said, `Don't be afraid.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``She saw me crying and brought me peppers and yogurt,'' Mrs.
Selvinaze said. ``She said, `Our people did a lot of bad things and
honest people suffered.' She was good to us. She told me, `The
foreigners will come in a few days and don't be afraid.'''
</P>
<P>
   Where is Mrs. Lakovic now? ``I don't know,'' Mrs. Selvinaze
said. ``Maybe she left. I told her I would always remember what she
did for us. But her son-in-law was a terrible man, and he killed
many people, like a butcher.''
</P>
<P>
   In the central city, more Italian troops were moving in, black
feathers bobbing on their helmets, pointing out to each other yet
another burned shop or house.
</P>
<P>
   On the road to the Pec Patriarchy, Serbs continued to load up
cars and trailers with suitcases, televisions, food, blankets,
mattresses and washing machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the Serbs are leaving Pec, and we cannot stop them,'' said
a priest named Miljko Koricanin, who leads the congregation at St.
Jovan, the Serbian Orthodox church in Pec. ``We go out to speak
with them and beg them to stay. But people are terrified that the
KLA will appear again.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Italians reached Pec Monday, he said, ``we talked with
the general and asked him to protect the people who stay here.
Otherwise, he'll have nothing to protect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thousands of Serbs are leaving and no one can stop them and
NATO doesn't stop them,'' Koricanin said. ``We asked the Italians
to put soldiers near the patriarchy and the churches and two
soldiers in every village. If we manage to keep the people here,
then the others will come back. People are just fleeing their
houses and they don't know where to go.''
</P>
<P>
   In the nearby town of Gorazdevac, he said, 600 houses belong to
Serbs, but only 30 Serbs remain. In Belo Polje, a mile away, only
20 old people are still there.
</P>
<P>
   Pec is to Serbian Orthodoxy what Rome is to the Catholics, he
said. ``This is a holy place, and if they take this, they will take
the soul from the Serbs, our dearest possession.'' By they, he
said, he meant the rebel forces.
</P>
<P>
   The priest's eyes reddened. ``It has been very difficult for us
when the Albanians left,'' he said. ``And it is very difficult for
us now. I can't lie to you, it's harder now, when our own people
leave. We go and ask them, beg them to stay. But they just want a
guarantee from someone, that someone guarantees them peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Is the separatist group here in Pec? He smiled. ``It's
everywhere,'' he said. ``If you stay overnight you will hear the
shooting. The proof they exist is very easy,'' he said slowly.
``Just sit with an Albanian civilian in his car and you will find
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Koricanin is not a monk; he has a family. And even he took his
wife and two sons away from Pec, ``and I haven't done anything bad
to anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked the names of sons, he began to cry. Stephan, he said, is
11, and Dusan is 8. Tears running down his beard to disappear into
his cassock, Koricanin cried, ``I don't know if I will ever see
them again.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he turned and walked away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
