<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5113 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-COURT-EXIT-BOS &LR;      06-14 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-COURT-EXIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE COURT ACTS TO HALT PROFILING IN TRAFFIC STOPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLEMENT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- In a stunning break with the nation's highest court,
the Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court ruled Monday that police
do not have an automatic right to order drivers and passengers out
of cars during routine traffic stops, saying the practice was ``a
clear invitation to discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   The 5-2 decision strikes at the heart of a police practice that
minorities say is used disproportionately against them, leading to
calls across the nation for an end to so-called ``racial
profiling'' in traffic stops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would behoove our law enforcement community . . .
to get on the stick here,'' said state Senator Dianne Wilkerson,
who played a key role in April's State House hearings at which
blacks testified about being stopped by police solely because of
their race.
</P>
<P>
   The five-judge majority said it will flatly ignore two US
Supreme Court decisions that empower police _ for their own safety
_ to issue so-called ``exit orders'' without fearing they are
violating the privacy rights of the people in the cars.
</P>
<P>
   The majority said the state's constitution, on which the US
Constitution was modeled, gives Massachusetts citizens greater
privacy rights. The court said it feared adopting the approach of
the US Supreme Court would lead to the kind of racial profiling
that has occurred most prominently in New Jersey, where state
troopers were found to have stopped blacks and Hispanics at much
higher rates than whites.
</P>
<P>
   ``That a small percentage of routine traffic stops may result in
the detection of more serious crimes is no reason to subject the
vast majority of citizens to orders to get out of their vehicles,''
Justice John M. Greaney wrote for the majority.
</P>
<P>
   Greaney, along with the court's only black judge, Justice
Roderick Ireland, indicated they were reacting to complaints from
motorists who said they'd been stopped by police simply because
they're black.
</P>
<P>
   ``Routine traffic stops may also pose unique hardships on
minorities who, it has been argued, are often the subject of stops
on pretext,'' Greaney wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The recent hearings at the State House have prompted legislators
to ask that police be required to record the race of those they
stop in order to assess the prevalence of racial profiling in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   As Ireland pointed out, ``Statistics show that such racial
profiling occurs throughout the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a stinging dissent, Justice Charles Fried, said the
majority had waded into a policy area best left to the Legislature
and had relied on ``the inflammatory issue of race'' to bolster a
poorly conceived conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I completely agree that the discriminatory enforcement of law
is a shame and disgrace,'' Fried wrote. ``(But) I think it is
fanciful to imagine that by weaving a gossamer garment of
complicated rules, we will do anything to root out this behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Fried said the US Supreme Court had drawn a ``bright-line''
standard that everyone can understand _ police have the power to
issue ``exit orders.'' It's designed to protect police officers and
any discomfort to law-abiding citizens is minimal, Fried said.
</P>
<P>
   Both the majority and Fried agreed on a key point, however. If a
police officer, acting out of legitimate concern for his or her
safety because of the acts of a specific individual, orders someone
out of a car, then the courts will back any prosecution that
results.
</P>
<P>
   ``While a mere hunch is not enough, it does not take much for a
police officer to establish a reasonable basis to justify an exit
order,'' Greaney wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the case that led to Monday's decision does not have
any racial component. In 1997, a state trooper pulled over a taxi
that drifted over a marked lane on Interstate 195 in Marion.
</P>
<P>
   The passenger in the rear seat, John D. Gonsalves, became
nervous and was removed by the trooper when he admitted he had
outstanding arrest warrants. The trooper then searched the seat and
found 78 grams of cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   A trial judge threw out the cocaine evidence against Gonsalves
because the trooper had no specific reason _ other than Gonsalves'
nervousness _ to take him out of the car and search the seat. The
Appeals Court upheld the ruling but Plymouth County prosecutors
appealed to the SJC.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the SJC said the drugs cannot be used as evidence
against Gonsalves, effectively ending the case, according to his
attorney, J. Drew Segadelli.
</P>
<P>
   The SJC, he said, didn't want ``to give the police unfettered
rights. This could be you or I. This is a great victory for the
people of Massachusetts.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dean Bennett, president of the State Police Officers
Association of Massachusetts, said the ruling simply reinforces
what he has long told colleagues from other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 49 states _ and then there is Massachusetts,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said troopers routinely pull over cars for traffic
violations, not because of the driver's race or gender. Through
contact with state police in such places as Maryland and New
Jersey, where racial profiling has drawn heavy criticism,
Massachusetts troopers have learned what not to do, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said the SJC majority ignored the reality of police
work, where a life-threatening event can grow suddenly out of
routine traffic stops. The trooper who arrested Gonsalves acted
wisely, Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand what their concern is,'' Bennett said. ``At
least the officer went home that night. And so did the bad guy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
