<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5115 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-BELGIUM-COX     06-14 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-BELGIUM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coca-Cola products pulled after illnesses in Belgium
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (f) Financial and (i) International categories.)
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Belgian government has ordered Coca-Cola Co. to
withdraw its beverages from the market after more consumers
reported becoming ill from the company's soft drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Health Minister Luc Van den Bossche took the action Monday after
anti-poison centers reported consumers with hemolysis, a condition
that destroys red blood cells. Symptoms included nausea, vomiting
and stomach aches.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola spokesman Robert Baskin said the company is
cooperating fully with Belgian authorities in removing its
products, including Coca-Cola, Coca-Cola Light, Sprite, Fanta and
Cherry Coke.
</P>
<P>
   Baskin said he believes this is the first time the company has
been asked to remove its entire inventory from a nation. Outside of
Belgium, no complaints have been reported, he said.
</P>
<P>
   While its Belgian business represents less than 1 percent of the
company's global sales, Coca-Cola controls nearly two-thirds of the
nation's soft-drink market.
</P>
<P>
   The Health Ministry said it will not permit sales to resume
until Coca-Cola traces the cause of the problem and makes sure that
its products are safe.
</P>
<P>
   Baskin said an independent scientific analysis shows the
products cited in the illnesses _ Coca-Cola and Coca-Cola Light _
``do not constitute a health hazard.'' He said the company has been
working ``around the clock to identify the cause of the incidents.
We expect to have an answer soon.''
</P>
<P>
   One incident involved Coca-Cola cans that had a nontoxic odor on
the exterior, Baskin said. About 40 students were hospitalized last
week and then discharged, he said. An additional 17 students were
reportedly hospitalized Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A separate incident last week involved glass bottles that had a
``nontoxic off-taste,'' Baskin said.
</P>
<P>
   The products are distributed in Belgium by Atlanta-based
Coca-Cola Enterprises, which recalled about 100,000 cases last
week.
</P>
<P>
   CCE, which is 40 percent owned by Coca-Cola, is known for having
a high degree of quality control, said John Sicher, editor and
publisher of Beverage Digest. ``Until the facts come out, no one
should draw any conclusions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's problems follow a major health crisis in Belgium
that started last month when chicken, eggs, beef, pork and dairy
products were found to be contaminated with cancer-causing dioxin.
</P>
<P>
   Some industry analysts said the Belgium government might be
acting aggressively on the Coca-Cola situation in light of the
dioxin scare.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Unger writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
