<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5118 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLAYING-REWARD-COX     06-14 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLAYING-REWARD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Family hopes large reward will reap information in murder case
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The family of a wealthy Atlanta businessman found shot
to death in his burning mansion 2 1/2 years ago is offering
$200,000 _ believed to be the largest private reward in state
history _ for information leading to his killer.
</P>
<P>
   The reward is second only to the $1 million posted for the
capture of Eric Robert Rudolph in connection with the 1996 bombing
at Centennial Olympic Park. And that was by the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never heard of any reward go this high,'' said John
Bankhead, spokesman for the Georgia Bureau of Investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The family of David L. Coffin Jr. announced the reward Monday.
The family also placed a display ad in today's Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, said Mike Perricone, vice president of
advertising for the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Coffin, whose family has been at the helm of a Fortune 500
corporation in Connecticut for more than 200 years, was found in
his kitchen under debris that fell during an arson fire at his home
shortly after 9:30 p.m. Dec. 10, 1996. Police said he had been shot
once in the head.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, Atlanta police arrested Scott Davis, a local
businessman. Coffin was dating Davis' ex-wife at the time of his
death, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The 34-year-old Davis, whose father is a forensic psychiatrist
who has profiled killers, was charged with murder, arson and three
break-ins at Coffin's Atlanta house.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was jailed for three months and released when a judge
signed a $500,000 property bond secured by his parents' home. The
bond was awarded because the Fulton County District Attorney's
office had not taken the case before a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors eventually dropped charges against Davis though he
remains a suspect. He is now living in San Francisco. Monday, his
attorney, Bruce H. Morris, said neither he nor his client were
aware of the $200,000 reward. Morris declined comment on the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't feel there was sufficient evidence against Scott
Davis,'' Fulton County District Attorney Paul Howard said Monday.
``We certainly have to consider him a suspect in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard said investigators in his Major Case Division are
doubling their efforts on the case as they work with Atlanta
homicide investigators. Atlanta Maj. Mickey Lloyd said his
detectives continue to follow leads in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our investigators are intensifying their efforts over the next
two weeks to bring the person to justice,'' Howard said. ``We'll be
working on some things I can't divulge, but we hope to have a
conclusion to this very soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Coffin, who was single, moved to Atlanta from Connecticut in
1991. He purchased his $375,000 home that August, court records
showed. According to friends, he was self-employed, ``buying
businesses and selling them for profit.''
</P>
<P>
   The family, through their Atlanta representatives, declined
comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that someone out there who is probably in this area
knows something about this and we hope this reward will help bring
them forward,'' Howard said. ``This reward is certainly
unprecedented.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyda Longa writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-99 2000EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
