<DOCNO> NYT19990614.0364 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5120 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PLANTS-FOR-SALE-BOS &LR;      06-14 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLANTS-FOR-SALE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMI PUTS FIVE GAS-FIRED POWER PLANTS ON AUCTION BLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Five gas-fired power plants that can supply about 4 percent of
New England's electric needs are being put on the auction block by
owners sensing a chance to earn top dollar for them.
</P>
<P>
   Energy Management Inc. of North Dartmouth, Mass. said Monday it
has retained Fieldstone Services Corp. to solicit bids for units in
Dartmouth and Dighton, Mass., and Pawtucket, R.I., and for plants
under construction in Tiverton, R.I., and Rumford, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Industry sources said that based on recent sales and
construction trends, privately held EMI could get upward of $450
million for the plants, whose output totals nearly 840 megawatts,
plus a premium for plants at choice spots on the transmission grid.
General Electric Co. owns half of the Dartmouth and Pawtucket
plants and wants to sell its stakes as well, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   One megawatt represents the power demand of 600 to 750
average-size homes.
</P>
<P>
   Electric industry restructuring in Massachusetts and other
states is driving a rapid consolidation of ownership of power
plants, as competitive companies take them over from utilities that
now only carry power to homes and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's early heat wave demonstrated the potential riches to
be made generating electricity locally, as shutdowns at six large
plants drove spot-market prices to 30 times normal levels.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, EMI is offering its long-term contracts for
155 million British Thermal Units a day of natural gas, so a buyer
could also choose daily to resell gas instead of generating
electricity if the gas market were stronger. The Bay State gas
market is also being deregulated this fall.
</P>
<P>
   James Gordon, founder and president of 24-year-old EMI, said:
``We think the market environment is right to bring a class of
state-of-the-art assets into the market. We just think the sun, the
moon, and the stars are aligned, and there are a lot of people who
want to be in this market.''
</P>
<P>
   Neal B. Costello, general counsel of the Competitive Power
Coalition, a generators' group, said to the surprise of some
officials that prices for power plants ``have not bottomed out,''
despite recent deals in which old coal- and oil-powered plants
fetched three or four times book value.
</P>
<P>
   With much of the country slow to join the deregulation
bandwagon, ``This is where the action is'' for companies eager to
get into power generation, Costello said.
</P>
<P>
   The gas-fired, combined-cycle units being sold include
265-megawatt units in Tiverton and Rumford, 68-megawatt units in
Dartmouth and Pawtucket, and a 170-megawatt unit in Dighton. Sales
are not expected to affect jobs at the plants.
</P>
<P>
   Several industry sources said modern gas plants like these have
been selling recently for $500,000 to $600,000 per megawatt or
higher, but EMI may get more if buyers are looking for a footprint
for expansion or arbitrage between selling gas and electricity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
