u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-2N     06-14 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
  
 Monday, June 14, 1999    
 Editors     
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service has filed or will file the following
stories for Tuesday. If you have questions, please call Chuck Lewis
or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920. For questions about Houston
Chronicle sports stories, please call 713-220-7896.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Adds: BAPTISTS; BKN-SPURS; and BKN-KNICKS.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIAN-ARMY (Washington) _ Experts on Russian politics say the
defiant occupation of Kosovo's main airport by 200 Russian soldiers
isn't a Russian army mutiny but instead reflects an effort by
President Boris Yeltsin to allay anti-western nationalism gripping
his country. By STEWART M. POWELL and ERIC ROSENBERG. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-G8 (Washington) _ President Clinton leaves Tuesday for
high-level talks in Europe, culminating in meetings with the
leaders of the leading industrialized nations and Russia. Even
before he leaves, it is clear that Kosovo and the presence of
Russian troops in the Serbian province will take center stage. By
BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-KOSOVO (Washington) _ Rep. Kevin Brady, R-Texas,
introduces a bill with Democratic support that would deny
reconstruction money to Yugoslavia until President Slobodan
Milosevic is stripped of power and brought to trial. By GREG
McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-CASINO (Washington) _ The Supreme Court strikes down as
unconstitutional a federal ban on most casino advertising on radio
and television, saying the prohibition illegally restricts free
speech. By STEVE LASH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   INHOFE-PORNO (Washington) _ The nation's largest gay rights
organization attacks Sen. James M. Inhofe after staff members for
the Oklahoma Republican were found to have downloaded pornographic
material from the Internet into the Senate computer system. ``It's
the ultimate hypocrisy,'' says David Smith, spokesman for the Human
Rights Campaign, referring to the senator's opposition to the
nomination of James Hormel as envoy to Luxembourg. By JUDY HOLLAND.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-2000 (New Castle, N.H.) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush
campaigns in New Hampshire, where he turns down challenges from
conservatives to appoint only pro-life Supreme Court justices. The
Republican presidential candidate gives a free-trade lunch speech
and advocates an anti-ballistic missile system. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS (Atlanta) _ Southern Baptist Convention President Paige
Patterson is asking President Clinton's home church, Emanuel
Baptist Church in Little Rock, Ark., to once again consider
disciplinary action against the president because Clinton declared
June as Lesbian and Gay Rights month. By RICHARD VARA.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   STAGECOACH-COACH (Houston) _ Stagecoach Holdings, Britain's
largest bus and train company, agreed to buy Coach USA, the largest
U.S. charter bus and tour operator, for $1.23 billion in cash and
$638 million in assumed debt, in line with its strategy of becoming
an international transport company. By LAURA GOLDBERG.
</P>
<P>
   DYNEGY-ILLINOVA (Houston) _ Dynegy, a natural-gas and power
company, agrees to buy Illinova for about $2 billion in cash and
stock to gain power plants in the Midwest that can ship electricity
to major U.S. markets. By JENNIFER WALSH.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN _ Republican lawmakers' loathing of President
Clinton drives them to distraction. They agree on no principles or
policies. Their only common bond is their unconcealed distrust of a
president they have been unable to destroy. Their selfish reaction
to his success in Kosovo was shameful. Once again Clinton had
slipped through their fingers just as they were about to close
their hands around his throat. By MARIANNE MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS-DIERKER (Houston) _ Houston Astros manager Larry
Dierker will undergo brain surgery Tuesday morning to alleviate a
blood-vessel problem that caused him to suffer a seizure during
Sunday's game at the Astrodome. By DAVID BARRON.
</P>
<P>
   With: BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS-FALLOUT (Houston) _ Houston Astros officials decline
to comment on how long they expect manager Larry Dierker to be
sidelined, but it is clear the team will be without its field
manager for much, if not all, of the 1999 season. By CARLTON
THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-SPURS (San Antonio) _ At the start of the season, San
Antonio Spurs coach Greg Popovich was the man on the hot seat. His
team was struggling and he was one loss away from being fired. Now,
Popovich has guided his team to the NBA Finals, has a new contract
extension in the works, and is the toast of the Alamo City. By
JONATHAN FEIGEN.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-KNICKS (San Antonio) _ With a week left in the regular
season, Jeff Van Gundy's job with the New York Knicks was hanging
by a thread. His boss already had contacted other coaches about
replacing him, his team was on the verge of the missing the
playoffs, and several key players were criticizing his strategy.
Yet Van Gundy survived that crisis and has since steered the Knicks
from the No. 8 seed in the East to the NBA Finals. Yet he still
doesn't know where he will be working next season. By MICHAEL
MURPHY.
</P>
</TEXT>
