<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5126 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-KOSOVO-BOS &LR;      06-14 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-KOSOVO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LACKING ORDERS, RUSSIANS CANCEL RESUPPLY OF TROOPS IN PRISTINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES RADIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia and Herzegovina _ Russian commanders informed
Western peacekeepers that they intended to resupply their troops at
the Pristina Airport with a convoy from Bosnia Monday. They
prepared to depart, then returned to their basecamp when the
expected orders to proceed to Kosovo did not come.
</P>
<P>
   Colonel Nikolai Ignatov, the ranking Russian officer in Bosnia,
said the convoy would consist of 30 soldiers and 15 vehicles
carrying food, fuel and water. Western officers said the troops and
vehicles were assembled at Bijeljima, near where a bridge crosses
the Drima River into Serbia, waited throughout the day Monday, then
returned to their base at Ugljevik.
</P>
<P>
   If the convoy had gone through, it would have represented an
escalation of an already delicate standoff between Russia and NATO
over Russia's role in the peacekeeping efforts in Kosovo. The
crisis in NATO-Russian relations was set off last Friday when 180
Russian troops and 46 vehicles left Bosnia, and took up positions
at the strategically important Pristina Airport, arriving ahead of
the NATO troops. The move surprised NATO, coming just hours after
President Clinton gave assurances that the international
peacekeepers would act in a unified manner to ensure the withdrawal
of Yugoslav forces and help resettle hundreds of thousands of
Kosovar Albanian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The resupply convoy now awaiting orders to enter Kosovo is from
that same Russian contingent.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has ties to the Serbian government and opposed NATO's
11-week bombing war against the Serbs. It has pushed NATO to have
its own sector of control in northeastern Kosovo where most of the
ethnic Serbs live. NATO has refused to allow Russia to operate
independently.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has about 1,300 troops in a Serb-dominated area of
northeast Bosnia, where they perform peacekeeping duties similiar
to those of three dozen other nations who have about 30,000 troops
in other parts of the country. Only the Russians are not under NATO
command.
</P>
<P>
   Colonel Lee Hockman, spokesman for the United Nations-
santioned, NATO-led Stabilization Force for Bosnia (SFOR), said
Ignatov told SFOR officers he had received orders from Moscow to
prepare but no orders to move forward, and decided to return to
base to await instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Hockman said Monday that Ignatov also had informed Major General
Kevin Burns, the NATO commander for the north section of Bosnia, on
Friday, that he had orders from Moscow to deploy a contingent of
200 soldiers in Kosovo to function as an advanced party for a
larger group which was to come from Russia.
</P>
<P>
   But NATO was surprised when, two hours later, the troops
departed, Hockman said.
</P>
<P>
   Ignatov is stressing to Western commanders that his country has
no intentions of pulling out of SFOR, and that the 180 troops
already dispatched to Pristina either would return to Bosnia or be
replaced, Hockmans said, adding that there is no indication that
the remaining 1,100 Russian soldier in Bosnia are doing any out of
the ordinary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-99 2005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990614.0368 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5127 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-ART-2ND     06-14 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
CONCORD, N.H.: was unforgiving.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clinton may be a drag on the character issue, but, oddly, his
widely acknowledged political skills have also taken a toll on his
vice president. The concern goes beyond vice presidential-itis, an
infectious disease usually caught by standing in the draft of a
commander-in-chief. Most people appear clumsy next to Clinton, and
Gore is no exception. A recent joint engagement in Texas proved
such a disaster for Gore that the campaign is now on high alert to
keep him and his mentor from sharing a stage.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's advisers say that his difficulty in establishing his own
persona has been aggravated by his running in a vacuum, against
himself rather than against an identifiable opponent with
vulnerabilities to be exploited.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only has Gore been running in a vacuum, but you have the
reflection of Bill Clinton,'' one Gore adviser lamented. ``We're
being compared to the absolute best.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Sosnick, a senior adviser to Clinton, put it a little
differently. ``Gore has been running so far against two perfect
people _ Clinton, whose skills as a candidate are taking on mythic
proportions, and Greta Garbo,'' he said, referring to Bush's
ability to appeal to voters without saying much.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign has been reluctant so far to acknowledge Bradley,
Gore's only rival for the Democratic nomination. But this is
proving harder as Gore finds he still needs to court certain
audiences, including union workers and Iowa Democrats, who are
pleased to have an alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're struggling with whether to engage Bradley,'' said Bill
Carrick, a Democratic consultant based in Los Angeles. ``Do you
raise his stature or ignore him and hope he doesn't get traction?
That causes some indecisiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore aides take solace in his strong showing in early polls
testing him against Bradley. But the picture turns darker when Gore
is matched against Bush. Voters know little about Bush, but he
leads Gore in public opinion polls; most recently, a Newsweek
survey had Bush ahead, 54 percent to 36 percent.
</P>
<P>
   By large margins, voters say Bush is more of a leader than Gore,
more inspiring, has a better moral character and is more able to
get things done. The governor polls ahead of the vice president
across every category of voter, most alarmingly among the elderly
and women, two bedrock Democratic constituencies without whom the
Democrats cannot win.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats worry that Bush's talk of ``compassionate
conservatism'' will blur the ideological lines and magnify Gore's
weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem facing Al Gore is the fact that people see
him as a politician, through and through,'' one Democratic
consultant said. ``It's not that he's not smart or doesn't
understand where America is at.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., said he had told Gore he was
putting too much emphasis on things like endorsements from elected
officials. ``People see him as more of a politician than he really
is,'' Schumer said. ``But he's a substantive, policy-oriented guy,
and I think that's going to come through.''
</P>
<P>
   Coelho also dismisses the personality factor, saying the public
is not looking for ``a drinking buddy'' but someone with
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want Al Gore to be Al Gore,'' Coelho said. ``If you start to
let the computer in your head dictate what you should do, then you
lose your heart.''
</P>
<P>
   It is Al Gore's heart, his campaign says, that will be on
display this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-99 2006EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990614.0369 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5129 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     06-14 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; AYN RANDISTS AGAINST COMPASSION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Ayn Rand Institute is in full cry over  &UR; George W. Bush &LR; 's
launch of his official presidential campaign based on the
principles of ``compassionate conservatism.'' The Randists, who
believe in individual enterprise, charge that Bush is following in
the ``timid footsteps'' of his father, whose notion of fighting the
Democrats was to talk about ``a kinder and gentler'' nation.
</P>
<P>
   What that ``compassion'' really means is ``liberalism,'' says
 &UR; Andrew Bernstein  &LR; of the institute, ``a hand-wringing capitulation
to the proponents of the welfare state.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Bernstein, ``Bush and the Republican exponents of
this `compassionate conservatism' are frightened appeasers,
scurrying to avoid being labeled heartless for supporting
capitalism and freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. They're not only soft, they're also poets. Senator  &UR; Phil &LR; 
 &UR; Gramm &LR; , R-Texas, wrote a poem to invite supporters to a
fund-raising barbecue on July 4. A segment, as quoted in The Hill:
``My heart is full./ I long for you./ I've missed your smile/ and
money, too. ... Just say yes/ and with panache,/ I'll buy the beer/
with your cash.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PRINCE STAYS BUSY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - A partial list of charities and organizations supported by
 &UR; Prince Charles &LR; , printed in Biography magazine, includes the
National Rifle Association and the Goon Show Preservation Society.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other groups mentioned: Atlantic Salmon Trust, World
Piano Competition, British Sub-Aqua Club, British Parachute
Association, the Worshipful Company of Fruiterers Fruit Culture
Trust, Museum of Garden History, Orders and Medals Research
Society, Specialist Cheesemakers Association and Welsh Black Cattle
Society.
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Prince Philip  &LR; was displeased to learn that two priests
kissed at a reception &UR; Queen Elizabeth &LR;  threw recently for chaplains
and former chaplains. Buckingham Palace will limit the guest list
for future parties to invitees and their spouses. Companions are no
longer welcome, says the Times of London.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Actress  &UR; Lorraine Bracco  &LR; has filed for bankruptcy, explaining
that she is out of money after a six- or seven-year custody battle
with &UR; Harvey Keitel &LR; , says the New York Post.
</P>
<P>
   - Miramax Chairman &UR; Harvey Weinstein  &LR; has been fined $300 for
lighting a cigarette in the bathroom of a Concorde on the way from
New York to London in December. Weinstein told the magistrate that
he was an ``extremely nervous traveler'' and a ``man of good
character, anxious to avoid the stigma of a criminal conviction.''
He also said that Miramax had helped the British film industry.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BUILDING TRADES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Watching ``high iron guys'' scampering over the
10-story-or-so-high scaffolding they're building at Pier 30 for the
ESPN X Games,  &UR; Robert Menzimer  &LR; suggests that their agility beats
any that will be demonstrated by the Extreme sportsmen. Scrambling
over the metal framework ``seems a lot scarier to me than bungee
jumping and skateboarding,'' writes Menzimer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Daryl Glen  &LR; says he saw a ``Maximum Occupancy 10'' sign on a
construction-site portable rest room on Pacific Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LAUGHING AND ASHAMED &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Bathroom humor is in, says the latest Entertainment Weekly,
listing the excess of ``The Spy Who Shagged Me'' and noting that
even ``The Phantom Menace'' has two scatological jokes (Jar Jar
stepping in excrement, for example).
</P>
<P>
   ``The notion of intelligent versus unintelligent comedy is
irrelevant to me,'' says  &UR; Mike &LR;   &UR; Myers &LR; , creator of spy Austin
Powers. ``It's not too stupid as long as it's funny.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ted Baehr &LR; , publisher of Movie Guide (which gives ratings for
moral content), has a different view: ``Relying on bathroom humor
over and over is an easy creative crutch that ultimately leads to
an uncivil society. A few flatulence jokes in `Austin Powers' are
innocuous, but the sum total of all that raunchy humor all summer
takes a toll.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``What many people lose sight of is that the net worth of these
ultrawealthy young people is tied up in company stock. You also
can't expect that much from people who are building their first
house and don't even have kids in college yet. By and large, the
fruits of that accumulation will be felt 15, 20 years from now.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; William H.  &LR; Gates II, father of billionaire  &UR; Bill Gates &LR;  and
director of his son's foundation, telling Wired magazine why young
millionaires can't be expected to be very charitable.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-99 2007EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
