<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5135 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-2000-HNS &LR;      06-14 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH VOWS NOT TO PUT FEDERAL-COURT APPOINTEES UP TO A `LITMUS TEST'
ON ABORTION 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW CASTLE, N.H. _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush, in his first
campaign visit to this important primary state, said Monday that as
president he would not require his federal-court appointees to meet
a ``litmus test'' on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   In his first extended news conference with national media since
leaving home over the weekend, Bush addressed the character issue
by refusing to directly criticize President Clinton's personal
integrity. He also refused to elaborate on his own admittedly
``irresponsible'' youth.
</P>
<P>
   However, he vowed, with his right hand raised, to ``uphold the
dignity of the office'' if he wins the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has frequently said he opposes abortions, a particularly
sensitive issue in the Republican Party. He recently signed a new
Texas law requiring parents to be notified before the procedure can
be performed on their underage daughters.
</P>
<P>
   But he also has cautioned that ``America is not ready to
overturn Roe vs. Wade because America's heart is not right'' and
that government should pursue policies that discourage abortions.
</P>
<P>
   His answer to the judicial-appointments question may give
ammunition to Republican opponents who insist on a harder
anti-abortion stance, despite a new poll showing that in New
Hampshire, at least, the majority of voters favor abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   With Bush 34 percentage points ahead of his nearest competitor
in that new poll, his rivals quickly pounced on his comments about
an abortion test for court appointees.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm hearing right now from the governor is waffling on
the one issue that can clearly explain compassionate
conservatism,'' said candidate Gary Bauer, who last week demanded
that Bush promise to impose an abortion litmus test on Supreme
Court nominees. ``If compassionate conservative means anything, it
has to mean do anything we can to stop the loss of 1.5 million
unborn children every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Quayle said that because his anti-abortion position was
``rooted in conscience rather than politics, those I select for the
most critical positions in government, including my running mate or
nominees to the Supreme Court, will share it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan called Bush's abortion stance ``grossly
inadequate,'' and Steve Forbes said, ``I believe you should appoint
justices on a matter of principle. One of those principles is
belief in the sanctity of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said people he considers appointing to courts will share
``my overall philosophy and ... strictly interpret the
Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That criterion will be applied for all issues across the
board,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no litmus test except for whether or not the
judges will strictly interpret the Constitution. I am not a lawyer.
My job is to pick the judges who are qualified.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiny New Castle, a coastal town of about 900 residents, was the
Texas governor's first stop in New Hampshire, which in February
holds the nation's first presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   Bush attended an outdoor rally with about 300 supporters under a
tent. He joined his wife, Laura, to read to 25 children in the town
library and shook a lot of hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've waited so long for him to come to New Hampshire,
everybody wants to hold on to his hand and welcome him,'' one
supporter remarked as the governor spent 20 minutes making his way
through the crowd to the tent, greeting dozens of people along the
way.
</P>
<P>
   Bush acknowledged that he was late starting his New Hampshire
campaign, but said his top supporter in the state, U.S. Sen. Judd
Gregg, already had a Bush organization in place. And he promised:
``I'll be back. I'll be back a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   A poll of New Hampshire voters in the Boston Herald on Monday
indicated that Bush already had won strong support. Among
registered New Hampshire voters, Bush had 45 percent compared to 11
percent each for Elizabeth Dole and U.S. Sen. John McCain. The rest
of the GOP field were in the single digits.
</P>
<P>
   With those numbers probably in his mind, Forbes challenged Bush
to meet his Republican opponents in five debates between July and
December.
</P>
<P>
   ``That way, the electorate will not only clearly discern where
the candidates stand on issues of the day, but who truly means what
they say, and who will have the Reaganesque strength to carry
through with their promises,'' Forbes said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been criticized for his vague stance on many national
issues.
</P>
<P>
   The poll for the Herald and WCVB-TV also showed that two-thirds
of New Hampshire voters favor abortion rights, including half of
New Hampshire Republicans. More than half of New Hampshire's
anti-abortion voters said in the poll conducted last week that they
would vote for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The children Bush greeted at the New Castle library were in
kindergarten and first and second grade. Bush read from ``The Very
Hungry Caterpillar,'' a picture book designed to help children
learn their numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many of you read more than you watch TV?'' he asked. When
about three-fourths of the children raised their hands, he added,
``Your teachers are doing a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also spoke to more than 1,000 people at a New Hampshire
Federation of Republican Women luncheon in Manchester, where he
credited New Hampshire with being the ``maker of presidents.''
</P>
<P>
   He also met with firefighters in Bow, attended a fund-raiser for
a Republican congressman in Bedford and visited supporters at a
reception in Goffstown.
</P>
<P>
   In his wide-ranging news conference in New Castle, Bush also:
</P>
<P>
   -- Promised to lay out a plan for cutting federal taxes on ``my
timetable'' later in the campaign. He already has vowed to veto any
increases in federal income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   -- Reaffirmed his opposition to racial quotas and preferences,
but said he wanted to expand opportunities for immigrants to
America.
</P>
<P>
   -- Said he was ``concerned'' that the Clinton administration had
negotiated a peace settlement for Kosovo without having a plan for
carrying it out. ``It's important that Kosovo not become
partitioned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   -- Said he wanted to develop and deploy an anti-ballistic
missile system because ``it's important to bring certainty to an
uncertain world.``
</P>
<P>
   -- Called for the removal of all barriers to free trade.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if his promise to usher in the ``responsibility era'' in
America was an attack on Clinton's personal behavior, Bush replied,
``No. I'm talking about an overall cultural phenomenon.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said that people elected to high office should realize
they have taken an oath to ``uphold the dignity of the office to
which we've been elected.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush did not take the bait when he was challenged by a New
Hampshire reporter to clarify what he has often called his own
``irresponsible'' behavior when he was younger.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a game in Washington. It's called `gotcha.' It's a
game where you start a rumor and make a candidate prove a negative,
and I'm not playing the game,'' he insisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to try to elevate the discourse to ideas and
philosophies.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who kicked off his national campaign in Iowa on Saturday,
planned to campaign more in New Hampshire Tuesday and attend
fund-raisers in Boston and Greenwich, Conn., before returning to
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
