<HEADER>
A5137 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAPTIST-CONVENTION-1S     06-14 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTIST-CONVENTION-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baptists convene in Atlanta for annual meeting
 &HT;    (EDS: 1ST LEDE: Adds Internet information)
 &HT;    By Gayle White and Kim Sue Lia Perkes
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As Southern Baptists by the thousand convene in the
Georgia Dome today, President Clinton, the nation's top Baptist
layman, is being criticized for his stand on homosexual rights
again.
</P>
<P>
   About 14,000 official ``messengers'' to the convention and many
more visitors and denominational officials are expected for the
annual gathering of the flock and its dose of praise and politics.
</P>
<P>
   The Southern Baptist Convention is going high-tech, making it
possible for Baptists worldwide to watch the two-day annual meeting
live on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Headliners from outside the denominational hierarchy include
football star Reggie White, known for his anti-homosexual stance,
and the Rev. Jerry Falwell, best known as founder of the now
defunct Moral Majority.
</P>
<P>
   Some convention attendees interviewed Tuesday said they looked
forward to the worship and fellowship.
</P>
<P>
   After years of strife for control of the country's largest
Protestant group, the conservatives who now lead it are ``getting
our focus back on reaching the world for Christ,'' said the Rev.
Gary Dean, an evangelist from Fulton, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jeff Spooneybarger, whose brother Timothy signed with
the Braves as a pitcher in Orlando last week, said he expected the
greatest achievement of the convention to be ``its spirit of
worship and unity.''
</P>
<P>
   And Trudy Sturgill, a first grade teacher and pastor's wife from
Pineville, Ky., said of her first convention, ``More than anything,
it's spiritually uplifting.''
</P>
<P>
   But SBC leaders in pre-convention events were not about to
ignore a White House proclamation issued June 11 proclaiming this
Gay and Lesbian Pride Month 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Baptist president the Rev. Paige Patterson, speaking on
a denominational radio show Tuesday, called for President Clinton's
home congregation, Immanuel Baptist Church in Little Rock, to
discipline him.
</P>
<P>
   The proclamation, said Patterson, is ``entirely inconsistent
with his confession as an evangelical Christian and certainly as a
Southern Baptist.''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson said the proclamation should be ``the subject of
church discipline. The fact that he is President of the United
States ought to make no difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's proclamation praised ``America's diversity,'' condemns
hate crimes and encourages all Americans to recognize Gay and
Lesbian Pride month and ``observe this month with appropriate
programs, ceremonies, and activities.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sermon Tuesday to the Southern Baptist pastor's conference,
the Rev. Richard Land, head of the denomination's Ethics and
Religious Liberty Commission and host of the radio show, once again
made reference to the proclamation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what appropriate action is,'' Land said. ``It's praying
that God will stay his judgment on this country until this man is
no longer our president.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the Southern Baptist Convention rejected an effort to
deny credentials to Clinton's church because of his stands on
abortion and homosexuality. And last year, the convention voted
down narrowly a move to call on Immanuel to discipline the
president.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Wiley Drake, a California pastor and self-described
rabble-rouser, said he will introduce a resolution Tuesday
discouraging Americans from observing Gay Pride month ``other than
to pray for the repentance and salvation of those caught up in this
sinful lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   To see the action live, go to www.namb.net and click on ``Live
Webcast.'' For it to work, you'll need the latest version of
RealPlayer, which can be downloaded off the convention Internet
site.
</P>
<P>
   Paige Patterson, the convention's president, plans to focus the
Southern Baptists on inner-city evangelism.
</P>
<P>
   Senior pastor, the Rev. J. Kie Bowman, of Hyde Park Baptist
Church in Austin, Texas, said for all the media hype that seems to
surround convention activities, Baptists should bear two things in
mind: Resolutions adopted on the floor are not binding on any
Southern Baptist, and the voting messengers cast personal votes of
conscience, not ones that represent their home congregations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't tell our people what to vote,'' Bowman said.
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.; Kim Sue Lia Perkes writes for The Austin
American-Statesman, Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
