<HEADER>
A5138 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-CAMP-COX     06-14 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-CAMP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anderson, Williams no-shows at Falcons camp
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The warm and fuzzy memories of the Falcons' first trip
to the Super Bowl seemed far away Monday when running back Jamal
Anderson and right guard Gene Williams were absent from the first
day of passing camp.
</P>
<P>
   Both players have made it clear that contract concerns are
keeping them at home from the optional-attendance camp _ Anderson
in Salt Lake City and Williams in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's agent, Jim Sims, even suggested that he might ask the
team to trade the All-Pro back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sent them a letter (Monday) that said unless we have some
sort of show of good faith they were moving forward, Jamal was not
going to attend passing camp,'' Sims said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't hear something that indicates we'll be moving
forward, we may ask that they rekindle (trade) talks. Hopefully, we
can be part of those discussions.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, 26, was second in the NFL last season with a
franchise-record 1,846 rushing yards on a league-record 410 carries
and led the Falcons to the Super Bowl and a 16-3 record. He has
4,063 yards in his five-year career.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is scheduled to make $1.6 million in salary this season
plus $1 million in incentives that were earned during the 1998
season.
</P>
<P>
   Falcons officials have had little or no discussion about
contract extensions with nine players in the final year of their
contracts, in part because of salary-cap concerns. The Falcons will
have only $400,000 to spend after signing draft choices.
</P>
<P>
   But general manager Harold Richardon contacted Sims in November
to start talking about Anderson's contract.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, an eight-year veteran, came to Atlanta in 1996 and
started 34 of 35 games the past two seasons. He earned $750,000
last season and is scheduled to make $1 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``My agent called them in the middle of last season and asked
about my future,'' Williams said. ``The timetable for an answer
kept getting pushed back and pushed back. I think I'm one of the
best in the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamal didn't get 1,800 yards alone. I know a lot of us are in
the same boat (in terms of contracts about to expire), but a lot of
those guys are getting paid what they deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves didn't seem too concerned about the absences of Anderson,
Williams and middle linebacker Jessie Tuggle, who is on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to get bent out of shape,'' Reeves said. ``I'd
like to have everybody here ... but it's not mandatory. I haven't
talked to Jamal, but I thought he was going to be here. He
indicated to (running backs coach) George (Sefcik) he was going to
be here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to help (extension talks) one iota if he's
here, nor will it hurt if he's not,'' Reeves said. ``I talked to
Gene (Williams), and he said he thinks (being here) won't help him
get an extension.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten of Atlanta's projected starters are in line to become
unrestricted free agents after next season. The others are Tuggle,
center Robbie Tobeck, wide receiver Terance Mathis, fullback Bob
Christian, defensive ends Lester Archambeau and Chuck Smith,
defensive tackle Shane Dronett and free safety Eugene Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   The team's best offer to Anderson calls for a long-term contract
averaging $5.2 million per year.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson wants $10 million or more, in keeping with what several
of the NFL's top backs got with recent extensions. Team officials
don't want to go that much higher than the franchise-record $6
million quarterback Chris Chandler got last fall with his four-year
extension.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt Jamal is one of the top five backs, and
we're willing to pay that,'' Reeves said. ``But he says he wants to
reach up and be top three. Jamal and his agent are looking out for
himself; we've got to look out for the whole organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Some teammates aren't sure what to think. ``I hope we keep
everything together,'' cornerback Ray Buchanan said, ``because
we've got a good thing going and a chance to start a dynasty. The
salary cap can change all that.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
