<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON TRAVEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., June 20)  
(ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TO CATALINA ISLAND BY HIGH-SPEED CAT
</P>
<P>
   The voyage between Long Beach, Calif., and Santa Catalina
Island, off the southern California coast, will be reduced by 30
minutes to under an hour with the introduction of a high-speed
ferry scheduled for the end of this month. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The trip on the new catamaran, operated by Catalina Express,
will take 45 to 50 minutes between Long Beach and the island
village of Avalon, versus 1 hour 15 minutes on a regular ferry.
Only a helicopter ride is faster, taking 15 minutes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The new ship, named the Starship Express, can accommodate 300
passengers at speeds of up to 40 miles an hour. The vessel is
designed with computer controls that are supposed to smooth what
can sometimes be a choppy ride. Passengers will be able to choose
between riding in the main cabin or in a deluxe cabin that features
priority boarding and more comfortable furnishings. Round-trip fare
is $38 for the main cabin, $58 deluxe. Reservations are strongly
recommended. Information: (800) 429-4601.
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER FLOWER SHOWS MULTIPLY IN ENGLAND
</P>
<P>
   Two new flower shows have been added to the British
horticultural calendar, one in London, the other in Cheshire in
northern England. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Regent's Park Show, from June 25 to June 28 in the southeast
corner of the Inner Circle of Regent's Park, is a revival of a show
founded by the Royal Botanic Society that flourished throughout the
19th century. The organizers _ the Royal Parks Agency, the Royal
Parks Enterprises and Park Events Limited _ hope to recreate much
of the atmosphere of the original shows with Victorian bandstands
and traditional tents. The centerpiece will be the Grand Floral
Marquee, an enormous tent in which more than 90 of Britain's top
nurseries will exhibit plants ranging from brand-new orchids to
traditional roses. The 10 or 12 show gardens will include a Bronze
Garden, in which all the planting will be in shades of bronze, and
a Ripple Garden, with landscaping that looks like ripples. The show
will also include tours that focus on Regent's Park's trees. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tickets are $16 if bought in advance, $19 at the door; $8 after
5 p.m.; children 5 to 16, $8. Strawberries and cream and champagne
will be served in a tea garden. Tickets (44-870) 904-0500. Open 10
a.m. to 7.30 p.m., until 6 p.m. June 28.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Cheshire show, July 22 to 25, will be held on a 25-acre site
in the heart of Tatton Park, a National Trust property 200 miles
northwest of London. The organizer, the Royal Horticultural
Society, also runs the Chelsea Flower Show and the Hampton Court
Flower Show.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In addition to tents housing displays by nurseries and plant
societies, there will be a Heritage tent devoted to horticultural
art, design and conservation, and 29 show gardens. Various
artisans, including a dry-stone waller, a stone carver, a saddler
and a rush weaver, will demonstrate their trades.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Admission is $19 in advance, $22 at the gate, children $8.
Advance booking (44-870) 607-7444. Tatton Park is in Knutsford, 10
miles from Manchester. A shuttle bus to the show will operate from
Altrincham station on the Manchester-Cheshire line. Information:
(44-1625) 534400.
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY RAISES PRICES; OTHER PARKS FOLLOW
</P>
<P>
   For the second year in a row, Walt Disney World has raised the
price of admission to its Florida theme parks. And once again,
Universal Studios and Sea World are keeping up with the neighbors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On May 23 a one-day, one-park ticket increased by $2, bringing
the price for ages 10 and older to $44, or $46.64 with tax. Tickets
for ages 3 to 9 went up by $1 to $35, or $37.10 with tax. The
attractions affected are Disney's Animal Kingdom, Magic Kingdom,
Epcot, the Disney-MGM Studios, Sea World Orlando, Universal Studios
and Universal's Islands of Adventure park, which opened on May 28. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Various combination packages are available that offer some
savings. More information about the Universal parks: (800) 711-0080
or www.universalstudiosescape.com. Walt Disney World: (407)
824-4321 or www.disneyworld.com. Sea World: (800) 327-2424 and
www.seaworld.com.
</P>
<P>
   NERO'S STATELY PLEASURE DOME REOPENS
</P>
<P>
   The Domus Aurea, the palace built by the Emperor Nero between
A.D. 64 and 68, is scheduled to reopen to the public on Thursday.
It has been closed since the early 1980's for extensive
renovations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The palace was famous in its time for its size and magnificence,
but members of the Flavian dynasty, who came to power soon after
Nero's suicide in A.D. 68, began to dismantle it as part of a
scheme to wipe out all traces of Nero's tyrannical rule. The
Emperor Vespasian started with the area where one of his own
building projects, the Colosseum, now stands, stripping away marble
and gilded decorations, while the Emperor Trajan filled the
remaining rooms and halls with earth to serve as a foundation for
his baths. This actually helped preserve the palace, which remained
buried for hundreds of years until it was rediscovered in the late
15th century.
</P>
<P>
   Renaissance artists were among the first to enter some of the
rooms, through holes bored into the vaults of the halls, and their
autographs can be seen alongside the stuccoed and painted
decorations.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Domus Aurea (the name means Golden House) was renowned in
antiquity for the wealth of its decorations, though today many
scholars dispute the claim that the most important rooms were
actually lined with gold and precious jewels. What is certain is
that many of the rooms, 150 of which have been dug up (out of
perhaps 300 or so), were richly embellished with frescoes and
stuccoes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Around 30 rooms will be open to the public, but more will be
visible on the sides because now they are well lighted. The visitor
will pass from the gardens of the Colle Oppio, facing the
Colosseum, through 40-foot-high corridors and vast rooms that give
at least some sense of the palace's former glory. The room
dedicated to the Homeric cycle, with its frescoes by Fabullus, for
example, is a rare chance to see the work of this celebrated
artist. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The focal point of the visit is the octagonal hall, a large room
with a semicircular dome similar to that of the Pantheon, including
the large oculus, or eye, in the center. The Roman historian
Suetonius wrote that the vault was covered by removable and
perforated tiles that rained flower petals upon Nero's dinner
guests. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Domus Aurea, on the Colle Oppio next to the Colosseum, will
be open daily from 9 a.m. to 8 p.m. Visitors will enter in groups
of 25 at 15-minute intervals. Tickets are expected to cost about $7
and can be reserved at (39-06) 481-5576.
</P>
</TEXT>
