<HEADER>
A5152 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-DUNCAN-COX     06-14 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DUNCAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Can the Spurs' Duncan fill Jordan's Nikes?
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO, Texas _ In the frenzy and eagerness to project
``the next Michael Jordan,'' everyone omitted from the list Tim
Duncan, the San Antonio Spurs' center with the demeanor of a
Caribbean hotel valet: pleasant, accommodating and, most
definitely, relaxed. No problem.
</P>
<P>
   And yet now, Duncan is there at the top of the list, very much
Jordan's heir in a couple of compelling ways. One, Duncan is
universally regarded as the best player in the NBA. And, two,
Duncan has led his team, the San Antonio Spurs, to within smelling
distance of the league championship, a Jordan staple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only is he the best player in the NBA,'' New Yorks Knicks
coach Jeff Van Gundy said, ``but fundamentally, he is so sound in
the way he plays the game. It's not flashy, highlight reel. It's a
coaching clinic. He has a fundamentally sound approach to the game.
It's not an athletic game. To me, from a coach's standpoint, that's
the beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   Which also describes Duncan's style. It is not anywhere near the
brilliance of Jordan, tongue-wagging and elevating dunks over
helpless foes early in his career and burying the unfathomable
fadeaways in the later years. Duncan would just as soon stick a
bamboo stick under his finger nail than exhibit flash. ``There's
only one Michael Jordan,'' Duncan said. ``And we won't see
another.''
</P>
<P>
   He's probably right, but the start of his career has been
nothing short of stunning. The Spurs _ winners of 42 of their last
48 games _ take on the Knicks in Game 1 of the NBA Finals beginning
Wednesday night at the Alamodome mostly because of Duncan's
dominance.
</P>
<P>
   He averaged 21.7 points in the regular season and had a
league-leading 37 double-doubles. In the playoffs, he has led San
Antonio to consecutive sweeps over the Los Angeles Lakers and
Portland Trailblazers with averages of 21.5 points and 10.4
rebounds. In Jordanesque fashion, he's reliable when the Spurs need
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best player in the league,'' exciting and athletic
Knicks forward Marcus Camby said. ``I'm just trying to get where he
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Camby and Duncan met in December 1995, when they
were superstar college juniors. Camby of UMass had 17 points 9
rebounds and 3 blocks to Duncan's 9 points (4 for 18 shooting), 12
boards, 4 blocks. And Camby's team won.
</P>
<P>
   Much has changed since then. ``We were both young, young pups,''
Camby said. ``I remember the hype. We were both high profile. I was
more of a scorer then, getting plays run for me. Right now, it's
definitely different roles.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan's anticipated role of complementary player to perennial
all-star David Robinson changed in Duncan's rookie season, when he
was named to first team All-NBA _and he's only tightened his hold
on Robinson's neighborhood since then. He was first team All-NBA
this season, plus first-team all-defense and an MVP candidate.
</P>
<P>
   All of it is surprising to everyone, including the coach who
helped hone his skills in college. Dave Odom of Wake Forest
conceded Monday from his office that even he did not envision
Duncan's rapid ascent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought by his fifth or sixth season, he'd be approaching
this good,'' Odom said. ``In no way did I feel he'd reach this
level in two years. But the thing I'm most proud of is that he
answers the bell every single night to the best of his ability. And
you can't say that too often about the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   Odom said Duncan's development at Wake was far less rapid. ``It
was gradual,'' he said. ``His first college game, we played Alaska
in the Alaska Shootout. We started him at the last minute, and he
had no points and three rebounds. It was a gradual incline in his
growth since then.''
</P>
<P>
   In his sophomore year, Duncan showed Odom all he needed to know
that the player would have a sparkling professional future. In a
game at Wake Forest against North Carolina, Duncan failed to
inbound the ball at the end of a tight game, and the Tar Heels went
on to win in overtime. ``It wasn't his fault,'' Odom recalled,
``but Tim never forgave himself. So a month and a half later, we
play at Chapel Hill. Timmy gets 29 points on 11-for-13 shooting, 21
rebounds and 5 blocked shots. Rasheed Wallace gets no field goals
and three rebounds. We win. And I think that shows you how much he
grew. He never forgot that other game. His determination is
incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   And so is his discipline. While other players exercise their
enthusiasm through high-fives, chest bumps, head-shaking and the
like, Duncan simply does his damage and runs down court. The blank
facial expression seldom changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get a real sense of pride watching him play, because I see
the presence he's carried to the NBA,'' Odom said. ``He just plays
on. He knows that in the end, his style will win out. And his
willingness to do the right things, make the right plays,
possession by possession is remarkable. He's not flashy. He's not
impressed with himself.''
</P>
<P>
   All he's done is impress others with his uncanny footwork in the
low post, which allows him to maneuver around stronger defenders
and over smaller ones. And when the inside is jammed, no problem.
Duncan, who grew up a swimmer in the Virgin Islands, simply moves
his game to the perimeter, where he's an accurate face-up jump
shooter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We rely on him to do a lot, and he does it,'' guard Avery
Johnsons said. ``And it's all so quite, so effortlessly. It's his
league now.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Bunn writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
