<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-NOTES15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NBA Notes: Johnson still questionable for Game 1
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO, Texas _ The New York Knicks are not counting on
Larry Johnson for Wednesday night's Game 1 of the NBA Finals
against San Antonio, but they are hopeful. Johnson's showing some
progress in the sprained right knee and he seems determined to be
healthy enough to play with a brace.
</P>
<P>
   His status will not be determined until just prior to the 9 p.m.
gametime. Johnson has spent virtually every minute of every day
since he got hurt Friday in Game 6 of the Eastern Conference finals
getting treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pain is pain,'' he said. ``I don't want to rule out Wednesday
or Friday. I'm just going to see what happens, how it feels and go
from there. But it's worse for me to play and not be able to do the
things I'd like to do than sitting out.''
</P>
<P>
   With Johnson either out or limited, the call in New York is for
Marcus Camby to start in his place. Camby has been a major
post-season conributor off the bench. Coach Jeff Van Gundy said he
had not made up his mind about his lineup, but it's likely Camby
will continue in his role as bench spark.
</P>
<P>
   Camby was not concerned about it. ``I'm no star,'' he said.
``I'm just a guy out ther among stars. I don't care who gets the
glory. I just want to get my ring and be a part of a championship
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, because Patrick Ewing is already out with a partially
torn Achilles, the Knicks plan to petition the league to add
another player to their roster. That likely would be forward Ben
Davis, who spent time with the team this season but was not on the
playoff roster. The NBA, however, likely will not grant them
another player.
</P>
<P>
   Super-loud Mario
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio leader Mario Elie, whose verbal lashing of David
Robins, Tim Duncan and Sean Elliott sparked the Spurs' turnaround,
refused to let up. Having won consecutive championships with the
Houston Rockets, Elie knows the virtues of being prepared.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, the Spurs are overwhelming favorites to become
the first former ABA team to win an NBA championship, and Elie will
not let his team fall prey to overconfidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting here is great, but I'm telling my guys every day, over
and over, we haven't done anything yet,'' Elie said. ``People call
us favorites. I told my guys to do all their shopping now so they
won't be out so much in public listening to all that crap. We've
got a long way to go. You think the Knicks care about being
underdogs? They didn't against Miami or Atlanta or Indiana. Why
would they against us? We're going to have to beat that team, and
we can't do it going into the series feeling comfortable. We have
to maintain an urgency.''
</P>
<P>
   The prodigal son
</P>
<P>
   Knicks forward and former Texas Christian star Kurt Thomas, who
missed nearly two years with an ankle injury, said he's glad he
disregarded friends' advice to sign as a free agent with anyone but
the Knicks. ``They said that I wouldn't play, that I wouldn't do
what I wanted,'' Thomas said. ``Now, I'm coming back for the first
time. I'm coming home the right way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Doctor is in
</P>
<P>
   Orlando's Doc Rivers made his first roster move as coach, and it
was not a pleasant one. He cut former Hawk Dominque Wilkins, with
whom he teammed with in Atlanta during the 1980s. Wilkins played
one season with the Magic but was seldom used by former coach Chuck
Daly.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
