<HEADER>
A5156 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-FINALS-COX     06-14 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FINALS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stars aging nicely so far
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ When people, including maligned sports fans in
western New York, went searching for evidence that possibly could
tilt the Stanley Cup Finals in favor of the Buffalo Sabres, two
factors stood out: the wizardry of Dominik Hasek and the receding
hairlines on the Dallas Stars' roster.
</P>
<P>
   The goalie hasn't disappointed. But those expecting the Stars to
require walkers by the middle of the series might want to
re-evaluate the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas, which holds a 2-1 lead going into Game 4 of the finals
tonight at Marine Midland Arena, appeared far less weary than the
more youthful Sabres on Saturday, when the teams were playing their
third game in five nights. Further, the Stars have outscored their
four younger playoff opponents _ Edmonton, St. Louis, Colorado,
Buffalo _ 32-16 in the third period and overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the advantage lies in younger legs right now,''
Sabres coach Lindy Ruff said. ``Before the series, I thought that
was a good theory. But I'm not thinking it now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' playoff roster includes 39-year-old Guy Carbonneau,
38-year-old Craig Ludwig and 35-year-olds David Reid, Brian
Skrudland and Pat Verbeek, all of whom have played key roles in the
postseason. Carbonneau played 19 minutes in Game 3, second-most
among Dallas forwards, won a game-high 17 face-offs and helped kill
off eight Stars penalties, blocking three shots.
</P>
<P>
   The secret: ``Vitamins,'' he said. ``Lots and lots of
vitamins.''
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau has played in 205 career playoff games and was on two
Stanley Cup winners in Montreal. He said he was amused when some
projected doom for the aging Stars. ``They've said the same thing
for the last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Keane, a relative pup at 32, said, ``When we lose a game,
our age always seems to come up. When we win, nothing is said about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny when people talk about the age of our hockey
team,'' coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``Age is nothing. The age of your
heart is more important.
</P>
<P>
   ``The common denominator with these veterans is, when they go on
the ice they have an arrogance about them,'' he said. ``It's a
great quality to have. They feel that regardless of their style of
play, their role, they're the best player on the ice. They really
feel they can impact the game in a positive way.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruff said his players ``burned out'' in Game 3 after throwing
countless bodychecks early in the game, then extending their shifts
too long. The Stars players often have short shifts of 30 to 40
seconds, and they play four forward lines whenever possible.
</P>
<P>
   But having a team of long-time veterans on the roster does have
its problems, Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to get your wings in coaching in the NHL, you need
to go through the experience of having a veteran team,'' he said.
``There can be a lot of conflicts. Because of their experiences,
they have some strong ideas on which direction we should point the
ship, and guys can get going a hundred different ways.''Jeff
Schultz writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
