<SLUG> BC-HKN-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stanley Cup Notebook: Hull considered 'doubtful' for Game 3
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Not withstanding the standard quota of injury
misinformation that flows from coaches in the playoffs, Dallas
coach Ken Hitchcock continued to express doubt Monday that Brett
Hull would play in tonight's fourth game of the Stanley Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   Hull, who scored two goals in the first two games of the series,
aggravated a groin pull in Game 3 and did not practice Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think he's doubtful,'' Hitchcock said.
``Realistically, we might be doing more damage than anticipated if
we put him in there, and I don't think we can take that chance
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull would not speculate on his status, but he did say, ``That
was the funnest practice I had all year.''
</P>
<P>
   He also criticized the ice conditions at Marine Midland Arena.
``It's just as bad, if not worse, than Dallas,'' he said, adding
that poor ice and stronger, faster players are the biggest reason
for the increase in injuries in the league.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he was dazed by the same check that led to his
exit last game, Hull said, ``No, you couldn't hurt this head.''
</P>
<P>
   Changes
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo coach Lindy Ruff labeled Dallas's Joe Nieuwendyk ``the
most dangerous player in the series right now,'' and said he will
make appropriate matchup changes. The Sabres' forward line centered
by Michael Peca, who had been shadowing the Stars' Mike Modano,
probably will open against Nieuwendyk. Ruff also might shuffle some
line combinations to spark some offense, particularly from the
scoreless Miroslav Satan.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, expect the Sabres to skate shorter, stronger shifts,
mimicking the Stars, and not overexert themselves throwing body
checks. ``One thing we did in Game 3 was we went out of our way to
keep hitting, and we wasted a lot of energy,'' Ruff said. ``We want
to finish our checks, but we don't want to be running from one end
of the rink to the other. Then, after 30 seconds, we have three
forwards worn out. We've got to be more under control.''
</P>
<P>
   Quote/unquote
</P>
<P>
   Ruff, when asked if he was thinking about having to win three
out of four games against Dallas to win the series: ``No. If this
had been a best out of three, then I'd be scared to death.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Schultz writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
