<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WANGO-TANGO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILD WILD WANGO TANGO 2 GOES OFF SMOOTHLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The only thing missing from KIIS-FM's Wild Wild
Wango Tango 2 hit parade Saturday at Dodger Stadium was a visit
from Jar Jar Binks.
</P>
<P>
   Binks was beaten to the promotional punch at the 55,000-seat
daylong event by an Austin Powers look-alike who worked the crowd
and posed for photos.
</P>
<P>
   Not that there was a lot of time for lollygagging around the
sun-baked stadium seeking out clones of Mike Myers.
</P>
<P>
   The Burbank Top 40 station produced a superbly well-run event,
headlined by Ricky Martin in his first Los Angeles appearance since
becoming a mainstream sensation, that got most of the 11 acts on
and off stage with a minimum of fuss or delay.
</P>
<P>
   The largely female audience was clearly pleased with the range
of performers, including sex symbols Martin, Enrique Iglesias and
98 Degrees, along with Britney Spears, Will Smith, M.C. Hammer,
Blondie, Shaggy, Nancy Sinatra, UB40 and Fabrice Morvan.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was sort of touching to witness so much female fan
power in one place, reacting with shrieks, tears and blown kisses
to the cute features and sculpted torsos on display.
</P>
<P>
   Musically, pop ruled the roost. Martin lived up to the hype,
delivering a slam-bang set that showed him to be a whirlwind of
eye-catching dance moves and engaging Latin-tinged pop.
</P>
<P>
   Opening with the smash hit ``Livin' La Vida Loca,'' Martin kept
the crowd on the far edge of hysteria, offering dynamic versions of
``Shake Your Bon-Bon'' and ``The Cup of Life,'' which he performed
on the Grammy telecast in February, sparking a fascination with the
pop audience that propelled his recent self-titled English-language
debut album to the top of the charts.
</P>
<P>
   The family-filled crowd also swayed to the sweet teeny-pop
balladry of cute-boy foursome 98 Degrees, decked out in camouflage
pants and bizarre ammo vests revealing crowd-pleasing bare chests.
</P>
<P>
   At least some of us were looking forward to Spears, although the
17-year-old pop queen's uninvolving set turned out to be the day's
biggest disappointment. File this kid under ``one-hit wonder.''
</P>
<P>
   The newly reunited Blondie fared better and eventually got the
crowd dancing at their seats with '80s cuts like ``Call Me'' and
``Rapture,'' plus the recent Euro-hit, ``Maria.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, Iglesias performed just one number before returning
backstage.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, booked to promote the forthcoming ``Wild Wild West''
film, mimicked the moves from his videos for ``Men in Black,''
``Goin' to Miami'' and the title track of the new flick, and was
joined by rapper Kool Moe Dee and former partner DJ Jazzy Jeff for
an energetic segment at dusk as anticipation built for Martin's 10
p.m. appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Our only complaint: More variety of food and drink was needed in
the stands. But in the end, a couple of Dodger Dogs, popcorn and
soda went down well with a particularly sweet bill. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
