<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOM-WAITS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAITS MAKES UP FOR LOST TIME AT WILTERN SHOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAMES HAMES  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ His band already in position, Tom Waits entered
the Wiltern Theatre from the back, coming through the roaring crowd
under spotlights and singing through a bright red megaphone,
mustering the audience like both Billy Sunday and the demon he came
to fight. He climbed on stage, stepped upon a short, dirt-filled
platform, kicking up dust and kicking into ``Black Rider.'' ``So
come on in/ It ain't no sin/take off your skin/and dance around in
your bones.''
</P>
<P>
   And the faithful, waiting 10 years since his last show like
this, were delighted.
</P>
<P>
   Making a run through crowd favorites (``I Don't Wanna Grow Up,''
``Jockey Full of Bourbon,'' ``Time'') and a big handful (``Picture
in a Frame,'' ``Eyeball Kid,'' ``Filipino Box Spring Hog,'' ``Come
on Up to the House'') from the recent ``Mule Variations,'' Waits
and band blazed a path through his (and co-writer/wife Kathleen
Brennan's) eight records, an observance of both the bright lights
and shadows of life's carnival. Waits makes a personable guide.
</P>
<P>
   He filled spaces between songs with schtick: anecdotes, bits of
trivia, L.A. stories. Waits' tidbits start out as mostly true but
end elsewhere _ a spider needing a foot rub, Western Avenue leading
to Mecca, L.A.'s one honest mechanic moving to Boston, or did he
say Austin? Waits' voice always sounds as if it's coming through a
megaphone, or to mix some metaphors from his songs, the broken
china voice of rusty brandy stirred with a nail.
</P>
<P>
   His arrangements are also mixed metaphors of sorts. There's that
German dance hall organ with the Pirates of the Caribbean banjo
done as a kind of samba. Add to that snippets of bluesy a capella
inside the orchestrated accidents and the ``what's that buzzing
noise?'' production that make up his sound. It's all very strange
yet vaguely familiar, like a deja vu that belongs to somebody else.
</P>
<P>
   And the faithful at Sunday's performance ate it up, screaming
approval for ``16 Shells From a Thirty-Ought Six'' from the pivotal
``Swordfishtrombones'' from '83, to singing along with ``Innocent
When You Dream'' from ``Big Time'' from '87, to laughing at the ad
libs in ``What's He Building?'' from ``Mule Variations.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, the crowd just wanted him to kick up some dust.
He did, after a two-encore and two dozen-song show, the stage
around his microphone and his pants were covered in dirt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-99 2033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
