<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITNESS SAYS HE SAW LEWIS SNIFF `SUBSTANCE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- A former longtime Celtics season-ticketholder said
Monday that he saw Reggie Lewis sniffing ``a shiny white powdered
substance'' in a public restroom at a Saugus pizza parlor a year
before he died.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying in the medical malpractice trial stemming from the
Boston Celtics star's death, Ronald J. Marks said he witnessed the
incident by chance, as he entered the men's restroom during a
Celtics charity auction he had attended with his two children in
July 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Marks, 49, said he entered the restroom alone and immediately
observed ``two tall African-American gentlemen,'' one of whom was
holding a ``two-inch plastic vial and miniature spoon with a white
powdered substance'' to the nose of the other man, whom Marks
identified as Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   He could not identify the other man, and he said no one else was
present.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was up against his nostril,'' said Marks, who acknowledged
a 20-year history of drug use dating to 1970, but who said he is
now sober. ``He was sniffing it.''
</P>
<P>
   During cross-examination, attorneys for Lewis's widow, Donna
Harris-Lewis, who has vehemently denied her husband used drugs,
attacked Marks's credibility, questioning him about his long
history of drug abuse and his long criminal record, which includes
several felony convictions for heroin possession and several
assault charges.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, asked by Harris-Lewis's lawyer, Robert G. Harley,
if he considered himself a ``family man,'' Marks replied that he
did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does that accord with you trying to run your wife over with a
car?'' Harley asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was her point of view,'' answered Marks, who has since
divorced, but whose former wife appeared in the courtroom for most
of his testimony, a fact pointed out by a defense attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Marks, who appeared uncomfortable on the stand, also
acknowledged that his former wife had once accused him of spraying
Lysol in her face, and that she had taken out three restraining
orders against him.
</P>
<P>
   Harley also produced a document suggesting that Marks falsely
told a psychologist in 1995 that he had no prior criminal record.
Marks denied doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Harley also accused Marks of repeatedly dodging efforts by his
law firm to locate and question him prior to the trial. Asked if he
had appeared in a window naked and shouted obscenities when a
private investigator hired by Harley arrived at his house, Marks
acknowleged that he had, but he noted that ``it was 10 p.m. and I
just got out of the bathtub.''
</P>
<P>
   Marks, who said he worked in ``packaging sales,'' said he held
Celtics season tickets from 1981 to 1994, and that he auctioned
them off after declaring bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, jurors were read a deposition from former Celtics
employee Wayne LeBeaux, who said he had smoked marijuana in his
condominium with Lewis and two women at a summer basketball camp in
Maine in the late 1980s or 1990.
</P>
<P>
   LeBeaux, who attorneys said was unable to testify in person,
began working for the team as ballboy in 1979 and rose to become
equipment manager and ``director of travel.'' His job was
terminated in 1997 with the arrival of new management.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors also heard from Dr. H. Thomas Aretz, a cardiac
pathologist at Massachusetts General Hospital and associate
professor of pathology at Harvard Medical School, who said the
cause of Lewis's death could not be determined by scarring found on
his heart during an autopsy.
</P>
<P>
   Called as an expert witness for the defense, Aretz said scarring
in Lewis's heart was ``not specific enough to say anything about
its specific cause,'' but that it was ``consistent'' with damage
caused by cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Aretz's testimony was intended to weaken the testimony of
Stanley Evans, the state's chief medical examiner, who said Lewis
died because his heart was damaged by a common virus and weakened
by structural defects, and that cocaine use played no role in his
death.
</P>
<P>
   As for whether Lewis's scarring had been caused by a virus or by
cocaine, ``I don't think you can say it either way,'' said Aretz.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Judge Thayer Fremont-Smith ordered jurors to
disregard the testimony of former Northeastern University health
director Job Fuchs, who had contradicted himself on the stand
Friday, saying both that Lewis had and had not tested positive for
drugs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-99 2033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
