<DOCNO> NYT19990614.0388 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5165 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BBA-SAFECO-SPI &LR;      06-14 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
NEW STADIUM COMING TOGETHER 
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-SAFECO-SPI   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Water drips down the stairways at Safeco Field and dust and
debris still cover other sections of the new stadium, particularly
down the left field line.
</P>
<P>
   With one month to go before the $517 million ballpark opens its
gates on outdoor baseball, those are good signs to Ken Johnsen,
director of the project for the Public Facilities District.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still a lot of work to do, but it will come together
overnight,'' he said, whistling comfortably during an energetic
tour of the structure he's managed the past three years. ``There
are just a lot of little things. And they are doing something to
just about everything.''
</P>
<P>
   The water isn't from a leaking roof or even a rainstorm. It's
from power washers hosing down the sections that are now complete.
And that disheveled look at the west end of the park exists only
because the plans called for the work to begin in right field, home
plate and outside before finishing around the other end.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always worked the project this way, so this is the least
finished part,'' Johnsen said, stepping through the club seat
section in left field and climbing to the suites above, which are
linked to a shared food and beverage area by a staircase.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the nuts and bolts are already fastened, but some double
shifts are being scheduled to make the final July 15 deadline.
Currently, there are about 750 workers on site, down from a peak of
about 1,000 when major work was being performed on the retractable
roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a good, aggressive pace in front of us,'' Johnsen
said, noting that Bank One Ballpark in Phoenix had about 1,000
people working around the clock to finish the stadium in time for
the 1998 inaugural season. ``Everybody who shows up to work
everyday is pumped. You really get high production right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are some details and fan amenities that may not be
complete until just before the gates open for the first game.
</P>
<P>
   The counters and kitchen fixtures in concession stands are now
going in, and they all sprout baseball-themed monikers, including
``Hit it Here Cafe,'' and ``Ribbies Barbecue.'' After they are
hooked up, the concession stands have to be inspected and cleared
by the Health Department and the Fire Department before the
opening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Concessions and concession hookup are probably the biggest
challenge that we will be absolutely be working on right up to July
15,'' Johnsen said.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the last details to be completed before the
park can be opened:
</P>
<P>
   The screen behind home plate now glares in the sun. It will be
painted black.
</P>
<P>
   About 600 Zenith televisions must be installed in suites,
concession areas, restaurants and media facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Panels one and two of the three-paneled roof have been tested,
but panel three has just been completed and awaits testing.
</P>
<P>
   The lights must be trained on a grid laid out on the field and
approved by Major League Baseball. Each of the 500 lights that ring
the top of the ballpark is being aimed at a specific spot.
</P>
<P>
   Most advertising and sponsorship signs are on site but are not
installed.
</P>
<P>
   Stairwells, seating areas and concourses are being power washed,
and each individual seat has to be checked and cleaned.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the unfinished final detail work resulted from
afterthoughts once construction began.
</P>
<P>
   One of the last changes, for example, was to add windows around
the southwest main gate, protecting the rotunda area from the
elements and blocking out gusts coming through the concourse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind, when it's cold and rainy, comes from the
southwest,'' Johnsen said. ``The feeling here was that you reach
the inside of the building when you go inside those gates, (so)
let's put some glass up.''
</P>
<P>
   Also yet to be completed is a cable around the upper seating
levels, strung three to four inches above the railings already in
place. Johnsen said that although the railing height met building
codes, concerns were raised that a higher barrier was needed. A
cable was chosen because it didn't disrupt views as much as a full
rail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept going back to what was the code, but there is a point
where people just don't feel comfortable,'' he said. ``There had
been a enough people who commented that these looked low.''
</P>
<P>
   Fine tuning the stadium is a process that might take several
years, according to Johnsen.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be places in the building where after you've
operated it for a while, you will have to make some changes,''
Johnsen said. ``I don't know what that is. It depends on the fans'
reaction and how they like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though it is still a month away from opening, Safeco Field
already has hosted a number of tour groups from other stadiums
being constructed, such as groups from Milwaukee, Houston and San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're coming to see us. Right now, this will be the best
ballpark in the world when we're finished,'' Johnsen predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would suffer a postpartum depression once all the
work is finished and the building is turned over to the Mariners,
Johnsen said he would like to return to the stadium with a press
pass just so he could cover every game and continue to spend most
of his time inside Safeco's walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels really good that it's turning out so well, but it's
not like it's going away once it's finished,'' he said. ``You can
come and visit it for years or bring your kids and your grandkids
here. Not only me, but there are three or four thousand other
people who can say, `I worked on that.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-99 2034EDT &QL; 
