A5174 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFI-100-LADN     06-14 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFI-100-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFI GUARDS LIST AHEAD OF `100 STARS' SPECIAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Eds: ``Tonight'' refers to Tuesday, June 15)  
By MARLA MATZER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ What becomes a legend most? If you believe the
American Film Institute, it's being elected to their list of the
top movie stars in cinema history. The results of their
invitation-only poll will be revealed at 8 tonight on the CBS
special ``AFI's 100 Years ... 100 Stars.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there will be only 50 ``legends'' named on the show,
with appearances by 50 contemporary stars including Dustin Hoffman,
Goldie Hawn, Lynn Redgrave and Jim Carrey.
</P>
<P>
   A videotape about the program sent to the press shows James
Woods praising Bette Davis, and Jessica Lange gushing about Marlon
Brando, for example. ``Bette Davis had an extraordinary way of
showing her vulnerability, yet she was incredibly strong as a
person,'' says Woods. Of Brando, Lange says: ``When you watch
Brando in `Streetcar' ... even in his stillness, it's so
thrilling.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Lemmon makes a brief appearance at the beginning of the
show to explain the criteria of who was eligible to be named a
``legend.'' Only those stars whose first on-screen appearance
occurred in or before 1950 _ or who have died, if their debut
occurred after 1950 _ are eligible. This renders Lemmon ineligible,
along with such actors as Clint Eastwood, Paul Newman and, as
Lemmon cracks, ``some guy named Matthau.''
</P>
<P>
   The show is hosted by Ms. Good-Ship-Lollipop (and a nominee)
herself, Shirley Temple Black. ``I think it's very important for
all of us to remember our past with the movie legends of our
time,'' said Black, who rarely makes entertainment-related
appearances these days. ``After all, movies are a mirror of the
time, very often. Sometimes the image is not very attractive in the
mirror. Other times, it's a beautiful or funny picture.''
</P>
<P>
   But what viewers will most want to find out is: Will Jimmy
Stewart beat out Humphrey Bogart? Will James Dean make the cut,
despite his career being cut short? Will famous rivals Bette Davis
and Joan Crawford both rate with voters? You'll have to tune in
tonight to find out, since results of the list are being kept
secret until airtime. The show will be in ``countdown'' format,
with the 25th-ranking male and female star announced, followed by
the 24th and so on.
</P>
<P>
   There are strong clues, however, as to who some of the top
vote-getters are. An ad this week for music and video retailer the
Wherehouse co-promoted the AFI show with special prices on videos.
Among the advertised films: ``All About Eve'' (Bette Davis),
``Rebel Without a Cause'' (James Dean), ``The Maltese Falcon''
(Humphrey Bogart) and ``Spartacus'' (Kirk Douglas). Even John Wayne
and Marilyn Monroe, two hugely popular stars who often haven't
gotten their due from critics, are likely to appear on the AFI
countdown.
</P>
<P>
   Coming one year after AFI's much-hyped and much-critiqued ``100
Years ... 100 Movies'' list, this list is again sure to arouse
controversy. AFI officials claim to be happy and satisfied about
the heated discussion of their list, which, for example, did not
include any of the films of Buster Keaton. They won't reveal how
many people voted among the critics, film executives and artists
that received ballots, other than to say the number was
``comparable'' to the number who voted on last year's poll.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that is quantifiable is the exposure AFI has gotten
from the process. The Los Angeles-based organization, like
publications including Entertainment Weekly, has found that lists
sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``The response has been phenomenal,'' said Jean Picker
Firstenberg, director and CEO of the AFI. ``I think we've
established ourselves as a national educational and cultural
entity. ... We get calls nearly every day now from organizations
around the country wanting to do joint projects with us.''
</P>
<P>
   This is important not only for AFI's stated mission of
``advancing and preserving'' the art of the moving image. It's also
important to the non-profit's bottom line, since it, like a number
of arts organizations, lost funding in the recent National
Endowment for the Arts budget cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's ``100 Movies'' special on CBS was a ratings success,
and the network is obviously counting on this special to repeat
that. They're devoting three hours of prime time to the ``100
Stars'' show.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the obvious commercial prospects, Firstenberg emphasizes
that extreme care was taken to keep the list from being ``a
popularity contest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To have a comprehensive appreciation ... you really have to
have time to understand a person's body of work,'' said
Firstenberg, explaining the criteria for the list. ``We decided to
use the half-century mark for our cutoff to make sure we were
considering the context and not just popularity.''
</P>
<P>
   Firstenberg hints strongly that this may not be the last list
you'll see from AFI. ``This is a very exciting time, because we're
not only celebrating a century, we're celebrating a millennium,''
says Firstenberg. ``I think there are many different ways to look
at this, because our connection to cinema is so profound ... I
think we'll be seeing more of this type of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The show: ``AFI's 100 Years ... 100 Stars.'' &QL; 
When: 8 to 11 tonight. &QL; 
Where: KCBS (Channel 2). &QL; 
The stars: Hosted by Shirley Temple Black. Brief appearances by 50
current stars, including Jack Lemmon, Julia Roberts and Billy Bob
Thornton; classic film clips featuring nominated ``legends.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
