<HEADER>
A5176 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REBELS-ART-110     06-14 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REBELS-ART-1100(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KLA BEGINS RE-ESTABLISHING ITSELF AS A FORCE TO BE RECKONED WITH 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-REBELS, KOSOVO-EUROPE-ASSESS) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRIZREN, Yugoslavia _ As Yugoslav troops withdraw under NATO
tanks and guns, the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army guerrillas are
coming down from the mountains and forests to stake their claim to
power.
</P>
<P>
   In Prizren, armed KLA soldiers manned checkpoints around the
city on Monday, tolerated, at least for the moment, by NATO
peacekeepers. The rebels have set up a headquarters in Pristina,
Kosovo's capital. KLA checkpoints have sprung up in other Kosovo
towns, including Suva Reka and Kacanic.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, the rebels seized one of Serbia's largest coal
mines and took control of a Serbian customs office at the border
crossing with Albania, in Morini.
</P>
<P>
   The swift emergence of the KLA as a new power on the ground
poses a delicate problem for the NATO peacekeepers, particularly
because of the growing political support the relatively small and
fractious band of guerrillas commands from Albanians here.
</P>
<P>
   A major purpose of the NATO effort is to end the Serb atrocities
that drove more than one million Albanians from their homes, and
Albanians view NATO as allies of the KLA. But the peacekeepers have
been at pains to stress that they are a neutral force, trying to
protect Serbs as well as Albanians. Under the terms of the peace
accord, the NAT0 forces are charged with demilitarizing the KLA.
</P>
<P>
   While rebel commanders say they are eager to cooperate with NATO
and have promised not to carry out reprisals against Serbs, they
have not given up their weapons in Prizren.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few hours after the bulk of Yugoslav forces and tens of
thousand of Serb civilians packed in buses and private cars left
Prizren to the jeers of the city's Albanians, the KLA appeared on
the streets brandishing its weapons and new-found authority.
</P>
<P>
   `'We are controlling the main part of the city,'' a senior KLA
officer known as Commander Drini told foreign reporters late on
Monday afternoon. `'We contacted KFOR and we agreed we would not
make any incident.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked later about the KLA's claim to control most of the city, a
spokesman for the German NATO force here, Maj. Dietmar Jeserich,
said:
</P>
<P>
   `'If they did control Prizren that would worry us. But if it's
just talk about it, it doesn't worry us.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, at least, the KLA was savoring its new freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Sokol Haziri, a 46-year-old former French teacher, reached the
edge of the city in the darkness on Monday morning, marching in
with 800 other guerrillas from the Kosovo Liberation Army's 124th
Brigade.
</P>
<P>
   By early evening he was manning a half-roadblock, half-giddy
celebration in the city's Shkolla-e-Re district, a flower stuck in
his ammunition vest, a Serb incendiary grenade in his hand and his
red-and-black KLA patch with the double-headed eagle safety-pinned
to the sleeve of his camouflage shirt.
</P>
<P>
   A radio was blasting `'The March of the KLA'' and the crowd was
singing along, hugging the soldiers. All over this graceful old
city, ethnic Albanians were streaming into the streets, celebrating
the departure of the Yugoslav forces _ and most of the serb
civilians _ cheering, waving Albanian flags and blaring car horns.
</P>
<P>
   KLA soldiers streamed into the southeastern town of Kacanic on
Monday, embracing and slapping each other on the back on streets
lined with looted homes and shops. Taking control of the local
police station, they hung an Albanian flag where the Yugoslav flag
flew only days ago.
</P>
<P>
   American soldiers reported little tension with the KLA in
Kacaninc. In contrast to Prizen, none of the KLA soldiers in
Kacanic were armed. Hajrush Luma, the 28-year-old deputy commander
of KLA soldiers in the town, said he had received orders to abide
by NATO's request that KLA soldiers not carry weapons. Individual
KLA soldiers said they supported demilitarization, whatever the
reason.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't need guns anymore,'' said Avni Lika, a 28-year-old
soldier. ``This is an ethnically clean town.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff Sgt. George Person, a U.S. paratrooper patrolling the town
on foot Sunday night, praised the KLA. ``They've been no trouble at
all,'' he said. ``They seem very supportive.''
</P>
<P>
   The KLA moved swiftly this weekend to seize control of some
strategic points. On Saturday morning, when NATO forces first
crossed the border from Macedonia, the KLA took over a mine at
Dobre Selo. The mine is a critical link in Kosovo's electrical grid
and was briefly held by the rebels last year.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the KLA took over what had been the Serbian customs
post at the Morini border crossing to Albania, through which the
bulk of the bedraggled refugees had poured at the end of March and
early April. About 10 to 15 KLA guerrillas were guarding the Morini
station late Sunday, according to Andrea Angeli, spokesman of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In the wrecked city of Suva Reka, the KLA had set up its own
checkpoints on Monday, manned by bearded guerrillas in black
berets, although there were no people in evidence and little
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Prizren on Monday echoed with chants of the rebels' initials,
UCK in Albanian, pronounced `'Oo-Che-Kah.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Shkolla-e-Re district the guerrillas strutted about in
uniforms and pieces of uniforms, some in camouflage, many in
varying shades of black. One had a lilac in the muzzle of his AK-47
rifle and an unlit cigarette tucked behind his ear under a baseball
cap. People came out to take pictures and videotapes of themselves
with the guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   `'I am feeling great as an Albanian'' said Hysen Huseni, who
said he had been fighting for a year and a half in the Drenica
region. `'This is the most happiest day of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting under a leafy tree in a walled garden, plates of
strawberries and cherries on a table in front of him and flanked by
an aid in a sleeveless Lakers basketball shirt, Commander Drini
said his men controlled `'the whole part'' of the city except for
the three main roads out, which he said they would leave clear for
the Serbs to depart.
</P>
<P>
   He said his troops would act as a kind of police force in the
initial unsettled period until NATO forces took full control.
</P>
<P>
   `'It's enough in this moment before the full deployment of the
international peacekeepers,'' he said. `'For the present situation,
it is very important to protect against criminals, people who want
to make profit from the situation. As for Serb civilians, the KLA
will not touch them.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Commander Drini, who speaks seven languages and wore purple
socks and Adidas mountain running shoes with his camouflage
uniform, readily acknowledged that there had been bursts of gunfire
in the air from his men as the tail of a Serb convoy passed.
</P>
<P>
   `'Yes, there was shooting, it was about 100 people right in
front of me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   `'I said `OK guys, you have used up half the ammunition,''' he
went on. `'But to see the Albanian flag in the streets of Prizren
after ten years (of Serb rule), it's an emotional experience. What
can I say?''
</P>
<P>
   The commander, whose nom de guerre means `'river'' in tribute to
his love of fishing, said the KLA would disarm if its political
leadership told it to, but implied this might have little real
meaning.
</P>
<P>
   `'What does it mean? We all live here. Sure, I have taken my
fishing stick and gone fishing. But what does it mean to disarm. It
is an Albanian tradition to have one arm with you,'' he said,
slapping his hip like a holster.
</P>
<P>
   `'We couldn't have a worse situation than 1998 to `99,'' he
said. `'Anyway the domination of the Serb forces is over.''
</P>
<P>
   That is what mattered to Haziri, the triumphant rebel.
</P>
<P>
   `'We are very happy,'' he said. `'When we came here the people
were very happy. They think they are safe now from the Serbs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
