<HEADER>
A5183 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-NH-COX     06-14 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-NH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush promises no litmus test for judges on abortion issueBy
Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW CASTLE, N.H. _ On the third day of his newly-minted
presidential campaign, Gov. George W. Bush said Monday he would not
use abortion as a ``litmus test'' for appointing federal judges.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no litmus test, except for whether a judge will
strictly interpret the Constitution,'' said Bush, who believes
abortion should be banned except in cases of rape, incest or
pregnancies that threaten the woman's life.
</P>
<P>
   At the first news conference since he announced his candidacy
Saturday, Bush said he would appoint judges who share his overall
philosophy and would not use the bench to make law.
</P>
<P>
   The comments put Bush in line for further heat from GOP
presidential contenders who targeted him several months ago when he
said he favors a constitutional amendment banning abortion but does
not think it's worth pursuing because it could not win voter
approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``If compassionate conservative means anything, it has to mean
do anything we can to stop the loss of 1.5 million unborn children
every year,'' said GOP hopeful Gary Bauer, a former Reagan
administration education official who is striving to make himself
the most strident anti-abortion candidate in the GOP race.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, as Bush was announcing his candidacy in Iowa,
Bauer, also in Iowa, challenged Bush to join him in vowing to
appoint only judges who oppose abortion rights. Bauer said the
country's next president could have two or three appointments to
the Supreme Court that could ``shift the balance of power toward
the pro-life side.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, never the darling of social conservatives though he aligns
with them on most issues, addressed the challenge during a foggy
oceanside news conference, attended by about 200 reporters, during
his first swing through the state with the first primary.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he would nominate Supreme Court judges based on three
criteria: Judicial temperament and ``do the judges share my overall
philosophy and will the judges strictly interpret the Constitution
as opposed to using the bench to legislate?''
</P>
<P>
   Other GOP presidential contenders pronounced Bush's position not
good enough.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan is ``a yes on an anti-abortion litmus test,''
according to spokesman Bob Adams. New Hampshire Sen. Bob Smith has
pledged ``only to nominate pro-life justices for the Supreme
Court,'' spokeswoman Karen Hickey said.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes said, ``I believe you should appoint justices on
matter of principle. One of those principles is belief in the
sanctity of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle said that because his
anti-abortion position was ``rooted in conscience rather than
politics, those I select for the most critical positions in
government, including my running mate or nominees to the Supreme
Court, will share it.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Elizabeth Dole, who shares Bush's opposition to
abortion but believes that the nation is not ready for a
constitutional amendment banning it, declined to clearly state
whether she would make abortion a litmus test for judicial
appointments.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will be one of the many issues she considers when she
appoints the most qualified judges,'' said Ari Fleischer, adding
that Bush's comments will cost him support among ``the
right-to-life vote.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the beginning of the challenges (Bush) is going
to face as he defines himself,'' Fleischer said. ``Nobody knows
what he stands for right now. He is very popular, and his
popularity is thin.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush appeared relaxed and confident as he answered questions on
a variety of topics for about 20 minutes. He said he'd boost
defense spending and build an anti-ballistic missile defense
system, and he promised to oppose increases in personal or
corporate income taxes. He said a detailed plan for simplifying the
tax code and lowering marginal tax rates is forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   The tax issue caused him some trouble last week in anti-tax New
Hampshire, when he appeared to waffle on a pledge not raise taxes.
After a Bush spokeswoman said he wouldn't sign an anti-tax pledge
signed by his GOP rivals, he reversed course and sent a letter to
the head of Americans for Tax Reform that was identical to the
formal pledge. He said Monday that the letter was, ``in essence,
taking the famous New Hampshire pledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also discussed racial preferences, reiterating his
opposition to racial quotas and his support for what he calls
``affirmative access.'' As an example, he cited the Texas law that
guarantees state university admission to the top 10 percent of
students in every Texas high school. The law was adopted in the
wake of the Hopwood decision banning consideration of race in
university admissions.
</P>
<P>
   Bush dodged a question on whether he believes President Clinton
epitomizes the ``if it feels good, do it'' philosophy he often
criticizes, saying only that ``when I put my hand on the Bible, I
will swear to uphold the dignity of the office.'' As he has in the
past, Bush declined to be specific about what he has described as
an ``irresponsible'' youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a game in Washington called 'gotcha.' You float a
rumor and make candidates prove a negative. I will not play that
game,'' Bush said. ``I made mistakes 20, 30 years ago, but I
learned from my mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said the governor will be offering
up his life story in an autobiography written by Houston Chronicle
sports columnist Mickey Herskowitz, who has chronicled the lives
late baseball great Mickey Mantle, University of Alabama football
coach Bear Bryant and former Texas Gov. John Connally.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor knew that other writers had decided to do
biographies even though he discouraged it,'' Tucker said. ``He
wanted to make sure there was one that was done right, so he
decided to cooperate with one person for one biography.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott S. Greenberger writes for The Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
