<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALMART-ASDA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAL-MART ENTERS BRITISH MARKET WITH $10.8 BILLION PURCHASE OF ASDA
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In its first foray into Britain, Wal-Mart Stores Inc.
agreed Monday to pay $10.8 billion in cash for Asda Group PLC,
Britain's third-largest supermarket chain, thwarting a rival suitor
at the last moment and threatening other British retailers with a
potentially devastating price war.
</P>
<P>
   The takeover agreement, equivalent to 220 pence, or about $1.36,
a share, is part of Wal-Mart's aggressive buying spree in Europe,
where tight zoning regulations make it almost impossible to build
big, new stores, leaving entrants into the businesses of
supermarkets and large mass convenience stores known as
hypermarkets no option but to acquire existing chains.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart's move came days before Asda, the dominant low-cost
discount market in Britain, had been set to conclude a $9.6 billion
all-stock deal announced April 16 with Kingfisher PLC, Britain's
sixth-largest retailer, which valued the company at 198 pence a
share. Kingfisher said Monday that it would not sweeten its offer,
but left it formally on the table.
</P>
<P>
   The bid by Wal-Mart, the world's largest retailer, follows its
acquisitions in Germany, where it bought the Wertkauf chain in 1997
and the Spar Handels hypermarket chain last year, seeking to unlock
new growth in Europe as the United States market becomes saturated.
</P>
<P>
   Of all Britain's supermarket chains, Asda offers the most
obvious fit to Wal-Mart. Its 229 British stores are generally 50
percent bigger than those of its competitors, it works on low
margins and sells a wide range of discounted, general goods. Last
year, Asda earned 317 million pounds, or about $512 million, on
sales of 9.8 billion pounds. ``We are dealing with Asda as a
company that is very similar to ours in culture,'' said Donald
Soderquist, senior vice chairman of Wal-Mart, which is based in
Bentonville, Ark. He acknowledged that the Kingfisher-Asda deal had
spurred Wal-Mart's bid: ``From time to time in the past, we've held
talks, but not about an offer. The Kingfisher merger created the
opportunity to look at it and become serious about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Allan Leighton, Asda's chief executive, said: ``The way we
operate is based mainly on ideas we pinched from Wal-Mart. So from
a colleague point of view, this is pretty much the perfect deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The bid sent Asda stock up 19 percent to match and even exceed
the bid price, reaching as high as 222.5 pence before falling back
to 218 pence. Wal-Mart shares rose 18.75 cents, to $42.875, in the
United States. But Kingfisher shares slumped 45 pence, to 791
pence. And other British retail stocks fell back sharply amid
worries that in Britain's already troubled supermarket business
Wal-Mart would cut prices at Asda to strengthen the chain's share
of the market. That would threaten other household-name stores like
Tesco, Sainsbury and Safeway, which would have to cut their prices
to stay competitive. ``They'll be nervous and wait to see what
happens,'' said Richard Perks, a retail analyst with Corporate
Intelligence, a consulting firm. ``The one thing they can't do is
try to knock Wal-Mart out.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares in J. Sainsbury PLC fell 18.5 pence, to 372 pence, and
Tesco PLC stock dropped 12.75 pence, to 178 pence. But Safeway PLC
stock rose 7.5 pence, to 252.25 pence, after a newspaper report
that it was being courted by the Kroger Co., the United States
supermarket chain, and the investment bank Blackstone Group.
</P>
<P>
   The Wal-Mart acquisition did not come as a total surprise. Even
at the time of the Kingfisher-Asda deal, analysts depicted the
proposed merger as a defensive ploy to thwart Wal-Mart's European
ambitions. A combination of the two British entities would create
the country's biggest retailer and a platform for expansion into
Continental Europe.
</P>
<P>
   That deal, though, has unraveled with remarkable speed. Asda
executives said Wal-Mart approached Asda just two weeks ago and the
agreement announced today came only days before the Asda-Kingfisher
deal was due for completion.
</P>
<P>
   The British acquisition, however, would still leave Wal-Mart
considerably short of a commanding position in the European market
that would enable it to squeeze concessions out of suppliers.
``They have a huge way to go,'' said Perks at Corporate
Intelligence, echoing the views of other analysts. ``In the U.K.
they bought a business. In Germany we are going to see them create
a business.'' And, because of strict European zoning laws, he said,
``if Wal-Mart wants to expand elsewhere in Europe, it's going to
have to do so through acquisitions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
