<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-USOPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURNS FROM TEAPOT HANDLE MIGHT HAMPER DUVAL IN OPEN
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ David Duval confirmed Monday that he would
play in the U.S. Open despite burning his hand on a pot handle last
Friday. But Duval said he might be hampered by lingering blisters
on his right thumb and forefinger.
</P>
<P>
   Duval worked on his putting Monday on the practice green at
Pinehurst Resort and Country Club's No. 2 course, but he will not
play a practice round until Tuesday. He wants to give his injury
more time to heal, but as world's No. 1-ranked player, he is also
running out of days left before Thursday's opening round. He still
has a nasty-looking blister about the size of a dime on his right
thumb and a smaller blister near the top of his right forefinger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it has been disruptive,'' Duval said of his
freakish accident in picking up a teapot at his home in Ponte Vedra
Beach, Fla. ``I was supposed to be here three days ago, and I
haven't even had a chance to hit balls. There's no pain now, but
there probably will be tomorrow when the blisters break and it gets
down to raw skin. But even that's speculation. I don't know what's
going to happen. I'm just trying to let them be as good as they can
for as long as they can, let it heal, then go from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, almost everyone who approached Duval Monday inquired
about his injury. After shaking hands with Duval, Jim Furyk looked
at Duval's hand and made a face. ``Yikes,'' said Furyk, shaking his
head when he looked at the swollen blisters.
</P>
<P>
   Before his injury, Duval was on almost everyone's list of
favorites for the year's second major, along with Tiger Woods, who
has won his last two tournaments. Now, Duval is unsure if he will
be 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Duval is considering wearing a glove on his right hand to
protect his fingers, but he is worried that it may feel too
uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that would make an awfully big change in feel,'' Duval
said. ``A lot depends on how it feels when the blisters pop. That's
when I'm really going to have to pay attention to making sure
they're clean, putting antibiotics on them and stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he felt cheated after sustaining an injury at such an
inopportune time, Duval said: ``I'm just generally not happy about
it. But I don't think, `Why now?' It's just one more thing I've got
to overcome. Sort of like a double bogey.''
</P>
<P>
   And Duval guaranteed that he would make his 7:30 a.m. tee time
Thursday, regardless of the pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might shoot 90,'' he said, ``but I'll be playing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
