<SLUG> BC-CLEAN-AIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EPA UNVEILS SMALLER PLAN TO CUT SMOG IN NORTHEAST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Mass., Pa., N.J., Del., Ind., Ky., Md., Mich., N.C.,
Ohio, W.Va., Va.) (nk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Stymied by two court rulings setting aside clean
air standards, the Environmental Protection Agency said Monday that
it had a new way to force power plants in 12 states to cut
pollutants that contribute to smog in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   The approach relies on petitions by four states _ New York,
Pennsylvania, Massachusetts and Connecticut _ saying that no matter
what they did within their borders they could not meet older smog
standards, because too much pollution blew in from other states.
</P>
<P>
   Using that argument, the agency said it could force plants in 12
states to reduce their output of nitrogen oxides by about 60
percent of what the agency had sought. Ten other states targeted by
the standards that are now in limbo would not be affected by the
petitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Northeast has been waiting a long time for these pollution
reductions,'' EPA Administrator Carol Browner said Monday in a
meeting with reporters. ``We had a path to get us there, a sensible
path. The courts robbed us of that opportunity, but we're not
giving up.''
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for utility and coal industries, which won the last
round in court, said they would also file legal challenges to the
new approach.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District
of Columbia ordered the agency to reconsider its new clean air
standards, which set potentially stricter ozone limits. The agency
had planned to use those standards to control pollution that is
blown into the Northeast where it contributes to smog, but in a
second ruling the court said it could not do so.
</P>
<P>
   The petitions that the agency said Monday it would use to do
that job were filed under an older standard that is still intact.
It sets a one-hour peak limit for smog, while the rejected standard
would have set limits over eight-hour periods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a procedural chess move,'' said Frank O'Donnell,
executive director of the Clean Air Trust, a nonprofit lobbying
group that supports the stricter standards that the court blocked.
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania and Massachusetts also brought petitions that the
agency will use. The petitions were filed in 1997 but the agency
set them aside, preferring to use a 22-state plan that said that
reductions were required under its new eight-hour rule. Using that
tool, the EPA had asked the states to specify how they would reduce
nitrogen oxides, giving them a choice of targets, including cement
kilns, large internal combustion engines in stationary
applications, large industrial boilers and large utility boilers.
Enforcing petitions instead will give the states less flexibility,
Browner said, because New York's petition, for example, identifies
individual power plants by name.
</P>
<P>
   Cars and trucks are another major source of nitrogen oxides but
the strategy to control cars is now set uniformly for most of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The petitions target 717,000 tons of nitrogen oxides a year in
the 12 states; the EPA had originally sought to get 1.1 million
tons from 22 states. The 717,000 tons comes to about 5 percent of
all nitrogen oxide emissions from the states, according to the
agency.
</P>
<P>
   New York and Pennsylvania portray themselves as victims in their
petitions, but they are among the states that other petitioners
list as being part of the problem. The other states where the EPA
will demand reductions are are New Jersey, Delaware, Indiana,
Kentucky, Maryland, Michigan, North Carolina, Ohio, West Virginia
and Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Several other states also filed petitions, but those were based
on the eight-hour standard, which is now in limbo. Other states
could also file under the one-hour standard, Browner said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Browner said that although she expected the court decisions to
be overturned in a year or two, that would still delay compliance
by that amount of time. She said the new strategy will keep some
reductions within the previous schedule seeking compliance by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court raised several objections to the EPA's
standard, including that Congress had given the agency too much
leeway in setting standards and that the agency had failed to
justify its decisions. The court also blocked a new standard on
fine soot, but soot was not part of Monday's action by the agency.
</P>
<P>
   At the National Mining Association, Quinlan Shea, a lawyer, said
that his group had already challenged whether the petition process
was legal under the Clean Air Act, but that the question had been
set aside when it looked like the EPA would issue an order to 22
states on its own. Now the challenge will be revived, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Industry will perceive this as an effort by EPA to continue to
game the process,'' Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   Browner, asked if she expected a court challenge, said: ``This
is the EPA. We will definitely be sued.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
