A5193 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUN-LEGISLATION-COX     06-14 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-LEGISLATION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No cover on gun control votes
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House will vote separately on a series of gun
control proposals, scuttling an earlier plan to vote on the
measures as part of a juvenile crime bill, Republican leaders said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The latest procedural move reflects the continued uncertainty
and confusion within Republican ranks over how they should handle
the most controversial elements of proposed gun restrictions, the
first the House has considered since banning assault weapons in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   GOP leaders claimed that separating out the gun control
provisions would provide a more honest and straightforward debate
when the House takes up the juvenile crime measure either Wednesday
or Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats immediately denounced the move as a ploy to make
it more difficult for some members to vote for gun control. Rep.
Richard Gephardt (D-Mo.), the House minority leader, said it was
easier for some members to vote for the 1994 assault weapons ban
because it was included in a larger crime bill.
</P>
<P>
   Requiring members to vote exclusively on gun control this time
around will make those votes politically more difficult, Gephardt
said. ``They don't want anybody to have any excuse to vote for this
bill,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.), a board member of the National Rifle
Association and a fierce opponent of any gun control, said he was
pleased with the move. He said he hoped it would make it easier to
defeat the measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a more intellectually honest and appropriate thing to
do,'' Barr said. On Monday, Barr sought permission from the House
Rules Committee to offer amendments deleting any gun control
language from the juvenile crime bill sent to the House floor for a
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Under the framework outlined by GOP leaders, the House will
consider dozens of amendments relating to gun control, both for and
against, as part of the debate on a proposal to require criminal
background checks for guns bought at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the more popular gun provisions, such as preventing
violent juveniles from ever owning a gun and requiring trigger
locks to be sold with guns, were deleted from the original juvenile
crime bill and given to politically vulnerable GOP members to offer
as amendments.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James Rogan (R-Calif.), for example, considered by many
analysts to be among the most vulnerable GOP incumbents, will offer
the amendment to prohibit violent juveniles from owning guns.
</P>
<P>
   The gun show language in the latest GOP bill would require
anyone purchasing a gun at a gun show to submit to a criminal
background check. Currently 20 percent to 40 percent of such sales
are exempted because there is no requirement that unlicensed
dealers at gun shows conduct the checks.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats charge that the House version would be much weaker
than a similar bill passed by the Senate, and they plan to offer a
substitute that mirrors the Senate language.
</P>
<P>
   But a group of six Democrats, four of whom represent rural
Southern districts, also will offer an amendment to weaken the
House gun show language even further. The amendment, drafted by
Rep. John Dingell (D-Mich.), would require the background checks to
be completed in 24 hours instead of 72, and it would allow
out-of-state gun dealers to transfer guns to in-state dealers.
</P>
<P>
   The House also will consider a second bill that deals
exclusively with developing new punishments and incarceration
guidelines for juveniles. Rep. Henry Hyde (R-Ill.), chairman of the
Judiciary Committee, plans to offer an amendment to this bill that
would prohibit the distribution of violent and obscene material to
juveniles. Hyde's bill also would require music CD and video
sellers to make copies of song lyrics available. Separately, Rep.
Bill McCollum (R-Fla.) will offer a sweeping amendment to establish
mandatory minimum sentences for juveniles and make it easier for
prosecutors to try juveniles as adults.
</P>
<P>
   As of Friday, Republicans leaders were moving on a track to
consider one massive bill. House Speaker Dennis Hastert (R-Ill.)
and Rules Committee Chairman David Dreier (R-Calif.) informed
Democrats of the change in tactics from on mid-day Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
