<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-G8-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S ROLE IN KOSOVO MAY OVERSHADOW CLINTON'S SUCCESS AS SUMMIT
CONVENES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As President Clinton heads to Europe Tuesday to
celebrate NATO's success with international leaders, his trip may
be overshadowed by Russia's unexpected role as a difficult partner
in Kosovo peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The primary purpose of Clinton's visit is the meeting of the
seven western industrialized nations and Russia in Cologne,
Germany, a summit that usually focuses on economic concerns but
this year will likely be dominated by the Kosovo situation and
rebuilding the region.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians, seeking a role in the peacekeeping, have refused
to cede control of the airport in Kosovo's capital city, Pristina,
after sending in several hundred troops in advance of NATO
peacekeeping forces. The move infuriated NATO commanders, who
continued to pour troops into the region Monday, and sparked
serious talks between Washington and Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, President Clinton telephoned Russian President Boris
Yeltsin while vice president Al Gore spoke with Russian prime
minister Sergei Stepashin to resolve the Kosovo situation.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the talks, Defense Secretary William Cohen will
meet later this week with Russian Defense officials in Helsinki,
Finland, to hash out what the Russian role should be in policing
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials tried to play down the latest impasse
with Russia, arguing that it had not interfered with NATO's plans
to send 50,000 troops to keep the peace in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we need to exaggerate this problem. This is
something that can be worked out,'' said Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright. ``We have said we want the Russians to be part
of it, they want to be part of it. I think it does not defy the
imagination here to figure out a way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, negotiations with the Russians have not been easy.
It has been less than clear who is in charge in Moscow these days,
with conflicting reports as to who authorized sending the troops
into Kosovo. The ailing Yeltsin is viewed with suspicion by many in
his military who believe he capitulated to the United States and
NATO by agreeing to the accord that forced Serb troops to retreat
from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Russia wants to control a sector in Kosovo but does not want its
troops under NATO command. NATO officials believe a sector
controlled by Russia, a longtime Serb ally, would divide Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The opportunity for NATO officials and Clinton to meet
face-to-face with Yeltsin may be limited. Yeltsin is not expected
to show up at the economic summit until Sunday, the third day of
the meeting, according to administration officials. Until then,
Russia will be represented by Stepashin.
</P>
<P>
   Before he arrives in Germany for the summit at the end of the
week, Clinton will speak to the International Labor Organization
Conference in Geneva and then fly to Paris to meet with French
President Jacques Chirac and Prime Minister Lionel Jospin.
</P>
<P>
   After Germany, the president flies to Slovenia, where he will
meet with its top leaders and address the citizens of that former
part of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The world leaders will have several matters to hash out when
they convene in Cologne, including how to coordinate the
reconstruction efforts in Kosovo. European countries have pledged
to pay the lion's share of the peacekeeping force and the
reconstruction effort.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders also will discuss their standard fare of economics,
including improving financial safeguards in developing nations. The
industrialized nations will consider a U.S. proposal to help reduce
the debt of poorer countries, a burden that administration
officials say has hampered their economic development.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also will address another problem in developing nations,
the use of child labor.
</P>
<P>
   At the International Labor Organization conference in Geneva,
Clinton will emphasize the need for many of the poor countries to
stop exploiting children.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Sperling, the head of Clinton's National Economic Council,
said Clinton will tell members of the United Nations agency that
these countries need to be helped into steering young people into
education or other opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Child labor is not an issue in which you can simply shut down
the factories or go for an easy solution,'' Sperling said. ``The
chances are too great that you will drive a 10-year-old boy from
the factories to running drugs, or an 11-year-old girl from the
factories to prostitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Following the Cologne summit, the president will go to Bonn,
Germany, to participate in the U.S. European Union meeting, a
summit that will focus on trade issues.
</P>
<P>
   After Bonn, Clinton will fly to Ljubljana, Slovenia, where he
will meet with President Milan Kucan.
</P>
<P>
   Slovenia was the first region to break from Yugoslavia after the
fall of communism and has been lobbying to become a member of NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The trip is a way of encouraging positive developments in a
small nation that sits in an unstable region of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slovenia is one of the countries that really has made
considerable progress, both economically and politically, in terms
of democracy and openness,'' said Sandy Berger, Clinton's national
security adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the other items on his agenda during the seven-day trip,
the president is sure to make time to emphasize the success of the
NATO bombing campaign in Kosovo. Some observers say that such
bragging might be appropriate, considering the considerable
skepticism voiced by many during the airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he deserves a victory lap,'' said Ivo Daalder, a
foreign-policy expert at the Brookings Institution who had been
critical of the bombing. ``He has pulled the rabbit out of the hat,
again.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
