<HEADLINE>
STOCKS MIXED AS INVESTORS WAIT FOR KEY REPORT WEDNESDAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices were mixed and activity remained subdued
Monday as traders and investors delayed putting money to work
before an important inflation report that is scheduled for release
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Long-term interest rates, which have risen sharply in recent
weeks and put pressure on stocks, eased a bit Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the drop in rates did little to alter the consensus that
the Federal Reserve will raise short-term interest rates to dampen
growth when its policy makers meet later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks that are sensitive to the business cycle, which do well
in an expanding economy, helped to push the Dow Jones industrial
average higher. But Internet stocks were crushed, pushed lower by
negative developments affecting three of the group's most important
companies _ America Online, Charles Schwab and Ebay _ as well as
concerns about higher interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big, high-cap stocks are the allure, and money is coming
out of technology and Internet stocks and even some small stocks''
to move into those companies, said Bill Allyn, head of listed
trading at Jefferies &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, however, money was not going anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   For the sixth time in the last eight sessions, fewer than 700
million shares changed hands on the New York Stock Exchange. At
832.2 million shares, volume on the Nasdaq market was a bit better
but still well short of the 1-billion-share trading sessions seen
recently.
</P>
<P>
   Led by DuPont, General Electric and Minnesota Mining and
Manufacturing, the Dow rose 72.82 points, or seven-tenths of a
percent, to 10,563.33. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index was
flat, rising 0.36 point, to 1,294.00.
</P>
<P>
   But the Nasdaq composite index, dragged down by the Internet
sector, fell sharply. At the close, the Nasdaq was off 49.57
points, or 2.03 percent, to 2,398.31.
</P>
<P>
   Some traders and analysts said the market's tone might change
after Wednesday's release of May consumer price data.
</P>
<P>
   The April numbers showed the biggest monthly increase in more
than nine years. That report rattled financial markets and led to
an ever-rising chorus that the Fed would move soon to raise
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   A report showing the April figures to be an aberration would be
helpful but hardly conclusive, said Jeffrey Applegate, chief
investment strategist at Lehman Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock market has priced itself for at least one Fed
tightening, and if the Fed does go, it will have to position itself
for another,'' Applegate said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the consumer price numbers look pretty benign, then the
market might take comfort from that,'' he added. ``But I suspect
this is not something that will be sorted out with the next one or
two data points. I don't think we are out of the woods yet. There
are just too many crosscurrents.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts who follow Internet stocks have been saying for some
time that the sector was particularly vulnerable. Still, Monday's
downdraft was particularly drastic.
</P>
<P>
   Concern about slowing subscription rates led to big declines in
America Online. At the close, the stock was down 9, to 90{. Ebay
continued to suffer from a computer system failure last week,
falling 29~, or 18 percent, to 136. And Schwab was punished after
it reported that its daily online trading volume fell 28 percent in
May, compared with April activity. The stock closed at 83 15/16 a
share, down 10 5/16.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the price-earnings ratios for companies like America
Online and Schwab, there is not much room for error,'' said Michael
Molnar, a managing director in retail sales and trading at Salomon
Smith Barney. ``These were material, fundamental events.''
</P>
<P>
   Weakness in these issues also helped to drag down other Internet
shares. Cisco Systems, a component of the S&AMP;P 500, fell 2~ a share,
to 107 13/16. Amazon.com shed 13 13/16, to 92. And Yahoo lost 16,
to 119\.
</P>
<P>
   For the Dow, DuPont gained 2~, to 70 3/16. General Electric
closed at 103}, up 2 13/32. And Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing
gained 3 5/16, to 89\.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, drug and medical service company shares slumped.
</P>
<P>
   Becton Dickinson, the nation's largest manufacturer of medical
syringes, declined 8}, to 30 5/16, after notifying Wall Street that
earnings for the third quarter and the full year would fall short
of expectations because of slower sales in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer continued to drop, falling 2], to 95[. And Warner-Lambert
slipped {, to 62\.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
