<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A BIZARRE SPRINGTIME KEEPS GOING
</HEADLINE>
  (First names are deliberately omitted in third graf.) 
(ms) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After staring at my screen saver for the past hour, I still
cannot come up with an argument why the Knicks absolutely cannot
beat the San Antonio Spurs in the finals.
</P>
<P>
   I want to clear my throat authoritatively and pretend I'm a hoop
maven and declare that the Knicks cannot possibly match the Twin
Towers.
</P>
<P>
   But all I know is what I have seen for the last month: Sprewell
and Houston bonding on the court, Camby coming on in the stretch as
Lemon Drop Kid did in the Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, this is hardly a triumphal bleat from some giddy
Knicks fan. I have no emotional attachment to them or their
organization, plus they are bad for my health _ late hours, indoor
games, stale air at their dismal practice gym.
</P>
<P>
   But they made the Garden rock last Friday, and I am not so sure
they cannot do it again when they come home next Monday.
</P>
<P>
   This team is a work in progress. The sum is greater than the
parts. This is not a normal season. An eighth-seeded team is in the
finals. Ignore their chaos at your own peril.
</P>
<P>
   In the late afternoon, I've had two cups of black coffee, a
snack of sushi and one hard candy. The basic food groups: caffeine
and soy and sugar.
</P>
<P>
   I have gazed at my screen saver some more. (It scrolls the teams
in Italy's national soccer league, Serie A; I programmed it myself
one slow afternoon.) Still, prudence does not raise her wise old
head.
</P>
<P>
   As I sit here, I put nothing past this bunch of lugs, whoever is
left of them. The Knicks say they'll make the decision about Larry
Johnson at game time Wednesday, which sounds like making busy work
for the San Antonio coaches. I saw the rolling block on Johnson on
Friday night, and I say he is out until the third game. I still
think the Knicks could catch the Spurs rusty Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about going after the proverbial split,'' Jeff Van
Gundy Monday, but you bet the coach would like to steal one and
hope L.J. is limber again next Monday.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, what do I know about San Antonio? I live in
the East. I have just spent this winter dealing with rampant
skulduggery in the Olympic movement, plus tracking down oddities
and calamities in my own time zone: John Calipari self-destructing
in New Jersey; Ernie Grunfeld getting whacked as an offering to the
new owners of the Garden. Who had time for Twin Towers out West?
</P>
<P>
   This is a big country. You can absorb just so much. It took
years for Easterners to appreciate Magic Johnson out in Los Angeles
the way we appreciated Larry Bird in Boston. Bird played at 7:30
p.m.; Johnson played at 10:30 p.m. That simple.
</P>
<P>
   In this weird little season following the owners' desperate
lockout, there were very few East-West games, which meant that Tim
Duncan and David Robinson were playing past my bedtime. I take
everybody's word for it that they are great, but I have seen
bizarre things from the Knicks lately, and I am loath to say they
cannot continue.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Houston is like some cold-blooded assassin out there.
(``The great scorers, if they can bury you, they bury you,'' Van
Gundy said Monday, regarding Houston's current binge.) A few weeks
ago I was scoffing at any comparison of Houston and Latrell
Sprewell's potential chemistry with the very real karma of Walt
Frazier and Earl Monroe back in 1973. I no longer scoff. Is it
possible the absent Grunfeld was on to something?
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks have the right attitude. Herb Williams _ probably
destined to be the star of one of these games _ seemed downright
insulted Monday when asked to give one reason the Knicks could win
the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really should be asking if there is any reason we can't
win,'' Williams said, almost huffily. ``Guys are going to go out
there and play their game. If they defense us, hats off to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston seemed totally unfazed by news that the Knicks were
9-point underdogs. ``It sounds a little low to me,'' he said.
``We're never going to say we're underdogs, but the way the media
and the experts talk, it sounds like it should be double digits.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks remember the lucky bounce against Miami, the lethargy
of Atlanta, the fortuitous 4-point call against Indiana. They are
on a roll. I say they win one in Texas, then they come home to the
Garden, where the Beast lives.
</P>
<P>
   This is, essentially, a team that did not exist two months ago.
After witnessing the Knicks' fast and furious evolution, I cannot
work up the conventional wisdom to pick against them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
