<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5215 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-1000&AMP;A     06-14 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-1000&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAV FORCES CONTINUE TO WITHDRAW AS NATO EXPANDS CONTROL OVER
KOSOVO
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ NATO slowly expanded its control over a
central swath of Kosovo on Monday, pouring thousands more soldiers
into major towns and villages but effectively ceding the airport
here in the capital to about 200 Russian soldiers who defiantly
occupied it three days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   By Monday evening, NATO officials reported no new clashes on
Monday like ones on Sunday. The force's commander, Lt. Gen. Michael
Jackson of Britain, said on Monday that German and British troops
who had opened fired in separate confrontations on Sunday in
Prizren and Pristina, killing two Serbs, had acted justifiably.
</P>
<P>
   Despite NATO's ever growing presence, parts of Kosovo remained
tense and, occasionally, chaotic. There were reports that a body
found near Suva Reka may have been that of a third German
journalist, a day after two others were shot to death. In Djakovica
and Pec, cities at the center of the civil war over the last year,
retreating Yugoslav forces set houses on fire.
</P>
<P>
   Long columns of Yugoslav army and police units continued to
withdraw on schedule, NATO commanders said, but as they went, they
intermingled on narrow roads with desperate convoys of Serbian
civilians and advancing NATO troops. ``We are in a difficult,
volatile and, at times, dangerous environment,'' Jackson said on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers from the Yugoslav army still controlled the roads into
Pristina's airport, southwest of here, where the Russian force has
settled in. The Yugoslav troops refused to let anyone pass, let
alone NATO troops. In a news conference in Pristina's main hotel,
the Grand, where Yugoslav soldiers are still quartered in the
basement, Jackson said Russia's role was a political issue, to be
decided at the political level.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Pristina, Jackson chided those who saw the impasse over
the airport as an embarrassment to NATO or a hitch in the
operation. He said he had not intended to establish NATO's
headquarters there, as NATO officials previously indicated, because
of the distance from the capital and the hazards of mines and
unexploded NATO bombs. ``I'm very happy to leave the airfield in
Russian hands,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the occupation's third day, more than 14,000
allied troops controlled an anchor-shaped area, stretching from Pec
in the west to Gnjilane in the east, with the capital, Pristina, at
the head.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's presence has begun to spread from the main corridors to
smaller roads and villages. Overhead, there is a constant thudding
of helicopters. The United Nations and relief organizations
delivered rations of food inside Kosovo on Monday for the first
time since NATO's bombing stopped. Aid workers handed out the food
to 18,000 refugees in Glogovac, many of whom had waited out the war
in the hills near some of the heaviest fighting between Serbian
forces and Kosovo Albanian separatists.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis McNamara, a special envoy from the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees, said NATO must move quickly to establish
control so that food, medicine and other supplies can reach as many
as 500,000 Albanian refugees believed to have fled their homes and
to have remained inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Although NATO said its deployments were on schedule, there have
been snags. After a half-start on Sunday blamed on congestion,
1,000 Marines from the 26th Marine Expeditionary Unit finally
crossed into Kosovo early on Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   With units from the 82d Airborne and 1st Armored Division having
arrived the day before, more than 2,000 Americans are now
patrolling their sector in the southeast.
</P>
<P>
   NATO will not control the entire province until the last
Yugoslav forces leave, which is required to happen by next Sunday.
The first phase of that withdrawal, from roughly a third of Kosovo,
must take place by Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said a quarter of the 40,000 Yugoslav soldiers
and police officers in Kosovo at the height of the conflict had
withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   As the soldiers left, so did Serbian civilians, many of them
from the southwest, around Prizren. Long, ragged convoys fled on
the road from Prizren to Gjnilane, toward an area with a larger
Serbian population.
</P>
<P>
   Sveta Jovicic, left with her three daughters and only two
blankets. She was sick, she said, in need of dialysis, but no
longer felt safe in Prizren. ``We have been living with terrorists
for two years,'' she said, her voice breaking. ``But where can go?
I don't know. I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Serbs were determined to stay. Blagoje Arsic said Serbs in
his village, Zitinje, voted on Monday and decided to stay in their
homes. ``I want to live in peace with my neighbors: no problems, no
hate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At Kosovo's border with Macedonia, deserted only days ago,
hundreds of Kosovar Albanian refugees began to flow back toward
their homes. In Albania, the tide of those wanting to return was so
great that German forces closed the border.
</P>
<P>
   Although hundreds of thousands remain in camps in Macedonia,
where aid workers are trying to convince them to stay until it is
safer to go home, the return of some on Monday showed a growing
faith in Kosovo's security in the wake of Serbian withdrawals.
Those better off went by car _ one so full that two men sat in the
trunk _ but a steady trickle of people walked north on the main
road into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Adila Zeneli, 40, returned with two sons and a daughter. Her
husband, a soldier in the Kosovo Liberation Army, called her in
Macedonia where she has stayed since the war began and told her it
was safe to return to their village, Kacanik. ``We are not
afraid,'' she said, ``because NATO is there.''
</P>
<P>
   So was the Kosovo Liberation Army. In town after town vacated by
retreating Yugoslav army and police units, the group's fighters
openly patrolled roads and fields, often only yards from NATO
troops.
</P>
<P>
   On a road north of Vitina now controlled by American troops,
Slavisha Maksimovic, a Serb, complained that he had to flee his
home in the village of Trpeza because armed members of the group
had appeared. He pleaded, unsuccessfully, with an American Marine,
Cpl. Derian F. Pritchett, who guarded a checkpoint outside of
Klokot. ``We can't do anything about that right now,'' Pritchett
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   NATO commanders fear that the rebels will not disband. At the
border crossing from Macedonia, American soldiers from the 82d
Airborne have begun searching every car for weapons they fear
refugees may try to bring in to the group's fighters.
</P>
<P>
   At an Army checkpoint south of Kacanik, Pvt. Wylie Shaffer,
armed with a grenade launcher, said he had stopped several Kosovo
Liberation Army soldiers and confiscated their weapons, mostly
AK-47s. ``We just ask them,'' he said, ``and they give them up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
