<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-GERMANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMAN PRESS ALARMED BY KILLINGS OF JOURNALISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ The killing of at least two German journalists in
Kosovo spread alarm at major German newspapers and magazines on
Monday, prompting editors to order correspondents to stick close to
NATO forces at all times and to avoid any risk.
</P>
<P>
   Volker Kraemer, a 56-year-old photographer with 30 years'
experience at the weekly news magazine Stern, and his colleague
Gabriel Gruener, 35, a reporter, were shot dead in uncertain
circumstances on Sunday as they drove through Dulje, a town about
midway between Prizren, in southern Kosovo, and Pristina, the
capital.
</P>
<P>
   Because the killings came against the backdrop of Serbia's
visceral hostility toward Germany, a sentiment rooted in savage
Nazi reprisals against Serbs during World War II and in the
repeated use of anti-German propaganda by the regime of the
Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic, they caused particular
concern.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Otto, a spokesman for Stern, said the two journalists and a
translator were killed by sniper fire. Kraemer died instantly, and
Gruener, whose companion is seven months pregnant, died after being
rushed to a hospital in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   But Mathiaas Doepfner, the editor of Die Welt, said he had heard
from his correspondent, Edith Kohn, who passed along the same road
five minutes before the journalists who were killed, that from
accounts of people who said they had been at the scene, the
journalists were executed.
</P>
<P>
   The journalists were lured out of their car with a promise that
they would be taken to the site of a mass grave and were then
executed by Serb gunmen, Doepfner said he had been told. He added
that he had ordered Ms. Kohn to stay in her hotel in Pristina for
the next two days and to avoid the volatile city of Prizren, the
base for about 8,000 German NATO troops.
</P>
<P>
   Another senior editor at a weekly publication also said he had
reports that the two journalists and the translator were executed
after being removed from their car. ``They were targeted as
Germans,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Uncertainty surrounded the possible death of a third German
journalist. The defense ministry retracted an earlier report that a
third journalist's body had been found, but Werner Adam, the
foreign editor of the Frankfurter Allgemeine, said he had heard
that a freelance journalist working for a South Tyrolian paper had
been killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are shocked and at a loss,'' said Michael Meier, the chief
editor of Stern. ``These colleagues were among our most experienced
and sensible reporters. The deaths are an unimaginable loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Gruener had served in Bosnia, Croatia and Slovenia in recent
years. Kraemer was a photographer well known for his work in
Eritrea, Sarajevo, South Africa and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have just spoken to our correspondent, Bernhard Kueppers,
and our instructions are, `Don't risk anything,' '' said Gernot
Sittner, one of two executive editors of the Sueddeutsche Zeitung.
``Absolutely no risk.'' But, like other editors, he said that
Kueppers, who is now in Prizren, would not be withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   The Sueddeutsche Zeitung lost its Balkan correspondent, Egon
Scotland, 43, when he came under Serb fire in Croatia on July 26,
1991. ``Obviously,'' said Sittner, ``we are particularly sensitive
because we have already lost one man in the Balkan wars.''
</P>
<P>
   Otto, the Stern spokesman, said the magazine still had
correspondents in the region and had decided not to order them out.
Rather, they have been asked to work full time on investigating
their colleagues' deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Klingst, the political editor of the weekly Die Zeit,
said the paper has two correspondents in Kosovo. ``They have been
told not to go off on their own, not to look for mass graves, and
to stick to the NATO soldiers _ Germans in Prizren and British in
Pristina. We are extremely shocked.''
</P>
<P>
   Serb resentment of Germany has scarcely eased in the 54 years
since the end of World War II. Bosnian Serb barracks during the
1992-95 war in Bosnia were regularly adorned with posters showing
the blue-and-gold European flag covered with swastikas. The slogan
read: ``Are you ready for Deutschmocracy?''
</P>
<P>
   Early German support for Croatian independence during the
Croatian war of 1991 cemented old Serb convictions that Germany has
had one consistent strategic aim in this century: penetration of
the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   As the Croats sang ``Danke Deutschland'' when the German move
helped them gain independence, the Serbs fumed at what they often
portrayed in Belgrade, their capital, as the policies of a Fourth
Reich.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, it is common sense that we are not cherished by the
Serbs,'' said Roman Leick, the foreign editor of the weekly
magazine Der Spiegel. ``But until these incidents, we had not
thought that Germans could be singled out and targeted. Indeed, we
are still not sure that was the case.''
</P>
</TEXT>
