A5219 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHURCH-VAN-COX     06-14 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCH-VAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Church van kills 3 in Georgia; seat belts likely not worn
 &HT;    By Joey Ledford and Bill Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAGRANGE, Ga. _ It's likely that none of the passengers in a
fatal church van crash on the interstate was wearing a seat belt,
Georgia State Patrol officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Troopers continue to investigate the Sunday afternoon accident
on southbound I-185 about 55 miles south of Atlanta, which took the
lives of three teenage members of St. James CME Church in Columbus,
Ga. Eight people were injured, some of them critically.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't finished looking at it, but they don't think
anybody had a seat belt on,'' said Gordy Wright, spokesman for the
Georgia State Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   Passenger vans that carry 15 or fewer passengers, like the
rented 1999 Dodge that carried the church group, are virtually
unregulated by the state.
</P>
<P>
   State law requires operators of vehicles carrying 16 or more
passengers to hold commercial driver's licenses, Wright said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 15-passenger van, rather than 16, means you can operate it
with a regular license,'' said Wright.
</P>
<P>
   The van is also exempt from Georgia's primary seat belt law,
which covers only vehicles designed to carry 10 or fewer
passengers, said Wright.
</P>
<P>
   All but the driver, Lula M. Pearson, 58, were ejected onto the
highway and the grassy shoulders around 3:52 p.m. just north of
exit 14, about 40 minutes north of Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   The van was carrying nine young members of the church youth
group, ages 13-16, who were returning from religious training at
Paine College in Augusta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   The driver was the only person aboard not thrown from the van,
``apparently because she was wedged in by the steering wheel and
console,'' said Georgia State Patrol Cpl. S.F. Hicks, assistant
commander of the LaGrange GSP post.
</P>
<P>
   The driver's husband, Ester Pearson, keeping vigil at West
Georgia Medical Center, said his wife was in ``sore, but good
spirits'' Monday following surgery for head injuries and severe
injuries to her hand. She was reported in fair condition Monday
evening.
</P>
<P>
   His wife does not yet know of the deaths, Pearson said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going that far yet,'' he said. ''She's been through
a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia State Patrol's Specialized Collision Reconstruction
Team is analyzing the accident, but Hicks said details concerning
speed and how the driver lost control are still under examination.
</P>
<P>
   Initial reports indicated that Lula Pearson fell asleep at the
wheel, Wright said. But investigators said passengers also told
them that she may have been looking in the rear-view mirror and
then returned her gaze to the road to discover the van had slipped
off the interstate's right-hand shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   The three victims were identified as Jonathan Lyle, 13, who was
flown to Atlanta Medical Center from the scene, where he died;
Cecil Jernigan,13, who died after transfer to Egleston Children's
Hospital in Atlanta; and Janice Jordan, l5, who died at the
LaGrange Hospital, said hospital spokeswoman Jan Nichols.
</P>
<P>
   The injured admitted to West Georgia Medical Center are Ebony
Brown, 13, listed in fair condition; and Maurice Kendrick, 15,
upgraded Monday afternoon from critical to guarded condition. His
brother William, 16, was treated for minor injuries and released.
</P>
<P>
   Tracie Fields, 13, and Natasha Kimbrough, 14, were transferred
to Columbus Regional Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Chester, 49, and Candice McKissie, 15, were admitted to a
hospital in Newnan, Ga., where they were listed in stable condition
Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
   William Kendrick Sr., 63, a retired Army sergeant major, said
his younger son Maurice underwent surgery for a ruptured spleen and
a collapsed lung Sunday night but ``he's doing fine today, though
he's sedated.'' Doctors had to removed the spleen, the elder
Kendrick said.
</P>
<P>
   Kendrick said he learned of the crash when the church pastor,
the Rev. James Hawkins Sr., called him around 4:30 p.m. Sunday, his
voice strained and nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, 'We got a problem, there's been an accident and
they're in the hospital.' I didn't question him,'' Kendrick said.
''I jumped in my shoes and drove here pretty fast. It sounded
serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Kendrick said he walked into the room and found Maurice strapped
to a stretcher, trying to get up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize he was hurt as bad as he was,'' he said. ''My
heart goes out to the children who were killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Joey Ledford and Bill Montgomery write for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
