<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5229 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GREAT-LAKES-WATER-ART     06-14 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREAT-LAKES-WATER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREAT LAKES REGION JEALOUSLY GUARDS ITS LIQUID ASSET
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARQUETTE, Mich. _ Stand on the southern shore of Lake Superior,
looking out at its gently tossing, deep blue immensity, and it is
hard to imagine anyone here ever feeling short of water.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the aftermath of a Canadian company's plan to send a
tanker full of lake water to Asia for bottling and sale as drinking
water, the very notion of shipping any of it abroad stirs anger
along both sides of the border in the Great Lakes region. Although
the company's plan was halted last year, a visitor need only walk
along the docks here to find universal hostility to water exports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't give one eye-dropperful away to anybody _ this is
our water,'' Ronald Pederson, a local boater, said as he sat
sipping coffee on a bench at a marina here Sunday morning, wearing
a white T-shirt that said, ``Michigan Lighthouses.''
</P>
<P>
   The water exports issue seems to be attracting more attention
these days because of a decline in Great Lakes water levels. The
problem is not water exports (there aren't any), but, with boaters
snagging propellers and running aground in unexpected places,
anything that has even the potential to affect the amount of water
in the lakes is suddenly of more than passing interest.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists attribute the drop in levels, which have always
varied somewhat, to unusually warm weather and below-average
precipitation. The level in Lake Superior, which has the cleanest
water in the Great Lakes and hence the most attractive for any
would-be water exporters, has dropped only three inches in the last
12 months, making it now seven inches below average for this time
of year. But levels in Lake Michigan and Lake Huron have plunged
two feet in the last year, one of the largest drops ever recorded.
Both lakes are now a foot below average.
</P>
<P>
   Some water from Lake Michigan is diverted each year to the
Mississippi River _ enough, in fact, to fill a tanker every two
hours. But this diversion, which was first undertaken in 1848 and
provides extra water to help river barges float over sandbanks, is
strictly limited by a Supreme Court decision. American and Canadian
officials say they are not aware of any additional proposals to
divert or export water from the Great Lakes, at least since the
death of the plan by the Canadian company, which would have filled
its tanker on the Canadian side of the border but, after
controversy, lost its permit from the Ontario government.
</P>
<P>
   Various exporting plans are being developed, however, to pump
water out of other lakes, in Canada and Alaska. The issue has
prompted so much concern that Canada barred water exports in
February and, with an eye on the possibility that further proposals
might involve the Great Lakes themselves, joined the United States
in asking for a study by the International Joint Commission, a
90-year-old bilateral agency that regulates water issues along the
border.
</P>
<P>
   Great Lakes water is seen as such a potentially exportable asset
to begin with because the lakes hold a fifth of all the world's
available fresh water, excluding the polar ice caps, at a time when
freshwater supplies in East Asia and the Middle East are becoming
polluted or depleted by rising populations.
</P>
<P>
   The water in Lake Superior accounts for more than half of all
Great Lakes water, and is also the cleanest. Superior has never had
many people or much heavy industry on its shores, and regulations
have so reduced the flow of sewage and other water pollution into
it that almost all the pollution still entering the lake is that
which simply drifts into it out of the air.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute here is such that even the North American Free Trade
Agreement has been dragged into it. Rep. Bart Stupak, a Democrat
whose district has 1,500 miles of shoreline on Lakes Superior,
Michigan and Huron, has been warning that if water exports begin,
lake water might become subject to the pact. In that case, future
efforts to restrict exports might be deemed an unfair trade
barrier, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Stupak first raised the issue during the debate that led to
congressional approval of Nafta in 1993, but it attracted little
attention from his constituents, who, he said, saw little harm then
in shipping lake water to nations abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``The water levels were high,'' he recalled, ``and people said,
`Why don't we give them a little?'''
</P>
<P>
   To allay any concerns, the Canadian, Mexican and United States
governments issued a joint statement on Dec. 2, 1993, the day
before the House of Representatives voted, that said none of the
three nations could be required by Nafta to export water. But the
statement also mentioned that water that had ``entered into
commerce'' was subject to Nafta. An American trade official who was
asked about the matter said that this mainly meant bottled water
and that even if some water from a lake was sold, the lake would
not be considered commercial. The International Joint Commission
nonetheless retained trade lawyers recently to study the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, even as falling lake levels displease many in the
region, there are some exceptions. David L. Lange, the owner of a
propeller repair business on the northern outskirts of Green Bay,
Wis., said he had fixed 600 propellers so far this year, compared
with 350 by this time in a typical year, as a result of boaters'
hitting rocks and sandbars.
</P>
<P>
   Lange said he would be delighted if someone drained a little
additional water out of the Great Lakes for export and water levels
dropped further. ``That would be wonderful,'' he said
enthusiastically. ``The lower the better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
