<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5230 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAPTISTS-CLINTON-HNS &LR;      06-14 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTISTS-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHERN BAPTIST LEADER CALLS FOR CLINTON TO BE DISCIPLINED OVER
GAY PROCLAMATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICHARD VARA 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The president of the Southern Baptist Convention on
Monday called for local church discipline against fellow
denomination member President Clinton for proclaiming June as Gay
and Lesbian Pride Month.
</P>
<P>
   Paige Patterson, president of the 15.7 million-member
denomination, issued the call for church discipline, as more than
14,000 convention delegates, known as messengers, converged on
Atlanta's Georgia Dome for Tuesday's opening of the national
convention's annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson, also president of Southeastern Baptist Theological
Seminary in North Carolina, castigated Clinton for issuing the
gay-pride proclamation last week. Every June, the U.S. gay
community observes the anniversary of the 1969 resistance to police
harassment and mistreatment at the Stonewall Inn in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (proclamation) is entirely inconsistent with his
confession as an evangelical Christian and certainly as a Southern
Baptist,'' Patterson said. ``I would call once again upon the
church in which the president holds membership to take before them
this proclamation he has made at the White House and make it the
subject of church discipline,'' Patterson said during a live
broadcast of a denominational radio program from the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson's call was greeted with applause from a small audience
attending pre-meeting activities.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Land, president of the convention's ethics and religious
liberty commission, also harshly criticized the president. ``I am
appalled that the president would abuse the office of the
presidency to call for an affirmation of a lifestyle that tens of
millions of Americans, based on their religious convictions,
believe to be a deviant lifestyle,'' Land said.
</P>
<P>
   Later during a pastor's conference, Land said, ``I will ask that
God stay his judgment on this nation until this man is no longer
president.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Rex Horne of Immanuel Baptist Church of Little Rock,
Ark., Clinton's pastor, could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   But Barry Toiv, a White House spokesman, defended the
proclamation. ``This proclamation is about preventing
discrimination,'' Toiv said. ``It is about preventing hate crimes;
it is about every American having an equal opportunity to
contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   The proclamation encourages ``all Americans to observe this
month with appropriate programs, ceremonies and activities that
celebrate our diversity, and to remember throughout the year the
gay and lesbian Americans whose many and varied contributions have
enriched our national life.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not the first time convention leaders have called for the
church to take action on Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson and Albert Mohler, president of Southern Baptist
Theological Seminary in Kentucky, called Immanuel to discipline
Clinton during the Monica Lewinsky investigation. But Clinton
issued a letter to the church apologizing for the incident and
publicly repented his role in the affair, defusing the calls for
church discipline.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the church's seating at the annual meeting in Houston
was challenged because of Clinton's controversial order permitting
gays in the military and his appointment of gays in his
administration. The convention's credential committee ruled,
however, that a church's seating at the meeting could not be
challenged on the views of a congregant.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates voted in the Houston meeting to distance themselves
from Clinton's policies. Horne at that time said he had talked with
Clinton on the gay and abortion issues. ``We try to show grace and
love, show the straight path and encourage people to take it,''
Horne said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Wiley Drake of Buena Park, Calif., said he would
introduce a resolution Tuesday ``discouraging all Americans from
observing this month in any way, other than to pray for the
repentance and salvation of those caught in this sinful
lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   Drake is the minister who called for the denomination to boycott
the Walt Disney Co. because of what he perceived as anti-family,
pro-gay rights policies of the entertainment conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   The Baptist denomination is nonhierarchical, and the local
church is autonomous. But the national convention, firmly
controlled by conservatives since 1979, has grabbed national
headlines with its countercultural views.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the national convention amended its doctrinal
statement calling for wives to ``graciously submit'' to their
husbands' authority.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
