<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   Koreas: Northern Intrusion &QL;
</P>
<P>
   North Korean ships again entered disputed waters off South
Korea, as the naval standoff between the two Koreas entered its
eighth day. North Korean Army officers are scheduled to discuss the
crisis with U.N. officials Tuesday at the border village of
Panmunjon.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia: Vote Count Continues &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One week after a parliamentary election, the vote count
continued at a snail's pace, still showing the opposition party of
Megawati Sukarnoputri in the lead. The ruling party, Golkar, was
trailing but did not appear to be out of the running for the coming
round of coalition-building and closed-door maneuvering to select a
president.
</P>
<P>
   Cambodia: Khmer Rouge Inquiry &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Three former guerrillas were questioned by investigators
preparing a case against their commander, Ta Mok, who is expected
to be the first Khmer Rouge leader tried for the mass murders of
the late 1970's. A second man, known by his nickname Duch, is also
in custody awaiting trial for his role as head of the Tuol Sleng
prison and torture chamber.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spain: Tight Campaign Predicted &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts predicted a closer race in the general
elections due by next year, after the opposition Socialist Party
cut the lead of the governing Popular Party in elections on Sunday
for the European Parliament, and for Spain's city halls and 13
regional parliaments. The big loser was the smaller, Communist-led
United Left coalition, whose nose dive at the ballot box was seen
as helping the center-left Socialists.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Ex-President Winds Up Visit &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Former President Carlos Salinas de Gortari has ended a visit to
Mexico, his first since he went into exile in March 1995, weeks
after he ended his 1988-1994 term. During his surprise two-day
return, Salinas visited his older brother, Raul, who is serving a
50-year prison sentence for the murder of a political rival. His
visit provoked protests, but before leaving he said, ``I'm tempted
to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Fugitive Politician Speaks Out &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mario Villanueva Madrid, the former governor of Quintana Roo who
became a fugitive to avoid arrest on federal racketeering and drug
crimes, said in an interview with the news weekly Proceso that he
was being victimized by aides to President Ernesto Zedillo whom he
had angered in a dispute within the governing party. Authorities
say they have no idea of Villanueva's whereabouts. Proceso said a
condition of its phone interview with Villanueva was not to reveal
his location or the interview date.
</P>
</TEXT>
