<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5232 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ZIP-VIRUS-COX     06-14 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIP-VIRUS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Experts expect the worst of the damage from the zip virus's to
dwindle
 &HT;    By Omar L. Gallaga
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Thursday night, Meg Wilson lost four years of
her life.
</P>
<P>
   While checking her e-mail, Wilson, a University of Texas
instructor, thought she had found a resume from a former student
she was nominating to a leadership program. What she found instead
was the Worm.Explore.Zip bug, a software virus that has struck
hundreds of thousands of computers since last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost all my (Microsoft) Word files, my PowerPoint files . .
. personal files are gone,'' Wilson said. ``That's about four years
of my life, gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday, Wilson was still trying to recover four gigabytes
worth of files. She said she believes she was able to get rid of
the virus _ which she thinks she got from a former student _ before
infecting 2,000 users whose names crowded her e-mail program's
inbox and who could have potentially been exposed to the worm.
</P>
<P>
   While most Austin-area companies said they had minimal damage
from the bug _ Dell Computer Corp. officials said the company only
had minor damage and a few frozen machines _ researchers said the
virus is going global.
</P>
<P>
   But there is good news: Researchers also said they believe the
worst of the Worm.Explore.Zip bug attacks are over, at least for
U.S. companies.
</P>
<P>
   The first alerts went out last week about Worm.Explore.Zip,
which is transmitted through files sent by e-mail and activated
when a user runs the attachment, said Eric Chien, senior researcher
at Symantec Corp.'s AntiVirus Research Center.
</P>
<P>
   Chien said that despite the virus' hits on companies including
AT&AMP;T, Boeing, Compaq Computer Corp. and Motorola Inc., early alerts
and distribution of anti-virus software kept most companies safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most major corporate enterprises are well aware the
virus is out there,'' Chien said. ``The worst definitely for the
U.S. is over. Most have eradicated it from their systems or
protected themselves against it.''
</P>
<P>
   Symantec's center in Santa Monica, Calif., was first alerted to
the virus June 6 when five Israeli companies spotted
Worm.Explore.Zip. The first instances of the bug in the U.S. came
three days later.
</P>
<P>
   Chien said the biggest threat now is to home users receiving
e-mail from work and in countries including Korea and China, where
many companies use outdated virus protection programs.
</P>
<P>
   The Worm bug is the third major virus to hit computers over the
past three months.
</P>
<P>
   Worm apparently strikes Microsoft programs, including Microsoft
Word, Excel and PowerPoint. Users are being advised to avoid
opening e-mail attachments unless they are confirmed with the
sender.
</P>
<P>
   If someone receives the virus, the e-mail should be deleted and
the trash folder should be emptied. Users are also being advised to
install and use anti-virus software or download updates for their
existing anti-virus programs.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the FBI was still investigating the origins of the
Worm bug as computer experts found new ways that it can spread.
</P>
<P>
   According the Computer Emergency Response Team at Carnegie
Mellon University, the bug may be able to spread outside of e-mail
attachments. ``Further analysis has shown that, once installed, the
program may also behave as a worm, and it may be able to propagate
itself, without any human interaction, to other networked
machines,'' CERT said in a statement on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The Worm bug can also spread to Macintosh computers that are
using software to run Microsoft Windows operating systems or
Macintoshes networked to Windows computers over a file-sharing
network, Symantec said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Mullen, owner of Austin's PC Guru, said that while he's had
inquiries about the virus from companies in the United Kingdom and
in other parts of the U.S., he's had few calls from companies in
Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems that most companies (here) have had sufficient
knowledge to put up protection against it,'' he said. ``This one
doesn't spread as rapidly as Melissa and is easier to detect _ if
you've got a virus that's deleting all your files, you know you've
got it.''
</P>
<P>
   Omar L. Gallaga writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
