u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOEING-AIR-SHOW-NYT     06-14 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-AIR-SHOW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING'S LITTLE 717 IS PUT ON CENTER RUNWAY
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LE BOURGET, France _ Boeing's centerpiece at the Paris Air Show
here is not one of its famous wide-body jumbo jets but the newest
and smallest member of its fleet, a stub-nosed little passenger jet
called the 717.
</P>
<P>
   The Boeing Co. flew in one of the first production models of the
twin-engine, 100-seat aircraft to put on display, and it is
planning to take it on a 10-city European tour after the air show
ends this weekend. Its executives are telling anyone who will
listen how inexpensive the 717 is to operate, how its new engines
surpasses even the most rigorous noise standards, and how it
provides travelers with as much overhead stowage space as a 747
jumbo jet.
</P>
<P>
   Yet many people in the commercial aerospace industry think that
the 717 already has one foot in the grave.
</P>
<P>
   The reason illustrates the challenges Boeing faces as it tries
to right itself and compete against Airbus Industrie, the European
consortium, after two disastrous years in which its commercial
airplane division wrote off $4 billion and missed out on the
biggest aviation-industry boom in history.
</P>
<P>
   Although the decision to build the 717 was made four years ago,
Boeing has sold only 117 of them. Last year, Airbus also decided to
enter the market for 100-seat jets. It announced its offering, the
A318, in April and has already booked more than 100 orders.
</P>
<P>
   Making money selling 100-seat jets is difficult because they are
expensive to build and airlines do not want to pay very much for
them. But Airbus and Boeing forecast that 2,000 to 2,600 planes
capable of carrying 70 to 100 passengers each would be bought by
airlines over the next 20 years. They do not want to cede that
market to each other, or to the three manufacturers of 50- and
70-seat regional jets _ Embraer of Brazil, Bombardier of Canada and
Fairchild Dornier, a German unit of Fairchild Aerospace _ who are
talking about building larger 100-seat models.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had we not launched the A318, we would have created a
vacuum,'' said John Leahy, Airbus' commercial director. ``We need
to have a full product line.''
</P>
<P>
   Airbus' solution was to shrink its 124-seat, twin-engine A319 to
create the 318. Like all Airbus jets, the A318, which will start
flying in 2002, will have common cockpit displays and controls. One
of Airbus' strongest selling points is that pilots can move from
one of its models to another with minimum training, which can add
up to millions of dollars in savings for carriers.
</P>
<P>
   It also makes the cost of the A318 easier to justify because
airlines that buy it will then have an incentive to order the
larger, more lucrative Airbus jets.
</P>
<P>
   The 717, on the other hand, has little in common with Boeing's
other models. Indeed, it started life at the McDonnell Douglas
Corp. as the MD-95, a successor to the successful DC-9. Boeing
inherited the plane after it bought McDonnell Douglas in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts thought that Boeing would cancel the MD-95, just
as it decided to stop making the other McDonnell Douglas models.
But after several months, Boeing announced that it would add the
jet to its product line and christened it the 717.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many doubted Boeing's commitment to the new plane and
speculated that the company had no choice but to keep the project
going because it would have had to pay heavy penalties to a
suppliers if it canceled development.
</P>
<P>
   When the company announced a review of all its operations
earlier this year, promising to eliminate planes that were ``value
destroyers,'' many analysts speculated that the 717 was at the top
of the list. Some industry executives even now believe that Boeing
is taking the 717 on tour as a prelude to canceling it by
fulfilling its contractual obligations to suppliers to make its
best sales effort.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing denies that. The idea that the company would cancel the
717 after most of the investment in the jet had already been made
was ludicrous, Alan Mulally, chief of the commercial airplane
division, said in an interview Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Philip M. Condit, Boeing's chief executive, sent a
letter to Moody's and Standard &AMP; Poor's, assuring the rating
agencies that Boeing was firmly behind the jet. The same month,
Boeing executives flew a 717, which is made at the old McDonnell
Douglas plant in Long Beach, Calif., to their Seattle headquarters
in an effort to promote the aicraft within company ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone who gets a look at the plane really likes it,'' said
Joseph Leonard, chairman and chief executive of Airtran, which is
scheduled to begin flying the first 717 in October. He estimated
that the plane would cost Airtran 10 to 12 percent less to operate
than its current fleet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not the slightest bit concerned about the number of
sales,'' he said. ``The 737 wasn't a very big seller in the early
days, and it became the best selling airplane of all time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
