<HEADER>
A5245 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT     06-14 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO STOP THE SPURS: KNICKS PONDER THE WAYS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ Chris Childs remembers the game with such
clarity that he grimaces and shakes his head when recalling the
details. The images of that debacle against the San Antonio Spurs _
almost 15 months ago _ are as fresh and focused as the film the
Knicks watched Monday in preparations for Game 1 of the National
Basketball Association finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks were in similarly dire injury straits for that game
in Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing and Chris Dudley were sidelined and the Knicks
started a super-small lineup, with Charles Oakley at center, Larry
Johnson at power forward and three guards. To exploit that, the
Spurs started three 7-footers with Will Perdue joining the regulars
David Robinson and Tim Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   The result: Spurs 95, Knicks 78.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan was matched up with Charlie Ward, who went 0 for 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave them everything,'' Childs said before the Knicks
arrived in San Antonio via chartered jet Monday evening. ``We gave
them inside. Outside. We became a stationary ball club. We tried to
play them in the halfcourt set where their legs and strength took
advantage of us. You can't play them the same way. We're a
different team now. We're a lot smarter.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely the Knicks will suffer the same fate now, even if
Johnson is unable to play in this series. His availability for Game
1 will be determined at game time Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   With Marcus Camby and Kurt Thomas on the team, and Dudley
healthy, the Knicks _ even without Ewing _ are in better shape
inside. When everyone is healthy, the Knicks' depth is so deep they
rarely worry about foul trouble. Now, because fouls follow Thomas
and Dudley around like lost puppies, managing their time will be
one of Coach Jeff Van Gundy's greatest burdens.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy said he learned more from the teams' first meeting
last season, a 90-84 Knicks loss in which there were more
conventional matchups. In that game, Duncan, just a few weeks into
his rookie season, and Robinson each scored 23 points, and Ewing,
who had not yet sustained his wrist injury, had 25 points and 15
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy has been circumspect about how the Knicks will defend
Duncan and Robinson. Dudley figures that neither can be stopped
entirely and that the Knicks will have to mix their defenses just
to limit their offensive production. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the Knicks double-team them, they must hope the guards Avery
Johnson, Mario Elie and the small forward Sean Elliott can't beat
the Knicks by themselves. While Duncan (21.5 points a game) and
Robinson (15.2) are the Spurs' leading scorers in the playoffs, the
much-traveled Johnson has quietly emerged with 14.1 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's feasible, but I'm not sure you'd want to go with the
double-team on both of them the entire game because it opens up too
much for everyone else,'' Van Gundy said. ``With Avery Johnson, no
matter where he has played, the strategy was `Make Avery Johnson
beat you.' And that's what he always does.''
</P>
<P>
   But Camby, who will be in the middle of this maelstrom, trying
to use his long arms and legs against either Robinson or Duncan, is
convinced that the Knicks will not be able to play them straight up
for an entire game without getting a lesson in why each is regarded
as a most valuable player candidate. ``Definitely, they are our
main concern,'' Camby said. ``Not just one player can guard them.
We're definitely going to have to rely on some help at some point.
I'm not going to tell you if we're going to double or triple, but
they're definitely going to command some double-teams at some time.
They're that great of players.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy would not say Monday whether Camby or Thomas would
start if Johnson is out, but at least the Knicks will have a bigger
lineup than they did when the Spurs pounded them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't give them everything,'' Van Gundy said. ``You can't
give them perimeter and post, transition and second shots. You have
to do something to limit some parts of their game. That's one of
the reasons we were effective against Indiana; we took away their
3-point game. Any team that's really dominant, as they have been,
is balanced. Teams that are inconsistent you can exploit because
they have weaknesses. This team has no weaknesses; that's why
they've won 10 playoff games in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   Just what the Knicks can hope to limit is still unclear. Because
Duncan and Robinson are both shot-blocking threats, the Knicks
would like to draw one of them away from the basket to play
perimeter defense. But if Johnson is out, the Knicks lose a scorer
with size who can shoot from long range.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks will run even more than they did against Indiana with
Latrell Sprewell (who will match up with Sean Elliott, a player he
says is so similar to him that it is like playing against a mirror)
and Allan Houston (against Elie) trying to drive into the lane,
headlong into the twin oaks planted there, hoping to draw a foul
from Robinson or Duncan, who have each fouled out only once in
their 12 playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been talking about penetrating and driving, but it's
easier said than done,'' Sprewell said. ``We still have to attack
those guys. We can't worry about them blocking shots. We can't be
timid. We have to be aggressive and try to get them in foul
trouble. We can do it. But I don't know how effective it's going to
be.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-99 2127EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990614.0425 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5246 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-ART-NYT     06-14 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP TO SEPARATE GUN-CONTROL MEASURES FROM JUVENILE-CRIME BILL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo., Fla., Calif., Texas)  (Eds: See also SMART-GUNS) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republican leaders decided Monday to separate
gun-control proposals from a piece of broader juvenile-crime
legislation and put the measures in their own distinct bill, a
surprising change in strategy that underscored the sensitivity of
the issue and instantly gave rise to conflicting interpretations.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said they were trying to make sure that new
restrictions on firearms had a fair shot at passing the House. That
outcome would be less likely, these Republicans said, if the
measures remained in a bill laden with so many other contentious
issues that it practically begged lawmakers on both the right and
the left to vote against it, leaving too narrow a center for
success.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said the Republicans' decision was really a tactic to
try to ensure the failure of gun control. By this thinking,
Republicans who wanted to vote against gun control had found a way
nonetheless to pass some legislation and deflect accusations that
they were doing nothing in response to the school shooting in
Littleton, Colo., two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this is really about is an attempt to give the interest
groups who want to kill this legislation the best chance,'' said
Rep. Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., the minority leader. ``I think it's
pretty clear what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla., who helped write the juvenile
crime bill, said that the new approach merely aimed to make sure
that the debate and votes on other aspects of the legislation, like
tougher penalties for children who commit crimes and new
restrictions on violence in entertainment, did not get lost in all
the attention being paid to gun control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that, as a practical matter, there's going to be
any substantive difference in the outcome,'' McCollum said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new plan, McCollum's crime bill, which allocates new
federal money for the prosecution and prevention of juvenile crime,
would be the vehicle for amendments that dealt with cultural and
religious matters, like one that proposes criminal penalties for
adults who let children have access to material with extreme
violence in it. This whole package would be debated and decided one
day this week.
</P>
<P>
   But gun-control measures would be considered either the day
before or after, and those provisions that succeeded would become
their own bill. If the House passed that bill, it would be combined
with the juvenile crime legislation without any additional vote.
</P>
<P>
   There were political calculations at work as the House Rules
Committee began Monday to consider about 175 proposed amendments to
the juvenile crime bill and Republican leaders gave hints of which
amendments would reach the floor, and how.
</P>
<P>
   By putting gun control in its own box, leaders had given its
fiercest Republican opponents a way to vote for conservative
cultural measures and tougher enforcement of crime without
approving any new restrictions on firearms.
</P>
<P>
   But they had also given Democrats opposed to aspects of the
legislation a way to vote for gun control. Senior Republican aides
said that Republican leaders felt they had to get some gun-control
measures through the House, or Speaker J. Dennis Hastert, who had
virtually promised that outcome, would suffer a potentially
debilitating embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   Republican aides said that the Rules Committee would probably
permit about eight modest gun-control measures, mostly addressing
the same issues as the provisions that the Senate passed, to reach
the floor.
</P>
<P>
   For mandatory background checks on buyers at gun shows,
Republican leaders would likely allow three alternatives of varying
strictness, with sponsorships that reflected interesting political
calculations.
</P>
<P>
   The most lenient gun-show measure, in line with the wishes of
the National Rifle Association, is likely to bear the names of six
Democrats. The harshest measure has at least one Republican joining
two Democrats as sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   But for other new restrictions on firearms, like child safety
devices on handguns, the Rules Committee would probably refer just
one measure, without any alternative, to the floor, Republican
aides said.
</P>
<P>
   A list of possible measures and their sponsors suggested some
cunning planning. For example, Rep. James Rogan, R-Calif., who
represents a district that has been getting increasingly
Democratic, has his name attached to a measure that bans firearm
ownership for any adult who has committed a violent crime as a
child.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats complained that Republican leaders were playing every
angle: giving gun control a way to fail while also setting
themselves up, by putting Republican names on many measures, to
claim some credit if it succeeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a peculiar procedure from the beginning,'' said
Rep. Martin Frost, D-Texas, the chairman of the House Democratic
Conference, ``and it's only getting more peculiar every day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
