u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-NYT &LR;      06-14 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AND YELTSIN CONFER BUT FAIL TO RESOLVE IMPASSE OVER RUSSIAN
TROOOPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and other senior American leaders
spoke with their counterparts in Russia on Monday but were unable
to resolve the impasse over Russian troops that has marred the
beginning of the peacekeeping mission in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   American officials tried to put the best face on the military
and diplomatic mess, but it was clear that Russia and the United
States remain far apart on critical questions arising from Russia's
demand to take part in the Kosovo military operation on its own
terms.
</P>
<P>
   Four high-level telephone conversations took place on Monday
between Washington and Moscow, but officials appear to have made
little progress in settling such issues as the size of the Russian
military contingent in Kosovo, its command structure and its
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke with President Boris Yeltsin of Russia for 23
minutes on Monday morning, their second conversation in two days.
Aides described the talk as ``good,'' but offered few details. The
two leaders agreed to dispatch their foreign and defense ministers
to Helsinki, Finland, this week for further talks.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is scheduled to meet Yeltsin this weekend in Cologne,
Germany, at the annual meeting of leaders of the major industrial
democracies and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright spoke with Igor Ivanov,
the Russian foreign minister, twice on Monday, officials in
Washington said. Vice President Al Gore telephoned Sergei
Stepashin, the Russian prime minister, and the two spoke for about
45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   After the conversation, Stepashin said that Russia intended to
play ``a substantial role'' in the Kosovo peacekeeping operation
under the auspices of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   In their conversations with the Russians, the American officials
were trying to determine, among other things, who ordered the
armored Russian column of about 200 soldiers to enter Kosovo last
Friday night in advance of NATO troops. The NATO soldiers were
supposed to form the vanguard of the forces being deployed to
police the peace plan.
</P>
<P>
   Albright, speaking at a briefing for reporters in the White
House, said there was apparent confusion in Russia and in
Yugoslavia over the Russian military move. She said she assumed
that Yeltsin had given the order but that the Russian military
``got out one step ahead'' of the political leadership in Moscow by
moving prematurely into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Another senior aide said, though, that it was clear to American
officials that Yeltsin had given the order to move Russian troops
into Kosovo. He contended that Yeltsin is enjoying the confusion he
has sown in Moscow and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said that administration officials sought assurances
that no additional Russian troops would move into Kosovo until
their zone of influence and questions of command and control are
settled at the Helsinki talks. There have been indications in
Moscow of preparations to dispatch troops to the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to stress that we welcome Russian participation'' in
the peacekeeping operation, Albright said on Monday. But she said
that the administration was sticking to its insistence on ``unity
of command'' in Kosovo, meaning that all troops operating there
would report to a single NATO commander.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
