<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WAL-MART AGREES TO BUY BRITISH SUPERMARKET CHAIN
</P>
<P>
   In its first foray into Britain, Wal-Mart Stores agreed to pay
$10.8 billion in cash for Asda Group, Britain's third-largest
supermarket chain, thwarting a rival suitor at the last moment and
threatening other British retailers with a potentially devastating
price war. The takeover agreement is part of Wal-Mart's aggressive
buying spree in Europe, where tight zoning regulations make it
almost impossible to build big, new stores, leaving entrants into
the businesses of supermarkets and large convenience stores no
option but to acquire existing chains.
</P>
<P>
   GREENSPAN SOUNDS NOTE OF CAUTION
</P>
<P>
   In congressional testimony, Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve
chairman, warned that increases in business efficiency could not
counterbalance the strains on the economy forever. But he did not
directly address the prospect of an increase in short-term interest
rates later this month.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS MIXED AS NASDAQ TUMBLES
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices were mixed and activity remained subdued as traders
and investors delayed putting money to work before an important
inflation report scheduled for release tomorrow. The Dow Jones
industrial average rose 72.82 points, or seven-tenths of a percent,
to 10,563.33. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index was flat,
rising 0.36 point, to 1,294.00. But the Nasdaq composite index,
fell 49.57 points, or 2.03 percent, to 2,398.31. The yield on the
30-year Treasury fell to 6.09 percent.
</P>
<P>
   OXFORD HEALTH REBUFFED IN COURT
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge rejected a motion by Oxford Health Plans for
dismissal of a shareholder suit against it, making an out-of-court
settlement more likely.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. BOWS OUT OF INTERNET VENTURE
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department has pulled out of a partnership with a
private company, Northern Light Technology, to facilitate finding
Government information on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   NATURAL-FOOD GIANT SWITCHES FOCUS
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two years, Irwin Simon, the chief executive of
Hain Food Group, has spent millions of dollars assembling an empire
of natural-food products. The company, which now has 27 brands and
more than 1,000 products, has been successful in getting its
products on the shelves of supermarket chains. Now it is switching
its advertising focus from retailers to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING PROMOTES A SMALLER PLANE
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's centerpiece at the Paris Air Show is not one of its
wide-body jets but the newest and smallest member of its fleet, a
twin-engine, 100-seat passenger jet called the 717.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN TO SEEK REBUILDING DEALS
</P>
<P>
   British Government officials plan to meet with business leaders
in London to devise a strategy for securing reconstruction
contracts in Kosovo, moving to offset a widespread view that
British companies lost out in the race to rebuild Kuwait after the
Persian Gulf war eight years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   NORTEL PRESIDENT PLANS TO RESIGN
</P>
<P>
   David House, president of Nortel Networks of Canada, the
communications equipment giant, will resign as soon as this summer,
the company said.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT CALLS HOSTILE WITNESS
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to prove that America Online had deceived the judge in
the government's antitrust trial against Microsoft about its plans
to compete with the software giant, Microsoft put its most
important rebuttal witness on the stand, David Colburn, a senior
executive from the on-line service. But several people dozed
through the questioning, and Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson told
Microsoft's lawyer, John Warden, to hurry up and finish.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
