A5249 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SCENE-NYT &LR;      06-14 0351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO TROOPS FIND SCORES OF FRESHLY DUG GRAVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KACANIK, Yugoslavia _ American soldiers on Monday sealed off
areas around this small town in southeastern Kosovo where other
NATO troops found what they said could be graves containing the
remains of scores of civilians killed by Yugoslav troops.
</P>
<P>
   At one site, a local cemetery, British troops found what
appeared to be 80 freshly dug graves with simple markers.
</P>
<P>
   Villagers and members of the Kosovo Liberation Army guerrilla
force showed reporters a narrow ravine just outside Kacanik that
contained a half dozen jackets and shirts that appeared to have
bullet holes in the shoulder and chest areas.
</P>
<P>
   They said they were among the belongings of more than 50 people
they said were killed by Serbs on April 9 in retaliation for a
Kosovo Liberation Army ambush the day before that killed a half
dozen Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   That night, they said heavy equipment was seen digging what
appeared to be a large mass grave in the local cemetery. But the
British soldiers taking control of the area discovered as many as
80 freshly dug individual graves in the cemetery, which they
believe could hold the bodies of the victims. The site was sealed
off, awaiting International War Crimes Tribunal investigators who
may arrive this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear whether the individual graves were what the
villagers said they saw being dug by the equipment in April. NATO
spokesmen also have accused the Serbs of exhuming the bodies of
execution victims from mass graves in recent days and then
reburying them in individual graves.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said this pattern occurred in Hallac, a village in
central Kosovo, where they said 20 people were killed in mid-April,
dug up more recently and then reburied in individual graves.
</P>
<P>
   If, as NATO officials suspect, this was part of an attempt to
cover up mass killings, the aim theoretically would be to try to
create the impression that the buried bodies were of people who
died individually in combat, not in a mass execution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
