</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- June 14, 1999 -- MILLENNIUM-FASHION-2, 6-14
-- From left, Ralph Lauren's silk jersey dress with a wrapped
halter top and a low-riding skirt is a sure-fire way to be noticed
at a tropical resort; paper taffeta dress by Oscar de la Renta with
fullness swept to the back and into a short train is the kind of
design that would be noticed at any festive gathering; a shoulder-
and back-baring dress of paperlike silk by Calvin Klein has a skirt
that is slightly longer and fuller in back. (Marilynn K. Yee/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- June 14, 1999 -- MILLENNIUM-FASHION-1, 6-14
-- A Celine design by Michael Kors that he calls ``the ultimate
bathing suit dress'' has a bra top that can be adjusted to control
exposure. Carolina Herrera's brightly colored paper taffeta dress,
right, has a row of beading at the top and an oversize shawl that
reverses from taffeta to pashmina. (Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) MANHASSET, N.Y. -- June 14, 1999 --
HEALTHFOOD-AD-COLUMN, 6-14 -- Irwin D. Simon, chief of the Hain
Food Group, checks out some of his company's products at a Long
Island supermarket. He is trying to attract consumers' attention in
the crowded market for natural foods. (Rebecca Cooney/New York
Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) PRIZREN, Yugoslavia -- June 14, 1999 --
KOSOVO-PRIZREN-6, 6-14 -- A rebel with the Kosovo Liberation Army
calling himself Commander Drini, holds up a girl during the group's
march into town on Monday. The swift emergence of the KLA as the
new power on the ground poses a delicate problem for the NATO
peacekeepers. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) CONCORD, N.H. -- June 14, 1999 -- GORE-CAMPAIGN-2, 6-14
-- Vice President Al Gore talks to New Hampshire reporters via a
video earlier this month. As he sets the stage for the official
announcement of his candidacy Wednesday in Tennessee, Gore still
seems to be painting by numbers, following the chalk while he is
learning to dance, telling his audience as much as reminding
himself exactly what he is doing and why. (Paul Hosefros/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) CONCORD, N.H. -- June 14, 1999 -- GORE-CAMPAIGN, 6-14 --
Vice President Al Gore talks to supporters during a campaign stop
earlier this month. As he sets the stage for the official
announcement of his candidacy Wednesday in Tennessee, Gore still
seems to be painting by numbers, following the chalk while he is
learning to dance, telling his audience as much as reminding
himself exactly what he is doing and why. (Paul Hosefros/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) PRIZREN, Yugoslavia -- June 14, 1999 --
KOSOVO-PRIZREN-5, 6-14 -- A convoy of Yugoslav soldiers drives past
a U.S. Army soldier leaving Prizren on Monday. NATO slowly expanded
its control over a central swath of Kosovo on Monday, pouring in
thousands of more soldiers into major towns and villages as Serb
forces, along with Serb civilians, left. (Alan Chin/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) HARTFORD, Conn. -- June 14, 1999 -- SMART-GUNS, 6-14 --
The prototype of the Colt Smartgun, a Colt law enforcement pistol,
at Colt Manufacturing. The wristband contains a transmitter which
sends a coded radio signal to a receiver in the firearm which it
instantly decodes allowing the weapon to fire. As the pressure for
smart guns grows, it is becoming increasingly clear that
personalized guns may not be the simple fix many proponents think
it is. As with so much in the national gun debate, it's development
has gotten mired in controversy. (George Ruhe for The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) WASHINGTON -- June 14, 1999 -- CONGRESS-GUNS, 6-14 --
Rep. Henry Hyde (R-Ill.) chairman of the House Judiciary Committee,
and the ranking minority member Rep. John Conyers (D-Mich.), left,
before the House Rules Committee on Monday to present their
amendments on gun control legislation. The U.S. House panel, faced
with more than 170 amendments on gun control measures, began
shaping the rules and boundaries for a gun control debate slated
for Wednesday. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) PRIZREN, Yugoslavia -- June 14, 1999 --
KOSOVO-PRIZREN-4, 6-14 -- Serbs wait for an escort to leave Prizren
at the Bogoslovia seminary on Monday. More than 11,000 ethnic Serbs
have fled Kosovo since last week's peace deal between Yugoslav
forces and NATO, the International Committee of the Red Cross said
on Monday. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) PRIZREN, Yugoslavia -- June 14, 1999 --
KOSOVO-PRIZREN-3, 6-14 -- A fighter with the Kosovo Liberatino Army
looks out over a street from an apartment complex that is empty on
Monday. It was hardly a few hours after Serbs pulled out of
Kosovo's second largest city when the KLA appeared on the steets
brandishing its weapons and new-found authority. (Tyler Hicks/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) LOS ANGELES -- June 14, 1999 -- FILM-RATINGS-ENFORCE,
6-14 -- From left, Lydia Ross, Dani Eisner and Lily Trussell, all
13, talk about the new policy of teen-agers being required to show
identification in order to enter R-rated film outside a shopping
center on Saturday. Prodded by President Clinton, theater owners
across the country last week announced that they would increase
checks of photo identification cards to enforce the R-rating. (Jill
Connelly/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) PRIZREN, Yugoslavia -- June 14, 1999 --
KOSOVO-PRIZREN-2, 6-14 -- A rebel with the Kosovo Liberation Army
jumps on a German military vehicle on Monday. Yugoslav forces and
anxious Serb residents made their second bid to flee the western
Kosovo city in large convoys on Monday as German and Dutch NATO
troops continued to pour into the area. (Stephen Crowley/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW CASTLE, N.H. -- June 14, 1999 -- NH-BUSH-4, 6-14 --
Emma Frampton, 6, yawns while Republican Presidential candidate
George W. Bush listens to his wife Laura while reading to children
at a school on Monday. Emma wore a tiara to celebrate her birthday.
Bush is touring New Hampshire on his maiden campaign swing through
states holding the first presidential primaries. (Andrea Mohin/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11)WASHINGTON -- June 14, 1999 -- KOSOVO-RDP, 6-14 --
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright confers with National
Security Advisor Sandy Berger during a briefing on the upcoming G8
summit next week, at the White House on Monday. President Clinton
and other senior American leaders spoke with their counterparts in
Russia on Monday but were unable to resolve the impasse over
Russian troops in Kosovo that has marred the beginning of the
Balkan peacekeeping mission. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) DENVER -- June 14, 1999 -- PRIVACY-LAWSUIT, 6-13 --
James Rapp, a private investigator, poses for a portrait recently.
A Federal Trade Commission lawsuit against a Rapp is being billed
by both sides as a landmark case, and Rapp is receiving significant
support from a coalition of other information brokers and debt
collectors, who see the government's action as a huge threat to
their livelihood. (Nico Totenhofd/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- June 14, 1999 -- SCI-FOSTER-CARE, 6-14 -- Dr.
Francine Cournos is a professor of clinical psychiatry at Columbia
University. Her book, ``City of One: A Memoir,'' was just published
by W.W. Norton. In her book, Cournos, a former foster child,
discusses the needs of foster children in America, who now number
more than half a million. (Don Hogan Charles/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) BETHESDA, Md. -- June 14, 1999 --
SCI-HYMAN-MENTAL-HEALTH, 6-14 -- Dr. Steven Hyman, in his
laboratory, was chosen as director of the National Institute of
Mental Health to take advantage of the new tools of psychiatry.
Hyman is something of a maverick and does not come from the ranks
of clinical psychiatry as his predecessors, a fact which has
irritated some people. But supporters say Hyman is just what is
needed to integrate his clinical research on the mind and body and
the latest developments in molecular biology.(Marty Katz/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) KEMMERER, Wyo. -- June 14, 1999 -- SCI FOSSIL-THEFT-3,
6-14 -- Vincent Santucci, right, chief ranger and resident
paleontologist at Fossil Butte National Monument, looking at
specimens dug up by other paleontologists near the monument. This
region, in southwestern Wyoming, consists of 8,000 acres of barren
land that is home to some of the best preserved plant and animal
fossils in the world. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) KEMMERER, Wyo. -- June 14, 1999 -- SCI FOSSIL-THEFT-2,
6-14 -- Using a special jet spray of baking soda,. a park service
paleontologist cleans fossilized bones of a 50-million-year-old
fish at the Fossil Butte National Monument. The monument consist of
8,000 acres of barren land that is home to some of the best
preserved plant and animal fossils in the world. (Kevin Moloney/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) KEMMERER, Wyo. -- June 14, 1999 -- SCI-FOSSIL-THEFT-1,
6-14 -- Vincent Santucci, the only pistol-packing paleontologist in
the National Park Service, is the chief ranger and resident
paleontologist at Fossil Butte National Monument in southwestern
Wyoming. Santucci patrols over 8,000 acres of seemingly barren land
that is actually home to some of the best preserved plant and
animal fossils in the world, samples of which are at left. (Kevin
Moloney/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW CASTLE, N.H. -- June 14, 1999 -- NH-BUSH-3, 6-14 --
Six-year old Eva Betti carries a handmade sign supporting Gov.
George W. Bush toward where the Texas governor was to make a
campaign stop Monday morning. Bush is touring New Hampshire in his
maiden campaign swing through states holding the first presidential
primaries. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW CASTLE, N.H. -- June 14, 1999 -- NH-BUSH-2, 6-14 --
Gov. George W. Bush during a news conference at a campaign stop
Monday morning. In a wide-ranging news conference on his maiden
campaign trip, Bush pledged to uphold the dignity of the presidency
if elected. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW CASTLE, N.H. -- June 14, 1999 -- NH-BUSH-1, 6-14 --
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas greets supporters at a campaign stop
Monday morning. Bush pledged on Monday to uphold the dignity of the
presidency, raising his right hand in an oath-swearing flourish
when questioned about his character. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) PRIZREN, Yugoslavia -- June 14, 1999 -- KOSOVO-PRIZREN,
6-14 -- German troops tried to keep order as ethnic Albanians
taunted a convoy of Serbs leaving Prizden, Kosovo's second largest
city, on Monday. Yugoslav forces and anxious Serb residents made
their second bid to flee the western Kosovo city in large convoys
on Monday as German and Dutch NATO troops continued to pour into
the area. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
