<SLUG> BC-QWEST-USWEST-NYT </SLUG>
 
QwEST SHARES PLUNGE 24 PERCENT IN BID'S WAKE  
(With QWEST-USWEST-ASSESS) 
(ms) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shares of Qwest Communications International Inc.,
the upstart telecommunications company, plummeted 24 percent Monday
after investors panned its $55 billion bid for both U S West, the
Denver-based local telecommunications concern, and Frontier Corp.,
one of the nation's long-distance companies.
</P>
<P>
   Qwest is hoping to woo U S West, one of the regional Bell
companies, and Frontier, the former Rochester Telephone, away from
the embrace of rival Global Crossing Ltd., which had agreed to buy
both concerns. Qwest, like the Bermuda-based Global Crossing, has a
lofty stock price fueled by the promise of high-flying growth
stemming from the Internet. Qwest is building an Internet fiber
optic network to link 150 metropolitan areas in the United States,
and hopes to expand into Europe as well.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Burnett, president of Merger Insight, said investors were
confused about how to value the combination that would marry the
more traditional telephone assets of U S West with the fast-growing
Qwest stock. Technology stocks, too, particularly Internet shares,
took a beating Monday, which also accounted for some of Qwest's
decline, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only winners here are Frontier and U S West,'' Burnett
said. But, he warned that neither Global Crossing nor Qwest would
easily emerge as the victor in what is likely to be a lengthy and
bitter battle for U S West and Frontier. ``This is not a short
race, but a marathon,'' he said. Plus, it is possible that Qwest
might try to acquire just one of the companies, most likely
Frontier, instead of both, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   What is clear is the deal Qwest announced Sunday was not nearly
as attractive to U S West and Frontier shareholders after Qwest's
stock declined Monday. Qwest said two days ago that it would offer
U S West shareholders stock valued between $78 and $80 a share. For
Frontier's part, Qwest would give shareholders $20 in cash plus
stock valued between $53 and $55. But in one of Qwest's most active
days on record, the stock fell $10.75 a share, to $34.125. With the
lower price, analysts said Qwest would pay U S West shareholders
about $60 in stock. Frontier shareholders would receive about $61
in stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a vote of disenchantment, but it is only one day,''
said Peter Schoenfeld, who heads P. Schoenfeld Asset Management in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Those values are close to the deals struck with Global Crossing,
giving investors little reason to prefer one company over the
other. Based on Monday's closing prices, Frontier shareholders
would get Global stock valued at about $63. Shareholders of U S
West could pick between two stocks _ one made up of the
combination's fast-growing Internet assets, the other, more
traditional telephone assets _ valued between $63 and $65 a share.
Shares of Global Crossing fell 37.5 cents Monday, to $50.375, while
U S West rose $3.125, to $58. Frontier rose $1.9375, to $57.375.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph P. Nacchio, the flamboyant chief executive of Qwest,
still contended his company's offer was ``superior'' despite the
fact that the stock's decline had made the deals comparable in
price. ``This is a major inflection point in terms of our future,''
Nacchio said on a conference call. ``I'm not surprised to see some
investors move out, and I would expect others to buy in.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the next few days are sure to be complicated as both U S
West and Frontier sort through the issues. U S West's board is
expected to meet this week to discuss the Qwest offer. Frontier
management is considering the Qwest offer as well.
</P>
<P>
   Global Crossing, for its part, reaffirmed its commitment to both
the U S West and Frontier mergers, despite recent rumors that it
was looking to get out of the deals. Robert Annunziata, Global
Crossing's chief executive, said in a statement Monday that his
company's offers for U S West and Frontier were superior, too, and
he expected both deals would close as planned. But even if Global
Crossing loses U S West, the company would earn an attractive door
prize _ U S West could have to pay Global Crossing as much as $850
million in breakup fees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
