<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5259 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NH-BUSH-ART-NYT &LR;      06-14 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NH-BUSH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN EARLY GOING, BUSH LONG ON CHARISMA BUT SHORT ON DETAILS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW CASTLE, N.H. _ Peggy McDonald, a retired dental assistant
who lives in this speck of a town on the New Hampshire seacoast,
pronounced Texas Gov. George W. Bush ``adorable'' when he showed up
to give a speech Monday, then proceeded to raise a red flag about
his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is well packaged,'' Mrs. McDonald said, ``but I don't know
what's in the package. I don't know what he stands for.''
</P>
<P>
   At the State Fairgrounds in Des Moines on Saturday night, Bonnie
Gobel, chairwoman of the Iowa Christian Coalition, marveled at
Bush's energetic presence, saying she had ``never seen a
presidential candidate draw so much excitement.'' But Mrs. Gobel
was stumped when the subject turned to Bush's position on abortion
rights, a prime issue for her organization as it considers whom to
endorse for the Iowa caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after the governor delivered his benchmark campaign
speech _ a broad-stroke address that offered the major themes of
his candidacy _ he has emerged as a personable and charismatic
campaigner, displaying a level of skill and taste for politicking
not seen on presidential battlegrounds since Bill Clinton first
came here eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But for all his obvious talent at presenting himself, he has
been notably vague on this closely watched national outing about
particulars, offering only scant details amid generalities _ on
everything from taxes to military spending to abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that details would come in time, and declared that he
would not be hurried into laying out any specific ideas this far
before the first caucuses and primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've been pretty darn specific,'' he said in an
interview on WMUR-TV, the ABC affiliate in Manchester. ``I'll have
a tax plan. I'll have the proverbial 10-point tax plan here. But
I'm going to put it out on my own timetable. This is a long
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   As Bush pointed out, it is extremely early. And it would be
highly unusual, in most years, for a candidate to be offering any
10-point tax plans at this stage. But as has been clear from the
reaction of Republicans eager to hear Bush these past few days,
this is anything but a usual year. And that is in no small part
because of Bush's strategy of trying to present himself as his
party's de facto nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is on the cover of Time and Newsweek this week, and NBC's
evening news program televised two segments on his campaign Monday.
That is the kind of coverage that would not typically be expected
before next February at the earliest. While it is in Bush's
political interest to remain vague for as long as possible _ the
more positions he takes, the more he risks losing the support of
voters who do not agree with him _ that might prove difficult in
this environment.
</P>
<P>
   As he traveled Monday through New Hampshire, which has a
justifiable reputation of being a state with informed voters who
ask informed questions, Bush painted in a few parts of his
political portrait. He is, he responded to a heckler in Bow, in
favor of the constitutional amendment prohibiting flag burning.
</P>
<P>
   When the heckler followed up with a sarcastic query about
whether he is also in favor of the First Amendment, which
guarantees the right of speech, Bush neatly retorted: ``You're
exercising it.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Bush said he supported the Second Amendment, which
protects the right to keep and bear arms. Bush said he backed some
restrictions on the gun purchases, but added: ``I believe that
people ought to be able to bear weapons. I believe that's part of
the Constitution of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   But the governor was fuzzy in responses on abortion rights. He
said he would not automatically reject judicial candidates because
they did not share his views on specific issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no litmus test except for whether or not the
judges will strictly interpret the Constitution,'' he said. ``I am
not a lawyer. My job is to pick judges who are qualified to serve
on the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   Twice, however, he avoided saying whether he would question
prospective judges about their views on abortion, or whether their
replies would help guide his selection.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that if elected, his first two priorities would be
pushing through a tax cut and increasing military spending. He said
he would support cuts in the marginal tax rates as well as programs
to provide tax relief specifically to poorer families. He also said
he might be open to a fundamental restructuring of the tax code,
although he declined to provide details.
</P>
<P>
   He said he opposed affirmative action but declined to say
whether he supported Proposition 209, the California measure passed
in 1996 that prohibited race- and sex-based preferences in state
hiring and contracting and college admissions.
</P>
<P>
   For all his vagaries, Bush clearly signaled Monday that he
intends, to some extent, to run in the Republican primaries against
someone who is not even on the ballot: President Clinton. He
invoked Clinton's difficulties when he was asked about passages in
his new stump speeches decrying a ``if it feels good, do it,''
culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important for any of us, who assume high office,
to understand that when we put our hand on the Bible, that we're
swearing not only to uphold the laws of the land, but that we are
swearing to uphold the dignity of the office to which we've been
elected,'' Bush said, raising his right hand as he recalled his own
oath of office, as cameras clicked furiously.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
