<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5270 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-LTGOV-HOSPITAL-CO     06-14 0345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-LTGOV-HOSPITAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Seriously ill' Bullock released from hospital
 &HT;    By Osler McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Former Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock, suffering from
congestive heart failure, left an Austin hospital for home care
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is very seriously ill,'' said Bullock's longtime friend,
Ralph Wayne, head of the Texas Civil Justice League and a former
state representative from Plainview. ``His friends are praying for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bullock, considered the last of the great legends of Texas
politics, had been diagnosed with lung cancer four and a half
months ago, the latest in a series of maladies he has battled for
years.
</P>
<P>
   But recent struggles with pneumonia pointed to the coronary
condition, an often slow deterioration of the heart muscle.
</P>
<P>
   Austin lawyer Ed Small said Bullock, whom Small saw a month ago,
told him he was feeling well despite his appearance to the
contrary.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't want anyone to feel sorry for him, that's for
sure,'' Small said.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock, who underwent heart bypass surgery in 1994, had a
pacemaker implanted last fall to correct an irregular heart beat.
He entered the Austin Heart Hospital on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock retired as lieutenant governor in January after serving
eight years in what is considered Texas' most powerful elective
office. A recovering alcoholic and chain smoker, he had one-third
of his right lung removed in 1972 because of nonmalignant tumors,
suffered a heart attack in 1979 and had the bypass operation
shortly before he won his second term in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   His dominion of the Texas Senate as its presiding officer _ and
of Texas politics in the 1980s and '90s _ was shaped by an iron
will and statewide relationships built from 40 years in politics,
either in office as state representative, secretary of state, state
comptroller or in practicing law or in the Austin lobby corps.
</P>
<P>
   Osler McCarthy writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
