<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990614.0445 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5275 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMART-GUNS-ART-1STLD-     06-14 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMART-GUNS-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESSURE GROWS FOR `SMART' GUNS, BUT NONE IS IN SIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to add, in 4th graf, the other five states in which smart-gun
legislation is known to be pending: Conn., Md., R.I., Mass. and
Calif. No other changes.)  (See also CONGRESS-GUNS) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Seven years ago, a group of engineering students at
Johns Hopkins University here was given $2,000 and an assignment:
Build a ``smart'' gun, a gun that could be fired only by its owner.
Using off-the-shelf equipment, the students developed a prototype
that, with wires hanging out of it, was neither attractive nor
practical. But it worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't pretty,'' recalled Stephen Teret, director of the
Gun Policy and Research Center at the Johns Hopkins School of
Public Health. ``But if three undergrads with $2,000 and no gun
experience could make it, it means others could do the same, too.''
</P>
<P>
   That, however, has not proved to be so easy.
</P>
<P>
   In the decade since the idea of a smart gun _ a gun that could
not be fired accidentally by a child or violently by a criminal who
stole it _ came up, it has come to be seen as a quick fix, cited in
lawsuits and in legislatures by gun-control advocates. So far,
legislation requiring that within five years all new handguns be
smart guns is pending before statehouses in at least eight states:
New York, Pennsylvania, New Jersey, Connecticut, Maryland, Rhode
Island, Massachusetts and California. And lawsuits to hold gun
makers financially responsible for not incorporating smart-gun
technology have been filed by New Orleans and 17 other
municipalities.
</P>
<P>
   But as the pressure for smart guns grows, it is becoming
increasingly clear that they may not be the simple fix many
proponents think they are. For one thing, no workable smart gun is
in sight, and as with so much in the national gun debate, its
development is mired in disputes, technological problems and even
questions about whether smart guns are, in fact, really a smart
idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to smart guns, there's no great fix out there
right now,'' said Joshua Horowitz, a lawyer with the Coalition to
Stop Handgun Violence, a gun-control group in Washington.
``Everyone who has looked at it said there is no quick, feasible
way of doing this. For people like us, there's a question of a
balancing point: Would smart guns increase gun sales or would they
save lives? And, from the industry's perspective, no one wants to
do it until they all have to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some gun makers welcome smart guns as a marketing opportunity to
improve sagging handgun sales; other gun makers oppose them as a
first step on a slippery slope toward gun control. Some gun-control
advocates say smart guns could cut down on the thousands of deaths
and injuries caused each year by suicide, homicide and
unintentional shootings. Other gun-control advocates oppose them,
saying smart guns could encourage people who might not have guns to
buy them, increasing the risk of handgun violence.
</P>
<P>
   While the National Rifle Association has officially remained
neutral on smart-gun technology, many of its members have lobbied
against it in various legislative hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Still, interest in smart guns is rising.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first guy to invent an affordable and reliable smart gun
will be a trillionaire,'' said Paul Jannuzzo, general counsel of
Glock, a gun manufacturer in Smyrna, Ga. ``It's absurd to say we're
hiding this technology. Why would someone be hiding it? They'd be a
wealthy person.''
</P>
<P>
   While the debates continue, efforts are under way in Washington
to get more government money for smart-gun research and
development. The National Institute of Justice, a federal agency,
is working with Colt's Manufacturing Co. to develop a prototype
smart gun for law-enforcement officers. A first test model,
developed with $500,000 in government money, is expected to be
delivered this summer. The goal is to cut the number of police
officers killed with their own weapons by assailants, an average of
six to 10 a year, or 10 percent to 16 percent of all police deaths
in the last decade, government statistics show.
</P>
<P>
   Police groups are putting their efforts behind a Clinton
administration budget proposal to spend $4 million on smart-gun
technology. Colt's, along with many members of Congress, is also
seeking up to $40 million in federal grants to develop the
technology, and behind-the-scenes lobbying has already begun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has demonstrated a model that is viable in the
marketplace,'' said Steven Sliwa, chief executive of Colt's.
``We've developed some interesting prototypes with the government,
but they haven't shown the durability and reliability needed to be
commercially viable.''
</P>
<P>
   Colt's lineup of semiautomatic handguns range in price at retail
from about $250 for a .22-caliber target pistol to $813 for its
.45-caliber Combat Commander. The smart-gun technology could add
$300 to $400 to the price of each gun, the company says.
</P>
<P>
   Why all the money for research is needed is simple: It is not
easy to make a smart gun. Essentially, a smart gun is a meshing of
a complicated 19th-century mechanical device, the gun, with
delicate and sophisticated computer engineering. Within the
footprint of an existing gun _ with controlled explosions, heavy
percussions and vibrations, dirty residues and high temperatures _
electronics would be embedded that would have to withstand this
high stress. It is like putting a laptop computer into a gun and
then having that computer decide when the gun will work _ and when
it will not. This is more complicated than what electronics in an
automated teller machine, in car dashboards, or even in missiles,
are asked to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conceptually, yes, smart guns are a great concept,'' said
Richard Roberts, director of special operations at the
International Union of Police Associations, which favors smart-gun
development. ``But from the street officers' level, they'll want
some real assurance that this baby will work.''
</P>
<P>
   Many types of smart guns have been proposed, each with problems.
Some prototypes operate on radio waves that allow a gun to operate
when it receives a signal from an owner's ring, wristband or pin.
But other radio waves can interfere with these signals.
</P>
<P>
   There are also biometric devices like fingerprint or voice
recognition, but those pose problems with accuracy. A report
prepared by Sandia National Laboratories in Albuquerque, N.M., on
smart guns concluded, ``It may take a generation of smart-gun
systems to come and go before a smart gun is not only common but is
favored over a nonsmart gun.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-99 2146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990614.0446 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5276 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-nhl-HNS &LR;      06-14 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-nhl-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL SULLIVAN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
BUFFALO, N.Y. _ He faced 29 shots in Game 3 and ended up on the
losing end of a 2-1 score. So what would Dominik Hasek like to see
when his Buffalo Sabres face the Dallas Stars in today's 7 p.m.
Game 4 of the Stanley Cup Finals at Marine Midland Arena?
<TEXT>
<P>
   More action assuming, of course, that means his teammates are
picking up the pace at the other end, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to stop the puck, whether it's 20 shots or 40
shots,'' Hasek said Monday. ``We have to create more chances. We
have to score more goals.''
</P>
<P>
   And for the Sabres to avoid falling behind three games to one in
the best-of-seven series, The Dominator may have to dominate on an
even grander scale.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he has been bad so far, by any means. The Czech has
kept Dallas very much in check for most of the first three games,
stopping 90 of 96 shots. (The Stars' other goal was an empty-netter
at the end of Game 2.)
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo, however, has scored just six goals against the league's
best defensive team, and so far that hasn't been enough to get the
job done. Before a raucous sellout crowd Saturday night, the Sabres
managed just 12 shots on goal, three each in the first and third
periods.
</P>
<P>
   With its defensemen laying back, Buffalo's front line fizzled on
all eight power-play opportunities, further adding to local
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason our defense didn't want to get involved the
other night,'' Sabres coach Lindy Ruff said Monday. ``It wasn't our
game plan to have them pull out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our success in the first few rounds was because we pinched,
because we got five guys involved. Typically, we didn't give up a
lot, even though we played like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek's brilliance makes that sort of risk-taking not only
possible but profitable. Buffalo, the No. 7 seed in the East, got
to the Stanley Cup Finals by pressing the issue and relying on the
fellow generally considered the greatest goaltender in the world.
</P>
<P>
   In the 15 games leading up to the Finals, Buffalo scored 50
goals. Often as not, the Sabres forced the attack with the
knowledge that the man with the Slinky for a spine could make up
for most of the defensive gaps that sort of strategy might create.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get back to that,'' Ruff said. ``We're going to
harp on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Against Dallas, that aggression has been muted, in part by the
Stars' smothering defense. Buffalo managed to split the first two
games in Texas despite scoring only five goals, but that offense
ground to a halt in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, this is no way to win a Stanley Cup, and the Sabres
realize they will have to get more heat on Stars goalie Ed Belfour
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to win the game,'' Hasek said, ``when you
only have 12 shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering the presence in the other net, that total is
particularly galling. Hasek was Belfour's backup when the two
played together in Chicago, and it has become clear that no love
was lost between them.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his former teammate's relative inactivity in Game 3,
Hasek grimaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's true,'' he said. ``But that's the way the Dallas
Stars play. They play well defensively and block many shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek has stopped most of what he has seen at the other end. He
has done so despite a groin injury that some have reported as a
hernia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I can feel it every day in practice and in games,''
he said. ``Once the puck drops, I don't think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing Hasek and the rest of the Sabres can't avoid pondering
once the puck drops tonight, however, is the make-or-break nature
of this Game 4. Should Dallas win, the Stars would have three
chances to close things out, and they have not lost three
consecutive games all season.
</P>
<P>
   First things first, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be the toughest game of the series,'' Dallas
center Mike Modano said. ``There's no doubt about that in anybody's
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually when you get outplayed on your home ice, there's a
response, a major regrouping.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars, in fact, faced an almost identical situation in the
Western Conference finals against Colorado. After losing Game 1 at
home, Dallas won Game 2, shut the Avalanche out in Game 3 in Denver
and had a chance to take a stranglehold in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars fell behind early in that one, battled back, then lost
in overtime. Coach Ken Hitchcock has made sure to mention the
similarities in the hope that recent history doesn't repeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a wonderful game, a great game,'' he said, ``but our
players felt at the end that we didn't sacrifice enough, we didn't
pay a big enough price.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's already been discussed. We owe ourselves a tremendous
performance in Game 4 because we let ourselves down a little bit in
Colorado.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Sabres gamble to pick up the offensive pace tonight, the
Stars should have their share of chances to redeem themselves.
Hasek knows what likely is coming, but he can still do the math.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to win three out of four games,'' he said. ``We can do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   If The Dominator dominates, anything is possible, as a No. 7
seed still playing for hockey's greatest prize can attest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
