<DOCNO> NYT19990614.0447 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5277 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMART-GUNS-ART-1STLD-     06-14 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMART-GUNS-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BALTIMORE: nonsmart gun.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even so, lawsuits calling for smart guns press on. Many suits
against gun makers have been filed by the same lawyers who sued the
auto industry seeking seat belts and airbags. Unlike the carmakers,
with their deep financial resources and large
research-and-development staffs, the gun industry is a collection
of small, marginally profitable companies _ the combined revenues
of all gun makers is only about $2 billion a year. By contrast,
Ford and General Motors each has revenues of over $140 billion a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Some say the industry is simply waiting for the government to
foot the bill. Steven Morton, chief executive of Oxford Micro
Devices, a semiconductor maker in Newtown, Conn., is working on a
fingerprint-activated gun. But he has yet to find a gun maker to
join him in a venture he estimates will take up to two years and
cost at least $5 million in research.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gun makers tell me they want to wait,'' Morton said. ``They
feel that sooner or later, Congress will put up the money for
research. So they are simply waiting for Congress to pay for
something so they don't have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Mossberg, a vice president at O.F. Mossberg &AMP; Sons, a
gun maker in New Haven, Conn., that is working on a smart gun,
said, ``We'd love to get government funds, but not with strings
attached.''
</P>
<P>
   As a debate rages in Congress over gun-control legislation _ a
measure focusing on who buys guns and how they are sold _ the
efforts to get more money directed to smart-gun technology are
taking place quietly, out of the spotlight. The important word here
is quiet _ no gunmaker or member of Congress wants to alienate the
National Rifle Association. A Washington lobbyist said the first
question asked by many members of Congress when approached about
financing for smart-gun research was, ``Where is the NRA on this
issue?''
</P>
<P>
   Gun makers understand that technology used to develop a smart
gun for law-enforcement officers, whose needs are more specialized
than the average citizen, could later be spun off for a civilian
model. The common notion is that an officer's gun would have to be
more durable, reliable and would be used under more circumstances,
outdoors and inside, in heat and in cold, than handguns used by
civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Because police officers are so skeptical of new equipment _ it
took over 30 years for many police forces to accept
bullet-resistant vests _ a smart gun that passes muster would have
to be an engineering marvel.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're asking cops to take a reliable product and give them a
gun that will be, by definition, less reliable,'' said Daniel
Rosenblatt, executive director of the International Chiefs of
Police. ``But, if you could get a smart gun to work, it would be
one of the most significant developments in the history of
firearms.''
</P>
<P>
   From a business perspective, the law-enforcement market is small
_ there are only about 600,000 police officers in the country _
making it difficult, on a cost basis alone, to justify high
research costs. For gun makers, the real prize is the larger
civilian market, where gun sales have been falling and where a new
product might stop the slide. In 1997, the most recent year for
which statistics are available, 3.7 million firearms were
manufactured in the United States, a sizable drop from 5.2 million
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The story behind the dropoff is the big decline in handgun
sales, falling to 1.4 million in 1997 from 2.8 million units in
1993, in the wake of anti-handgun campaigns and the market's
saturation.
</P>
<P>
   A study from the Johns Hopkins University gun policy center that
appeared in The New England Journal of Medicine last year showed
that 71 percent of adults surveyed favored legislation mandating
personalized guns. Among gun owners, 59 percent favored such bills.
To gun makers, that is a sign of enormous market opportunities. To
some gun-control advocates, that is a sign of enormous problems
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gun industry thinks that smart guns would allow them to
develop additional markets of 60 million new handgun owners,'' said
Kristen Rand, senior counsel at the Violence Policy Center in
Washington. ``If anything close to that would happen, we would see
a significant increase in firearms-related deaths as people get
lulled into a false sense of safety. Smart guns send a message that
handguns can be made safe and there can be magic guns where no good
people will ever be hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   In a few months, more cities are expected to follow New Orleans
and file lawsuits, and more bills are expected to be introduced in
more statehouses. These efforts are being led by the Johns Hopkins
center, whose director, Teret, is a former plaintiffs lawyer who
battled for airbags a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he thinks he can re-create that success.
</P>
<P>
   ``As with cars and airbags, I believe litigation will be most
effective for an industry as intransigent as the gun industry,''
Teret said. ``It's not a question of whether Beretta can afford to
design a smart gun, but whether they can afford to make a gun
without these safety devices.''
</P>
</TEXT>
