<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5278 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STANLEYCUP-SABRES     06-14 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STANLEYCUP-SABRES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sabres aren't in a panic
 &HT;    By Brian Biggane
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ One dominating performance has put the Dallas
Stars in command of the Stanley Cup finals. Another one tonight and
the engraver can start going over the Dallas roster to make sure he
has the correct spelling on names like ``Skrudland'' and
``Nieuwendyk.''
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo coach Lindy Ruff has been telling his players to treat
Game 4 like a Game 7. Center Curtis Brown clearly picked up on the
theme Monday when he called it ``the biggest game of our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   While most reporters seem to agree that Dallas could wrap it up
in two more games, the Sabres were insisting their 2-1 disadvantage
was only a temporary setback.
</P>
<P>
   ``With our goaltending, speed and aggressiveness,'' Ruff said,
``we feel we can climb back in. Being down one game is not the end
of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the two-day layoff between games, Stu Barnes added, ``It may
be good for us. We've had time to step back and take a look.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres also had time to get in a full practice Monday in
which Ruff reviewed a number of changes in the game plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were disappointed with how we played,'' Ruff said. ``But in
the same sense we were leading with five minutes left in the second
period, and played poorly. If we can get back to the way we skated
and handled the puck (earlier in the series), we'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Some areas where the Sabres need _ and expect _ to improve:
</P>
<P>
   Length of shifts: Ruff hopes to keep his players fresher by
limiting shifts to 30-35 seconds, down from 45-50.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a stretch in the first and second periods where the
changes were 2-to-1,'' Ruff said. ``Two of their lines would play
against one of ours. That type of energy took its toll on us, and
cost us (the first) goal when we didn't get off.''
</P>
<P>
   Trade slappers for wristers: Ten Stars blocked 19 shots, far
more than the 12 that wound up on net. Buffalo's game plan is to
create scrambles and finish rebounds, but neither can occur unless
the puck gets through in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent some time working on the wrist shots at the end of
practice,'' Ruff said. ``We've got to find a way to get it
through.''
</P>
<P>
   Wake up Miroslav Satan: Buffalo's 40-goal scorer during the
regular season has eight points in the playoffs _ and none in this
series. His two shots on goal in Game 3 were his first of the
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not looking at him to find a way to score three goals;
that's not going to happen,'' linemate Joe Juneau said. ``He knows
what he can do. He can be real good for us. I think he's going to
be just fine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time Satan steps on the ice he's facing three or four of
their biggest defensemen,'' Ruff said. ``There's no way around
that; you've got to battle through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Get the defense involved: Jason Woolley and Alexei Zhitnik rank
1-2 in Buffalo playoff scoring, but neither played the aggressive,
gambling style in Game 3 they had earlier in the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason our defense didn't want to get involved,''
Ruff said. ``It wasn't in the game plan to have them pull out. Our
success in the first three rounds was because we had five guys
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When they collapse in the defensive zone our forwards don't
have a lot of space,'' Zhitnik said. ``If we get a chance to go in,
we've got to take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Get to more loose pucks: Buffalo has a significant speed
advantage, but careless dump-ins have allowed either goaltender Ed
Belfour or the Dallas defense to gain control before the Sabres'
attack can get organized.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can dump it smarter, and at the right times, to give you a
better chance to get control,'' Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   Relax and enjoy: The combination of youth and playing the first
home game in the finals in 24 years resulted in the Sabres, as
Zhitnik put it, ``squeezing our sticks too tight'' in Game 3. Being
back in their familiar underdog role should make the Sabres a
looser bunch tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the first round on, people were saying we shouldn't be
here,'' winger Geoff Sanderson said. ``That's partly why we've been
so successful and outplayed the other team.''
</P>
<P>
   The disparity in shots and thoroughness of Dallas' win in Game 3
seems to have subdued fans in Western New York. But Ruff and his
gang insist they're as confident as ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were disappointed, there was a letdown,'' Ruff said.
``But if we can go out and win Game 4 we'll get it right back to
that level.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Biggane writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
