<HEADER>
A5279 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STANLEYCUP-STARS-     06-14 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STANLEYCUP-STARS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dallas defense taking control
 &HT;    By Brian Biggane
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ The emerging dominating force in this year's
Stanley Cup finals isn't a scorer or a goaltender. It's a Dallas
defense that confounded and frustrated the Buffalo attack with 19
blocked shots in Game 3 Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said his philosophy doesn't call for
blocked shots as much as it demands defenders to patrol critical
areas around the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're asking our players that nothing gets through, whether
it's blocking with your body, your stick, or just (skating) out
from certain angles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We view that as an offensive tool. (Because) if we can
frustrate the opposition, make them gamble and push harder than
they want to push, we can counterattack quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``From the vantage point of an offensive player,'' defenseman
Daryl Sydor added, ``getting shots blocked is frustrating. Our guys
don't really like to do it; it's more a reaction thing. When you've
got guys who do it really well, you feed off it.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of Dallas' blocked shots came against the Buffalo power
play, which totaled just one shot on goal in eight chances in Game
3. Sabres defenseman Alexei Zhitnik pointed out the Sabres broke
two sticks on a 5-on-3 advantage and were impatient on other
occasions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not frustration, it's just part of the game,'' he said.
``If you're going to be afraid to shoot the puck, nothing's going
to happen. You have to try to make a shot _ a wrist shot, any shot
_ and maybe it'll go through.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabres considering changes: The two-day break between Games 3
and 4 gave Buffalo coach Lindy Ruff time to consider some lineup
changes.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff had been playing Michael Peca, one of the league's top
defensive forwards, against the Mike Modano line, but said he was
likely to send Peca out against Joe Nieuwendyk, who had both Dallas
goals in a 2-1 win Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, Nieuwendyk is their best player, so we'll have to
address that situation,'' Ruff said. ``In all likelihood we'll
address Michael to him, but we still have to worry about Modano.
That's kind of a Catch-22.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruff also was juggling his lines, swapping wingers Joe Juneau
and Geoff Sanderson. If the changes stick, Juneau will play
alongside Curtis Brown and Miroslav Satan while Sanderson will be
paired with Stu Barnes and Brian Holzinger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thinking was Sanderson's speed was opening things up in
the other series,'' Ruff said, ``but Joey's a better puckhandler
and a better passer, so we thought we'd take a look at it. I don't
know if we're going to stick with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Noteworthy: With their AHL team in Rochester having lost 5-1 in
the Calder Cup finals to Providence, the Sabres recalled veteran
left winger Randy Cunneyworth and two rookies, right winger Dean
Sylvester and goaltender Michel Baron.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Biggane writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
