<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PRIZREN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBS FLEE PRIZREN AS ALBANIANS CELEBRATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRIZREN, Yugoslavia _ Serbs left this city in the thousands on
Monday, jeered by ethnic Albanians who then danced on bridges and
cobblestone streets and set about the business of wiping their city
clean of the symbols of the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Men smashed the windows of the Cafe Sfinga, the headquarters for
a prominent Serbian paramilitary leader; a hamburger stand; a
lawyer's office, and a bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   Outside a mosque, working with a wire brush and dishwashing
detergent, two men scrubbed away the yellow spraypaint of a Serb
symbol _ meaning ``only unity can save the Serbs'' _ from a stone
fountain used by Muslims to wash before prayers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a Serbian symbol,'' one of the men, Bahtiar Belloda, 23,
said. ``But this is our house.''
</P>
<P>
   While there were no reports of major violence, Albanians threw
rocks at carloads of departing Serbs. In the early evening _ as
Albanians banged on traditional drums and fired off guns in
celebration _ more than 100 Serbs cowered in a monastery near
downtown, waiting to find a way out of the city.
</P>
<P>
   This may well be the face of a new Kosovo: NATO peacekeepers
patrolled Prizren, as did soldiers from the Kosovo Liberation Army,
which has set up checkpoints and now claims to control most of this
city in southern Kosovo. By early afternoon, there were virtually
no Serbian troops here.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian civilians, fearing revenge from ethnic Albanians, had
gone in large numbers _ no one was sure how many _ and Serbs said
the numbers would only grow.
</P>
<P>
   One man, Bogoljub Spasic, 71, showed a cut on his forehead and a
blackened right eye, saying the Kosovo Albanian rebels had beaten
him on Monday morning as they searched for a gun in his house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I don't have a gun,' and they started to beat me,''
he said. Finally, he said, his wife, Jelica, 69, who was sitting on
her luggage at the monastery, got a gun from a Serbian police
officer and handed it over to stop the beating.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO gave us a guarantee of security, that the KLA would be
demilitarized,'' said a man at the monastery who would only give
his first name, Darko. ``Within two days they are inside the
city.''
</P>
<P>
   All through the night, hundreds of trucks of Serbian soldiers,
and some civilians, rumbled through town _ passing a gruesome
reminder of their defeat, the bullet-riddled car and mangled body
of one of two Serbs shot dead by German peacekeepers on Sunday
night after the Serbs opened fire. The body was finally removed in
the late morning.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday afternoon, NATO officials said that another 300
vehicles left town, ferrying some 5,000 people north toward Serbia.
The civilians left much as the Albanians had left Kosovo over the
last two months: with anything of value that they could carry.
</P>
<P>
   Albanians lined the streets downtown, hurling stones and
screaming: ``Murderers! Thieves!''
</P>
<P>
   Masar Kuksi, a 47-year-old Albanian, recognized his own car
being driven out of town with a Serbian family inside. ``You stole
my car!'' he yelled. But it did not cloud his happiness, a feeling
that spread around the streets here for hours, as Albanians whizzed
around the streets, honking their horns and flashing victory signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nothing _ one car,'' he said. ``They have done worse.''
</P>
<P>
   In the crowd, Kujtim Hashani, a 39-year-old electrician, cheered
the cars out of town. ``We are liberated,'' he said. ``They will
never come back. Kosovo is Albanian.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if all soldiers and civilians alike should leave, he said
there would be a few exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those whose hands aren't bloody can stay,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But how many have bloody hands?
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety percent of them,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
