<SLUG> BC-STAGECOACH-COACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAGECOACH TO BUY COACH USA IN $1.24 BILLION DEAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LAURA GOLDBERG 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Stagecoach Holdings of Scotland has agreed to buy
Houston-based Coach USA, the nation's largest operator of tour,
charter and sightseeing buses, for $1.24 billion in cash, or $42 a
share, company officials said Monday. Stagecoach, an international
bus and train company, also plans to assume $638 million of Coach
USA's debt.
</P>
<P>
   Coach USA's stock, which has closed under 30 since mid-February,
ended the day Monday at 41 3/8, up 2 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our two companies have a shared background of successful
growth by acquisition, and we have found a high degree of
compatibility between the two management teams,'' Brian Souter,
Stagecoach's chairman, said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   For Stagecoach, the deal means its first entry into North
America, while analysts said that for Coach USA it means more money
for acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Evan Smith, an analyst at Sanders Morris Mundy in Houston who
follows consolidators, said the $42 a share price was fair, but
might be a bit on the low end of a fair range.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stagecoach is an accomplished, acquisition-oriented
transportation company just like Coach but on a larger scale,''
Smith said. ``Strategically, it makes sense that the management
teams would get along. Seems like the cultures fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Coleman, a transportation analyst with Banc of America
Securities praised the deal, calling the share offering a very good
price.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives (Coach USA) increased access to capital to keep
growing,'' Coleman said.
</P>
<P>
   During a conference call for investors and analysts, Larry King,
Coach USA's chairman and chief executive, said no layoffs or
changes in Coach USA's operations are planned. King will keep his
current title and will join Stagecoach's board.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very much the platform for Stagecoach's growth in
North America,'' said Keith Cochrane, Stagecoach's finance
director. ``The focus is going to be growth, not cutback.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach USA plans to continue running its business from Houston,
the company said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, I feel it's sad that a foreign company sees the
opportunity more than U.S. investors,'' said Steven Harter,
president of Notre Capital Ventures II, which was the principal
founder of Coach USA.
</P>
<P>
   Harter, on the board of Coach USA since its creation, said there
is a small-cap company malaise among investors.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, he said, was the right thing for shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stagecoach is a great company and they see the opportunity,
and I think it's going to be a great merger,'' Harter said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say there is growth potential in the bus business as
governments privatize services, corporations outsource
transportation needs, and the population ages, creating a bigger
market for tour and charter services.
</P>
<P>
   Coach USA was formed in September 1995 but had no operations or
revenues before May 1996 when it went public. Coach USA, which
began with six companies, has since acquired more than 70.
</P>
<P>
   It operates in Canada and throughout the United States, and
provides commuter transportation, airport shuttle, contract
services for local governments and corporations, and taxi services.
</P>
<P>
   King also said Coach USA was looking to the school bus market as
a growth opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Coach USA, which had 1998 revenues of $803 million, employees
about 12,500 people.
</P>
<P>
   Among its activities, Stagecoach _ which employees 37,000 people
and has annual revenues of roughly $2.5 billion _ operates bus,
train and airport businesses in the United Kingdom; buses and
ferries in New Zealand; and buses in Sweden, Finland, Portugal,
Australia, Hong Kong and China.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
