<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOKIE COLANGELO OUT SIX TO EIGHT WEEKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Anaheim Angels rookie outfielder Mike
Colangelo will miss six to eight weeks because of a torn ligament
in his left thumb, a result of the scary outfield collision he had
with teammate Reggie Williams on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo was examined by hand and wrist specialist Dr. Norman
Zemel on Monday when the tear was discovered. He was placed in a
cast that he'll wear for three weeks before being evaluated.
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo, making his major-league debut Sunday after being
called up Saturday night, was in good spirits after Sunday's game
when it seemed he would be OK. He had been taken off the field on a
backboard because he had upper-back pain, but X-rays of his
cervical spine were normal. He also had X-rays of the thumb, which
were normal.
</P>
<P>
   But while there was no break, there was a tear of the ulna
collateral ligament in the thumb. He did not make the trip with the
team to Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo had three plate appearances Sunday before the
seventh-inning injury. He singled to center, walked and grounded
out. He also had an outfield assist.
</P>
<P>
   Why me?: Manager Terry Collins has been asked numerous times,
and he still doesn't have an answer. The question was asked again
after Colangelo's injury: When you're alone and thinking about
everything that's happened, do you ever ask, `Why me? Why us?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I've asked myself, what can we change? What can we adjust? Is
there something we're missing?'' Collins said. ``But you look at
the injuries we've had, and they're not from a lack of training,
they're from aggressiveness. Every one except (Gary) DiSarcina,
which was a fluke.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put the fences in front of the dugouts, but Mo (Vaughn)
would have went for that ball anyway. And the next time Tim Salmon
has to dive for a ball, he will. Jim Edmonds got his bad shoulder
from crashing into fences. It so happens that our injuries have
cost us a lot of time.''
</P>
<P>
   While DiSarcina is nearing a return, Salmon is a month away and
Edmonds two months. Vaughn is limited to DH duty because of his
tender left ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what anybody else says, they play the game the
right way,'' Collins said. ``They're not going to not dive for
balls, or not slide or not run hard to first base because they're
afraid they're going to a pull a muscle. With situations like this
you say, can we do anything different? Do we train less? Do we
train more? The answer's no. (Injuries) just happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon update: Right fielder Tim Salmon (sprained left wrist)
also was examined by Dr. Zemel and continues to improve. There is
no timetable set for his return.
</P>
<P>
   Percival on a roll: Closer Troy Percival continues to dominate.
With his perfect inning Sunday, Percival has allowed no runs and
only one hit in his past 17 outings (161/3 innings). He's second in
the American League with 18 saves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-99 2157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
