<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5292 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-RDP-NYT &LR;      06-14 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-RDP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT AGREES TO CONSIDER CASE ON AID TO RELIGIOUS SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., Md., N.Y.)  (See also SCOTUS-GAMBLING) 
(mk) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Adding an important religion case to the docket for
its next term, the Supreme Court on Monday agreed to decide whether
the Constitution permits public schools to provide computers and
other ``instructional equipment'' for use in religious school
classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The case challenges a firm line the court drew in a series of
parochial school aid cases in the 1970s _ a line between textbooks,
which public schools were permitted to lend to religious schools,
and all other instructional material, which the court viewed as too
easily placed in service of the parochial schools' religious
mission and therefore impermissible.
</P>
<P>
   Relying on that distinction in a decision last year, the federal
appeals court in New Orleans ruled that the public school system of
Jefferson Parish, La., could not make available to religious
schools within its district computers that it had acquired under a
widely used federal program.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is seeking to expand that program,
part of the Elementary and Secondary Education Act of 1965, to help
provide computers and Internet connections to every classroom in
the country, public and private alike. Unless the lower court
decision in this case is overturned, that goal will be impossible
to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   Under the education act, public schools that receive federal aid
for special services and equipment, including computers, must share
the material on a ``secular, neutral and nonideological'' basis
with students in private schools within the district boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   Supporting the parochial school parents in Louisiana who brought
the Supreme Court appeal, Mitchell vs. Helms, No. 98-1648, the
administration told the justices that if the court's precedents
still require the ``categorical rule'' that the appeals court
applied, then it is time to re-examine those precedents.
</P>
<P>
   The case therefore has clear implications for broader questions
concerning the use of tax dollars for the benefit of religious
institutions in general and schools in particular. Although the
constitutionality of publicly financed vouchers for religious
school tuition is not directly before the court, this case will be
closely watched for indications of what the justices will do when
they eventually accept one of the voucher cases now beginning to
fill the legal pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   The court's approach to the clause of the First Amendment that
prohibits an ``establishment'' of religion has been in flux. Two
years ago, in a case from New York, the court overturned a
precedent and ruled that the establishment clause was not violated
if public school systems sent teachers onto the premises of
parochial schools to teach federally financed remedial classes.
Other recent decisions, including one from 1995 that required the
University of Virginia to underwrite a student religious
publication on the same basis as other publications, have suggested
that the court's longstanding emphasis on church-state separation
is being replaced by a new emphasis on protecting religious
activities and institutions against unequal treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The ferment on the court _ many of the recent cases have been
decided by 5-4 votes _ coincides with a political ferment over the
relationship between religion and government, a combination that is
likely to keep this case in a bright spotlight until the justices
decide it, perhaps as long as a year from now.
</P>
<P>
   The court stepped back from a second church-state dispute
Monday, declining to hear a challenge by a Maryland college
affiliated with the Seventh-day Adventist Church to its exclusion
from a program of state aid to private colleges. The Maryland
Higher Education Commission's conclusion that the program of
Columbia Union College was ``pervasively sectarian,'' and therefore
ineligible for the aid, was upheld by the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals, in Richmond, Va.
</P>
<P>
   While the court on Monday made no comment in turning down the
appeal, Columbia Union College vs. Clark, No. 98-1509, Justice
Clarence Thomas filed a four-page dissenting opinion. He said the
court should ``scrap the `pervasively sectarian' test and reaffirm
that the Constitution requires, at a minimum, neutrality, not
hostility, toward religion.''
</P>
<P>
   The court's other actions on Monday included these:
</P>
<P>
   Federal employees: The court ruled, 5-4, that in deciding
discrimination cases by federal employees against government
agencies, the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission has the
authority to award not only back pay but compensatory damages for
illegal discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, West vs. Gibson, No. 98-238, interpreted the Civil
Rights Act of 1991, which for the first time made compensatory
damages available to discrimination plaintiffs who are successful
in court, whether against a private employer or the government. The
question was whether the new remedy also applied when the
commission, rather than a court, resolved the case.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Stephen Breyer wrote the majority opinion, which was
joined by Justices John Paul Stevens, Sandra Day O'Connor, David
Souter and Ruth Bader Ginsburg. Justice Anthony Kennedy dissented,
joined by Thomas, Chief Justice William Rehnquist and Justice
Antonin Scalia. The dissenters said the federal government had not
waived its sovereign immunity with sufficient clarity to permit the
commission to award damages.
</P>
<P>
   New York death penalty: Without comment, the court turned down
an appeal by the district attorneys in Brooklyn and Rochester,
N.Y., of a ruling last year by New York's highest court that struck
down the plea-bargaining provisions of New York's death penalty
law.
</P>
<P>
   Under the New York law, defendants who plead guilty to capital
murder are safe from execution; they can receive a maximum sentence
of life in prison. But defendants who take their chances by going
to trial can receive a death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Court of Appeals ruled last December that this
system, unusual among death-penalty states, placed an
unconstitutional burden on a defendant's Sixth Amendment right to a
jury trial and Fifth Amendment right against compelled
self-incrimination. The appeals court's decision was based on a
1968 Supreme Court precedent, United States vs. Jackson, which held
that it was unconstitutional to offer a benefit to capital
defendants for pleading guilty and waiving their right to a jury
trial.
</P>
<P>
   In their appeal, Hynes vs. Tomei, No. 98-1533, District
Attorneys Charles Hynes of Brooklyn and Howard Relin of Monroe
County urged the court to overturn that precedent in light of the
much greater role that plea bargaining plays today in the criminal
justice system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-99 2202EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
