<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5296 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPURS-ART-NYT     06-14 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPOVICH AND SPURS WANT VICTORIES NOT VINDICATION 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Just four months ago, the black and silver
juggernaut known as the San Antonio Spurs seemed to be on the verge
of collapse. Greatly talented and expected to contend for a
National Basketball Association championship, the Spurs had a 6-8
record and were in danger of losing more than a playoff spot; their
coach and general manager, Gregg Popovich, was in the kind of
trouble that only Jeff Van Gundy can appreciate.
</P>
<P>
   Popovich's Spurs were too loaded to be foundering, so everyone
was pointing a finger at the coach. Spectators at the Alamodome
were drowning him in boos. Ticket-holders were penning letters of
condemnation to the team's owners. Fans were flooding the phone
lines of sports talk radio with venomous comments. Local columnists
and broadcasters were on the attack. And the Spurs' chairman, Peter
Holt, was reportedly speaking with Doc Rivers about taking
Popovich's place on the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   With the club saying its future in San Antonio was riding on the
public's willingness to finance the building of a new arena, the
probability that Holt would make a coaching change was increasing
with each inexplicable loss. Then, the Spurs drilled the Houston
Rockets by 17 points on the road, and two nights later, the Dallas
Mavericks by 16. Then they defeated the Los Angeles Clippers and
the Denver Nuggets and five other opponents en route to winning
nine straight games.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the calls for Popovich's head disappeared and
eventually turned into praise. All of that has been forgotten in
the euphoria that accompanies a trip to the NBA finals, and
Popovich, 50, has no interest in drumming it up again in a
how-do-you-like-me-now sort of way.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I don't feel vindicated,'' said Popovich, whose team has
gone 42-6 since its 6-8 start and will play host to the Knicks in
Game 1 of the four-of-seven-game finals Wednesday night. ``I don't
think in terms of vindication. I don't think you have a right to do
that. If I think in terms of vindication, I will become a negative
individual.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who correlate negativity with hard-nosed, old-school
coaching tactics already think Popovich has reached that point. At
times, some of his younger players have grown weary of his
authoritarian approach to coaching. But the Spurs' leaders _ David
Robinson, Mario Elie and Avery Johnson _ view Popovich as a leader
and appreciate his assertiveness. In fact, when Popovich's job was
on the line, Johnson addressed some of his teammates, imploring
them to put forth more effort to save their season and their coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel connected to him because he's the guy that brought me
in,'' said Johnson, who was cut by five teams, including the Spurs,
before Popovich brought him back to San Antonio in 1994. ``So I
took it personally when they were talking about him being fired. He
didn't talk much about it, but we listen to the radio and we read
the newspapers, so we knew what was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Elie, in his first year with the Spurs after signing as a free
agent, has an obvious fondness for Popovich, despite his coach's
dogged personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pop stays on us, man,'' Elie said. ``We watch a lot of film.
Lord knows we don't want to lose a game because if we do, we know
we're going to have to sit through a one-hour film session with
Pop. And he'll bring up everything that we did wrong. So the guys
say, `Let's not lose' because we don't want to have to sit through
film with Pop.''
</P>
<P>
   Elie added: ``He's in charge, and we know that. Nobody talks
back to Pop. He doesn't really ride guys. He just makes his point
one time, and the guys accept it and do it because they don't want
to have to hear him say it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Popovich learned his no-nonsense techniques as a student at the
Air Force Academy. After walking on the basketball team as a
freshman, he worked tirelessly on his game to become the club's
captain and leading scorer as a senior. Upon graduation, he toured
Eastern Europe and the Soviet Union with the United States armed
forces team, where he played so well that he earned a tryout for
the 1972 Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   Popovich failed to make the squad and spent the next six years
as an assistant coach at his alma mater before taking a
head-coaching job at tiny Pomona-Pitzer in Claremont, Calif.
Finally, in 1988, he landed a job in the NBA as Larry Brown's
assistant in San Antonio. After four years there, he moved to
Golden State as an assistant under Don Nelson before rejoining the
Spurs as the general manager in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Popovich has revamped the Spurs' roster almost
entirely, with Robinson being the only San Antonio player remaining
from when he took over. When Popovich fired Bob Hill as coach in
1996 _ and named himself as the replacement _ on the day that
Robinson returned from the injured list, he irritated people
throughout the organization.
</P>
<P>
   But now that the Spurs are in the finals _ in part because of
Popovich's off-season acquisitions of the key role players, Elie
and Jerome Kersey _ that too has been forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   And the relieved Popovich, who recently received a vote of
confidence from Holt, is even joking a bit, such as about the
Knicks' short-handedness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry Johnson and Patrick Ewing will both be here on
Wednesday,'' he said with a smile. ``You can't trust those guys
from the big city. If we said guys were hurt, you could trust us.
But both of those guys will probably start and play 37 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
