<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASD-JAPANESE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASD IS EXPECTED TO START TRADING SYSTEM FOR JAPAN STOCKS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Association of Securities Dealers is expected to
announce Tuesday that it will form an electronic trading system
similar to its Nasdaq Stock Market to list and trade Japanese
stocks, securities industry officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The market's structure will be similar to that of the Nasdaq
market, the electronic, dealer-based system that is the world's
second largest behind the New York Stock Exchange. The new venture
will also offer trading of United States companies, the officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's Softbank Corp., which specializes in Internet-related
investments, is expected to be a partner in the NASD venture,
industry officials said. Trading is to begin sometime late next
year.
</P>
<P>
   The NASD, the parent of the Nasdaq market, has been moving to
reorganize itself as a ``market of markets,'' expanding its
presence both in the United States, through its purchase last year
of the American Stock Exchange, and overseas, through joint
ventures with foreign markets.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the association is trying to stem the loss of
business to electronic communications networks, which are
electronic systems that match customer orders and account for more
than one-quarter of all the trading in Nasdaq stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The American Stock Exchange has also faced competitive pressures
as some of its largest stock listings, including Viacom, the
entertainment giant, have defected to the New York exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the Japanese joint venture were expected to be
announced at 8:30 a.m. Tuesday in New York. Frank G. Zarb, chairman
of the NASD, is expected to join in the announcement via video
transmission from Japan.
</P>
<P>
   A Nasdaq spokesman declined to comment Monday on reports of the
joint venture, which initially appeared in Nihon Keizai Shimbun, a
Japanese newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq has already listed shares of 16 Japanese companies on its
market. Those shares trade in the form of American depository
receipts.
</P>
<P>
   But Nasdaq has had a difficult time recruiting Japanese
companies. Since 1984, only one company has joined the market. And
last month, the largest foreign listing on the Nasdaq market, the
Toyota Motor Corp., announced it was moving to the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq and its parent organization have previously aided in the
organization of several overseas markets similar to Nasdaq, with
varying success. Easdaq, a European version of Nasdaq, was
organized in Belgium in 1996, but has listed only 43 companies.
Among them are a few American technology companies, like Xoom.com
and Pixtech.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq also helped in the formation of Ausdaq, an Australian
exchange, and Rasdaq, a Romanian stock exchange. The NASD was
approached in the early 1990's by its counterpart in Japan about
the possibility of creating a Nasdaq-like market, but the venture
was not completed, a Nasdaq official said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Japan Securities Dealers Association set up, by
itself, a market for trading small-cap Japanese stocks. Trading in
those stocks is tracked by what is known as the Jasdaq stock index,
but it has no affiliation with Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear whether Nasdaq will be able to use the Jasdaq
name for its contemplated Japanese joint venture.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq and its parent have recently pursued several other joint
ventures with foreign markets. In December, the NASD and the Hong
Kong Stock Exchange announced the establishment of a working team
to develop broader cooperation on the sharing of technology and
dual listings of stocks. In addition, the exchanges set up an
Internet site to provide information on stocks traded in each
market.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Nasdaq announced that it would open an office in
Shanghai to help recruit companies to a Nasdaq listing and to
provide support for Asian companies whose shares are traded on the
Nasdaq exchange. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
