<HEADER>
A5298 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLENNIUM-FASHION-AR     06-14 1303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRESSING UP THIS NEW YEAR'S EVE? DESIGNERS HOPE SO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Are you tired of hearing about the millennium yet?
</P>
<P>
   It seems the world can be divided into three groups of people
this year: those who don't want to hear the word millennium one
more time, those who are feverishly planning how to celebrate it
and those who anticipate making lots of money from those doing the
celebrating.
</P>
<P>
   Among the people who see dollar signs dancing in their dreams
are retailers who expect to sell scads of party clothes because,
the thinking goes, anyone going to a ``Happy New Year 2000'' party
will want to wear something special. There may be shortages of
champagne, caviar or hotel rooms, but there is no danger that there
will be a dearth of party clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Stores are asking designers for evening dresses, and designers
are whipping them up. The resort-holiday collections being shown
this month for delivery in October, November and December are
geared as much to holiday finery as to beach wear. The problem is
that most of the styles, rather than pointing the way to a new
century, could have been shown almost any year. For many designers,
inspiration came not from the future, but from the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of holiday north, holiday south,'' said Donna Karan,
who is calling her new collection Celebration 2000. It ranges from
a gauzy silver-shot full silk skirt in pale yellow, coral or white
(updated with a tube top) to a short black strapless dress
glittering with beads that would suit a modern-day flapper.
</P>
<P>
   As a nod to today, she based many styles on jersey tubes or
T-shirts, then layered tulle sprinkled with beads over them for
resort outings or added beaded fringe for dancing the centuries
away at a gala in town. And how about a crystal-beaded apron to tie
on over just about anything instead of wearing jewelry? It might be
just the thing for someone fearful of traveling with the real
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kors has given a lot of thought to this holiday season,
which he expects to start as early as October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our customers are talking about it already,'' he said. ``I
think even people who never, never want to go out New Year's Eve
will want to go out. I'm doing a lot of take-away clothes, but
dressy for evening. Even in the most casual resorts, this year
they'll dress. And people will be going to cities as well as to
resorts. You're going to have people coming to New York and people
going to Sydney, Australia, to London, to Paris, to Hong Kong.''
</P>
<P>
   His signature collection has youthful styles like packable
strapless dresses of paper taffeta with smocked tops. He's done
them short, in celadon, and long in black. ``You don't want to wear
something uptight and old-fashioned,'' Kors said, ``and this year
you don't want something that doesn't pack.''
</P>
<P>
   So he has also provided an off-the-shoulder silk sweater that
can be worn with shorts for day and with a long skirt for evening.
And white satin jeans with a beaded stretch tank in platinum gray.
``Platinum for the millennium,'' he explained. But the
quintessential Michael Kors look is a simple white taffeta shirt
worn with black pants discreetly scattered with jet beads.
</P>
<P>
   The line Kors designs for Celine is more glamorous, with a bare
black halter dress he calls ``the ultimate bathing suit dress''
because the top is cut like a swimsuit. There's also a pareo dress
that looks like a long scarf tied halter-style around the neck,
with long silk fringe dripping from the hem. (A lot of designers
are gung-ho for fringe.) For resorts, the scarf-dress comes in
coral; for cities, in black with jet beads. Also in the scarf mode
is a one-shoulder poncho in jet-encrusted black georgette, shown
with black stretch pants.
</P>
<P>
   ``People wear a lot of color at resorts,'' he said, ``but if
you're packing four or five evening things, you'll pack some black
along with the color.''
</P>
<P>
   Calvin Klein used fabrics like washed satin, ribbed silk or
paperlike cotton and double-layered stretch organza for long,
flowing skirts worn with tops that bare the arms and shoulders.
Thin fabrics are layered or embroidered tone-on-tone or given a
sprinkling of sequins. Colors range from white to peaches and pinks
he describes as ``face-powder colors, just pale washes of color.''
</P>
<P>
   Although most styles are geared to evenings at resorts, someone
might adapt a sequined white camisole for city wear by teaming it
with a dark skirt instead of a white one and wrapping up in a big
stole.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Lauren's collection focuses on resort wear but includes
dressy clothes for parties in the city. Sexy jerseys come in black
and white or shades of blue taken from the colors of the Caribbean
sea and sky.
</P>
<P>
   A halter dress with skinny straps that crisscross in back comes
in black or white. A cropped halter top that wraps and ties in
front and that is paired with a low-riding bias-cut skirt comes in
azure. A black and white beaded georgette tube, shown with black
jersey pants, defies geography, but a multicolored fringed skirt of
Indian beadwork would probably look at home only in the tropics.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to color, Carolina Herrera is all for it. ``I
think the millennium is about color,'' she said, gesturing toward a
rack glowing with orange, turquoise and red evening wear.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are pieces to mix, like this turquoise beaded top with
an orange skirt,'' she said, ``or this striped top in turquoise,
white and tan to mix with anything.''
</P>
<P>
   There are also long dresses with beading, either etching a
discreet border around the neckline or forming an all-over floral
design. And Ms. Herrera has provided two-toned bravura stoles that
reverse from pashmina to taffeta to add a touch of drama to any
event.
</P>
<P>
   The dresses are very slim or have full taffeta skirts that
billow gracefully but can be folded almost flat for packing. A navy
blue taffeta is dark enough for a city ball yet has a sliplike top
that is bare enough for southern climes. It looks rather like a
1950's prom dress without the boning and crinolines.
</P>
<P>
   The versatility of being suitable for wearing in the north or
south is the ideal many designers strove for. Another common thread
is full skirts, either gently flared or ballgown-wide, perhaps
signifying a yearning for a more romantic era. Oscar de la Renta's
collection includes a strapless paper taffeta dress in a muted
plaid of rose, blue, pink and wine with fullness in back, ending in
a train, and a ballgown skirt of yellow and blue plaid taffeta that
is poufed up in front and, for a modern touch, shown with a yellow
silk sweater.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership of Mark Badgley and James Mischka is known for
beaded columns but has expanded the repertory to include
full-skirted ballgowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been doing a lot of trunk shows,'' Mischka said, ``and
women are all looking for that great dress. Last week in Seattle we
sold nine elaborate $10,000 gowns. People are taking the millennium
parties very seriously. So for this collection we focused on things
that are right for resort and right for New York, going into
spring.''
</P>
<P>
   He described an iridescent pink taffeta dress with an A-shaped
skirt and a train as ``in between slinky and ballgown.'' But a
Wedgwood blue and cream striped taffeta embroidered with white
beads and crystals on the strapless bodice has a bouffant skirt
worthy of a ball at Tara.
</P>
<P>
   A nostalgic spirit has struck much of the fashion world at the
end of a century that has seen tremendous progress in science and
society. Does anyone really expect the Y2K bug to send the world
back to 1900?  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-99 2211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990614.0461 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5299 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-NYT &LR;      06-14 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LONDON FINANCIER SEEMS TO HAVE HELPED MILOSEVIC ACCEPT ACCORD
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ A British financier, acting with the knowledge of the
German and Finnish governments, held secret negotiations with
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic that appear to have helped
Milosevic reconcile himself to the peace agreement announced on
June 3, German and Swedish officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Castenfelt, a London investment banker with close ties to
the Russian government, secretly entered Serbia on May 29 and
remained in Belgrade until June 4, they said. He met with Milosevic
before Martti Ahtisaari, the president of Finland and the European
Union envoy, arrived on June 2 for conclusive talks with Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   After his meeting with Milosevic in a garden in central
Belgrade, Castenfelt was taken to a bunker in the city where he
drafted a memorandum that laid out the positions on which the West
would not shift and those on which some negotiation was possible,
the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The memorandum was taken to Mr. Milosevic by his chief of
security,'' a person with intimate knowledge of the visit said.
``It proved decisive, and opened the way to the quick accord with
Mr. Ahtisaari.''
</P>
<P>
   The involvement of Castenfelt, who has helped steer Russia
toward accords with the International Monetary Fund, was first
reported on Monday in The Financial Times.
</P>
<P>
   His role _ which the officials said was also known to the United
States _ reflected a concern among some top Russian officials that
Russia's Balkan envoy, Viktor Chernomyrdin, was not making headway,
and a feeling in the German and Finnish governments that a ``back
channel'' could be useful.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, Western governments vowed throughout the 11-week
NATO bombardment that there would be no negotiation with Milosevic.
Castenfelt's involvement was therefore potentially embarrassing.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Steiner, the chief diplomatic adviser to German
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, said he met with Castenfelt twice _
on May 26, three days before the secret mission, and on June 7,
after his return. But Steiner said the only purpose of the meetings
was to gather information and to exchange views, insisting that
Castenfelt's visit made little difference to the diplomatic
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``What led Mr. Milosevic to accept our terms was two things,''
Steiner said. ``First, the growing toll of an increasingly powerful
NATO bombardment. Second, the fact that he realized that Russia
would not give up its ties to the West to save him.''
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James Rubin dismissed the notion that
Castenfelt played a critical role in bringing Milosevic to heel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic didn't need a secret meeting to know what the NATO
conditions were,'' Rubin said. ``He could have watched TV. So there
was no channel that provided critical information on what he needed
to do. The idea that he changed his position through these
discussions is sheer and utter nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   But Karl Kaiser, who was the foreign affairs adviser to
Schroeder during his election campaign, said, ``Mr. Castenfelt
played a central role in showing Milosevic how the accord could be
made to look better than what was offered at the Rambouillet peace
talks.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's refusal to sign the accords reached at Rambouillet,
France, led directly to the NATO air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser, who arranged the meetings with Steiner, and Castenfelt
first met and discussed the Kosovo war at a meeting of the
East-West Institute, a research organization, in Berlin on April 9
and 10, just over two weeks after the bombing began. John Kornblum,
the American ambassador to Germany, was also present.
</P>
<P>
   Castenfelt, who once worked for the Dillon Reed investment
banking firm, and now owns a London financial company, Archipelago
Enterprises, is close to Chernomyrdin and is trusted by Russian
President Boris Yeltsin, the officials said. He declined to be
interviewed for this article.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser said that while it was clear that Serbian forces would
have to withdraw from Kosovo and that NATO forces would have to be
allowed to deploy there under any settlement, the timing of these
moves and their link to a halt in NATO bombing were more flexible.
Examining the statement by the Group of Seven industrialized
nations in early May, in which Russia and the West first outlined
terms for a settlement, Kaiser and Castenfelt saw other points that
could be used in discussion with the Serbian leader.
</P>
<P>
   The first was that Yugoslavia's sovereignty over Kosovo was
reaffirmed. The second was that a call for a review of Kosovo's
status after three years, which was in the Rambouillet plan, was
not explicitly in the Group of Seven statement.
</P>
<P>
   The third was that the composition of the ``international
force'' in Kosovo was partly open to discussion. And the fourth was
that the force would arrive under a United Nations mandate, unlike
the NATO presence called for at Rambouillet.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The officials said that Castenfelt's visit was arranged by
senior Russian military officials, who made contact with
Milosevic's military and security entourage in Belgrade. He flew to
Sofia, crossed the Bulgarian border at Gradina, was picked up by
Serbian security officials and driven to Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   He stayed at the Inter-Continental Hotel. Milosevic, officials
said, met the financier in a garden. The meeting lasted about two
hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was extraordinary how little Milosevic seemed to know
before the memorandum and the talks clarified things,'' an official
said. ``He really seemed in the dark about NATO's thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   What is clear is that for whatever reason, the Yugoslav leader
decided to accept the terms presented by Ahtisaari and Chernomyrdin
with remarkable speed when they met him on June 2.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Steiner said it was absurd to suggest that Milosevic had in any
way secured a better deal than he would have had at Rambouillet.
``To begin with,'' he said, ``Rambouillet allowed for a substantial
Serbian security presence in Kosovo, whereas now all Serbian
soldiers and police have been obliged to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   But a person involved with the mission said, ``What we basically
did was to pre-sell the agreement, and that is exactly the way it
worked out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
