<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEIDNER-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION LOSES A TRUE ESTHETIC EYE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CATHY HORYN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The death of David Seidner last week in Miami Beach brought an
end to a talent that was far too individual, far too stubborn and
classically obsessed to be conventionally successful, though he
was. Rarely has a modern-minded photographer, whose work appeared
regularly in the pages of fashion magazines and who poured out a
steady stream of books and advertising images for clients like
Revlon and Yves Saint Laurent, soared so freely while having one
foot planted in the clay of the Greeks.
</P>
<P>
   Seidner, born in Los Angeles in 1957, combined a free-thinking
California character with the Old World esthetic life he discovered
in Paris at age 19, and developed into an original photographer.
``His infatuation with French intellectual society, which always
blended with the fashion world, did color his eye,'' said the
writer Bob Colacello, who met Seidner in the late 1970s. Initially,
</P>
<P>
   Colacello, who was then an editor of Interview, was put off by
what he said were Seidner's attempts to control every aspect of how
his work was used.
</P>
<P>
   Friends, who are organizing a memorial service for Seidner, who
had AIDS for 15 years and was 42 when he died, invariably describe
him as a kind of head-to-toe esthete, someone who quoted
philosophers, collected Jean-Michel Frank furniture and wore
vintage Gucci loafers, typically with skinny moleskin trousers.
Certainly, in the lush, freewheeling era of Paris in the late
1970s, Seidner had no trouble making connections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, David was a very precocious kid,'' said Tom Fallon, a
former executive at Bill Blass, who hired Seidner to shoot the
designer's advertisements, which he did for 10 years up until his
death. ``You couldn't help but respond to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Colacello added, ``If you were young and attractive and out at
night, eventually you met someone who said, `You must meet Yves.'''
Seidner not only met Yves, but also went on to produce some of the
most enduring advertising images for the house of Saint Laurent _
indeed, for any fashion house.
</P>
<P>
   Seidner's contemporary subjects were often portrayed in
historical mode _ the Miller sisters, most famously, when they
appeared in Vanity Fair in 1995 as if full-blown from the brush of
Boldini. Yet somehow the images looked modern. ``His style had
nothing to do with what was trendy or of the moment,'' said Robert
McElroy, Seidner's agent for many years. ``It was very contrary.''
</P>
<P>
   But then, there was an essential contradiction in Seidner. ``To
many magazine editors,'' said George Cortina, the stylist who
worked on the Miller sitting, ``David was too much of an artist,
and yet the artist himself didn't think he was enough of one. He
didn't fit perfectly in one world or the other. He was sort of an
abyss unto himself.''
</P>
<P>
   A perfectionist, Seidner was famous for having his subjects pose
for hours under intense lights (``like a hot day at the beach,
times 2,'' Cortina said), while orchestrating every millimeter of
movement _ from the tilt of a head to the tiniest fold of fabric.
He also tried to exert extraordinary control over his images, even
how they were presented on the page.
</P>
<P>
   For a series of Sargent-inspired portraits that appeared last
year in Vanity Fair, he photographed 17 subjects, exhausting
himself and nearly everyone else. ``Believe me,'' said David
Harris, Vanity Fair's art director, ``the Sargent shoot brought
everyone to their knees.''
</P>
<P>
   Graydon Carter, the magazine's editor in chief, added with a
laugh: ``He shot my wife and daughter. It took so long, they were
older at the end of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Muriel Brandolini, a decorator who was a close friend of
Seidner, said it was particularly difficult for a man of Seidner's
esthetic sensitivity to witness his own physical decline. ``He'd
say, `I look so bad,''' Mrs. Brandolini recalled. ``It was a
contradiction. Here he was creating beauty and, at the same time,
seeing his own face change in the mirror.'' She suggested that this
frustration, combined with his exigent nature, had the effect of
turning his personality into a wedge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved David,'' Mrs. Brandolini said, ``but he harmed himself
with his hardness toward himself and others.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last months of his life, Seidner had sold most of his
possessions, including his beloved Frank furniture, and had gone to
live in Miami Beach. In a corner of his ocean-front apartment, in a
space not larger than four feet square, he began photographing
orchids. It was all he could manage, but he made dozens of images
of those flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks before he died, Cortina said, Seidner told him, ``I
cannot take the sort of pictures I want to take any more, because
they have killed me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
