u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-NYT &LR;      06-14 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME REFUGEES SLIP BACK INTO KOSOVO DESPITE DANGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ Ignoring warnings about land mines and armed
Yugoslav troops, several hundred returning refugees slipped back
through the closed border into Kosovo on Monday by taking a
dangerous path on a wooded mountainside as periodic gunfire rang
out in the hills.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear who was firing the shots, although aid
organizations speculated that they came from members of the Kosovo
Liberation Army, the rebel group that fought Yugoslav forces in
Kosovo, to warn the refugees to go back for their own safety.
</P>
<P>
   But a member of the rebel group _ which intervened on Sunday at
the main border crossing to help enforce the closing, and which
still occupies the border itself with the apparent assent of NATO
and the Albanians _ said the firing came from local people in
Albania shooting their guns into the air for recreation.
</P>
<P>
   Not enough Kosovo Albanians were returning to create the
``nightmare scenario'' of a rush back home by hundreds of thousands
of refugees who were expelled from Kosovo this spring by the
Yugoslavs. But Rupert Colville, a spokesman for the U.N. high
commissioner for refugees, called it a ``mini-nightmare'' because
of the danger of land mines and, at least until midday, hundreds of
armed Yugoslav troops who swarmed over the road just a few miles
inside the Kosovo border.
</P>
<P>
   The border opened chaotically Sunday to the news media and aid
agencies for the first time since the crisis began. Refugees were
largely kept from re-entering by the German NATO forces controlling
the Kosovo side of the border. A number of refugees got in during
the confusion, but more than 200 refugees, mostly men wanting to
check on their houses and families, were held back.
</P>
<P>
   In their frustration, the refugees climbed over a railing to get
on a bridge that led them right up to the barbed-wire roadblock
into Kosovo, where they clamored to the German troops to let them
go back home. Aid workers say the mood got increasingly ugly until
late in the day, when rebel fighters effectively pushed the
refugees back. Since then, the rebels have controlled the middle of
the bridge, the actual border line, in between the Albanian police
on the Albanian side and the German soldiers on the Kosovo side.
</P>
<P>
   Monday at 6 a.m., the Germans closed the border into Kosovo to
the news media, citing the nearby Yugoslav troops and the shooting
deaths of at least two German journalists on Sunday in Kosovo. Then
they re-opened it at noon after they said the Yugoslavs had moved
on.
</P>
<P>
   But in a repeat of what happened on Sunday, more than 200
refugees _ some of whom could see their houses from the border _
turned up and were denied entry. Impatient, many headed up a
hillside path that crosses over into Kosovo, in partial sight of
the Germans, the rebels and the Albanians. The U.N. refugee agency
estimated their number at ``several hundred'' over the course of
the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``They go on the mountains here, and we can't do anything,''
said Sgt. Christian Schuh, a German soldier at the border post. But
twice Monday, he said, he had seen rebel fighters go after refugees
once they reached the Kosovo side of the road and bring them back.
</P>
<P>
   Aid workers spent fruitless hours Sunday and Monday trying to
persuade the refugees at the border that it was still dangerous to
go home, particularly to villages where there could be land mines
in the fields and booby traps left in houses. Colville, the refugee
agency spokesman, said a land mine was discovered on Sunday only
six feet from the road at the border post.
</P>
<P>
   Ferit Saramati, 37, of the village of Dobrush, was one of those
waiting Monday morning to cross the border, even though he admitted
he was afraid of land mines. But he said he was not afraid of
Yugoslav troops. ``I know they are not there anymore,'' he said.
``We know that our village is empty.''
</P>
<P>
   At 10 a.m., a German soldier told the refugees through a
bullhorn to have patience. ``Wait a little bit,'' he said in
German, which was then translated into Albanian. ``The way you are
going through the mountains is very dangerous, and we can't give
you protection.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was no evidence of a coming mass exodus of Kosovo
Albanians at the refugee camps here Monday night. At the camp run
by Doctors Without Borders, for example, refugees played
volleyball, did laundry and kept up with NATO's advance into Kosovo
on their radios.
</P>
<P>
   Shaip Pllana, 40, a laboratory technician from northern Kosovo,
said he knew that German journalists had been killed on Sunday.
``When it's possible to go back, we'll go back,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-99 2224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990614.0468 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5311 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN     06-14 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE THINGS HURT DODGERS IN BIG WAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Dodgers tried to shake things up
when they fired pitching coach Charlie Hough. However, a 7-10
record is not what they had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   They've held team meetings, they've made changes in the lineup
... and still the team is struggling to win.
</P>
<P>
   It may be June and there are still 101 games remaining, but the
Dodgers are learning talent and coaching changes don't make an $80
million team better.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have the ability _ any team with Kevin Brown, Raul
Mondesi, Gary Sheffield, Eric Karros and Jeff Shaw is talented _
they just aren't doing the little things or the right things.
</P>
<P>
   It's why the Dodgers are 29-32 and why they were seven games out
of first place Monday. Los Angeles was 3{ games out of first when
Hough was fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frustrating isn't the word for it,'' Dodgers catcher Todd
Hundley said. ``It's a combination of things going wrong all at one
time. We have to, as a group, find a way to turn it around. We play
with a certain sense of urgency, and maybe it's too urgent. Maybe
(we put) too much pressure on ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' best chance at winning has been when Brown pitches.
In fact, it's been their only chance at winning lately. Brown, who
starts tonight when the Dodgers open a season-long, nine-game
homestand with the first of three against the Pittsburgh Pirates,
is the only starter to win in June. He's done it twice.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have three wins this month, losing three straight,
six of seven and nine of 12. Lately, their inability to get the
clutch hit, or make the key pitch, is overshadowed by their lack of
concentration.
</P>
<P>
   ``With what was said before the season, and the statements made,
teams are going to come after you much harder,'' Sheffield said.
``Management, they expect (us to win), and we have to perform. You
have to ask, is this the best team it could be?''
</P>
<P>
   If so, the next month might be worse than the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers may have former Gold Glove winners and all-stars at
nearly every position, but they've been shown time and again, by
Pittsburgh and Oakland and Florida and just about everyone else,
that attention to detail counts.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have failed to move runners over, let alone
hit-and-run. They don't take pitches _ they're ninth in the
National League in walks (295) and 10th in on-base percentage
(.339). Their batting average is 13th (.265) out of 16 teams,
forcing them to rely on the stolen base. They've been caught
stealing 27 times, third most.
</P>
<P>
   It all adds up to a team 12th in the league in runs scored, and
everyone knows you have to score to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stretches where we've been good, we've been hitting home
runs ... to tie the game,'' Hundley said. ``Fundamentally, it's
been tough. It hasn't been consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' problems aren't entirely offensive. They've
committed 47 errors, which have led to 32 unearned runs, third most
in the NL behind budget ballclubs Pittsburgh and Montreal. They
consistently miss cutoffs, and on some odd occasions, cut the ball
off when it should go through.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to play the game better, do the little things, play
better defense,'' said Dodgers third baseman Adrian Beltre, who
leads the team with 13 errors. ``We're not playing good defense
right now, especially myself.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's also the pitchers, particularly starters not named
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Chan Ho Park and Ismael Valdes have been erratic, Darren
Dreifort wild and Carlos Perez has been terrible. As a staff, the
Dodgers are tied for 11th worst with 237 walks, or 3.86 per nine
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, the pitchers don't hold runners on well and the catchers
don't throw runners out.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Davey Johnson called a team meeting before Sunday's 9-3
loss to Oakland, which featured the A's scoring five times with one
ball hit out of the infield _ and that was a pop up second baseman
Eric Young lost in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth inning, a shining example of what Dodgers baseball is
at this time, featured three walks, a hit batter to force in a run
and a strikeout-wild pitch that allowed two runs to score on
Hundley's throwing error.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll survive,'' the usually unflappable Johnson said. ``We'll
be all right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
