<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBIAN RETURNEES REVEL IN JUST BEING ALIVE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NIS, Yugoslavia _ Yugoslav soldiers leaned out of a civilian
bus, waving and whooping noisily, as it swept down the main street
bringing them back to this Serbian town Monday. People out
strolling in the warm evening on the main square looked up and
waved back.
</P>
<P>
   This town, home to the 3rd Army, which has done the bulk of the
fighting in Kosovo over the last year, has been welcoming its
troops home for several days now. Soldiers in camouflage fatigues
are everywhere, downing beers in the outdoor cafes and strolling
around town, overwhelmingly relieved to be back.
</P>
<P>
   After dark Monday the streets resounded with car horns blaring
and people whistling and shouting. ``I am very happy it's over,''
said one bearded reservist walking along the street. ``I got back
yesterday and now I've been told I can go home. It was difficult,
but we survived.''
</P>
<P>
   Relief is still the main feeling. Both soldiers and civilians
are just grateful the bombing has stopped, said Zoran Zivkovic,
mayor of Nis and an opposition party leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it will be a matter of minutes and hours for most people
to remember all the problems they had before the war and which have
been multiplied by the war,'' he said in an interview in his
office. ``Problems of basic living needs, economic survival and how
to support their families.''
</P>
<P>
   President Slobodan Milosevic, apparently in an effort to scotch
brewing public dissatisfaction, made a rare appearance Monday, his
first since the start of the NATO bombing. He went to the northern
city of Novi Sad to inaugurate the reconstruction of one of its
destroyed bridges.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech by the ruined bridge, he urged people to rally to
the task of rebuilding.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest 11 weeks since World War II are behind us,'' he
said. ``Now that we have peace again, new tasks await us. These are
to rebuild our country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish our country and our people a fast recovery,'' he added,
vowing to rebuild the bridge in 40 days.
</P>
<P>
   In Nis, Zivkovic was dismissive of Milosevic's speech. The
bridge is only one of 39 that will have to be rebuilt, he added,
and the country has no money. He estimated that in Nis alone, it
would cost $100 million to $200 million to rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   The president has until the end of the summer, while the weather
is good, to sort out the country's most pressing problems, Zivkovic
said. And he will not be able to do that without foreign aid and
investment, Zivkovic asserted, adding that he hoped other nations
would not isolate Serbia further and create ``another Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   The country experienced great tension and trauma during the
bombing, he said, and like the survivor of a car accident, is now
living in the euphoria of just being alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a high chance of being killed and you survive,''
Zivkovic said. ``After that, for a time, you feel lucky. But that
feeling dissipates and you start to realize that you have worse
problems than before.''
</P>
<P>
   The people of Nis, who had been among the most fervent
supporters of democratic change and Western policies, have buried
34 civilians, he said _ casualties of NATO. Among them were 11
killed when cluster bombs hit a market on May 7.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly for the moment, the soldiers in Nis are still feeling
lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are happy we survived, that we are alive,'' said a
20-year-old conscript who would give his name only as Nikola,
sitting in a cafe with two fellow soldiers. They arrived back from
Kosovo three days ago from their antiaircraft unit and have spent
much of the last two months hunkered down in trenches in the woods
in western Kosovo, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is good to see civilization after three months,'' said
another soldier, Dragos, also 20, taking a long pull on his beer.
The two said they were counting the days until their year of
military service was up. ``We are in double digits now,'' said
Dragos, meaning fewer than 100 days.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing they did was to call their families and
girlfriends, they said. ``They were happy,'' Dragos said. ``They
had not heard from us for three months, they didn't know if we were
alive or not.'' Afterward the soldiers hit the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not want this,'' said Nikola, gesturing to encompass
the war, the NATO bombing and the whole issue of Kosovo. ``We enjoy
sitting in cafes and chatting. But it was the bad policy of our
side _ they failed to solve it in a peaceful way. So NATO bombed
us.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Dragos said that as a child, he had wanted to be a soldier,
``but now, no way.'' Nikola, who said he had trained to be a
mechanic, insisted that he would never choose a military career,
despite the army's attempts to persuade conscripts to become
professional soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The two were initially reticent when asked if friends had been
killed in Kosovo. Fighting their emotions, they revealed that they
had lost several, both in the NATO strikes and in Kosovo Liberation
Army attacks.
</P>
<P>
   They changed their tone then, saying they were proud to have
defended their country against the most powerful alliance in the
world. And thinking about their friends who had died, they said it
had been worth fighting to keep Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   As conscripts, they saw the streams of Albanians being expelled,
but said they had played no part in the purging. As to fighting the
rebels, they said that although they had not taken part in any
offensive, their positions had often been attacked.
</P>
<P>
   Yet they seemed to doubt whether the peace deal struck last week
was better than that offered in March, before the bombing began.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am happy it has ended,'' Dragos said, ``but it could have
ended this way three months ago.''
</P>
</TEXT>
