<SLUG> BC-DYNEGY-ILLINOVA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DYNEGY, ILLINOVA TO MERGE IN $2 BILLION DEAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JENNIFER WALSH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Dynegy agreed on Monday to a $2 billion merger with
Illinova, an Illinois electric and gas company, giving the
energy-marketing firm electric plants and lines in major Midwest
markets.
</P>
<P>
   The new company, which will be called Dynegy and will be based
in Houston, will have total revenues of about $17 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The merger will broaden the combined firms' energy-trading
strategies and will allow two large shareholders to follow through
on plans to reduce their stake in Dynegy, company officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It creates tremendous opportunities for the new company more
quickly than either company could have achieved on its own,'' said
Chuck Watson, chairman and chief executive officer of Dynegy.
Watson will run the combined company as chairman and CEO.
</P>
<P>
   The combined assets from both companies is expected to lower
costs and allow Illinova to be more competitive in its marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives us the opportunity to access lower-priced electricity
in other markets that Dynegy is already involved in,'' said David
Butts, senior vice president of Illinois Power, a subsidiary of
Illinova, based in Decatur, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction follows a trend of combining different types of
energy in the electric industry.
</P>
<P>
   Houston-based Enron Corp. bought Portland General Corp. in
Portland Ore., while Houston-based Reliant Energy, which owns
electric and natural gas companies, has expanded into trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this merger, the combined company becomes one of the few
players in the energy industry that possesses resources in energy
marketing and trading and power generation,'' Watson said. ``We're
confident this thing is going to be a company that will be a real
force in energy convergence.''
</P>
<P>
   Layoffs are expected in overlapping administrative positions for
about 5 percent of the combined work force of about 6,500.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Dynegy fell by 7/16 to close at 18 1/4 on Monday.
Illinova rose by 5/16 to close at 25 5/8.
</P>
<P>
   Dynegy enters the transaction as the larger company with sales
of $14.3 billion in 1998. Illinova had sales of $2.43 billion in
1998. When the deal is completed, Dynegy's shareholders will own
slightly more than 50 percent of the new company.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company can now produce 15,000 megawatts of energy,
which can light about 1.5 million residential homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not too big, but more than what they were,'' said John
Olson, energy analyst for Sanders Morris Mundy, adding that the
amount makes up about 2 percent of the country's market.
</P>
<P>
   The merger also provides an option for Britain's BG PLC and
Canadian chemical company Nova Corp. to sell their combined 50
percent stake in Dynegy for about $645 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like a solid transaction on both counts,`` Olson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors in Dynegy will get either $16.50 in cash or 0.69 of
the new share, while Illinova shareholders will swap their shares
with the merged company's shares. The deal acquires Illinova's
$2.25 billion debt and will include an $85 million termination fee.
</P>
<P>
   While this allows two long-term shareholders to exit, Chevron
Corp. will be upping its stake in Dynegy.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco-based company, which owns 29 percent of
Dynegy, announced it will take all stock in the deal and invest
$200 million to $240 million in the new company.
</P>
<P>
   ``This company (Dynegy) is in a growing area with
deregulation,'' said Mike Libbey, spokesman for Chevron, the
nation's fourth-largest oil company. ``It's got a centralized
energy in marketing and sales. We think Dynegy is positioned to
take advantage of that growth.''
</P>
<P>
   The transaction will be complete once Illinova sells a
nuclear-fueled power station in Clinton, Ill. Illinova currently is
in talks with Philadelphia-based Peco Energy Corp. to buy the plant
by the end of the year. Peco is currently managing the plant and
assuming maintenance and operating costs in an interim agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction is expected to be completed in March 2000, after
approval from the Securities and Exchange Commission, the Federal
Energy Regulation Committee, and the Illinois Commerce Commission.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
