<SLUG> BC-SENATE-AIDES-PORN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE AIDES ARE DISCIPLINED FOR SEX IMAGES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A few Senate aides downloaded some pornography to
their computers recently, probably with the expectation that their
actions would remain private. And so they might have, if their
data-gathering from the Internet had been less exhaustive.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, they collected enough material to foul up the
computer system in their boss' office. Their boss is Sen. James
Inhofe, a conservative Oklahoma Republican, who, it is safe to
assume, was not amused.
</P>
<P>
   Inhofe's chief spokesman, Gary Hoitsma said the aides, who
apparently violated a Senate regulation against downloading
pornographic or obscene materials, had been disciplined. But the
Capitol Hill newspaper Roll Call, which reported the episode
Monday, noted that Hoitsma declined to provide details ``in
deference to legitimate privacy concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Roll Call commented that the concern for privacy was ``odd''
given Inhofe's opposition to the appointment of James Hormel as
ambassador to Luxembourg. Inhofe has expressed concern that Hormel,
who is openly gay, might embarrass the United States by trying to
promote his lifestyle overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Hoitsma said that Roll Call's linking of the pornography
incident and the Hormel issue was ``totally ridiculous, and pretty
shoddy journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton installed Hormel last week, using the
prerogative of a president to fill a vacancy while Congress is not
in session. In retaliation, Inhofe said he would use the
prerogative of a senator to block future presidential nominees.
</P>
</TEXT>
