<SLUG> BC-COUNTRYWIDE-ACQUIRE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LENDER TO BUY INSURER BALBOA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Countrywide Credit Industries Inc., the nation's
largest independent residential mortgage lender and servicer, has
said it is buying a life and casualty insurance company for $425
million.
</P>
<P>
   Countrywide's board already has approved the purchase of Balboa
Life and Casualty Insurance from Associates First Capital Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The unit, based in Irvine, has about 600 employees and is one of
the nation's leading writers of credit-related insurance in the
nation. It specializes in auto and homeowners insurance for
creditors such as mortgage holders.
</P>
<P>
   Balboa does business in all 50 states and had net premiums of
$234 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's deal further broadens Countrywide's presence in the
insurance business.
</P>
<P>
   In November, the company began an aggressive campaign to offer a
full range of insurance coverage. It operates Countrywide Insurance
Services Inc., a full-service insurance agency.
</P>
<P>
   Countrywide agents will now be able to offer Balboa's products,
said Stan Kurland, president and chief executive officer of
Countrywide Home Loans and chief operating officer of parent
Countrywide Credit Industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Countrywide has a significant presence in the retail
distribution of insurance. The synergy is not placing (Balboa's)
people but actually using the entity as a preferred provider of
coverage for our agency,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase of Balboa will be funded in part by $200 million of
new common stock, equivalent equity-related securities, along with
unsecured debt.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Jonathan Gray at Sanford Bernstein in New York said
Countrywide's core business will remain making home loans. Balboa's
operations are small compared with the home loan segment, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do have an array of products they are cross-selling. They
have a base of customers who have done business with the company
... and will offer this customer list other products and many other
financial services,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Countrywide fells 87.5 cents to $39.3125 on light
trading Monday.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
