<HEADLINE>
AIRPLANE MAKERS DISAGREE ON DEMAND FOR SUPERJUMBO JETS 
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-BOEING-OUTLOOK-SPI   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ There was a jumbo size disagreement Monday between The
Boeing Co. and Airbus Industrie at the Paris Air Show.
</P>
<P>
   The two airplane makers presented their current global aircraft
market outlook for the next 20 years, and they could not have come
to more different conclusions about the market for a plane bigger
than the 747.
</P>
<P>
   With its 747, Boeing today enjoys a monopoly on planes that can
carry more than 400 passengers. Airbus wants to break that Boeing
stranglehold and is planning to develop a plane called the A3XX
that will be able to carry upward of 600 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Whether there is a market for such a large plane has been one of
the industry's hottest topics for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Baseler, vice president of marketing for Boeing Commercial
Airplanes, told reporters at a morning briefing Boeing believes
there is a 360-plane market worldwide for a plane bigger than the
747 between now and 2018.
</P>
<P>
   And most of those planes will not be needed until after 2008, he
said. Over the next 10 years, the market for a so-called superjumbo
is only 80 planes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's hardly enough planes to justify the huge development
costs, and Boeing has decided for now not to build anything bigger
than the 747, though it may eventually stretch the current version
of plane to carry about 100 more passengers. Stretching the 747
would cost far less than building a new plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really a niche market,'' Baseler said of the potential
customer base for something bigger than a 747.
</P>
<P>
   ``It keeps going down and down and down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The 360-plane figure is down about 100 planes from Boeing's
market forecast a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Airbus sees this market much differently, which is why it
maintains it will go ahead with the development by next year of the
A3XX.
</P>
<P>
   In his briefing Monday, Adam Brown, vice president of
forecasting and strategic planning for Airbus, said the market for
a plane the size of the A3XX is about 1,500 aircraft, which
includes about 300 freighters.
</P>
<P>
   If Boeing is right, Airbus could be building a white elephant.
If Airbus is right, Boeing could be left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Aboulafia, aerospace analyst with the Teal Group, a
market analysis firm, said Monday that Boeing's numbers are
probably too low and those of Airbus are almost certainly too high.
But Boeing is probably closer to the actual market, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not convinced that's the smartest thing to do,'' he said
of the Airbus decision to proceed with development of the A3XX.
</P>
<P>
   Though Boeing and Airbus don't agree about the need for a bigger
plane, they do agree that the world's aircraft market over the next
20 years will grow significantly.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is forecasting that the world's airliner fleet will more
than double to 28,425 aircraft by 2018, representing some $1.38
trillion.
</P>
<P>
   That's close to the Airbus prediction that 15,500 new jetliners
valued at $1.3 trillion will be needed by passenger and cargo
airlines over the next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's Baseler said the largest share of the market, more than
$570 billion, will be dedicated to intermediate twin-aisle planes
such as its 767 and 777.
</P>
<P>
   Market fragmentation and less regulation, especially in the
Asia-Pacific region, will open many new routes, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
