<SLUG> BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PRO BASKETBALL: AT LAST, A RING FOR ROBINSON OR EWING
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Robinson's life will be easier without Patrick Ewing to
guard him in the middle this week. He can roam the key freely, have
an inch or two more of room to shoot his left-handed rainbow jumper
and not have to worry about defending against Ewing's fakes and
fallaways on the other end of the court.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is a part of Robinson that wishes Ewing were playing,
the part that feels for his counterpart _ the way only another
aging center who has been unable to lead to his team to a title
could.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't wish an injury on anybody at this time of the
year,'' Robinson said. ``This opportunity doesn't come around very
often.''
</P>
<P>
   At some point Tuesday at the Alamodome after practices, Robinson
will meet up with Ewing. The two 7-footers will presumably segue
from a handshake into an embrace, exchange pleasantries. Then they
will go about their duties in the National Basketball Association
finals beginning in San Antonio tomorrow night: Robinson spinning
along the baseline, combining his talents with Tim Duncan's for the
San Antonio Spurs; Ewing pumping his right arm in the air from the
Knicks' bench, emotionally charging his team because physically he
is no longer able.
</P>
<P>
   And in two weeks, one will be fitted for a ring, killing the
perception that neither was ever of championship ilk. Whether it's
Ewing or Robinson, a semblance of justice will be meted out for the
two most maligned players in the NBA's Top 50 of all time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that way,'' Robinson said of measuring a
player's greatness by the championship rings he wears.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what you do night in and night out is what matters,''
he added after the Spurs' practice in San Antonio. ``But if that's
the standard that people are going to set, then you have to go out
and get it.
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``Being a champion is the most important thing in
our sport because there are a lot of guys who are just good out
there. Being able to get over that hump, and figure out what it
takes to move to that next level, is a big part of the measurement
that people use for greatness. I want to learn how to win it.
That's what's fun for me. Where I fit in history? I couldn't really
care less.''
</P>
<P>
   Soft, that's what the Admiral was often called. Before this
playoff run, he was on his way to being remembered as a frustrated
silver medalist in San Antonio the way Ewing was in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In a league where players become aloof entertainment moguls
before some reach age 21, Robinson was said to be too accommodating
and pleasant for his own good. Scowling people like Bill Russell
won titles, it was said.
</P>
<P>
   The kinship between Ewing and Robinson goes beyond their
bittersweet careers. They played college basketball in the
Washington area: Ewing at Georgetown and Robinson at Navy. No. 1
draft picks in different years, their careers were defined more by
Hakeem Olajuwon's dominance of them in the mid-1990's than by what
they accomplished themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, they have also had the invisible mantle of Franchise
Player lifted from their name plates.
</P>
<P>
   ``For so long, they were called upon to score to get the team
over the top,'' said Herb Williams, the 41-year-old Knick reserve
center. ``Now that their teams added talent around them, they don't
try to go out and do everything they did before, because then you
start to step on people's feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a good player _ no, a great player _ to understand
the game of basketball and where he fits in. And that he needs to
play his role, night in and night out. Both of those guys did the
same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing accepted a reduced role more begrudgingly than did
Robinson, who welcomed Duncan into the fold like a brother from
whom he had been separated at birth. New York's Big Fella did not
speak much to Marcus Camby when he was first acquired and was
privately concerned about Latrell Sprewell's shot selection the
first few months _ many of his shots being launched before Ewing
crossed midcourt.
</P>
<P>
   Just as he had previously placed trust in Allan Houston, Ewing
eventually gained confidence in his new teammates this season and
understood how their athleticism could make life easier for him.
Post-Up U. was suddenly becoming Up-Tempo State, and the
possibilities were tantalizing for Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   Urging his teammates to ``get me my ring'' during the Pacers
series, the day after a partly torn Achilles' tendon sidelined him
for the season, he began to see the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of great players go through this league and never get a
ring,'' Williams said. ``It's so tough to get there and so many
things can go wrong. You got to be good, but you also got to be
lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you need help. One player does not win a championship.''
</P>
<P>
   For so long, Robinson and Ewing have been deemed unreliable in
the clutch _ as if they were somehow the main reasons their teams
faltered in the post-season.
</P>
<P>
   In two weeks, the labels will begin to die. ``Soft'' will slowly
become ``determined'' and ``stubborn'' may eventually become
``unselfish.'' And maybe, just maybe, two of the great centers of
their era will get their due.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're both champions in my mind; they have been forever,''
Knicks Coach Jeff Van Gundy said. ``But now I think the outside
world is going to recognize one, at least, as a champion. And
hopefully, people can get by the fact of whether you have a ring or
not as being the sole determinant of who's a champion and who's
not.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
