<SLUG> BC-NORTEL-RESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTEL SAYS ITS PRESIDENT WILL RESIGN
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   David L. House, president of the Nortel Networks Corp. of
Canada, the communications equipment giant, will resign as soon as
this summer, Nortel said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   House had been chief executive of Bay Networks Inc., a big maker
of data communications gear. Nortel, formerly Northern Telecom
Ltd., bought Bay last summer for $9.1 billion in stock in a bid to
bolster its presence in the Internet market. Nortel, like many
other big makers of traditional phone gear, is moving fast to
expand into offering advanced data communications equipment.
</P>
<P>
   House did not outline any specific future plans. Nortel said it
had no plans to fill the post and that John Roth, vice chairman and
chief executive, would assume House's operational and management
duties.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market may very well view House's departure as good
for Nortel. At Bay, he had at best a mediocre track record in
delivering consistent earnings growth, and the stock was known as a
roller coaster. Cisco Systems Inc., one of Bay's main competitors,
far outstripped Bay in delivering advanced products and stellar
financial returns.
</P>
<P>
   Nortel is facing the formidable technical challenge of
integrating Bay's data-networking technology with Nortel's
traditional telephone equipment. If House's departure demoralizes
former Bay executives, that may set back the effort.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent Technologies, North America's biggest maker of
communications equipment and Nortel's longtime rival, may soon face
similar issues. In January, Lucent announced a $20 billion deal for
Ascend Communications Inc., another big data-networking concern.
The deal is set to be completed in the next few weeks, but few
analysts expect Ascend's senior leadership to remain intact as part
of Lucent. Many analysts expect Mory Ejabat, Ascend's chief
executive, to depart Lucent within months of the deal's closing.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Nortel also created the new position of chief
technology officer and named Bill Hawe, a former Bay Networks
technology executive, to fill it. Hawe will oversee Nortel's
technology strategy and investments in and acquisitions of smaller
technology companies. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-99 2250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990614.0482 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5331 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EMBRYO-RESEARCH-NYT &LR;      06-14 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMBRYO-RESEARCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUMAN EMBRYOS USED, BUT NOT CLONED, IN GERON'S RESEARCH
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Geron Corp., which has sponsored the leading research on
primordial human cells, said Monday that it was conducting research
on discarded human embryos in the hope of learning how to convert
the ordinary cells of a patient into stem cells that can be used
for self-repair.
</P>
<P>
   The company denied a report Monday that it was trying to create
cloned human embryos and said that it had no intention of doing so.
Rather, its recently announced collaboration with the Roslin
Institute of Scotland, the cloner of Dolly the sheep, was an effort
to understand how eggs ``reprogram'' the nucleus of an adult cell,
said Dr. Thomas Okarma, Geron's vice-president for research.
</P>
<P>
   If the reprogramming process was understood, biologists might be
able to take an ordinary cell from a patient and convert it into a
stem cell, using the reprogramming factors found in an egg. A group
of the stem cells might then be used to repair the patient's
tissues.
</P>
<P>
   Okarma said Geron was working with animal eggs and with human
eggs rejected by fertility clinics because they were not viable.
The company's biologists said they hoped to see what factors from
the fluid, or cytoplasm, of the egg bind to its nucleus, in the
hope that these factors would show how the nucleus was
reprogrammed. An article on the company's research appeared in The
Washington Post on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Geron, a biopharmaceutical company in Menlo Park, Calif.,
financed the research of two university scientists who isolated
human embryonic stem cells last year for the first time. Congress
has forbidden the use of federal funds for such purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Geron, a company whose goal is to combat aging, worked to
isolate human embryonic stem cells because the cells have the
potential of turning into liver cells, eye cells, neurons _ all of
the body's cell types. Stem cells, can in principle, be used to
repair all of these tissues.
</P>
<P>
   But Geron's human embryonic stem cells are likely to be rejected
by most patients because they belong to an individual with an
incompatible immune system. Though there are theoretical ways to
fix the problem, the company has decided to take a leaf from the
animal cloners' book.
</P>
<P>
   In animal cloning, the nucleus of an adult cell from one sheep,
say, is inserted into a second sheep's egg cell, whose own nucleus
has been removed. Adult cells typically have their genes
permanently switched off, save those needed for specific roles.
Unknown factors in the cytoplasm of the recipient egg can
apparently release the switched-off genes in the adult cell's
nucleus, reprogramming it so it can take over the egg cell,
creating an embryo that grows into a twin of the animal that
provided the nucleus.
</P>
<P>
   Geron said it was not interested in cloning animals or people
but in discovering the reprogramming factors and applying them to
mature cells from a patient, to avoid rejection by the patient's
immune system and any ethical problems of using cells from a
discarded human embryo.
</P>
<P>
   At no stage of the process, as it has been described, would a
human embryo be created. Though human embryonic stem cells can
generate all the tissues of the body, the tissues are not formed in
an orderly fashion unless the cells are inside the hollow sphere of
an early human embryo. The cells that form the sphere, known as
trophoblasts, seem to be responsible for organizing the inner cell
mass, from which embryonic stem cells are derived, into a properly
formed embryo.
</P>
<P>
   Embryos are created, however, in the process being pursued at
Advanced Cell Technology of Worcester, Mass., which announced last
November that it had transferred nuclei from human cells into cow
eggs. The human nuclei are thought to take over the cow egg, so
that the hybrid embryo quickly becomes human during the few days it
lives.
</P>
<P>
   The company's experiment was performed several years ago and
then halted. But Dr. Robert Lonza, an official at ACT, said Monday
the experiments had been resumed recently with two goals in mind.
One, like Geron's, is to discover factors that enable the egg to
reprogram the nucleus. The other is to create embryonic stem cells
from a patient by inserting a nucleus from the patient's cells into
a cow egg and then take the stem cells from the hybrid embryo,
which would be discarded.
</P>
<P>
   Other scientists are skeptical of this approach because of
evidence that mitochondria, the energy-producing organelles in the
cytoplasm of the cow egg, would not work well with a human nucleus.
</P>
<P>
   Lonza said that recently, Dr. Neil First of the University of
Wisconsin formed hybrid embryos using denucleated cow eggs and
nuclei from mice, monkeys and other animals. The embryos did not
grow to term in a cow's uterus, suggesting, he said, that cow-human
hybrid embryos would not be viable. Lonza said the company was
considering ways to replace the cow mitochondria with human
mitochondria.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-99 2252EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990614.0483 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5332 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-DIERKER-HN     06-14 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-DIERKER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTROS MANAGER TO UNDERGO BRAIN SURGERY TUESDAY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID BARRON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Astros manager Larry Dierker will undergo brain
surgery Tuesday at Methodist Hospital, where doctors will attempt
to remove a 1 1/2-inch tangle of blood vessels that triggered his
violent seizures Sunday at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors will operate at about 7:30 a.m. to repair a condition
known as an arteriovenous malformation, removing a 4-cm clump of
vessels in the frontal portion of Dierker's brain that caused the
52-year-old manager to begin convulsing during an Astros-San Diego
Padres game.
</P>
<P>
   While the condition requires surgery that could sideline Dierker
for several weeks, doctors ruled out the presence of a tumor and
graded Dierker's condition as the least serious on a five-point
scale of potential scenarios.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the least-risky types of brain surgery that
could be performed,'' said Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker.
``I'm not going to say that this is the same as breaking an arm and
setting the bone, but under the circumstances, they (Methodist
physicians) are optimistic and feel he will have a full recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker remained hospitalized Monday in stable condition at
Methodist's intensive-care unit. Televisions and radios are not
allowed in Dierker's room, but Astros owner Drayton McLane Jr. said
nurses were asked to give him inning-by-inning updates on Monday
night's Astros-Atlanta Braves game.
</P>
<P>
   At the ballpark, the Astros saluted their absent manager by
hanging his familiar No. 49 jersey in their dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Monday, Dierker was visited at Methodist by Astros first
baseman Jeff Bagwell and second baseman Craig Biggio. Both were
buoyed by Dierker's upbeat demeanor and the optimistic prognosis _
especially since they had been told Sunday night there was a 95
percent chance Dierker was suffering from a brain tumor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in good spirits,'' Bagwell said. ``He's got a big day
ahead of him, but obviously being the other end of what it could
have been is a lot better. And that's great.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dierk's talking about being back on the bench in two weeks.
That's nice. It makes it a lot easier on us right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Biggio added, ``Maybe our thoughts and prayers were answered
yesterday in getting some of the results back.''
</P>
<P>
   Methodist Hospital officials, citing privacy requirements, would
not discuss arteriovenous malformations, known in medical shorthand
as AVMs, as they related to Dierker's case.
</P>
<P>
   However, the hospital said it annually performs about 350
craniotomies, or surgical openings of the skull, to remove AVMs or
tumors. A large number of those procedures involve tumors,
Methodist said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James Rose, a professor of neurological surgery at Baylor
College of Medicine in Houston, said the type of surgery faced
Tuesday by Dierker usually takes three to seven hours to perform.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recovery depends on the size and location of the malformation,
but after surgery, the patient typically spends a day in the ICU
and three days more in the hospital,'' Rose said. ``Usually,
patients resume normal activity in four to six weeks, but I'd think
Dierker could probably get back in the saddle in a couple of
weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite that estimate and Dierker's comments to Bagwell,
Hunsicker would not speculate on when the manager could return.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, that's the least thing on my mind,'' Hunsicker
said. ``The only thing on my mind is that the operation is
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker said he was told that the tangled vessels had been
present for at least two or three years. Other authorities said
such conditions can be present at birth.
</P>
<P>
   A doctor familiar with Dierker's case said hemorrhaging
associated with the mass produced swelling in the brain, which in
turn triggered the seizures that affected Dierker for up to 20
minutes Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The mass was said to be in a ``noneloquent'' portion of the
brain, meaning an area that is not associated with motor, language
or visual skills.
</P>
<P>
   Headaches are cited as warning signs of AVMs, and Hunsicker said
Dierker had suffered headaches in recent days. He said the manager
remembered little about Sunday's game, which the Astros led 4-1 in
the bottom of the eighth inning when play was suspended.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he was sorry he missed the grand slam (by Derek Bell
in the sixth inning, which accounted for the Astros' four runs),''
Hunsicker said. ``In fact, he didn't know what inning the game was
in when (the seizures) hit him. He remembers the first couple of
innings, but after that, he doesn't remember the rest of the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Team officials said Sunday that Dierker had suffered a seizure
in San Diego in June 1996, a year in which he had several medical
problems. However, Hunsicker said Monday those reports were
incorrect. He would not elaborate on the nature of Dierker's health
at that time.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker was taken to Methodist Hospital Sunday after he was
stricken with a series of full-body seizures in the Astros' dugout.
He underwent a magnetic resonance imaging exam, or MRI, Sunday
night and an arteriogram on Monday that confirmed the presence of
the AVM and ruled out a tumor.
</P>
<P>
   Players gathered in prayer on the field after Dierker was
removed by ambulance, a scene Hunsicker said typified the quality
of Astros players and coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big part of our success here is the people,'' Hunsicker
said. ``We've got special people here, on and off the field, and
yesterday was just a great example of how this team came together
in a time of crisis and showed the public what they're all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Astros fans visited the team's World Wide Web site
Monday in record numbers to receive updates on Dierker's condition
or offer recovery wishes. About 1,675 visitors left e-mail get-well
messages for Dierker.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the spectrum, the Astros said about 15 fans
visited Astrodome ticket windows Sunday to demand refunds from the
suspended Astros-Padres game. No refunds were granted, but the
Astros said they would consider giving a free ticket for a weekend
game to Sunday's ticket holders.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
