<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990614.0486 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5464 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPURS-DUNCAN-COX     06-14 1853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-DUNCAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Tim Duncan bio
 &HT;    By Mark Rosner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO, Texas _ Television cameras scanning the NBA Finals
for effusive gestures from its most acclaimed player will have to
settle for nuance.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Duncan will not hang from the rim and swing his legs like
Shaquille O'Neal does. He will not invent moves en route to a
twisting, off-balance shot, like any number of young players. He
will not pound his chest so everyone knows that he has heart.
</P>
<P>
   When the Finals begin Wednesday night in San Antonio, the Spurs
forward might cut through the heart of the New York Knicks, using a
soft jump hook, a deft drop step, or a quick, spinning move to the
basket.
</P>
<P>
   No, the NBA, which sells glitz with its games, will just have to
live with fundamentally correct, old-school basketball _ with the
reality that Duncan did not arrive in the league cable-ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim has no MTV in him at all,'' Spurs Coach Gregg Popovich
said. ``Tim's disposition is such that his priorities are
unbelievably mature for his age (23). He just comes out and does
his work. He's not interested in attention or whether people ooh
and ah.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan might never develop a mega-watt personality like Michael
Jordan or Magic Johnson, nor does he appear interested in that. He
does not record CDs or act in movies. He prefers not to indulge the
media, merely enduring sessions with reporters and keeping them as
brief as possible. Inquiries about his laid-back, seemingly aloof
personality are among the few things that seem to agitate him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't help me. It doesn't hurt me,'' Duncan said. ``I
don't really care. I've never been one who is up or down. It's who
I am. I'm not going to change.''
</P>
<P>
   The 7-foot Duncan arrived last season from Wake Forest
University with post moves better than anyone this side of Hakeem
Olajuwon and with impeccable footwork that others required years to
master. Duncan's San Antonio sidekick, David Robinson, figured all
of that out before they had ever played in an NBA game together.
Robinson, a renowned defender, considered Duncan's ability to score
against him the ultimate test of the rookie's acumen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was passing it a little too well,'' Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan is so impressive that Robinson did not complain when
Popovich appointed the younger, more polished offensive player as
go-to guy this season. For nine years, the 7-foot-1-inch Robinson
held the job, averaging 25 points a game. He was the league's most
valuable player in 1995. This season, taking fewer shots, Robinson
averaged 15.8, while expending more energy in his new role as the
Spurs' anchor on defense. Even so, he sometimes at least shares the
primary role with Duncan if an opponent puts a weaker defender on
Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   After an adjustment period during which Robinson said he was not
sure of his role in the offense, Robinson has excelled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course there was an adjustment,'' Robinson said. ``Before,
I was used to getting the ball as much as I wanted and pretty much
doing whatever I wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you have a guy like Tim, you have to use his talents,''
Robinson said. ``I don't have a problem with that. The biggest
thing about Tim is that he wants to get better. He cares about what
he's doing. He's willing to work, and he's very unselfish. Those
are combinations that are hard to find in such a talented player.
You've got to enjoy working with a player like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as Popovich predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew right from the beginning that Tim would be a good match
for David, because there would be respect between them,'' Popovich
said.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, who has two years left on his contract, can exercise
an option to get out of the deal after this season. He said that is
unlikely. Few, if any, teams could pay him under the NBA's salary
cap the $13.3 and $14.7 million he would receive from the Spurs the
next two seasons. Robinson enjoys the Spurs' success, and he is a
pillar of the city, having given several million dollars to
educational programs and the needy.
</P>
<P>
   Having two versatile, athletic 7-footers in the game has
provided the Spurs with more talent than opponents can counter. Los
Angeles Lakers Coach Kurt Rambis assigned his biggest player,
O'Neal, to guard Robinson, which left no one to contend with
Duncan. Portland Coach Mike Dunleavy focused more on Duncan, and
Robinson elevated his offensive performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've learned to use each other,'' Duncan said. ``I think it
was limiting at first, but we've found ways to feed off each other
instead of get in each other's way.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he works best around the basket, Duncan is dangerous from
farther out, shooting bank shots from the wings or jumpers from
beyond the free-throw line, skills normally associated with smaller
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim is as fundamentally strong as any big man I've seen,''
veteran teammate Steve Kerr said. ``He has the great post moves,
the terrific footwork. You have to really understand the game to
see how fundamenally sound he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Popovich said that when he pointed out a tactical error that
Duncan made a few weeks ago, Duncan cut him off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got about one word out of my mouth, and he said `I know,' ''
Popovich said. ``He understands the game the way Magic Johnson did
or Larry Bird did.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan, who averaged 21.7 points and 11.4 rebounds a game during
the regular season, is producing at a similar pace in the playoffs
_ 21.5 and 10.4. He averaged 29 points during the Spurs' four-game
sweep of the Lakers, who had the temerity to guard him with one
player, sending useless help to the scene of destruction as Duncan
laid the ball in the basket.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan hit the winning shot in game two, a jump hook from the
baseline. He scored 70 points in the two Los Angeles games without
taunting the Lakers or high fiving Jack Nicholson at courtside. At
one point in the series' third game, teammate Mario Elie came to
the startling realization that the score was Duncan 20, the Lakers
22.
</P>
<P>
   Most of time Duncan performs without expression. But Duncan does
make subtle gestures, though, like after he and Minnesota star
Kevin Garnett dueled basket for basket during one playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a point that we both looked at each other and
winked, like `Good shot. Good shot,' `` Garnett said. ``Tim is a
great competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   The highly emotional Elie once wondered about Duncan, confusing
his calm demeanor for a lack of passion. That was about the time
the Spurs were 6-8, and Elie, new to the team, was shooting verbal
arrows across the locker room at Duncan, Robinson and Sean Elliott,
criticizing them as being too soft to succeed against top
competition. The Lakers' O'Neal had already dismissed Duncan and
Robinson as lightweights unfit to compete against him.
</P>
<P>
   Elie and O'Neal, the latter swept from the playoffs, have since
come to appreciate and understand how Duncan operates. How could
they not? The Spurs have won 42 of 48 since their 6-8 start.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no one fiercer on the court than my man Tim,'' Elie
now says.''I thought early in the year our guys were getting pushed
around. Then we progressed and said, `Hey, we're not going to get
pushed around any more.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Elie calls Duncan the 'Big Easy', a reference to the elegance
with which he plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim is so laid-back and cool,'' Elie said. ``He has such a
smooth game, and he looks like he does everything effortlessly.''
</P>
<P>
   Long before Jordan retired as the NBA's king last winter, media
pundits who are part of the league's fabric began trying to
identify the next Jordan. No one has passed inspection, not Grant
Hill, Penny Hardaway, O'Neal or Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   Smart money says no one will elevate himself to the rarified air
in which Jordan worked, but many suggest that Duncan will soon be
the best player in the NBA if he is not already.
</P>
<P>
   Kerr, who played with Jordan in Chicago for more than three
seasons, detects important similarities between Jordan and Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   ``That guy has the work ethic and the talent that reminds me of
(Jordan),'' Kerr said. ``They have a passion for the game. Tim
really loves to play. Loves to. And Michael was the same way.
Usually what separates the great players from the good ones is that
the guys who have unbelievable talent and passion become great
players.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan might play like a throwback and conduct himself with
restraint, but he is not 23 going on 43. He competes seriously
against teammates at video games. He has a few tattoos. He wears
his shorts backward in practice. And he has a sharp wit,
particularly when needling his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   But overall, Duncan is so unlike many contemporary young players
that he did not even make an issue of the new NBA collective
bargaining agreement, and no one stands to lose more money than he
does. Under the old rules, a player whose contract expired could
re-sign with his team for any amount the owner was willing to pay.
Several NBA players have six-year contracts totaling more than $100
million. Now, if Duncan remains with the Spurs after his rookie
contract expires next season, he can receive $71 million for six
years, perhaps $100 million less than he could have grabbed before.
</P>
<P>
   If Duncan cannot sell the game with personality, he might
enhance it with his mastery of the fundamentals. Many young players
who have tried to emulate Jordan work harder on style _
degree-of-difficulty dunks _ than skill. Jordan himself came to the
NBA with great athleticism, but it was only through exhausting
effort that he developed one of the deadlier jump shots, something
missing from many repertoires today. That is one reason scoring
continues to decrease.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all grew up with Jordan's `Come Fly with Me' video,''
Detroit's Grant Hill once said. ``We're the slam-dunk generation.
Nobody would work on their skills on the playground.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has taken responsibility for what he sired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess some of that crept in because of myself and Charles
Barkley,'' he said last season. ``With our ability to take over a
game and sell ourselves as individuals, we have infected the game
as much as we have helped it.''
</P>
<P>
   Young players who watch Duncan will not find fancy dunks to
copy. They might learn to use proper footwork and the backboard _
old-fashioned stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan, formerly a competitive swimmer, began learning
basketball skills after Hurricane Hugo in 1989 destroyed the pool
he worked out in back home in St. Croix in the Virgin Islands. He
didn't like swimming in the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think Tim is a new millennium player,'' Spurs point
guard Avery Johnson said. ``All of the kids on the playgrounds are
trying to do crossover moves and shoot threes and dunks. When
people really get a chance to see Tim in the finals, I want kids to
run to the playgrounds and shoot jump hooks. Work on their
footwork. He's just a different kind of player, and that's what I'm
excited about.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Rosner writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
