<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERGLADES-CASINO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Miccosukees open casino in Everglades
 &HT;    By Paul Reid
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Stand on the shoulder of the Tamiami
Trail west of Miami for long enough and any number of shapes will
rise before you from the infinite expanse of water and grass that
is the Everglades: a sleek, snowy egret; the fat neck of a bull
alligator; a black cloud of mosquitos; a blacker thunder cloud.
</P>
<P>
   A casino.
</P>
<P>
   The Miccosukee Resort and Convention Center is open for
business.
</P>
<P>
   Miccosukee tribal elders and casino management hosted a
ribbon-cutting ceremony Monday afternoon for the new casino, and
then partied into the night to the sounds of the Four Tops, Little
Richard, Hootie and the Blowfish and Chuck Berry.
</P>
<P>
   Fireworks blazed and WWF wrestlers thumped each other to the
wild applause of hundreds of VIP invitees and thousands of South
Floridians who braved a three-hour, six-mile traffic jam on Tamiami
Trail. They were answering the call to celebrate ``in one of the
last remaining natural wonders of the world: the South Florida
Everglades.''
</P>
<P>
   The $50-million, nine-story, 302-room resort was built after the
federal government granted virtual sovereignty to the Miccosukee
tribe within almost 700 acres of the Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   Gambling is not new to the Everglades. The Seminole tribe has
sponsored bingo for more than 20 years, the Miccosukee for nine.
But a gaming resort of this size is usually seen in Las Vegas or
Atlantic City. Nationwide, gaming resorts built on Indian land
bring in more than $6 billion and are filling once empty tribal
coffers.
</P>
<P>
   But the Everglades is environmentally unique. Except for a
portion of the Bangladeshi coast, there is nothing quite like the
Everglades on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Is there an inconsistency with developing a slice of the
Everglades just as Washington is getting set to spend $7 billion on
cleaning up the ecosystem?
</P>
<P>
   Is there an irony in the Miccosukee _ traditional protectors of
the Everglades since they settled here almost 150 years ago _
turning their land into a tourist destination?
</P>
<P>
   Promise to protect
</P>
<P>
   ``We were here first and have always protected the land and
continue to do so,'' tribal Chairman Billy Cypress said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pollution is a threat to the Everglades, entertainment is
not,'' he said. ``The federal government sets standards for the
Everglades yet they build prisons and immigration detention centers
out here. Our hotel is 20 miles from our homeland, on the edge of
the Everglades. It's not a threat.''
</P>
<P>
   The new hotel will also benefit the tribe's 470 members.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hotel will employ 500 people, including many tribal
members,'' said hotel director of marketing, Janice Jefferson.
``We're sold out already for our first convention, the United South
and Eastern Tribes.''
</P>
<P>
   Depiction of early lifestyle
</P>
<P>
   A large wall mural behind the resort's registration desk depicts
a Miccosukee family in traditional garb among the untouched flora
and fauna that once was the Everglades. Monday night, their
descendants were gathered around the slot machines.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Reid writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
