<HEADER>
A5470 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-HATECRIME-MURDER-     06-14 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-HATECRIME-MURDER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Duo convicted of hate crime murder
 &HT;    By Scott Hiaasen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The beating death of 29-year-old Steven
Goedereis by two teens last year was fueled not by fear or
retribution, but by the pair's prejudice against gays, two juries
said Monday in convicting the teens of hate crimes in the murder.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Donahue, 17, and Billy Dodge, 18, both of Greenacres,
Fla., could face more than 30 years in jail after they were
convicted by two separate juries Monday that heard testimony
together for much of the three-week trial.
</P>
<P>
   Donahue was convicted of second-degree murder and robbery as a
hate crime, while Dodge was convicted of third-degree murder as a
hate crime.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said the teens beat and kicked Goedereis more than
20 times after Donahue encountered Goedereis walking down 10th
Avenue North late one night. Donahue and Goedereis each were on
their way home, and both had been drinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``They became head hunters,'' said Assistant State Attorney
Renelda Mack. ``They didn't stop until they got enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Donahue told police Goedereis called him ``pretty'' and grabbed
him. In response, Donahue punched Goedereis and ran off to find his
friend Dodge; the two then returned to continue beating Goedereis
on the pavement outside a convenience store.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers largely conceded the teens' roles in the
beating. The question for jurors became one of motive: Did they
beat up Goedereis because he was gay, as prosecutors said, or was
their thinking more complicated?
</P>
<P>
   Donahue's lawyer, Joe Atterbury, said his client felt threatened
by Goedereis' overture, and suggested that Goedereis was committing
a crime himself by propositioning a minor for sex. When Donahue
went back to his friends, he told them someone had tried to rape
him, according to testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Dodge went with Donahue to find this would-be rapist and to see
if the man was the same person who had been stalking Dodge's
girlfriend, said Mitch Beers, Dodge's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors in Donahue's case quickly rejected his argument of
self-defense, convicting Donahue in just over an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't buy that he was threatened at all,'' said juror
Jeffrey Labelle of Boynton Beach. ``They showed us no evidence that
Steven even said anything to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Another juror, John Gramling of Lake Worth, said the fact that
Donahue went back to the street with Dodge looking for Goedereis
belied any argument that he was in danger.
</P>
<P>
   Donahue also was convicted of robbery as a hate crime because he
took Goedereis' book bag after punching him.
</P>
<P>
   The second jury struggled more with Dodge's case, deliberating
for 3 1/2 hours before convicting him of the lesser crime of
third-degree murder. Specifically, the jury found Dodge committed
the third-degree felony of aggravated battery that led to
Goedereis' death.
</P>
<P>
   Beers argued that Goedereis' injuries were not so obviously
severe that Dodge should have known the man's life was in danger.
He called the verdict a ``major victory'' for his client.
</P>
<P>
   The jury also found that Dodge's crime was a hate crime, Dodge
could face a more severe prison term. He and Donahue are scheduled
to be sentenced in September by Palm Beach County Circuit Judge
Harold Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   Goedereis' family was reserved after the final verdict was read
Monday night. ``We'll see what happens at sentencing,'' his father
said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Hiaasen writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
