<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 23:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5474 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTHFOOD-AD-COLUMN-     06-14 1314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTHFOOD-AD-COLUMN-ART-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: MAKING SOY SOUND SEXY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the last two years, Irwin Simon, the chief executive of
Hain Food Group, has spent millions of dollars assembling an empire
of natural-food products ranging from snack foods and soy milk to
condiments like mayonnaise. His company made its latest acquisition
in May, paying $70 million for the privately held Natural Nutrition
Group and its collection of brands that include Health Valley
cereals. The move lifted Hain's projected annual sales to $300
million, about triple what they were in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with 27 brands and more than 1,000 products, the company is
confronting the problem of how to attract consumers' attention and
build brand loyalty, especially among people who are not already
buying natural foods. It is a tall order, considering the intensely
competitive natural-foods business, which is rife with rival
products, and the challenge of making bland names like
``Breadshop'' and ``Westsoy'' zingy and memorable to the average
shopper.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and others who follow the industry argue that consumers
have only the foggiest awareness of even the most venerable brands
in the health-food business and that Simon faces an uphill battle
to change that.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have so many brands that it would be difficult to
delegate the marketing dollars efficiently,'' said Steve Hoffman,
publisher of Natural Business, an industry newsletter. ``This is a
day and age when it's become more and more competitive and brand
building, brand recognition and brand ownership are becoming more
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   In part because the natural-foods business has grown so fast _
between 10 percent and 15 percent a year recently _ retailers that
specialize in it have begun to market their own brands, competing
directly with Hain, which already has competition within the
category. ``You're seeing a rise in private label products in
stores like Wild Oats and Whole Foods,'' Hoffman said, ``and they
say that's because there's no brand recognition in the natural-food
sector.''
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers, particularly baby boomers, are turning to such foods
as part of an effort to live healthier and maybe longer. And
natural products often cost more _ increasing the profit potential
for stores that carry them.
</P>
<P>
   But as companies like Hain elbow their way into mainstream food
stores, they must go head to head with the colorful and heavily
advertised products of companies like Nabisco Group Holdings'
Nabisco and General Mills. While consumers may want them and
retailers may like them, that does not always mean there is plenty
of shelf space available to them.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting that, until now most of Hain's advertising budget was
spent on marketing to retailers. That effort has paid off, with
Hain present in many supermarket chains, including Kroger, Fred
Meyer and Food Lion. It has also been pushing to get its brands _
which include Weight Watchers snacks, licensed from H.J. Heinz, and
the Estee line of artificially sweetened foods aimed primarily at
diabetics _ into drugstores and other outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Those advertising priorities are about to change, according to
Maureen Putman, the company's vice president for marketing. ``In
fiscal 2000, which starts July 1, we are swinging the pendulum to
consumer advertising,'' she said. That includes hiring outside
agencies for the first time. Lotas Minard Patton McIver in New York
is working on a campaign for Terra Chips, the designer vegetable
chips acquired by Hain last summer, and another Manhattan agency,
Hard Hats Inc., is developing a campaign for Westsoy, a soy-milk
beverage line Hain took over when it bought Westbrae Natural in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Both campaigns will consist of radio and print ads and are still
on the drawing board, Mrs. Putman said, adding that she expected
Hain to spend ``around 6 percent of sales'' on advertising, which
would put the spending for the coming fiscal year at about $18
million. ``We first needed to get the products into distribution,''
she said, explaining Hain's original advertising strategy. ``Now we
need to let consumers know about them.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While Terra Chips has a distinctive name, product and package,
the campaign's goal is to increase sales. The Westsoy effort is
slightly more challenging: Not only are the ads supposed to get
people who do not drink soy milk to try it but also to win over
people who buy some other manufacturer's product.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big obstacle here of course is taste,'' said Karin
Miksche, the creative director of Hard Hats, a three-year-old
agency with billings of $14 million. ``Most people, when you say
`soy beverage' go `Yuck!' or `Ewww.' That's what we have to
overcome to generate trials.'' Most print ads for soy milk show a
glass of it, or a cereal bowl, and she plans to get away from those
well-worn paths, she said, although she would not give any further
details.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Putman said advertising on Web sites would also become a
priority in the coming months. ``It is an expensive proposition,''
she said, noting that new Web sites can cost $50,000 to $100,000
each, ``but for brands like ours that require education, Web sites
are important.'' The Earth's Best line of baby food, made by Hain
and sold in natural-food stores under a license agreement with
Heinz, is advertised through a link on Baby.com, she said. Other
advertising efforts include direct mailings and coupons.
</P>
<P>
   Simon, whose background in sales and marketing at Slim-Fast
Foods Co. and the Haagen-Daz unit of Diageo reveals that he is not
exactly to the health-food manner born, has used debt to acquire
companies almost continuously since he formed the publicly traded
Hain in 1993. With his pinstriped suits and his summer place in
East Hampton, Simon appears much more the financier than the
counterculturist. Along with the new ad campaigns, he plans to drop
some products, particularly those that overlap with others in the
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to look at what are the three or four pillars of each
brand,'' he said, noting that the company's Health Valley unit was
known for soup, cereal and baked goods, while Westbrae was
considered ``vegetarian and organic.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, new product introductions seem to have been
key to the company's growth. Just this year, Hain introduced 14 new
products, including a ``Hain Kidz'' line, which consisted of
marshmallow-crisp cereal and snack bars, animal cookies and a
company riff on gummy bears; two new cracker lines; four Westsoy
products, including a soy-milk pudding, and Terra Stix snacks.
Since it acquired Terra Chips last July as part of an $80 million
buyout of the Shansby Group, Hain has widened distribution and
introduced Terra Blues, a blue potato chip.
</P>
<P>
   The Hain Kidz line, while it was a timely move, immediately ran
up against ``Whole Kids,'' a line of staples like apple juice and
peanut butter from Whole Foods, one of the biggest natural-food
retailers in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Not all natural products have done well for Hain. Its 1997 net
sales fell by more than 5 percent, largely because it was deeply
vested in the rice-cake business. And while profits have usually
tracked sales in percentage increases, some wonder whether that
will continue once Hain slows the pace of its acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Simon said investors seemed to like what's going on. The
company's shares closed at $21 Monday, up from their 52-week low of
$10.75 in October but down from their 52-week high of $28.625 in
June 1998. ``People are looking at what the growth is in our
existing businesses,'' he said. ``You can't mask that with
acquisitions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
