<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5477 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DRUGS-CHURCH-NYT &LR;      06-14 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DRUGS-CHURCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATHOLIC BISHOPS CALL FOR OVERHAUL OF NEW YORK DRUG LAWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The state's Roman Catholic bishops called on the
governor and the state Legislature Monday to overhaul New York's
stiff drug laws, saying they have filled the state's prisons with
addicts who would be better served in drug treatment programs.
</P>
<P>
   In a two-page statement, the New York State Catholic Conference,
the lobbying organization for the state's Catholic bishops, also
said the laws' tough mandatory sentences had caused New York's
prison population to swell at enormous public expense since their
enactment in the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``As moral teachers, we believe the time has come, after a
quarter-century of experience, to urge all New Yorkers to advocate
for a more humane and effective system to rehabilitate addicts and
protect public safety,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   The laws, adopted in 1973 under Gov. Nelson Rockefeller, call
for some of the toughest prison sentences in the nation for drug
offenses. Critics have charged that the laws have needlessly
clogged the state's prisons with drug offenders, many of them
nonviolent addicts, who might have a better chance of
rehabilitation in a drug treatment program or some other, cheaper
alternative to prison.
</P>
<P>
   The statement released by the bishops on Monday came as a broad
coalition of judges, criminologists and politicians from both
parties began an aggressive campaign urging Gov. George Pataki and
the Legislature to scale back the drug laws drastically, if not
repeal them, in the current legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   Under the drug laws, judges must abide by rigid sentencing
guidelines that require long prison terms for drug offenses,
including lower-level crimes like possessing a small amount of
narcotics. For example, someone convicted of selling more than two
ounces of cocaine, heroin or other controlled substances, or
possessing more than four ounces, must get at least 15 years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   In their statement, the bishops backed two of the main goals
sought by critics of the drug laws: the abandonment of the current
sentencing structure for drug crimes and the restoration of
discretion to trial judges in determining the punishment for drug
offenders. The statement also said the laws' mandatory drug
sentences put far too many nonviolent drug offenders behind bars
without addressing their fundamental problem: their addiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people who are currently incarcerated and serving long
and costly sentences in our state prisons are persons with
addictions,'' the bishops said. ``The individual and common good
would be better served if these persons were treated for their
illness in an addiction treatment program rather than a prison or
county jail.''
</P>
<P>
   It is far from clear whether lawmakers will heed the growing
calls to overhaul the state's drug laws this year. Pataki, a
Republican, has proposed some changes to the laws, but his plan is
being opposed by Democrats in the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Among the changes the governor is seeking is allowing appellate
judges to cut the minimum sentence to as little as 10 years,
although only in cases involving first-time felons convicted of
relatively minor crimes like possessing a small amount of drugs
above the four-ounce minimum.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 9,063 people went to state prison for drug offenses.
That brought the total of people serving state prison terms for
nonviolent drug crimes to slightly more than 22,000, or almost a
third of the state prison population of 70,000, according to the
state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
