<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-INVEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH INDUSTRY SEEKING A SHARE OF BALKAN REBUILDING WORK
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Three days after British troops led the NATO advance
into Kosovo, British government officials plan to meet with
business leaders Tuesday to devise a strategy for securing Kosovo
reconstruction contracts.
</P>
<P>
   They will try to offset a widespread view that British companies
lost out in the race to rebuild Kuwait after the Gulf War eight
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting, at the Department of Trade and Industry here, is
expected to focus on making sure that British companies know well
in advance how to bid for contracts that the European Union has
estimated could be worth as much as $3.5 billion in the next three
years.
</P>
<P>
   The amount is much smaller than the likely cost of rebuilding
power-supply installations, roads, bridges and other big capital
projects damaged by bombing in the rest of Serbia. Those costs have
been estimated by European officials at $30 billion to $50 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But the question of rehabilitation in the worst-damaged areas is
clouded by political opposition in Washington and London. Both
President Clinton and Prime Minister Tony Blair oppose the idea of
spending money on reconstruction in Serbia outside Kosovo while
President Slobodan Milosevic remains in power. Clinton has also
insisted that the bulk of reconstruction money come from the
Europeans, not the United States.
</P>
<P>
   This means that the initial focus will be on rebuilding in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overall aim is that British companies are well placed to
bid for contracts,'' said Carrie Deverell, a spokeswoman for the
Department of Trade and Industry. The creation of what she called a
task force is certain to be part of a broader European race to
compete for contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the allied bombing was under way with no immediate
likelihood of a suspension, senior European officials met with
business leaders in Brussels on May 19 for informal discussions,
during which Goran Lindahl, chief executive of the giant
Swiss-Swedish engineering company ABB, proposed the creation of a
body to oversee the rebuilding and revival of the entire Balkan
region.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, according to the text of a speech he gave in
the presence of officials including Romano Prodi, incoming head of
the European Commission, Lindahl warned that without bold action to
reduce the financial risks of operating in the region, private
companies would ``wait a long time for stabilization to be achieved
before they commit new investments.''
</P>
<P>
   Britain's assumption, according to Pauline Shearman, a
strategist at the Confederation of British Industry, is that the
European Union and international financial institutions will
provide the bulk of international financing for reconstruction
projects. She said that the confederation, as the main umbrella
group for British manufacturers, wanted to insure that ``British
companies have suitable access to the opportunities and the
information'' required to bid for projects.
</P>
<P>
   The outlines of the British strategy are still vague. But, Ms.
Shearman said, companies that are already scouting for business in
Croatia and Bosnia would probably seek contracts in road building,
power generating and water supply in the Kosovo region. ``As far as
we are concerned there are no immediate plans for the Serbia
situation,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Colin Adams, executive director of the British Consultants
Bureau, a lobbying group financed by consulting firms in a broad
range of industries, said British companies did not want to be left
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point to bear in mind,'' he said, ``is that there is often
a perception that British companies can be slow off the mark. We
felt that in Kuwait we could have managed things a little better,
and there was a feeling that British companies could have won more
contracts. The whole objective is to make sure that we have our
loins properly girded, and have a clear plan.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He said nearly 60 of the British Consultants Bureau's 300
members had shown interest in seeking Kosovo contracts. They
include companies specializing in work ranging from agricultural
revival to civil engineering to mine clearing.
</P>
<P>
   One British company reported to be interested is Amec PLC, a
civil-engineering business that played a big part in repairing
Sarajevo's gas system from Bosnia war damage, and is now looking
for contracts in water supply, health care, power, railroads and
oil and gas supply.
</P>
<P>
   Other British construction-engineering concerns said to be
interested in reconstruction work are Ove Arup &AMP; Partners and Mott
MacDonald.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
