<DOCNO> NYT19990614.0493 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5481 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-MOOD-HNS &LR;      06-14 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-MOOD-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
When Jeff Bagwell and Craig Biggio visited Larry Dierker at
Methodist Hospital on behalf of their Astros teammates Monday
afternoon, their fallen manager left them with a message.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``He told us to take three out of four from the Braves,''
Bagwell said.
</P>
<P>
   Why not go for the sweep?
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he didn't want us to get too greedy,'' Bagwell added.
</P>
<P>
   One day after surviving the scare of his life, Dierker still
wasn't out of the woods. But he was in a lighthearted mood, and
that was enough to inspire his players to move forward without him.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker, who suffered a grand mal seizure during the eighth
inning of Sunday's suspended game against the San Diego Padres,
learned Monday that he has a condition known as arteriovenous
malformation, a collection of blood vessels that dislodged and
caused the seizure. He will undergo brain surgery today.
</P>
<P>
   According to Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker, doctors say
the prognosis is excellent. Although no definitive timetable has
been placed on Dierker's recovery and subsequent return to the
dugout, Astros owner Drayton McLane Jr. indicated Dierker could be
away from the team for as long as a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife, Elizabeth, and I visited Larry today, and he was very
upbeat,'' McLane said. ``He told us he thought he could be back in
two weeks, but the doctors say a month is more realistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Until then, the team with the best record in the National League
is under the guidance of interim manager Matt Galante, who
officially began his tenure as Dierker's fill-in when he presented
the Astros' lineup card to home-plate umpire Wally Bell before
Monday's game against the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Galante also visited Dierker at the hospital Monday, although
the two didn't talk much about the direction of the team. They
mostly talked about Sunday _ things Dierker remembered and a few he
did not, such as Derek Bell's sixth-inning grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did remember the last conversation we had before his
seizure, which surprised me,'' Galante said. ``I asked Dierk, `Was
I so boring that I put you to sleep?' He was in good spirits, and
that was good to see.''
</P>
<P>
   The news regarding Dierker's condition was better than some
feared _ there was legitimate concern Sunday night that he might
have a tumor _ and Hunsicker believes that will help the club move
forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team is relieved,'' Hunsicker said after meeting with the
players to update them on Dierker's situation. ``This could have
been a lot worse. You can't take brain surgery lightly, but the
prognosis has taken some of the tension out of the clubhouse. I
clearly saw a much more relaxed team (than on Sunday).''
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell, who was at the plate when Dierker's seizure began, said
seeing his manager Monday eased some of his concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like seeing the same old Dierk,'' Bagwell said.
``Obviously, there's nothing exciting about brain surgery, but the
prognosis is better than when we thought he might have a tumor.
Last night, it looked about 95 percent bad. Hearing today's news
was like getting the good 5 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Galante, 49, has served as Dierker's bench coach since the
beginning of the 1998 season, and he will handle both roles until
Dierker returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old days, managers didn't have much help,'' Galante
said. ``It's always going to be awkward when you come in as the
replacement; I did it twice in the minor leagues. But it's less
awkward here because I've been around some of these guys for so
long. I know the personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every decision I make is not going to be perfect. But we have
good players, and they're going to win games. Hopefully, when Dierk
comes back, our (National League Central) lead will be even bigger
than it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Galante reiterated that Dierker's absence won't bring about
drastic changes regarding the way the Astros are managed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no real differences as far as the game goes,''
said Galante, who has extensive experience as a minor-league
manager and also has overseen teams in the Caribbean winter
leagues. ``Larry and I always discussed every situation anyway. It
was his choice when it came to making those decisions, but we
always talked about them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other thing that you have to keep in mind is that we have
very good players, and those guys know how to play the game. I'm
here to mind the store and keep Dierk's seat warm until he gets
back. If his absence is short-term or long-term, so be it. I'm just
minding the store.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros can only hope business will remain good.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
