<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-STARR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE NEXT STARR REPORTD 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, June 15:
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Starr has apparently decided to tie up the many loose
ends of his mammoth investigation with a final, detailed report on
a range of questionable activities involving Bill and Hillary
Clinton that disappeared from public view the moment Monica
Lewinsky came along. According to the law and by precedents set by
earlier independent counsels, the public deserves a final
accounting, and Starr has the right to give his view on matters
that did not rise to criminal indictments. But what he does not
have a right to do is disrupt New York's Senate campaign, which is
likely to include Mrs. Clinton. He should not time his report to
the electoral calendar or slant it to present her in the worst
light.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Starr can partly repair his reputation for bad judgment
by getting this report right as to both timing and tone. Given the
fact that his predecessor, Robert Fiske, began investigating
Whitewater five years ago, there is no reason that Starr cannot
present his report in fairly short order. To wait until next year,
when Mrs. Clinton's campaign would be in full swing, would simply
confirm her allies' worst suspicions. In addition, the report
should be an evenhanded recitation of the evidence, including any
exculpatory findings.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, any report on Whitewater, the mysteriously migrating
Rose Law Firm records, Travelgate and Filegate is likely to
discomfit Mrs. Clinton. So may the two forthcoming trials involving
Webster Hubbell, the former associate attorney general and a
longtime friend of the Clintons. But since Starr has decided not to
indict Mrs. Clinton, the task of bringing these matters into the
electoral arena belongs to her prospective Senate opponents, not
Starr.
</P>
<P>
   All that said, it is to be hoped that if Mrs. Clinton does enter
New York politics, she will remember all the harm that
Arkansas-style stonewalling did to her husband's administration and
to the nation. The Clintons' decision not to answer reasonable
questions about Whitewater led directly to the appointment of a
special prosecutor. Congress, in turn, was repeatedly frustrated by
the White House's blocking tactics, by its meddling with legitimate
investigative arms of the federal government and by its refusal,
from the 1992 campaign onward, to provide a consistent factual
narrative of the Clintons' financial history. Had the president and
his associates provided all the evidence on Whitewater and the
other assorted scandals when they were invited to, Mrs. Clinton
would not have to worry about Starr's final report. Indeed, she and
her husband might not even have encountered Starr to begin with.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
