<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CHINA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BACK TO BASICS WITH CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, June 15:
</P>
<P>
   One of Washington's top diplomats, Thomas Pickering, is leading
a team of American officials to Beijing to explain and once again
apologize for the mistaken NATO bombing of the Chinese Embassy in
Belgrade. Pickering's visit on Wednesday should end the period of
icy hostility brought about by this incident, which killed three
Chinese journalists. In the coming days, Beijing should resume
discussions with Washington on the World Trade Organization and
other important matters that it has frozen since the embassy
attack.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration needs to give China and the American
people a fuller explanation of the events that produced the
apparently accidental bombing. In an age of computer targeting and
laser-guided bombs, mistakes this egregious should not happen.
Washington must also fairly compensate the families of the three
Chinese victims.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese, for their part, have assumed from the start that
the attack was deliberate. That judgment should be put aside and
Pickering, who comes prepared to offer a detailed reconstruction of
the incident, should be given a fair hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Washington and Beijing have an important agenda to attend to,
headed by the issue of China's admission to the WTO. The two
countries came close to agreeing on entry terms during the visit of
Prime Minister Zhu Rongji to America this spring. If Beijing is
ready to resume discussions where they broke off, a deal should be
possible quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Talks should also be renewed on other matters, including human
rights, relations between the two countries' armed forces and trade
rules for militarily sensitive items like computers and satellites.
There is also the unresolved question of alleged Chinese political
contributions to American election campaigns. These are all
sensitive issues, even more so after the recent Cox committee
report on Chinese nuclear espionage. But discussing them is more
productive than dwelling on the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
