<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-REDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDS BEAT METS, 8-4 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Getting runners on base has not been a problem for
the Mets this season. Driving them home has, at times. On Monday
night, they left the bases loaded twice.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds erupted for five runs after Jason Isringhausen was
lifted for a pinch-hitter in the top of the sixth inning, three of
them on Aaron Boone's tie-breaking home run off Turk Wendell, as
Cincinnati scored an 8-4 victory over the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Such is life when your two best hitters are given the evening
off. Or when your bullpen has to come in game after game before the
eighth inning, almost always in a tight game.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell was pitching one night after recording a save. The
right-hander had come on in relief of Greg McMichael, who was
pitching for the third time in four games since coming off the
disabled list. McMichael walked the first two batters he faced
after the Mets had gotten Isringhausen off the hook in the top of
the sixth when they tied the game at 3-3.
</P>
<P>
   McMichael came back to strike out the next two batters. On came
Wendell, who has now appeared in 35 of the Mets' first 63 games.
Two pitches later, Boone homered to left and it was a 6-3 game.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps McMichael (0-1) and Wendell were tired. Manager Bobby
Valentine thought Mike Piazza and John Olerud were. The Mets'
lineup had a decidedly different look. Last week, Valentine had
said Bobby Bonilla would sit out six games. For the first time in
eight days, Bonilla _ who did not start the last six games _ was in
the lineup. But it was at first base and not in the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine gave his regular Nos. 3 and 4 hitters, Olerud and
Piazza, the night off, as the Mets began a road trip after winning
six of their last seven games. The switch-hitting Bonilla batted
cleanup against left-hander Ron Villone, while Benny Agbayani, who
hits right-handed, batted third.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine said that Piazza, who had started every game since May
20, had requested the day off. Piazza said Valentine suggested it
and he agreed. General manager Steve Phillips said the Mets were
playing Bonilla, who has feuded with Valentine, merely to give a
day off to Olerud, who started 61 of the Mets' first 62 games, and
that the team was not trying to showcase Bonilla for a trade. ``I
think he can play first base,'' Valentine said of Bonilla, who had
made one other start there this year. ``I wouldn't put him there if
I didn't. He said, `Whatever we need.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine added that Bonilla would not be rejoining the outfield
rotation any time soon. ``But I don't see that we have any
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   And Phillips said he still felt as he did on Saturday, when he
said of last week's feuding between Valentine and Bonilla, ``It's
resolved.'' There was a pause. ``For the time being,'' Phillips
continued, adding that a meeting last weekend between Bonilla and
Valentine has taken ``some of the urgency off any of the other
options we have to consider.''
</P>
<P>
   Those options include trading Bonilla or even releasing him. For
his part, Bonilla said: ``I've got no more to say. I'm tired and
I'm exhausted. That's to everyone. There'll be no more from Bo.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla finished 0 for 5, but he did drive in a run, in the
first inning, when he grounded into a force at second with the
bases loaded and nobody out. Villone _ who issued four of his seven
walks in the first _ walked Roger Cedeno on a full-count pitch with
two outs to force in another run, giving the Mets a 2-0 lead on
just one hit, Edgardo Alfonzo's single.
</P>
<P>
   It was the only hit the Mets would record against Villone, who
tossed 36 pitches in the first. The Englewood, N.J., native was not
charged with another run until the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds tied the game on solo homers from Michael Tucker (with
two outs in the third) and Barry Larkin (with one out in the
fourth). And when Michael Cameron singled with two outs in the
fourth, stole second and scored on Aaron Boone's double that
rattled around the left field corner, the Reds had a 3-2 lead
against Jason Isringhausen.
</P>
<P>
   Villone was removed after walking the first batter of the sixth
inning, but the Mets tied the game against Scott Williamson when
Rey Ordonez lined a sacrifice fly with the bases loaded and nobody
out. But just as they had in the first, the Mets left the bases
loaded as Alfonzo struck out to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   And then the Mets' bullpen collapsed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
