<HEADER>
A5490 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES15-CO     06-14 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glavine feeling frustrated
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ It's been almost a month since Tom Glavine got a win,
and while he continues to feel better about his recent work on the
mound, last year's Cy Young award winner is starting to get
impatient.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets old going in afterward and saying `I feel good about
what I'm doing and I'm giving the guys a chance to win,''' said
Glavine, who is 3-7 and has three losses and a no-decision in his
past four starts. ``I'm still sitting there with a loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine said in his previous start against the Devil Rays, he
had ``great stuff'' and he continues to try and build on that. The
key for him is to incorporate some new strategy into his approach
against hitters, something he's had to do because his control
hasn't been what he wanted and possibly because the strike zone
hasn't been as forgiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm throwing some pitches when in the back of my mind I'm
wondering if that's the right pitch for the situation,'' Glavine
said. ``There's still some uncertainly because I'm trying to change
my pattern.''
</P>
<P>
   For Glavine, that means pitching inside more and mixing in more
breaking balls, instead of using predominantly his sinking
fastballs and change-ups away.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm at my best, my change-up is always a good pitch,''
Glavine said. ``I'm trying to get out of that pattern.''
</P>
<P>
   Even still, Glavine's not going to get too torn up about his
record at the moment, especially when he pitches tonight in the
Astrodome, site of Astros manager Larry Dierker's collapse on
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a whole lot worse things in life than being 3-7,''
Glavine said.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz absent
</P>
<P>
   John Smoltz did not travel to Houston with the Braves for their
four-game series here. Manager Bobby Cox said he had given Smoltz
permission to stay home for a family engagement and wasn't sure
when he would rejoin the team. Smoltz did not return messages at
his Duluth, Ga. home Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, Smoltz made his third start since coming off the
disabled list for an inflamed elbow, the one that's given him
problems for much of his career. Smoltz gave up a season-high seven
runs in his shortest outing of the season _ 2 1/3 innings _ against
the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Television shots of Smoltz showed him wincing in pain while
warming up Sunday night, though Smoltz said afterward his elbow was
not a factor. Cox and Glavine reiterated that on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I looked up it was a 94 mph fastball,'' said
Glavine, who said Smoltz didn't mention anything to him about his
elbow. ``I think it was one of those nights when he made a good
pitch and gave up a blooper, made a bad pitch and got
</P>
<P>
   hit hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Lasting loss
</P>
<P>
   After getting swept by the Orioles over the weekend, scoring
only three runs in the three losses of 6-2, 5-0 and 22-1, the
Braves admitted feeling a bit jolted.
</P>
<P>
   ``A loss is a loss, but a butt-kicking is a butt-kicking,'' said
cleanup hitter Brian Jordan, who was 2-for-10 in the series with no
RBIs. ``A shellacking is a shellacking. It was almost one of those
games where you feel hopeless.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said it was tough to work back from big first-inning
deficits like 4-0 Saturday and 5-0 on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's that they say `What goes around comes around?' '' said
Jordan, referring to the Braves 20-5 victory against the Rockies in
Colorado on April 18.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan scored the only run on Sunday night when he scored from
third on a short fly ball by Ryan Klesko. TV replays showed
third-base coach Ned Yost throwing up a stop sign, but Jordan said
he didn't see the sign, he only heard Yost say ``ho, ho'' and he
thought he said ``go.'' Jordan stuck by his aggressive play in that
situation and said Yost agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
