<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pitching dooms Braves again
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ This Braves team is having a hard time finding ways to
pick itself up and pull itself together and the Astros weren't
about to make it any easier on Atlanta Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Houston, the team with the National League's best record at
38-23, continued the trend by beating the Braves 10-4 in the first
game of a four-game series at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   Behind a three-double night from Craig Biggio and three
consecutive run-scoring hits off Kevin McGlinchy in the sixth
inning, the Astros extended their winning streak to four games and
prolonged Atlanta's losing streak to four in a row after a weekend
sweep by the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   The emotionally-drained Astros were the ones who picked
themselves up Monday night. In the previous 24 hours they had seen
their manager, Larry Dierker, collapse in a seizure in their dugout
and learned he would have to undergo brain surgery today for a
treatable blood vessel condition.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves nipped at the Astros' heels by cutting their leads to
2-1, 3-2, and 4-3 but never found enough of an offensive push to
make a difference, stranding runners at third base twice, before
Houston pulled away late. Atlanta's pitching held out for five
innings, before the bottom fell out in the sixth when the Astros
batting around.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in four starts, Braves rookie pitcher Odalis
Perez pitched poorly. He walked a season-high seven batters, ran
counts full on a regular basis, and bore the headache of at least
two baserunners in each of the six innings he pitched. Through the
first five innings, he'd thrown almost twice the pitches Houston
left-hander Mike Hampton had, 111-58.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
