<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-AKIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIGERIAN PLAYER A POSSIBLE MEDIA DARLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The 1999 FIFA Women's World Cup tournament, which
begins this weekend, could make a media darling of Nigeria's
``Marvelous'' Mercy Akide before it's over.
</P>
<P>
   Her team, with players who wear basketball-style, knee-length
shorts and a goalkeeper with Dennis Rodman-like blonde hair, will
get its fair share of attention, too.
</P>
<P>
   Akide, the leader of the Super Falcons, speaks softly and has a
glowing smile. Her words convey confidence in a team ready to shock
the soccer world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't come here for a vacation,'' said Akide, when asked
if she's enjoyed her stay in Los Angeles. ``We went to Hollywood
and enjoyed some of your French fries, but our mission isn't to
look around the city. Our mission is to make our country proud.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nigerians failed to get a victory in the previous two
Women's World Cup tournaments, in 1991 and '95, but stormed through
the African women's soccer championships to qualify for this World
Cup, outscoring opponents, 25-0.
</P>
<P>
   They are in the same group as the United States, but first will
face North Korea on Sunday at the Rose Bowl. It's the second game
of a doubleheader that pits Germany against Italy in the first
game.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Nigerians rarely face competition outside of Africa,
few soccer experts have given them much of a chance.
</P>
<P>
   But as China, one of the pre-tournament favorites, found out
during a 4-3 scrimmage loss to the Super Falcons at West L.A.
College over the weekend, they're dangerous and extremely
confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told everyone during the FIFA world all-star game in
February that we are going to surprise the world,'' Akide said. ``I
told the media we are not afraid of anything, not the United
States, not anyone. They are all just girls like us. We have the
experience of the past two World Cups and, with God on our side,
we'll do something special in this tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria will get its shot at the United States on June 24 in
Chicago, and Akide has an interesting way of describing the
matchup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not afraid of them,'' she said. ``Like I've been saying,
they're just ladies like us. That will be an exciting game because
the U.S. has great players. But it will be our chance to show the
world how good we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Akide has enjoyed her celebrity status in Nigeria. She led the
Falcons with 10 goals during WWC qualifying and, because of her
5-foot-11 stature, she's easy to spot on the field and on the
streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I walk around, they call me Miss Marvelous,'' said Akide
proudly. ``I walk the streets and they give me gifts along the way.
I feel like a queen; it's a wonderful feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the WWC qualifying tournament, Akide was relatively
unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the competition, I fasted for a week, praying all the
time,'' she said. ``I asked God to make me popular in the country.
I wanted to be a heroine, to prove wrong those who didn't believe
in me. I am glad that God answered my prayers.''
</P>
<P>
   With the huge attention the Nigerian team has received back
home, many of the players believe they're on a mission from God.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sing prayers before and after the game because God owns
this team,'' Akide said. ``Whatever we do, we put God first before
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Patience Avre, who scored three goals in the scrimmage against
China, said God is their secret weapon.
</P>
<P>
   ``God is watching over us,'' she said. ``We sing to Him, we pray
to Him and if He wants us to win, we will do it for Him.''
</P>
<P>
   Nigerian coach Ismaila Mabo said the team sings for other
reasons, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The singing makes them forget any troubles and focus on what
they're going to accomplish,'' Mabo said. ``They also sing in order
to psyche themselves and get ready for the game. And they sing
about conquering their opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   There seems to be a strong Nigerian following in Los Angeles.
Roughly 200 supporters appeared for the scrimmage against China.
They cheered throughout the match, hugging each other after every
Nigerian goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soccer is a wonderful medicine for the people,'' Mabo said.
``We have tremendous support back home. And to see the people in
L.A. come out really does a lot for this team. We play with passion
that God and our people give us. Because of that support, we have
that extra effort to win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
