<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SCOTUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: GANGS, GAMBLING AND THE SUPREME COURT 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, June 15:
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court does not lightly overturn federal and state
laws enacted with a worthwhile social purpose in mind. But in two
of its latest rulings, the court quite correctly struck down a
Chicago ordinance intended to combat gang activity and a federal
law aimed at curbing the problems associated with legal gambling.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-to-3 ruling last week in the Chicago case recognized the
terrible impact gang activity can have on neighborhoods. But,
following a line of cases going back decades, the majority decision
_ written by Justice John Paul Stevens and joined by Justices
Stephen Breyer, Sandra Day O'Connor, David Souter, Ruth Bader
Ginsburg and Anthony Kennedy _ also recognized the inherent danger
to basic freedoms when police are given too much discretion to
target innocent people.
</P>
<P>
   The vaguely worded statute made it a crime to ``remain in any
one place with no apparent purpose'' in the presence of a suspected
gang member when ordered by a police officer to move on. Before
lower courts put the law on hold in 1995, the Chicago police
arrested more than 42,000 people, most of them young
African-American and Latino men often guilty of nothing more than
standing outside with their friends and not dispersing as ordered.
At a moment when the problem of racial profiling by police is
coming under heightened scrutiny, the court's concern about vague
statutory language providing a cover for arbitrary police behavior
was especially welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's unanimous ruling against the federal ban on broadcast
advertising by gambling casinos turned on free-speech principles.
At issue was a federal law that outlawed such advertising even in
states, like Louisiana, where casino gambling is legal. The Justice
Department had defended the ban, emphasizing the problem of
compulsive gambling and gambling's link to organized crime. The
court, again with Stevens writing, did not quarrel with the
government's aim of discouraging gambling, but noted that the
regulatory scheme was riddled with exceptions _ permitting ads for
state lotteries and casinos run by Indian tribes, for example,
notwithstanding the potential social costs. That has left the
airwaves saturated with lottery and other gambling advertising,
making it impossible for the government to show that its
interference with commercial speech was tailored to advance the
stated governmental interest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-99 2343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
