<SLUG> BC-NY-MALPRACTICE-AWARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY FINDS MALPRACTICE DURING A BIRTH, AWARDS $76 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A jury has ordered the New York City Health and
Hospitals Corp. to pay $76.4 million to a 12-year-old girl who
suffered brain damage and other permanent injuries during her birth
in what her lawyer called a botched delivery.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of the largest medical malpractice verdicts recorded
against the corporation, which runs the city's hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The award, returned last Friday by a jury in Manhattan, was made
to Gaelle Prindilus, who was born on Jan. 16, 1987. Her lawyer,
Thomas A. Moore, said Monday that she was born with her umbilical
cord wrapped around her neck and with no medical personnel in the
hospital room to attend her mother, Yverose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given that the infant was already severely compromised for 17
hours, and was strangled by her own umbilical cord and was not
breathing, every second was crucial,'' he said. ``Yet there was no
one on hand to administer immediate resuscitation and live-saving
measures. This was a classic example of the indifferent and
horrendous care that the city's HHC has been chastised for.''
</P>
<P>
   Eugene Borenstein, the chief counsel to the hospitals
corporation, denied that there had been anything improper in the
delivery and insisted that the care at Harlem Hospital Center had
been ``excellent.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the city would move to have the verdict set aside as
``grossly excessive'' and, failing that, would appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Gaelle's mother, Yverose Prindilus, is a housewife and her
father, Sensois Prindilus, has worked as a kitchen helper and a
janitor to pay for her medical care. Gaelle suffers from cerebral
palsy, requires a wheelchair and round-the-clock care and cannot
read or write. The family _ there are five other children _ lives
in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Moore said the verdict included $35 million for future medical
care and loss of earning capacity, $5 million for past suffering,
and $36.4 million for future suffering. He said the city had
refused a settlement offer of $3.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Previous medical malpractice awards against the city include
$112 million awarded by a Queens jury last year in an obstetrics
case that was later reduced in a settlement to $4.5 million. Also
last year, a Manhattan jury awarded $49 million in another
obstetrics case, and a Bronx jury in 1995 ordered the hospitals
corporation to pay $42 million to the mother of a girl injured at
birth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
