<HEADLINE>
TWO TEAMS HAVE LOGISTIC PROBLEMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Since FIFA Women's World Cup officials aren't
officially in charge until Wednesday -- the four countries (Italy,
Germany, North Korea and Nigeria) participating in Sunday's opening
doubleheader at the Rose Bowl are expected to make their own
arrangements for training.
</P>
<P>
   Well, North Korea was the first to experience bad luck, missing
their scheduled training at Pomona Pitzer College because the van
that was supposed to pick them up at their Arcadia hotel never
showed up. According to German players who are staying at the same
hotel, the Korean's waited for at least an hour before calling it
an afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Germans were late to Monday's training at Pomona, as
their van was a half hour late because of traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we were late because of an accident or something,''
said German coach Tina Theune-Meyer. ``But it's OK, today was a
light day.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen of Germany's players were given the day off because
they played in the German club championships on Saturday. They
spent the day at Santa Monica beach.
</P>
<P>
   ___German defender Steffi Jones, the daughter of an American
serviceman, said the toughest adjustment is getting use to the
weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``The temperature here is much higher than in Germany,'' she
said. ``I'm glad we're training near the end of the day because the
weather is tough on us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Germans will visit Universal Studio's this morning before
resuming training at Pomona.
</P>
<P>
   ___Those who would like to see the Nigerian national team can
attend a free scrimmage at West L.A. College today at 3 p.m. The
Nigerians are facing a Torrance Club team.
</P>
</TEXT>
