<HEADER>
A5508 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-DAVIS-NYT &LR;      06-14 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-DAVIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENNETH S. DAVIS, 86, FDR BIOGRAPHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kenneth Sidney Davis, the author of a four-volume biography of
Franklin Delano Roosevelt, died on Thursday at University Hospital
in Madison, Wis. He was 86.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, said his wife, Jean.
</P>
<P>
   Davis did not belong to the fraternity of trained historians.
Yet, like Shelby Foote, another nonacademic chronicler of the past,
Davis had a respect for detail and an understanding of the sweep
and the interlocking significance of events.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a real grasp of the historical craft,'' said Alan
Brinkley, a professor of history at Columbia University. The
Roosevelt work is ``a wonderful narrative biography and probably
the most thorough.''
</P>
<P>
   The volumes of Davis' ``FDR'' biography _ ``The Beckoning of
Destiny, 1882-1928,'' ``The New York Years, 1928-1933,'' ``The New
Deal Years 1933-1937'' and ``Into the Storm, 1937-1940'' _ were a
lifetime project, representing more than 30 years of labor.
</P>
<P>
   Davis traced Roosevelt's transformation from a Hudson Valley
aristocrat with an instinctive conservatism to the architect of the
New Deal. He argued that it was Roosevelt's exposure to the liberal
traditions of New York state politics, including child welfare
reform and trade unionism, that made possible his radical
transformation.
</P>
<P>
   But in writing about Roosevelt, Davis did not fall prey to the
biographer's occupational hazard of being awed by his subject. He
was unstinting in his assessment of Roosevelt's character, seeing
him as at once charming and aloof, superficial and profound,
idealistic and opportunistic, even at times capable of ``a thin,
steely edged cruelty.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis criticized Roosevelt for his refusal to support
antilynching legislation in Congress and for not coming to the aid
of the Jews in World War II. He found fault with his attempt to
pack the Supreme Court, his ``isolationist sentiments'' during the
1930s, and particularly his failure to take early action against
Japanese aggression in China.
</P>
<P>
   `` Davis' picture of a cautious, ineffective leader is
overdrawn,'' Robert Dallek wrote in 1993 in a New York Times review
of ``Into the Storm.'' Nonetheless, he added, the work, ``despite
its many questionable judgments, will take its place in the
Roosevelt literature as a standard against which other, more
sympathetic historians will have to argue.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his Roosevelt biography, Davis was the author,
co-author or editor of some 20 books, including biographies of
Dwight D. Eisenhower, Charles A. Lindbergh and Adlai E. Stevenson.
In his early life, however, Davis seemed destined for a career in
agriculture rather than history. Born in Salina, Kan., where his
father was a college professor, Davis was educated at the Kansas
State University of Agriculture and Applied Science (now Kansas
State University). He received a master's degree in science at the
University of Wisconsin. After working briefly as a reporter at The
Topeka Daily Capital in Kansas, he became an information specialist
at the Soil Conservation Service in the Midwest, where he worked
until 1942.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, Davis was a war correspondent for Doubleday
&AMP; Co., attached to the Supreme Headquarters of the Allied
Expeditionary Forces in London and Normandy. After the war, he
became a public relations assistant to Milton Eisenhower, the
younger brother of Dwight D. Eisenhower, at the U.S. Commission for
UNESCO. In 1955, he was a speechwriter for Stevenson. When asked to
name his favorite among his three biographical subjects, Lindbergh,
Roosevelt or Stevenson, Davis answered: ``Adlai Stevenson. He would
have made a great president.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis' first wife, Marie Olenhouse, died in 1988. Two years
later, he married Jean Dormer. He is also survived by a sister,
Ella Rae Friel of Sacramento, Calif., and a stepdaughter, Jane
Mitchell of Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   When Davis began writing his Roosevelt biography he was
determined, he said, to make it only one volume. Instead, he said,
``my first volume grew and grew.'' In December, he finished a fifth
volume, ``The War President.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The book was finished,'' his wife said on Monday. ``We left
for Arizona. And there the cancer was diagnosed.'' Robert Loomis,
Davis' editor at Random House, said he did not know when the last
volume would be published.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
